<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0608 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CHRISTIES-AUCTION-ART     05-10 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIES-AUCTION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PICASSO PORTRAIT IS AUCTIONED FOR $28.6 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo _ NYT40 _ has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A portrait that Picasso painted in just two and a
half hours in 1932 sold at Christie's on Tuesday night for $28.6
million. While that work brought the highest price, Picassos of
different styles and dates accounted for the four top lots in an
auction of 20th-century art that several experts described as hot
and cold.
</P>
<P>
   The sale totaled $72.9 million, in the middle of its estimate of
$64.3 million to $84 million. Of the 42 works offered, 34 found
buyers.
</P>
<P>
   The evening made less money and sold fewer paintings, drawings
and sculptures than Christie's sale of Impressionist and
post-Impresssionist art on Monday night, which totaled $104.5
million for 42 sold out of 47 works offered. The big difference was
the atmosphere. Monday's bidders were both controlled and
controlling in terms of prices. On Tuesday night, top-quality works
tended to sell far above expectations; less desirable ones were
dismissed in short order.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a strong market, but at the same time not crazy,'' said
Christopher Burge, Christie's honorary chairman, who was the
evening's auctioneer.
</P>
<P>
   The sale's one blockbuster _ ``Still Life With Tulips,'' the
1932 Picasso portrait of his mistress Marie-Therese Walter _
appeared to have three serious bidders.
</P>
<P>
   The painting is particularly unusual: it is both a portrait and
a still life. It was painted on March 2, 1932, and on the back
Picasso recorded not simply the date but the hours he painted it: 9
to 11:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's had estimated it would bring $25 million to $30
million and had given the seller, an unidentified European
collector who had owned it since 1957, a guarantee (an undisclosed
minimum price that an auction house promises the seller regardless
of the sale's outcome).
</P>
<P>
   After the sale, several theories about the identity of the buyer
were discussed outside Christie's. Some people sitting directly in
front of Burge said they thought the buyer was a Sammy Ofer, the
Israeli shipping magnate. Others said that the winning bid, which
was taken by Barbara Strongin, Christie's director of auction
operations, was made by Christie's, buying the painting back.
Auction house officials would say only that the painting was bought
by an ``anonymous buyer.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the four Picassos sold well above their estimates. ``Head
of a Woman With Bangs,'' painted on June 2, 1938, was estimated at
$2 million to $3 million. Five bidders tried hard to take home the
decorative portrait of the artist's mistress Dora Maar. It
eventually sold to an unidentified bidder for $4.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   A far later Picasso, ``The Painter and His Model,'' executed
from April 2 to 6, 1963, shows the artist armed with a palette and
brush sitting at his easel painting a nude model facing him. Six
bidders went for the painting, estimated at $1.5 million to $2
million. It was finally sold for $3.7 million to Franck Giraud,
Christie's head of 19th- and 20th-century art worldwide, bidding by
telephone for an unidentified client.
</P>
<P>
   Picasso's ``Bust of Woman Seated on a Chair,'' painted on Oct.
12, 1939, also brought a high price, though not as high as
Christie's had hoped. Another unidentified telephone bidder bought
it for $4.7 million, just over its low estimate of $4.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   (Final prices include Christie's commission, 17.5 percent of the
first $80,000 plus 10 percent of any amount above that. Estimates
do not reflect commissions.)
</P>
<P>
   One record was set on Tuesday night, for a drawing by Matisse.
``Study for `Pink Nude''' (1935) attracted a seven determined
bidders. A preparatory drawing for a painting in the Cone
Collection at the Baltimore Museum of Art, it was expected to bring
$1 million to $1.5 million but was finally bought for $2.7 million
by a gray-haired man glued to a cell phone, whom Christie's
described as a European dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Not everything did so well for Christie's. It had guaranteed a
Cy Twombly painting, ``Untitled'' (1968), one of the few works in
the artist's blackboard series executed on a white background. It
was estimated at $3 million to $4 million. Several people tried to
buy it, but only for the right price. It went to an unidentified
telephone bidder for $2.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Franz Kline's ``Untitled'' (1958), a 52-by-91-inch example of
the Abstract Expressionist painter's black-and-white compositions,
was estimated at $2.2 million to $3.2 million. No one lifted a
paddle, and Burge stopped trying at $1.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Also unsold was Andy Warhol's 1963 portrait of Elizabeth Taylor,
estimated at $1.8 million to $2.5 million; it never drew a bid
higher than $1.2 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
