<SLUG> BC-BIG-GAME-LOTTERY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUGE JACKPOT LURES CROWDS WITH $1 AND DREAMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Undaunted by the slim odds of Tuesday night's draw, people in
several states rushed to join a ticket-buying frenzy for the
largest potential jackpot in the history of lotteries: $350
million.
</P>
<P>
   The chances of hitting a winning ticket for the seven-state
lottery called The Big Game, which is sold in Georgia, Illinois,
Maryland, Massachusetts, Michigan, New Jersey and Virginia, were
one in 76 million, said Tandi Reddick, a spokeswoman for the
Georgia Lottery Corp.
</P>
<P>
   But that did not slow people intent on a chance at the jackpot.
In the Northeast, New Yorkers flocked over the bridges and through
the tunnels to New Jersey on Tuesday, to buy the $1 tickets in
anticipation of last night's drawing.
</P>
<P>
   Others relied on colleagues, friends and family members from New
Jersey to give them a shot at the prize. Justin M. Turner, a senior
associate at the accounting firm of PriceWaterhouseCoopers LLP, put
in $5 and joined an office pool of about 40 tickets, bought by a
colleague from New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your odds increase when you're in a pool, even though it is
still about a zillion to one that we will pick the right numbers,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The drawing took place on Tuesday night at 11 p.m. at the WSB-TV
studios in Atlanta; the winning numbers were 1, 2, 12, 33, 37 and
Big Ball 4. No announcement of any possible winners was expected to
be made until 6 o'clock Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The total jackpot, going to just one person, would pay, after
taxes, either $8.9 million a year for 26 years, or a lump sum of
$114 million.
</P>
<P>
   The enormity of these numbers drew a steady stream of ticket
buyers at a Krauszer's Food Store in West Orange, N.J., on Tuesday.
The buyers said that the prospect of winning, while remote, was too
remarkable to pass up.
</P>
<P>
   And even if they were underwhelmed by their own prospects, hope
sprang eternal for their relatives and friends across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Foster, a computer consultant from West Orange, was there
on Tuesday buying tickets for himself and his brother in Florida _
60 in total.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night's prize had been growing since March 3, when one
winning ticket purchased in Massachusetts brought in a jackpot of
$18 million. Previously, the largest American jackpot was $295.7
million, drawn in a Powerball lottery by 13 machinists in
Westerville, Ohio, in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In raw numbers, only one jackpot worldwide has been larger than
the one drawn Tuesday. In December, a lottery in Spain called El
Gordo, or the Fat One, reached $1.2 billion. But that sum was
broken up into thousands of prizes, spreading the individual
winnings thinner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
