<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDDHA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HULL DECLARES STATEWIDE BUDDHA DAY  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY EDYTHE JENSEN  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - The Bible is out and Buddha is in when it comes to
Gov. Jane Hull's proclamation preferences.
</P>
<P>
   Hull, who last year vowed never to proclaim another statewide
``Bible Week'' because she didn't want to offend any religious
group, signed a proclamation May 3 ``to commemorate the birth of
Sakyamuni Buddha.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor was unavailable Tuesday, but spokeswoman Francie
Noyes said the Buddha birthday proclamation differs from Bible
Week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This proclamation endorses the ideas of tolerance and
liberty,'' she said. ``The idea it promotes is one of religious
freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull and Gilbert Mayor Cynthia Dunham are the only state
political leaders to honor the founder of Buddhism, who was born in
Nepal 2,540 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Dunham recognized May 17 as Buddha's birthday during
the Town Council meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Eisenberg, director of the Arizona Civil Liberties
Union, had asked to speak at the meeting, but the mayor did not
acknowledge her before making the proclamation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the Arizona branch of the American Civil Liberties
Union sued Hull and Dunham for their Bible Week proclamations.
</P>
<P>
   Hull rescinded her Bible Week because of the suit. Dunham,
backed by lawyers from Pat Robertson's American Center for Law and
Justice, fought for hers.
</P>
<P>
   In September, U.S. District Judge Roslyn Silver dismissed the
ACLU's suit on grounds the Gilbert residents named as plaintiffs
didn't prove they were damaged.
</P>
<P>
   She did not rule on the proclamation's constitutionality, and
the ACLU has asked her to reconsider the dismissal. Silver has not
yet ruled, and Dunham proclaimed Bible Week last year.
</P>
<P>
   Eisenberg said she is to meet with the organization's legal
committee Wednesday to determine what action, if any, it will take
on the Buddha proclamation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ACLU fights for the free exercise of religion,'' she said.
``But government should not promote or endorse religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisenberg earlier said she was surprised to learn Hull issued a
Buddha proclama tion ``because it is inconsistent with her stated
intent not to offend anyone with religious proclamations.''
</P>
<P>
   Rev. Terry Kennard-Dhamapala of Chandler made the requests and
was notified of Hull's proclamation Tuesday. The Bible Week issue
inspired him to make his Buddha birthday requests.
</P>
<P>
   But Dunham insists her proclamations for the Bible and Buddha
are cultural and historical, not religious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bible Week isn't about religion,'' she said. ``It's about
diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull signed the proclamation just as Kennard-Dhamapala submitted
it, but Dunham cut the following: ``Religion is most free when it
is observed voluntarily at private initiative uncontaminated by
government interference and unconstrained by majority
preference.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
