<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 00:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0623 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-GOLDWATER-AZR &LR;      05-10 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDWATER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI HAD FILES ON GOLDWA
 TER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 BY CAROL SOWERS 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - The late Arizona Sen. Barry Goldwater, creator of
modern conservatism, was once thought to be too liberal by the FBI,
in part because he was backed by ``a large percentage of Negroes''
during his Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The files, which were published Monday by APBnews.com, a
Web-based news service, also show that FBI Director J. Edgar
Hoover's G-men linked Goldwater to a mob ster and disclosed that
Goldwater had been the target of 20 threats, one of which forced
him to detour his plane during his 1964 GOP presiden tial campaign.
</P>
<P>
   During Hoover's watch, the FBI was known for launching
investigations into political leaders and Black organizations, and
for its exhaustive search for Communists and mob figures.
</P>
<P>
   Goldwater fell into that net, even though he was ``as straight
as a string,'' said John Rhodes, a former Arizona congressman who
served alongside the senator during more than 30 years in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes, 83, said Tuesday that he was shocked to learn that the
FBI kept files on Goldwater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of any reason why they would,'' Rhodes said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the FBI released only a portion of its files on the
senator, the documents reveal that the agency doggedly pursued
Goldwater, known as ``Mr. Conservative,'' during much of his
political career.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the senator defended Hoo ver and his investigations,
and the two were friends.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps one of the most startling revelations in the 1,364 pages
ob tained by APBnews.com under the federal Freedom of Information
Act is the first entry, dated Feb. 3, 1953.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI document says that Gold water, Arizona's newly elected
sena tor, had been mentioned several times during a meeting of the
Pro gressive Party in Phoenix in Novem ber 1952, the year he was
elected to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Party members, the FBI said, were talking about ``the manner in
which the Progressive Party might influence Senator-elect Goldwater
and cause him to support the program and aspirations of the
Progressive Party, since he was supported by a large percentage of
Negroes in the Phoenix area.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes laughed aloud at the entry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe it,'' he said. ``I think they (the FBI) were a
little out of line worried about anyone being in the Progressive
Party.''
</P>
<P>
   The Feb. 3 entry also includes a letter from Hoover to Goldwater
indicating that the senator had re quested a look at his own FBI
files.
</P>
<P>
   But Hoover, who wouldn't be bound by the federal Freedom of
Informa tion Act until 1966, refused to give him the files.
</P>
<P>
   In a short note to Goldwater, Hoover said the ``files of this
bureau are maintained as confidential and avail able for official
use only.''
</P>
<P>
   Well into Goldwater's second Senate term, the FBI issued a
curious memorandum on the square-jawed senator.
</P>
<P>
   In the March 4, 1959, memo, the FBI connected Goldwater to
Phoenix racketeer Willie Bioff, who died in a car bombing in 1955,
and at the same time thanked Goldwater for supporting the agency on
the Senate floor five years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Agents said Goldwater, who left the Senate in 1986 and died in
1998 at age 89, had once sought a presiden tial pardon for Bioff,
but made no other reference to their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes remembers Bioff ``as a Las Vegas gambling type'' and said
Goldwater ``had nothing to do with him officially.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1959 memo also praised Gold water for denouncing a magazine
article criticizing the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   The documents also detail 20 threats against Goldwater during
his unsuc cessful White House bid in 1964. Hoover wrote a July 1964
memo asking his agents to carefully list the threats so agents
wouldn't be con fused about which were under inves tigation.
</P>
<P>
   In a July 10, 1964, memo titled ``Threat To Assassinate Senator
Barry Goldwater,'' the FBI said an unidentified man in California
asked a woman whether she was ``as desperate about GOLDWATER as I
am, and wondered whether she knew of anyone else who felt as he
did.''
</P>
<P>
   That same day, while talking with another woman, the man said he
was going to assassinate Goldwater, the memo says.
</P>
<P>
   Just 11 days later, a man appeared at the FBI office in Phoenix,
calling Goldwater a ``buzzard, a ruthless individual who is a
fascist, Commu nist and one who would utterly destroy American
democracy if elected president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Agents escorted the man out of their office.
</P>
<P>
   Another threat in August 1964 forced the FBI to detour
Goldwater's plane from Washington National Airport to Dulles
International Air port, and two months later, a man was spotted
peering into Goldwater's home with binoculars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
