<HEADER>
A0630 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-ROADS-FOREST-SFCHRON(     05-10 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROADS-FOREST-SFCHRON(ANALYSIS) </SLUG>
  
 ANALYSIS: PLAN MARKS CHANGE IN FOREST SERVICE DIRECTION  &HT;     By GLEN MARTIN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although it appears to have satisfied no one completely, the
U.S. Forest Service's proposed new policy on road building in
protected areas marks a dramatic change in federal land policy.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, which was formally released Tuesday, offers a
``preferred alternative'' that would end road construction on 43
million of the 192 million acres of forests and grasslands
administered by the service, most of it in the West.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, the proposal changes the service's guiding mandate
from a ``multiple use'' approach emphasizing recreation, grazing,
mining and logging to one of forest preservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impressive that the administration and the forest service
have changed from viewing forests as a source for (timber, minerals
and livestock feed) to considering them intrinsically important in
their own right,'' said Warren Alford, a conservation organizer
specializing in forestry issues for the Sierra Club.
</P>
<P>
   Multiple-use advocates viewed the new plan with suspicion,
warning that it raised the possibility of more stringent
regulations later on. Environmentalists generally applauded the
plan's broad goals but expressed concerns that the proposals didn't
offer sufficient protections.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would delay until 2004 plans to establish a
roadless policy for the Tongass National Forest in Alaska, the
world's largest tract of pristine temperate rain forest.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists also complained that the plan will allow
logging in roadless areas as long as no roads are constructed, and
that off-highway vehicles _ such as tractors and all-terrain
vehicles _ may be permitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Logging and off-road vehicles are real threats to our
remaining wildlands,'' said Alford, ``and the decision to defer the
Tongass isn't in keeping with the president's commitment to a bold
vision for preserving important public lands.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal will also allow roads for mining claims in roadless
areas, said forest service spokesman Matt Mathes, explaining that
the controversial federal mining law of 1872 still `'reigns supreme
in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   The law allows ``reasonable access'' on legitimate mining claims
for gold, silver, copper, gypsum and barite. The new proposal could
restrict exploration and development for oil, gas, coal, geothermal
sources, sand and pumice.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal will be open to public comment for 90 days. The
forest service is expected to make a final decision on a new policy
by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   If the preferred alternative is adopted, different areas of the
country will be affected to different degrees.
</P>
<P>
   For example, far more road construction plans would be halted in
Idaho, Montana and Nevada than in California, said Mathes.
</P>
<P>
   That's because California's regional forest service supervisors
decided several years ago to refrain from building roads in areas
that didn't have them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time there was talk about entering a roadless area in
California for (logging or other projects) it was very
controversial,'' said Mathes. ``As a consequence, the proposal
doesn't affect this state as much as it does some others in the
West.''
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists emphasize a simple proscription on roads
isn't enough to protect the Golden State's forests _ particularly
its diminished stands of old-growth timber.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still some serious loopholes,'' said Scott Black,
the director of the California Wild Heritage Campaign, a coalition
of about 80 environmental groups devoted to obtaining protections
for California wildlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, you can still log,'' said Black. ``You can log with
helicopters, or with cables and towers. The proposal also allows
for the construction of skid trails up to 700 feet long, so you can
ring a grove of old trees with trails, then take them all out by
tractor.''
</P>
<P>
   Black said several stands of ancient trees are threatened in
California because they can be logged by such alternative methods.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists aren't the only ones expressing
dissatisfaction with the plan. Groups favoring the forest service's
historic ``multiple use'' concept are also displeased.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the surface this looks fairly benign,'' said Don Amador, a
spokesman for the Blue Ribbon Coalition, a group that promotes
varied uses of public land, including recreation and logging.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when you look at the Clinton land legacy generally _ his
planning directives, his recent creation of several national
monuments _ we think this could just be a precursor for more
restrictive policies later on,'' Amador said.
</P>
<P>
   Amador said the forest service promises meaningful public
dialogue before a final policy is adopted.
</P>
<P>
   ``But given the administration's record, we aren't (convinced)
there will be legitimate public input at the local level,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Amador said he has particular concerns about California in
regard to the new proposal. He said the amount of national forest
land in California available for multiple use almost precisely
matches the area designated to remain roadless under the new plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a coincidence that makes me nervous,'' he said, fearing
that all California forest land may be made off limits to
commercial and recreational use.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 0103EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000510.0010 </DOCNO>
