<SLUG> BC-MOON-A5 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 6-48-1 ELECTRA PIC WRITETHRU FOR 5S   ,13p9  By Steve Rubenstein
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Chronicle Staff Writer
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR; r &LR; t wrapper  &LR; i A Houston company is selling tickets to the moon
for $12,500, but you have to be dead first.
</P>
<P>
   The Celestis company is now booking reservations for its next
lunar voyage, scheduled for early next year. Space is available,
providing you can fit into a vial the size of a lipstick container.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the fourth flight for the company that, since 1997,
has been sending the cremated ashes of its customers on rockets
into space. Previous trips _ or ``missions,'' as the company calls
them _ have carried the ashes of Star Trek creator Gene Roddenberry
and drug guru Timothy Leary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to open the space frontier for everyone,'' said
Charlie Chafer, co-founder of Celestis. ``Baby Boomers want to do
things a little differently.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has announced exciting plans for anyone planning to
be dead by next year. Not only will there be a second mission to
the moon, but another ship full of ashes will be dispatched into
deep space, on a flight that could last until the end of time. That
one costs $12,500, too.
</P>
<P>
   The ashes are carried aboard commercial rockets launched from
Vandenberg Air Force Base in Southern California. Each rocket can
carry 200 vials containing what the company calls a ``symbolic
portion` of a customer's ashes, about 1 percent of the amount from
a typical cremation. Remaining remains remain cq all 3 &LR;  remains  &LR; on
Earth.
</P>
<P>
   On its Web site (www.celestis. com) the company called $12,500
space rides for dead people ``remarkably affordable ... when
compared to the cost of an average funeral.'' Trips into Earth
orbit are even cheaper, at only $5,300.
</P>
<P>
   Payments may be made on the installment plan.
</P>
<P>
   Customers who choose the cheaper flight, into Earth orbit, do
not get to stay in space forever. Eventually, the orbit of the
Celestis ``memorial satellite'' decays, and the craft reenters the
atmosphere and ``vaporizes like a shooting star,'' the company said
_ meaning that the customer gets to be burned up twice.
</P>
<P>
   The lunar flights end with a crash landing on the moon. The
company calls it an
</P>
<P>
   ``impact.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened to planetary geologist Eugene Shoemaker,
whose ashes were aboard the Lunar Prospector spacecraft when it
crashed near the south pole of the moon in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of MOONBURI (81725 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The company says its clients have included scientists, truck
drivers, teachers, celebrities and kids. NASA lunar geologist
Mareta West, who helped pick the Sea of Tranquility landing site
for Apollo 11 in 1969, has a confirmed reservation for the next
moon flight. She died in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   If the launch malfunctions, the company said, ``refunds are
available'' _ although how the customer would be able to spend it
was unclear.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of MOONBURI (81725 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
