<HEADER>
A0637 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v PM-BUDGET-NYT     05-10 1691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For WEDNESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, May 10.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-IRAN-MISSILES (St. Petersburg, Russia) _ As concerns
mount in the United States and Israel that Iran's secretive missile
and nuclear weapons programs could pose new threats in the region,
the case of Yuri Savelyev, a leading Russian missile scientist who
persisted in his efforts to aid the Iranians in the face of
official sanction, illustrates the behind-the-scenes cooperation
between the Russian and U.S. governments to stem the flow of
missile technologies to Iran. But at the same time, it also reveals
the deep-seated resistance within the Russian establishment against
abandoning Russia's strategic role in cultivating clients and
contracts for transferring military technology. By Patrick E.
Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRIA-EU (Vienna, Austria) _ At least six of the 15 members of
the European Union have expressed a readiness to work toward
suspending sanctions imposed on Austria, raising hopes here that
the measures may be lifted within the next few months. Austrian
officials identified the countries as Spain, Italy, Ireland,
Greece, Finland and Denmark. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-ABACHA (Geneva, Switzerland) _ Authorities pursuing what
Nigeria says is billions of dollars looted from the country during
the rule of the late strongman Sani Abacha say they have found $630
million in Luxembourg bank accounts connected with his sons. By
Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-ARMENIANS (Elazig, Turkey) _ Groves of mulberry trees at
lakeside resorts are about all that remain from the days when this
region was a center of Armenian life. Here in eastern Turkey, the
passage of several generations has not been enough to wipe the
killings of 1915 from memory. To most Turks the events of 1915 seem
distant, but in the Armenian consciousness they are a vivid and
constant presence. Awareness of what is simply called ``the
genocide'' is acute in Armenian communities around the world. By
Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   PALESTINIAN-ANTHEM (Bethlehem, West Bank) _ With scores of
pinstriped businessmen milling about the hotel ballroom, it looked
like any other shareholders meeting. But when the meeting was
called to order, the first piece of business was a song. A sheet of
lyrics in Arabic was distributed for the few who did not already
know the words. Everyone rose, and with swelling emotion sang every
verse of ``My Homeland,'' the unofficial Palestinian national
anthem. By William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MONT-ASBESTOS (Libby, Mont.) _ Libby, Mont., is reeling from the
medical, psychological and financial consequences of a 67-year-old
mining operation, which once provided desperately needed
high-paying jobs here in the vast stretches of northwest Montana.
Although W.R. Grace shut it down in 1990, the mine is being blamed
for scores of cases of respiratory illness and death from exposure
to the tremolite. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Locator map
has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   REAGAN-COLDWAR (Eureka, Ill.) _ Ever Since Ronald Reagan
graduated from college here, legends about him have swirled around
the tiny campus and town. Now, a peace garden will be dedicated
here in his honor, marking the first ever Cold War-era memorial,
which includes a bust of Reagan and a piece of the Berlin Wall. By
Ellen Almer.
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION-COLUMN (Undated) _ Schools were blamed during the
economic dowturn of the 1980s, but somehow no one is giving them
credit for the propserityy of the past seven years or apologizing
for the criticism of the earlier period. By Edward Rothstein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-BATTLEGROUND (Undated) _ While courts struggle over the
recording industry's challenge to digital music-swapping, Ian
Clarke, a 23-year-old Irish programmer, is moving on to the next
battleground. He is finishing a program that he claims will make it
impossible to control the traffic in any kind of digital
information. His program, known as Freenet, is intended to make it
possible to acquire or exchange such material anonymously while
frustrating any attempt to remove the information from the Internet
or determine its source. Clarke is one of a group of programmers
who have set themselves on a collision course with the world's
intellectual property laws. They express the hope that the clash
over digital copyrights will produce a world in which all
information is freely shared. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT14) has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Investors who missed out on the
biggest-ever U.S. initial stock offering last month need not worry
or hurry. Shares of AT&AMP;T Wireless Group are back down at their
offering price and, judging by Tuesday's trading pattern, may not
be heading back up again soon. By Patrick McGeehan with Seth
Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   CIO-MANAGEMENT (Undated) _ In corporate America, an increasing
number of chief information officers _ the folks in charge of the
computers _ are amassing greater power as top bosses and company
boards realize how crucial technical expertise is in staying ahead
of the competition. A recent survey found that companies are
increasingly looking to a new generation of chief information
officers to be business strategists, and that these ``new'' CIOs
spend at least half their time outside the information-technology
department on efforts like developing and incubating new prospects
for electronic commerce. By Sana Siwolop.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphics have been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   DOTCOM-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Much has been made of the need for
dot-coms to generate awareness of their names among computer users.
Internet companies are spending billions of dollars online, in
print and on television to establish their brands. Now comes a
study that tries to identify the winners and losers in the big
branding struggle. By Allison Fass.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN-ANIMATOR (Dateline to come) _ On Alexander Petrov, the
Russian animator who won an Oscar for his 22-minute film ``The Old
Man and the Sea.'' By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   TATE-MODERN (London) _ What are people going to say in 100 years
about all these new museums for modern art that we're building? The
latest behemoth is the new Tate Modern, across the Thames from St.
Paul's. The queen inaugurates it Thursday and on Friday the public
arrives. The museum is of course a contribution to contemporary
art, not just here but throughout Europe, and a major achievement
by Nicholas Serota, the quietly subversive Tate director. To
Britons who for decades got admirable but tepid Ben Nicholson and
Barbara Hepworth when they went to the old Tate for modern art, the
new Tate must seem like a revolution. Dozens of living artists of
different generations and nationalities (Bruce Nauman, Matthew
Barney, Juan Munoz, James Coleman, Ilya Kabakov, Tatsuo Miyajima,
Rebecca Horn _ the list goes on) are mixed in among Brits. No doubt
the choices will cause grumbling because all choices do, but they
seem fine. And all this comes when London is suddenly vying with
New York as the mecca for contemporary art. A Critic's Notebook by
Michael Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   COLLABORATOR-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Collaborator: The
Trial and Execution of Robert Brassilach,'' by Alice Kaplan
(University of Chicago). Reviewed by Richard Bernstein.
</P>
