</P>
<P>
   RESTAURANT-SMELLS (Undated) _ A few weeks ago, I walked into Al
Forno in Providence, R.I., expecting a good meal. I got something
else. I left the lean, cool evening air and stepped into the
restaurant's foyer. It felt as if I had stepped into another world.
The earthy aromas of burning wood, yeast, roasting chicken and
herbs and smoke enveloped me. The restaurant smelled like food, and
I could not think of a single New York restaurant that smelled so
good. Or, for that matter, one that smelled like anything at all.
Over the past few decades, aroma, especially in better restaurants,
has slowly disappeared. And now as more ambitious restaurants open
by the minute, an aroma-free environment has become something of a
norm. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
