<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0639 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-TEACHERS-GOVERNOR-SFC     05-10 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHERS-GOVERNOR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN VICTORY FOR TEACHERS UNION, DAVIS RELENTS ON SCHOOL
SPENDING  LEVEL
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ A day after thousands of teachers rallied at the
Capitol, Gov. Gray Davis cut a deal Tuesday to bring California's
schools close to the national average in per-pupil spending in
return for the state's most powerful teachers union dropping an
initiative that would have forced him to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Davis agreed to give schools an additional $1.84 billion in
discretionary funding, which he said equals $328 more per pupil.
</P>
<P>
   That would bring California's spending on each student to $6,353
for the next fiscal year, according to Davis' figures. The most
recent available national average is $6,638 for 1997-98, according
to the National Education Association.
</P>
<P>
   Counting the money pledged Tuesday, public schools will receive
$3.6 billion more than they did last year, and Davis said there
will be even more when he announces his revised budget later in the
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the end of it,'' Davis told reporters. ``That is
just the portion we're talking about today. There will be more
proposals later in the week which will take the number up higher.''
</P>
<P>
   After Davis makes his revised budget numbers public, he and the
Legislature will begin the process of negotiating on all of the
spending. By June 15, the Legislature is required by law to pass a
budget for the fiscal year that starts July 1, but last year was
the first in several years in which that deadline was met.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said the money will cover cost-of-living adjustments that
were not paid to California schools during times of budget deficits
in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though our economy is booming, teachers are still
suffering from the recessionary cutbacks of the early 1990s,''
Davis said in a statement released Tuesday afternoon after hours of
closed-door meetings with the president of the California Teachers
Association and the Democratic leaders of the Assembly and Senate.
``Today's proposal repays California's debt in full.''
</P>
<P>
   The teachers association, one of Davis' biggest supporters when
he ran for governor, was also hoping to avoid spending millions on
the ballot initiative, especially because Davis has said he would
oppose the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the group will use its political muscle to try to
defeat another measure already on the November ballot that would
allow parents to use public money to send their children to private
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``The political climate has changed,'' said teachers union vice
president Barbara Kerr. ``We seem to be headed in the right
direction with the Legislature, and we want to be focused on
defeating the voucher initiative.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerr said the commitment brings California much closer to the
national average.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only are we significantly closer, but school districts
will know that the money will be there next year, so they can do
long-range planning,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Since education spending in California reverted to state control
after Proposition 13, per-pupil expenditures have crept up at a far
slower pace than elsewhere in the nation, coming to a virtual
standstill in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   While other states, like New York and New Jersey were pushing
their per-pupil dollars beyond the $10,000 mark, California's
hovered at about half that amount. It was only last year that
per-pupil spending in California began to rise.
</P>
<P>
   The $1.84 billion is the amount schools lost from 1991 to 1994,
when no cost-of-living adjustments were made on school spending.
Local school districts are owed $1.79 billion and county offices of
education $48 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic leadership in the Legislature helped broker the
deal, arguing that the time was right to put forth the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going to have this initiative on the ballot that would
have been counterproductive, shall we say. And now we're not,''
said state Senate President Pro Tem John Burton, D-San Francisco.
``But the important deal is more money for school districts to do
their business. It could mean new football jerseys, a kick in
starting-teacher salaries, music programs. Whatever a district
feels is important to their kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement avoids a nasty fight over the union's proposed
initiative, a fight that both sides could live without.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is extremely good news,'' said Kevin Gordon, a spokesman
for the California Association of School Business Officials. ``It
was going to be a very uncomfortable fall campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Monday, 8,000 teachers poured into Sacramento to show their
support for the union-sponsored initiative and to demand more
discretionary funding.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate budget approved this week gave school districts $1
billion in discretionary money. Davis' announcement increases that
to $1.84 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That is a big jump in discretionary funding over last year, when
schools received a little less than $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will provide local districts an opportunity to establish
their own spending priorities,'' said Sen. Jack O'Connell, D-San
Luis Obispo. ``Many of the reductions imposed on districts in the
past can now be restored _ teacher salaries could see a potentially
significant increase. Also, what works for rural districts, what
they need to spend money on, is often very different from a major
urban district.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
