<HEADER>
A0640 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     05-10 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BIG MITT TOO CLOSE FOR MCGWIRE  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If Mark McGwire can't hit a home run into the
giant glove atop the left-field bleachers at the Giants' new
ballpark, I say the guy is a fraud. A wimp. A palooka.
</P>
<P>
   The glove is 501 feet from home plate. McGwire is king of the
tape-measure home run; he should be wearing that glove out.
Especially with the new, improved major-league ball, 20 percent
livelier than last year's model.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's lords deny they juice up the ball, but they can't
explain this year's epidemic of homers.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's the cows. Ball covers are made of cowhide, and it
could be that due to the hormones we use to fatten cows, their hide
is thicker and springier. Maybe that's what is meant by ``and the
cow jumped over the moon.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, playing their fans for suckers, are offering $1
million to some fan if a Giants' player hits a homer into the big
glove. Barry Bonds? He ain't got 500-foot pop, especially not to
the opposite field.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the big-mitt shot will happen next season, when the
baseball lords juice up the ball another 20 percent and Dusty Baker
makes his comeback as a player.
</P>
<P>
   NOW THAT the Board of Supervisors has voted to outlaw
discrimination against large people, does that mean all those dorky
losers have to peel off their ``No fat chicks'' bumper stickers?
</P>
<P>
   STRANGE THOUGHTS lurk in the minds of readers.
</P>
<P>
   The recent scientific scoop here _ that rats and cockroaches who
eat baking soda, unable to burp, explode _ has people thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you suppose baking soda would have the same effect on
newspaper executives and politicians?'' ponders Dennis Green.
``Let's find out.''
</P>
<P>
   Save your baking soda, Dennis. Scientific studies show that
politicians and newspaper execs are incredibly efficient at
expelling hot gas.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Cameron has an idea for luring kids away from violent video
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember Ant Farm, which came with live ants and a food
supply?'' Cameron asks. ``How about Roach Farm, complete with live
cockroaches and baking soda. For $1,000 in unmarked bills, I'll let
you and the mayor in on the IPO.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Ron, you want to engage in day-trading of cockroachbellies
with the old horse-trader?
</P>
<P>
   A LEGEND has checked out.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Winters, who presided behind the bar at Capp's Corner in
North Beach for the past 27 years, sat down at the bar last
Thursday, had a heart attack and was dead before he hit the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Sam, a star lineman at USF in the Matson-Marchetti-St. Clair
glory days, was the very model of the gruff bartender with the
heart of gold. He never asked for a favor but granted a million. He
wasn't much on mixing exotic drinks, and his prices, for the
regulars, got stuck somewhere in the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place was like his front room,'' says Capp's owner Tom
Ginella.
</P>
<P>
   On weekend mornings, Sam's loyal legion of NBRs (North Beach
Regulars) would be waiting at the door when he opened at 6. On
Sundays they'd go to church and come back for Sam's free
picnic-type buffet.
</P>
<P>
   Ginella says the free lunches will continue. Wouldn't want to
get the big guy sore.
</P>
<P>
   WHY YOU SHOULD always have an English teacher proofread your
school buses:
</P>
<P>
   In Pittsburg, Pat Wille pulled up to a traffic light behind a
Pittsburg Unified School District bus with large letters painted on
the back: ``Stop when red light flash.''
</P>
<P>
   IN TRANSACTIONS, the Sporting Green's fine-print capsulization
of the day's trades and injuries, Jim Sullivan spotted this: ``NBA
Entertainment named Cliff Kaplan senior vice president, global
media programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Crows Sullivan, ``I'm stoked, because I picked Kaplan in my
sports administration fantasy league.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm down. I drafted the Giants' exec who said, ``Hey, the plans
for this new ballpark have way too many urinals.''
</P>
<P>
   THE GENTRIFICATION of the city continues, and Lotta Dotz wonders
if citizens don't deserve a new newspaper _ The San Francisco
Monocle.
</P>
<P>
   You know, a paper fine-tuned to the refined sensibilities of the
haves. The paper would be placed on your ``Welcome, depending'' mat
each a.m. by a correctly liveried cyclist on a titanium Merlin.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper would be a tough project to get off the ground,
but maybe with a JOA with the devil ...
</P>
<P>
   REMEMBER Baba Ram Dass, the guru kind of guy who introduced
Timothy Leary to LSD and had many celebrated followers, including
the Beatles?
</P>
<P>
   Well, Baba rented a house in Tiburon from Joe Rinehart. A friend
asked Joe, ``Have you talked with Ram Dass?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah,'' Joe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did he give you words of wisdom?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What did he say?''
</P>
<P>
   ``He said the toilet's broken.''
</P>
<P>
   SO NOW IT'S brainwashing if Elian decides he wants to stay with
his dad and return to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Bob Smith (R-N.H.) says the kid is being kept in a
``concentration camp'' and hints that Elian is being drugged so
that he'll go along with the commie propaganda program.
</P>
<P>
   Why is it that Republicans always get the funny lines?
</P>
<P>
   There's no question Elian would have better toys, now and as an
adult, if he stayed in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes, maybe, blood is thicker than Big Wheels.
</P>
</TEXT>
