<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0645 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-ROCKIES-HN     05-10 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-ROCKIES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
A five-run deficit after three innings would be akin to getting
sentenced to a loss at most ballparks. But at Enron Field, parole
is just around the corner.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A poor outing by Scott Elarton was pardoned by a relentless
offensive attack led by Craig Biggio and Ken Caminiti, who powered
the Astros to a 13-8 come-from-behind victory over the Colorado
Rockies on Tuesday night before a crowd of 32,130, a season low for
the second day in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Biggio and Caminiti had two hits and four RBIs apiece, and four
Astros relievers held the Rockies to a run on two hits in 4 innings
as the Astros snapped a three-game losing streak at Enron Field,
where they are 4-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hitters' game tonight,'' said Astros manager Larry
Dierker, whose team outhit the Rockies 11-10. ``But it was also a
pitchers' game in the sense that we kept hitting and they didn't.
We haven't had too many wins here, so we'll take one any way we can
get it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros trailed by six runs after 4{ innings, setting the
stage for their largest comeback of the season. They scored five
runs in the bottom of the fifth, highlighted by Caminiti's
Enron-aided grand slam, and took the lead with a four-run sixth
inning highlighted by Biggio's three-run triple.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not out of any game at any time in this ballpark,''
Caminiti said. ``It was good to see us put up a couple of big
innings. The way things have been going for us, we need some
positive things to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Lefthanded reliever Yorkis Perez pitched a perfect sixth inning
to qualify for his second victory, and Mike Maddux and Billy Wagner
also delivered scoreless work out of the Astros' bullpen. The only
blemish on the bullpen's performance was Todd Helton's
eighth-inning solo homer off Doug Henry.
</P>
<P>
   Just as impressive as the bullpen's solid work was the tenacity
of the Astros' offense, which kept piling on runs even after the
victory appeared secure. In fact, their three-run eighth inning
robbed Wagner of a save opportunity, which he'll gladly sacrifice
in any victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept getting after it,'' said Astros catcher Mitch
Meluskey, who replaced Tony Eusebio in the bottom of the sixth
inning. ``We'd better start doing that (piling on the runs) because
that's what other teams have been doing to us in this ballpark. We
need to play to win all the way to the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Eusebio was taken to Methodist Hospital after he was hit on the
left elbow by a pitch from Rockies reliever Julian Tavarez. X-rays
were negative, and Eusebio's status will be evaluated daily.
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing the Astros had to fret about Tuesday was
the pitching of Elarton, who allowed seven runs on eight hits in 4
innings, matching his shortest outing of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elarton's outing wasn't good,'' Dierker said. ``He didn't have
any kind of curveball, and his control of his fastball was shaky.''
</P>
<P>
   Elarton struck out the first batter he faced, Curtis Goodwin, on
three pitches but immediately started falling behind hitters and
paid the price. Mike Lansing doubled on a 3-1 pitch and scored on
Jeff Cirillo's two-run homer _ on a 2-0 pitch _ off the left-field
limestone. Cirillo has hit in a career-high 15 consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got behind hitters, threw the ball down the middle of the
plate, and they made me pay for it,'' Elarton said.
</P>
<P>
   Elarton settled down in the second and was coasting in the third
until the defense abandoned him. Larry Walker lifted a
harmless-looking two-out fly ball down the left-field line, and
three Astros _ left fielder Matt Mieske, shortstop Russ Johnson and
Caminiti, the third baseman _ converged on the ball. The ball
dropped among them and skipped into the seats for a ground-rule
double.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get better at catching pop flies,'' Dierker said.
``I've seen more pop flies drop this season than I did all of last
year. I'm not going to cast blame; I'm just going to say that
somebody should have caught that ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of resting in the dugout after what should have been the
third out, Elarton faced a challenge with Cirillo due to bat. He
walked Cirillo and served up a three-run homer to Todd Helton, who
leads the National League with 38 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros finally joined the scoring in the fourth inning when
Roger Cedeno scooted home from third on a Scott Karl breaking ball
that Rockies catcher Brent Mayne was unable to handle. But Colorado
responded with two more runs in the fifth to go up 7-1.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti's 1,000th hit in an Astros uniform was a memorable one.
Although the fifth-inning fly probably would have been an out in
most ballparks, at Enron Field it was good enough for the sixth
grand slam of his career.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros got another run in the inning on Biggio's
fielder's-choice grounder to pull within 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't hit it far, but it was high,'' Caminiti said of his
grand slam. ``Because it's so short out there, I knew it had a
chance. I was blowing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Dierker: ``That was definitely an Enron slam.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros took the lead in a four-run sixth inning that
featured Biggio's three-run triple and an RBI single by Richard
Hidalgo. Prior to Tuesday, Biggio was hitting .188 with just one
RBI and one extra-base hit in his previous 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got big hits all night,'' Dierker said, ``and that was good
to see.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
