<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: PERSEVERING IN SPITE OF PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Thirty years and two days after Willis Reed hobbled out
of the Madison Square Garden tunnel and set a New York standard for
big-game heroism, there are examples everywhere that the
contemporary professional basketball player has been living up to
the legend quite well.
</P>
<P>
   Here at the American Airlines Arena on Tuesday night, Patrick
Ewing discarded his ice packs again and continued his mission to
become a limping champion in his own right, while Tim Hardaway
taped up his badly sprained left foot and returned to his pursuit
of local Willis-hood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who in this league doesn't play with any pains or nicks?''
Ewing said before the Knicks evened their war of halfcourt
attrition with a wildly uneven 82-76 victory over the Heat in Game
2 of the Eastern Conference semifinal, a game so unsightly you
wondered if everyone, including the refs, was in need of medical
attention.
</P>
<P>
   This has been the postseason of playing with pain, for muscular
forwards and frail guards, aging warriors and young bucks,
franchise players and scrappy vets. They didn't put up with 82
regular-season games and all those insufferable practices to let
their bodies deprive them of rich post-season desserts.
</P>
<P>
   So Grant Hill tried to play on a broken ankle against Miami in
the first round. Karl Malone shook off a recent sprain after
scrambling off the bench when a teammate dove into it. Jason Kidd
rushed back from what was supposed to be a season-ending broken
ankle. Allen Iverson has played on with a medical chart that is
longer than him. His Philadelphia backcourt partner, Eric Snow,
pushed himself Monday night until the dam broke.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was bawling, right?'' Chris Childs said, posing as a
question what he already knew because he would have preferred for
the camera to have lied.
</P>
<P>
   Childs had only seen Snow on the bench during Indiana's victory,
then tuned out before the Turner Network cameras later found Snow
still in tears, and out for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry, really sorry, to hear that,'' Childs said. ``I know
him, just from being cordial around the league. Allen's the best
player on that team but he would be the first to tell you that
Eric's their leader. It's a shame. He played. He tried.''
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Miller ran Snow until his injured foot gave out. Tuesday
night, the Knicks had Charlie Ward attack Hardaway and Ward, of all
people, was their leading scorer for much of the game. On the
court, there is no sympathy, only matchups to be exploited.
</P>
<P>
   The players are paid handsomely, but their money is guaranteed
and they don't have to play when they are hurting and they all know
exactly what Hardaway is feeling when Ward or Childs turns him on
defense and lights what Hardaway said feels like a fire inside his
foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't understand what a high threshold of pain we have
to have to just get to this level,'' said Childs.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Van Gundy said, ``Some players don't like to be out there
when they can't play their best.'' Not Hardaway or Ewing. Between
visits to the acupuncturist for back spasms, Ewing has often looked
glacial in this series but there he was, hitting the biggest basket
of the game, lofting a sweet jumper over Alonzo Mourning in the
third quarter after Miami had surged to within 51-50. And there he
was again, putting back Latrell Sprewell's missed drive with a 1
minute 34 seconds left to snuff out one final Heat charge.
</P>
<P>
   As Ewing learned last spring, no doctor can guarantee that an
injury can't be made worse by playing. Hardaway, in a contract
year, said his father has told him, ``Do what you have to do but
don't be foolish and go out there and hurt yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   He's vowed to ``fight through the pain'' and he gave Pat Riley
another valiant 30 minutes and 13 points on Tuesday night. Hardaway
just doesn't have the mobility for dribble penetration, and Miami's
offense has no margin for error when Mourning is contained, as he
was on Tuesday night. Conversely, the Knicks won despite Sprewell
and Allan Houston shooting a combined 5 for 27. It's a long shot
that Miami can survive. Hardaway will probably have to settle for
an opponent's respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big men go up and back,'' Childs said. ``He's a guard, cutting
this way and that way. He wants to be out there.''
</P>
<P>
   This time of year, most of the players do, but they are
vulnerable, human. At a time when more and more fans have grown
tired of the corporate hype, and when premier games are as tough to
watch as last night's, that's not a bad marketing thought for a
sport under television-ratings siege.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 0141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
