<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-McCAIN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 EDITORIAL: McCAIN'S MEDICINE  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, May 10:
</P>
<P>
   For a defeated candidate in the Republican presidential race,
Sen. John McCain has not suffered from lack of attention. With his
high poll numbers, McCain might have made a credible third-party
candidate in November. On Tuesday, however, he took the prudent
course and endorsed Gov. George W. Bush, joking that he preferred
taking his medicine now rather than later. Clearly he figured that
he had a brighter future inside the GOP than as a spoiler outside
it. It was disappointing that Bush offered no concessions on
campaign reform or other issues in return for an endorsement he
really needed.
</P>
<P>
   There is a certain GOP ritual for defeated candidates to endorse
the nominees of their parties, but it often goes awry. In 1976 Gov.
Ronald Reagan of California gave such a tepid endorsement of
President Gerald Ford that Ford never fully recovered. Back in 1960
Richard Nixon, then the vice president, was so eager to win the
endorsement of Gov. Nelson Rockefeller of New York that he agreed
to a set of party principles, known as the Fifth Avenue compact,
that made him suspect among party conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   In approaching the meeting with McCain on Tuesday, Bush seemed
to have this history in mind. He made it clear that he wanted the
senator's endorsement, but did not want to seem to want it too
much. In their joint news conference the governor tried to stress
how much they had in common. But he did not look especially pleased
about McCain's vow to continue pressing his agenda. He may have
been wondering whether the senator would try to do that at the
convention in Philadelphia this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The continuing popularity of McCain can be seen in many surveys,
including a recent NBC/Wall Street Journal poll showing that 23
percent of the voters would prefer him over Bush or Vice President
Al Gore. The USA Today/CNN/Gallup poll shows him with higher
approval ratings than either man. The Bush campaign has always been
quick to assert that McCain got his biggest victories in states
where independents and Democrats could join with Republicans and
vote in the primary. But it is these independent-minded voters who
will determine the winner in November. It will not be easy for
either Bush or Gore, both wealthy political heirs, to attract
voters who are drawn to McCain's outsider appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, for his part, has been resistant to identifying with two
issues that seem intrinsic to McCain's appeal. One is campaign
finance reform, particularly the McCain-Feingold soft-money ban,
which Bush opposes. Another is McCain's opposition to a gigantic
tax cut that would use up the budget surplus. Bush probably feels
locked in on taxes, but he would be smart to adopt McCain's stand
on campaign finance reform. Otherwise he may find that McCain
voters are as hard to get as the senator's endorsement was.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 0150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000510.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0654 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-DEUTCH-NYT &LR;      05-10 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-DEUTCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: JOHN DEUTCH AND THE LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, May 10:
</P>
<P>
   If the director of central intelligence transfers highly
classified materials to insecure computers at his home, he may well
be violating the law, and his conduct requires an immediate and
full investigation. But when faced with just such actions by John
Deutch in late 1996, the CIA and the Justice Department badly
fumbled the case. They are now scrambling to make amends, with
Justice belatedly initiating a criminal investigation. But the
affair once again demonstrates that the agency cannot adequately
investigate itself and that Attorney General Janet Reno has
consistently failed to enforce the law against top Clinton
administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   Deutch was a demanding and effective leader of the CIA who did
much in his short tenure to address the agency's past abuses and
reform its practices. But enlightened leadership does not provide
immunity from the law, and Deutch's carelessness cried out for a
rigorous investigation by the FBI under the direction of a seasoned
prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it received cursory examination by the CIA and no
investigation by the FBI. Historically, the CIA has put more energy
into covering up mistakes and misconduct than investigating them.
Ironically, Deutch worked hard to change that culture. But when his
own behavior became an issue in December 1996 as he was preparing
to return to private life, some of the very aides he had recruited
to help reform the CIA may have tried to protect him. Nora Slatkin,
who served as executive director, and Michael O'Neil, who was the
agency's general counsel, failed to insist on a thorough
investigation and may have tried to impede examination of the case.
Both deny doing so, but their conduct was sharply criticized by the
agency's inspector general and a White House intelligence board.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA security staff, which never bothered to interview
Deutch, wrote an anemic report in 1997. By the time the agency got
around to notifying the Justice Department, the one-year time limit
for appointing an independent counsel had expired. In April 1999
Reno inexplicably decided not to pursue the matter, without
ordering an F.B.I. investigation. George Tenet, Deutch's deputy and
successor, removed his security clearances in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   It seems clear that Deutch received special treatment because he
was a top official, and that Reno gave him the benefit of the
doubt, just as she has done for others in the administration. For
an experienced prosecutor, she has an uncanny instinct for ignoring
or misreading the evidence and the law when top officials are
credibly accused of misconduct. Before the books are closed on this
case, the actions of Deutch and his former colleagues must be
carefully examined. If the evidence warrants prosecution, the high
positions they held should be no barrier. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 0154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000510.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0656 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-MARRIAGES-NYT &LR;      05-10 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MARRIAGES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THOROUGHLY MODERN MARRIAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, May 10:
</P>
<P>
   Despite their many differences, New York's Senate candidates,
Rudolph Giuliani and Hillary Rodham Clinton, hold at least one
belief in common. Both assert that there should be what Clinton
calls a ``zone of privacy'' around the personal lives of elected
officials and their families. Both, it seems, also have a talent
for stirring public curiosity about their inner lives and an
inclination to accuse the media of pursuing information for which
the public has no real appetite.
</P>
<P>
   What the public finally decides about this Gothic novel of an
election and these two fascinating, highly polarizing personalities
is the key question, of course. Assuming, as everyone hopes, that
Giuliani's health allows for a full campaign, the answer is seven
months away. Our guess is that in the interim the non-tabloid press
will respect the request for privacy from Giuliani and not go in
search of further information about him, his wife, Donna Hanover,
or his friend Judith Nathan. Notwithstanding the complaints of
President Clinton's defenders about shifting standards of privacy,
the mainstream press has never been quick to carry information
about politicians' personal conduct unless that information issued
from official sources or seemed related to officeholders'
fulfilling of their public obligations.
</P>
<P>
   But candidates cannot expect journalists, strategists or voters
to be brain-dead when it comes to analyzing the political impact of
the full public record. In the current U.S. Senate campaign, that
record includes the candidates' comments, in press conferences and
interviews, about their marriages and, in Giuliani's case, social
engagements that occurred in public view. In New York's chaotic
information environment, the record also includes paparazzi photos,
gossip columns and tabloid news, and this fact poses a special
challenge for journalists who are commenting on the campaign. Like
it or not, voters have a right to reach conclusions about a
candidate's judgment and temperament based on what they learn from
a variety of sources about the person's life. They also have a
right to commentary that sorts through what is central and what is
peripheral to the task of electing a leader.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, such judgments cannot ignore local history. This
state has the widest strike zone in American politics when it comes
to candidates' private lives and domestic arrangements. Gov. Nelson
Rockefeller's re-election in 1962 after a very public divorce
testifies to that fact. While Clinton's and Giuliani's stories are
very different, they may now be on something like an equal footing
in regard to drawing on that tradition of tolerance. Early polls
showed that Clinton had suffered among professional women for being
perceived as too tolerant of a misbehaving husband. But the issue
of marital balance may be neutralized, especially if the mayor is
perceived as the less sympathetic partner in his family
arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Also, no one knows how deeply the tradition of tolerance runs
among voters who identify themselves as cultural and religious
conservatives. Clinton has been anathema to many of them. Giuliani
could now face slippage in sectors of that coalition _ for example,
Catholics, Orthodox Jews, upstate independents _ where he had
expected an advantage. While a Daily News poll showed that 77
percent of those contacted viewed Giuliani's friendship with Nathan
as a private matter, 12 percent said they viewed him more
negatively. In a close election, fractional shifts can be decisive.
</P>
<P>
   If these factors seem to tip in Clinton's favor, it may be
simply a matter of her difficult news being out earlier. And
Hanover's statement on the steps of St. Patrick's Cathedral about
``decisions'' to come could portend additional headlines for
Giuliani. But the mayor, for his part, seems confident that the
Clintonian privacy zone will work in his favor, or else he would
not have used his daringly transparent description of Nathan as a
``very good friend.'' That ``very'' could become the most famous
adverb in a campaign that, if it keeps running at this pace, will
be remembered as a Rorschach test of contemporary New York
attitudes toward candidates, their private lives and their public
marriages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 0159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
