<DOCNO> NYT20000510.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0658 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-EMBASSY-ATTACK-RENO-N     05-10 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMBASSY-ATTACK-RENO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TO SEEK DEATH PENALTY IN EMBASSY ATTACKS, DEFENSE SAYS
</HEADLINE>
  By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - Attorney General Janet Reno has authorized federal
prosecutors in Manhattan to seek the death penalty against at least
one defendant in the bombings of two U.S. Embassies in East Africa
in 1998, according to defense lawyers in the broad terrorism
conspiracy case.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's decision, which has not been made public, sets the stage
for the first death penalty case in the United States involving an
act of international terrorism, lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant, Mohamed Rashed Daoud al-`Owhali, has been accused
of being a passenger in a truck that carried the bomb in the
explosion at the American Embassy in Nairobi, Kenya, on Aug. 7,
1998. That bombing, along with a nearly simultaneous explosion at
the embassy in Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, killed more than 200 people
and wounded more than 4,000.
</P>
<P>
   Al-`Owhali is one of three defendants in custody in New York who
are eligible for the death penalty in the bombings; no decision has
been made in the cases of the other two. All three have pleaded not
guilty.
</P>
<P>
   David I. Bruck, a lawyer for al-`Owhali, confirmed late Tuesday
that he had been told of Reno's decision, which he called
``folly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The government claims that this young man has already tried to
detonate himself into paradise,'' he said. ``Now it's offering to
do the job itself, providing him with a glorious death while the
world watches. Is this how to deter terrorism?''
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Smilon, a spokesman for U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White,
declined to comment on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have described al-`Owhali as a would-be suicide
bomber in the Nairobi blast. The government has charged that he
admitted to investigators that he tossed a dummy grenade at a
security guard seconds before the bomb was to go off, and that the
bombing was intended as a ``martyrdom operation in which he did not
expect to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, Bruck and another lawyer, Leonard F. Joy, told
Judge Leonard B. Sand of U.S. District Court in Manhattan that
their client had ordered them not to go to Washington for a recent
meeting with Reno's staff, where they had intended to argue against
the death penalty. The lawyers did not explain their client's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Reno must rule on all requests from federal prosecutors to seek
capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   The three men facing capital charges are to be tried later this
year with three others, who could face life in prison, for their
roles in the embassy bombings and in what prosecutors say was a
worldwide terrorism conspiracy to kill Americans abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities suspect that the conspiracy was masterminded by
the Saudi exile Osama bin Laden, who is believed to be living in
Afghanistan under the protection of the fundamentalist Taliban.
</P>
<P>
   Bruck, in his sharp criticism, said Reno's decision could
complicate the government's efforts to win other countries'
cooperation in returning bin Laden for trial because ``it implies
that the U.S. intends to execute bin Laden, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Since no Muslim country is likely to hand him over to be
killed,'' Bruck said, ``it may really mean that the U.S. has given
up on ever getting bin Laden, and has decided to content itself
with killing his foot soldiers instead.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruck added: ``In our new role as global executioner, we're
about to learn the hard way what Israel and England _ countries
facing much greater terrorist threats _ have long understood:
turning accused terrorists into martyrs only makes a bad situation
worse.''
</P>
<P>
   White, the U.S. attorney in Manhattan, recently sought Reno's
authorization for a death penalty case against a second of the
three defendants eligible for the death penalty, Khalfan Khamis
Mohamed, who has been accused of a role in the Tanzania explosion.
Reno has not ruled on that request.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the third defendant, Mohammed Saddiq Odeh, White
has not yet indicated whether she will seek the death penalty. But
death penalty experts who have followed the case say they
ultimately expect the government to seek the death penalty against
all three.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Bruck said he hoped Reno would reconsider her
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, in an unusual strategy, the defense lawyers for all
three of the defendants facing capital charges filed a 30-page
memorandum with Justice and State Department officials, arguing
that seeking the death penalty would harm this country's foreign
policy and damage its counterterrorism efforts.
</P>
<P>
   One lawyer in the broader terrorism case said that the death
penalty case against al-`Owhali has been limited by Reno to those
counts charging his participation in the Nairobi bombing, in which
more than 200 people were killed. Al-`Owhali was also indicted in
the bombing in Tanzania, although prosecutors have not offered
evidence publicly of his involvement in that attack.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 0206EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000510.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 02:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0660 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-SHAQ-LADN     05-10 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SHAQ-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SLAM DUNK FOR SHAQ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. - The date, time and place for Shaquille
O'Neal's coronation as the biggest, baddest, most dominant player
in the NBA was set Tuesday. When the moment at last arrived, he
embraced it not with the ferocity of a backboard-altering slam
dunk, but with the style and grace of his slickest spin move to the
hoop.
</P>
<P>
   It took eight seasons for O'Neal to evolve from a player with
great abilities into simply the greatest player on the floor. That
time has arrived, and the gap between O'Neal and the rest of the
league is so wide that he claimed Most Valuable Player with the
greatest mandate in history - 120 of 121 possible first-place
votes.
</P>
<P>
   But the game's most physically imposing individual accepted the
mantle with dignity, humility, gratitude - and, of course, his own
unique sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``From this day on,'' O'Neal said, ``I would like to be known as
`The Big Aristotle.' Because it was Aristotle that said,
`Excellence is not a singular act, but a habit. You are what you
repeatedly do.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And this year I just wanted to come out and be very consistent
and dominate and play hard.''
</P>
<P>
   He did, repeatedly and habitually, in true Aristotelian manner.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal outpaced the league in scoring average (29.7 points) and
field-goal percentage (.574). He was the first player since Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar in 1976-77 to finish among the top three in scoring,
rebounding, field-goal percentage and blocked shots.
</P>
<P>
   It was a season for the record books, capped by a vote for the
record books. With 99.2 percent of the first-place votes, O'Neal
eclipsed the 96.5 percent Michael Jordan garnered in 1995-96, when
he received 109 of 113.
</P>
<P>
   The award was a slam dunk long ago, leaving only the question of
whether O'Neal would become the first to win the media vote
unanimously.
</P>
<P>
   That distinction was lost when Fred Hickman of CNN gave his
first-place vote to Philadelphia's Allen Iverson (and listed O'Neal
second).
</P>
<P>
   At one time, such snubs would elicit a snarl from O'Neal. But at
age 28, he has evolved off the court as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to thank you all for voting for me,'' he said,
``and the one guy who didn't vote (for me), thank you too. I
appreciate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, O'Neal seemed humbled by his achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was kind of hard to believe, that I had the highest
percentage, because I've always felt that Michael Jordan and guys
like Magic (Johnson) and Kareem and Wilt (Chamberlain) were the
greatest players in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   For O'Neal to join that roster, he had to complete his game.
That was a challenge put forth immediately by coach Phil Jackson,
O'Neal's hand-picked mentor, when he was hired last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Shaquille's always been an indomitable kind of
force,'' Jackson said. ``He's been a dominator inside as a scorer
in this league, averaging from 27 to 30 points a game over a long
period of time, and everybody knew he could score, but yet the
whole aspect of his game - passing, rebounding, assists, blocked
shots, turnovers - all those things were very important for a
basketball team at the other end. And I think when Shaquille took
those as indicators of his ability to work within the team and the
system, I think that was really what was another growth step for
him, and made this an MVP season. Scoring's not the only thing that
attracts people, but defense and domination in there is the thing
that's really important.''
</P>
<P>
   MVP was a goal mentioned more often by teammates and friends
than O'Neal himself, but upon accepting the Maurice Podoloff Trophy
for the first time, he said ``I'm happy.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal - in his own words ``knick-knack injury free'' for the
first full season since signing with the Lakers in 1996 - put good
health, great conditioning and Jackson's tutelage to work. His
rebounding average (13.6) and blocked-shots average (3.03) were the
best since his rookie year in 1992-93. His assists average (3.8)
was a career high, and second on the Lakers only to Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal and Bryant (who received a fourth-place MVP vote) also
smoothed over some well-publicized tensions to become arguably the
best one-two punch in the league. Their combined talents led the
Lakers to a 67-15 record, best in the league and second best in
franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Lakers are prohibitive favorites to win the
championship. They hold a 1-0 lead in their conference semifinals
series against the Phoenix Suns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early in the season, when I was out with a broken hand, he
stepped up and played at a high level every night,'' Bryant said.
``I knew then he was going to be MVP. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``It's his consistency. Night in, night out, he performs at a
higher level than anybody else in the league. That's why he's the
MVP.''
</P>
<P>
   How consistent? O'Neal missed just two games due to injury, one
due to suspension and averaged a career-high 40 minutes in the
other 79 games. He got 10 or more rebounds in all but 15 games,
scored at least 20 points in all but seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Showing he can cure any ailment, O'Neal even appeared to heal
his Achilles' heel - the free throw. After the All-Star break, he
made 58.5 percent of his foul shots.
</P>
<P>
   None of this was surprising to the man who lured O'Neal from
Orlando to O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, this gentleman works very, very hard at this
game,'' said Lakers executive Jerry West, who predicted the MVP
season in October. ``I'm not a person who makes idle predictions,
but I saw something at training camp from the first day of training
camp and I made a prediction,which I'm happy I made. ... Laker fans
have an awful lot to look forward to in future years here.
Shaquille, I can't tell you how proud I am of you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The ultimate team award is to win an NBA championship,'' West
said, ``but the ultimate individual award is to win this award,
because truly this was the best player in the NBA this year, by an
awesome amount.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal honored his parents and family and said his father, Sgt.
Phil Harrison, cried when he told him the news. He also thanked
West, owner Jerry Buss, Jackson and of course, his teammates - who
were happy to return praise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the only person that can stop Shaquille O'Neal is
Shaquille O'Neal,'' said Glen Rice. ``And thus far that hasn't
happened. And he's just going to continue to keep running through
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Charting O'Neal's development from great player to MVP,
teammates always came back to one word: desire.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has that desire to be good. And he wants to be the best
player there,'' said Ron Harper, who once played alongside
five-time MVP Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   What does the MVP award mean for the Lakers? ``That you better
step up and win a championship is what that means,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   That's next on O'Neal's menu.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like Mr. West said, the ultimate goal is to win a
championship,'' O'Neal said. ``And I feel real good about my team.
As a matter of fact, this is the best team I've ever played on. I
like our chances. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can get it done this year, it would be nice. My plate
will be full as a player. Right now, I'm missing the macaroni. I
got the chicken, I got the salad, I got the rice, but right now I'm
just missing the macaroni. Get the full-deal meal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
