<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LBPT </SLUG>
 
DiSARCINA WILL BE EXAMINED FURTHER 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Shortstop Gary DiSarcina, placed on the 15-day
disabled list after leaving Monday's game with a sore shoulder, was
examined Tuesday by orthopedic specialist Dr. Frank Jobe but team
officials said there were no results to report and that he would be
looked at further today.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina, who began the season on the 15-day disabled list with
a bruised left thumb, was bothered by shoulder problems late last
season and sat out the previous five games to rest it.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, 7-5 with DiSarcina in the lineup and 10-12 without
him, will rely on utilityman Benji Gil to replace DiSarcina, who
was batting a team-leading .395 with 11 RBIs. Two of his five
errors this season have come in his last two games, both poor
throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts in a lot of ways,'' Manager Mike Scioscia said when
asked what losing DiSarcina for an extended period would mean.
``Taking nothing away from Benji Gil, but this is a veteran,
experienced player who's the glue to the club on and off the field.
You see the way the infield reacts when he's out there. He's a guy
you hope is not out long term.''
</P>
<P>
   Trent Durrington, a second baseman for the Angels last season,
was recalled from Triple-A Edmonton to fill DiSarcina's spot on the
roster. He worked out Tuesday at shortstop and will backup Gil and
second baseman Adam Kennedy, and also give the Angels a
pinch-running option, Scioscia said.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Ortiz may have made his last start as an Angel for a
while.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz, who was hit for three homers and eight runs in 3 2/3
innings, is scheduled to make his next start Saturday against
Texas. But that's also the day that Jason Dickson is due to come
off the disabled list. With Jarrod Washburn pitching well at
Edmonton, even Ken Hill's injury may not give Ortiz a reprieve.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia said before Tuesday's game that no decision has been
made regarding Ortiz, the club's No.1 pitching prospect, but he
hinted that the 24-year-old right-hander --- who is 2-2 with a 6.90
in six starts --- may be better served trying to develop in the
minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Consistency has been the problem. Monday, for example, he got
nine consecutive outs at one point, then walked two hitters and
gave up a three-run homer to Jeremy Giambi. That was followed by
two singles and a homer by Terrence Long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's shown some baby steps (in improvement),''
Scioscia said. ``But honestly, it's tough to learn things at the
major league level. He's got a lot a lot of things going for him
--- he has a tremendous arm and he's a competitor. With guys like
Ortiz, (Jarrod) Washburn and (Scott) Schoeneweis, the big picture
is always in mind. We want to keep every option open to serve his
development in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   Troy Percival says he learned a lesson from his blown save
Friday in Seattle: don't always leave your curveball in the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   He brought it with him Monday and as a result Percival closed
out a 9-8 victory over Oakland for his ninth save in 10 tries.
After Ben Grieve ripped a fastball down the right field line for a
one-out double, Percival struck out pinch hitter Olmedo Saenz
looking at a curveball and Jeremy Giambi on a check swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotta throw that pitch,'' Percival said of his curve.
``Against Seattle, I got myself in that rhythm (of fastballs).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
