<SLUG> BC-BBN-MATCHUP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS' BROWN TO FACE JOHNSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The games become blurs. Playing 162 of them across six
months makes it difficult to distinguish one from another in most
cases.
</P>
<P>
   But now and again one comes along that takes on a very different
personality, and one of those times arrives tonight at Bank One
Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   In the age of light-hitting infielders smashing home runs to the
opposite field, once in a while a pitcher's duel is possible, and
that's what everyone is expecting as Arizona lefty Randy Johnson
opposes Dodgers right-hander Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'd be nice to step back and watch it from the front row of
the seats,'' Dodgers second baseman Mark Grudzielanek said. ``It's
an all-time matchup.''
</P>
<P>
   Without question, Johnson is the most dominant pitcher these
days. He's on his way to a second straight Cy Young award, tying a
major-league record with six wins in April and going 7-0 with a
0.93 ERA in seven starts. In 58 innings, Johnson has 75 strikeouts
and has allowed 31 hits.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who spent two weeks on the disabled list with a broken
right pinkie, is 2-1 with a 2.45 ERA. He's 1-1 with a 1.23 ERA
since returning from the injury.
</P>
<P>
   What's made Johnson so devastating in the past few seasons is
his control. A bugaboo early in Johnson's career was his walks, but
he began cutting that total down three years ago. Now, it's reached
the ridiculous stage.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who's thrown four complete games and pitched in all but
4 of the possible innings in his starts, has walked 13 batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year he's probably been more dominant than ever,'' said
Dodgers manager Davey Johnson, whose teams are 6-1 lifetime against
Randy Johnson. ``He's throwing the breaking ball more and throwing
it over. At times earlier in his career, he would overthrow and be
wild, and you could come in and bop him. But he's throwing that
breaking ball and backdooring it.''
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks center fielder Steve Finley has seen it from both
sides. Finley was a teammate of Brown's on the San Diego Padres
team that lost to the Yankees in the 1998 World Series. And he's
spent the last two seasons with Johnson in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really know if he's throwing the ball better this year
than last year, because he pitched so well last season, but he's
been awesome,'' Finley said. ``I faced him in the minor leagues and
when I was in Baltimore, but he was a different pitcher than he is
now.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the second time in two seasons the pair have met, but there
isn't nearly the hoopla and excitement surrounding this
confrontation. They met opening day last season, after the Dodgers
pursued both heavily in the free-agent market.
</P>
<P>
   However, Johnson opted to come home and pitch for the
Diamondbacks, signing a four-year, $52.4 million contract. Brown
went to the Dodgers for $105 million and some chartered jet rides
over seven years.
</P>
<P>
   And the opening-day matchup at Dodger Stadium never came close
to fulfilling the expectations. Brown allowed 10 hits, including
three homers, and five runs in 5 innings. Johnson pitched seven
innings and allowed two runs on five hits, but he walked six. All
of which mattered little when Raul Mondesi homered in the 11th
inning for a Dodgers win.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have two guys like that facing each other, it's good
for baseball,'' said Dodgers utility infielder Jose Vizcaino, who's
4 for 10 lifetime against Johnson. ``I get excited for one side but
not for the other. You know there won't be a lot of runs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 0240EDT &QL; 
