<HEADLINE>
ANGELS LOSE GAME, HILL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ The Angels' most pressing question is no longer how
will their young pitchers hold up or how will they respond to
rookie manager Mike Scioscia or how long can they stay in the AL
West race.
</P>
<P>
   The question they're grappling with now is who will it be today?
</P>
<P>
   One day after shortstop Gary DiSarcina - ``the glue to the
club,'' according to Scioscia - was placed on the disabled list,
the Angels lost staff ace Ken Hill, who strained a muscle in his
rib cage early in Tuesday's 5-2 loss to Oakland before 15,308 at
Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Hill sank to his knees and buried his face in the ground after
throwing a 2-0 pitch to Miguel Tejada in the third inning. He
stayed there a few minutes until he was helped to his feet and
escorted off the field by trainer Ned Bergert and Scioscia.
</P>
<P>
   Hill's injury was serious enough that he didn't even attempt a
throw to see if he could stay in the game, and afterward the club
placed him on the disabled list and said he would undergo an MRI
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   It's the fifth time in just over three seasons that the
34-year-old Hill has landed on the disabled list. Most of the
previous problems centered around an arthritic right elbow, on
which he had surgery in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Hill looked uncomfortable on the previous pitch to Tejada but
waved Scioscia and Bergert back to the dugout. When Scioscia
arrived on the next pitch, he said Hill had a hard time catching
his breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty bad,'' Scioscia said of the injury. ``There's a
pretty wide range depending on the severity. It can be two to three
weeks or two to three months. I'm speculating. I don't have M.D.
after my name, but I'm speaking from experience.''
</P>
<P>
   So, even though the Angels are hovering around the .500 mark and
playing with renewed enthusiasm and vigor under Scioscia, it's
beginning to look like last season as far as injuries are
concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Hill hadn't pitched well - he is 3-4 with a 7.41 ERA
- his presence on the young staff was valued.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got hit with a couple of tough injuries,'' Scioscia said.
``You look at Gary DiSarcina and Ken Hill - those are two big parts
of our ballclub. But that's part of baseball and part of a 162-game
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn said the Angels can't afford to look back on last year
when injuries were only part of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just got to stay positive and regardless of who's out
there, go out and play ball,'' Vaughn said. ``We're still right in
the thick of it. There's too many months left. The next guy just
has to step up and do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Trent Durrington was recalled Monday to replace DiSarcina and
Mike Fyhrie will take Hill's spot on the pitching staff. However,
Jason Dickson returns from the disabled list Saturday and could
take Hill's start on Sunday, though Scioscia was noncommittal.
</P>
<P>
   Adding insult to injury Tuesday was the way Oakland right-hander
Gil Heredia tamed the Angels, shutting them out on four hits until
Darin Erstad led off the eighth inning with a booming home run to
center field.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels added another run in the ninth, but Jason
Isringhausen got Erstad to ground into a fielder's choice to earn
his sixth save.
</P>
<P>
   Heredia (4-2), who walked two and struck out two, had only two
major threats but stranded two runners in the second and the
seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The Athletics gave Heredia an early cushion, jumping to a 2-0
lead in the second and adding solo homers by Ben Grieve in the
fifth and Jeremy Giambi in the seventh, and making it 5-0 when the
Angels couldn't turn a bases-loaded double play in the eighth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
