<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS GET NO RELIEF IN LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - This year's bullpen was a strength for a month, but it
has turned into last year in the past week or so.
</P>
<P>
   The set-up men aren't setting up, or they're limping to the
ninth. And when given the opportunity to closer, Jeff Shaw isn't
closing.
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen was battered again, culminating with a five-run 12th
inning, and the Arizona Diamondbacks got a grand slam from Damian
Miller off Orel Hershiser in an 11-7 win against the Dodgers on
Tuesday at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   It's the Dodgers' third straight loss, and they're 5 games
behind Arizona and in third place.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hate to lose, and you hate to lose that way,'' Dodgers
manager Davey Johnson said. ``Orel, he's used to starting and
getting in a little better rhthym and locating better, but I had a
lot of confidence bringing him in. It never should have gotten to
that point a three-run lead in the eighth.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers took a 7-6 lead in the top of the 12th on Todd
Hollandsworth's RBI fielder's choice. But Hershiser, trying for his
first save since 1988, couldn't hold it.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Finley had a bases-loaded sacrifice fly to tie the game.
After Hershiser hit Kelly Stinnett with a pitch to load the bases,
Miller hit a hanging slider for a grand slam with one out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more difficult than I thought,'' Hershiser said of
relieving. ``Maybe I've underestimated how tough it is to get
rhythm and experience just coming in as a reliever. It's been one
speed and one location out of the bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen collapse began in the eighth, in a situation that
screams for a lefty reliever, of which the Dodgers didn't have. The
Dodgers led 6-3, but Arizona marched its lefties to the plate to
load the bases off Terry Adams. Steve Finley singled in a pair of
runs to make it 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw, who's blown three straight save chances, allowed one-out
double to Danny Klassen. A passed ball on catcher Todd Hundley
moved Klassen to third and forced the Dodgers to bring the infield
in. Switch-hitter Andy Fox tied the game 6-6 with a broken bat
bloop single to left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I broke his bat in half,'' said Shaw, who has three blown
saves and a loss in his last five games. ``I'm doing everything
that I'm capable of doing to keep the game in hand. It's not that
I'm making mistakes, because I'm not. (Double) just inside the
line, a broken bat, what are you going to do?''
</P>
<P>
   Lost in the collapse of the bullpen was a strong effort from
starter Carlos Perez, who left after seven innings with a three-run
lead only to watch the Dodgers' bullpen have problems.
</P>
<P>
   However, Perez, who's won three straight decisions, was curious
as to why he didn't go out to pitch the eighth inning. He allowed
three runs on six hits and didn't walk a batter. He threw 94
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was surprising to me that the way I'm feeling, I just got a
ground-ball double play and I know I don't have a lot of pitches
and there's a lot of left-handers coming up in the eighth, and I
find myself out of the game,'' Perez said. ``It's the manager's
decision, and I don't want to complain, but I wish he left me out
there for another inning. I know they had a lot of lefties coming
up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
