<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-EDWARDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDWARDS LONG A TARGET OF PROSECUTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ After a remarkable roll in which he was elected to
four terms as governor of Louisiana, won fortunes in Las Vegas, and
flummoxed a generation of federal prosecutors, Edwin W. Edwards has
finally lost out.
</P>
<P>
   A fixture in Louisiana politics for nearly four decades, Edwards
was convicted Tuesday on 17 counts of racketeering and extortion.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards's 45-year-old son, Stephen, was also convicted in
connection with an elaborate scheme to shake down investors in
Louisiana casinos.
</P>
<P>
   The former governor, still debonair and speaking with the lilt
of his native Cajun country, said after the verdict: ``I regret it
ended this way, but that is the system. I have lived 72 years in
the system and I will live out my life in the system.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial, which began shortly after the first of the year,
transfixed the state for months. Federal prosecutors charged that
Edwards made raw demands to raise millions of dollars in cash.
</P>
<P>
   In a dramatic appearance on the witness stand, Edwards asserted
he was being victimized by zealous prosecutors and betrayed by
former friends.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards and six other defendants were ensnared by a 33-count
indictment, charged with racketeering, conspiracy, extortion,
fraud, and money laundering.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the case was an accusation against Edwards by
Eddie DeBartolo Jr., who owned the San Francisco 49ers before he
was implicated in the scandal. After reaching a plea bargain
agreement with prosecutors and paying a $1 million fine, DeBartolo
testified that Edwards shook him down for $400,000 in cash in
exchange for Edwards's help in winning a riverboat casino license
in Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Though Edwards acknowledged receiving the money, he claimed it
was a legitimate consulting fee and said DeBartolo insisted upon
paying in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the money was seized by the FBI during raids on
Edwards's home and office three years ago. Edwards had been a
target for months; the FBI wiretapped his telephones and installed
secret video and audio tape-recording devices in his home and
office.
</P>
<P>
   Another well-connected Louisiana politico, Robert Guidry,
testified that he passed on upward of $1.5 million to Edwards and
his son for their help in obtaining a license for his Treasure
Chest casino. Guidry, a longtime associate of Edwards, said he
agreed to place some of the payments in a garbage bin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dumpster might have gotten it, but I didn't,'' Edwards
testified.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards is the latest in a long line of colorful characters who
have held the office of governor in Louisiana. His career, now
ended, outlasted the political lifetimes of such figures as Huey P.
Long, the self-styled ``Kingfish'' who grabbed dictatorial powers
until he was assassinated in the halls of the state capitol in
1935; ``Uncle Earl'' Long, brother and successor to the slain
Kingfish, whose last administration was highlighted by his liaison
with a Bourbon Street stripper, Blaze Starr; and Jimmy Davis, the
``Singing Cowboy,'' a man better remembered for his recording of
``You Are My Sunshine'' than his stint in government.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years Edwards defied convention. After winning a third
term in 1983, he chartered two jetliners to convey hundreds of
lobbyists and contributors on a gambling excursion to France.
Edwards charged each $10,000 for the trip.
</P>
<P>
   When he won a fourth term in 1991, Edwards moved his girlfriend,
Candy Picou, into the governor's mansion, where she hosted her high
school class's 10th reunion. They were married in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards also held high-stakes poker games at the governor's
mansion and gambled frequently at Las Vegas, using such pseudonyms
as E. Nuff, T. Wong, and Muff Alotta. He estimated that he won
nearly $2 million gambling during a 10-year period that ended in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   His third term, in the mid-1980s, was marred by two trials in
which Edwards was accused of racketeering. Prosecutors said Edwards
intervened in the state licensing of hospitals after getting $2
million in payoffs. His first trial ended in a hung jury; the
second in acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards's most memorable campaign came in 1991, in a run-off,
against David Duke, a Nazi sympathizer and erstwhile leader of a
division of the Ku Klux Klan. ``We're both wizards under the
sheets,'' Edwards quipped, alluding to his own reputation as a
ladies' man. Edwards's partisans produced bumper stickers saying:
``Vote for the Crook. It's Important.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
