<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When did my lifestyle go high-dollar?
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ I just got the appraisal on my South Austin
house in the mail, and I can't figure out why the market value on
the house shot up this year from $83,193 to $91,585.
</P>
<P>
   I understand that people all over town are getting stuck with
appraisal hikes so the Austin Independent School District can send
$33 million next year to other parts of the state to educate other
people's children. But I don't think my little two-bedroom house is
worth $91,585.
</P>
<P>
   I'm trying to think what improvements I've made that might make
the Travis Central Appraisal District think I live in a -- ansion.
Maybe it's the kiddie pool. We got rid of the plastic kiddie pool
15 or 20 years ago. Ever since, the appraised value of my house
keeps rising.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, that must be it. Maybe if I went out to Home Depot and
bought another plastic kiddie pool and set it in the back yard, my
taxes would go down.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't that I've had a constant parade of Californians coming
by my house, trying to buy the place, either. In fact, since I
moved into my house 22 years ago, I have yet to have -- single
Californian come by my house, ring the doorbell and offer me
enormous piles of cash.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe my appraisal keeps going up because I live among the
glitterati. My next-door neighbor, Bernice, ran for Miss Williamson
County back in 1959. Too many stars _ maybe that's my problem.
</P>
<P>
   Oh sure, I have made some recent improvements that may have led
the appraisal district to jack up my appraised value more than
$8,000 in a single year. A few weeks ago, I broke down and bought a
lawn mower. Shortly after, I broke down and mowed the lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe after I mowed the lawn the appraisal district figured out
my house is, in fact, inhabited. Making matters worse, ever since I
bought my new lawn mower, there's been a spate of lawn mowing going
on in my neighborhood, which may make the appraisal district think
I'm living in a swank area. For example, right after I got the new
lawn mower, my neighbor Rich Mann _ and that's his real name _
found out about it and came over and borrowed it. Then he mowed his
lawn, too. This is what you call a South Austin beautification
program.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the fact that I cleaned out my garage _ sort of _
a few weeks back. I loaded a pile of old clothes in the back of my
car and drove them over to Goodwill and dumped them off.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the appraisal district saw me lugging old T-shirts out of
the garage and decided the house was suddenly more valuable.
</P>
<P>
   I ought to get a special South Austin tax exemption because of
some of my neighbors, however. I ought to get a big tax break
because of the college-age guys who live in the rent house two
doors down. These guys are always playing the bongos in the back
yard. Boingy boingy boingy. Boingy boingy boingy boingy boingy.
It's like living next to a Tarzan movie, without the chimpanzee.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently these guys think they're Matthew McConaughey. Heck,
one of them may be Matthew McConaughey, for all I know. Don't ask
me if they're wearing pants, because I haven't been by to check.
</P>
<P>
   If the Travis Central Appraisal District people think this all
adds up to $91,585 worth of house, they have rocks in their head--
.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso can be reached at 512-445-3606 or at
jkelso(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
