<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Women stand tall in honor
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Gloria Anticoli couldn't help noticing the small
stature of the three women being awarded honorary doctorates at the
University of Dayton on Sunday. Virginia MacMillan Varga, Sister
Mary Peter Traviss, and Evangeline Lindsley all hovered around 5
feet, give or take an inch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at them and think, 'the three Mighty Mouses,'''
Anticoli said, pointing to the banquet table where the women were
honored after the commencement. ``It makes me think about the power
of women.''
</P>
<P>
   The honorees all came of age when physical stature _ read gender
_ translated into intellectual and professional stature. When
people really bought into this stuff about ``the weaker sex.''
</P>
<P>
   And boy, did these women prove them wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Varga became one of the first women inducted into UD's Athletic
Hall of Fame for her athletic exploits in no fewer than four
sports. But it was off the field that she truly distinguished
herself, opening Gloria Dei Montessori School _ the first program
in Dayton _ in 1962, and becoming nationally recognized as a leader
in the Montessori movement.
</P>
<P>
   Sister Mary Peter Traviss is a Dominican sister dubbed ``The
First Lady of Catholic Education'' by Today's Catholic Teacher for
her work in Catholic education research. UD President Brother
Raymond Fitz praised her as ``among the top five people in Catholic
education in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   In 41 years as a teacher at Roosevelt High School, Evangeline
Lindsley taught government and civics to generations of Dayton
youth. She incorporated real life into the lesson plan, fighting
for equality for women and for black students.
</P>
<P>
   The women exhibited a common humility, a greater eagerness to
share credit than to receive it.
</P>
<P>
   Varga, a 1951 UD graduate, confessed that she made her husband
read the notification letter to make sure some clerical error
hadn't been made.
</P>
<P>
   Anticoli wasn't surprised by that reaction from her friend of
nearly 50 years. ``Ginny didn't talk a lot about what she was going
to do; she just did it,'' she said. ``These are women who knew who
they were and what they stood for. They did it quietly and didn't
expect the accolades.''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Mary Peter said the true glory belongs to her students
and their research. But, she conceded, ``Catholic education and its
quality are passions of mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Claiming that ``old age has its privileges,'' Lindsley, 103,
remained in her seat. ``I stand today _ well, I'm not standing very
well _ on the shoulders of friends who, through their hard work,
carried our ideas to fruition.''
</P>
<P>
   False modesty? None of these women gave that impression.
</P>
<P>
   They projected, instead, a sense of interconnectedness, of women
building upon one another's accomplishments. As you went around the
room, you found guest after guest whose lives had been touched by
these women.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Turner of Dayton came to cheer on her relative, Evangeline
Lindsley. Yet she remembered the time, only 22 years ago, when her
oldest daughter was in grade school, and Ginny Varga was the only
one who would let her play soccer. There were no soccer leagues for
girls at the time, but Varga included girls on Gloria Dei's team
``even though that meant they automatically forfeited every game,''
Turner recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Girls didn't ``count'' in youth soccer then _ but they always
counted for Varga.
</P>
<P>
   These women are thrilled and honored by their newly minted
doctorates. But they never needed titles or caps and gowns to
remind them of the power of women.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
