r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN11-COX     05-10 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    San Francisco cracks down on menace to civil rights: the fat
joke
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas_ ``When the aliens come, they will eat the fat ones
first,'' declared a San Francisco billboard for an area fitness
outfit.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco was the wrong place to put a little humor into an
advertisement encouraging fat people to get fit.
</P>
<P>
   Fat San Francisco residents shouted, pouted and stamped their
ponderous feet.
</P>
<P>
   To San Francisco's hefties, this was a weighty issue. Just as
the Founding Fathers did with King George, beefy Bay-area residents
also demanded redress for their grievances.
</P>
<P>
   The oversized residents appealed to San Francisco's Board of
Supervisors for protection against harmful advertisements, fat
humor and remarks or actions that could cause them discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   As residents of the epicenter of America's sensitivity trends,
San Francisco's skinny people picked up on this new movement.
</P>
<P>
   Bony Bay-area natives weren't about to let fat people cut them
out of special protection from equally damaging scrawny jokes or
thinly disguised remarks and actions that hurt the feelings of
weight-challenged residents.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, but if fat and skinny people are going to get government
protection, San Francisco's short people didn't want to be left
out. Surely, said vertically challenged San Francisco residents,
short people deserve just as much protection as do fat people and
skinny people.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, if San Francisco's fat people, skinny people and
short people are going to get government protection, tall people
also deserve protection. After all, how would you like to be asked
``How's the weather up there?'' every day?
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Board of Supervisors expanded their proposed
``fat ordinance'' to include skinny, short and tall. Now it's
against the law in San Francisco to discriminate, in word or deed,
against fat, skinny, short or tall people.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents are doubly protected. Tall skinny people could be
doubly insulted by bean-pole jokes.
</P>
<P>
   According to a New York Times article by Evelyn Nieves, San
Francisco's new ordinance puts size in the same anti-discrimination
codes that already protect people based on race, religion, color,
ancestry, age, sex, sexual orientation, gender identity, disability
and place of birth.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Wann, the 5-foot-6-inch 270-pound head of the local
National Association to Advance Fat Acceptance, said, ``We don't
need a diet. We need an end to discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   One supporter of San Francisco's new anti-discrimination size
ordinance complained in the Times article that doctors often tell
fat people that they need to lose weight when they seek medical
treatment for specific ailments.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds as though doctors now can be hauled into court if they
suggest while removing a corn that an obese patient should lose
some weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important that this law passed because it can have
far-reaching implications outside of San Francisco,'' the woman
said. That scares the pants off the rest of America.
</P>
<P>
   To add size to government protections for all people except
those who are dead-perfect average means that short, tall, fat or
skinny people who feel they were insulted, turned down for a job,
passed over for a raise or given a hard time by a sales clerk can
add to America's glut of lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   There also is the intriguing problem of determining exactly who
does not deserve special government protection.
</P>
<P>
   What is tall, short, overweight or underweight? Can a
6-foot-four-inch NBA guard sue over short jokes by his teammates?
</P>
<P>
   If the San Francisco law spreads nationwide, there probably will
be one very bland white straight guy born in a small town in Iowa,
about 5-feet-10-inches and 167 pounds, who you could joke about.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is the Senior editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 1050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000510.0038 </DOCNO>
