r a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS11-FILE     05-10 1754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS11-FILE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   FILE 1 of 2
</P>
<P>
   Q: Faced with high fuel costs, could motorists realize some
savings by mixing octane ratings? For example, if 10 gallons of
premium gasoline (93 octane) were mixed with 10 gallons of regular
(87 octane), wouldn't that work OK? Or is this not recommended by
the experts?
</P>
<P>
   A: The only problem with that would be the ``hassle'' of putting
in 10 gallons of one type, then clearing the pump before putting in
10 gallons of the other, said Ric Cobb of the Georgia Petroleum
Council. Beyond that, you're not likely to encounter any danger or
problem with engine wear from mixing octanes, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Cobb said when prices got so high recently, he would fill up his
car with the highest octane available. Then, after using about
one-fourth of the tank, he would top it back up with 89 octane
fuel. When he had used about half that tank, he would put in 87
octane. Although his car normally uses 93 octane, he experienced no
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Only high-performance cars or old cars might suffer a bit of
knocking with lower-than-recommended octane levels, but for most
drivers it won't matter, Cobb said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've heard two sets of figures for the odds of winning the
Big Game jackpot. Some reports say 1 in 76 million, others 1 in 78
million. What is correct, and how are the odds determined?
</P>
<P>
   A: When you hear that the odds are 1 in 76 million, that's an
approximation. To be exact, the odds of getting 5 correct white
balls and the correct Big Money ball are 1 in 76,275,360 (per $1
play), according to the Georgia Lottery Corp. The GLC's Tandi
Reddick explained that the odds are determined by the total number
combinations possible with the 50 white balls and the 36 gold
balls.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you give us some history of baseball's All-Star Game,
which is coming back to Atlanta on July 11?
</P>
<P>
   A: The tradition of All-Star Games in baseball dates to an 1858
series between teams of stars from Brooklyn and New York (they were
called ``picked nines'' in those days). But the current All-Star
series began in 1933, when Chicago Tribune sports editor Arch Ward
persuaded hesitant league owners to go along with his proposal for
a game between stars from the American and National leagues, to be
played in Chicago during that city's Century of Progress
exposition.
</P>
<P>
   Under Ward's plan, fans voted for the best players, who then
played each other. Various changes have been made since then in who
makes the choices, but as of 1970 the selection of starting lineups
has been returned to the fans. Each team's manager still selects
the pitchers, however.
</P>
<P>
   Worth noting: Babe Ruth hit a home run in the first All-Star
Game.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I never saw anything explaining how Regis Philbin was chosen
to host ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.'' I think he makes the
program, and is a valuable asset. Can you tell me how he got the
job?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's said that Philbin had been shopping around for something
to do _ other than ``Live! With Regis and Kathie Lee'' _ for some
time. ABC had suggested, among other things, a remake of ``Whom Do
You Trust?'' the 1950s quiz show that launched Johnny Carson's
career. But, as Philbin himself told a Newsweek reporter, he was
interested in ``something new.''
</P>
<P>
   When his agent gave him a tape of ``Millionaire,'' which already
was a smash hit in Britain, Philbin was captivated. He called
Michael Davies, ABC's executive vice president for alternative
series and specials, begging to do a U.S. version of the program.
``He totally `got' the show,'' said Davies, who had offered Philbin
other programs. ``He understood why it worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Around the same time as the shootings at Kent State
University in Ohio, several students at Jackson State University in
Mississippi were shot by state troopers. Can you refresh my memory
about that incident and what, if anything, was done to the
troopers?
</P>
<P>
   A: In the early hours of May 15, 1970, 11 days after the
shootings at Kent State, some 40 Mississippi state patrolmen and 26
Jackson city policemen opened fire on a crowd of students gathered
around Alexander Hall, a women's dormitory.
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by the Kent State shootings, sentiment about the Vietnam
War, a history of angry confrontations between white motorists and
black students on a street running through the campus, and rumors
of the assassination of Charles Evers (mayor of Fayette, Miss., and
brother of civil rights leader Medgar Evers), students and
onlookers had set fires, overturned a dump truck and pelted cars
with rocks and bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials cordoned off a 30-black area around
the campus and at one point a bottle exploded near Alexander Hall,
sparking rumors of a sniper. According to press accounts, that's
when the shooting began. The barrage left two dead and more than a
dozen wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Later that year a federal grand jury in Jackson failed to return
any indictments, ending the possibility that officers involved
would be prosecuted. Families of those killed and wounded sued the
city of Jackson and the state of Mississippi, but in 1974 a federal
appeals judged ruled that damages couldn't be awarded because it
was impossible to determine who was to blame. In 1982, a final
appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court failed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The Big Game is played in seven states. Where does the
drawing take place? It seems to be in Atlanta every Tuesday and
Friday night, but does it rotate to other places as well?
</P>
<P>
   A: The drawings indeed are held in Atlanta, at the WSB-TV
studios, said Parquita Nassau of the Georgia Lottery Corp. The
drawings, originally held in Chicago, were moved here in 1998 and
do not rotate to any other city, she added.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the origin of the word Dixie?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are several theories, including one that it derives
from the Mason-Dixon Line, or another that it's from the French
word dix, meaning 10, which was printed prominently on the back of
$10 notes issued by a New Orleans bank before the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   But a more likely explanation, according to the Facts on File
Encyclopedia of Word and Phrase Origins, is that the first Dixie
(or Dixieland) may have been in _ surprise _ New York.
</P>
<P>
   The encyclopedia states that the Charlestown Courier of June 11,
1885, mentioned that a person named Dixie had owned a large tract
on Manhattan Island. The story was that ``Dixie's,'' as the tract
was known, ``became synonymous with an ideal location combining
ease, comfort and material happiness of every description.''
</P>
<P>
   After slavery was abolished, the name apparently was transferred
when many people moved south, and presumably looked back to their
old homeplace with feelings of regret.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I heard that Steve Irwin, of the ``Crocodile Hunter'' cable
TV program on the Animal Planet, had died from a snake bite. Do you
have any information about it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not so. A Discovery Channel spokeswoman said this rumor _
along with another one that he was killed by a crocodile _ makes
the rounds about once a month. It's ``totally false,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When the Atlanta Braves were on their 15-game winning streak,
it was reported that the 1916 New York Giants held the record for
the longest one in Major League Baseball history, at 26 games. Who
were the members of that team?
</P>
<P>
   A: Fred Merkle, first base; Larry Doyle, second base; Art
Fletcher, shortstop; Bill McKechnie, third base; Dave Robertson,
right field; Benny Kauff, center field; George Burns, left field;
Bill Rariden, catcher; Charles ``Buck'' Herzog, utility; and
pitchers Jeff Tesreau, William ``Pol'' Perritt, John ``Rube''
Benton, Fred Anderson, Ferdinand ``Ferdie'' Schupp, and Harry
``Slim'' Sallee.
</P>
<P>
   The team, by the way, ended that season with 86 wins, 66 losses.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I wore an MIA bracelet for many years. I recently lost it and
would like to buy another, but the company where I got my first one
is out of business. Does anyone make them now?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. Bracelets for prisoners of war and those missing in
action still are available. As one company that sells them notes:
``These bracelets are still worn to keep the issue alive for more
than 10,000 of our brave soldiers still not accounted for.'' The
name, rank, branch of service, home state, date and country of
capture or disappearance are engraved on each bracelet.
</P>
<P>
   One manufacturer is BattleZone Ltd., P.O. Box 266, Towaco, NJ
07082, or e-mail at bzone(at)thebattlezone.com, or fax at
973-402-7226. Four styles are available, priced at $10.50-$16. You
can order them via its Web site,
www.thebattlezone.com/powmia/bracelets.html.
</P>
<P>
   Another source is Stemarco Engraving, 1908 E. 7th St., Odessa,
TX 79761 (915-334-6900). Bracelets, in eight styles, are $5-$50 and
can be ordered online at www.ov-1.com/misc/bracelet-order3.html.
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article about a man flying to the North Pole in an
open-cockpit airplane made me wonder: What would the windchill
factor be for someone in an open airplane, going about 160 miles an
hour, with the air temperature 40 degrees below zero Fahrenheit?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you're thinking it might be several hundred degrees below
zero, the number may surprise you. It would be about 45.3 degrees
below zero.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Yeaton of the Weather Discovery Center at Mount Washington
Observatory in New Hampshire explained that the actual increase in
windchill is minimal ``once you get beyond a 40 mph wind.''
</P>
<P>
   As Yeaton said, the Windchill Equivalency Temperature doesn't
compute well for extreme temperatures and wind speeds. Windchill
was developed in Antarctica in 1939-40 by Paul Siple and Charles
Passel to determine how the combination of cold and wind would feel
on exposed human flesh. ``The key is `exposed,' '' he said. ``When
you add any clothing, the formula would not apply.''
</P>
<P>
   The Antarctica experiments used the increased rate of freezing
in a cylinder of water at various temperatures and windspeeds.
</P>
<P>
   The easiest way to determine windchill is to use the Web site
for the National Weather Service _
www.srh.noaa.gov/elp/wxcalc/windchill.html _ and plug numbers into
the calculator. Charts also can be found in World Book
Encyclopedia.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
