<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 10:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0759 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS11-FILE     05-10 1788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS11-FILE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   FILE 2 of 2
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some time ago, there was talk about Mattel making a more
realistically proportioned, meaning smaller busted, Barbie. What
ever became of that?
</P>
<P>
   A: Reports in 1999 about Barbie being reduced were ``media
hype,'' a spokesman for Mattel told Q&AMP;A. He added that the company
never had any intentions of altering her proportions, and all that
was done at the time was to change her ``face sculpting.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the company is planning to introduce ``Jewel Girl''
Barbie this August, with bigger hips, a smaller bust and a ``more
athletic figure to appeal to teens,'' he said. She will have a
belly button and no seam, so she can bend and flex, which he
described as ``important changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is the word ``ain't'' now acceptable in the English language?
I say it is, but an English teacher friend of mine insists that
it's not.
</P>
<P>
   A: Although it's heard fairly often, especially in the southern
and south-central states, ``ain't'' is considered ``nonstandard.''
So your teacher friend is correct.
</P>
<P>
   Even educated people use it in such expressions as ``She ain't
what she used to be,'' ``You ain't heard nothin' yet'' and ``Ain't
that the truth,'' but those are for deliberate effect or humor, and
still fall into the nonstandard category.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In 1972, a fire at the military personnel archives in St.
Louis destroyed the military records of thousands of people.
Recently I heard that some records had been found that possibly
could replace those that were lost. Do you have any information?
</P>
<P>
   A: The National Archives and Records Administration has received
numerous inquiries from people who have heard that ``10 million
medical records'' have been found. Like you, these people wondered
if they were duplicates of the records that were burned on July 12,
1973, at the National Personnel Records Center.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, they were summaries for admissions to medical
treatment facilities, and contained limited medical information.
They numbered 7.8 million, not 10 million as the rumor had it.
</P>
<P>
   About 16 million-18 million official military personnel records
were lost in the fire. No duplicate copies were maintained,
according to the records administration, nor was a microfilm copy
ever produced. And there were no indexes created before the fire.
So they're considered to be lost forever.
</P>
<P>
   The records involved were those from the Army, concerning
personnnel discharged between Nov. 1, 1912, and Jan. 1, 1960 (an
estimated 80 percent were lost); and Air Force, personnel
discharged between Sept. 25, 1947, and Jan. 1, 1964, with names
alphabetically after Hubbard, James E. (an estimated 75 percent
were lost).
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have seen the letters PA in television listings for certain
programs, such as ``NYPD Blue.'' What does that mean?
</P>
<P>
   A: It stands for Parental Advisory. Broadcasters use it before a
show airs _ and it's also included in TV listings _ to inform
viewers that there might be some material deemed inappropriate or
offensive (meaning strong language and/or nudity) to children or
even adults.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When readers inquire about the origins of words, Q&AMP;A
frequently mentions two books,``Morris Dictionary of Word and
Phrase Origins'' and ``The Facts on File Encyclopedia of Word and
Phrase Origins.'' Where can these reference works be obtained?
</P>
<P>
   A: If bookstores don't have them in stock, ask that they be
ordered. Bookstores get the data they need from ``Books in Print.''
The Morris work is published by HarperCollins; the encyclopedia is
published by Facts on File. Both are still in print. Several other
books on the same subject also are available in paperback and are
still in print.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Around the time of World War II, anyone entering the Navy was
given a seven-digit serial number. I always understood that the
first three digits indicated what part of the country the person
was from. Where can I get a listing of these numbers with the
related areas they represented?
</P>
<P>
   A: The idea that the first three digits indicate where a person
was from appears to be a rumor of long standing, said John Reilly
of the Navy Historical Center. He added that he had been in the
Navy himself and had heard it discussed over the years. However, he
said no person or agency, including the Navy Personnel Command,
could verify it or provide any information to support it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the status of author Kurt Vonnegut Jr.? Several months
ago I read that he was ill, but I never saw anything else.
</P>
<P>
   A: The ``Slaughterhouse Five'' and ``Breakfast of Champions''
novelist, 77, suffered smoke inhalation in late January after a
small blaze broke out on the fourth floor of his East 48th Street
brownstone in Manhattan. He was taken to New York Presbyterian
Hospital, where he initially was listed in critical but stable
condition.
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor, Hans von Stackelberg, was credited with saving
Vonnegut; his wife, photographer Jill Krementz; and their daughter,
Lily, 17, from serious harm.
</P>
<P>
   Vonnegut was released from the hospital in mid-February.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I obtain a copy of the 10-minute White House video
with President Clinton spoofing himself? I've seen only bits of it
shown on various TV programs.
</P>
<P>
   A: It's available for purchase, but only as part of a video of
the entire White House Correspondents' Dinner, held April 29 at the
Washington Hilton. Call C-SPAN Archives (877-662-7726) and ask for
item No. 156877. The cost is $31.95, which includes shipping and
handling.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was the body of Elian Gonzalez's mother ever recovered? If
not, was it just assumed that she drowned?
</P>
<P>
   A: The body of the mother, Elizabet Broton, hasn't been reported
found. So yes, it's assumed that she drowned along with her
companion, Lazaro Rafael Munero, and his brother, Jikary Munero,
whose bodies also weren't reported found.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There's an online company, Webvan, that takes orders for
groceries and delivers them in some U.S. cities. Is Webvan publicly
traded? If it is, what is the stock symbol?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's on Nasdaq: WBVN. If you're interested in investing,
Webvan advises you to contact your stockbroker. Shares aren't
available through Webvan. Information online: www.webvan.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I want to be a bone marrow donor, or at least register to
become one. I found some information on the Internet, but it looks
like it will cost me $60-$100 simply to be screened. What can you
tell me?
</P>
<P>
   A: To become a volunteer marrow donor, you must be between the
ages of 18 and 60 and in general good health, according to the
National Marrow Donor Program. A blood test administered through an
authorized donor center is required to enter your tissue type onto
the National Registry.
</P>
<P>
   The cost for the human leukocyte antigen tissue-typing test is
$35-$90, depending on the donor center, the level of testing
performed, and the laboratory that completes the test. However,
alternative methods for being tested may reduce the cost. For
instance, some donor centers will ask for whole blood or blood
component donations in exchange for the cost of the testing, and
there also may be funding available.
</P>
<P>
   Information can be obtained from local donor centers. For the
National Marrow Donor Program, call 1-800-627-7692. The program's
Web site _ www.marrow.org _ has information and outlines the
surgical marrow extraction procedure, which is done under
anesthesia, and the risk of possible side effects.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A few years ago, I read with interest about a man with AIDS
who tried an experimental treatment using transplanted bone marrow
from a baboon. I haven't heard anything since then. Do you have any
new information?
</P>
<P>
   A: The patient, Jeff Getty of Oakland, Calif., received a
transplant of baboon bone marrow on Dec. 14, 1995. The idea was
that, since baboons appear to be immune from the effects of the
AIDS virus, the AIDS-resistant baboon stem cells might take root in
Getty's bone marrow to produce AIDS-fighting cells. But it didn't
work. Baboon cells were found in his body for only two weeks after
the transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Getty's condition improved dramatically during the
six-month period after the operation. His doctors couldn't explain
why. One possibility, Getty said, was that irradiation therapy
before the surgery slowed his immune system, which in turn weakened
the AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, Getty credited the experiment with
extending his life long enough so he could begin taking the latest
generation of AIDS drugs. In the meantime, Getty has become a
spokesman for ``xenotransplants,'' in which animal organs are
transplanted into humans.
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't been in the news for more than a year, but at last
report his condition was described as ``stable.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you know anything about the Navy vessel USS Gregory,
DD-802? My father served on it, and I was named for it. Also, what
does DD stand for?
</P>
<P>
   A: DD is the Navy`s designation for a destroyer. DD-802, of the
Fletcher class, was built at Seattle-Tacoma Yard in Washington
state and commissioned in 1944. It had a displacement of 2,050 tons
and a length of 375 feet, 6 inches; a complement of 329; a speed of
35 knots; and was outfitted with five torpedo tubes.
</P>
<P>
   The Gregory eventually was turned over to the Naval Weapons
Center at China Lake, Calif., for use as a target, said John Reilly
of the Navy Historical Center.
</P>
<P>
   While some information is available online _
http://metalab.unc.edu/hyperwar/USN/ships/DD/DD-802Gregory.html _
everything that has been written about DD-802 or any Navy ships is
as near as a major library, Reilly said. Look for Volume III of the
Dictionary of American Naval Fighting Ships.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the 10 longest tracks on the NASCAR circuit?
</P>
<P>
   A: The longest is Talladega Superspeedway, Talladega, Ala., at
2.66 miles, followed by: Pocono Raceway, Pocono, Pa., 2.5 miles;
Daytona International Speedway, Daytona Beach, Fla., and
Indianapolis Motor Speedway, Indianapolis, Ind., 2.5 miles; Watkins
Glen International, Watkins Glen, N.Y., 2.45 miles; Heartland Park
Topeka, Topeka, Kan., 2.1miles; California Speedway, Fontana,
Calif., and Michigan Speedway, Brooklyn, Mich., 2 miles; Sears
Point Raceway, Sonoma, Calif., 1.9 miles; and Atlanta Motor
Speedway, Hampton, Ga., 1.54 miles. Information online:
www.nascar.com/tracks.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
