<P>
   EDITORIAL-MOMS _ Editorial urges support for the Million Mom
March. (The Atlanta Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   EDITORIAL-CRIME _ One big flaw in Vice President Al Gore's
prospective crime program unveiled in Atlanta last week was his
advocacy of a so-called victims rights amendment to the
Constitution. Only a few days before, the Senate decided not to
vote on such an amendment, recognizing that boat won't float. Gore
should, too. (The Atlanta Constitution). 8.
</P>
<P>
   McCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Three women are being awarded
honorary doctorates at the University of Dayton on Sunday: Virginia
MacMillan Varga, Sister Mary Peter Traviss, and Evangeline
Lindsley. The honorees all came of age when physical stature _ read
gender _ translated into intellectual and professional stature.
When people really bought into this stuff about ``the weaker sex.''
Boy, did these women prove them wrong. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ According to a New York Times article by
Evelyn Nieves, San Francisco's new ordinance puts size in the same
anti-discrimination codes that already protect people based on
race, religion, color, ancestry, age, sex, sexual orientation,
gender identity, disability and place of birth. (Nethaway, Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ I understand that people all over
town are getting stuck with appraisal hikes so the Austin
Independent School District can send $33 million next year to other
parts of the state to educate other people's children. But I don't
think my little two-bedroom house is worth $91,585.(Kelso, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
