<P>
   EBAY-PAINTING (San Francisco) _ The seller of an abstract
painting on online auction site eBay _ which set off a bidding war
by art lovers who speculated it was a lost masterpiece by late Bay
Area painter Richard Diebenkorn _ admitted to concocting some
details about how he came to discover the piece. By ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   EXAMINER-SALE (San Francisco) _ The fight over the future of San
Francisco's daily newspapers continued in court, as attorneys for
the Fang family tried to shoot holes in the testimony of
consultants for former mayoral candidate Clint Reilly, one of whom
admitted to making multimillion-dollar math errors. By SETH
ROSENFELD. (1STLD-WRITETHRU expected.)
</P>
<P>
   HIGH-SCHOOL-REPORTERS (Berkeley, Calif.) _ High school reporters
Megan Greenwell and Iliana Montauk are finding the price of fame
isn't as bad as they thought. The two have been highly sought by
newspapers and magazines for interviews since The San Francisco
Examiner published a story about how the students first reported
part of a bizarre tale that led to the federal indictment of a
prominent East Bay landlord. By MATTHEW YI.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOB-DANZIG (Houston) _ He's completely comfortable talking about
the metaphysical, but Robert J. ``Bob'' Danzig never expected to
become an advance man for those winged messengers people call
angels. Danzig, 66, left his post running Hearst Newspapers two
years ago to become a motivational speaker and author. In his new
book, ``Angel Threads'' (Frederick Fell Publishers Inc., $14.95),
he recounts stories from his life and others' lives showing how
life journeys can be reshaped by ``angels.'' By CECILE S. HOLMES.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ROCKER (Undated) _ They finally got around to booing John
Rocker in Atlanta the other night. Not because Rocker's sentiments
had just been translated from Der Fuhrer's German to the King's
English. Not because Atlanta Braves fans came down with a case of
collective conscience. It was because he was brought in to protect
a ninth-inning lead but he provided the sort of relief that rat
poison would give to an upset stomach. By STEVE CAMPBELL.
</P>
