<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-20MINUTE-MENUS-ADV24-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV24 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDITORS: For use Wednesday, May 24, or thereafter.)  
 HEALTHY 20-MINUTE MENUS: CUCUMBER, SMOKED FISH AND BEET SALAD  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by 20-MINUTE-MENUS clients. Nonsubscribers can
use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, see end of text. 
 By MARIAN BURROS    
 c.2000 Foxcraft Ltd.    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yogurt. Do you remember the ads showing 100-year-old Russians
who survived to such a ripe old age because they ate yogurt? How
else could you convince people to eat that slightly tart mixture
when sour cream was so much creamier and sweeter.
</P>
<P>
   Some terrible things have happened to yogurt since those good
old days. They have added artificial sweeteners, fake fruit
flavors, sugar, honey. It has gotten so that whatever tart taste
yogurt naturally had is now hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly isn't anything you want to find in a recipe for
goat cheese dressing, a cucumber yogurt salad or one made with
smoked fish and beets.
</P>
<P>
   Plain yogurt may be an acquired taste but it's a taste worth
acquiring. Not only does it drastically reduce the calories in many
dishes, it adds a very appealing taste to others.
</P>
<P>
   In the smoked fish and beet salad the yogurt cuts the sweetness
of the beets and the richness of the fish. It provides a similar
service in the cucumber, raisin, walnut salad. And in the goat
cheese dressing it provides the volume while reducing the calories
in the goat cheese.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes call for nonfat yogurt, but if you aren't worried
about calories or fat you can use whole milk yogurt or low fat
yogurt. Each of these recipes can be prepared in advance and
refrigerated overnight. If you prepare the cucumber raisin salad
ahead, do not add the walnuts until just before serving.
</P>
<P>
   CUCUMBER, SMOKED FISH AND BEET SALAD
</P>
<P>
   16-ounce can beets
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup nonfat plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped chives
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped oregano
</P>
<P>
   1 large Kirby cucumber ( 2 cups chopped)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup thinly sliced red onion
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup smoked salmon, trout, tuna
</P>
<P>
   1. Rinse and drain the beets thoroughly to get rid of the extra
red juice. Cut beets into halves or quarters depending on the size
of the beets.
</P>
<P>
   2. Combine the vinegar, sugar and yogurt.
</P>
<P>
   3. Wash and dry the chives and oregano and chop; add to yogurt
mixture.
</P>
<P>
   4. Wash but do not peel the cucumber. Chop into about 1/4-inch
dice.
</P>
<P>
   5. Slice the onion; cut the smoked fish into bite-size pieces.
</P>
<P>
   6. Add the beets, cucumber and onion to the yogurt mixture and
stir well.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings as side dish
</P>
<P>
   YOUR PANTRY
</P>
<P>
   Balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Sugar
</P>
<P>
   Nonfat plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING LIST
</P>
<P>
   16-ounce can beets
</P>
<P>
   Bunch chives (1 tablespoon)
</P>
<P>
   Bunch oregano (1 tablespoon)
</P>
<P>
   1 large Kirby cucumber (2 cups)
</P>
<P>
   Small red onion (1/2 cup)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup smoked salmon, trout or tuna (about 3 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION INFORMATION PER SERVING: 85 calories, less than 1 gram
fat, no saturated fat, 5 milligrams cholesterol, 5 grams protein,
15 grams carbohydrate, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   CUCUMBER YOGURT SALAD WITH WALNUTS AND RAISINS
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup walnuts pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup raisins, preferably red flame
</P>
<P>
   1 cup plain, nonfat yogurt
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 medium cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds Kirby cucumbers
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1. Stir walnuts and raisins into yogurt with the olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   2. Finely mince the garlic. Wash, trim and and finely chop the
cucumbers. Add garlic and cucumbers to yogurt. Season with pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   YOUR PANTRY
</P>
<P>
   Garlic
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Nonfat plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   Whole black pepper
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING LIST
</P>
<P>
   Small package chopped walnuts
</P>
<P>
   Small package raisins (preferably red flame)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds Kirby cucumbers
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION INFORMATION PER SERVING: 150 calories, 7 grams total
fat, less than 1 gram saturated fat, 1 milligram cholesterol, 50
milligrams sodium, 5 grams protein, 20 grams carbohydrate, 2 grams
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   GOAT CHEESE DRESSING
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces reduced fat goat cheese
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup nonfat plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced scallion
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1. Mash the goat cheese with vinegar, mustard and yogurt until
well blended.
</P>
<P>
   2. Wash, trim and chop scallion and stir into yogurt mixture.
Season with pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: About 1 1/2 cups
</P>
<P>
   Note: To serve with pear slices, eliminate the scallion. Can be
used as a dip, too.
</P>
<P>
   YOUR PANTRY
</P>
<P>
   White wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   Nonfat plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   Whole black pepper
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING LIST
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces reduced fat goat cheese
</P>
<P>
   Bunch scallions (1)
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION INFORMATION PER SERVING: 25 calories, 2 grams fat, 1
gram saturated fat, 5 milligrams cholesterol, 44 milligrams sodium,
2 grams protein, 1 gram carbohydrate, less than 1 gram fiber.
</P>
