<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0880 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-HARGROVE-BOS &LR;      05-10 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-HARGROVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARGROVE NOW HAS A BIRD'S-EYE VIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the last five years, Mike Hargrove awoke with a
feeling of insecurity each day. Now he understands why.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since 1979, he will be sitting in the
visitors clubhouse when his team plays in Cleveland. What happened
to him last December _ when he was fired as Indians manager despite
winning five straight AL Central titles _ was a shocking reminder
that there is no substitute for winning world championships, even
if you've had one of baseball's most dominating ball clubs year
after year. His Indians twice made it to the World Series, in 1995
and 1997, but failed to win it all, and Hargrove was vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Hargrove, the Baltimore Orioles couldn't afford
to work with an all-or-nothing philosophy. They hired Hargrove to
manage, giving him a three-year contract with a club option for
2003.
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove's nine-year record of 721-591 appealled to Baltimore,
and he became the Orioles' fourth manager in six years.
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove knows he has stepped into a lion's cage. The club he
inherited has an average age of 32 years old. The club's mainstay,
Cal Ripken, is one of several players who can become free agents
after the season. That list also includes Harold Baines, Mike
Bordick, Charles Johnson, Will Clark, and Mike Mussina.
</P>
<P>
   In Cleveland, Hargrove's teams averaged 94 wins a season the
last five years. Baltimore's average in that time was 83 wins per
season, and that includes seasons in which Johnson's team won 98
and 88 games, back to back. The Orioles made the playoffs those
years, and won their Division Series, but they lost in the ALCS
both time, to the Yankees and Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove took nothing for granted in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may have been the only person who didn't concede the
division title to the Cleveland Indians,'' he said. ``Each year I
went in there with all my insecurities flaming. I never have
approached anything as a sure bet.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what I'm feeling now is no different in that regard. We're
obviously in a lot more difficult position in the East Division
than it was in the Central. If I have to get up every morning and
affirm to myself that I'm a winner, then there is something
missing. I feel like I've been a winner for a long, long time.''
</P>
<P>
   After a solid 14-10 April, the Orioles have slipped a bit in
May, but they are right on the heels of the Red Sox, with whom they
begin a three-game series in Camden Yards Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Hargrove said, he had trouble making the adjustment to
a new organization. The break with Cleveland was not without pain.
Speculation persisted before the firing that his players were not
responding to his leadership. He'd been around the Indians
organization for 20 years and was an intergal part of the movement
that lifted the club out of the doldrums of the previous three
decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a sense of what happened and what went wrong,'' said
Hargrove. ``But you'd have to go to the other side to get a view of
what they felt brought this on.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem Hargrove had to deal with in Cleveland was
outfielder Albert Belle, who left as a free agent in 1996. The two
were reunited this spring and are apparently friends again.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I found out he was here,'' said Hargrove, ``it didn't
bother me a bit. It was ironic but it didn't cause me to lose any
sleep. Albert has been fantastic since Day One.''
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove said the kind of success Cleveland has been enjoying
won't come overnight in Baltimore. In his first three full seasons
managing the Indians, 1992-94, they were a young team with little
real talent. They won 76, 76, and then 66 games (in the shortened
1994 season). During that period, they started signing up young
players like Belle, Sandy Alomar, Manny Ramirez, Carlos Baerga, and
Jim Thome to long-term contracts. A turning point was the opening
of Jacobs Field in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I took over the Indians in 1991,'' said Hargrove, ``it
was pretty much a mix of veterans and young players. We started the
rebuilding program for real in 1992. That took our payroll down to
$8 million-$10 million. It had been $32 million at the end of the
1991 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of credit has to go to John Hart for directing that
effort. He certainly didn't let any grass grow under his feet. One
of his favorite words is `proactive.' In other words, we would
trade a player in that regard _ too soon rather than too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Orioles can use that same system to cure what ails
them, Hargrove said, ``The Orioles haven't reached that point yet.
But we still feel that the talent level is here. If we get the
right breaks along the way, we can still compete with the Red Sox
and Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weakness of this team so far is our pitching staff. We
haven't pitched well at all. It hasn't been just one player. It's
everybody. But we really feel that it's just a matter of the
pitching staff jelling. The strength is that we swung the bats and
scored runs. We aren't going to steal a lot of bases.''
</P>
<P>
   The retooling of the Orioles might come sooner than later,
according to Hargrove.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony DeMacio, our chief scout, and his staff have done a good
job, especially in this last draft,'' said Hargrove. ``We hope to
stockpile our farm system. It's an ongoing process. I don't want to
say we're where we want to be yet but we've taken big strides in
that direction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
