<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONDO PURCHASE COULD CRIMP RETIREMENT PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I'd like to retire in two years and to buy a condominium. I
plan to copurchase this condo equally with my partner, and we have
set a $300,000 ceiling. I now rent, am single, and have no debts or
dependents. I add $50 a month to my investment in Putnam Growth and
Income and $60 a month to the money market fund. Is my plan
feasible?
</P>
<P>
   J.D., Newton Highlands, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't know how much you feel you will need to live on in
retirement, but I would be more comfortable with a more modest
condo purchase than you seem to have in mind. Let's do some math.
With your current additions of $110 a month to your savings, you
would have $477,752, presuming an overall portfolio return of 8
percent for the next two years. If you then spent $150,000 of it
for the condo, you would have $327,752. You might anticipate a 6.5
percent yield on this if it were invested in a fixed-income
portfolio, providing you with $21,303. Add in Social Security and
you would have a $32,163 annual income stream.
</P>
<P>
   There are two questions here. One is whether that would meet
your living expenses, including condo taxes and maintenance. The
second problem is future inflation. If you put all of your savings
in fixed-income investments and spent the yield, you would have no
protection against the inflation of the later years of your
retirement. Yes, there will likely be small Social Security
increases, but not enough to make a major difference. A better plan
would be to leave a sizable chunk of money in growth investments,
such as the Putnam Growth and Income and MFS Massachusetts
Investors funds _ say $125,000. But that would then reduce the
yield from your fixed-income portfolio to $13,173, and with Social
Security included, you would have a $24,033 income stream in
retirement. Lots of people can live comfortably on such an income.
If you cannot, the alternatives include a more modest condo
purchase, saving more, or retiring later.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I would like to retire from my high-stress job as soon as
possible. I am single with no dependents and contribute $9,600 a
year to my company's 401(k) plan. I need about $50,000 in annual
income. I would do part-time and odd jobs to make up about $8,000
of that income, and draw from my investments for the rest. Am I
dreaming? If I retire now, what kind of income could I safely draw
from my investments? What should be my investment goal in order to
be in a position to retire the way I want?
</P>
<P>
   C.H., Laguna Miguel, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I am guessing what prompted this question at this point.
Probably not by coincidence, if you put your $674,500 portfolio
into fixed-income securities, it would deliver almost precisely
that $42,000 that you feel you would need. But it also would
probably eventually loom as a monumental mistake. This is because
the earlier you retire, the more money you will need to have.
Certainly it is only prudent at your tender age to presume that
most of your life is ahead of you, and if you retire now on what
looks like a manageable budget, inflation will wreak havoc on your
plans _ and pretty quickly, too. I would think that, at a minimum,
you should count on working another five years. At that point, with
8 percent average annual portfolio growth and ongoing contributions
of $9.600 a year, you would have a $1,063,541 accumulation. By that
time, you would need $59,384 to support the life style that $50,000
income provides today. You would need a fixed-income portfolio of
roughly $900,000 to supply that, leaving you with only about
$163,000 to leave in growth vehicles that would protect you against
future inflation. Even that, I feel, is not enough.
</P>
<P>
   So I ran the numbers out to eight years, at which point you
would have an accumulation of $1,383,546 and would require $65,840
to support your target life style. That would mean a fixed-income
portfolio of roughly $1 million, with $383,000 in stocks as your
inflation hedge. A perfect situation? No. You would still be
retiring at age 53, and still have many years before you. The
buffer isn't really big enough, but you could probably pull through
at that stage.
</P>
<P>
   As for the portfolio, I suggest that you trim the money market
holdings to a minimum level that you would feel safe with as
emergency funds, moving the remainder to a Vanguard Index 500
holding. Other than that, it looks fine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Am I doing the right thing, having all my assets in Vanguard
funds? I am 96, but mentally 45. I have been in the markets since
1927 _ in and out. What do you think?
</P>
<P>
   C.R., Chula Vista, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I think you have nothing to worry about. Although all of your
holdings are within the same fund family, what you own is five
separate and distinct business entities, which happen to have the
same management company in common. Each mutual fund within a family
holds its assets separate from those of other funds, and separate
as well from the assets of the parent company which manages the
family's funds. In the case of Vanguard, the parent company is a
mutual entity, owned by the shareholders of the funds that make up
the Vanguard Group. Although the Vanguard Group is a solid entity,
there is one small situation which might give shareholders pause.
This involves owners of the group's money market funds. When a
money market fund gets in trouble with an investment, the worst
possible outcome would be that the fund would have to break the
buck, which is industry jargon for going below the $1 constant
value money market funds seek to maintain. Never in the history of
money market funds has a retail fund broken the buck _ in every
case where such a situation loomed the parent company that
established it has made up the difference, taking blame for the
misjudgment that got the fund in trouble. But since Vanguard is a
mutual company, there are no assets which could be diverted to
rescue a money market fund if it got in trouble. Is this a matter
of scouring a pure blue sky for clouds?: You bet it is. Vanguard's
funds are conservatively and prudently managed, and this is a worry
so tiny that I consider it insignificant. And for the record, in
the past when I have had some cash to park, I have used Vanguard's
Prime Money Market fund _ and slept like a baby.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I was raising two children when I left a job in 1989, so I
bought life insurance. Now the kids are gone, and I would like to
discontinue the policy, invest the cash value in a life insurance
fund, and use the money I had been spending on the premiums for
long-term health care insurance. My question involves the tax
implications. Is this considered ordinary income, or is it
claimable at all? The way I figure it, I paid in about $7,000, and
if there is any tax at all, it should be on what it has gained.
</P>
<P>
   R.C., Scottsdale, Ariz. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. According to J.K. Lasser's ``Your Income Tax,'' you are
correct. If the cash received on the surrender of a policy exceeds
the premiums paid less dividends received, the excess is taxed as
ordinary income. So unless you received dividend checks, the tax
liability would be for about $3,300.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
