</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-INDIANS-BALDWIN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 BALDWIN'S 3-HITTER PUTS HIS FALSE FENWAY STARTS IN PAST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Despite appearances, this was not gallows humor, James
Baldwin insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Some 2 1/2 hours before game time at Fenway Park, the Chicago
White Sox righthander was engaged in some good-natured _ and hardly
strenuous _ wrestling with bullpen catcher Man Soo Lee. It was a
short-lived match, lasting only until one of the White Sox looked
up from the day's ``Masterpiece Theatre'' fare on the clubhouse VCR
_ ``Dumb and Dumber'' _ and, with mock indignation, ordered Lee to
desist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leave him alone,'' the protective teammate warned Baldwin's
adversary in horseplay. ``He's got to work tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a pulled muscle or some such calamity during pregame
hijinks might have been preferable to Baldwin's order of business:
taking the mound at Fenway Tuesday against a team that had savaged
him on the two catastrophic occasions he had ventured there last
season. In an aborted start June 26 and a punitive relief stint two
days later, Baldwin allowed a total of 11 hits and 10 runs in 2 1/3
innings _ a spiffy 38.57 ERA _ as the Red Sox bludgeoned Chicago by
scores of 17-1 and 14-1.
</P>
<P>
   But Baldwin claimed there were no scars on his psyche when he
returned to the scene of the crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always do that,'' he said of his pregame ritual with Lee.
``That's something that I never change, because you've got to keep
the guys loose. You can't worry about going out there and facing
those hitters all the time. If you're going out there thinking
about it, a lot of times you're not going to do too good.''
</P>
<P>
   For proof that ``What, me worry?'' are words to live by, Baldwin
never looked better than he did while doing the unthinkable to the
Red Sox. He made them look like an outtake from ``Dumb and
Dumber,'' flustering them to distraction while registering the
first shutout of his five-year career, a three-hit, 6-0
masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   The only ball hit with authority off him was Troy O'Leary's
first-pitch single to center field in the fifth inning. That was
sandwiched around a pair of Trot Nixon softies _ a bloop single to
left with one out in the first and an infield hit behind second
base opening the ninth _ as Baldwin disposed of Boston in a mere 2
hours 22 minutes, notching 71 strikes and eight strikeouts among
his 102 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, this visit to his 1999 burial ground wasn't
particularly traumatic for Baldwin, but it seems nothing is. He
strives for simplicity, both in execution and analysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just another ballpark,'' he said. ``Last year was last
year. This year is this year. I don't think about stuff like that.
All I think about is going out and throwing strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   His impact was more profound than his assessment. So dominant
was Baldwin that he confounded even his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I saw was him throw his fastball and curveball equally
well,'' said first baseman Paul Konerko, whose sixth-inning single
scored the only run Baldwin needed. ``It seemed that when they were
thinking fastball, he'd throw a curveball. And when they were
thinking curveball, he'd throw a fastball. It's almost like he knew
what they were thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   He sure fooled Konerko, because Baldwin doesn't make things so
complicated. Perhaps that's one reason that while the venue may
have been unlikely, his success wasn't. At 28, the 6-foot-3-inch,
210-pound North Carolina native has blossomed into one of the elite
pitchers in the American League. His 6-0 record is tied for the
league's best, and his 2.34 ERA is among the league's lowest.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox can dolefully attest that he is a revelation,
because while Baldwin has been a consistent double-figure winner
throughout his career, he's never exceeded 13 victories. But while
going an indifferent 12-13 last season, he provided hints of
excellence by winning eight of his last 10 decisions.
</P>
<P>
   How to explain the transformation? Simple, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, I don't think I was attacking the hitters the way I am
this year,'' said Baldwin. ``I'm more aggressive this year.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he now ranks as the bona fide stopper on manager
Jerry Manuel's staff, a status he reinforced tuesday night with
Chicago on a 1-7 skid.
</P>
<P>
   ``JB has been a guy that's saved us a number of times this
year,'' said Manuel. ``Any time we've been on a little slide, he's
been the guy to stop it. You've got to be on a real good roll (to
do that).''
</P>
<P>
   The secret, Baldwin illustrated with his Fenway revival show, is
to roll with the punches. And forget the knockouts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
