<SLUG> BC-BBA-WHITESOX-THOMAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE BIG HURT' TOOK HIS LUMPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Frank Thomas readily accepts the blame. The fault, he
ruefully acknowledges, was entirely his. It's not as if he wasn't
warned, repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   For almost a decade, to be precise, while he was recklessly
establishing himself as a one-man Chicago White Sox pantheon
without regard for the consequences, Thomas had heard the
admonitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I set lofty standards at a fairly young age,'' a chastened
Thomas recalled before a game against the Red Sox at Fenway Park.
``Guys told me it would be tough to match them later.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the cocksure folly of youth, Thomas ignored the sages.
He blithely continued along his path of destruction as baseball's
most protean slugger, compiling Cooperstown credentials while
becoming the only player in history to bat .300 and collect 100
walks, 100 runs, 100 RBIs, and 20 homers for seven consecutive
seasons (1991-97). In fact, only two players _ nonentities named
Lou Gehrig and Ted Williams _ ever hit this superfecta as many as
four years running. But Thomas refused to learn from history.
</P>
<P>
   Just as his doomsaying elders had cautioned, he paid royally for
that stratospheric excellence the past two years. Performances that
most mortals would have killed for _ 35 homers and 125 RBIs in
1998, a .305 average last season _ were considered resounding duds
relative to vintage Thomas. For the first time, soft spots were
exposed _ a .265 average in 1998, a mere 15 homers and 77 RBIs last
season _ where previously there had been none. For just about
anyone else, they could have been overlooked. In the gilded context
created by Thomas, they were glaring.
</P>
<P>
   And they merely led the charge of indignities that besieged
Thomas. He endured the ugly dissolution of his marriage, which had
been unraveling for several years. His volatile relationship with
manager Jerry Manuel, who took over in 1998, was pure tabloid
fodder. He was virtually the lone survivor amid a roster demolition
that left him to compensate for the mistakes of the raw kids who
surrounded him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stuck out like a sore thumb,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He was as fickle as a diva in his indecision about whether to
continue playing first base, his position since he came out of
Auburn University as a 6-foot-5-inch, 270-pound power prototype, or
take cover as the designated hitter. And he was hounded by injuries
_ a bone spur in his right ankle, a corn on his small right toe _
that made a shambles of his classic swing and left him pitifully
vulnerable to the inside stuff that exploitative pitchers gleefully
heaped upon him.
</P>
<P>
   And suddenly, Thomas discovered, there were infidels in the
cathedral. His initial exposure to boos from his former idolators
at Comiskey Park hurt the Big Hurt a lot more than his foot did.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a humbling experience,'' said Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   He can view his desolation from a dispassionate distance now.
Retrospect has been cushioned by renewed success. Thomas again is
wreaking havoc instead of being wracked by it. He is batting .364
with 6 homers and 25 RBIs, numbers more representative of his
eminence. Perhaps an even greater indication was his hauteur, the
prerogative of virtuosos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy with my start,'' he sniffed, ``but it could be a
little better. I feel I should have more homers and doubles.''
</P>
<P>
   He will soon. Manuel and third-year hitting coach Von Joshua are
positive of that. They realize Thomas has been a terror despite
being plagued by a balky hamstring and a sprained right ankle
suffered during the final exhibition of the spring. And they are
giddy in their anticipation because they believe that for the first
time, they are seeing the real Frank Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   From a clinical perspective, Joshua has observed the return of
Thomas's nonpareil swing: ``I see a lot more patience at the plate.
He's back to taking his walks a lot more. He's not diving, not
chasing pitches like he was last year. Pitchers realize they can't
go inside on him anymore. He's not moving his head. He's quieted
his head down quite a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   That assessment has a more cosmic application because Thomas's
head indeed is in a better place.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a different person this year,'' said Joshua. ``He's much
happier, much chirpier. He seems to be more focused on his game.''
</P>
<P>
   Manuel believes that resolve was forged in adversity:
``Unfortunately, I think the negative exposure he received
strengthened him to be better.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Joshua, ``He was locked and loaded from day one. I could
see what made Frank great.''
</P>
<P>
   Attitude, for one thing. Manuel _ who like Thomas dismisses
reports of a rift between player and manager as a media concoction
despite documentation to the contrary _ was heartened when his
reluctant superstar came to him during camp and volunteered to play
first base, which was what Manuel had been trying to sell him all
along.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he wanted to get back on the field, back to being that
Hall of Fame presence,'' said the manager. ``His focus was much
different. He had a completely different mind-set.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas agreees with the psychoanalyses to a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully,'' he said, ``this will be a breakout season to show
I can still do it.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he reminds us, let's not get carried away by
this renaissance. Thomas never stopped doing it; he just stopped
doing it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say I'm back,'' he pointed out, ``because I've
never really gone anywhere.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
