<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALEM'S TIES TO MORMONS RECALLED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA AND MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mention Salem and religion in the same sentence, and most people
immediately think witchcraft. But the Massachusetts community also
has a strong and little-known connection to Mormonism.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Smith, the American prophet whose writings inspired the
founding of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, once
predicted that gold would be found in Salem. He visited Salem as a
young boy and again after founding his church, and numerous Salem
residents followed the church west in the mid-19th Century.
</P>
<P>
   Smith even visited the local museum, the Peabody Essex, signing
the visitors' register in 1836. Now the connections between Smith
and Salem, along with some rare artifacts from the museum's
Phillips Library and the church's Utah headquarters, are the
subject of an exhibition at the Peabody Essex Museum.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit and a series of events in Salem, along with the
expected opening of a Mormon temple in Belmont, Mass. this year,
are expected to draw thousands of Mormons to the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that the Mormon church was going to be building a
temple in the metropolitan Boston area, and we realized that we had
some very critically important pieces of the Mormon past,'' said
William T. La Moy, cocurator of the exhibit. ``We think we have an
interesting representation of how the church evolved and moved
west.''
</P>
<P>
   Mormon officials, who loaned several objects to the exhibit, are
delighted.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of our members did not know how rich Salem was in church
history,'' said Sue Schmidt, regional public affairs director for
the Mormons. ``People had no idea Joseph Smith had been to Salem,
or that some of the early members at Salem contributed greatly to
the success of the church.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith was born in 1805 in Sharon, Vt., to a family that had
lived for generations in Topsfield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   In 1813, after doctors had bored holes into his leg bone in an
effort to combat typhoid fever, Smith's mother sent her 8-year-old
son to Salem in the hopes that the sea breeze would speed his
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1836, after forming a church that he said restored an
ancient form of Christianity, Smith returned to Salem to explore
the possibility of establishing a base there.
</P>
<P>
   Smith had prophesied that gold would be found in Salem, and his
followers later concluded that the prophesy was metaphorical,
referring to the wealth of people heading from Salem to the West. A
Salem Mormon named Nathaniel H. Felt, who at one point provided
housing to Smith's successor, Brigham Young, ultimately led about
100 Salem residents west.
</P>
<P>
   Mormonism was controversial in Massachusetts, but not nearly as
controversial as in the Midwest, where Mormons were persecuted and
Smith was murdered in Illinois in 1844. Among the exhibits are
early chronicles of the Mormon stay in Salem from a newspaper
called the Essex Gazette, a pro-Mormon broadside and an anti-Mormon
tract from Salem illustrating that the church was the subject of
debate, and 19th Century engravings showing the Mormons travelling
west in handcarts and wagons.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit, ``From New England to the Great Salt Lake,''
features a number of rare items from the Peabody Essex collection,
including a letter from Smith detailing church persecution in
Missouri, rare first and fourth editions of the Book of Mormon, and
original guidebooks used by Mormons traveling west in the early
19th Century. The church has provided the museum with sculptures,
paintings, etchings, photographs, and lithographs from its own
collection in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit also includes a genealogy work room where visitors
can explore their family trees. The Mormon church emphasizes
genealogy because of its belief that the dead can be baptized and
thereby achieve salvation.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit runs through Aug. 27 at museum ($10 admission for
adults. Information: 800-745-4054, www.pem.org).
</P>
<P>
   A variety of events are taking place in conjunction with the
exhibit, including concerts, walking tours, and lectures
(Information: 877-SALEM-MA, www.salem.org).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sacrament of the Sick
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since early in the second century, if not before, Christians
have attempted to replicate the healing power of Jesus with rituals
in which priests lay hands on, anoint, and pray over the sick.
</P>
<P>
   The ritual was known as unction, meaning anointing. By the early
middle ages, it had become extreme unction because it was performed
as part of the last rites for dying individuals, and its purpose
had shifted from physical healing to a healing of ``the sickness of
soul that might keep you from everlasting life,'' according to the
Rev. Richard N. Fragomeni, a professor of liturgy and preaching at
Catholic Theological Union in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``My own grandmother didn't want a priest to come when she was
sick, because that would be seen as a sign that she was dying,''
Fragomeni said.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic bishops gathering at the Second Vatican Council of the
mid-1960s decided to restore the rite to its ancient purpose,
replacing the rite of extreme unction with what is now termed the
sacrament of the sick.
</P>
<P>
   The ritual, which still includes prayer, anointing with oil, and
laying on of hands, is now performed by priests for anyone in
physical or mental pain, whether chronic or acute, and not just for
those on their deathbed.
</P>
<P>
   The Spiritual Life welcomes questions about religion and
suggestions for stories by mail to Religion News, PO Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107-2378, or by e-mail to religion(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
