<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL SUBURBAN MOMS BE THERE IN NOVEMBER? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I &UR;  &LR; should be clear that in the most violent nation in the
wealthy world, I am happy that a Million Mom March exists at all.
The mom of our two boys is going. Her mom is going. It is not every
Mother's Day that mothers go to Washington to attempt to change the
course of human hist, er, herstory.
</P>
<P>
   It is exciting. Underneath the surface, it is also an
excruciating political and racial moment. Sunday's Million Mom
March certainly will be a momentous photo op if enough black and
brown mothers of bullet-riddled inner cities lock arms with white
mothers of suburban privilege. There is undeniable power in seeing
a rainbow of women who, like my wife and mother-in-law, would not
join the National Rifle Association if you held a . . . I guess
this is not the right moment for that cliche.
</P>
<P>
   That is power for a moment. The question is whether there is
enough power for a movement. This is where the Million Mom March
becomes a racial question. The legacy of the rally utterly depends
on whether white mothers return home to muzzle the guns of America
where it counts, in the voting booth.
</P>
<P>
   The Million Mom March plays on the notion that women, spared the
horrors of testosterone, can nurture us away from Columbine, from
deaths like 6-year-old Kayla Rolland and garden variety gunshots in
domestic disputes and drug deals. On the gun issue alone, that
would seem to be the case. A recent Pew poll found that 73 percent
of women make controlling gun ownership a higher priority than gun
owners' rights, compared to 59 percent of men.
</P>
<P>
   If white women were voting solely for the president most likely
to take gun control seriously, the November election would be a
done deal. Republican candidate George W. Bush supports gun
ownership far more shamelessly than Democrat Al Gore. While Gore
has made modest restrictions part of his stump speech, Bush, the
Texas governor, signed into law the right to carry concealed
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   So far, guns have not affected Bush's poll numbers with women. A
poll by Emily's List, a women's Democratic fund-raising group,
found Gore to be only 6 percentage points ahead of Bush among
women. A poll by the political newspaper Hotline found Bush to be
four percentage points ahead of Gore among women.
</P>
<P>
   Last week a Wall Street Journal/NBC News poll found Bush to have
an overall lead over Gore, 46 percent to 41 percent. The Journal's
poll found Bush to lead Gore by 15 percentage points overall in the
suburbs and by 10 percentage points among white women. Any overall
leads Gore has in any polls among women are due to his guaranteed
support among African-American women, who have been sick of guns
for a long time and would not vote for Bush if you held a _ OK, OK,
I quit.
</P>
<P>
   The volatility of white women voters was seen in the 1992
presidential election. Bill Clinton made far more obvious overtures
to women than Republican rival George Bush. Yet white women split,
41 percent to 41 percent, for Clinton and Bush. ``A majority of
white women supported neither the Democratic Party nor President
Clinton in the 1990s,'' Anna Greenberg of Harvard University's
Kennedy School of Government has said.
</P>
<P>
   A huge example of white women leaders marching one way and white
women voters fleeing in the opposite direction has been affirmative
action. When affirmative action went before the voters in
California and Washington state, groups such as the National
Organization for Women, urged women to keep it.
</P>
<P>
   White women have benefited from affirmative action more than
people of color. But opponents of affirmative action successfully
cast the issue only in terms of black people getting unfair
advantages. In both states, white women decisively voted to kill
affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   The Million Mom March was organized mainly by white
suburbanites. They should get credit for recognizing how late they
came to the issue after a violent 1980s and early 1990s in
low-income neighborhoods of color. The creator of the Million Mom
March, Donna Dees-Thomases is honest enough to say that she did not
care deeply about gun violence until the victims ``looked like my
children.''
</P>
<P>
   But coming late to an issue means there is that much more work
to do with white women back home. Bush may be bad on guns, but so
far he is winning over many white suburban women with his rhetoric
on education. That could be a decisive factor in November since
Gore will likely lose the white male vote by as much as a 2-to-1
margin.
</P>
<P>
   So there is no telling what the legacy of the Million Mom March
might be. The progun Bush is bridging the gender gap. Gore is for
some gun restrictions, but does not yet have enough white women in
the fold to overcome his deficit with white men.
</P>
<P>
   If Gore becomes president, there is a chance for some headway on
guns. If Bush gets in, you will not get him to sign a gun control
measure if you held a . . . sorry. The Million Mom March is a
moment. To muzzle guns requires a movement. The movement has to
march to the ballot box. November will begin to tell us if a
million moms can change the course of American herstory, or if guns
will remain as American as mom and apple pie.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
