<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000510.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0897 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WORKING-MILLIONAIRES-     05-10 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-MILLIONAIRES-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... not working.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of course, the notion of work might seem considerably more
attractive when you own the company and have the power and perks
that go with being in charge. But not everyone who has plenty of
money to retire sits in the corner office. Robert Gamble, 40, and
his wife, Martha Miller, 41, are both nurse practitioners even
though, when he turned 18, Gamble was startled to discover that he
had just come into $2 million in family wealth. The money grew over
the years, and despite the couple's best attempts to give it all
away to a variety of social causes (``The trust officers and my
family thought we were out of our minds,'' Gamble muses), some of
the money still remains. In his adult life, Gamble has been a
carpenter, a construction laborer, and a human rights worker in El
Salvador, among other things. Today the couple, who have three
children, work for the Boston Health Care for the Homeless Program
treating people with AIDS, severe alcohol abuse, pneumonia, and
other problems of street life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of wanting to work is the Protestant work ethic, I
guess,'' says Gamble. ``But working is also part of what links you
to other people. It's a way of being connected. It's important for
me to be involved with something worthwhile, but I also enjoy
interacting with people _ personally, philosophically, and
spiritually _ who are on the fringes. It's important for me to
participate.''
</P>
<P>
   June Tatelman would say much the same thing. Neither Tatelman
nor her husband would seem to have to work, given that Eliot
Tatelman is the Eliot of Barry and Eliot, the ubiquitous brothers
of Jordan's Furniture and the chain's quirky TV ads. Last year the
duo sold the local four-store family business, which they joined 27
years ago when it had one showroom and five employees, for an
undisclosed sum reported to be at least $250 million. The Tatelman
brothers continue to run the company, with Eliot admitting that ``I
still stick my nose into everything.'' But June Tatelman, 52, works
despite the family's financial success, too. And she does not
oversee a company that now employs 1,300 people.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she rises at 6 a.m. each weekday to get ready for her
job as a teacher at a Middle School in Sudbury. It is there that
she teaches wellness classes _ on sexuality, decision making,
conflict resolution, and the like _ to seventh- and eighth-graders.
Like Gamble, she talks about the lure of making attachments through
her work, of connecting closely with a group of people she would
probably never encounter otherwise. ``I get attached to new kids
every year,'' she says. ``Sure, some days they drive me out of my
mind. But we talk about subjects'' that are hard ``for kids to talk
about. When they're talking to me like that, and they're listening,
I think I get more from them than they get from me.
</P>
<P>
   ``So retirement is meaningless,'' she says. ``It's like retiring
from life.''
</P>
<P>
   For some well-heeled people who continue to work, staying on the
job has given them both the wherewithal and the clout to do the
right thing. Tatelman and her husband operate a weeklong summer
camp for children infected and affected by AIDS, for example. Singh
has started a foundation to fund a grade school in India that he
attended as a child. And Novack has set up a family foundation that
focuses on disadvantaged youths. Says Connors, who has been a
contributor to and fund-raiser for a number of local causes:
``Visibility and power _ or maybe the illusion of power _ can be
used for good. I can raise a lot more money as chairman and CEO of
Hill Holliday than as the former chairman and CEO.''
</P>
<P>
   Connors, who started his ad agency with $1,500 ($1,000 of it
borrowed) 32 years ago, can look about 500 feet down and two blocks
north from his present office and pick out his former quarters. He
says the value of the approximately $115 million in stock he
received when he sold the company to Interpublic Group of Companies
has virtually doubled. ``But retire?'' he asks. ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't ever been promoted,'' Connors adds, grinning. ``I've
got the same title I had in 1968. Picasso supposedly dropped his
brush and died. Charles Schulz, too. This is what I do. I work.
It's not a four-letter word.''
</P>
</TEXT>
