u f BC-WORKING-MILLIONAIRES-     05-10 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-MILLIONAIRES-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 TAKE THE MONEY AND RUN? NOT THESE GO-GETTERS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
``Every morning I get up and look through the Forbes list of the
richest people in America. If my name isn't on it, I go to work.'' 
_ Sign posted at Maynard, Mass. headquarters of monster.com,
world's largest career Web site. 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ And even if their names were on it, they would probably
go to work. Susan Bailis, who four years ago reaped the financial
benefits of selling Massachusetts' largest provider of elder care,
certainly would. So would Robert Gamble, who is a $25-an-hour nurse
practitioner despite inheriting a fortune that wended its way down
from the 19th-century founder of Procter &AMP; Gamble Co. And so would
Jeff Taylor, 39, who is monster.com's CEO/founder and puts his net
worth at somewhere over $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   You might think, with a firecracker 1990s economy that minted
each new multimillionaire faster than you could shout ``Call my
broker!'' that the notion of retirement would be as hot as the next
IPO. You might think that all those buyout beneficiaries,
fat-pocket heirs, and dot-com cowboys (despite the recent stock
market volatility) would have been eyeballing the Palm Beach real
estate ads, working full time on their golf games, and generally
contemplating a life wherein their most difficult chore would be
squeezing the tomatoes at the local Publix supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   You might be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Bailis. Once a $7,600-a-year-social worker, the
54-year-old entrepreneur found herself in 1996 with ``more money
than I'd ever seen.'' She and her partner, Alan Solomont, had just
sold ADS Group for $100 million, and although she will not reveal
her share of the proceeds, Bailis says she could have retired more
than comfortably. Instead, she and Solomont eventually formed a
small company that operates a number of elder care ventures. ``I
never, even for a moment, considered not working,'' Bailis says
firmly. (There is another reason, besides money, that she might be
expected to do something else with her time: She has Stage IV
metastatic breast cancer.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Work provides a structure to my life,'' Bailis explains as she
sits in an upholstered wing chair in her large, bright office hard
by the Massachusetts Turnpike. ``I need an office to come to, a
place that's a station for me, a place where work gets parceled out
and letters get written. And work gives me self-esteem because it's
doing something that society puts a value on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Work, for me, is one of the basic nutrients of life. I don't
take vitamins. I take work.''
</P>
<P>
   For others who have clearly acquired the means to retire, work
is a prescription that is taken for an assortment of reasons:
</P>
<P>
   --Taylor, a former disc jockey who created monster.com based on
a dream he had at 4 o'clock in the morning and whose goal is to be
US secretary of labor, talks about the ego rush he gets from mixing
his ``personal brand'' with his company's brand.
</P>
<P>
   --Jack Connors, 57, who sold his advertising firm of Hill
Holliday Connors Cosmopulos for a reported $115 million two years
ago, says he has stayed in his corner office 39 floors above Boston
because he feels he is ``one of an increasing number of people who
don't want to stop growing.''
</P>
<P>
   --Jerry Greenberg, 34, a former Harvard University wrestler who
founded Sapient Corp., a successful Cambridge, Mass. company that
facilitates Internet commerce, looks at work partly as a kind of
competition and declares that ``the absence of stress would make it
awful.''
</P>
<P>
   --Irma Mann, 65, who sold Irma Mann Strategic Marketing 17
months ago, has remained with the company and will begin teaching
at Boston University in September because, she said, ``I'm not into
rocking chairs, and I want to be in the mix of the action.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, work is for many people simply a fire that the
acquisition of riches cannot extinguish. In the muted downtown
Boston offices of Loring, Wolcott &AMP; Coolidge, where $5.6 billion in
individual and family wealth is managed, senior trustee Lawrence
Coolidge _ whose own eventually prosperous Yankee family arrived on
Boston's shores in 1630 _ contends that most of his clients keep
their noses to the grindstone even though they have more than
enough financial resources to do otherwise. ``Too much of nothing
makes a fellow mean,'' announces the bow-tied, Coolidge, 64,
quoting Bob Dylan. Then he adds a lyric of his own: ``It's not a
very satisfying life to be a sybarite.''
</P>
<P>
   For some folks, then, work is a kind of moral imperative. J.
Stuart Moore, who founded Sapient with Greenberg in a basement
nearly a decade ago in no small part through the liberal use of 13
personal credit cards, can today tabulate his stake in the publicly
owned company at more than $1 billion. When Moore, 38, talks about
work, he echoes the clerical zeal of money manager Coolidge: ``A
life of leisure isn't a meaningful life,'' he says. ``It isn't a
satisfying life. I know I couldn't live that way.''
</P>
<P>
   True, Moore takes his five children bike riding, power boating,
and skiing on the weekend. He says he consciously tries to
``engineer'' a life that combines family with work. But he also
speaks of work in almost spiritual tones, contending that ``you
have an obligation to deploy your capabilities, and if you don't do
that you'll end up in a bad place.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the Charles River, in a comfortable second-floor office
overlooking the Boston Public Garden, Kenneth Novack views his work
similarly, as a kind of crusade. The 58-year-old attorney, who is
the vice chairman of America Online Inc. and holds about $300
million in unexercised stock options (``I've also got substantial
assets outside the company,'' he says), is a true believer in AOL
chairman Steve Case and the firm's stated goal of making online
connectivity as ubiquitous as the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Stop working? At 58? Not while ``we're all pointing at the same
star,'' Novack replies eagerly. ``We have other people in the
company worth over $100 million, too,'' he adds. ``Why do we work?
Because we really believe we have that mission. Certainly, we don't
have to work.''
</P>
<P>
   For many dot-com types in particular, work means creating an
environment where they do not mind spending a lot of their time.
Consider Jeet Singh, 36, who cofounded Art Technology Group, now a
publicly owned e-commerce software developer, with his partner
Joseph Chung in an apartment nine years ago. Today Singh, who is
given to wearing jeans and cowboy boots around the office, likes to
point to the wide open spaces of Art Technology's Cambridge
headquarters, where cubicles are absent and there are amenities
such as a pool table and on-site massages. ``When we started, Joe
and I talked about the environment we wanted,'' Singh says. ``We
talked a lot about what the work lifestyle was going to be. We
asked ourselves, `Can you build a company where, if it succeeds,
you'd want to hang around?' So we set out to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh and Chung began Art Technology with $5,000. Each now owns
about $416 million worth of stock in the company. ``We thought that
if we made $10 million in our lifetime that we'd be done, then we
wouldn't have to work any more,'' says Singh, who has not moved out
of his South End home since striking it rich but has added an
airplane to his personal assets and is shopping for a home on St.
Bart's. ``Now it's very difficult to imagine myself not working.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
