<HEADLINE>
FINDING A STORY OF REDEMPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps this is a good time to climb on a soap box.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI Inc., on the downside of its wildest-ever six-month stock
gyration, has lost nearly two-thirds of its value since a January
peak.
</P>
<P>
   Initial public stock offerings of CMGI portfolio companies,
including portal offering AltaVista Co., were pulled when the
market came tumbling down. The prices of other public companies
that count CMGI as a big shareholder have suffered shocking
corrections.
</P>
<P>
   With that backdrop, CMGI will take its turn thursday with dozens
of other technolgoy companies presenting their stories to investors
this week at the 28th Annual Chase Hambrecht &AMP; Quist Technology
Conference in San Francisco, certainly one of the two or three most
important tech investment forums of the year.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't anything special about an Internet company that rode
a hot stock toward the end of 1999 into the first months of this
year, only to get shelled soon thereafter. But CMGI shares were
driven to extremes, soaring higher and crashing harder than most
Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its movements are amplified because a lot of the valuation in
the stock reflects the potential for the initial public offerings
of its subsidiaries and venture funds,'' said analyst Phil Leigh of
Raymond James.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Internet stocks are moving up, the environment for IPOs
is much more favorable. When they move down, the environment
becomes much less favorable,'' he said. Other Internet business
development companies, like Internet Capital Group, took similar
hard falls.
</P>
<P>
   The question of the moment: Can investment conference exposure
help a stock like CMGI right now, or does it remain at the mercy of
an overpowering investment tide? And what story would the Andover,
Mass. company need to tell to make a difference?
</P>
<P>
   Telling the story and getting others to repeat it is an
important process. Consider what was happening in mid-November,
just as CMGI shares were beginning to move higher.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 15, a Monday on which CMGI shares closed at a
split-adjusted $50.625, Internet investment bank Wit Capital
Research initiated coverage of the company with a buy
recommendation. The next day, CMGI chief David Wetherell presented
the company story to investors at the Bloomberg Internet conference
in San Francisco. The following day, Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co. initiated
coverage of CMGI with a buy recommendation, and a Prudential
Securities analyst raised his price forecast for the stock.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the week, CMGI shares had appreciated by about 25
percent and would continue to move smartly higher until
mid-December, when infuential Internet analyst Henry Blodget of
Merrill Lynch initiated coverage of CMGI. That day, CMGI shares
surged 21 percent to a split-adjusted $135.125.
</P>
<P>
   While Internet stocks were rising sharply, CMGI had roared ahead
by 170 percent in a period of about six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   True, the CMGI IPO-driven performance was adding fuel to the
market's Internet mania at the time. But how did CMGI's biggest IPO
of all, the offering of AltaVista first announced in December, fit
into the picture?
</P>
<P>
   ``The (CMGI) story was being promoted, there's no question about
it,'' said analyst Ullas Naik of First Albany Corp. ``But in the
background, CMGI is telling a lot of these large brokerages that if
you want to compete for the AltaVista IPO, you have to cover
CMGI.''
</P>
<P>
   And most of the companies CMGI had helped take public were
generating mind-boggling returns for their investors. Companies
with less than $10 million in quarterly revenue were reaching
valuations in the range of $8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was a time when some investors came to the
conclusion that any CMGI company was dipped in magic waters,'' said
Leigh.
</P>
<P>
   That was powerful stuff, considering CMGI had dozens more in the
pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Internet bubble burst, it hurt perhaps worst of all
for many of those same public CMGI portfolio companies. Navisite
Inc. has plunged 75 percent from its March high. Ventro Corp.
(formerly called Chemdex) has sunk 89 percent from a February peak,
and Engage Inc. is down 77 percent from a March high. Critical Path
Inc. has lost nearly two-thirds of its value from its high this
year and Mothernature.com is down nearly 80 percent in 2000 so far.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the long fall, CMGI stock analysts remain almost
universally bullish on the company. Leigh, Naik, and others
describe CMGI as a superior Internet investment: diversified,
backed by plenty of money, and matched with high-quality partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you buy CMGI now and put it away for five or 10 years,
you're going to do extremely well,'' said Naik.
</P>
<P>
   The catch: Like every other public Internet company, it must
demonstrate the ability to produce money makers. That means
portfolio companies may stay private longer to mature before they
hit the public market.
</P>
<P>
   It's not so fast a track, but better news for everyone in the
long run. It might even be the story for the soap box.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
