<HEADLINE>
SOME SAY ECONOMIC MEASURES THAT MATTER ARE FEW, FLAWED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Don't check your stocks every day, most financial
advisers say. Rebalance your portfolio once a year, or every
quarter at most. Ignore the daily swings in the market.
</P>
<P>
   That can be hard to do when newspapers and financial news
broadcasters offer a river of stock market data. And increasingly,
our round-the-clock media also offer a flood of economic numbers.
Almost every day brings a new statistic on the health of the
economy, along with analysts willing to say what it means for the
stock market.
</P>
<P>
   But if you shouldn't check your portfolio every day, why should
you constantly take the temperature of the economy?
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these numbers are just clutter in my head,'' said
Allan Meltzer, an economist at Carnegie-Mellon University in
Pittsburgh and leader of a Federal Reserve-watching panel called
the Shadow Open Market Committee. ``They mostly tell me what's
already happened, not what's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The clutter comes not only from the sheer number of economic
indicators, but because most are revised several times as more
information becomes available. A news story on gross domestic
product may be reporting the second or even third iteration of a
number that was announced a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, a single indicator may contain conflicting messages.
Last month, for example, the government reported that housing
construction took its biggest tumble in six years. That's good,
economists said; it suggests that economic growth is moderating,
and the Fed might not raise interest rates much more.
</P>
<P>
   But the same report said a key part of the construction sector _
single-family homes _ was actually growing faster than before.
That's bad; the economic boom seems unbridled, after all.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the government announced that gross domestic product
was lower than expected for the most recent quarter. (That's good;
growth is slowing.) But the same report said that consumer spending
grew by its fastest pace in 17 years. (Never mind; fast growth lies
ahead.)
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, a person can be reasonably well-informed while
bypassing most economic statistics. The trade balance,
durable-goods orders, the index of leading economic indicators _
all these are often reported and easily ignored, many analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   For the average investor, there are two or three economic
reports worth following: employment, gross domestic product, and
the consumer price index. ``Those are the headline numbers _ not
only to stay educated, but because the Fed looks at the same
things,'' said Wayne Ayers, chief economist at FleetBoston
Financial Corp.
</P>
<P>
   And a main reason for studying economic data is to keep abreast
of the Fed.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's job is to keep inflation low. If the economy is
growing quickly and seems likely to spark inflation, the Fed
probably will raise interest rates to cool the economy.
</P>
<P>
   But higher rates tend to hurt the stock market. When credit is
expensive, consumers cut back on their spending, and businesses
have to pay more for their own borrowing. The result is lower
corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, investors may want to guess the direction of
interest rates to help determine the fair price for a stock.
</P>
<P>
   Employment, gross domestic product, and the consumer price index
are broad measures of economic growth and inflation. Some of the
numbers _ and the numbers behind the numbers _ give clues to the
future of the economy. Others show only what has occurred already.
</P>
<P>
   The monthly employment report, for example, includes the
unemployment rate, which is a lagging indicator of economic
activity. It tends to rise only after the economic growth has
peaked and already is starting to slow.
</P>
<P>
   But the same report gives data on hourly earnings, which is
considered a leading indicator of inflation. When companies have to
pay workers more, they eventually may raise the prices of their
products.
</P>
<P>
   The employment report is the result of two government surveys:
one of households and one of businesses. In the first, the
government asks people to say whether they are employed and, if
not, whether they are looking for work. This not only shows how
many Americans are working but how many are potential workers who
happen to be out of a job just now. That information is important:
The economy cannot grow very much unless it can draw on more
workers.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of businesses is considered more accurate. ``The
sample is more reliable and actually shows what people are doing,
as opposed to what they want to do or say they are doing,'' said
Ayers. This survey shows how many people are on payrolls, giving a
second snapshot of the number of working Americans and a sense of
how robust economic activity is. The business survey also produces
information about hourly earnings, hours worked, and other aspects
of working life.
</P>
<P>
   The king of all economic statistics is gross domestic product _
or GDP. But it is produced quarterly, whereas the unemployment
report comes out monthly.
</P>
<P>
   GDP is considered the broadest measure of economic activity, a
single number that considers everything from consumers at shopping
malls to government spending on tanks and roads, business
investment in computers and factories, and international trade. It
is expressed as a dollar amount representing the total value of
goods and services produced in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But because so many factors go into the GDP, it can be useful to
read each quarter's report and consider the numbers behind the
headline number.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of ways to get to a particular GDP total,''
said Larry Horwitz, senior economist with Primark Decision
Economics in Boston. ``You can have lots of defense spending and
just a few cars sold, or lots of cars and just a few guns. Did we
export a tremendous amount and yet have a fairly weak domestic
economy, or is it the other way around?
</P>
<P>
   ``All these things give you the same GDP number, but the
implications for the future are quite different.''
</P>
<P>
   Another factor colors the GDP number: Not all of its components
are considered equally reliable. Business inventories, for example,
are part of the GDP and can indicate whether a recession is on the
way. When companies make a lot of things that remain on store
shelves, it suggests that consumers have stopped buying and that
factories will have to slow production.
</P>
<P>
   However, each quarter's earliest GDP number is based on an
incomplete survey of inventories at businesses, said Roger Brinner,
chief economist at Parthenon Group, a Boston consulting and
investment firm.
</P>
<P>
   And inventory is hard to measure. ``It's a relatively small
number for any one business establishment, and you're adding up a
ton of things _ inventories held by manufacturers, retailers,
wholesalers,'' said Horwitz. ``It's hard to capture.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the GDP may contain unreliable numbers about
international trade. The government keeps tabs on imports, because
it taxes so many of them. But exports are harder to track. The
government only gets a solid sense of exports over time, after
checking with trading partners, several economists said.
</P>
<P>
   There is even more debate about the reliability of the consumer
price index, or CPI, one of several government measures of
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The CPI measures prices at the consumer level, as opposed to the
prices that manufacturers and other businesses pay for goods.
Responding to critics, the government recently adjusted the CPI to
take better account of new technologies, such as cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   But some consumer groups also complain that the CPI does not
capture enough of the rising cost of drugs, health insurance, and
property taxes. And some economists say the index does a poor job
of considering that the quality of products also improves over
time, that cars and computers have become better. If prices are
rising, it is important to know that consumers also are getting
more for their money.
</P>
<P>
   Economists add two other caveats when considering economic data.
First, remember that the numbers for one quarter are often
``annualized,'' or amplified as if they represent a year's worth of
activity. This is done to make comparisons among numbers easier.
But it also means that a small change in one quarter can leave the
false impression that it is really a big change.
</P>
<P>
   For example, said Brinner, the government may revise a quarter's
GDP figure by a meager 0.1 percent. When annualized, the change
becomes a more significant 0.4 percent, ``and the markets get all
excited,'' Brinner said. But at heart, the government is only
making a small change in its view of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The second caveat is that the government is always revising its
numbers, which can yield big changes in our view of the past.
</P>
<P>
   When President Richard M. Nixon imposed wage and price controls
in 1971, the available numbers showed that inflation was
escalating. ``But the data have been revised so that it doesn't
look now like there was much inflation,'' said Murray Weidenbaum,
who led the White House Council of Economic Advisers during the
early Reagan administration. ``The current version of the data says
they shouldn't have done anything.''
</P>
<P>
   When inventory data were revised after the Arab oil embargo of
1973-74, they showed that the nation had been awash in unsold
products. ``It totally changed the view of the world for policy
makers,'' said Horwitz. ``The economy was much sicker than people
thought'' because of the embargo.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, the Labor Department revised several decades'
worth of productivity data and found a sharper rise during the
1990s than previously thought. For some analysts, the new numbers
were proof that the Internet and computer technology are truly
making businesses and workers more efficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every number gets revised many times. Don't hang onto any one
number,'' warned Weidenbaum. ``The past is as uncertain as the
future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 1351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
