<SLUG> BC-CMGI-DOWNTURN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECH-SECTOR DOWNTURN PUSHES CMGI INTO LAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CMGI Inc. has been one of the nation's highest-flying Internet
investment companies, but lately it has resorted to a distinctly
old economy tactic: layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Two companies controlled by CMGI have eliminated 72 jobs in
recent weeks as the parent company presses its divisions to control
costs amid a general downturn in the technology sector.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Internet search firm AltaVista Co., majority-owned
by CMGI, has cut about 60 jobs since last fall and is considering
more cuts, following last month's postponement of its initial
public offering.
</P>
<P>
   Like other Internet stocks, CMGI's shares have fallen sharply.
They closed at $56.625 Tuesday, down 61 percent since early March.
While the layoffs have affected just a small fraction of CMGI's
5,000 employees, they reflect a shift in focus away from pure
growth to business fundamentals _ a shift also playing out in other
Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors have sent out a loud and clear signal: `Show us that
you're going to move to profitability,' '' said CMGI spokesman Bill
White. Once, he said, CMGI was concerned its units build their user
base and market share; now, he said, ``We think every single (CMGI)
company should be looking at both revenue and expenses.''
</P>
<P>
   CMGI is best known for the minority stakes it holds in Internet
companies such as Lycos Inc. CMGI also holds majority positions in
16 operating companies, including AltaVista, CMGI Solutions, and
MyWay.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI hadn't announced the recent job cuts, but Tuesday the
company confirmed about 45 jobs are being eliminated from its CMGI
Solutions Web site development unit.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the jobs will be shed from among the roughly 150
employees the company has at offices in Andover, Mass. and in
Washington, D.C. The positions are being eliminated as CMGI
combines the unit with Tallan Inc. of Glastonbury, Conn., in which
it purchased a majority stake for about $920 million in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, CMGI also confirmed its MyWay.com unit would lay off
27 employees as it changes its strategy to focus on selling
services to larger companies.
</P>
<P>
   The 60 jobs eliminated at AltaVista, based in Palo Alto, Calif.,
were first reported by The Industry Standard magazine, and mainly
relate to a shift at AltaVista's Shopping.com unit from a consumer
goods site to a shopping directory service.
</P>
<P>
   AltaVista spokesman David Emanuel said the company added other
jobs in recent months that offset the cuts. He and CMGI's White
said the parent company also has tried to find jobs at its other
units for most employees whose positions were eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   But more layoffs could be coming. ``We're studying further cuts
as we respond to market conditions,'' Emanuel said. AltaVista has
about 800 employees, including about 80 in Andover, where its
Raging Bull investor chat service is based.
</P>
<P>
   Adams Harkness analyst Steven Frankel said the cuts show CMGI is
paying heed to new market dynamics. ``Nowhere is it etched in stone
that the Internet was a pathway to riches for everyone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But AltaVista should be careful its layoffs don't undercut its
progress toward an initial public offering, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 1352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
