<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON SUFFERS FROM `WEST WING' ENVY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   These days in Washington, it's hard to tell ``The West Wing''
from The White House without a scorecard.
</P>
<P>
   Cast members of NBC's hit drama about the inner workings of
President Josiah Bartlet's (Martin Sheen) administration were the
main attraction at the recent White House Correspondents'
Association Dinner. Early this month, the actors were in Washington
filming the secret season-ending blockbuster episode that will air
next week. And USA Today political columnist Walter Shapiro was
recently dining with a cabinet member when show's 9 p.m. Wednesday
air time approached. ``Oh my God,'' Shapiro recalls the official
exclaiming. ``I've got to tape `The West Wing.' ''
</P>
<P>
   So pervasive is this art-imitating-life phenomenon that at the
correspondents' dinner, President Clinton jokingly noted that
``West Wing'' 's ``first season got a lot better ratings than mine
did.''
</P>
<P>
   There may be more to that than just Beltway party patter. ``The
West Wing'' is certainly a solid ratings success, ranking 27th
among prime time shows. Brill's Content magazine published a cover
story saying the program ``beats the Washington press corps to the
real story'' of White House politics. Even more impressive is ``The
West Wing'' 's popularity at a time when people seem to feel
cynical about politics, detached from Washington, and worn down by
``Clinton fatigue.''
</P>
<P>
   In a March issue of the Weekly Standard magazine, contributing
editor John Podhoretz concluded that ``West Wing'' creator Aaron
Sorkin took ``the story of the Clinton White House and eliminated
what he sees as its most troubling aspect'' _ Bill Clinton. (Like
Clinton, Bartlet is a liberal/centrist with an eager young staff,
but unlike the president, he projects a flinty morality and
rock-solid rectitude.)
</P>
<P>
   Others see the show tapping into a subconscious public desire
for a reconnection not only with government, but with politicians
they can admire, perhaps inviting comparisons to the resonance of
John McCain's straight shooter campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've become so cynical, so disaffected,'' says TV Guide
senior editor J. Max Robins. ``Here, we see the human side, the
music comes up, and the light hits the president, and he does the
right thing. I think there is a part of us that wants to think
government can work.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Thompson, founder of Syracuse University's Center for the
Study of Popular Television, sees ``West Wing,'' along with the
wildly popular ``Who Wants To Be A Millionaire'' and the
Oscar-winning film ``Forrest Gump'' as part of a burgeoning
anti-irony and anti-cynicism backlash in popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times when I'm watching `The West Wing' and I think
I'm watching `Mr. Smith Goes to Washington,' '' says Thompson. ``As
funny as the big irony movement (pioneered by smirking entertainers
like David Letterman and Steve Martin) was, there was a sense of
its total emptiness.''
</P>
<P>
   The surprise, he adds, is that the show puncturing public
cynicism against big government is none other than a ``government
show.''
</P>
<P>
   It's even more surprising given TV's poor track record of
politics in prime time. Citing such duds as the short-lived
``Senator'' segment of NBC's old series, ``The Bold Ones,'' and
Fox's ill-fated ``Mr. President'' starring George C. Scott,
television historian Alex McNeil says, ``these shows have been
monumentally unpopular. The traditional wisdom is that people
aren't interested in politics for entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean everyone is entranced with ``The West Wing.''
Conservatives have accurately identified the show _ which is
pro-gun control, gung-ho on campaign finance reform and disdainful
of the religious right _ as resolutely liberal.
</P>
<P>
   ``West Wing'' consultants also include Democratic luminaries
like former Clinton press secretary Dee Dee Myers, former Jimmy
Carter pollster Patrick Caddell, and Lawrence O'Donnell, an ex-aide
to Senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan. Critiquing an episode in which
Bartlet gave his state of the union address, the conservative Media
Research Center said he delivered a speech ``every liberal dreams
the real president would provide: The `era of big government is
over' is itself over.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the show seems to surmount ideological pitfalls. ``You
see them (the characters) making deals, you see them compromising.
You see them as flawed human beings,'' says Robins. ``That's what
kind of makes the show work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the liberal good guys,'' acknowledges Thompson. But
``in a good drama, the characters will blow away the partisan
identification every time.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro has a simple explanation for why ``The West Wing'' is
must-see-TV in the Beltway. ``At a point when everything tells
Washington it's not relevant . . . here is Hollywood saying you are
relevant. Of course Washington loves it.''
</P>
<P>
   As to why it's playing well in Peoria, Newsweek senior editor
Jonathan Alter thinks the credit goes to Sorkin's unusual ability
to make even the minutia of government entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorkin has managed to deal with substantive issues _ like the
census _ in prime time when most cable networks wouldn't even deal
with them at midnight,'' he adds. ``He managed to figure out how to
create drama around complex and sometimes dull issues . . . it
helps to make serving in government sexy again. And that's a huge
contribution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 1356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000510.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0913 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-TOURE-ART-BOS &LR;      05-10 1781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-TOURE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 A WARRIOR OF WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VANESSA E. JONES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Askia Toure is on a roll. He is talking about the murder of
Malcolm X and how, in the aftermath, he helped calm explosive
emotions between members of the Organization of Afro-American Unity
and the Nation of Islam. Then he jumps to the subject of drugs and
how they've annihilated modern-day black and Latino communities.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, he stops mid-sentence and starts shaking his round,
dimpled face with a rueful chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   ``See, you got me going,'' says Toure (Tour-RAY), 61, who lives
in Boston. ``I'm supposed to be talking about literature and my
philosophical book on Pharaohs.''
</P>
<P>
   The work in question is ``Dawnsong! The Epic Memory of Askia
Toure,'' a book of poetry released in March. Toure calls the work,
which eulogizes such jazz greats as Sun Ra and John Coltrane as
often as it teaches about ancient African civilization, an attempt
to ``restore our imagery, our archetypes, and our history'' in a
country where Africa's story is often ignored. It's the author's
fifth book and first published work since his ``From the Pyramids
to the Projects: Poems of Genocide and Resistance,'' which won an
American Book Award in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Toure's eventful life as a radical could easily push his writing
to the background. During stints in Philadelphia, San Francisco,
Atlanta, and New York, he has interacted with a list of historic
figures that reads like a who's who in art, letters, and politics.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, he honed his intellect under the guidance of writer
Langston Hughes, educator John Henrik Clarke, and visual artist
Jacob Lawrence. Along with friends like poets Amiri Baraka, Sonia
Sanchez, and Ishmael Reed, Toure was an important member of the
Black Arts Movement of the late 1960s. He helped develop the
movement's ideology, which was based on linking art with political
activism, an idea that continues to guide how Toure leads his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``People assume I'm a militant activist,'' says Toure, who
hasn't achieved the literary popularity of Sanchez, Baraka, or Reed
in part because of his grass-roots work. ``They think it's the only
thing I'm capable of.''
</P>
<P>
   But those who have followed Toure's career know him as a writer
who's capable of much more. Julius Thompson, director of black
studies at the University of Missouri-Columbia, calls Toure ``one
of the major voices'' out of that period. Adds Thompson, who has
written a book on the Black Arts Movement, ``he's also a
fascinating interpreter of poetry.''
</P>
<P>
   Or let Baraka, who's known Toure since 1961, explain it in
vintage 1960s radical-speak: ``What Askia is doing is still
teaching a kind of anti-imperialist essence. . . . He's done a lot
of focusing on Egypt and ancient kinds of black civilizations. But
at the same time he offers a contemporary attack on what's still
oppressing most of the people in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Toure moved to Boston in 1997 specifically to focus on his
writing. He says he has about five manuscripts in various stages of
completion, which he works on when he's not speaking at public
engagements or mentoring local poets.
</P>
<P>
   But at this moment, Toure chuckles, using the Yoruba word for
father, ``Baba got to do a little work for himself.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bennu bird, emerge from your ashes,
</P>
<P>
   broadcast ecstatic cries
</P>
<P>
   to the ibis, your kindred;
</P>
<P>
   welcome a new sun rising from
</P>
<P>
   Nile waters, like a bright flamingo
</P>
<P>
   shrieking with joy. . . .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
``Dawnsong! (for the Ancient Anu/Nubians: founders of Nile Valley
Civilization)'' from the book ``Dawnsong!'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Toure relaxes into a sofa at the home of his agent, his compact
body clad in a multihued African-style tunic worn over conservative
black pants. His short dark Afro, long sideburns, and goatee are
fighting a losing battle against silver-gray hairs.
</P>
<P>
   Some things about Toure simply shout 1960s radical. The way, for
instance, he calls his cronies from that era ``comrades.'' But he
moves easily between mainstream and Afrocentric cultures, littering
his conversation with references to Clarke, Senegalese scholar
Cheikh Anta Diop, and poet Percy Shelley. His literary influences
include not only such African-American greats as Hughes, Gwendolyn
Brooks, and Margaret Walker, but Pablo Neruda and William Butler
Yeats.
</P>
<P>
   Why Yeats? Because he used poetry and plays to awaken the
national consciousness of the Irish suffering under British rule,
Toure explains. ``I automatically identified with that.'' After
all, it's the effect Toure wants to have on African-Americans
fighting for equal rights when they read his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people feel that African people are inferior,'' says
Toure. ``They probably don't say this to our face. And what's that
based on? `Well, you don't have any (African) history. It's not in
the books.' That's why our task is to restore our archetype.''
</P>
<P>
   It's at these moments, when Toure starts talking about racial
inequality, that his passion becomes palpable. He leans forward,
his arms gesticulate, his voice rises to an attention-grabbing
boom.
</P>
<P>
   Toure's politicization began at the dinner table of his Dayton,
Ohio, home at a time when he was known as Rolland Snellings. He'd
hear his Hampton University-educated parents talking about the work
of Dr. Martin Luther King. During trips to the South, he witnessed
his parents' anger when they were forced to get food from the back
door of restaurants and eat in the car because of Jim Crow laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``During those days the racial situation throughout the country
was really almost unbearable,'' says Toure's father, Clifford
Snellings, 85, who still lives with his wife, Nannie, in Dayton.
``That was our pet gripe. It, maybe, inspired (Toure) to go out and
do what he could.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until Toure was in New York studying painting at the
Art Students League that he got pulled into the vortex of poetry
and activism. By the late 1960s, through the Black Arts Movement,
he too was using poetry and plays to develop the political
consciousness of working-class African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Toure first met Baraka in 1961 at the Metropolitan Opera House,
where both were protesting after the murder of Patrice Lumumba, the
Republic of Congo prime minister. The death of four girls in
Birmingham, Ala., in a church bombing in 1963, which Toure still
speaks of in a whisper, further spurred him to join the civil
rights struggle. (He was also active in the Student Nonviolent
Coordinating Committee during the 1960s.)
</P>
<P>
   Around the same time, Toure was introduced to a group of poets
that included Ishmael Reed, Tom Dent, and Calvin Hernton. Toure had
become what he calls a ``closet scribbler'' while still a teenager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd been writing stuff and just,'' he says, mimicking stuffing
paper into a drawer, ``putting it away.''
</P>
<P>
   Toure finally decided to read his scribblings to his new
friends. He expected to get ``smashed,'' he says. Instead, they
encouraged him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The visual arts didn't have a chance after that,'' he notes.
</P>
<P>
   One element of Toure's work that influenced Baraka was his
presentation. ``Askia always had a songlike quality to the way he
read,'' Baraka explains, ``almost like you would expect of (a)
troubadour.'' That was the effect of the years Toure spent singing
doo-wop before moving to New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the old dudes,'' Toure recalls joyously, launching
into an impromptu ``doo, doo, doo, de, doo'' example. ``All the
sisters would be hollering and screaming.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Our children are the blessings of our lives;
</P>
<P>
   they are the living embodiment of the Future;
</P>
<P>
   they are the future
</P>
<P>
   knocking at the doors of the Present.
</P>
<P>
   They are sacred; we should defend
</P>
<P>
   our children the way we defend our religion.
</P>
<P>
   With them we represent continuity:
</P>
<P>
   the Living, the Dead, the Unborn. . . .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
``From the Pyramids to the Projects, From the Projects to the
Stars! (An Afrikan-American Saga)'' from ``Dawnsong!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During a recent poetry event for Building Bridges, a
collaborative of Boston organizations working with young black men,
Toure gave an impassioned reading of ``From the Pyramids.''
Projecting his voice from one side of a room and then the other, he
pivoted back and forth to make a connection with the hundred people
packed into the space. His singsong delivery recalled the
inflections of a Baptist minister.
</P>
<P>
   These are the kinds of events that fill his days now, nothing
like the radicalized world he once blossomed in. The political
change is evident even in his personal life. Toure, who is
divorced, has one son who is studying filmmaking under the
Ethiopian director Haile Gerima, best known for his 1993 film
``Sankofa.'' Another son is a Wall Street stockbroker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black people have changed a lot, though it looks like we're
waking up again,'' notes Toure, giving as an example the poetry
revival he feels is occurring in Boston. Then he adds, with a touch
of distaste, ``Since Reagan and Bush we've gotten very
conservative. Not all black people, but certainly the so-called top
drawer of black people: professionals and middle class.''
</P>
<P>
   Toure, meanwhile, still ardently tries to make the groggy become
fully awake. Earlier this year, he spoke to a group of students at
Wellesley College. For a poetry reading he's planning for Mother's
Day in Central Square, Cambridge, a multicultural mix of writers
will read 41 poems, representing the total number of bullets shot
by the New York police officers who killed African immigrant Amadou
Diallo last year.
</P>
<P>
   And just as Hughes, Lawrence, and Clarke did for him, Toure
mentors young local poets.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is just very respectful of our generation,'' says Kanasha
Herbert, a Northeastern University senior, who named her infant son
Palenque after a Toure poem. It's a vivid contrast to other
literary types who ``talk a lot of trash,'' Herbert continues.
``He's always talking about how important our generation is and he
sees better and bigger things for us.''
</P>
<P>
   He's also there to help them interpret the meaning of such
political events as the Million Man March and the Rodney King riots
and link them to other things happening in the diaspora, such as
the current golden age of black intellectualism.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `This is what a movement is,' '' Herbert recalls. ``
`You don't have to wait for someone to tell you that.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 1357EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
