<HEADER>
A0915 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-10 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S THE FUTURE OF NEWSPAPERS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN 
c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; What you have here in your mitts, ladies, gentleman, and
children of all reading ages, is a manufactured product, an
information packet that began life variously as a pine tree, a
soybean, a freshet of water on some pristine Canadian forest floor,
and, not least we hope, a gleam in the eye of someone with access
to a keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   That's it: today's newspaper. What you see is what you got in
your lap, your breakfast table, or, if you're Web-surfing, your
screen. The paper is a thing, not a flow of bits and bytes and
pixels and pixies. No virus here. Just the information: news,
views, lists, advertisements, temperature charts for the world,
highs-and-lows for not only Moscow and Sydney but for any stock or
bond or mutual fund that could possibly be of the remotest interest
to anyone with two quarters. We're talking Ye Olde Economy here;
the real deal.
</P>
<P>
   It hit 94 in Bangkok Monday, but got as low as 44 in Buenos
Aires. Those are just two of the tidbits you may have missed in the
daily book-equivalent which is your 365-days-a-year newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   What prompts this re-telling of the daily newspaper saga is the
appearance Monday of a 16-page advertising supplement in The New
York Times: ``Newspapers: Anchor of the Information Age.''
</P>
<P>
   Since dragging your anchor is the greatest fear of any sailor
becalmed on a lee shore, I paid special attention to the combined
effort of the newspaper industry to reassert relevance in the new
economy, which to many newspaper proprietors is the Yeee-economy,
or the Yikes-look-out-below economy.
</P>
<P>
   The headline on the lead article troubled me naught: ``No
Republic Can Flourish Without Newspapers.'' I buy that. Hey, I sell
that. I know something most people don't; that there has never been
a famine in a country with anything resembling a free press. No,
you can't eat this newspaper. But newspapers, and the popular
outrage they can kindle, have kept a lot of people eating in a lot
of places with precarious food supplies.
</P>
<P>
   But who do the newspaper publishers elect to write their
most-important argument? Who's the lead-off batter? Walter
Cronkite! Now, I yield to no one in my conviction that Uncle Walter
is a revered newsman who is properly revered. But does it not
strike you as slightly odd that the newspaper industry chooses a
retired TV anchorman to tout the benefits of the newspaper?
</P>
<P>
   ``A Glorious Medium,'' echoes the chairman of the Newspaper
Association, which boasts 2,000 member papers. ``Newspapers Capture
the Future,'' argues John Sturm, NAA president. Alas, Mr. Sturm,
there is a ``drang'' behind every ``sturm.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's that pesky Internet that is causing our various owners
to drang their anchors. A few weeks ago before my turn at the
microphone at the annual clambake of the New England Newspaper
Association, the CEO of a newspaper chain spoke about the potential
of newspapers in the computer age. First question from the floor at
his conclusion was: ``If the newspaper business is such a good
business, how come you're selling all of your newspapers?''
</P>
<P>
   Duh! Well, the fellow said, he was just following the family's
orders; in five years 80 percent of the chain's revenue would be
from electronic sources, etc.
</P>
<P>
   I thought of that in perusing the annual report of The New York
Times Co., which owns the chair I'm in, the keyboard I pound, and a
lot of other media stuff. The Times just bought the Worcester
Telegram to go with the Globe, acquired in 1993, but the Times is
selling off some smaller papers among the 21 others it owns.
</P>
<P>
   The Times is also planning to issue tracking stock, which
essentially peels off from the current shareholders the interactive
dot-com end of the business. Even though newspapers are the one
mass medium functioning profitably at the end of the century that
were around in 1900, the landscape is littered with gloom and doom.
</P>
<P>
   When Mike Causey typed up his last Federal Diary column Monday
for the Washington Post, it was 11,287th after 36 years, in which
he chronicled the ins and outs of the federal work force for the
350,000 federal payrollers and their dependents who throng the
nation's capital. Where's Mike going? To a dot-com, natch.
</P>
<P>
   Notice a trend here? ``Sell on your strength and stop
highlighting your negatives,'' barks Lauren Rich Fine, a Merrill
Lynch executive who follows media. ``Newspapers will likely find
themselves partnering with historic competitors such as radio, TV
and magazines to create fully robust sites that are `the brand' in
a local community.''
</P>
<P>
   Since this particular columnist _ er, ``content provider,'' in
the new economy lingo _ always tries to catch up to what already
happened, I paid heed to last week's speech by Times publisher
Arthur O. Sulzberger Jr. at the International Press Institute
convention. He is ``agnostic'' on how best to deliver the goods,
i.e., the stuff we read and look at, whether via ink on dead pine
trees inside of trucks burning oceans of diesel fuel, or via some
cable, modem, or wireless gizmo.
</P>
<P>
   So hook me up to those jumper cables: I'm content to be a
content provider. Just don't make me swallow the whole firehose off
the Internet. I'll settle for a soda straw, a small one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
