<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0943 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS &LR;      05-10 1560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FIGHT OVER SAN FRANCISCO NEWSPAPERS CONTINUES IN COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SETH ROSENFELD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The fight over the future of San Francisco's
daily newspapers continued in court this week as attorneys for
local publisher Ted Fang, who is attempting to buy the San
Francisco Examiner, tried to shoot holes in the testimony of
consultants for Clint Reilly, who has filed an antitrust lawsuit to
block the Hearst Corp.'s sale of the Examiner and purchase of the
San Francisco Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a consultant to Reilly, who failed in his bid to buy
the Examiner, admitted to making multimillion-dollar math errors
concerning the cost of running that newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Reilly's attorney Joseph M. Alioto said he would
not call his client to the stand. Reilly had been expected to be a
star witness.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Hearst said it expected to announce Wednesday that
a former judge had agreed to lead an inquiry into whether Examiner
publisher Timothy O. White had violated journalistic ethics in
offering Mayor Willie Brown favorable treatment in The Examiner's
editorial pages in exchange for Brown's support of Hearst's plan to
buy the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unequivocally, any practices that compromise editorial
independence or integrity will not be tolerated in the newsrooms of
any of our newspapers,'' said George B. Irish, president of
Hearst's newspaper division, in a letter to Chronicle employees
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony Tuesday centered on several newspaper industry
consultants to Reilly who asserted that the Fang family would be
unable to publish The Examiner as a viable competitor to a Hearst
Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   J. Scott Schmidt, a former president of Thomson Newspapers West,
which owned several daily and weekly papers in California,
testified Hearst's subsidy was not enough to support a ``worthy
competitor'' to The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt said it would take a subsidy of at least $50 million a
year for three to five years. And, he testified, the Fangs would
have to boost The Examiner's current daily circulation of 108,968
to about 300,000 to attract enough advertising to finance a
competitive paper. The Chronicle's circulation is 465,535.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt said a competitive metropolitan newspaper had full
coverage of sports, arts, business and local, national and
international news.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination by Christopher Hockett, an attorney for
the Fangs, Schmidt acknowledged that he had no information about
the Fangs' plans for publishing The Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   And he admitted making math errors that resulted in his
over-estimating some annual costs of publishing The Examiner by $28
million, though he said he stood by his overall conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Ingram, a former senior vice president of the San
Francisco Newspaper Agency, which handles joint business operations
for The Examiner and the Chronicle, also testified as a consultant
to Reilly that the Fangs would not be able to publish a true
competitor to the Chronicle with the Hearst subsidy.
</P>
<P>
   The Fangs lack the necessary presses, which are costly and
unavailable for rent in San Francisco, Ingram said.
</P>
<P>
   Under Hockett's questioning, Ingram said he, too, had no idea of
the Fangs' plans, and had not checked local press availability
since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Ingram noted that he sent a Feb. 13 e-mail saying Reilly, on
learning Hearst might offer a subsidy to a buyer of The Examiner,
was ``happy as the fox in the hen house.''
</P>
<P>
   Hockett asked Ingram, ``And why are foxes happy when they get
inside hen houses, sir?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know much about foxes,'' Ingram replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not because they're about to do something good for the
public, is it, sir?'' Hockett.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Vaughn R. Walker, who is hearing the case,
declared the question argumentative, and Hockett withdrew it.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto said later that Reilly had been happy because he thought
Hearst was beginning to negotiate with him in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly was an unsuccessful bidder for The Examiner. Court
documents indicate he offered March 7 to buy The Examiner, but
sought a $200 million subsidy from Hearst over six years.
</P>
<P>
   Irish may be called to testify as early as Wednesday about what
he knew of White's talks with Brown, Alioto said.
</P>
<P>
   Irish is temporarily replacing White, whom Hearst suspended
indefinitely with pay.
</P>
<P>
   White sent Irish two e-mails about conversations he'd had with
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 30, 1999, White said he and Examiner Executive Editor
Phil Bronstein had had lunch with Brown that day, and, ``I asked
Willie how I was going to justify to my superiors in New York
wanting to support him and cooperate with him when he was seeming
to go out of his way to make our lives difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown was opposing Hearst's initial plan to buy the Chronicle
and close The Examiner if no buyer for it could be found.
</P>
<P>
   In court on May 1, Alioto asked White, ``Is it not correct that
you were in fact intending to convey to Mayor Brown that his
support for Hearst's proposed acquisition of the Chronicle would
result in more favorable treatment for him in The Examiner?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' White replied, adding, ``That wouldn't affect the
journalism side. It would affect the editorial side.''
</P>
<P>
   White later said he was tired and confused by Alioto's
questioning.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto then introduced part of a December deposition transcript
in which White gave similar testimony to the U.S. Department of
Justice, which was reviewing Hearst's proposed purchase of the
Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said Friday that Irish's testimony ``may clear the air,
or it may substantiate the suggestions which Mr. Alioto's
examination of Mr. White brought forth.''
</P>
<P>
   Irish, Walker said, ``can explain what he understood some of
these communications to be and explain the actions that he took or
the actions that he did not take.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not convinced that it's irrelevant, but I must also say
I'm not sure what the relevance is.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Bennack, Hearst's president, was also expected to testify
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Irish also said he expected to announce Wednesday that a former
judge had agreed to lead a review of whether suspended publisher
White had violated journalistic ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Irish responded Tuesday to a letter responding to 80 Chronicle
staff members who called on Hearst to fully investigate the matter
while being fair to White, who they said they valued for his
decency and judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Irish's letter said the jurist, who was not named, would make a
full and impartial review of the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Debra Shriver, a Hearst spokeswoman, has said Irish and other
Hearst executives were not aware of White's offer to Brown.
Bronstein has said ``there were no negotiations of press coverage
of any kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Reilly contends Hearst's proposed purchase of the Chronicle will
result in an illegal monopoly in which Hearst owns the only major
metropolitan daily newspaper in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly claims Hearst's plan to sell The Examiner to the Fangs,
and to give them a subsidy of up to $66 million over three years,
is a sham meant to facilitate Hearst's purchase of the Chronicle.
He contends the subsidy is insufficient to run a viable competitor
to Hearst's Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst disputes Reilly's contentions. Gary Halling, a Hearst
lawyer, has said The Examiner could not survive in its current form
outside its profit-sharing agreement with the larger Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   He has argued that The Examiner is a failing enterprise, and
that as a result Hearst may legally shut it or sell it and buy The
Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   No law requires Hearst to give any buyer of The Examiner a
subsidy, Halling says.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst is giving the Fangs a subsidy to satisfy local
politicians, including Brown, who said they wanted San Francisco to
have at least two daily newspapers, he says.
</P>
<P>
   The Fangs deny their deal with Hearst is a sham. They have said
their Examiner would compete with Hearst's Chronicle for readers
and advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1965, The Examiner and the Chronicle have had a joint
operating agreement to share combined revenue and costs of
printing, advertising and circulation. They split the remainder,
with each paying the costs of its independent editorial staffs.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was set to expire in 2005, but Chronicle
Publishing Co. decided to sell the Chronicle to Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   The trial on Reilly's suit is the nation's first to consider
whether early termination of a joint operating agreement violates
the 1970 Newspaper Preservation Act, which permits the agreements
as exemptions to antitrust laws. The act was meant to keep alive
newspapers that might otherwise fail, so communities could benefit
from multiple editorial voices.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto says Hearst's plans violate the act. Halling says it does
not apply to terminations of the agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly says he has legal standing to sue as a subscriber who
would be affected by Hearst's alleged monopoly ownership of the
Chronicle, and as a private attorney to protect the public
interest.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto said after court that he had decided not to call Reilly
as a witness because Hearst had agreed Reilly was a subscriber. But
he noted Hearst had not agreed Reilly had standing to sue, an issue
up to Walker. Hearst or the Fangs could call Reilly to testify,
Alioto said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
