a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     05-10 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER-IN-LAW JOKES JUST A PART OF AMERICAN CULTURE
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to a beer commercial (my source of information for
just about everything), Americans do not know much about Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Our neighbors to the north (or is it the south?) think we think
most Canadians are lumberjacks or fur traders who live in igloos,
eat blubber and use a dog sled to drive back and forth to work at
the hockey-stick factory.
</P>
<P>
   In a Molson beer commercial, a character dubbed ``Joe Canadian''
has become something of a national folk hero by disputing these
stereotypes and standing up for Canadian patriotism, such as it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in peacekeeping, not policing,'' says Joe, his voice
rising, ``diversity, not assimilation; and that the beaver is a
proud and noble animal.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe is now shouting: ``Canada is the second-largest land mass,
the first nation of hockey and the best part of North America!''
</P>
<P>
   I am glad to see that Canada is developing a sense of national
pride and I will not quibble over the fact that, as patriotic
slogans go, ``The beaver is a proud and noble animal'' is hardly in
the same class as ``Remember the Alamo!'' ``Make love, not war'' or
even ``Nixon's the one!''
</P>
<P>
   And it is true that we Americans do not know as much about
Canadians as we should, up to and including the fact that they love
their mothers-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   According to a survey of 600 Canadians by Hallmark Canada and
Chatelaine magazine, 90 percent of respondents said they love their
mother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those urban legends that everyone hates their
mother-in-law,'' Garth Jay, vice president of the greeting-card
company told Reuters. ``It's nice to finally have the statistics to
debunk the old myth.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps loving one's mother-in-law is part of the
``peacekeeping, not policing; diversity not assimilation'' thing
that Joe Canadian prattles about in his beer commercial, but I
seriously doubt that it is something that will improve
Canadian-American relations to the point that we consider replacing
the eagle with the beaver as our national symbol.
</P>
<P>
   Tasteless mother-in-law jokes are an integral part of our
culture, much like blubber and igloos are to the Canadian culture.
We may be willing to concede that Canada is the second largest
landmass, but we'll never give in on the mother-in-law thing, no
matter how much the greeting-card companies would wish it to
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the definition of mixed emotions?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing your mother-in-law driving over a cliff in your new
car.''
</P>
<P>
   If we bow to Canadian pressure and stop repeating tasteless,
stereotypical mother-in-law jokes it is just a matter of time
before we also have to stop repeating tasteless and stereotypical
blonde jokes, Polish jokes and jokes involving a priest, a minister
and a rabbi.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother-in-law was bitten by a dog yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How is she now?''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's fine, but the dog died.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that you hear fewer mother-in-law jokes now than you
once did has nothing to do with political correctness or the fact
that the jokes were not all that funny in the first place. It is
nothing less than a Canadian conspiracy, the ultimate goal of which
is to replace our president with a prime minister and assimilate
our beavers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are some of the anagrams you can make out of the words
`mother-in-law?' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``A molten whir, thermal wino, minaret howl, alert him now,
alter him now, nail the worm, am Hitler now, woman Hitler.''
</P>
<P>
   As it is every year, Mother-In-Law Day this year will be
celebrated the week before Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
