<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 14:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0953 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-EBAY-PAINTING-HNS &LR;      05-10 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBAY-PAINTING-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     SELLER CHANGES HIS STORY ABOUT Ebay ARTWORK  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ZACHARY COILE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The seller of an abstract painting on online
auction site eBay _ which set off a bidding war by art lovers who
speculated it was a lost masterpiece by late San Francisco area
painter Richard Diebenkorn _ admitted to concocting some details
about how he came to discover the piece.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Walton, a Sacramento lawyer who put the piece up for bid
on eBay, also said Tuesday he would put the $135,805 sale of the
painting on hold until an independent expert confirms that the
piece is an original work by Diebenkorn.
</P>
<P>
   If the work is authentic, the sale of the painting to a Dutch
art collector will proceed, Walton said.
</P>
<P>
   The revelations came a day after the sale made headlines when
the painting, an abstract orange and green landscape, set off a
frenzy of bidding by art lovers around the world. The painting was
offered on eBay at an initial bid of 25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The high bidder, Robert Keereweer of Nieuwkoop, Netherlands,
never saw the painting in person, but was convinced it was a
Diebenkorn after seeing a photo of the piece online showing the
signature, ``RD `52'' - possibly referring to the artist's initials
and the year 1952.
</P>
<P>
   Walton, who offered the painting under the eBay username
``golfpoorly,'' never claimed the piece was by Diebenkorn or by any
other known artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got this big abstract art painting at a garage sale in
Berkeley back in my bachelor days,'' he wrote in his description of
the painting. ``Then I got married, and my wife has never let me
keep it in the house. She says it looks like it was done by a
nutcase.''
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday, Walton admitted that he had made up parts of
that story.
</P>
<P>
   In his description, Walton wrote that the painting has a hole in
it caused by a child's Big Wheel.
</P>
<P>
   But Walton revealed in a late Tuesday interview with the
Sacramento Bee that he had made up the story about his wife and
child, and actually has neither. But he insisted the painting was
not invented. He would not allow the press to see it, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going nuts. I feel like this is getting out of control and
everyone is blowing it out of proportion,'' he said. ``I'm dreading
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Walton also told the Bee that contrary to his earlier plan to
turn the painting over to Keereweer soon, he would have it
appraised before completing the sale. If it didn't turn out to be a
Diebenkorn, the sale would not go through, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Keereweer, an art lover and software executive who lives about
12 miles south of Amsterdam, said the hole could be fixed easily
and estimated that when fixed, it would be worth about $500,000 to
$1 million. He was not sure if he would sell it.
</P>
<P>
   Keereweer, who placed the highest bid on the painting Monday,
said he has mentally prepared himself for the possibility that the
piece is not an original.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried,'' he said. ``It's part of taking the risk. If
you buy a share of a company, you don't know how it will perform.
The biggest risk is doing it and trying to explain it to my wife.
She thinks I'm nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Keereweer, the managing director of Softwarehuis, a company he
sold 10 months ago, said he sold some shares of the company to
afford the painting.
</P>
<P>
   He said he has experience collecting art, but ran out of time
for the hobby a few years ago when his first child was born.
Someone told him about eBay about two months ago, and since then he
has bought other works of art, including a $3,850 Franz Kline oil
painting and a $1,700 Rodchenko mixed-media piece.
</P>
<P>
   Keereweer studied art history for five years in college and said
he felt fairly confident that the painting was an original.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a typical way of his painting; it's a typical subject;
the colors were right,'' he said. ``We'll find out in a few days
whether this is the laughable thing of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   Diebenkorn, who died in 1993, was one of America's greatest 20th
century artists. He was born in Portland in 1922, but settled in
Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   He is associated with the rise of Abstract Expressionism in the
1940s and 1950s. He painted abstract and representational images,
and is best known for his ``Ocean Park cycle,'' a series of
paintings he produced in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   His 1959 painting, ``Horizon: Ocean Park,'' sold at Sotheby's in
1998 for $3.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Diebenkorn's daughter, Gretchen Grant of Berkeley, said she had
no idea if the piece was a work by her father.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father was a very private person and he painted in his
studio alone,'' Grant said. ``Although my mother saw most of his
work and I saw a great deal of it, we certainly didn't see all of
it. Some things were sold many, many years ago, in the 1950s, and
have never been seen since. Things pop up now and again at auction
that we knew about, but had never seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant is cataloging all her father's work and said she is nearly
done but is missing information on a few works that she knows were
painted and sold, but does not know where they are now.
</P>
<P>
   This is not one of them, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't match anything we have records for that we're
missing,'' Grant said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Suzanne Herel of The Examiner staff and the Associated Press
contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
