   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-MAIN _ ATLANTA _ News of the day: Portions of the Gonzalez
family arrive in Atlanta from Miami. Anti-return group expected to
demonstrate this afternoon in front of federal courthouse _ one of
many skedded at U.S. courthouses in major cities as a show of
support for keeping Elian in the US. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: The AJC is trying for a late afternoon interview with
Lazaro and Marisleysis Gonzalez after they arrive in Atlanta. If
the interview is granted, a story will be expedited. Photo is
standing by, also.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-RALLY _ Protesters plan to be at federal buildings in 13
major cities today in an attempt to keep Elian Gonzalez in the
United States. Members of Miami's Cuban Democracy Movement are
organizing today's protests. They promise that the demonstrations
in cities like Chicago, Washington, New York, Los Angeles and Miami
will all be peaceful. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-LAWYER _ Spencer Eig, a lawyer for Elian Gonzalez, speaks
at a metro Atlanta synagogue. (Pickel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-KIDS _ ATLANTA _ The central question before the federal
appeals court on Thursday is, can a 6-y-o make a complicated
decision about different political cultures. Bigger question for
6-year-olds is can they spell asylum? Looking to present a voices
sort of piece here -- either in story or grafic form -- that relies
on smart writing and is based on interviews with other 6-year-olds
about their knowledge of words like asylum , parolee and other
words that have come up in reference to Elian. Will be based on two
days of interviews in schools with crosssectin of kids, including,
we hope, some Cuban-American kids. (Bixler, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-MIAMI _ MIAMI _ The city I returned to after living in
Atlanta for the past 21/2 years is Miami, the place where I was
raised after my parents and I left a turbulent Cuba in the throes
of Fidel Castro's communism. Right now, Miami is mired in its own
ugly episode of hatred and rhetoric. (Longa, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SC-FLAG _ COLUMBIA, S.C. _ South Carolina House is expected to
vote today to remove the Confederate flag from the top of the
Statehouse. A memorial on the capitol's grounds that is the focus
of the debate was vandalized early today. The words ``take it down,
don't put it here'' were spray painted in red on the monument to
Confederate war dead in front of the Statehouse. (Manuel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   METHODISTS _ CLEVELAND _ Daily coverage, as merits, of United
Methodist General Conference in Cleveland. Issues coming up this
week are same-sex blessing, a new TV ad campaign to rival the
Mormons, legislation apologizing for the denomination's past racism
and trying to raise a huge amount of money for historically black
Methodist colleges that include Clark Atlanta U., some
denominational reorganization, and possible resolutions on Elian
and gun control, to name a few. (GWhite, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (l) Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   JONBENET _ (developing, mugs of Ramseys) The parents of Jon
Benet Ramsey file suit in Travis County federal court against an
author of a book about their daughter. That's all we know.
Developing. (Ball, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   AMTRAK _ Amtrak plans to add passenger service on FEC tracks
from Jacksonville to West Palm Beach by 2005. Also, Amtrak will
have four daily trains from Miami to Orlando, carrying an estimated
625,000 riders per year, according to a plan they released today at
the request of DOT officials. Not only will there be a
Miami-to-Orlando train, but a Tampa-to-Orlando one and a
Tampa-to-Miami route. Amtrak folks say this will save $90 million
in operating costs, car accidents and emission problems. We'll see
what local planners have to say about the silver trains trekking
through coastal residential neighborhoods. The trains would go 79
mph to110 mph. And in 20 years, there should be service from Fort
Lauderdale to Fort Myers and Jacksonville to Pensacola. (McGinness,
Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ Microsoft is due to respond by Tuesday
to the government's proposed remedies in the antitrust case against
the software company. (Glass, Cox News Service). 22.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
