<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF NOTHING ELSE, GO FOR THE VIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa , Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are some places you agree to go to just for the sake of
getting out.
</P>
<P>
   Some of us know this as the anywhere-but-here syndrome, which is
why you some nights find yourself consenting to a movie like, say,
``Three Kings,'' or stretching a stop for frozen yogurt into a
dining-out experience.
</P>
<P>
   That is kind of how I approached going to the Giants' new Pac
Bell ball park. I am not a sports fan nor given to wearing orange
and black or speaking in ``play ball'' metaphors. But it was a
Friday night and we were out on the town, sort of.
</P>
<P>
   Then I made an amazing discovery. I could become a ball park
fan. Right off, as we passed a chorus line of palm trees and hiked
a ramp as steep as Lombard Street to our seats, I gushed to my
husband, ``This is the best ball park I've ever been in.'' He
rightfully asked how many ball parks there have been in my life.
</P>
<P>
   I once went to Candlestick for the tailgate party and my dad
took me to Yankee Stadium when I was 8. But I have relatives who
rhapsodize over Fenway Park and friends who grew up with Wrigley
Field and Tiger Stadium and I kind of like the Americana notion of
people bonding with a ball park.
</P>
<P>
   By now every San Francisco Bay Area and out-of-town hard core
fan and sports writer has weighed in on the merits of the splashy
new park, but I offer a companion's perspective.
</P>
<P>
   First, the view: If you go to a ball park to look out and around
and only occasionally down on the ground, you will be thrilled at
all you can see. It's tight and close enough you could probably
make out your friend across the way if you knew what section he was
in. But the view is the best, a panorama usually only available to
those in high places and frequenters of penthouse restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   You can see cargo ships, ferry lights, boat lights, bridge
lights. There's Oakland and Mount Diablo and wind surfers. I
noticed another companion sitting nearby was so mesmerized she put
her book down.
</P>
<P>
   The weather: The famous fog came in, blowing across like smoke,
but it didn't leave its wet hand print. It just kept on going and
there was no wind. The guy two seats over from us could actually
spit straight down at his shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Dress requirements: The coziest person I saw was a little girl
wrapped in a blanket and sitting in her father's lap. If you're too
big for that you can prepare for the cooling night by packing a few
accessories. The mother and child sitting next to me pulled gloves,
hats and scarves from their backpack. The woman offered me her
gloves when she went for a beer, but I would have preferred her
socks.
</P>
<P>
   Comfort level: The seats are almost as friendly on your back as
an office ergonomics chair and they're backed up tight into the
next row so you can stash your purse safely underneath. The drink
holders are a nice touch.
</P>
<P>
   Food: Expensive, of course. The basic hot dog is a few big bites
worth and the bun is timid but with enough onions and sauerkraut,
it's an adequate meal, although next time I'm searching out the
Vietnamese chicken salad. Still, it's a relatively cheap way to eat
al fresco in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Bathrooms: On the top row they open to the stars, which is
almost like camping. There was no waiting for the Ladies Room,
which was probably a fluke.
</P>
<P>
   People-watching: Second to airports, ball parks are voyeuristic
pleasure houses. Most people are paying attention to the game, so
are unaware that the person behind and to their left is staring,
making note of who's holding hands, deciding if the red leather is
real leather. Eavesdropping is effortless. Two guys in front of us
started talking about the female announcer and I was prepared to
lean in and defend her but it turned out they're admirers.
</P>
<P>
   Cordiality: Ball parks are good places for people to interface,
particularly after talking to a computer all day. Strangers seem to
make small talk at a ball game, like they've all been invited to
the same party and are best friends of the host. Of course it's
mostly about baseball, but it's sociable. The woman next to me
returned to her seat to see that one of our guys was at first base.
``How did he get there?'' she asked. I thought that must have been
obvious. How many ways can there be? But I said, ``I didn't notice.
I was looking at the planes landing in Oakland.'' I pulled on my
husband's sleeve. He said, ``base hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Crowd: It's good to be with thousands of people who are
basically happy to be where they are, put their hands over their
hearts for the national anthem and are patient enough to sit for
three hours while the players take their sweet time throwing the
ball around.
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhood: South Beach is posh but accessible, with
restaurants with good wine lists, where half the clientele is
dressed for dinner and the other half is covered with peanut dust
and wearing sport shoes. Now that's a night out, even though the
Giants lost.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. The Press Democrat is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 1438EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
