<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0977 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-QUEER-FOLK-TV-$ADV14-     05-10 1264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUEER-FOLK-TV-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CONTROVERSIAL BRITISH SERIES SEDUCES SHOWTIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, May 14) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ One year ago, the fast-moving, darkly funny series
``Queer as Folk'' scorched the British television landscape. The
show, about a group of gay men in Manchester, was marked by so much
graphic language and explicit sex _ some of it with a 15-year-old
boy _ that just about everyone seemed outraged. At least at the
outset.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was absolutely torn apart by the right-wing press, by the
left-wing press, by gay people, by straight people,'' said Russell
T. Davies, the cheerful, 37-year-old Welsh-born writer who created
the series for Britain's Channel 4. He laughed. ``There was nothing
like that show on British television,'' he said. ``Now I'm eager to
see what you Americans do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't have to wait too long.
</P>
<P>
   After five months of negotiations, the Showtime cable network
has picked up ``Queer as Folk'' and plans to turn it into a
22-episode series set in a blue-collar Eastern city, probably
Pittsburgh. Executives at Showtime, who vied with HBO for the
series and are plainly seeking to be more competitive with that
highly successful cable network, said that ``Queer as Folk'' would
be as explicit in the United States as it was in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this show was unique,'' said Jerry Offsay,
Showtime's president of programming. ``I had never seen characters
like these on television. The characters were unapologetic, they
lived their lives the way they wanted to. There were great twists
and turns and reverses in the storytelling. This show will be as
edgy as any television series has ever been in America.''
</P>
<P>
   The American version, which is now being written and is set to
be broadcast later in the year, will mirror the British show _ with
one significant difference. The firestorm that rocked Britain after
the first episode of ``Queer as Folk'' was set off in large part by
the affair the 29-year-old lead character, Stuart, has with Nathan,
who is 15. An advertising man consumed with the hunt for sex,
Stuart has a best friend, Vince, who has been entranced with him
for years. But the icily seductive Stuart cares only about having
sex as often as he can with as many men as he can.
</P>
<P>
   In the American version, the youth will be nearly 18. ``The boy
is on the cusp of being the legal age,'' said Tony Jonas, one of
the executive producers of the series and a former president of
Warner Brothers Television. ``The idea is, kids who are seniors in
high school are being sexual. We can't deny that. It's the
reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonas had been trying to sell Offsay another show when the
Showtime executive asked him to be one of the producers of ``Queer
as Folk.'' ``When I first saw the material,'' said Jonas, ``there
was a sense of shock. But once you got past the shock, this was
solid, intelligent and caustically funny material.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Jonas as executive producers of the series are Rob Cowen
and Daniel Lipman, who are also writing the first episodes. Cowen
and Lipman created the NBC series ``Sisters'' and won an Emmy for
their 1985 drama, ``An Early Frost,'' one of the first television
films about AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Cowen said: ``There are a lot of gay characters in commercial
television and films now, but not a show like this. There's never
been anything like this. It's an odd mix of very graphic material
that's also witty and charming.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Showtime had placed no restraints on the writing team.
``We will not be accused of watering down the series,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lipman said the producers and Showtime wanted to avoid setting
the series in a heavily gay neighborhood like New York's Chelsea,
Los Angeles' West Hollywood or San Francisco's Castro district.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted it in a place where you couldn't say, `It's those
people out there,''' Lipman said. ``These characters don't work in
entertainment or fashion. They're average people in an average
town.''
</P>
<P>
   The British series was set not in London but in Manchester,
where Davies lives. ``I didn't want to write something with a
message,'' said Davies, who has spent most of his career writing
dramas and soap operas for British television. ``Because I'm gay, I
was always putting in gay characters in my plays. In this case, I
wanted to entertain and captivate an audience. All right, they're
gay. Let's get on with the story.''
</P>
<P>
   The reaction to the British show in some ways followed his
formula. The initial wave of shock had disappeared by the time the
eight hourlong episodes of ``Queer as Folk'' had completed their
run in 1999. (They were followed by a two-hour show this year.)
</P>
<P>
   Initially, gay groups objected to what they saw as the show's
sensationalism, fearing that its affluent, promiscuous and
thoroughly vapid characters would feed into gay stereotypes.
Critics, especially in conservative newspapers, denounced the
characters' freewheeling sexuality and were shocked by the underage
sex. But like most of the characters in the British series, Nathan
_ who wants a real relationship and not a one-night stand _ turned
into a more complex and stronger figure as each episode unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's surprising to me is that the criticism didn't just calm
down, it actually reversed itself,'' Davies said. ``A reviewer in
The Daily Mail, who hated it at first, said later that she felt it
was the most important piece of television in years.''
</P>
<P>
   No actors have been cast for the American series. But several
writers who have written gay-themed plays, films or television
dramas have joined the show: Richard Kramer (``Tales of the
City''), Jonathan Tolins (``Twilight of the Golds'') and Jason
Schafer (``Trick'').
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, making a risky show like ``Queer as Folk'' has no
downside for Showtime. The network, with 22.3 million subscribers,
has for years struggled in the shadow of HBO, which has 35.7
million. ``Queer as Folk'' will, if nothing else, attract
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Offsay said Showtime's pledge to turn ``Queer as Folk'' into a
long-running series was a decisive factor in the decision by
Channel 4 and Davies to sell the rights to the cable network. ``Our
willingness to go straight to a 22-episode series probably
prevailed in the end,'' Offsay said. At the same time, the network
promised to stick as close to the British series as possible,
especially in matters of candor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We run R-rated movies as a staple of our service,'' Offsay
said. ``The content can be edgy. We don't develop cop shows, or
lawyer shows, or doctor shows. People get them free on every
network. We're always looking for something better _ and different
_ than what the networks are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   He believes that because there will be so many more episodes of
the American series, the writers will be able to turn some of the
British version's lesser characters into prominent figures. This
will include a lesbian couple who have just had a baby.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Davies said he had initially been nervous about
the American version. ``I was worried that it might become
blander,'' he said. But after reading a draft of the opening
two-hour episode, Davies said he believed his fears were
unwarranted. ``I picked it up with trepidation,'' he said. ``But
I'm really pleased. They were remarkably faithful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Good stories never die, and this is a good story,'' he added.
``So we're telling the story in different ways and in different
settings, reinventing the story. And that's what you should do.''
He laughed. ``I can't wait to see it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
