<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 14:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0979 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-HISTORIC-RECREATION-M     05-10 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISTORIC-RECREATION-MUSIC-ART-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEGOTIATING BETWEEN OLD AND NEW 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., May 14) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By BERNARD HOLLAND    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The illusion _ or is it delusion? _ of historical re-creation
onstage is being addressed with a number of wise words and deeds.
In Rameau's ``Platee'' at the New York City Opera and Carlo Gozzi's
``Green Bird'' at the Cort Theater, 18th-century theater enters
into heavy negotiation with the present.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Jonathan Miller, the English director, writing in
The New York Review of Books and explaining, among other things,
why Debussy's ``Pelleas et Melisande'' is perhaps happier in the
land of Proust than in some medieval ur-German forest of misty
place and date. The Metropolitan Opera, meanwhile, has labored on
with its 13-year-old production of Wagner's ``Ring,'' splendidly
sung and played, and couched, to the consternation of many, in a
misty photo-realism all its own.
</P>
<P>
   As Miller rightly points out, music survives history more easily
than stagecraft does. Theater, dealing with people's lives,
catalogs the events around them, the streets they walk on, the
clothes on their backs and the furniture they sit on. Even when we
reconstruct the facts and the artifacts, the chemistry that binds
all these things together is lost. Shelf life has expired; the
ingredients have become inert.
</P>
<P>
   Music is more primal, more specific than the day to day. Music
is not about what happens to people but about their states of mind
and heart when it is happening. Morals change. Standards of conduct
change. Characters ride horses or drive trucks. But I suspect that
the visceral rushes of pain and pleasure stay pretty much the same,
as constituent parts of an emotional DNA that survives in a
straight line from Adam and Eve to Elvis Presley.
</P>
<P>
   First ``Platee,'' elegantly staged and clothed by the Mark
Morris Dance Group and Isaac Mizrahi, and then ``The Green Bird,''
marvelously reimagined by Julie Taymor, have an advantage over
social melodrama (``La Boheme'') or political activism (``The
Marriage of Figaro''). Rameau's gods and goddesses and Gozzi's
stylized physical comedians and magic tricks occupy made-up worlds
where realism is in the eyes of beholders, be they Baroque or
space-age. Because everything is imaginary, the room to maneuver
widens.
</P>
<P>
   If Taymor's Truffaldino and Smeraldina had lived in Gozzi's
Rome, I suspect they would have been very like the Brooklyn sausage
vendors she has made of them. Comedy is by nature topical. The
topics change in 250 years, so the comedy must, too. One of the
minor tragedies for opera today is Mozart's ``Abduction From the
Seraglio,'' which is filled with glorious music and lamed by period
humor that seems inextricable from the plot and simply isn't funny
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The principles of exaggeration and absurdity endure, but comedy
must be made exaggerated and absurd for a whole new set of people.
The Marx Brothers are our commedia dell'arte. The accents change,
and the wisecrack is introduced. The racetrack, the ocean liner and
the college campus become the streets of Rome or the Italian
countryside. But exchanging one set of props for another is not as
easy as it sounds. Required is not the literal equation but an
instinctive knack, a sense of taste and judgment that an enterprise
has or hasn't. We can be thankful that Taymor has it all the time,
and Morris and Mizrahi almost always.
</P>
<P>
   What helps both Rameau and Gozzi toward 21st-century success are
the blurrings between old and new. The Shakespearean diction of
Taymor's King (Derek Smith) tunes into and out of neurotic Upper
East Side New Yorkese. The pear-shaped vowels of Brighella (Reg E.
Cathey) lapse happily into Jamaican street slang. Morris' dancers
whirl balletically one moment and take the disco floor the next. In
both events, old and new are thrown into the same pot and made to
swim together. It is an excellent idea, this sweet-and-sour mix;
the recipe sounds easy, too, but the doing is again dependent on
the taste and judgment of whoever is doing the throwing.
</P>
<P>
   The obstacle to most updates of old stage pieces is the simile,
or if you like, the metaphor. The 18th century is reborn in
21st-century form, and you are invited to see how the details match
up. But three is a crowd. Simile descends on words and music like a
mother-in-law on a newlywed's household. That Susanna's servant
quarters are like a maid's room in Trump Tower or that Wotan and
company are Ruhr Valley industrialists makes interesting
sociological fodder, but it gets in the way.
</P>
<P>
   A retailer has been interposed between theatrical message and
audience reception. To pass from one to the other now requires a
translation. The listener must stop and think, ``This really means
that.'' In ``Figaro,'' Mozart wants Susanna to go straight to your
heart. The update insists first that you get the joke it is making.
Make the metaphor as cunning as you will _ line up 18th with 21st
century precisely _ and still the added transaction deflects the
concentration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pelleas'' has an easier time, but for another reason. The
opera's methodology is imprecision itself, leaving the facts to
fade and the heart and mind behind the facts to take precedence.
Maeterlinck's characters wander like sleepwalkers. They (and often
the audience) have only vague ideas of where they have come from or
what their destination will be. If the Met ``Ring'' sees ancient
castles and murky forests through Wagner's 19th-century eyes,
Miller's production hears in Debussy's music the exquisite
melancholy and discreet repression of the composer's own France.
Both ways lay claim to authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
