<DOCNO> NYT20000510.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0999 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-HIGH-SCHOOL-REPORTERS     05-10 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGH-SCHOOL-REPORTERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TEENAGERS DISCOVER FAME ISN'T SO BAD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MATTHEW YI  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ High school reporters Megan Greenwell and
Iliana Montauk are finding the price of fame isn't as bad as they
thought.
</P>
<P>
   The two have been highly sought by newspapers and magazines for
interviews since The San Francisco Examiner published a story about
how the students first reported part of a bizarre tale that led to
the federal indictment of a prominent East Bay landlord.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the girls and their parents are in exclusive negotiations
with a Southern California movie production company that's offering
$50,000 for the rights to the story.
</P>
<P>
   The teenagers' article stems from the carbon monoxide poisoning
death of an Indian girl who was found unconscious along with her
younger sister in their downtown Berkeley apartment last November.
</P>
<P>
   While most San Francisco area media outlets reported the
incident as a tragic death of a recent immigrant, Greenwell, 16,
and Montauk, 17, wrote a piece questioning why the victims had
never been enrolled at Berkeley High School and including
allegations of possible indentured servitude.
</P>
<P>
   The article appeared in the Dec. 10 issue of the students'
bi-weekly high school newspaper, the Jacket.
</P>
<P>
   The story went unnoticed until The Examiner reported the arrest
of Lakireddy Bali Reddy, 62, in January and followed up with a
story about the Berkeley High article.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of Reddy's arrest, authorities alleged that the real
estate tycoon had illegally brought immigrants into the United
States from his home village of Velvadam in south India.
</P>
<P>
   Court papers charge that Reddy also smuggled the two carbon
monoxide poisoning victims and their roommate into the United
States so he could have sex with them.
</P>
<P>
   The fantastic case has forever changed the lives of those
involved, starting with Reddy, who owns more than 1,100 apartments
in the East Bay, and the budding journalists Greenwell and Montauk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, a part of me is like, `This is cool, I'm going to
be in a movie,''' Greenwell said. ``But more realistically, I think
it's a real good idea, because what everybody has said is that they
want an inspiring movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing we've been talking about is that usually teens get
(media attention) because they commit crimes. So, I think if (our
movie) can show teenagers in a positive way, it'll be really
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Montauk added that another motivation to make this movie was to
get the message out about the plight of recent immigrants who came
to the United States with hopes of bettering their lives, but often
ended up victims of unfair labor practices.
</P>
<P>
   In the case against Reddy, the businessman also is accused of
giving little or no pay to employees at his Berkeley realty office
and Indian restaurant, Pasand Madras Cuisine, often only offering
food and board in exchange for their service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked to the (movie production) people who have come
up, about specific concerns, which are the issues of indentured
servitude and poverty, and whether they will be explained
in-depth,'' Montauk said.
</P>
<P>
   A part of this conviction stems from the girls' earlier dealings
with reporters who wanted a piece of their story.
</P>
<P>
   They received calls from magazines like People, Glamour, YM and
even the infamous tabloid the National Enquirer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially in the first week of the story ... `sex slaves'
(and) the `multimillionaire' were the key phrases repeated over and
over. When we got into it, it was `cute little girls discover sex
slave ring (run by) a multimillionaire,''' Greenwell said. ``We
were kind of going like, `That's not how it happened.' First of
all, we didn't write anything about sex slaves. Nobody seems to get
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Reddy's sex allegations had come to light only when he was
arrested in January.
</P>
<P>
   But there have been upsides to the attention as well, including
numerous calls about movie deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point we realized that we had to actually get together
and talk about this,'' said Iliana's father, Lance Montauk. ``We
discussed basically whether our lives will be ruined by
Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
   After a breakfast meeting between the two families and the
Jacket's advisor, Rick Ayers, everyone gave the green light to
pursue a movie deal.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, representatives of three separate production
companies flew up to meet with the girls.
</P>
<P>
   Lance Montauk, who is brokering the deal, said three companies _
Studio City-based Longbow Productions in Los Angeles County,
Burbank-based Green and Epstein, and DeeGee Productions, which has
offices in Los Angeles and Chicago _ had offered money.
</P>
<P>
   The families have decided to exclusively negotiate with Longbow
and will most likely get $50,000 if the deal goes through, Lance
Montauk said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are (the girls) taking advantage of the situation? Sure,
they're taking advantage of it,'' said Megan's father, Jim
Greenwell. ``But they're also talking about some sort of mechanism
to help the family of the girl who died.''
</P>
<P>
   The details haven't been worked out, but the students say
they're considering splitting the money into thirds. Greenwell and
Montauk would each keep a third, with the remainder going to the
surviving carbon monoxide victim and her family in India.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we felt was that we can buy our way out of the moral
dilemma and help (the victims) out with finances,'' Lance Montauk
said, explaining that the families at first were uncomfortable
about making money from the plight of the Indian victims.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
