<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1001 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-RABBI-MOTHERS-DAY-NYT     05-10 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RABBI-MOTHERS-DAY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER'S DAY THOUGHTS OF A FAMILY MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By RABBI ELI HECHT  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    When my wife gave birth to our sixth child, I was as truly happy
as any man could be. As an American Jew, I had always felt that I
should have at least six children _ one for each 1 million of the 6
million Jews who were killed during World War II.
 &HT;    Even though I was as pleased as any father could be, I learned
that some of our friends felt differently. They claimed that a
large family deprived children of love and education. Somehow, I
felt they had missed the boat.
 &HT;    Sure, bringing children into the world is a great
responsibility, but then responsible people have all the more
reason to have children.
 &HT;    There are those who base their decision to limit the size of
their family on thoughtful research, but questionable judgment.
They anticipate having a family with apprehension, as though a
child were a liability. But, in fact, each child is an asset.
 &HT;    It is well-documented that Jews educate their children at an
early age. Children are introduced to prayer as soon as they can
talk. Reading and writing are considered a basic necessity that
must be provided to each child. It is for that reason Jews have
been called, ``the children of the book.''
 &HT;    If anything, though, we ought to be concerned with the education
of all children and increasing the quality of their family
dynamics.
 &HT;    I recently experienced a strange situation. With Mother's Day a
few weeks off, I was feeling very grateful to my wife for giving me
a loving home and six children. I know how hard she works to
provide the family atmosphere we enjoy.
 &HT;    To show my affection and appreciation I decided to give her some
perfume.
 &HT;    I found myself in a department store overwhelmed by the various
perfume displays. A pleasant sales clerk asked me if I needed some
help. After explaining that the perfume was a gift for my wife, she
asked what I had done to necessitate the gift.
 &HT;    I was so taken aback that I laughed. It seems that people only
buy perfume when they have done something improper.
 &HT;    ``Look,'' I said, ``I love my wife and just want to buy her a
gift, no more, no less. She has given me six great children.''
 &HT;    The sales clerk related our conversation to her co-workers, who
told me that I was quite a fellow. Embarrassed, I wondered what was
so incredible about this simple act?
 &HT;    It must reflect the fact that we have lost the value system of
the family structure. There was a time when some unmarried men and
women wanted a sexual encounter without the consequence of
children: love and intimacy with neither marriage nor children.
Now, some women want children without love or marriage.
 &HT;    Maybe it should have been no surprise that I looked like ``such
a guy'' for wanting to buy my wife a gift even though there was no
special reason.
 &HT;    So this year on Mother's Day, I will enjoy the blessings of my
loving wife and my wonderful children, my assets. I hope my old
friends will experience even a fraction of that joy.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    c.2000 Rabbi Eli Hecht
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Rabbi Eli Hecht is vice president of the Rabbinical Alliance of
America and past president of the Rabbinical Council of California.
He is the director of Chabad of South Bay in Lomita, Calif. and
writes a monthly Op-Ed column for the Long Beach Press-Telegeam.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 1457EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
