A1006 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-OKLAHOMA-BARBECUE-TEX     05-10 0395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OKLAHOMA-BARBECUE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I NEED CLUES ABOUT OKIE 'CUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BUD KENNEDY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Guests from Oklahoma, help me.
</P>
<P>
   I don't understand some foods.
</P>
<P>
   Say, Oklahoma barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   The beef is sliced thin, as in Kansas City. The sauce is thick,
as in parts of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   There's a ``hot'' barbecue sauce, as in the South.
</P>
<P>
   There's pork. It's also sliced thin, so it's almost exactly like
the beef. There's no sweet pork sauce or rib sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Sausage? It's hit-and-miss _ nowhere near as good as the
masterful homemade sausage of Central Texas, but better than the
wretched links served in North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   And what's up with all the curly fries?
</P>
<P>
   The best barbecue I've found in Oklahoma is still the pork rib
dinner at Unka Pete's BBQ in Caddo, just past Lake Texoma two hours
north of Fort Worth and Arlington. That's because owner Robert
``Unka Pete'' Jones' thick ribs are closer to familiar Texas
flavor.
</P>
<P>
   I dined at two legendary Sooner State barbecue restaurants one
recent weekend. One was a winner. The other left me wondering.
</P>
<P>
   Van's Pig Stand in Shawnee and Norman, Okla., was the winner
last weekend. Van's celebrates 70 years June 5, so it's Oklahoma's
oldest barbecue restaurant still in the founding family. (Texas'
oldest opened in 1927: Riscky's BBQ in Fort Worth.)
</P>
<P>
   Van's serves smoky beef, mild pork, exceptional sausage and hot
links. The dining room is lined with hilarious old pictures,
including 70 years' worth of cheerleaders for the Shawnee High
School Wolves.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of Oklahoma City, Jake's Ribs in Chickasha
draws much larger crowds and serves much larger portions _ but not
better food.
</P>
<P>
   Jake's is definitely a bargain. One side order of curly fries
filled a large platter _ and stacked 4 inches deep. The combination
barbecue platter could easily have fed three people.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the pork ribs were very ordinary by Texas standards, the
thin-sliced meats lacked much flavor, and the sausage tasted as if
it had only paused briefly in the hickory pit.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe readers from Oklahoma can explain OK 'cue.
</P>
<P>
   (Bud Kennedy writes a food column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7538, or e-mail:
budk(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 1500EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000510.0089 </DOCNO>
