u a BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN     05-10 0415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIERRA RELEASES TWO NEW HOYLE GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   By LONNIE BROWN   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Crossword puzzles, like solitaire games, are one of the
real-life things that easily make the transition to computer
screens. It's easier to backspace over a mistake on a computer than
it is to erase on paper _ and sometimes, the computer will give you
help with a word.
</P>
<P>
   Hoyle Crosswords from Sierra Attractions (Windows, Macintosh;
about $20) has 500 crossword puzzles. They can be worked on the
computer screen, or printed out for completing later (or working
both on and off the computer).
</P>
<P>
   There are five levels of difficulty for the puzzles. And plenty
of help is available if needed. The computer will provide hints for
harder words. Also available: Webster's New World College
Dictionary, Fourth Edition. Using it, players can search for words
or for definitions.
</P>
<P>
   Crosswords can be used by one player, or two can play using the
same computer. Players may also play over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   An option allows users to install the game completely on the
hard drive so there's no need to find the disk when running the
game. That's also a nice feature for laptop users.
</P>
<P>
   Backgrounds and music for the puzzles can also be customized.
</P>
<P>
   The CD is one of two new introductions in the Hoyle series. The
other offers variations on two classic games: Hoyle Solitaire and
Mahjong Tiles.
</P>
<P>
   The disk (Windows, Macintosh; about $20) has 50 solitaire games
including: Forty Thieves, Spider, Klondike and Pyramid. It also has
new, video-arcade solitaire games (Fast 21 and Three Towers).
Players of past Hoyle card games will find larger cards with bigger
numbers in this release.
</P>
<P>
   The CD also has classic mahjong tiles. They're used in the game
where players try to find matching tiles in order to remove them
from a layout and win the game. There are more than 60 layouts on
the CD.
</P>
<P>
   New to this version: Memory Tiles and Gravity Tiles. The first
game lets players try to find matching pairs in the least amount of
time; the second has tiles stacked in columns for players to
remove.
</P>
<P>
   Players can compete with friends, play over the Internet, and
make their own layouts.
</P>
<P>
   For information, visit the company's Web site: www.sierra.com/
attractions.
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is associate editor of The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla. He can be reached by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol.com. The
Ledger is a member of the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
