 ART ADV.: Photos with AUTHOR-TOURE, WORKING-MILLIONAIRES and
WHITESOX-BALDWIN are being transmitted to NYT Photo Service
subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, please contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta
 &LR; at the Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of
graphics or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LA-EDWARDS (New Orleans) _ After a remarkable roll in which he
was elected to four terms as governor, won fortunes in Las Vegas,
and flummoxed a generation of federal prosecutors, Edwin W. Edwards
finally loses out. By Curtis Wilkie. 790 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) -- Mention Salem and most people think
witchcraft. But the Bay State community also has a connection to
Mormonism. By Diego Ribadeneira and Michael Paulson.
</P>
<P>
   NYHAN-COLUMN (Undated) -- What's the future of newspapers? By
David Nyhan.
</P>
<P>
   JACKSON-COLUMN (Undated) _ Will suburban moms be there in
November? By Derrick Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   NOLAN-COLUMN (Undated) -- Lucky for Al Gore; fund-raising
scandal isn't gripping voters. By Martin F. Nolan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIFESTYLE (l) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BEAM-COLUMN (Undated) -- There has been no shortage of reasons
advanced for the failure of the critically acclaimed ABC teledrama
``Wonderland.'' By Alex Beam.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AUTHOR-TOURE (Undated) _ Sixties radical and Black Arts Movement
member Askia Toure eulogizes jazz greats like Sun Ra and John
Coltrane in his latest work of poetry. By Vaness Jones. 1800 words.
PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-COLUMN (Undated) _ These days in Washington, it's hard to
tell The West Wing from The White House without a scorecard. By
Mark Jurkowitz.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FLAWED-INDICATORS (Washington) _ Each week brings new economic
numbers, but the ones that matter are few and flawed, some
specialists say. By Aaron Zitner. 1770 words.
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-MILLIONAIRES (Boston) _ They've alread made millions
starting up new companies. So do they take the money and run? Not
these go-getters. They're at it again. By Nathan Cobb. (2 takes)
PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   ONJOBS-COLUMN (Undated) -- At some point in our lives, most of
us will have to confront our need for a raise, a more flexible
schedule, a change in duties, or some other workplace issue. By
Diane E. Lewis. 1160 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; CMGI-DOWNTURN (Undated) _ CMGI, hit hard by the downturn in
the technology sector, turns to layoffs to help the bottom line. By
Ross Kerber. 580 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   ONBUSINESS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Few Internet stocks have plummeted
this year like CMGI, which has lost nearly two thirds of its value.
Most of CMGI's publicly traded investments have plunged along with
it. Now they're making pitches this week at the year's most
important Internet stock conference. By Steven Syre and Charles
Stein.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCE-HOOKER (Undated) _ Is retirement at age 62 feasible? By
Kenneth Hooker.
</P>
