<DOCNO> NYT20000510.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1038 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-BRITAIN-MUSEUM-0511-C     05-10 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-MUSEUM-0511-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LONDON'S NEW TATE MODERN SET TO OPEN
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ A 50-year-old power station on the banks of the River
Thames will be reborn Thursday as the Tate Modern, the world's
largest museum devoted to 20th Century art.
</P>
<P>
   Labeled the ``Cathedral of Cool'' by London newspapers, the new
gallery will display more than 600 works in the cavernous red brick
building across the river from St. Paul's Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   The vast post-war structure was designed by famed British
architect Sir Giles Gilbert Scott, who also designed London's
familiar red telephone boxes. The old plant has been revived in a
US$205 million reconstruction designed by Swiss architects Jacques
Herzog and Pierre de Meuron.
</P>
<P>
   The designers retained the shell of the power station with its
towering central chimney. It dwarfs its neighbor, the reconstructed
Shakespeare's Globe Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   The museum will be opened officially by Queen Elizabeth Thursday
with a celebrity-packed party to follow in the evening. The guest
list includes such art denizens as Madonna, Cher, Mick Jagger and
Jerry Hall. Black market tickets to the party are going for 1,000
pounds (about US$1,600).
</P>
<P>
   For everyone else, the Tate Modern opens for free on Friday and
thereafter, as public art museums in Britain generally do not
charge for admission.
</P>
<P>
   The old Tate, about a quarter the size of the new museum _ which
used to house the nation's largest modern collection _ has been
reshaped into a gallery of British art.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking innovative ways to display the eclectic collection, the
Tate Modern's curators have organized the artwork into four
categories: Landscape/Matter/Environment; Nude/Action/Body; Still
Life/Object/Real Life; and History/Memory/Society. All the great
names of the 20th century from Picasso to Matisse to Pollock to
Mondrian, are present.
</P>
<P>
   The size and scope of the museum and its arrival in a city as
culturally important as London have forced comparisons with the
other important 20th century art museums, the Pompidou in Paris and
Museum of Modern Art in New York _ both of which are much smaller
than the Tate Modern.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the reviews have been mixed, but the critics have found
consensus in their expressions of awe at the size of the place.
</P>
<P>
   ``God, the size of it,'' wrote Tom Lubbock for the The
Independent. ``Whatever the Tate Modern may be, it's more than just
a gallery. It is an event.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kimmelman of the New York Times wrote with some distaste
that he wasn't sure that bigger meant better. ``The Tate is in part
a temple to vanity, the vanity of a culture that equates spectacle
with substance, with half the building devoted to a vast
entranceway, the museum's deeply gloomy signature space _ and with
an installation that is occasionally eccentric to the point of
distraction.''
</P>
<P>
   Visitors unencumbered by a critic's erudition, may find the
place an entertaining stew of visual and sensory experiences. The
vast turbine hall, which is 600 feet long and 12 stories high, is
fitted with massive sculptures, including a giant steel spider.
</P>
<P>
   The galleries are simple and functional and offer surprises at
many turns. One moment you are plunged into a blacked-out video
installation, the next you find yourself taking in a view of the
river and city during one of the occasional gaps between galleries.
</P>
<P>
   Enter another room and see Monet's elegant water lilies
competing for your attention with a splattered drawing by Richard
Long. In one room, there's a portrait of a glass of water that
imagines itself to be an oak tree alongside a painting of a glass
on a table and a drawing of a computer.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Searle of The Guardian also was troubled a bit by the
sometimes odd arrangement of works, but not enough to dampen his
enthusiasm for the place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The display, flawed and problematic as it is, reminds us that
modern art is still an experiment rather than a linear progression
of indisputable masterpieces,'' he wrote. ``This is great.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s E-mail address is: BertR(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.tate.org.uk
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 1546EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000510.0097 </DOCNO>
