<SLUG> BC-UNILEVER-STREET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNILEVER EARNINGS JUMP 12 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds, price quoted in last graf does not reflect market close.)  
 By JENNIFER FRIEDLIN   
 c. 2000 TheStreet.com/N.Y. Times.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unilever (UL:NYSE ADR), the British-Dutch consumer goods giant,
reported a 12 percent jump in its first-quarter earnings Wednesday
as the company's restructuring efforts helped to lower costs.
</P>
<P>
   Unilever, whose products include Lipton teas and Dove skin-care
products, said its net profit, excluding exceptional items, rose to
716 million euros ($659 million), or 0.71 euro a share, from 640
million euros, or 0.57 euro a share, in the year-earlier period.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue rose a modest 1 percent, to 9.69 billion euros from 9.64
billion euros.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our strategy of focusing resources on leading brands is on
track,'' Unilever Chairman Niall FitzGerald said in a statement.
``We are managing the migration to a faster-growth portfolio
without endangering our profitability.''
</P>
<P>
   Unilever is currently in the process of divesting its
nonstrategic holdings while acquiring companies seen as capable of
contributing to long-term growth. Unilever recently agreed to
acquire SlimFast Foods and Ben &AMP; Jerry's Homemade (BJICA:NASDAQ)
for a total of about $2.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of Unilever's 400 leading brands grew over 3 percent in
the quarter even as sales in Europe, the company's largest region,
slipped 3 percent. Operating profit, however, rose 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Sales rose by 3 percent in North America, the company's second
biggest region, and by 9 percent in the Asia and Pacific region.
Operating profits were up 17 percent in North America and 41
percent in the Asia and Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
   Unilever's ADRs were up 7/8, or 4 percent, to 25 3/8 in early
trading Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
</TEXT>
