<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-LEONE-U.N.-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. PEACEKEEPERS PREPARE FOR CLASHES WITH REBELS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ With its political options running out, the
U.N. mission in Sierra Leone deployed its peacekeepers Wednesday in
anticipation of a clash with rebel fighters advancing toward the
capital, Freetown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll do what we have to do to defend ourselves and the
government,'' the U.N. spokesman, Fred Eckhard, said Wednesday.
``We hope it won't come to a pitched battle, but we are preparing
for one.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the peacekeepers had been pulled back around Freetown
and were digging in at the entrances to the capital.
</P>
<P>
   With the West African country sliding back into war, Eckhard
also said the United Nations would no longer report the movements
of its troops or clashes with the rebels, who are already engaged
against government forces.
</P>
<P>
   As thousands of refugees streamed toward Freetown, fleeing the
fresh fighting between the government and the rebels, some
representatives of U.N. aid agencies set out from the capital to
determine the size of the influx of refugees and how much food and
water would be needed to accommodate them.
</P>
<P>
   At U.N. headquarters, officials met with diplomats from Jordan,
India and Bangladesh who have agreed to speed up the delivery of
new infantry battalions committed to the peacekeeping mission. The
United States, Russia, Canada and the Netherlands have also offered
to provide air transportation for the reinforcements into Sierra
Leone. The arrival of the new troops would increase the mission's
military strength to 11,700 soldiers from the current 8,936. But
U.N. officials said the airlifts would not begin for at least
another 10 days because it was unclear how much equipment the
reinforcements would bring.
</P>
<P>
   Eckhard pointed out that the lightly armed peacekeepers now in
Sierra Leone were not configured or equipped for conventional
combat, a role that they were nonetheless preparing to assume.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council met Wednesday in a closed session, and
Sierra Leone was on its agenda. But the council adjourned without
any comment on the deteriorating situation there.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   With the peacekeeping mission approaching the brink of collapse,
U.N. officials admitted that they still knew little or nothing
about the whereabouts and condition of the more than 500
peacekeeping troops who have been seized and disarmed by the
rebels.
</P>
<P>
   One captured detachment of 200 Zambian soldiers was reported to
have been moved to Koidu, a rebel stronghold in eastern Sierra
Leone. There was still no word on the fate of a second group of 200
Zambians who were also reported to have been detained. Attempts to
deliver food and other supplies to the captured peacekeepers have
largely failed.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials confirmed Wednesday that 13 armored personnel
carriers seized a week ago from the Zambians had been painted black
and were apparently being used by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Revolutionary United Front, as the rebels call themselves,
has made no demands for the return of the captured peacekeepers,
leading U.N. officials to describe them as detainees rather than
hostages. The rebel leader, Foday Sankoh, initially denied holding
the peacekeepers, and his disappearance on Monday has left the
United Nations with no way to negotiate for their release.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations had been counting on a meeting of nine
regional African leaders on Tuesday in the Nigerian capital of
Abuja to help advance a political settlement.
</P>
<P>
   In a communique, the nine leaders condemned the Revolutionary
United Front for taking U.N. peacekeepers hostage and called for
their immediate and unconditional release. They also warned that
the amnesty against prosecution granted to Sankoh and other leaders
when they signed the peace treaty last July could be revoked and
that the rebels could be tried for war crimes. The rebels gained
notoriety during the eight-year civil war for mutilating civilians
and lopping off hands, arms and feet.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The regional leaders also promised to use ``all means at their
disposal, including the military option'' to prevent the rebels
from taking over Sierra Leone. But they stopped short of offering
immediate help to the beleaguered U.N. troops, saying that their
defense ministers and chiefs of staff would meet next Wednesday to
consider ``the practical modalities'' of reviving the West African
intervention force that had battled the rebels earlier, opening the
way to the peace treaty signed last year between the government and
the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan considered the Abuja
communique ``useful and positive,'' Eckhard said, but added that
U.N. officials would have no comment on its details until they had
studied it further.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Despite the chaos, U.N. officials refused to admit that the
peacekeeping mission to Sierra Leone had failed. ``For as long as
it's possible, we're going to hang in there and try to revive this
peace process,'' Eckhard said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
