<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1047 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-BEERNUT-TEX     05-10 0336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEERNUT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEER'S CLAIM TO FAME IS A WEAK ONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL BOURGEOIS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Famosa is a beer that easily could be mistaken for something
made in Taiwan, formerly known as Formosa, but it (the beer) is
produced in Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   In Central America it is known as Gallo, and the label includes
an image of what looks like a chicken, but it (the bird) is
supposed to be a quetzal, the national bird of Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   Gallo is the bestselling beer in Guatemala, or so says
Cerveceria Centro Americanea, the Guatemala City brewer. But when
it came time to export, the brewery found that a well-known
California winery already had dibs on Gallo, so the bottles
exported to the United States carry the label Famosa, or
``famous.'' It still has the bird picture.
</P>
<P>
   Now this beer may be famous in Guatemala, but Famosa or Gallo is
a highly ordinary beer. It is very drinkable, with a hoppiness
reminiscent of Budweiser, but it is undistinguished.
</P>
<P>
   It has a good color and head and a pleasing aroma. I found the
finish a tad metallic, but the same is true of Budweiser, which
tastes very similar. So why bother? Just get a Bud; it's cheaper
and easier to find. Close your eyes and pretend it's Famosa.
</P>
<P>
   If you must, Famosa is found in bars, restaurants and stores in
cities with significant Hispanic populations, in south Florida and
from Texas to California. The company says it's also available in
Oregon, Washington, D.C., Chicago, New York and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Famosa's sister and brother exports include: Dorada Draft (How
can it be draft if it comes in cans and bottles?); Moza, a dark
bock beer; and Monte Carlo Beer, which the company says ``appeals
to the more mature palate with more income.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, I've never encounted a palate, mature or immature, that
had any income.
</P>
<P>
   (Paul Bourgeois is beer critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
