<SLUG> BC-INTERNATIONAL-PAPER-STREET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNATIONAL PAPER INCREASES BID FOR CHAMPION 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds, prices in last two grafs do not reflect the market close)  
 By CAROLYN KOO   
 c. 2000 TheStreet.com/N.Y. Times.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   International Paper (IP:NYSE) increased its bid, now valued at
$9.5 billion in cash, stock and assumed debt, for rival paper
manufacturer Champion International (CHA:NYSE) on Wednesday, a bid
that Champion has declared ``superior'' to UPM-Kymmene's (UPM:NYSE
ADR) earlier $9.1 billion proposed cash and debt acquisition of
Champion, an increase of 3 percent over the bid agreed upon three
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   UPM-Kymmene responded by saying it will ``consider'' the new
situation, noting that it has until Friday at 5:00 p.m. EDT to
submit another proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The new offer from International Paper, the world's largest
producer of paper, values Champion at $75 a share, $50 in cash and
$25 in stock, a 13.1 percent premium to Champion's closing price
Tuesday of 66 5/16. A merger with Champion would give International
Paper a larger share of the growing market for magazine paper and a
stronger foothold in the quickly consolidating paper industry.
</P>
<P>
   International Paper unexpectedly bid $6.2 billion in cash and
stock for Champion at the end of April, in an attempt to thwart
Champion's union with UPM-Kymmene of Finland. UPM-Kymmene's stock
had fallen sharply since the deal was agreed upon in February,
making it less enticing for Champion investors.
</P>
<P>
   If Champion, based in Stamford, Conn., accepts the proposal,
International Paper will make a $75-a-share cash tender offer for
two-thirds of the outstanding Champion shares. Following a merger,
each remaining Champion share will be converted into International
Paper stock with a market value of $75.
</P>
<P>
   However, if Champion shares are trading below $34.50 a share at
the time of the merger, each remaining Champion share would be
converted into 2.17391 International Paper shares.
</P>
<P>
   International Paper expects a merger to result in $425 million
in annual cost savings. The Purchase, N.Y.-based company also said
that a merger should add to its earnings in the first full year
after completion of the deal and over the life of the cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Back in February, UPM-Kymmene, Europe's second-largest paper
maker, said it would exchange 1.99 of its ordinary shares for each
outstanding share of Champion common stock. At the time, the
exchange ratio represented a premium to Champion shareholders of
about 30 percent over the average ratio of the two stocks during
the past month. The deal then was valued at $8.7 billion in stock
and debt, but is now valued at only $7.9 billion since
UPM-Kymmene's stock has fallen and the euro has lost so much value
against the dollar. The deal represented the industry's first
substantial cross-Atlantic merger.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of International Paper were down 1 1/8, or 3 percent, to
36 1/8 in midday Wednesday trading, while UPM-Kymmene's American
depositary receipts were up 1, or 4 percent, to 29 3/8.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Champion were up 5 7/8, or 9 percent, to 72 3/16 in
midday Wednesday trading.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
</TEXT>
