<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW MCCAIN AND BUSH CAN GO ON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They looked comfortable together _ about as comfortable as
Evander Holyfield and Mike Tyson after the ear-biting incident.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately _ or unfortunately, depending on your point of view
_ George W. Bush and John McCain didn't have to square off in a
boxing ring to settle their differences. In their meeting Tuesday
at a Pittsburgh hotel, in fact, the former rivals for the
Republican presidential nomination evidently avoided fisticuffs and
even name-calling.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was followed by a televised display of congeniality
that was every bit as convincing as McCain's insistence that he
holds no ``rancor'' against Bush as a result of the candidates'
no-holds-barred primary battle.
</P>
<P>
   Right. And Monica Lewinsky holds no rancor against Linda Tripp
for taping their telephone conversations and giving the tapes to
Ken Starr.
</P>
<P>
   It's obvious that McCain is still ticked off about being
rejected by Republican voters from coast to coast _ and that it's
all he can do to speak Bush's name without snarling. Maybe McCain
will stop sulking in time to run for president again in eight years
_ when Bush is finishing up his second term in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said that he holds no ``rancor.'' He conspicuously didn't
say that he holds no ``grudge.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain is one of the great grudge-holders in big-time politics.
It would be astounding if he harbored no trace of bitterness toward
the man who derailed his Straight Talk Express.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain's lingering anger is his problem, not Bush's.
</P>
<P>
   The nominee-to-be was no doubt pleased to bury the hatchet. So
much has been made of the smoldering Bush-McCain feud that it had
to be a relief to throw some water on it.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's success or failure in the fall election, however, will
not be significantly affected by McCain's support _ any more than
it would have been affected by McCain's lack of support. Forget the
poll that imagines McCain pulling down 23 percent of the vote in a
Bush-Gore-McCain race. McCain isn't running, and even if he were,
he would never command that much support.
</P>
<P>
   And whatever support he might command is not transferable.
McCain backers _ like most voters _ will choose the candidate who
strikes them as best qualified to be commander in chief and best
equipped to deal with the issues and problems they care about.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's endorsement and two bucks would have bought Bush a
pari-mutuel ticket during his visit to the Kentucky Derby on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, it can't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   It's always helpful when a vanquished opponent decides to come
over to the winning side _ even if he surrenders grudgingly and
with a scowl on his face.
</P>
<P>
   So it was good news when McCain, asked why he hadn't used the
word ``endorsement,'' responded: ``I endorse Gov. Bush, I endorse
Gov. Bush, I endorse Gov. Bush ...''
</P>
<P>
   Even better news was McCain's announcement that he had asked
Bush ``that I not be considered for vice president of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   And the best news of all? That came in an exchange between Bush
and a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Reporter: ``Gov. Bush, Sen. McCain said that he didn't want to
be considered. Is that it? Is it over?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush: ``I take him for his word.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe now we can put an end to all this mindless chatter about a
Bush-McCain ticket. McCain would be a horrible choice as the
Republican candidate for vice president.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, McCain has said time and time again that he
doesn't want to be vice president. For another: Can you imagine
these two guys going through the entire campaign wearing those
pained expressions that we saw during their Pittsburgh news
conference?
</P>
<P>
   Like the reporter said: That's it. It's over.
</P>
<P>
   McCain did his partisan duty by swallowing his pride _ for a
moment, at least _ and endorsing Bush. The media's beloved Sen.
Straight Talk now can get back to doing what he does best:
promoting himself and his ``reform agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bush can get down to the task at hand: winning the election.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com (Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
