<SLUG> BC-OBIT-THOMPSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETER THOMPSON, 65, AN ACTOR AND TEACHER 
</HEADLINE>
   By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Peter Thompson, an actor on stage and in film who
later taught drama for more than 20 years, died on April 24 at New
York Hospital in Manhattan. He was 65 and lived in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was complications from heart surgery, said Robert
Cosenza, his companion.
</P>
<P>
   An Oklahoma native with boyish good looks, Thompson studied
theater at the University of Oklahoma and later migrated to New
York.
</P>
<P>
   His most fruitful years onstage came in the early 1970s as a
member of the American Shakespeare Festival in Stratford, Conn. In
three seasons there he played several major roles, including Cassio
in ``Othello,'' with Moses Gunn, which moved to Broadway; and
Bertram in ``All's Well That Ends Well.'' In 1971 he appeared in
O'Neill's ``Mourning Becomes Electra,'' opposite Sada Thompson and
Jane Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   By then Thompson had also begun to dabble in directing, staging
productions like ``Slow Dance on the Killing Ground'' and ``You
Can't Take It With You'' in Atlanta. In 1976 he received favorable
reviews for his direction of ``Lemon Sky,'' by Lanford Wilson, at
the Westside Theater in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   That same year he began teaching acting and scene study at
Michael Howard Studios in Manhattan, where he once trained.
Thompson also taught at the Circle in the Square acting program, in
affiliation with New York University.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Cosenza, Thompson is survived by a brother,
William, of Oklahoma City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 1607EDT &QL; 
