r e BC-BESTSELLERS-TEX     05-10 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BESTSELLERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BESTSELLER' MAY NOT MEAN WHAT YOU THINK IT MEANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have you ever been on the fence about a book, and you ultimately
decided to buy it because it had ``National Bestseller'' festooned
across the cover?
</P>
<P>
   If so, you're certainly not alone. As is the case with movies,
word-of-mouth opinion about a book has always carried more weight
for most people than critical reviews, and there's no greater gauge
of a book's mass appeal than the bestseller lists.
</P>
<P>
   Or so you probably thought.
</P>
<P>
   It seems pretty simple to the average consumer: Stores report
book sales, and those books that rang up on the register most often
are the bestsellers. The problem is that bestseller lists don't do
it that way.
</P>
<P>
   From the prestigious New York Times list to the surging USAToday
ranking, in-store book sales are only one of many factors in the
makeup of prominent weekly bestseller lists. And how much of a
factor is known to only the secretive select few who compile them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not reveal our process, though I'll say we factor in
changing conditions in the (book) industry,'' says John Wright,
who's in charge of the list for the New York Times. ``But we
certainly do include actual sales, from about 4,000 bookstores and
wholesalers.''
</P>
<P>
   The complicated formula is used because, at least to publishers,
weekly ``book sales'' figures don't necessarily mean any books have
left the stores. Publishers usually sell their books at radically
discounted prices to wholesalers (also known as ``distributors''),
who resell the books to retailers from Borders to the local
mom-and-pop shop. But bookstores, having bought the books, can
subsequently return unsold copies to publishers for credit on
future book orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a concession bookstores won from publishers in the
early 1960s,'' says Larry Swindell, former books editor of the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram and the Philadelphia Inquirer and a founding
member of the National Book Critics Circle. ``Publishers had found
it increasingly difficult to persuade booksellers to stock titles
that represented high-risk sales.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also when traditional bestseller lists became tainted,
critics say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Members of the general public think bestseller lists indicate
books sold over the counter in stores to consumers,'' says Michael
Hoynes, marketing director for Book Sense, a subdivision of the
American Booksellers Association. ``But that isn't the case. If,
say, a publisher reports that it sold 2,000 copies of a book to
Distributor X, and that sale of 2,000 is counted in a bestseller
list, in reality, six months later only 1,000 copies might actually
have been sold to consumers, and 1,000 copies will be returned to
the publisher.''
</P>
<P>
   This has been a problem for weekly list compilers since the
returns system was instituted. Wright says The New York Times has a
``way of factoring in a percentage (of returns),'' though he
acknowledges it's ``not that big a factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Hoynes is not an objective observer himself. He was
hired by the booksellers association, which represents the
interests of the rapidly dwindling ranks of independently owned
(''nonchain'') bookstores, to develop a bestseller list that would
rival The New York Times and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want another way to indicate to consumers that independent
stores offer different advantages from the chain stores,'' Hoynes
says, citing chain stores' emphasis on big-name writers and major
launches at the expense of releases from smaller publishers and
lesser-known authors. ``Our list, with weekly information gathered
from more than 300 (independent) stores, reports from actual sales
to consumers. Nothing else is in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Since their inception (The New York Times list debuted in 1935),
bestseller lists have been presented as useful information for
consumers. But, of course, they are also powerful sales tools for
publishers and bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Publishers could use bestseller status to sell more copies of
a book to stores,'' says Swindell, because the bestseller tag often
had a hypnotic effect on book consumers searching for a good buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, what we care about is what the consumers respond
to,'' says Stuart Applebaum, senior vice president of Random House.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing the influence The New York Times wielded with its
list, USAToday debuted its own bestseller list in 1993, which
lumped hardcover and paperback titles in one all-encompassing
group. The Wall Street Journal followed in 1994. Both, like the
Times, used private formulas to tabulate rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Now major retailers like Barnes &AMP; Noble have gotten in on the
action, creating bestseller lists based on their own internal sales
figures _ and discounting books that are on their list. Internet
giant Amazon.com ranks about 1.2 million titles in order of its
sales and updates its Top 100 list hourly.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no single list satisfies everyone. Christian book
publishers believe they face blatant discrimination, because most
lists either ignore or give little weight to sales from independent
Christian shops, which comprise about one-third of all operating
bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is obvious,'' says Rolf Zettersten, publisher of
Nashville, Tennessee-based Thomas Nelson. ``I know we have books
that sell 100,000 copies (in Christian stores) and never show up on
The New York Times bestseller list.''
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, book club sales are excluded from all the major
lists.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is currently no way of instantaneous tracking of all
sales, like I believe the record industry has with Billboard
(magazine),'' Wright says. ``The book industry is more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, no two bestseller lists ever have the same books in
the same order. This is an advantage to publishers, because the
more bestseller lists there are, the better the odds that a book
will rank on at least one of them. And if a title gets on even the
last rung of one of the major lists _ The New York Times, USAToday,
Publishers Weekly, The Wall Street Journal _ publishers can market
it as a bestseller without noting that it perhaps ranked 15th on
one list for one week and never appeared on any others.
</P>
<P>
   Wright even concedes that the mighty New York Times benefits
from distribution and discussion of its bestseller list.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prestige of it is good for the paper,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   One might say the consumer is the only one who doesn't benefit
from the proliferation of bestseller lists, though that wouldn't
quite be true, either. To be sure, it's impossible to figure out
from the bestseller lists which books actually sold the best in any
given week, but book buyers do benefit in that most chain
bookstores offer substantial discounts on titles appearing on the
major lists.
</P>
<P>
   For many bibliophiles, 25 to 40 percent off is worth a little
confusion.
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7720, or e-mail:
jguinn(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
