<HEADER>
A1063 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     05-10 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV28-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., MAY 28, 2000. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 2000 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: We have an old lamp that originally belonged to my wife's
mother and has sentimental value. This lamp needs repair badly.
</P>
<P>
   The electric cord is frayed and should be replaced and the
switch no longer works properly. I'm not sure what else is wrong,
or even if the lamp can really be repaired so it will be safe to
use.
</P>
<P>
   Do you think it is possible for a do-it-yourselfer to repair
such a lamp without having to call in an electrician?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you are even moderately handy it should be no problem.
Most lamps have only a limited number of parts (as shown in the
illustration).
</P>
<P>
   When a lamp does not work it is either the lamp socket with its
built-in switch that needs replacing, or the electric cord and plug
that should be replaced. Your best bet is to replace all of them.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the shade and its harp, then take the socket apart by
removing the upper brass shell and the cardboard insulation sleeve
under it.
</P>
<P>
   Disconnect the wires from the terminal screws and tie a length
of cord to the end of this wire before you pull the wire out from
the bottom. The cord can then be used to pull the new wire back up
through the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Pull out the wire and unscrew the brass socket base, then screw
the new socket base in place.
</P>
<P>
   Use the cord to pull the new wire back up from the bottom and
connect this to the terminals on the new socket's base.
</P>
<P>
   Reassemble all parts in reverse order.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I painted the concrete stoop in front of my house about a
year ago and realize that it is now slippery when wet.
</P>
<P>
   What is the easiest way to get this deck paint off the concrete?
</P>
<P>
   A: Your best bet is to use a heavy duty, semi-paste paint
remover.
</P>
<P>
   Brush on thick layers of this and allow to soak for about 15-20
minutes, then scrub off with a stiff brush dipped into a detergent
solution.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid working in the sun if possible, and flush off with lots of
plain water.
</P>
<P>
   Protect plants and turf by covering with plastic and by hosing
off continuously.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The chain link fence around our yard needs painting. I tried
using a large brush, but this takes forever.
</P>
<P>
   Spraying is impossible because my neighbor won't stand for it.
</P>
<P>
   What other suggestions can you offer?
</P>
<P>
   A: The fastest and easiest method is to use a roller.
</P>
<P>
   Buy a long-nap roller cover with fibers at least 3/4'' long and
roll the paint on slowly with moderate pressure.
</P>
<P>
   To protect plants and grass, cover the ground with a plastic
drop cloth and slide this under the metal fence.
</P>
<P>
   The job will go faster with two people working, one following
behind the other to catch drips and runs, and to smooth out the
original application.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The old wood floor in our dining area is in reasonably good
condition but needs refinishing.
</P>
<P>
   There are quite a few spaces between the floor boards that I
once tried to fill with a ``wood dough'' but this dried up and
cracked out in less than a year.
</P>
<P>
   What can I do to fill these cracks permanently while still
maintaining the hardwood floor look?
</P>
<P>
   A: Short of cutting many narrow strips of matching wood for a
snug fit between the boards there is little you can do without
redoing the entire floor.
</P>
<P>
   The only other solution I can think of, if you want to retain
the appearance of a hardwood floor, is to recover the entire floor
with some type of wood parquet tiles, or with prefinished wood
flooring in strip form.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``ANATOMY OF A LAMP'' goes with this
column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: Lamps have a number of simple parts and can be easily
taken apart for repairs or replacements.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
