<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAT YOUR VEGGIES SO YOU WON'T FEEL GUILTY ABOUT DESSERT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A reader e-mailed looking for the recipe for the yellow
squash-zucchini-bacon casserole served at Luby's cafeterias. I
found that recipe in the cookbook the company published in 1996;
it's sold at the cafeterias.
</P>
<P>
   Dollie Hovland of Whitney, Texas, volunteered a recipe that is
making the rounds among her friends. The recipe was printed in her
electric co-operative paper and is getting rave reviews.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, we had a request for the chewy chocolate cookies
that are sold in several area supermarkets. We found this recipe at
www.Allrecipes.com, a terrific source for recipes on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   LUBY'S FRENCH BAKED SQUASH
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8
</P>
<P>
   4 cups yellow squash slices (1/4-inch thick)
</P>
<P>
   4 cups zucchini slices (1/4-inch thick)
</P>
<P>
   3 slices bacon, diced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup slivered red onion
</P>
<P>
   10 3/4-ounce can condensed cream of celery soup
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup finely diced red bell pepper or pimento
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In medium saucepan, bring 2 quarts water to boil. Add squash and
zucchini. Cook 3 to 4 minutes or until almost crisp-tender. Drain.
</P>
<P>
   In 10-inch skillet, cook bacon until crisp. remove with slotted
spoon and reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Add onion to bacon drippings. Cook and stir over medium heat 2
minutes. Drain off drippings. Add reserved bacon, soup, red bell
pepper or pimento, salt and pepper. Mix well. Remove from heat.
Fold in vegetables. Transfer to 2-quart baking dish. Cover with
foil.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 30 minutes. Remove foil. Sprinkle with cheese. Place under
broiler to lightly brown cheese, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 87 calories, 5 grams fat, 8
grams carbohydrates, 5 grams protein, 10 milligrams cholesterol,
719 milligrams sodium, 47 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Luby's Cafeteria 50th Anniversary Recipe Collection''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   GERMAN CHOCOLATE UPSIDE-DOWN CAKE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 10-14
</P>
<P>
   Cake:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup flaked coconut
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   18 1/2-ounce package German chocolate cake mix
</P>
<P>
   3 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   Topping:
</P>
<P>
   8-ounce package cream cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   1 pound powdered sugar, sifted
</P>
<P>
   Grease 13-by-9-by-2-inch pan. Line with wax paper and grease
paper. Sprinkle coconut and pecans in bottom of prepared pan; set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   Combine cake mix, eggs, water and oil in large bowl; mix
according to package directions. Spoon batter over coconut and
pecans.
</P>
<P>
   Combine cream cheese and butter in saucepan; cook over low heat,
stirring often, until butter melts and mixture is smooth. Stir in
powdered sugar. Spoon mixture evenly over batter.
</P>
<P>
   Bake at 350 degrees for 40-45 minutes. Cool in pan on wire rack
for 10 minutes; invert cake onto a serving plate. Remove and
discard wax paper.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 533 calories, 31 grams fat, 63
grams carbohydrates, 6 grams protein, 86 milligrams cholesterol,
467 milligrams sodium, 52 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CHOCOLATE CHEWS
</P>
<P>
   Yields 3 1/2 dozen
</P>
<P>
   1 cup semisweet chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup white sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   Melt chocolate chips in heavy saucepan over very low heat. Stir
to evenly melt.
</P>
<P>
   Cream together butter and sugars until light. Beat in eggs, one
at a time. Stir in melted chocolate and vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   In a bowl, whisk together flour, baking powder and baking soda.
Add to butter mixture slowly. Blend thoroughly. Shape into 1-inch
balls and place on a greased cookie sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Bake at 350 degrees for 12 to 14 minutes. Let sit on cookie
sheet for a minute or two before removing to a rack to cool.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per cookie: 83 calories, 4 grams fat, 11
grams carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 16 milligrams cholesterol, 44
milligrams sodium, 43 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ www.Allrecipes.com
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
