r d BC-PRODUCE-CO-OP-TEX     05-10 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRODUCE-CO-OP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVINGS ON VEGETABLES ARE BUT ONE BENEFIT OF JOINING A PRODUCE
CO-OP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KATHRYN HOPPER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My neighbor Pam is one of those moms I idolize.
</P>
<P>
   She grows roses the size of basketballs and installs her own
wood floors, and her kids always seem to have their shoes on.
</P>
<P>
   So when she decided to let me in on one of her secrets, I
listened intently over the hum of her Suburban's engine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an opening in the co-op, do you want in?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' I said, not really knowing what I'd just agreed to but
sure that if Pam was involved, it would be a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   That day, I became one of nine Grapevine and Southlake moms
united by their thriftiness and love of fresh food in a fruit and
vegetable co-op.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, I was pretty ignorant about the co-op thing. I
associated the term with the 1970s era ``back-to-the-Earth''
movement, picturing hordes of hippie moms in and around Berkeley,
Calif., stockpiling bulgur wheat and organic peanut butter.
</P>
<P>
   Our co-op operates on a smaller scale, but the principle is the
same, ``co-op''erating to help save time and money. For $20 a week
per member, you get two boxes of fresh produce to fuel your family.
</P>
<P>
   On days when the order came in, I could forgo McDonald's and
make a simple supper of fresh corn-on-the-cob, tomatoes in vinegar,
cantaloupe slices and strawberry shortcake.
</P>
<P>
   Each member takes a turn buying the produce, making the trip to
wholesalers located by the Dallas Farmers Market.
</P>
<P>
   When I joined, I got a schedule and assorted tips about which
wholesalers had a reputation for hiding rotten goods in the bottoms
of the boxes.
</P>
<P>
   I also received a survey that noted which vegetables were
popular with members and which ones we were absolutely, positively
not to buy.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, I didn't pay too much attention to the survey. On
my first buying trip, I bought cabbage. A no-no. Where I saw bowls
of fresh slaw, my fellow members saw only six heads that would
stink up their kitchens when boiled. I tried to make up for it by
handing out slaw recipes, but the damage was done.
</P>
<P>
   That's when I recognized that being in a co-op takes compromise
and creativity. Unless you are doing the shopping that week, you
are at the mercy of your fellow members and their tastes.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, members stick to the basics: green beans,
tomatoes, potatoes and corn. But occasionally things get a bit
exotic and you're forced to expand your culinary horizons.
</P>
<P>
   I learned this with squash. A native Southerner, I thought
yellow crookneck squash was the only variety. But my fellow co-op
members were mostly Yankees who bought me boxes full of
bizarre-looking acorn and spaghetti squash.
</P>
<P>
   I had no idea how to prepare these strange squashes, but I
relied on my ``Fanny Farmer Cookbook'' and tips from fellow
members. I learned how to microwave and bake acorn squash into
tenderness and dump enough brown sugar on top that my kids don't
recognize it as a vegetable.
</P>
<P>
   Being in a co-op also means dealing with mass quantities. For
example, one week, my co-op order included 40 cucumbers. I ran
through my recipes for cucumber soups and salads, then hit cucumber
overload.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble was, I still has about 20 left. Rather than let them
rot, I brought them to work and handed them out to co-workers, who
started calling me ``the cucumber queen.''
</P>
<P>
   As with any organization, there are logistics to deal with. In
our co-op, each member pays upfront in cash, $20 for a full order,
before joining. Sometimes, if one order is too much for a family,
two moms split an order, each paying $10.
</P>
<P>
   Our co-op has six orders, or about $120. With that, we can
usually get three or four fruits and four or five vegetables.
That's more than enough to feed my very hungry family of five and
have plenty left over. During the holidays, I had enough oranges,
grapes and bananas to put together gift baskets for my sons'
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   When an order comes in, members bring their cash and hand it
over when picking up the produce. If you split an order with
someone, one of you pays the $20 for a full order, then splits up
the order for the other.
</P>
<P>
   We keep a notebook that lists all the produce items purchased
and who paid, an informal record system that's packaged in a
plastic envelope with a calculator.
</P>
<P>
   One of the unexpected benefits has been teaching my three sons
basic math. When we go shopping, they help me figure out how many
of the 72 oranges each member should receive. They learn to count
by helping me sort out the orders in our garage. Sometimes the
counting is skewed by my 2-year-old, who likes to take a bite out
of errant apples.
</P>
<P>
   Having an ample supply of fresh fruits and vegetables means I
don't have an easy excuse for ordering pizza every night. The co-op
has helped us get somewhere close to the recommended servings of
fruit and vegetables each day. It also forces me to plan ahead,
figuring out what meals I need to make days (as opposed to minutes)
beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the best benefits is the bond I've forged with other
members. I feel I'm no longer flailing around in the rough seas of
suburban domesticity. I've united with superior modern-day
gatherers against junk food, microwave meals and overpriced produce
departments.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks, Pam.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The savings
</P>
<P>
   Can being in a co-op save you money? Here's a comparison between
the last co-op order and what similar goods would have cost at the
grocery store:
</P>
<P>
   Co-op...........Store
</P>
<P>
   2 quarts strawberries......$1.33....$5.98
</P>
<P>
   6 grapefruit...............$1.50....$1.98
</P>
<P>
   3 cantaloupes..............$3.00....$5.27
</P>
<P>
   18 bananas.................$2.08....$3.75
</P>
<P>
   5 tomatoes.................$1.66....$3.50
</P>
<P>
   20 tangerines..............$1.63....$9.03
</P>
<P>
   12 Granny Smith apples.....$2.50....$5.88
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds onions............$1.66....$3.30
</P>
<P>
   4 heads romaine lettuce....$1.46....$5.13
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds broccoli crowns...$1.75....$6.00
</P>
<P>
   10 pounds russet potatoes..$1.83....$3.99
</P>
<P>
   Total.....................$20.40...$53.81
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Note: Store prices are from a local grocery store, May 2
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
