<DOCNO> NYT20000510.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1070 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CHINA-INTERNET-$ADV14     05-10 1575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-INTERNET-$ADV14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    VENTURE CAPITAL, CONSUMER DEMAND FUELING CHINA'S DOTCOM
EXPLOSION
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., May 14 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By JULIE CHAO 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Eleven years ago, Steve Sun was a student
hunger-striker on Tiananmen Square being interviewed by CBS News's
Dan Rather on why China needed democracy. Today, with an American
MBA and three years of Wall Street experience, he is a dotcom chief
executive with a 14th-floor corner office in one of Beijing's
newest high-rises.
</P>
<P>
   He and two partners decided only late last year to get in on the
Internet action in China. They threw together a business plan in 10
days, raised more than enough capital in two weeks to start their
company and launched Sinobit.com less than two months later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the signing of the (World Trade Organization) agreement
between China and the United States that really expedited the
process,'' Sun said, referring to the sweeping trade accord signed
last November. ``We had a conference call that night and really
moved fast.''
</P>
<P>
   He is part of a trickle of students with a U.S. education
returning to China which, though not nearly significant enough to
reverse a decades-long brain drain, is certainly helping fuel the
explosive growth of the Internet in this country of 1.3 billion.
From nearly all facets _ users, entrepreneurs and investors _
interest in all things Web-related is huge and the pace of change
has been breakneck.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Silicon Valley squared,'' said Jay Chang, an analyst
for Credit Suisse/First Boston in Hong Kong who specializes in the
Internet in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, government restrictions on content and certain
business operations may be hindering the Web's development, but
entrepreneurs see them as just a part of doing business. In fact,
dotcoms are being formed at the rate of two a day, according to the
state-run China Daily.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the government's blocking of certain foreign Web sites
keeping surfers away. The number of Internet users here has been
doubling every six months for the last two years, reaching 8.9
million at the end of last year, according to official Chinese
government figures. Although penetration is low, if triple-digit
growth keeps up, China could have the world's largest Internet
population in just five years.
</P>
<P>
   Almost more quickly than Web surfers can log on, Chinese
entrepreneurs have been giving them more places to click to _ from
sports and entertainment sites to on-line bookstores and
newspapers. Sinobit, which helps select start-ups find capital,
hoped to get 3,000 applications in its first year for its ``Dream
Lab,'' where potential investors can review business plans. In less
than two months, with very little advertising, they received more
than 5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Feeding this expansion are venture capitalists, mostly from the
United States, but also from Hong Kong, Japan and within China
itself. Until just a of couple months ago, the sense was that they
were throwing money at just about anyone with an idea and an
impressive management team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was happening all the time _ some Chinese kid with an MBA
and a slick business presentation getting loads of money,'' said
Mark Baldwin, chief executive of Zhaopin.com, a Beijing
head-hunting firm with a job listing site. ``(Venture capitalists)
love people who talk their language.''
</P>
<P>
   While overseas investors are now showing somewhat more restraint
toward new start-ups, analysts say they don't seem to have the
patience in China that they did with the U.S. market, where they
allow a few years to build an audience before worrying about
profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whereas in the United States, you had that honeymoon
traffic-only stage for a couple years, in China, 1999 was all about
growing page-views. In 2000, they're starting to focus on
revenues,'' said Christopher Mumford, founder of YaoLan.com, the
leading baby-care Web site. ``I think in six to nine months, it's
going to be, 'OK, you have to show us a profit.'''
</P>
<P>
   Having the U.S. experience to go by is both a blessing and a
curse, Chinese analysts and executives say.
</P>
<P>
   While Chinese dotcoms have emulated many of the American
business models, they worry that U.S. investors are blindly
applying they're own market conditions to China, which lags at
least a couple of years behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like feeding a baby with beef,'' said Joseph Chen, chief
executive of ChinaRen.com, a Web site geared towards young people.
``A baby needs milk.''
</P>
<P>
   The most intense competition is among the portals, which are
also the leading consumers of foreign capital and are all vying to
become the Yahoo of China. ChinaRen, a U.S.-funded company started
by Chen and two other under-30 Chinese students who all met at
Stanford University, is not unlike other start-ups in that it
spends 70 percent of its budget on marketing and public relations.
It has booked billboard space for the next year-and-a-half. In
fact, billboard space in Beijing is sold out for the next three
years, mostly to high-tech companies.
</P>
<P>
   Because the industry is so young, the search for experienced
employees often leads to a rival's personnel list, which is a
highly-guarded commodity at many companies. Chen said one of his
project managers was offered a six-fold salary increase by a
competitor. He convinced the employee to stay with a promotion and
a 60-percent pay raise. ChinaRen programmers make as much as
US$3,000 a month _ a phenomenal salary in China, where the average
factory worker's monthly wage is less than US$150 and a
journalist's less than US$400.
</P>
<P>
   Executives from U.S. high-tech companies are also being poached
by China's dotcoms. Henry Huang, chairman of a high-tech P.R. firm
in Beijing whose clients include Microsoft, Dell and Intel,
estimates 70 percent of the Chinese managers and directors working
for the big-name American companies have jumped ship for a
start-up.
</P>
<P>
   ChinaRen focuses on the under-25 set, allowing them to create
their own Web pages and post photos.
</P>
<P>
   But in the midst of these unprecedented new avenues for personal
expression, ChinaRen is ever mindful not to upset China's communist
government. With more than 20,000 new photos uploaded every day, 10
people are employed just to vet them. CEO Chen says they avoid
``pornography, politically sensitive stuff; no religious promotion.
It's strictly entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese government has conflicting motives, analysts say,
wanting to maintain control over the Internet while wanting to see
it develop.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to become a 21st-Century superpower,'' said Chang,
the Internet analyst. ``To do that, you have to use the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The legal and regulatory framework is still playing catch-up.
While dotcoms wait for a comprehensive set of rules, they've had to
work with piecemeal restrictions on who can provide original news
content, how much foreign investment is allowed, and when and how a
Chinese company can go public abroad. Sina.com, the leading portal,
was forced to carve out its Chinese assets and operations before
listing on Nasdaq last month. And other Chinese dotcoms with IPO
dreams will have to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Although Chinese Web sites may be politically tame, Internet
exhibitions _ which seem to take place every other week here in
Beijing _ can veer towards the wild side. At COMDEX last month,
attendees were treated to Western women in precariously fastened
halter tops, surrounded by a crowd five-deep, shaking and kicking
to the blasting music while girls in metallic miniskirts and roller
blades handed out brochures.
</P>
<P>
   At Internet World, the audience mobbed the seminar speakers _
mostly Internet executives and investment bankers _ like they were
rock stars. But instead of asking for an autograph, it was a
business card they were all after.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   While Internet companies in China are careful to stay well
within political boundaries, most recognize the Web's potential to
transform Chinese society.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, you can say anything you want on the Web,'' said Lu
Benfu, an Internet researcher at the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences, government think tank. ``This will open society even
more. Secondly, it will help Chinese people enter the world
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Much as Westerners talk about the free-wheeling Internet
fomenting political change, though, Chinese people, who've proven
adept at adapting to new technologies, don't see it as such a
revolutionary new medium.
</P>
<P>
   ``China will change on its own path at its own speed, but with
determination from the top'' Chen said. ``No external force will
change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the 1989 student demonstrations at Tiananmen Square are
``kind of remote now'' for Sinobit.com's Sun, he still hasn't
forgotten about the six students from his university killed in the
massacre.
</P>
<P>
   And while the Internet for him foremost is a business venture,
``at least a side effect will be to promote democracy and freedom
in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   (Julie Chao's E-mail address is: juliec(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.cnnic.net/e-index.shtml: The China Internet Network
Information Center issues bi-annual reports on Internet
demographics and the most popular Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
