<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS BACK MEDICARE PRESCRIPTION DRUG BILL 
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional Democrats rallied Wednesday around a
bill that would offer prescription drug benefits as a standard part
of the Medicare program, in contrast to the approach favored by
Republicans, who want to subsidize private insurance to help pay
such costs.
</P>
<P>
   Several dozen House and Senate Democrats joined in a display of
unity at the White House, where they said they had agreed on a
proposal to offer coverage of prescription drugs to all Medicare
beneficiaries _ 39 million people who are elderly or disabled.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' proposal is similar to a plan offered by
President Clinton, but it is somewhat more generous to
beneficiaries and somewhat more expensive to the government.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and members of Congress appeared in the White House Rose
Garden with Betty Dizik, a 73-year-old widow who said she skips
prescribed medications for diabetes and a heart condition because
she cannot afford them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not asking for a handout or charity,'' Dizik said. ``I'm
willing to work and do my part. I'm just asking for a little
help.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' proposal is embodied in a bill introduced
Wednesday by the Senate minority leader, Tom Daschle of South
Dakota, with 32 of the 45 Democratic senators as co-sponsors. The
House Democratic leader, Dick Gephardt of Missouri, said he would
soon introduce a bill nearly identical to the Senate measure.
</P>
<P>
   In a Congress controlled by Republicans, the Democrats have no
chance of seeing their bills enacted. But they hope that by taking
a unified position, they can put pressure on the Republicans and
promote negotiations to enact legislation in this election year.
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail, Vice President Al Gore and many
congressional Democrats have pummeled Republicans as slow to act on
prescription drug benefits.
</P>
<P>
   But the president sounded a more conciliatory note. ``We all
know we can't achieve our efforts without bipartisan support in the
Congress,'' Clinton said Wednesday. ``That's why, just as we are
trying to do with the patient's bill of rights, we want to reach
across the aisle to encourage Republican support, as well. This can
and should be a truly bipartisan effort.''
</P>
<P>
   The congressional Democrats, like Clinton, say Medicare should
cover half of a person's drug expenses up to certain limits _ half
of the first $2,000 in drug expenses starting in 2002. The ceiling
would rise gradually. By 2009, Medicare would cover half of the
first $5,000 in drug expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some drugs cost much more than $5,000 a year. The
congressional Democrats would provide assistance for people with
very high expenses; Medicare would pick up all of their drug costs
after they spend $3,000 or $4,000 of their own money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
