<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV14-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GORE NEEDS TO PERFECT CAMPAIGN STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;    (For release Sunday, May 14)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Al Gore has a great deal to say about many issues
in this campaign, but the manner in which he says them may at times
lose rather than win votes.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that Gore, for all his years in politics, often
tends to use old arm-waving, floor-stomping, pre-television
techniques while George W. Bush campaigns with a cool, confident
expression, a modulated voice and control of his arms.
</P>
<P>
   Style may not win elections. But it can help. In 1960 charm,
good looks and a facile sense of humor were the qualities that
edged John Kennedy across the victory line over a charmless Richard
Nixon in history's closest presidential balloting.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin D. Roosevelt's buoyant personality and wit undoubtedly
played a role in his four presidential victories. In 1940, seeking
an unprecedented third term, FDR sabotaged Republican hopes when,
before a cheering throng in Madison Square Garden, he ridiculed GOP
isolationists by reciting, in the meter of ``Wynken, Blyken and
Nod,'' the names of three prominent ones _ ``Martin, Barton and
Fish.'' Soon the audience was chanting with him. And before long
the campaign was over, and Roosevelt was the victor.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, he employed humor again and even more
effectively as he sank the Republican's Goodship Thomas E. Dewey.
Speaking at a Teamsters' dinner to a national radio audience, FDR,
according to biographer Frank Freidel, gave ``one of the most
effective performances of his career.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the night he described how the Republicans had attacked
``my little dog Fala'' with the lucicrous charge that Fala had been
left behind when the president visited the Aleutians and that
millions of tax dollars had been spent to fly him home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't resent attacks, and my family doesn't resent
attacks,'' said the president in mock seriousness, ``but Fala does
resent them. You know, Fala is Scotch ... and his Scotch soul was
furious. He has not been the same dog since.''
</P>
<P>
   The audience roared with laughter as did millions of radio
listeners across the land.
</P>
<P>
   As for poor old Tom Dewey and his presidential aspirations,
Harry Truman sank them again four years later.
</P>
<P>
   Truman knew how to invigorate an otherwise dull campaign speech
with a healthy dose of Harry's ``give 'em hell'' remedy. Ronald
Reagan was adept at using self-deprecating humor to lighten his
campaign speeches and win the hearts of his audience. Since he was
the oldest man ever elected president, he had a great time poking
fun at his age.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has seen Gore at a lunch, dinner or reception knows
he is a friendly man of intelligence and good motivation who enjoys
a good laugh at himself. He was at his best at the annual Gridiron
dinner here in March at which politics and politicians were spoofed
by newspapermen and women who saw and heard a Gore that the public
rarely sees and hears.
</P>
<P>
   Substituting for Bill Clinton, Gore made outrageous fun of
himself and proved the stellar attraction of the evening. Humor
often can be more effective than bombast.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton reclaimed his political king-of-comedy crown at the
annual White House Correspondents Association dinner late last
month when he showed a homemade movie on how little a lame-duck
president has to do.
</P>
<P>
   The film pictures Clinton answering the White House telephones,
preparing a brown-bag lunch for his wife Hillary as she headed to
New York to campaign for the Senate, watching clothes spin round in
a washing machine and rinsing off the presidential limousine.
</P>
<P>
   There is a fine line between presidential humor and presidential
seriousness. A candidate who does or says too many foolish things
can find himself in just as much trouble as one who constantly is
ponderous and pontificating.
</P>
<P>
   One of Gore's problems is that he sometimes tends to whine. At
other times, he takes an issue and rambles on about it when a
short, crisp explanation of his position would suffice.
</P>
<P>
   It was inevitable that Social Security would become a major
issue, dividing Gore and Bush. Given the erratic manner in which
the stock market has behaved of late, Gore has a good argument when
he complains that senior citizens could get burned badly if they
were to follow Bush's proposal and invest their Social Security
retirement funds in private accounts.
</P>
<P>
   He has another good issue in the declaration of National Rifle
Association First Vice President Kayne Robinson that the NRA has
``unbelievably friendly relations'' with Bush, who presumably as
president would name Supreme Court justices opposed to gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Gore has solid positions on such key issues as
education, the environment and Medicare. His problem appears to be
a desperate desire to become president and a silly inclination to
shed his proper, affluent upbringing and act like one of the boys.
</P>
<P>
   His task is to be wise, articulate and presidential. At the
moment Bush is doing a better job than Gore in practicing those
traits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
