<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERS QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. What is the difference between registering a domain name and
reserving one?
</P>
<P>
   A. If you go to a registration company like Network Solutions to
buy a name for your Web site but don't yet have the host servers
set up for your site, you can reserve the domain name of your
choice so it will be there when you are ready to set up the site.
If you already have your Web host servers in place, you can
register the domain name and provide the domain-name company with
the technical information about your host server that it needs for
registration. Some registration companies will let you register the
name even if you don't have your host information and will hold it
for you until you are ready.
</P>
<P>
   Register.com, another company that sells domain names, recently
announced a Domain Lock Down service for corporate customers. The
service, which costs $99, provides security against those who might
try to tamper with or hijack a registered name.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a Macintosh and use Netscape to browse the Web. When I
have tried to start Netscape lately, it has begun to open, then
crashed. I haven't installed any new software that might be
conflicting with it, and nothing on my system is different.
</P>
<P>
   A. There are a number of factors that could be affecting your
browser, but there is a quick fix to try before picking up the
phone to call for tech support. The Preferences file for your
Netscape software may have become corrupted, and that could cause
it to shut down almost as soon as it starts up.
</P>
<P>
   Double-click on your Mac's hard drive icon and find the System
Folder. Inside that is a folder called Preferences; in there you
will see a folder called Netscape. Inside that will be a file
called Netscape Preferences. Drag that file to your desktop, and
retart your Mac.
</P>
<P>
   Try to start Netscape as you usually would and see if it opens
properly. If it does, then your old Preferences file was probably
corrupted, and you can throw out the one on your desktop. Netscape
will create a new Preferences file if it doesn't find one in the
System Folder. One side effect of discarding your Preferences file,
though, is that your custom settings (including your choice of home
page and font size) will return to the default settings, so you
will have to reset them.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is the minimum software I would need to make my own Web
pages?
</P>
<P>
   A. If you want to take the time to learn HyperText Markup
Language (HTML), the code used to create Web pages, you can get by
with just a basic text editor like the Windows WordPad or the
SimpleText program that comes with each Macintosh. You can view
your Web pages with any Web browser, and you may want to get an
image-editing program for use with graphics and pictures on your
page. A file transfer program like WS-FTP for Windows (or Fetch for
the Mac) will be needed to upload your finished pages to your Web
server.
</P>
<P>
   Most people would rather not have to learn HTML, and there are
plenty of commercial programs available that will let you create
your Web pages by dragging and dropping objects and type onto a
page layout. These programs convert your creations into the HTML
code, and some also include site-management tools that help you
keep track of all the pages on your site. GoLive from Adobe Systems
and HomeSite from Allaire are two options. Programs like Complete
Web Studio by Sierra Home are aimed at home users and simplify the
process even more.
</P>
<P>
   The latest versions of Microsoft Word for both Mac and Windows
will let you save Word documents as HTML files. Many Internet
service providers like America Online will not only give you space
on their servers to keep your Web pages but will also offer you
simple programs to help you create your own pages.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd
Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959, or by e-mail to
Q&AMP;A(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
