<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1089 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN11-CO     05-10 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: A man's house is his castle _ moat
and all
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ A fellow I know who is moving across the country
sent his wife on ahead to find them a house.
</P>
<P>
   When I talked with him the other day, his wife had called to
tell him she had found them a house.
</P>
<P>
   Not just any house, but absolutely the very house that he's
always wanted.
</P>
<P>
   It was a brand new house in a brand new development, she said,
and, in fact, they would be among the very first families moving
in.
</P>
<P>
   This struck him as somewhat of a surprise, seeing as how the
very house he had always wanted was an older house in an
established part of town.
</P>
<P>
   That's what he told me. But he didn't tell his wife. He didn't
have the chance. She was talking too fast.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't tell his wife that. She was still talking too
fast.
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen has the kind of counter tops they've always wanted,
she told him, and in the back yard there's this concrete thing
where the water runs off, but she couldn't wait for him to see the
counter tops because they were the very kind they had always
wanted, and _
</P>
<P>
   He finally managed to get a word in.
</P>
<P>
   Back up a minute, he said. What concrete thing where what water
runs off where?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, you know, she said. No, he said, he didn't know. Tell me, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, she said, it's very nice. She was thinking it would be the
place where the children would like to play.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't say what he was thinking. What he was thinking was
drainage ditch.
</P>
<P>
   By that time she was back to the kitchen counter tops. Finally,
he managed to again interrupt her.
</P>
<P>
   Tell me, he said, exactly how the lay of the land is in the back
yard.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, I don't know, she said. Sort of higher up along the fence
and dipping down in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   It's beautiful, she was saying. It's a bog, he was thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, that's what he told me, but I don't think he told his
wife that. I don't think he had the chance. She was already back
talking about the kitchen counter tops, and this time he didn't
interrupt to ask anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Had it been me, I would have asked more about the kitchen
counter tops.
</P>
<P>
   Mainly, I would have asked how high off the floor they were.
</P>
<P>
   I think that after they buy this house, and I think they will,
they're going to want counter tops that are high off the floor,
particularly when it rains a lot.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not anything I would tell him. I would tell him how
lucky he is that his wife has found the very house he's always
wanted. I would tell him it's a moving experience.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(AT)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
