<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1091 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-TRADER11-COX     05-10 0384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADER11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trader Publishing acquisition to double circulation
 &HT;    By Matt Kempner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trader Publishing Co., partially owned by Atlanta-based Cox
Enterprises, will nearly double its weekly circulation with a $520
million acquisition of 300 free-distribution, classified
advertising magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Trader Publishing, based in Norfolk, Va., is already the largest
publisher of niche advertising publications for automobiles and
boats, according to Conrad M. Hall, Trader's president and chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Enterprises, owner of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, and
Landmark Communications each own 50 percent of Trader. Landmark,
based in Norfolk, owns the Weather Channel and other media
properties. Cox referred questions about the transaction to Trader.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of Dallas-based publisher UAP Inc. will expand
Trader's offerings into the apartment and real estate segments,
where Trader has relatively little presence, Hall said Tuesday.
UAP's top publications include Apartments for Rent and Harmon
Homes.
</P>
<P>
   Trader will buy UAP from London-based United News &AMP; Media.
United News is selling several units as part of a planned merger
with Carlton Communications that will create the United Kingdom's
largest commercial TV company.
</P>
<P>
   Trader has annual revenue of $650 million, and the new
properties will give the company additional revenue of $300
million, Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said the new titles will bolster Trader's weekly free
circulation by 4.1 million. Trader already has free circulation of
3.6 million and paid circulation of 1.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Among Trader's 355 titles are Auto Trader, Boat Trader, Auto
Mart and The Employment Guide.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the publications are distributed in convenience stores,
groceries and vending boxes in markets throughout the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The company also operates Web sites such as Traderonline.com.
</P>
<P>
   UAP has little presence on the Internet, Hall said. ``We hope to
dramatically expand their Internet offerings.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall said he expects the acquisition of UAP to close by the end
of June, but it first must be reviewed by the U.S. Justice
Department. Hall said he doesn't expect any problems.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
