<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GARDENING CHORE WITHOUT ANY BLISTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since it was such a beautiful, sunny day, I suppose I could have
been outside, shoveling compost and dirt into the big hole where
the pond used to be before we got the dog that likes to swim and
eat electric pumps.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, I was at my computer, trying to move icons that
represented a clump of Stella de Oro day lilies across a grid to an
area occupied by some icons that represented ostrich ferns. Those
needed to be deleted because _ have I mentioned this already? _ the
dog chews on ostrich ferns. With the little icons' habit of
clumping up on each other, that click-and-move exercise is harder
than it looks.
</P>
<P>
   So are most gardening chores. With blisters imminent and the
hole in the yard still half-empty, I was lucky last week to stumble
across this free Landscape Planner tool while I was shopping at
Garden.com. Within minutes of creating a plan and naming it ``Area
Formerly Known as the Pond Garden,'' I forgot all about the gaping
problem in the (real) area and instead began to daydream about the
soothing, silvery-leafed hostas I was (virtually) planting in the
wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, I preferred the icons to the actual digging, because
for me the pleasures of gardening have always been as much about
avoiding any job as doing it. I think that's why I spend so many
hours in the winter huddled with seed catalogs, planning ambitious
acres of cutting gardens at a time when the ground is too frozen to
work.
</P>
<P>
   If you share my, uh, relaxed sensibility, then the Internet is
the perfect place to shop for plants. That's because I learned,
during a recent online shopping trip, that it is not easy to find
everything you need quickly or in a single place. So you will
probably be forced to delay both gratification and physical labor.
</P>
<P>
   There are relatively few full-service plant and garden-supply
retailers with large inventories who have ventured into the online
market. Live plants, after all, are fragile. They should be
inserted into the dirt only during certain seasons. And they are
notoriously cranky about being packed and shipped.
</P>
<P>
   Not to belittle any concerns the plants might have, but as a
shopper I would like to see bigger selections. I had hoped, last
week, to save a lot of time by comparing prices online, then
placing a fast order or two. With a wait of a few days for
delivery, I would have plenty of time to dig or more likely, to
supervise the shoveling efforts of my husband, who loves the dog.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my town,'' said CarrieAnn Cutler, a researcher at Gomez
Associates who studies the online garden retail market, ``there are
five stores where I can go out and look at each plant I'm buying.
It's hard to compete with that. But this should be a segment
fulfilled by many more retailers, so I think you'll see that the
growth is just beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Cutler recommended Myseasons.com (www.myseasons.com) in addition
to Garden.com (www10.garden.com). Both offer full refunds for
unsatisfactory merchandise, and she said she liked them for their
site tools and reference materials, and for fulfilling the wide
range of plant needs of both beginners and expert gardeners. If you
order, make sure you know what you are getting. Garden.com, for
instance, ships stock in different sizes and conditions, depending
on the plant. Unlike a local nursery, which at this time of year
will sell most plants in containers, perennials you buy online may
come bare-root.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the rest of the online landscape consists of established
mail-order catalog companies that have put up tandem Web sites, as
well as thousands of smaller retailers specializing in specific
plants. While those sites tend to be idiosyncratic _ for instance,
some can only handle online orders that arrive via e-mail and
others have no plant photos _ they may offer wide selections of
their specialties.
</P>
<P>
   Two I like are Hortico Nurseries (www.hortico.com), a Canadian
grower with more than 700 varieties of roses (but watch out for the
hefty shipping costs), and Granite Hill Gardens
(www.granitehillgardens.com), headquartered in Maine. Granite Hill
has a wide selection of ornamental shrubs and responded within two
hours last week by e-mail to a pricing question about a certain
rhododendron (Ken Janeck) whose blossoms start out bright pink,
then fade.
</P>
<P>
   To test the online arms of the mail-order catalog companies,
last week I made a shopping list of about a dozen fairly common
plants widely available in my local nurseries at this time of year:
perennials like Heuchera Palace Purple and Japanese painted ferns,
rhododendrons (Purple Gem) and a sprawling old rose called
Zephirine Drouhin.
</P>
<P>
   I went shopping at three reliable companies _ Jackson and
Perkins (www.jacksonandperkins.com), White Flower Farm
(www.whiteflowerfarm.com) and Wayside Gardens
(www.waysidegardens.wte.net) _ whose plants I have bought, with
satisfaction, in the past. While each had at least one of the items
on my shopping list, none offered all or even most. In fact, many
perennials and roses were sold out. (The Wayside Gardens site was
not updated to reflect sold out merchandise. Only when I phoned a
toll-free number to double check did I learn which items were no
longer available.)
</P>
<P>
   When I phoned Renee Beaulieu, White Flower Farm's public
relations manager, to ask about the possibility of restocking, she
said that I was too late this year to get a climbing rose called
New Dawn and that I also could forget about a Begonia mixture that
I coveted. As for the rest of the 600 products in the company's
spring catalog? ``We're really at the end of our ordering season,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Beaulieu suggested instead that I order next spring's bulbs now.
The selection of 600 different bulbs from the company's fall bulb
catalog is online; orders placed before July 1 will get a 5 percent
discount.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can order them today and you won't deliver them until the
fall?'' I asked. ``There's no way I could go outside and plant them
now?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The iris we start shipping in August,'' Beaulieu said. ``Most
others, later.''
</P>
<P>
   August is a long way away. So it seemed safe to order $178 worth
of iris reticulata and yellow hyacinths and purple tulips.
</P>
<P>
   That freed me to return to the Landscape Planner at Garden.com,
where I also ordered Heuchera Palace Purple ($4.99 a plant for
bareroot specimens, compared with $11.99 for a bushy container
plant at a local nursery). Garden.com informed me the plants would
not arrive before May 15, which gives me enough time to think about
how an icon representing a big brown dog might look sitting right
in the middle of them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 1704EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000510.0132 </DOCNO>
