u p BC-POL-TICKER11-COX     05-10 2324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Politics and something about bedfellows
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York Mayor and Senate candidate Rudy Giuliani, who has been
seen frequently in public with a close female friend, Judith
Nathan, announced today he's arranging for a formal separation from
his wife of 16 years, Donna Hanover. Giuliani told reporters that
he has spoken to Hanover and his two children about the move, but
refused to give details. ''It's been a very painful road; hopefully
we'll come to an agreement that protects our children,'' Giuliani
said. ``This is something that has developed over some period of
time.'' Giuliani emphasized that he is not yet getting a divorce.
Hanover, an actress and TV personality, is rarely seen in public
</P>
<P>
   BUSH PROPOSES HEALTH CARE TAX BREAKS
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush moved further onto traditionally Democratic turf
by proposing tax incentives for the elderly to buy health care
insurance, and financial relief for people who care for a parent or
other elderly relative at home. He did this today at the Ridgecrest
Village Senior Center in Davenport, Iowa. The plans were fueled by
statistics showing that half of older women and one-third of older
men are likely to need nursing home care. Under the first proposal,
Bush would provide a full income tax deduction for long-term care
insurance payments to everyone not already on employer-subsidized
long-term care plans. Estimated cost: $5.1 billion over five years.
Bush also proposed establishing an additional tax exemption for
each elderly spouse, parent or other relative cared for in
someone's home. That exemption is currently $2,750 a year.
Estimated cost of that: $2.3 billion over five years.
</P>
<P>
   BUT W., WE HARDLY KNOW YOU
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush urged newspaper execs today to focus on issues of
substance rather than political sniping. Speaking from Iowa via
satellite to the Newspaper Association of America convention in New
York, Bush was pressed by New York Times publisher Arthur Ochs
Sulzberger Jr. about his willingness to meet with newspapers'
editorial boards. Bush has complained to his traveling press corps
that the Times' opinion pages are too liberal for his taste.
Sulzberger said he had informally surveyed some of his colleagues
at the convention _ both liberals and conservatives _ and none had
met Bush personally. ``For those of us who have responsibility for
the editorials that run in our papers and for helping to shape that
point of view up to and including endorsements, we feel a little
bit of loss not being able to actually sit down with you, look you
in the eye and have a bit of a discussion and dialogue,'' the
publisher said.
</P>
<P>
   COACH OSBORNE WINS A BIG ONE
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska Attorney General Don Stenberg took the first step
toward reclaiming Sen. Bob Kerrey's seat for the Republicans,
easily defeating Secretary of State Scott Moore and two other
candidates in the GOP primary. Stenberg will take on popular former
Gov. Ben Nelson, who easily beat a homeless man who was his only
opponent in the Democratic primary. And retired Nebraska Cornhusker
football coach Tom Osborne routed his two opponents in a GOP
contest for the House and will face Democrat Rollie Reynolds, a
real estate investor, in November. In West Virginia, Gov. Cecil
Underwood, who was elected to his first term as governor in 1956
and to his second term in 1996, easily won the GOP nomination for a
third term. At 77, Underwood is the nation's oldest governor. He is
also the only Republican in a statewide office in West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH WITH EDGE IN ELECTORAL COLLEGE
</P>
<P>
   Six various state polls were released today on big Electoral
College states with the most potential impact in the November
general election. Al Gore led 50-36 percent in California and 56-36
percent in New York, giving him firm leads in the two largest
states with a total of 87 electoral votes. George W. Bush led 70-23
percent in his home state of Texas and 47-40 percent in Florida,
where his brother Jeb is governor _ two states with a total 57
electoral votes. Gore and Bush were statistically tied in
Pennsylvania and Illinois _ two states with 45 electoral votes.
Overall, Bush leads or has an edge in 17 states with 183 electoral
votes, while Gore is ahead in 10 states with 146 electoral votes,
according to an analysis of state polls out this year. Electoral
votes needed to win: 270.
</P>
<P>
   GOOD THING HE GOT HIMSELF SCREENED
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Giuliani, New York Newsday reports, has slashed funds for
prostate cancer screening in his current New York City budget plan.
Giuliani, who was diagnosed with the disease himself a couple weeks
ago, would eliminate a $750,000 program to provide free testing to
uninsured New Yorkers. Other potential cuts in public health
include a $2.1 million reduction for health programs for poor
children and a $1 million cut for family planning services in poor
communities suffering from high infant mortality rates.
</P>
<P>
   THEORETICALLY, YES _ POLITICALLY, EH?
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore, who's been something of a stealth supporter of the
proposed trade deal with China, has finally flown a few sorties
visible on everyone's radar screen. With a tough House vote on the
deal two weeks away, Gore, at the White House with the current
president and two ex's _ Jimmy Carter and Jerry Ford _ gave his
most robust defense yet of the deal to give China normal trading
status on a permanent basis, despite the fierce opposition of
unions, environmentalists and human rights activists: ``It is right
for American jobs. It is right for the cause of reform in China,
and I believe it will move us closer to the strong and stable world
community that we all seek to create.'' Even so, questions remained
about whether his heart's in the effort, and whether a Gore
administration would do much to expand free trade. ``I don't think
he's motivated on this,'' says Gary Hufbauer of the Institute for
International Economics, who backs lowered trade barriers.
</P>
<P>
   COME HULL AND HIGH WATER
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret that Arizona Gov. Jane Hull's endorsement of a
fellow governor, George W. Bush, over her fellow Arizonan, John
McCain, left bad feelings. Last month, Hull agreed to give up the
governor's prerogative of leading the state's delegation to the
Republican convention. McCain easily won the primary and thus the
right to control the state's 30-member convention delegation. Now,
the New York Times reports that McCain wants his wife, Cindy, to
lead the delegation instead, something that rankles Hull
supporters. The issue is to be decided at the state party
convention on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   McCAIN JOCKEYING FOR 2004 POSITION
</P>
<P>
   John McCain positioned himself for a possible presidential bid
in 2004 with his belated endorsement of George W. Bush. Senior
McCain campaign aides say that they expect the three-term senator
from Arizona to seek the White House four years from now if Bush
loses to Al Gore in November. The defeated Republican challenger
embraced Bush just warmly enough at their summit in Pittsburgh to
escape blame if the Texas governor goes down. But McCain signaled
that his hard-hitting populist insurgency is merely sidelined _ and
not scuttled _ by his defeat at the hands of Bush's privately
funded $70 million juggernaut in the GOP primaries.
</P>
<P>
   NO JOCKEYING AT ALL WITH BRADLEY
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore still has not met with Bill Bradley, who has not stumped
or raised funds for Gore since grudgingly agreeing to help him two
months ago. The ex-New Jersey senator has refused to relinquish his
nearly 500 delegates and has refrained from urging the 3 million
Americans who voted for him to switch their allegiance to the vice
president. There has been no public purging of the bad blood
Bradley has for Gore, whom he said cannot be trusted with the
presidency. Said Mike Murphy, chief media strategist for John
McCain, to the Washington Times: ``Bradley still has enough
national stature to create huge and horrific problems for Gore.
Bradley's important and is being ignored by Gore. And if Bradley
wanted to, he could make a lot of trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   BAYH-BAYH AND NIGHTY-NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton says he hopes someday to cast a presidential
vote for Sen. Evan Bayh, an Indiana Democrat seen as a possible
running mate for Al Gore. Clinton heaped much praise on Bayh at a
fund-raising event in Maryland for Indiana Rep. Baron Hill. Bayh
attended the fund-raiser, but left before Clinton's speech so he
could return home to tuck his children into bed. ``He went home,
and he should have,'' said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   TEXANS MOVING IN
</P>
<P>
   Another ally of George W. Bush has joined the Republican
National Committee. Ray Hunt of Dallas, chairman and CEO of Hunt
Oil Co., has been named finance chairman of the RNC's Victory 2000
Committee. Hunt is a longtime supporter and close friend of Bush.
The head of the committee is another Texas Republican, Fred Meyer,
a former state party chairman. Having sewn up the GOP presidential
nomination, Bush has been shifting allies to the RNC. Other Bush
backers now there include his campaign political director, Maria
Cino, a deputy for political and congressional relations; and
Jeanne Johnson Phillips, one of Bush's original Texas fund-raisers,
now deputy chairman for operations.
</P>
<P>
   NO WHINING, JUST MOAN-ING
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party's new interim chairman says he wants to hold
onto the job despite its obvious drawbacks. The party ``sort of
runs the chairman instead of the other way around,'' said Gerry
Moan. ``It's not easy.'' Moan, vice chairman since July, became
chairman of the fractious organization when Pat Choate resigned
last week, citing family illness. Party officials, as well as a
presidential nominee, are to be elected at the Reform convention
Aug. 10-13 in Long Beach, Calif. Moan, 52, is a Long Island, N.Y.,
native who moved to Tucson, Ariz., in 1998. He is a materials
manager for Maxi Switch Inc., a manufacturer of computer circuit
boards.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET FILTER IN PRESIDENTIAL POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   The rise of the Internet and nonstop news cycles has repaved the
road to the White House. But despite the big changes brought on by
online access to campaigns, a primaries post-mortem by Eric Hauser
and Howard Opinsky, press secretaries for Bill Bradley and John
McCain respectively, concluded that television still remains the
best way to connect with the voters. Money may be raised over the
Internet, but it's spent on TV advertising. The workshop itself was
an Internet event, available via a live interactive video stream on
CNN's allpolitics.com Web site. It was sponsored by the Joan
Shorenstein Center on the Press, Politics and Public Policy at
Harvard, in collaboration with CNN.
</P>
<P>
   CATSKILLS SCHTICK, BUT THE YIDDISH ACCENT?
</P>
<P>
   Southern Baptist Al Gore tried out a Borscht Belt routine before
about 450 members of the Anti-Defamation League in Washington. He
noted his presidential campaign is headquartered in Nashville and
dished up what he called the latest top ``Jewish
Country-and-Western'' tunes to come out of Music City . No. 4: ``I
was one of the chosen people until she chose somebody else.'' No.
3: ``The second time she said `Shalom' I knew she meant goodbye.''
No. 2: ``I've got my foot on the glass, now where are you?'' And
No. 1 (drum roll, please): ``Mommas don't let your ungrateful sons
grow up to be cowboys when they could very easily just have taken
over the family business that my own grandfather broke his back to
start and my father sweated over for years, which apparently
doesn't mean anything now that you're turning your back on such a
gift.'' The audience roared with laughter and applauded.
</P>
<P>
   KENNEDY CHALLENGER SHORT OF SIGNATURES
</P>
<P>
   Despite predictions that Republicans might not have a Senate
nominee this year in Massachusetts, GOP hopeful Jack E. Robinson
said today he has collected enough signatures to challenge Sen.
Edward Kennedy in November. Robinson said he submitted 13,000
signatures to local town clerks before the 5 p.m. Tuesday deadline.
U.S. Senate candidates need 10,000 certified signatures to get on
the ballot. Of those 13,000, only 5,800 have been certified so far,
according to Secretary of State William Galvin, and the remainder
are subject to challenge for a variety of reasons. Robinson, 39, is
an African-American former Eastern Airlines executive now running a
cell phone business. If he fails to get on the ballot, it will mark
the first time since 1916, the year United States senators began
being popularly elected, that a Massachusetts Democratic Senate
candidate will run without Republican opposition.
</P>
<P>
   YOU SCRATCH MY BACK . . .
</P>
<P>
   A coming fund-raiser in Georgia is stoking speculation about
political races four years or so down the road. On Monday, Jeanne
Shaheen, the Democratic governor of New Hampshire, will be the
beneficiary of an event in Atlanta _ a bit south of Concord _ that
planners hope will raise at least $25,000 for her re-election. And
one of the hosts, as well as one of the contributors, will be
Georgia Gov. Roy Barnes, a first-term Democrat who is beginning to
win national attention for his policies on improving schools and
limiting sprawl. The New York Times quoted Barnes chief of staff
Robert Kahn as saying his boss is simply supporting a fellow
Democratic governor, not pocketing a chit to be cashed for New
Hampshire's first-in-the-nation primary in 2004 or 2008. The event
for Shaheen is being organized by Michael Coles, a prominent party
fund-raiser and Barnes ally who met Shaheen while working for Vice
Al Gore in New Hampshire last winter.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda
</P>
