<SLUG> BC-EVERYDAY-ETHICS-COLUMN-ADV14-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV14 
 EVERYDAY ETHICS 
 FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 14, AND THEREAFTER.
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by EVERYDAY ETHICS clients. Nonsubscribers can
use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, see end of text. 
 By RANDY COHEN 
 c.2000 Randy Cohen 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IF IT LOOKS LIKE RAPE ...
</P>
<P>
   Q. In New Orleans for Mardi Gras and drinking heavily, my
friends and I got separated. When I returned to our hotel, I found
my college roommate in bed with a girl from our school. Days later,
I learned he'd had sex with her while she was in a
drug-and-alcohol-induced stupor. In my view, he is a rapist, but I
don't know how to react, given my friendship with him and my
sympathies for her.
</P>
<P>
   _ Anonymous, Virginia
</P>
<P>
   A. This does sound like date rape, and the first thing you
should consider are the wishes of the victim. How is she
responding? Does she want to report this to the police? What help
would she like from you? Her interests are paramount.
</P>
<P>
   Your attitude toward the rapist should be shaped by his attitude
toward his crime. If he is remorseful and has asked his victim's
forgiveness and looked for a way to make amends and sought
counseling, then you can continue your friendship. Remember, people
make bad _ even dreadful _ choices. It is how they respond to their
errors that is key. However, if he brushes off the entire matter,
then you should have no more to do with him.
</P>
<P>
   After all, how could you? Will you introduce him to your other
female friends? Will you warn them to avoid him? It is difficult to
see how you could ever again think of him in an amicable and
unguarded way.
</P>
<P>
   And you should say all this to him. Tell him that you value his
friendship, but that unless he takes this seriously and realizes
that he has a problem with drinking, or alcohol, or women, then you
can no longer be his friend.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Back in high school, a girlfriend and I debated the abortion
issue in Sunday school. I favored legal abortion; she did not, even
to save the mother's life, because if a woman died it was God's
will. A few years later, she sent me a letter detailing her own
abortion. Now, decades later, she is a professor at a college of
our denomination. Should I out her?
</P>
<P>
   _ Anonymous, Illinois
</P>
<P>
   A. I'd chalk up her conversion to necessity; life has a way of
altering our adolescent ideas. If I were held to everything I
advocated in high school, I'd still be listening to the Dave Clark
Five and sporting an unattractive haircut _ not a pretty picture.
</P>
<P>
   If her work at the college does not include taking an
anti-abortion stand, then her personal beliefs on this issue are
not relevant, and you should respect her privacy: that is, no
outing. If, however, she aggressively takes a public anti-abortion
stand, then her hypocrisy is entirely to the point, and you can
include it in the debate. But before you take so strong a step,
have a conversation with your old friend. It can't hurt to know
more about the causes of her action and the consequences of yours.
</P>
<P>
   Q. While working for a major studio, some co-workers and I were
mistakenly issued extra paychecks. I suggested that we alert the
payroll department, but my friends disagreed. Since the show was
almost over, payroll would not have time to uncover the mistake.
Plus, we had worked extra hours for a particularly parsimonious
studio. I put my check away uncashed but never called payroll
because that would be snitching on my friends. Was my response
appropriate?
</P>
<P>
   _ Anonymous, Los Angeles
</P>
<P>
   Q. Some people think that the American film industry is stale
and unimaginative, but I'm encouraged by the boundless ingenuity of
your colleagues when it comes to justifying whatever happens to be
in their interest. Of course you can't keep the money. And while
you needn't explicitly inform on your friends, you must tell the
payroll office about the mistake with your check.
</P>
<P>
   Do you have ethical questions that you need answered? Send them
to ethicist(at)nytimes.com, or Everyday Ethics, New York Times
Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St., 14th floor, New York, N.Y. 10168.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
