<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1101 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-INDUSTRIAL-MATERIALS-     05-10 1340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDUSTRIAL-MATERIALS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVASION OF THE DESIGN LAB MUTANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: See also INDUSTRIAL-GELS) By STEPHEN P. WILLIAMS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was a time, in the distant '80s, when Corian
was such an exotic material it had to be installed by licensed
technicians. Now it's just another tired surface at Home Depot, and
everyone is lusting for raw concrete countertops that resemble
picnic tables at a state penitentiary.
</P>
<P>
   New materials for the home are being introduced daily, some with
the half-lives of fashion accessories. Recently, a fabric coated
with Philippine chicken feathers came on the market, in the form of
lampshades. Surely some enterprising design aficionado already has
fantasies about feathering his breakfast nook. Can infamy, and
Kmart, be far behind?
</P>
<P>
   Homeowners of America, the future is here. Picture a house clad
with shiny steel shingles. Imagine traversing a floor made of glass
tiles suspended several inches in the air on thin metal posts.
Would you feel safe sleeping next to walls made of loose rock held
in place by supersize garden fencing? How would the neighbors react
to a house built from concrete pig-sty partitions?
</P>
<P>
   All these materials and more are available from a growing number
of designers who are bypassing traditional materials _ wood,
plaster and marble _ for less costly industrial supplies. Driven by
budget, or simply eager to explore the sculptural possibilities and
light transmission of unconventional fabrics and resins, designers
read chemistry journals, NASA Web sites and labels in hardware
stores. They advocate chemical filters as wallpaper and medical gel
packs as seat cushions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're undergoing a design revolution in the use of materials
these days,'' said Paola Antonelli, an associate curator in the
department of architecture and design at the Museum of Modern Art.
She foresaw this change in her groundbreaking 1995 show at the
Modern called ``Mutant Materials,'' which credited scientists with
inventing the new materials that architects and designers use in
unorthodox ways.
</P>
<P>
   Material Connexion is the place to find these new materials in
Manhattan. Anyone with $500 dollars for four hours of assisted
research is welcome to explore this for-profit private archive at 4
Columbus Circle. The architecture team Diller &AMP; Scofidio thumbed
through the thousands of samples on file while researching
materials for their innovative redesign of the Brasserie restaurant
on East 53rd Street. The cash-poor can view design riches in the
free lobby exhibits.
</P>
<P>
   While Material Connexion has its share of natural materials like
coconut fabric and bamboo paneling, most of the samples are plastic
or metal. While design-minded inhabitants of the late 20th century
considered fake materials declasse, today's strivers say materials
can't be fake enough. Brazenly artificial resins, chemical foams
and bizarre three-dimensional fabrics are all the rage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the changes we're seeing now will be as radical as what
happened in the '60s,'' said George Beylerian, who founded Material
Connexion four years ago. ``Plexiglass was new. Urethanes.
Beautiful lacquers and plastics. Materials then made designers
jump. I give the equation M equals D: materials drive design.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so. But it's also true that materials can drive architects
and designers crazy. The very fact of its newness means that a
material has to be tested before it is used, to be sure it is
strong enough and doesn't have some undesirable quality like toxic
vapors. Building codes offer some protection against faulty
applications. Some decisions are obvious.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the Swiss architects Jacques Herzog and Pierre de
Meuron were not taking engineering risks when they designed walls
made of loose rock held in check by wire mesh cages at the Dominus
Estate Winery in the Napa Valley. They knew at the mesh, called
gabion, had been used to hold back rocky hillsides all over the
Alps.
</P>
<P>
   But often architects must don white coats and investigate. This
willingness to explore is essential to the work of Jeff Parsons and
Manuel Fernandez-Casteleiro of Manhattan, who used a transparent
mesh divider in their White Street office made from tennis court
fence windscreens, to add the appearance of structure without a
wall. The architects' inventive nature prompted a Park Avenue
couple to let them build an elevated glass floor in their
apartment's art gallery/guest room. Parsons and
Fernandez-Casteleiro designed the floor to reflect diffused light
from the cloth-covered windows back up onto their paintings. In the
process they gave the apartment some thrills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overnight guests said the reflections from the glass were so
disorienting they feared having to make their way to the
bathroom,'' said a beaming Fernandez-Casteleiro.
</P>
<P>
   He can beam because he knows there is no real danger. The
architects designed the steel pegs and glass tiles themselves,
laboriously poring over computer simulations and a mock-up on their
office floor to make sure the client would not be hearing the sound
of breaking glass. The only person who ended up suffering was the
apartment's housekeeper: The gap between the glass and the subfloor
makes a perfect lint trap. But the only way to get a vacuum in
there is to lift up the floor tiles one by one with a suction cup.
Is this in anyone's job description?
</P>
<P>
   The apartment was recently sold, and one suspects the new owners
will just rip everything out and start over, perhaps with something
practical like a parquet floor. But all is not lost. The couple
asked the designers to make over their next town house.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're thinking about mutating the glass floors to the walls as
a way of dematerializing the interior of the town house,''
Fernandez-Casteleiro said. Housekeepers, pray for release to the
god of Windex.
</P>
<P>
   But mutating is what these guys do best. They encased the bar at
the East Village restaurant Coup in the same rubber used as shock
absorbers in bridge construction. The finished bar has the look of
unpolished black Corian and the feel of a bicycle grip. Equally
surprising is that the deep mahogany colored ``wood'' panels in
Coup are made from phenolic resin, a plastic normally used to
insulate high-voltage switches.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Diller and Richard Scofidio, who won the James Beard
award for restaurant design on Monday for the Brasserie, in the
windowless basement of the Seagram Building, also specialize in
mutating materials. Wanting to suggest transparency at the
entrance, they called on Mary Bright, who specializes in
architectural curtains _ not the velvet kind.
</P>
<P>
   Bright suggested an entry curtain that appeared to billow even
though it was immobile, and subjected mesh and plastic to what she
calls a stretch test, meaning she hung them in her studio for a few
days to see if they changed shape. The resulting ``wall'' does not
seem too far removed from a shower curtain, except for one
curiously compelling detail. Faced with city ordinances, Bright
installed shiny zippers that let a small panel of mesh curtain fall
away, revealing an exit sign that glows mysteriously.
</P>
<P>
   Another ethereal glow emanates from the resin tables Diller and
Scofidio designed for the restaurant. ``Elizabeth gave us pretty
detailed drawings, with the metal understructure visible from above
the tabletop,'' said Karen Atta, of Atta Inc, the Manhattan
workshop that made the tables. ``It was a real challenge to cast
the understructure directly into the resin, which we'd never done
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Resin, which is a type of cast plastic, tends to expand and
contract at a faster rate than metal, and on Atta's first seven or
eight attempts the resin cracked right off the metal as it cooled.
Finally she devised a way to slow the cooling process and solve the
problem. Atta recently began selling similar tables to the public
at prices ranging from $700 to $3,000 _ example of how new
materials can be more expensive than the old-fashioned ones.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Dan Rockhill, an architect, and his associate, David Sain, take
a similarly labor-intensive approach to the houses they build
themselves around Lawrence, Kan., using hand-cut steel shingles
unpainted concrete panels.
</P>
<P>
   Rockhill continues his radical experiments with his students at
the University of Kansas who have banded together under the moniker
Studio 804. They chose an unusual marine-grade plywood to clad a
home built for a low income family in Lawrence. The plywood is made
from okoume, a water-resistant wood from Gabon _ available through
North American Plywood in Santa Fe Springs, Calif. It is a lustrous
brown, is reasonably priced for good-looking wood siding at 89
cents a square foot, and needs a only a coat of varnish for
protection.
</P>
<P>
   Future generations of au courant materials will not only have to
look good and be strong, they will need many of the senses that
humans have, said Atonelli at Modern. Foams now ``remember'' shapes
and there are fabrics that release antibacterial substances.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology Media
Laboratory envision superhuman abilities for future materials. They
predict that the dividing line will blur between objects in the
home and the computers that will run them. For these houses, far
``smarter'' than those being created today, materials had also
better be on their toes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your shoes should be retrieving the day's personalized news
from the carpet before you even have time to take off your coat,''
says one Media Lab manifesto. If these explorers have their way,
weird plastics and chicken feather fabrics will soon seem as quaint
as bricks and mortar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
