<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1144 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ONDAATJE-BOOK-REVIEW-     05-10 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONDAATJE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANIL'S GHOST': UNEARTHING THE TRAGEDIES OF CIVIL WAR IN SRI
LANKA 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Publication notes appear at end of review.)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the Sri Lankan setting for Michael Ondaatje's delicately
fragmented new novel, the figure known as the artificer assumes
special importance. This is the artisan deemed worthy to paint eyes
on a statue of the Buddha, a task that may be done only at 5 a.m.
(the hour of the Buddha's enlightenment) with the help of a mirror,
so as not to look straight into the deity's gaze.
</P>
<P>
   It is by this indirect means that ``the artificer brings to
light sight and truth and presence,'' one of the book's many
haunted characters observes. The author, in contemplating the
dreadful toll that the civil war beginning in the mid-1980s has
taken on his native land, aspires to the same role.
</P>
<P>
   As he did in ``The English Patient,'' Ondaatje is able to
commingle anguish and seductiveness in fierce, unexpected ways.
``Then he turned on a slim hose and let it hover over each bone,''
he writes alluringly, ``air nestling into the evidence of the
trauma as if he were blowing cool breath from a pursed mouth onto a
child's burn.''
</P>
<P>
   That image, for all its sensual loveliness, happens to describe
a forensic examination of the skeleton of a headless torture
victim. Of the warfare among government, antigovernment insurgents
and separatist guerrilla forces that provides the book's implicit
backdrop, he writes: ``And we were caught in the middle. It was
like being in a room with three suitors, all of whom had blood on
their hands.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anil's Ghost,'' like the 33-year-old heroine of its title,
steps into this catastrophe at a point when much of its damage has
already been done. Born in Sri Lanka but having spent much of her
life in England and America, Anil returns to her childhood home
under the auspices of a Geneva-based human rights organization. A
forensic anthropologist, she is part of a team investigating
possible war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anil had read documents and news reports, full of tragedy, and
she had now lived abroad long enough to interpret Sri Lanka with a
long-distance gaze,'' Ondaatje writes. ``But here it was a more
complicated world morally. The streets were still streets, the
citizens remained citizens. They shopped, changed jobs, laughed.
Yet the darkest Greek tragedies were innocent compared with what
was happening here.''
</P>
<P>
   Anil finds herself paired for the investigation with a
government-selected archaeologist named Sarath, a remote man 16
years her senior. Together Anil and Sarath find four skeletons whom
they nickname Tinker, Tailor, Soldier and Sailor, the last a source
of obsessive fascination. Anil becomes convinced that pinpointing
Sailor's identity and the circumstances of his death will provide
the damning evidence she and Sarath are seeking. But only in this
detective-story premise, and in the curiously theatrical gesture
that ends the book, does ``Anil's Ghost'' adhere to any
conventional storytelling patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``The English Patient'' (despite the exquisite fluency of
Anthony Minghella's screen adaptation) ``Anil's Ghost'' is a novel
more in name than in essence. The author of 11 books of poetry,
Ondaatje brings an oblique poetic sensibility to unraveling the
mysteries at work here. Layers peel away from both Anil and Sarath,
with a past full of ghosts for each of them and with assorted
vignettes and memories scattered across the book's fertile
landscape. The path through this terrain is not a clear or simple
one.
</P>
<P>
   The book drifts in flashback, for instance, from Guatemala to
the Miami bedroom where Anil has a tryst with her married lover,
Cullis, who is as much on her mind as Sailor the skeleton. She
speaks about the Spanish names for bones; he says he has written
something about Norwegian snakes. While Cullis sleeps, in the kind
of effortlessly bewitching gesture Ondaatje creates so gracefully,
she photographs him, then buries the film inside his suitcase as a
souvenir.
</P>
<P>
   But as to how such moments _ or those in which Anil writes a
letter to John Boorman about his film ``Point Blank'' or ponders
lyrics to a song set in New York state by the McGarrigle sisters _
connect with the book's essential business in Sri Lanka, that
remains indistinct. Frustratingly so, since the scattered aspects
of this voyage of discovery are separately so powerful.
</P>
<P>
   The book's real strengths lie in its profound sense of outrage,
the shimmering intensity of its descriptive language and the
mysterious beauty of its geography, with so many discrete passages
that present the artificer in Ondaatje so well. The atlas itself,
artfully used _ with places named Ambalangoda and Andigama,
Ginigalpelessa and Boralesgamuwa _ enhances the sense of the
gorgeously exotic throughout.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing is to be able to live in a place or a
situation where you must use your sixth sense all the time,'' says
a surgeon in the story, describing what is most inviting about this
morally outraged, viscerally vivid book.
</P>
<P>
   Like the elderly blind sage Palipana, Sarath's mentor, who has
had the gift of reading between the lines of texts to glimpse
hidden meanings, Ondaatje does not deal comfortably with the
obvious. But his sixth sense _ his poet's sense _ is akin to that
of Ananda, the book's character who is ultimately assigned the job
of imagining Sailor's missing features. What Ananda recreates is
not the literal physiognomy of Sailor. He conjures a different
face, one that means much more.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ANIL'S GHOST'
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Ondaatje
</P>
<P>
   311 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 1743EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000510.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1145 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-CISCO-EXPAND-BOS &LR;      05-10 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISCO-EXPAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CISCO TO OPEN ITS LARGEST FACTORY, IN NEW HAMPSHIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the latest sign that the Internet-driven new economy is
breathing life back to New England's old manufacturing economy,
Cisco Systems Inc. will open its largest factory in a building that
once cranked out computers for Digital Equipment Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of workstations and servers, the 674,000-square-foot
plant in Salem, N.H., will soon be making optical networking
equipment, the latest technology for ferrying vasts amounts of
Internet traffic over fiber-optic lines.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco is buying the plant for more than $40 million. At full
capacity, it is expected to have 2,500 workers, about 25 percent
more than it had at its peak when Digital owned it, according to
Carl Redfield, Cisco's senior vice president for manufacturing, who
had visited the plant several times when he was an executive at
Digital.
</P>
<P>
   Though Cisco is based in San Jose, Calif., the network equipment
maker has been making rapid inroads into New England. Just last
week, the company said it would buy ArrowPoint Communications in
Acton for $5.7 billion in stock. The purchase is Cisco's eleventh
acquisition in New England, and its second largest worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   But the announcement was marred by reports that the US
Securities Exchange Commission is looking into the possibility of
insider trading in the ArrowPoint deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The SEC has made a preliminary inquiry into the situation,''
Mojgan Khalili, a Cisco spokeswoman, confirmed, saying the probe is
routine. ``Cisco is cooperating fully as expected,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cisco's recent expansions into New England continues to
be regarded as a positive development, with the company poised to
hire thousands of local workers for its plant.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco's decision to locate its sixth and largest manufacturing
plant in Salem reinforces the region as the hub of the rapidly
growing optical networking industry, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half of North America's capabilities for producing optical
networking equipment is within an hour's drive of each other'' in
New England, Redfield said. ``That was part of the reason why we
decided to establish a plant here.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisco also needed a plant that could be up and running quickly
so Cisco could keep up with a flood of customer orders, and the
Salem site met that requirement, said Redfield. Otherwise, Cisco
risks losing customers to rivals Lucent Technologies Inc. and
Nortel Networks Inc., and a crop of New England-based upstarts such
as Sycamore Networks Inc. in Chelmsford, Mass. and Appian
Communications in Boxborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The optical networking industry has been booming and is expected
to grow from sales of $6.6 billion in 1999 to $23 billion in 2003,
according to estimates by RHK, a market research firm in South San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Optical networks use light to transmit vast amounts of
information over glass fibers that resemble thin fishing lines.
Telecommunications companies around the world such as AT&AMP;T and Bell
Atlantic have latched on to optical networks as the latest
technology for ferrying video and voice traffic over the Internet.
And companies such as Cisco are scrambling to meet the exploding
demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cisco is just beginning to address the optical environment,''
said Chris Nicoll, a director at Current Analysis, a market
research firm in Sterling, Va. ``They've made a number of
acquisitions in this space. But the company now needs to get it all
together into a cohesive solution.''
</P>
<P>
   The Salem factory is expected to become Cisco's hub for its
optical networking business. But the decision to open its own plant
is unusual because the company prefers to outsource most of its
manufacturing to contractors in a system the company calls
``virtual manufacturing.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisco owns just five factories worldwide, including two in
Silicon Valley, one in South Carolina and two in Italy and France
that came from Cisco's February acquisition of Pirelli Optical
Systems. Cisco decided to open its own plant because very few
outside contractors exist for this relatively new product.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd love to farm this out, but there's no one to farm it out
to today,'' said Redfield. ``This is a case where we will have to
build the expertise in-house and then transfer that capability to
our manufacturing partners.''
</P>
<P>
   The Salem plant has sat idle since Digital's new owner, Compaq
Computer Corp., sold the property for $29 million earlier this year
to Boston-area real estate investors Donald Levine and Lewis
Heafitz. Cisco's deal to purchase the plant and the surrounding 110
acres of land is expected to close in June. The company said it
will spend up to $50 million to improve the property.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco is already hiring technicians and engineers to work in the
plant so it can start shipping orders by the end of the year,
Redfield said.
</P>
<P>
   After Cisco's recent flurry of acquisitions, New England has
become Cisco's largest presence outside of California in square
footage. The company recently purchased 580 acres of land in
Boxborough, Littleton and Harvard, and is building about 1.8
million square feet of office space on the property. With
ArrowPoint, Cisco now employs 2,200 workers in New England, about 8
percent of its total work force.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco's stock fell $3.25 a share to $59.50 Wednesday after
Cisco's chairman, John Chambers, said the company was having
trouble getting enough parts to meet demand and the shortage could
hurt the company's future financial performance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
