<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000510.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1162 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-INNOVATION-ECONSCENE-     05-10 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INNOVATION-ECONSCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC SCENE: GOVERNMENT SPENDING ON INNOVATION NEEDED IN NEW
ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: In the excerpt from Adam Smith, there are some 18th-century
spellings.) 
 By JEFF MADRICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Could we be hearing right? The Treasury Secretary, Lawrence
Summers, made a speech in San Francisco on Wednesday that not only
talked some economic sense but whose first priority was not to
assuage the financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Summers again pushed the line that open markets around the
world were essential to future growth. But he also broached a more
sensitive subject: maybe some of those surplus Treasury balances
should be used to buttress the so-called ``new economy'' rather
than to reduce taxes or shore up Social Security. This is one of
the most important economic speeches of the Clinton administration.
Better late than never.
</P>
<P>
   Behind Summers' point is that the new economy requires spending
on education and research because it is based not on big factories
and distribution systems but on ideas and innovation. Some of those
government surpluses should be spent on just these matters, rather
than worrying about reducing interest rates by cutting government
borrowing even more. He is essentially right, in my view. Maybe
more right than he realizes.
</P>
<P>
   This economy is not any more ``new'' than the economic
transformations of the 1920s, 1950s and 1960s were in their day
(and surely no more revolutionary than around the last turn of the
century.) In fact, for all the raves from Washington and Wall
Street, economic growth even in the late 1990s was not equal to the
fastest growth rates of those eras.
</P>
<P>
   But beginning in the mid-1990s, there was an unmistakable rise
in the rate of economic growth that has just about confirmed that a
transformation similar to those that occurred at past turning
points is now underway. In my view, this transformation is less
potent than those in the past, but potent it will be.
</P>
<P>
   To maximize its potential, however, will require more effort
than Americans generally acknowledge. Every such economic
transformation in the past was accompanied by enormous increases in
spending on education, transportation, communications, and,
ultimately, technological research. Much of this was undertaken or
subsidized by the government.
</P>
<P>
   Take education. In the 1800s, Americans developed a free
mandatory primary school system. In the early 1900s, high school
education spread rapidly. And after World War II, aided by the GI
Bill and the expansion of public universities, Americans went to
college in droves.
</P>
<P>
   Or take transportation. In the 1800s, first canals, then
railroads were built. In the early 1900s roads followed. And in the
1950s and '60s, Washington _ under the guise of national defense _
paid to build the interstate highway system.
</P>
<P>
   In communications, the telegraph first knitted together the
nation _ and began the connection to the global economy. Then came
the telephone, followed by television. Now, it's the Internet. And
just as the telegraph reduced inefficient transportation
requirements _ after all, people didn't have to get on a horse to
deliver a message anymore _ the Internet may reduce transportation
needs as well by, among other things, encouraging more shopping
from home.
</P>
<P>
   But every economic transformation has unique characteristics as
well. Enter Summers. He says that the new economy requires more
innovation. In fact, all such economic transformations were based
principally on new ideas and exciting innovation, as Joseph
Schumpeter, the economic exponent of creative destruction, so
clearly pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   I think Summers is right that the demand for innovation has
increased dramatically. This didn't start only a few years ago,
however. The innovation economy began in the mid-1970s when
Japanese manufacturers, led by Toyota and Honda, learned how to
make varied and high-quality cars far more productively than their
Detroit counterparts. Suddenly, there were many more types of cars
on the road at affordable prices. Standardized markets were
replaced by fragmented ones, and the rate of introduction of new
products rose dramatically, not only for manufactured good, such as
packaged food and appliances, but for services, such as airline
trips, cable television and financial products such as mutual
funds. None of this could have happened without the computer.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, new products, marketing ideas, financial strategies,
innovative salesmanship and constant change became the keys to
competitive success. A new product rushes in, as Summers says,
captures the market and is quickly displaced by a still newer one.
This is far from a new model, but the pace is faster.
</P>
<P>
   The implication is that an educated and sophisticated work force
and on-going aggressive investment in technological research are
now more important than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   How does American society make the most of this? As in the past,
it will require government funds. Not for everything, especially in
the modern age, which has so many more capable people and developed
private institutions than in the past. But it was New York state
that first built the canals; the federal government that subsidized
the railroads and paved the highways; local government that built
the nation's schools; land-grant universities and the military that
spawned a lot of our technology.
</P>
<P>
   Some will demur. Indeed, private industry built the
communications infrastructure in the 20th century and is now
building the Internet. But the Pentagon, as is apparently now known
by every school child, developed the Internet in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   And there is strong economic theory to support a role for
government. Let me quote from Adam Smith, no modern liberal:
</P>
<P>
   ``The third and last duty of the sovereign or commonwealth is
that of erecting and maintaining those publick institutions and
those publick works, which, though they may be in the highest
degree advantageous to a great society, are, however, of such a
nature, that the profit could never repay the expence to any
individual or small number of individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Most economists now recognize that some investments of crucial
benefit to society as a whole will not be made by business because
any single company, or even industry, will not reap all the
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The remarkably prescient Adam Smith had it right 225 years ago.
By renewing our faith in public investment, Summers is following in
his footsteps. Given what we have read about Summers' ambitions,
nothing would please him more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
