<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, May 11, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms will be active early Thursday in
Illinois and Indiana as the remnants of a thunderstorm complex
drift to the southeast. Meanwhile, the area of low pressure that
triggered this system Wednesday night will cause chilly rain in the
northern Plains Thursday. Farther west, snow showers will be found
in the mountains of Wyoming and Montana as colder air sweeps
southward.
</P>
<P>
   The Northeast will turn cooler Thursday in the wake of a cold
front. Showers and clouds will linger in northern New England,
although places farther west will see sunshine by the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure moving over the Southeast will provide sunny skies
and unseasonably high temperatures. The deserts of the Southwest
will remain very hot. Valley showers and mountain snow will
continue to plague the Pacific Northwest as moist breezes surge
inland.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: MIDNIGHT SUN
</P>
<P>
   Though much of the East has had unusual warmth in early May, the
surest sign of approaching summer is at frosty Barrow, Alaska. The
sun rose at 2:50 a.m. Wednesday and will remain above the horizon
continuously until Aug. 2. At Barrow, the northernmost weather
station in the United States, the summer sun will be obscured by
clouds nearly 80 percent of the time. The nearby Arctic Ocean
typically remains covered with ice until late July, keeping the
average air temperature at 33 degrees during the reign of the
midnight sun.
</P>
</TEXT>
