<HEADER>
A1169 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS11-COX     05-10 0486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CD mini reviews
 &HT;    By Nick Tate and Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   POP-ROCK
</P>
<P>
   `Wasp Star (Apple Venus 2)'
</P>
<P>
   XTC / TVT Records / 12 tracks / Our critic's grade: A
</P>
<P>
   After two decades, you'd think XTC would tire of updating the
Beatles every few years. You'd be wrong. And we should all be
grateful that Andy Partridge and Colin Moulding are sticking it
out. XTC's latest Lennon-McCartney homage is the duo's best album
in 15 years. Gone (wisely) is the arty orchestra play that drenched
1999's spotty (if often brilliant) ``Apple Venus.'' In its place
are the tight guitar-bass-drums pop, baroque lyrics and killer
hooks that made XTC an enduring '80s-radio treat. Catchy songs like
``Stupidly Happy'' and ``Playground'' echo XTC classics like
``Mayor of Simpleton'' and ``Respectable Street.'' And much of
``Wasp'' has that irresistible hum-along-at-first-listen quality
that rewards repeated listenings. Bottom line: This just might be
the best record Paul McCartney never made.
</P>
<P>
   www..charm.net/(tilde)duke/xtc/beatown
</P>
<P>
   .html.com
</P>
<P>
   _Nick Tate
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Live in Detroit''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Frampton. CMC International.14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   The curly locks are gone. The choir-boy vocals have grown
ragged. And the crowds have thinned (along with his hair). But
Peter Frampton's live show, as rendered here, hasn't changed a lick
since his monster 1976 hit ``Frampton Comes Alive!'' Those sappy
first-kiss acoustic ballads. The chiming rock-guitar solos. That
silly voice-box trick. It's all here. Again. Which begs a question:
Why bother? It's one thing to reprise a classic with a new element.
Pink Floyd did it with ``The Wall Live.'' So did Joni Mitchell with
her symphony-backed hits collection. But it's another thing
entirely to contrive a second lightning strike with a
by-the-numbers retread. Midway through ``Show Me the Way II,''
Frampton sums it up nicely when he confides, ``I can't believe this
is happening ... again.'' Frankly, Pete, neither can we.
</P>
<P>
   www.frampton.com.
</P>
<P>
   _Nick Tate
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``Goodfellas''
</P>
<P>
   504 Boyz. No Limit Records. 22 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   If there's a battle on CD between New Orleans-based hip-hop
labels No Limit Records and Cash Money Records, No Limit has added
a new weapon to its arsenal. Its name is Krazy. And it's almost
scary how much his muscular vocals dip, wind and sound a lot like
the late charismatic rapper Tupac Shakur. Other than that, the
re-emergence of Master P, Silkk the Shocker and Mystikal under the
name of their home's area code is the usual lengthy visit with the
rich and project-minded. Without longtime collaborators Beats by
the Pound, the production doesn't come off as confident, but
``Wobble, Wobble,'' ``Check 'em'' and ``We Bust'' are still catchy.
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
