<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Daring portrait of dysfunctional family
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A beaut. The ever more remarkable Kevin Spacey leads a stellar
ensemble cast (Annette Bening, Thora Birch, Chris Cooper) in this
scarily disturbing, daringly hilarious comedy-drama that won five
Oscars, including best picture of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Mendes (Broadway's ``Cabaret'') and former Mariettan Alan
Ball (a sitcom heavy hitter) have fashioned a fin de siecle
tragifarce centering on Spacey as a man caught in midlife limbo.
Combining the compassion and quirkiness of a James L. Brooks film
with the darker charge of David Lynch's ``Blue Velvet'' period, the
movie is a hauntingly optimistic elegy for America the Beautifully
Screwed Up.
</P>
<P>
   Among its other well-deserved Oscars: best director, screenplay,
actor (Spacey) and cinematography.
</P>
<P>
   `American Beauty'
</P>
<P>
   Rated R / Our critic's grade: A
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   OTHER RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Bringing Out the Dead'' (R) _ Martin Scorsese performs
another deft autopsy on New York after dark in this savage,
sorrowing look at a few days in the life of a paramedic whose beat
is the mean, messy streets of Hell's Kitchen. As played by Nicolas
Cage in ``Leaving Las Vegas'' mode, he's alcoholic, burned out and
haunted by the spirits of those he couldn't save. A kinda romance
with Patricia Arquette doesn't work, but there's excellent work by
John Goodman, Ving Rhames and Tom Sizemore as Cage's various
partners. Think of a big-screen ``ER'' episode, only given the full
Scorsese treatment. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Mystery, Alaska'' (R) _ A by-the-numbers but fairly pleasant
David-vs.-Goliath comedy on ice. Russell Crowe, Hank Azaria and
Burt Reynolds star in TV wiz David E. Kelley's tale of small-town
hockey lovers taking on the New York Rangers. The movie piles on
raunchy jokes and is a soggy series of bite-size vignettes and
spoon-fed emotions. For all that, it's still pretty watchable.
Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Straight Story'' (G) _ David Lynch shifts gears in this
lyrically simple little film based on the true story of 70-plus
Alvin Straight (Oscar nominee Richard Farnsworth), who drove his
1966 John Deere riding mower more than 300 miles to reconcile with
his estranged brother (Harry Dean Stanton). The movie is a sublime
celebration of America at its most beautiful: kind, welcoming,
gloriously eccentric. Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For future video release dates:
www.comingsoon.net/videos.htm
</P>
