A1173 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-RINGEL11-COX     05-10 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-RINGEL11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dance movies that have all the right moves
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   All you need to know about dance in the movies can be summed up
in five words: Fred Astaire and Gene Kelly. They're the guys. The
ones to watch. The ones to keep watching. But the new dance-centric
movie ``Center Stage,'' opening Friday, reminds me that dance
movies come in all shapes, sizes and forms. Here are a few ideas to
keep you on your toes:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``All That Jazz'' (1979) _ A Me Musical to top off the Me
Decade of the '70s, Bob Fosse's quasi-autobiographical movie about
a driven but brilliant director/choreographer has a kind of ``4
1/2'' plot. But, boy, those moves _ especially the singularly
sensational mass-audition opening that made any movie version of
``A Chorus Line'' redundant. In the Fosse role, Roy Scheider seems
in a perpetual sweat, but then, that's the kind of movie this is _
a highly charged, glitzed-up tribute to, as Fosse/Scheider says,
``magic time.'' This is also the movie that rescued Jessica Lange's
career. True, her role as an enigmatic Angel of Death isn't big,
but it gave her work after the ignominy of ``King Kong.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Red Shoes'' (1948) _ Distinguished director Michael
Powell put his best foot forward with this poetic tribute to the
enchantments of ballet. The story line is simple melodrama: A
renowned impresario (Anton Walbrook) discovers a sublime young
dancer (Moira Shearer) and makes her a star. But her love for her
art is challenged by her falling in love with a young composer
(Marius Goring). The movie takes its name _ and, in a sense, its
theme _ from the Hans Christian Andersen fable about a young girl
bewitched by her red dancing slippers. Powell writes in his
voluminous memoir that the project was conceived with Merle Oberon
in mind. When that fell through, he insisted on casting a dancer in
the lead. But Shearer, he adds, never cared about making movies;
like her character, she only cared for dance. ``I never let love
interfere with business,'' he wrote. ``Or I would have made love to
her. It would have improved her performance. A dancer is like a
nun.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Turning Point'' (1977) _ On the one hand, the movie is
notorious for receiving 11 Oscar nominations and going home with
none. On the other, it's a well-crafted and well-acted (and, best
of all, well-danced) look at the behind-the-scenes world of ballet
while, at the same time, being a study of friendship and choices.
Anne Bancroft is the aging prima ballerina, and Shirley MacLaine is
her former colleague, who long ago turned her tutu in for a
homemaker's apron. Their battleground, so to speak, is MacLaine's
dancing daughter (Leslie Browne), who comes to New York to
apprentice with Bancroft's company. Mikhail Baryshnikov introduced
his genius to moviegoers as the troupe's charming but ego-ridden
star. He also earned one of those 11 nominations in the best
supporting actor category.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``West Side Story'' (1961) _ It also nabbed 11 Oscar
nominations, but it went home with 10, including best picture,
director (split between Robert Wise and choreographer Jerome
Robbins) and both supporting awards in acting (George Chakiris and
Rita Moreno). As the first movie to ``modernize'' the ``Romeo and
Juliet'' saga, screenwriter Ernest Lehman's adaptation of Arthur
Laurents' play places the lovers' tragedy against the backdrop of
feuding gangs in Manhattan, circa 1960. Leonard Bernstein's score
is pulsatingly powerful, and Stephen Sondheim's lyrics trickily
memorable, but what everyone remembers is the dancing, especially
the celebrated six-minute opening sequence. You're never alone _
snap, snap. You're never disconnected.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For recommended ballet videos:
www.balletdance.about.com/entertainment/balletdance/msubvid.htm
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
