<SLUG> BC-BUYERS-EDGE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With the click of a mouse, online service delivers the goods to
your house
 &HT;    By Sabine Morrow
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grocery shopping may never be the same _ not since Webvan.com
brought the supermarket to Atlanta's doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   The dot-com delivery service officially began rolling out meat,
potatoes and more from its Suwanee warehouse to kitchen counters
May 1.
</P>
<P>
   Buyer's Edge couldn't wait to see how the system works, so with
the help of Roswell homemaker Donna Kibler, we put Webvan to the
test right out of the gate.
</P>
<P>
   Kibler, a stay-at-home mother of two boys ages 8 and 10, usually
shops on Mondays, so she places her order through Webvan.com on
Sunday afternoon. All she has to do Monday is wait for Webvan.
</P>
<P>
   We hang out with Kibler as she navigates her way around
Webvan.com. Here's how it goes:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sunday, April 30
</P>
<P>
   2:10 p.m.: Kibler takes a break from digging a drainage pipe in
the front yard with her geologist husband, Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Kibler begins her virtual trip to the supermarket _ shoes off
and relaxed in a comfy chair in front of her PC. It takes a few
minutes to tinker with the registration page but faster than you
can say, ``Will I ever find a parking space?'' Kibler schedules her
delivery for the
</P>
<P>
   3-3:30 p.m. time slot the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's on to selecting items and scratching them off her
written list.
</P>
<P>
   Sliding her mouse down the bread list, Kibler is pleased to find
the IronKids Round Top Bread her family likes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pay about $1.89, so at $2.24, this is a little more
expensive,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   However, she quickly finds a loaf of sourdough in the Artisans
Bread section that at $2.44 was quite a bit less expensive than
what she usually buys.
</P>
<P>
   Kibler continues. She double clicks on a pint of yogurt to
enlarge and checks to see if it's what she wants. It is _ and with
a click it ends up on top of the growing list on the left side of
her screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, it's tallying right there,'' she says, pointing to the
running total. ``I love that. I'm going to save the meat for last
to see what I can afford,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She moves on to the vegetables. She's picky about apples. ``They
have to be really crisp, not soft at all.''
</P>
<P>
   3:08 p.m.: Kibler nears the end of her list. Like visiting a new
store, it takes awhile to navigate and find what you're looking
for.
</P>
<P>
   3:25 p.m.: Kibler maneuvers her mouse to the meat section. She
picks out a USDA Choice eye of round roast between 2 and 4 pounds,
a pack of chicken breasts and four inch-thick New York steaks.
</P>
<P>
   As she scans the final total of $119.31, Kibler notes it isn't
more than what she typically spends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some things cost a little more,'' she decides, ``but then
others are less, so it pretty much evens out.''
</P>
<P>
   3:35 p.m.: She quickly checks out by entering her credit card
number. Less than an hour and a half has passed since she logged
on.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Monday, May 1
</P>
<P>
   2:30 p.m.: Delivery day finds Kibler digging in her front yard
again. This time, it's flowers. She's pleasantly surprised when the
beige van with the Webvan logo pulls up to her house 15 minutes
early.
</P>
<P>
   2:45 p.m.: Courier Joe Gilbert loads bright yellow and green
plastic containers on a dolly. Kibler despises grocery shopping and
isn't fond of lugging the endless sacks from car to kitchen. No
such hassle with Webvan.com. Gilbert brings everything into the
kitchen, unloads the boxes and places all items on the counter.
</P>
<P>
   2:55 p.m.: Kibler makes a beeline for the bread and apples.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bread is soft and squishy like we like it, and the apples
are really crisp.''
</P>
<P>
   Score another one for Webvan. ``I really like my roast,'' she
says as she continues to sort her purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Kibler thinks the lean steaks look just like what she would have
picked out.
</P>
<P>
   After Gilbert sets everything out, he prints out Kibler's
receipt from a little printer attached to his belt. The bill is $15
less than she figured because of a ``grand opening'' promo. He also
gives her an itemized list of her order before he leaves.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  3:04 p.m.: Everything is put away.  &QR;  Postscript: The entire
process has taken a little more than two hours all told, and Kibler
never left her driveway.
</P>
<P>
   What is Webvan.com?
</P>
<P>
   Online grocery store Webvan.com was introduced last year in San
Francisco. Officials chose Atlanta as its second market because,
after San Francisco, it's the most Internet-connected city in the
world, says Chris Ohlund, Webvan's general manager in Atlanta.
Eventually, officials hope the concept will click in major cities
nationally.
</P>
<P>
   With a simple click on the Atlanta icon on the home page, you
can buy 50,000 products online. These include groceries, bakery
items and deli meats as well as health and beauty products,
flowers, baby products, books and office supplies _ everything from
soup to nuts for a dinner party.
</P>
<P>
   Say, for example, you want to find your favorite box of cereal.
Under groceries, click on breakfast, then on cold cereals, then
flakes and brans. You have 21 different choices, including
Kellogg's Corn Flakes (12 ounces, $2.57), Post Natural Raisin Bran
(25 ounces, $3.57) and Kellogg's Cracklin' Oat Bran (17 ounces,
$4.57). Or how about nutitional cereals? Your 20 choices include
Total (10 ounces, $3.77) and Special K (12 ounces, $3.67). And a
shredded wheat lover has 12 choices.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a thrifty shopper, click on the sale icon to find
good deals on items ranging from Lender's Onion Bagels to fresh
strawberries to Hunt's tomato sauce.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to ordering food, you can get many extras. Click on
Sensations and enjoy the following:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Easy recipes: Select a category, from appetizers to desserts,
and call up recipes for cheddar cheese grits, swirl French toast,
chocolate chip pie and mint juleps.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Weekly menus: Choose from a week's worth of menus, quick
recipes and shopping lists.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chef's corner: Read interviews with such culinary experts as
cookbook author Paul Prudhomme, olive oil and winemaker Maurizio
Castelli and restaurant owner Alice Waters. Includes recipes and
cooking tips.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Simple uses and techniques: Learn professional tips for
preparing food and planning meals _ for example, making ice cream,
using fresh herbs, doing Sunday brunches.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Webvan favorites: Read about favorite suppliers _ Aubrey
Originals, Ben &AMP; Jerry's, Tom's of Maine.
</P>
<P>
   _Marylin Johnson
</P>
<P>
   PRICE PATROL
</P>
<P>
   We compared Webvan's prices on four staples found on a typical
family's weekly grocery list with those at four area chain
supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   TROPICANA PURE PREMIUM ORIGINAL
</P>
<P>
   64 fluid ounces (2 quarts)
</P>
