   CREST REGULAR TOOTHPASTE
</P>
<P>
   6.4 ounces
</P>
<P>
   Webvan: $2.47
</P>
<P>
   Kroger: $2.49
</P>
<P>
   Ingles: $1.97
</P>
<P>
   Cub Foods: $2.48
</P>
<P>
   Publix: $2.49
</P>
<P>
   _Michelle C. Brooks
</P>
<P>
   What we like
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More flexibility and free time. You no longer have to worry
about rushing that quart of ice cream straight home from the store.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The wide variety of items available, ranging from cold
medications to pet supplies, books to postage stamps, flowers to
body salts.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Saves gas and wear and tear on your car.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  No tip neccessary. Webvan couriers aren't allowed to accept
them.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Webvan takes $15 off your bill for every customer you refer.
And you can refer up to 20 people per year.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Webvan.com lets you keep your list in the system, so you don't
have to begin from scratch each time.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Shoppers might be less inclined to impulse shop, and those
with children won't have to worry about them wanting everything in
sight.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Prices are not substantially higher than conventional grocery
stores.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  As at the grocery store, selected items are on sale each week.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quality is at least on a par with conventional grocery stores.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Delivery is free for orders of $50 or more and $4.95 for
orders under $50. However, through July, delivery is free for all
orders.
</P>
<P>
   What we didn't like
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Coupons aren't accepted.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  You can't see and touch the products you want or read the
nutrition labels.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  You have to be organized and order everything you need so you
don't end up making extra treks to the grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Webvan doesn't deliver to all metro areas, but the company is
expanding its reach (check the Web site to see if your neighborhood
is served).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Beer and wine cannot be delivered in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chef-prepared meals aren't being offered in the Atlanta area
at this time.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sabine Morrow writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
