<HEADER>
A1176 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-BUNTCAKE-RECIPES     05-10 3156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BUNTCAKE-RECIPES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bundt pan makes for a boffo presentation
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bette Justice of Marietta yearned for a Bundt pan when she moved
to Atlanta from Cincinnati after graduating from college some years
ago. But the popular pan was hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, my aunt sent one to me from Boston, and I've used the
pan now for over 25 years,'' Justice wrote in an e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   A good Bundt pan is worth seeking out and then cherishing for
decades. Especially with so many delicious recipes for making the
most of the hills, ridges and vales in the cake pan's design.
</P>
<P>
   Those same ridges and vales, of course, can make greasing a
Bundt pan a challenge. Some time ago we asked Shirley Corriher for
advice. Baker's Joy, a nonstick cooking spray that greases and
flours the pan at the same time, can be ideal. Lecithin is the
greasing agent; it contains fewer calories than many oils used for
greasing pans.
</P>
<P>
   Corriher also offered the ``double-grease'' technique as an
option. Butter the pan well and place in the freezer for five
minutes or so, just long enough for the butter to set. Then oil the
pan (with vegetable oil or vegetable-oil spray), dust with flour
and immediately pour in the batter.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that the beautiful shape of the Bundt pan can be
used for other purposes. My friend Fern Hallman uses mini-Bundt
pans as rice molds. And Sarah Lopez sent this e-mail suggestion for
a fat-free, sugar-free, carbohydrate-free way to enjoy the Bundt
pan: Hold the pan upside down by the center and hit it gently with
a wooden spoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Bundt pan is a heavy-duty one, the resulting resonance
matches the quality of a fine Tibetan bell,'' Lopez said.
</P>
<P>
   THE TUBE PAN VS. THE BUNDT PAN
</P>
<P>
   One of the frequent questions we get concerns the difference
between the tube pan and the Bundt pan. One woman called while her
oven was still smoking, angry that a peanut butter poundcake recipe
we had published had spilled over.
</P>
<P>
   After talking with her for a few moments, we quickly figured out
the problem _ she had poured a recipe intended for a tube pan into
a Bundt pan.
</P>
<P>
   For the record: a 10-inch tube pan (or angel food cake pan)
holds 16 cups of batter. It's shown at left. A 10-inch Bundt pan
holds 12 cups of batter.
</P>
<P>
   Anytime you are wondering how much a pan will hold, simply fill
with water and then pour water into a measuring cup (or pour water
from measuring cup into the pan). Baking pans generally can be used
interchangeably if they hold about the same amount of batter.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Lemon Jell-O Poundcake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 40-45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Bette Justice won first prize at a company picnic with this
popular recipe. First, poke holes in the cake; then glaze, letting
it really seep in.
</P>
<P>
   For the cake:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1 (3-ounce) package lemon gelatin
</P>
<P>
   1 (18.25-ounce) package lemon cake mix (such as Duncan Hines)
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   4 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   Juice of one lemon or 1 teaspoon lemon flavoring
</P>
<P>
   For the lemon glaze:
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup ( 1/2 stick) margarine, melted
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sifted confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   To make the cake: Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Grease a 10-inch
Bundt pan. Bring water to a boil and stir in gelatin. Set aside to
cool. In a large mixing bowl, combine cake mix, oil and cooled
gelatin mixture. Mix well. Add eggs and lemon juice. Pour into
prepared pan and bake 40 to 45 minutes or until light golden brown.
Cool in pan approximately 20 minutes, then invert onto serving
plate.
</P>
<P>
   To make the lemon glaze: Combine melted butter, confectioners'
sugar and lemon juice in a small mixing bowl. Mix on medium-high
speed for 3 to 5 minutes, or until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Using a fork, poke holes all over the cake. While cake is still
warm, drizzle with lemon glaze.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 406 calories, 8 grams protein, 21 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 46), 49 grams carbohydrates, 107
milligrams cholesterol, 378 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Martin's Sour Cream Poundcake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 1/4 hours
</P>
<P>
   This delectable poundcake sets the Zeta Tau Alpha sisters
bidding against one another at their annual fund-raiser. It's
delightful with fresh strawberries and whipped cream. Thanks to
Linda Williams Cattanach of Blairsville for sending it in.
</P>
<P>
   1 cup (2 sticks) butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   3 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   6 large eggs, separated (beat whites first until soft peaks
form, and set aside)
</P>
<P>
   3 cups all-purpose flour, sifted
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sour cream or plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon lemon extract
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon almond extract
</P>
<P>
   In a large mixing bowl, cream butter and sugar. Add egg yolks, 1
at a time, beating well after each addition. In another bowl,
combine flour and baking soda. Add sour cream alternately with
flour to sugar mixture. Fold in beaten egg whites. Add vanilla,
lemon and almond extracts. Spray Bundt pan with Baker's Joy. Pour
in batter and place on middle rack of cold oven. Set oven to 325
degrees. Bake for 1 hour and 15 minutes, or until cake tester
inserted in middle comes out clean. Let cool in pan 15 minutes;
remove from pan.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 390 calories, 5 grams protein, 17 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 39), 56 grams carbohydrates, 86
milligrams cholesterol, 198 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Pistachio Chocolate Chip Bundt Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Geier of Berkeley Lake has many of her mother's Bundt
cake recipes. She says this one has become a birthday favorite in
the family.
</P>
<P>
   1 (18.25-ounce) box yellow cake mix (without pudding in the mix)
</P>
<P>
   1 (3.4-ounce) package Jell-O Pistachio Instant Pudding
</P>
<P>
   4 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped pecans or walnuts
</P>
<P>
   1 (6-ounce) package semisweet chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   Confectioners' sugar for dusting
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Grease and flour Bundt pan. In a
large mixing bowl, combine cake mix, pudding, eggs, vegetable oil,
water and vanilla. Mix with an electric mixer on medium speed for 4
minutes. Gently fold in the nuts and chocolate chips until
well-distributed. Pour into prepared pan.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 1 hour or until done. Check by inserting a knife or noting
whether the cake is pulling away from the pan. Let cool on wire
cake rack. When cool, remove from pan; sprinkle confectioners'
sugar on top by shaking 1 or 2 tablespoons through a small wire
sieve.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 492 calories, 6 grams protein, 28 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 51), 58 grams carbohydrates, 107
milligrams cholesterol, 357 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate Coconut
</P>
<P>
   Bundt Cake (above)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 70 to 75 minutes
</P>
<P>
   My ``tunneling'' technique leaves a bit to be desired. The
``tunnel'' of filling never seems to land in the center. But it
sure doesn't matter _ I always end up with a pretty, tasty cake.
This was no exception. My tunnel of filling was near the top, but
this cake knocked my socks off. I'll be serving it at summer
gatherings. Thanks again to Barbara Geier.
</P>
<P>
   For the filling:
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg
</P>
<P>
   1 (8-ounce) package cream cheese (regular, not lite)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup flaked coconut
</P>
<P>
   1 (6-ounce) package semisweet chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   For the cake:
</P>
<P>
   2 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   3 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup unsweetened cocoa
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons baking soda
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup hot coffee
</P>
<P>
   1 cup buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped nuts
</P>
<P>
   For the glaze:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons cocoa
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 to 3 tablespoons hot water
</P>
<P>
   To make filling: In small bowl of electric mixer, beat sugar,
vanilla, egg and cream cheese until smooth. Stir in coconut and
chocolate chips. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   To make the cake: Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Grease and flour
Bundt pan. In large bowl of electric mixer, combine sugar, oil and
eggs. Beat 1 minute at high speed. Add flour, cocoa, baking soda,
baking powder, salt, coffee, buttermilk and vanilla. Beat 3 minutes
at medium speed, scraping bowl occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   By hand, stir in nuts. Pour 1/2 of the batter into Bundt pan.
Carefully spoon prepared filling over batter. Top with remaining
batter. Bake for 70 to 75 minutes until top springs back when
touched lightly.
</P>
<P>
   Cool upright in pan for 15 minutes. Remove from pan. Cool
completely.
</P>
<P>
   To make glaze: In a medium saucepan, combine confectioners'
sugar, cocoa, butter, vanilla and hot water and bring to a low boil
for 1 to 2 minutes. Drizzle glaze over cool cake.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 681 calories, 9 grams protein, 37 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 49), 86 grams carbohydrates, 94
milligrams cholesterol, 623 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Aletha Little Texas Rum Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings Preparation time: 20-25 minutes Cooking time:
about 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   This is the cake that turned heads on the elevator for Anne
Hayden of Atlanta. It uses rum extract instead of the real thing,
so it's ideal for the whole family.
</P>
<P>
   For the cake:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup (2 sticks) butter
</P>
<P>
   2 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   3 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon rum extract
</P>
<P>
   For the glaze:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups granulated sugar, divided
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons rum extract
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees. Grease and flour Bundt pan.
</P>
<P>
   To make the cake: In large bowl of an electric mixer, cream
butter and sugar until light. Beat in eggs one at a time, beating
well after each addition. In a medium mixing bowl, sift together
flour, soda, baking powder and salt. Add to the butter mixture,
alternating with buttermilk, beginning and ending with the dry
ingredients. Add the extract and pour into prepared pan. Place pan
in oven and bake 1 hour or longer, until a toothpick inserted in
the cake comes out clean.
</P>
<P>
   When done, cool in the pan for 10 minutes, then turn out on a
plate. While the cake is cooling in the pan, prepare the glaze.
</P>
<P>
   To make the glaze: Cook to a rolling boil 1 cup sugar and 1/2
cup water. Cool and then add 1 1/2 teaspoons rum extract and 2
tablespoons sugar. Brush on the warm cake in several coatings,
sprinkling granulated sugar over the cake between each coating. The
coating has a crunchy, glistening texture when finished that
provides a wonderful contrast to the tender cake.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 376 calories, 5 grams protein, 14 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 33), 59 grams carbohydrates, 111
milligrams cholesterol, 278 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Spicy Sweet Treat
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: about 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   We bet Rita Brommer's friends love to see her coming, since she
often makes this cake for meetings, parties and hostess gifts when
she visits folks out of town.
</P>
<P>
   3 cups all-purpose flour, divided
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground allspice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1 cups chopped fruit (such as prunes, apricots, raisins or dried
apples)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped nuts
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) margarine or butter
</P>
<P>
   2 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 cups canned applesauce
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Grease and flour 12-cup Bundt pan.
In a medium mixing bowl, combine 2 cups flour, cinnamon, cloves,
allspice, nutmeg and baking soda.
</P>
<P>
   In another bowl, combine fruit, nuts and remaining 1 cup flour.
</P>
<P>
   In a third bowl, cream butter or margarine and sugar until light
and fluffy. Add applesauce and blend. Stir into flour mixture
gradually, beating after each addition until smooth. Stir in
floured fruit and nuts. Pour into prepared pan and bake for 1 hour
or until a toothpick inserted in center of cake comes out clean.
Remove from oven and cool in pan for 10 minutes. Turn out onto a
rack to finish cooling.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 224 calories, 3 grams protein, 11 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 43), 30 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 183 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Tunnel of Fudge Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 50-60 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 2 hours, 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This recipe from the 1966 bake-off contest is one of the most
popular Pillsbury recipes of all time. The cake was created by Ella
Helfrich of Houston, and originally called for a frosting mix for
the filling that is no longer available. So the Pillsbury kitchens
have updated the recipe _ but it's every bit as good. The
popularity of the fluted Bundt tube pan increased after this recipe
won the contest.
</P>
<P>
   For the filling:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   1 (3.4-ounce) package chocolate fudge
</P>
<P>
   pudding and pie filling mix (not instant)
</P>
<P>
   1 (6-ounce) package (1 cup) semisweet chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   For the cake:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/3 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup (1 1/2 sticks) butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup shortening
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   4 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup unsweetened cocoa
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chopped walnuts
</P>
<P>
   For the glaze:
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup unsweetened cocoa
</P>
<P>
   4 to 6 teaspoons milk
</P>
<P>
   In medium saucepan, combine 1 1/2 cups milk and pudding mix;
cook as directed on package. Add chocolate chips; stir until
melted. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Grease and flour 12-cup Bundt pan
or 10-inch tube pan. In large bowl, combine sugar, butter and
shortening; beat until light and fluffy. Add vanilla and eggs; mix
well. Lightly spoon flour into measuring cup; level off. Add flour,
1/2 cup cocoa, baking powder, salt and 1 cup milk; beat at low
speed until moistened. Beat 3 minutes at medium speed. Stir in
walnuts.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve 2 cups of the batter. Pour remaining batter into
prepared pan. Spoon filling in ring on top of batter, making sure
it does not touch sides of pan. (You may not use all the filling,
but you should use at least 2/3 of it.) Spoon reserved batter over
filling.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 50 to 60 minutes or until cake springs back when touched
lightly in center. Cool 1 hour; remove from pan. Cool 1 1/2 hours
or until completely cooled.
</P>
<P>
   In small bowl, combine confectioners' sugar and 1/4 cup cocoa.
Add enough milk for desired drizzling consistency. Spoon over cake,
allowing some to run down sides.
</P>
<P>
   Use very sharp or serrated knife to slice cake. Best when served
same day; store any remaining cake in refrigerator. _ From ``The
Best From 50 Years of Bake-Off Contests'' (Pillsbury Cookbooks,
$2.99)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 506 calories, 10 grams protein, 32 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 56), 51 grams carbohydrates, 108
milligrams cholesterol, 254 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Quick Monkey Bread
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 30-40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Ann Parker of Kennesaw sent along this recipe, her favorite for
a Bundt pan. It is indeed quick, and our tester said it should be
served immediately. Warning: This is addictive.
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup chopped pecans, divided
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   3 (10-ounce) cans refrigerated buttermilk biscuits
</P>
<P>
   1 cup firmly packed brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) melted butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Grease a 10-inch Bundt pan.
Sprinkle 1/2 cup chopped pecans evenly in bottom of pan.
</P>
<P>
   In a shallow dish, combine granulated sugar and cinnamon.
Separate biscuits and cut in quarters. Roll each piece in
cinnamon-sugar mixture and layer into pan. Sprinkle remaining 1/4
cup pecans through layers of dough.
</P>
<P>
   Combine brown sugar and melted butter; pour over dough. Bake 30
to 40 minutes. Cool bread in pan 10 minutes, then invert onto
serving platter.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 406 calories, 5 grams protein, 19 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 43), 55 grams carbohydrates, 2
milligrams cholesterol, 653 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Banana Cake With Chocolate Ganache (above)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings Preparation time: 15 minutes Cooking time: 1
hour
</P>
<P>
   We loved the intense banana aroma and flavor of this easy cake.
It's delicious as is, but even better with rich ganache frosting.
</P>
<P>
   2 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup canola or vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   3 large eggs, room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   4 overripe bananas, mashed with a fork
</P>
<P>
   3 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees. Lightly grease a Bundt pan. Place
sugar, oil and eggs in the bowl of a mixer fitted with a paddle
(preferably) and mix until light and lemon colored. Add vanilla and
bananas and mix until just combined. Scrape down the sides of the
bowl. Add flour, baking soda, salt, baking powder, cinnamon and
nutmeg and mix until just combined. Scrape down sides of bowl and
pour into the prepared pan. Transfer to oven and bake until a
toothpick comes out clean, about 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Cool cake in the pan for 20 minutes. Invert onto a rack and cool
to room temperature. Frost the top with Dark Chocolate Ganache (see
recipe below). _ From: ``The Bake Sale Cookbook'' by Sally Sampson
(Fireside, $15)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (without ganache): 528 calories, 6 grams protein, 26
grams fat (percent calories from fat, 45), 69 grams carbohydrates,
86 milligrams cholesterol, 281 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Dark Chocolate Ganache
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings, enough for 1 Bundt cake
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup semisweet chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   Place chocolate in a double boiler over medium heat and cook
until almost all the chocolate has melted. Take off the heat and
stir until chocolate is smooth. Gradually add cream, stirring
constantly, until smooth. Set aside to cool. _ Adapted from: ``The
Bake Sale Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 71 calories, 1 gram protein, 6 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 71), 6 grams carbohydrates, 7 milligrams
cholesterol, 2 milligrams sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
