<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BUNTCAKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A Bundt cake on the table is a fluted sign that festive times
are ahead, and a reminder of past celebrations
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barbara Geier remembers that the highlight of many of her
childhood weekends was a family outing to a college football game.
Sure, the games were fun; but the Bundt cakes were even better.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother and her friends would exchange their favorite Bundt
cake recipes so they wouldn't get bored with the same cake each
week,'' said Geier of Berkeley Lake, Ga. ``I make many of them now
for special occasions.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Zipfel of Smyrna, Ga., fondly recalls her mother jotting
down Bundt cake recipes from a radio show called ``Party Line''
that aired in Searcy, Ark. Her mother shared the recipes with
Zipfel's grandmother. And during visits, Zipfel and her grandmom
would often sneak a slice to share over secret early-morning chats
before others in the house woke up.
</P>
<P>
   For 50 years, Bundt cakes have added that festive touch to so
many occasions. Sure, bake the cakes in some other pan and the
flavor will be pretty much the same. But flutes add flair.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to put the typical heavy, sweet icings on
them,'' explained Geier. ``Yet they are incredibly tasty. They
always draw rave reviews.''
</P>
<P>
   If ever there was a weekend to pull the fluted beauty off the
shelf, it's this weekend. Why not thank Mom for all those Bundt
cakes she's baked over the years by making her a special one for
Mother's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, we have Moms to thank for the Bundt pan. Fifty years
ago, a group of Minneapolis homemakers (members of the Hadassah
Society) asked the local Northland Aluminum Products if they could
produce a cast aluminum pan similar to the kugelhupf pan popular in
Germany. A few were made for them, along with a few extra, under
the Nordic Ware brand name.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years later, a poundcake baked in the Bundt pan was featured
in the Good Housekeeping cookbook, and demand picked up. But the
Bundt pan really earned its spot on the kitchen shelf at the 1966
Pillsbury Bake-Off. One of the top recipes was the Tunnel of Fudge
cake. After the competition, Pillsbury received more than 200,000
requests for help in finding the pan and Northland had to operate
on 24-hour shifts to meet the demand.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there are an estimated 40 million Bundt pans in America.
There's probably one in your mother's kitchen, if not your own.
There are numerous sizes and even a couple of variations on style
(festive and star) available today _ just take a peek at
www.bundt.com.
</P>
<P>
   The name Bundt comes from the German word ``bund,'' which means
a gathering. So the Bundt cake is meant to be special enough for
gatherings and parties. Rita Brommer of Lilburn thinks so. She
takes a Bundt cake she calls Spicy Sweet Treat to her senior
meetings and whenever she goes visiting out of town.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Hayden of Atlanta loves to use her Bundt pan to make a rum
cake. She once took the cake to her office when she worked in New
York. ``The odor of the rum filled the elevator and heads began to
turn to find out what poor soul had been hitting the bottle so
early in the morning,'' recalls Hayden, who actually uses rum
extract in the cake. The recipe is inside, along with others from
Geier and Brommer and Linda Williams Cattanach of Blairsville.
</P>
<P>
   Cattanach shared a coveted recipe she and her Zeta Tau Alpha
sisters loved _ Virginia Martin's Sour Cream Pound Cake. Martin
passed away a few years ago, but since then Willa Jones has
continued the tradition of baking the poundcake in a Bundt pan and
offering it up for auction at the group's annual fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was always a spirited and good-humored competition to
take the cake home,'' said Cattanach. ``It's the top bid of the
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
