<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Web full of recipes sure to warm Mom's heart
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just because your mother has given you a million things doesn't
mean she wants you to do the same for her on Mother's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than pointing and clicking yourself into debt dipping
into the fancy and expensive Mother's Day gifts that abound on the
Internet, most mothers would prefer something from the heart.
Mother's Day is truly an observance where, gift-wise, it really is
the thought that counts. As ever, a meal thoughtfully prepared,
with special touches meant just for her, can be more memorable than
an expensive gift. Balancing out all the e-commerce are many sites
brimming with pure inspiration and ideas on how to make the day
special for Mom.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If you want to pull off an extra-special day, this is a good
place to start. A Mothers Day Celebration at
food.homearts.com/food/thoughts/enter/46enta16.htm offers
straightforward advice on how to ``wow your biggest fan _ and
toughest critic _ on her special day'' with a party in her honor
and great food. Starting with ``Setting the Mood,'' it suggests:
``It's spring. Keep it light, airy and informal.'' It has tips
about invitations (forget just using the phone _ make it special
with a handwritten invite). Special Mother's Day touches for napkin
rings, place cards, music, candles and flowers also are included.
Menu suggestions for a Mother's Day brunch include seasonal choices
like Salmon and Asparagus Salad or Bow-Tie Pasta With Baby
Artichokes and Basil. For an appetizer, a light fruit compote or
salad of pineapples, strawberries and mangoes is suggested. For a
Mother's Day Sunday supper: leg of lamb with pistachio topping,
spring risotto and couscous-stuffed artichokes. Sections also
include stunning desserts and extravagant beverages.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Holiday Channel at www.holidaychannel.com/mothersday is
another good place to visit if you want to expand on the
chocolates-and-flowers routine. How about surprising Mom with an
authentic recipe favored by her personal heartthrob celebrity? Here
you will find Frank Sinatra's favorite clam sauce, scrod from Paul
Newman, grilled tuna from Billy Joel and others. Also included is a
to-do list outlining what to do, hour by hour, for a perfect day.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If you are not a whiz kid in the kitchen and feel you're not
up to the challenge of whipping up a gourmet meal for Mom, check
out A Million Dollar Menu for Mom at
secure.foodwine.com/food/egg/egg0598/mealmom.html. You'll find
detailed instructions on how to produce a fabulous menu of Shrimp
Cocktail Appetizer, Cold Poached Salmon With Tangy Mustard-Mayo
Sauce, Tender Steamed Asparagus, Orange-Scented Couscous and
Raspberry Granita for dessert. It has a timetable, shopping list,
equipment list and minute-by-minute, hold-your-hand instructions,
along with pictures of everything so you will know how it's all
supposed to look.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If you decide that going to a restaurant is still the thing to
do, visit Nice and Easy Mother's Day at
www.party411.com/holidays-mothers.html _ a site that considers the
notion that dragging everyone over to Mom's house for Mother's Day
is as much fun for her as doing the wash. But even at a restaurant
you can add a personal touch. The site advises that you provide the
floral centerpiece. Just let the restaurant know you're bringing in
something so they will make room. Or go for a surprise (for Mom)
and drop it off or have it delivered.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mother's Day with a teenage slant and doable breakfast in bed
menus and recipes can be found at ``A Girls World Online Clubhouse
at www.agirlsworld.com/amy/pajama/mothersday/.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Younger kids with some adult help can get some ideas for Mom's
breakfast in bed at
www.geocities.com/Athens/Acropolis/1465/momsdayideas.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dining In: A Mothers Day Brunch at
www.comzone.com/nwnews/wwissues/v21n31/home1.html features a menu
that includes a blender cheese souffle, heart-shaped biscuits,
asparagus risotto, poached salmon with spinach and fruit tarts.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The menus at Mother's Day at
members.aol.com/fographics/mother.html take you through the whole
day. Breakfast in bed features strawberries and sour cream omelet.
Dinner features an easy recipe for hot crab dip with crostini,
roasted Cornish hens, wild rice, brussels sprouts and rhubarb
crunch. A family buffet goes Italian with an antipasto and lasagna.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S THE THOUGHT
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Some lovely examples of Victorian Mother's Day art are at
www.tssphoto.com
</P>
<P>
   /mom/mom.html. You can design your own card by choosing a
picture and an appropriate quote. Click on Mother's Day Tributes
for quotes from the likes of Lincoln (``I remember my mother's
prayers, and they have always followed me. They have clung to me
all my life'') to Balzac (``The heart of a mother is a deep abyss
at the bottom of which you will always find forgiveness''). If your
mom is wired, you can e-mail your original card or print it out and
use snail mail.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Holiday Spot at theholidayspot.com/mothersday/index.htm
offers special Mother's Day certificates that you can personalize
and print along with poems and recipe for a Mother's Cake.
</P>
<P>
   BEVERAGE
</P>
<P>
   Apricot Splash
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Here's a luscious drink to accompany a special Mother's Day
breakfast in bed.
</P>
<P>
   Crushed ice
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 ounces apricot brandy
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces apricot nectar
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces champagne
</P>
<P>
   Mint sprig
</P>
<P>
   Lime wedge
</P>
<P>
   In a large cocktail shaker, combine crushed ice with brandy,
lime juice and apricot nectar. Pour into a tall glass, splash
champagne into the drink and stir briefly. Garnish with mint and
lime wedge.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 219 calories, less than 1 gram protein, trace of
fat (percent calories from fat, less than 1), 10 grams
carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 7 milligrams sodium, less than 1
gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
