<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATION11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta's Little Five Points is funky, friendly and brimming
with fun spots
 &HT;    By Sabine Morrow
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe you've ventured into the heart of Little Five Points to
take in a play. Or perhaps you've taken out-of-towners _ to prove
that Atlanta really does have a bohemian edge.
</P>
<P>
   But if you haven't thought of funky Little Five Points as a
shopping venue, it's time to take a walk on the wild side.
</P>
<P>
   You can spend a good slice of a sunny afternoon people watching,
shopping for that eclectic little treasure, getting your navel
pierced and having your fortune told.
</P>
<P>
   And all this just on the strip of Euclid Avenue from Fifi
Mahony's to El Myr restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Stanton of Buckhead was window-shopping on Euclid
recently while waiting for a friend she was meeting for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really grateful that we have a place like Little Five
Points,'' she says. ``Where else around here can you be entertained
by the merchandise and the customers?''
</P>
<P>
   On Euclid Avenue you'll find that most shops have been recycled
many times, pretty much unrecognizable from their original intent.
For instance, the space that now houses Home Store Futon Gallery
was for years a Piggly Wiggly, then an A&AMP;P and more recently
Sevananda Natural Foods Market.
</P>
<P>
   In December it opened as a slick wood and brick showroom filled
with futons and accessories of every size and color, including
contemporary frosted glass stacked tables, cotton rugs and candles.
If you have a Midtown loft to furnish, this is the place to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Wander down to Urban Tribe Tattoo and you won't find sailors on
shore leave getting ``Mom'' emblazoned on their chests. Instead
you'll see young adults pouring over photos of tattoo designs in a
brightly lit area heavy with the scent of antiseptic. At the large
glass counter, you can peruse a variety of rings to decorate
various pierced body parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get a lot of people coming in here, especially this time of
the year. They're wearing less clothes and want to show some
skin,'' professional piercer Alyson Funderburk says.
</P>
<P>
   Make that embellished skin. According to Funderburk, Tribe's
business is equally divided between piercings and tattoos. Oh, and
if you're wondering what are the most popular body parts for
piercing at Tribe _ navels and tongues. Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   For the literary type, A Cappella Books offers new books as well
as used and out-of-print volumes. Here you can sell and trade books
you no longer want.
</P>
<P>
   Cross the street and enter Gypsy Market through a courtyard
beckoning with a bubble machine, pungent incense, seductive
drumming and a psychic reader. Inside this exotic warren you'll
find a cache of incense, candles, crystals and Allen Ginsberg's
books of poetry. Those who need a bit of relaxation can make use of
Gypsy Market's Mind Ride, a machine intended to transport the user
to a calm, centered state.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking that perfect pair of oh-so-tall platform sandals to go
with the teeny crochet bikini? Check out Envy clothing store for
both.
</P>
<P>
   If your taste runs to black vinyl, pastel lace, a little
delicate something in chains and 6-inch spike heels, consider
meandering through Throb.
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss its twisted sister store, Fifi Mahony's. Here you can
buy that hard-to-find Zombie green lipstick from Ben Nye Makeup,
tiaras and even body glitter. But outrageous hairpieces and wigs
draw many folks in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had 16-year-old girls going to the prom who want
baby-pink wigs to match their dresses,'' manager Tim Scott says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their parents would rather they wear a wig than dye their hair
that color. But we have that, too, if they want.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Getting there: Take the Downtown Connector to the North
Avenue exit (the Varsity will be on your left). Turn left on North
Avenue (crossing over the interstate) and travel east about 2 1/2
miles. Then, go right onto Moreland Avenue until you reach the
intersection of Euclid Avenue; turn right.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hours: Most stores are open daily. Some stores stay open until
7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Parking: Metered and nonmetered street parking and parking
behind some stores, including Outback Outfitters &AMP; Bikes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Restrooms: Restrooms available in most restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Accessibility: The sidewalks are pretty rough, and some of the
stores are cramped for space and not ideal for wheelchairs.
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  You won't find typical fast-food chain fare in this part of
town. Check out E.A.Y.C. (Euclid Avenue Yacht Club) when you want a
boisterous, publike atmosphere. Here you'll dine on pork burritos,
Kansas City brisket sandwich plates and even veggie Philly
sandwiches. Can't have a yacht club without seafood, so you'll also
find a fried fish sandwich as well. My guess, however, is that much
of the clientele goes for those Bloody Marys made from scratch.
Prices range from $2.25 to $7.50. 11 a.m.-2:30 a.m.
Mondays-Fridays; noon-2:30 a.m. Saturdays; 12:30-11:30 p.m.
Sundays. 1136 Euclid Avenue. 404-688-2582.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Calcutta Restaurant is a culinary paradox. Not only will you
find typical Indian dishes such as tandoori chicken and
mulligatawny soup, but you'll also encounter Cajun chicken
eggrolls. You're in Little Five Points _ enough said. Prices range
from $2.25 to $11.25. Lunch:11 a.m.-3 p.m. Mondays-Saturdays.
Dinner: 5:30-10:30 p.m. Mondays-Thursdays; 5-11 p.m.
Fridays-Saturdays; 5-10:30 p.m. Sundays. 1138 Euclid Avenue.
404-681-1838.
</P>
<P>
   A sampling of the shops on Euclid Avenue in Little Five Points:
</P>
<P>
   Apparel
</P>
<P>
   Callalillies Vintage Clothing, 1129 Euclid Ave.
</P>
<P>
   Envy, 1143 Euclid Ave.
</P>
<P>
   Mossi Hat &AMP; Clothing, 1130 Euclid Ave.
</P>
<P>
   Rene Rene Designs, 1142 Euclid Ave.
</P>
<P>
   Swails' Thing, 1129 Euclid Ave.
</P>
<P>
   The Clothing Warehouse, 1146 Euclid Ave.
</P>
<P>
   Throb, 1140 Euclid Ave.
</P>
<P>
   Gifts/Jewelery
</P>
<P>
   African Connection, 1107 Euclid Ave.
</P>
<P>
   Boomerang, 1145 Euclid Ave.
</P>
<P>
   Gypsy Market, 1127 Colquitt Ave.
</P>
<P>
   Soul Kiss, 1154 Euclid Ave.
</P>
<P>
   Specialty
</P>
<P>
   A Cappella Books, 1133 Euclid Ave.
</P>
<P>
   Fifi Mahony's, 1152 Euclid Ave.
</P>
<P>
   Home Store Futon Gallery, 1111 Euclid Ave.
</P>
<P>
   Outback Outfitters &AMP; Bikes, 1125 Euclid. Ave.
</P>
<P>
   Stratosphere Skateboards, 1141 Euclid Ave.
</P>
<P>
   Urban Tribe Tattoo, 1131 Euclid Ave.
</P>
<P>
   Sabine Morrow writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
