<SLUG> BC-DAUGHERTY-MUSIC-$ADV14-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SYMPHONIST OF ELVIS AND BARBIE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., May 14) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By KATHRYN SHATTUCK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a brilliant afternoon recently, fresh off a flight
from Detroit and eager to absorb the sun's rays pouring into a
frenzied haunt near Lincoln Center, Michael Daugherty was doing
what he claims to do best: peeling away layers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you?'' he asked his unwitting accomplice, a waitress,
sizing her up. ``Are you an actress or a dancer?''
</P>
<P>
   ``An actress and a singer, mostly musical theater,'' she
responded, complete with a new Screen Actors Guild card, a small
part in an Off Off Broadway show and hopes for a break, soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you have to be patient,'' Daugherty said, gesturing
toward Avery Fisher Hall, the home of the New York Philharmonic.
``I'm 45 years old, and I'm just having my first piece played over
there. It takes a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, yeah,'' she said. ``In fact, I just got a guy who is 38
or something, and he just got a Broadway play.''
</P>
<P>
   Daugherty smiled, his bubble only slightly deflated by the
woman's reluctance to play his game. ``Well, some people have it
young,'' he said, ``but usually it takes time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``By the way, is there a Xerox machine anywhere in the
restaurant?'' he asked, not quite matter-of-factly. ``Would you
mind making a few copies for me?''
</P>
<P>
   Charmed, the waitress headed toward the back office, papers in
hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what my father has done his whole life,'' Daugherty
explained. ``Wherever I am, I talk with people: the store owner,
the concertmaster, the waitress. I like to talk. I like to listen.
Some composers are always filtering everything out to write `pure'
music. I'm always tuned to the outside.''
</P>
<P>
   With its pop-culture imagery and playful inclusion of jazz, rock
and funk, Daugherty's music could hardly be called pure in any
sense of the word. And where on earth _ or beyond _ he is tuned,
listeners may judge for themselves beginning My 17, when the
Philharmonic, conducted by Leonard Slatkin, presents Daugherty's
``U.F.O.,'' a concerto written for and about the Scottish
percussionist Evelyn Glennie. Commissioned by Slatkin and the
National Symphony, the work was given its premiere last year in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Daugherty described the effervescent Glennie, who, improbably
for a percussionist, is deaf, as having an ``otherworldly, magical
presence.'' The work, drawing its inspiration from the
flying-saucer shape of cymbals (one of Glennie's is named Alien
Disc by the manufacturer) and from the myriad other unidentifiable
objects in a percussionist's battery, fits neatly into Daugherty's
gimmick-laden catalog.
</P>
<P>
   He has, after all, paid musical homage to Liberace (``Le Tombeau
de Liberace'' for piano and orchestra), Elvis Presley (``Dead
Elvis'' for bassoon and orchestra), J. Edgar Hoover (the string
quartet ``Sing Sing''), Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis (the opera
``Jackie O''), Desi Arnaz (``Desi'' for symphonic winds), Barbie
(``What's That Spell?'' for two vocalists and small ensemble) and
Superman (``Metropolis Symphony''); sometimes, even in non-operatic
works, the characters are represented by musicians in costume. A
cursory glance also reveals titles evocative of 1930s pulp
magazines, names like ``Sunset Strip,'' ``Route 66,'' ``Flamingo''
and ``Bizarro.''
</P>
<P>
   Daugherty has held news conferences in bowling alleys. And the
cover of his CD ``American Icons'' shows him, all 6 feet 8 inches,
wearing a beret and a leather vest, and pattering on bongos in the
middle of a heartland highway.
</P>
<P>
   All of which raises the question: is this stuff for real?
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' Daugherty said, rattling off a list of
commissions in the works for ensembles including the Philadelphia
Orchestra and the Chamber Music Society of Lincoln Center, which
this year awarded him its Elise L. Stoeger Prize. ``There's a
veneer of pop culture, but think about the way film critics write
about alternative movies: say, `Buffalo 66' or `Pulp Fiction.' They
play off American culture. In classical music, this really hasn't
been done much. It is a lonely journey in some ways.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It was a journey Daugherty began in Cedar Rapids, Iowa, where
his mother was a physical-education teacher and his father a
dance-band drummer who subsidized his livelihood with stints as a
used-car salesman, an ambulance driver and a manager of a women's
clothing store. The oldest of five musical brothers, who all turned
professional, Daugherty grew up playing keyboards in local bands,
enamored of the soulful syncopation of early Motown and the wails
and growls of James Brown, whose recordings he tracked down in
black-owned beauty shops across town.
</P>
<P>
   He studied jazz at North Texas State University but discovered
instead a passion for orchestral music. In 1976, he moved to New
York, where Pierre Boulez was the Philharmonic's music director,
and the driving force in composition was an exhaustive complexity.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, on a Fulbright fellowship, he traveled to Paris to
study at Ircam, the center for acoustical and musical research
founded by Boulez. There, in front of his computer, Daugherty
himself subscribed to the more-is-more theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided that I wanted to understand the most complex music
being written at the time, and I learned how to do that,'' he said.
``And then I had all the techniques under my belt, but at the same
time I couldn't find a connection with my past. Anything emotional
to me, I couldn't make that connection in any way.''
</P>
<P>
   He fared better at Yale, to which he had been drawn by his
curiosity about the Connecticut composer Charles Ives and, in turn,
Ives' interest in another New Englander, Ralph Waldo Emerson. While
working toward a doctorate (which he earned in 1986), he studied
composition with Earle Brown, Jacob Druckman, Bernard Rands and
Roger Reynolds, trying to determine, in his words, ``what it meant
to be a composer, emotionally.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was something that was never discussed in all my
schooling,'' he said. ``All through the years, you're going to
concerts, meeting composers, but the emphasis is always on the
technical: how to build, how to write, how to come up with new
tuning systems or new ways to structure music using mathematical
principles like algorithms. Now I was searching for an emotional
core.''
</P>
<P>
   He found it through the nurturing of the Hungarian composer
Gyorgy Ligeti, with whom he studied from 1982 to 1984 in Hamburg,
Germany. ``Ligeti was the one who encouraged me to look back to my
roots,'' he said. ``Here you had one of the heavy avant-garde
composers of the 20th century telling me that European contemporary
music was dead and to look back to America.''
</P>
<P>
   Returning to the Midwest for the first time since he had left
for college, to a teaching gig at Oberlin College in Ohio,
Daugherty rekindled his love of car culture and embarked on an
adventure of rediscovery, driving through the back roads of
America, rummaging around book stores and antique markets and
mulling over the tales he pried from strangers who passed his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to spend hours going through outdoor flea markets, with
thousands of people selling knickknacks,'' he said. ``I would
discover one thing, maybe an old postcard, and I'd get the idea for
a piece. It was something that connected with me, like an icon or a
relic from the past. Going through those flea markets was like
going through the Louvre, but instead of Egyptian artifacts you'd
have American artifacts.''
</P>
<P>
   In his studio in Ann Arbor, where he now teaches composition at
the University of Michigan and lives with his wife, Yopie Prins, a
professor of English and comparative literature, and their
11-year-old daughter, Evelyn, named after Daugherty's mother, he
tinkers on his computers far into the night, responding to visual
stimuli scattered across walls and shelves, the fruits of his
never-ending peregrinations.
</P>
<P>
   Daugherty's music, imbued with a wry sense of timing and eerie
references to the past, is a sort of collage, though he loathes the
term (along with ``postmodern'') for its implied sterility and lack
of integrity. A single concept is explored in its most literal
sense; then layer after layer is peeled away, in the manner of an
archaeological exercise, until countless associations have been
examined.
</P>
<P>
   In ``U.F.O.,'' Daugherty envisioned limitless possibilities in
the changing nature of the percussion world. ``If you say, `eight
metal instruments,' and you let the percussionist choose them,'' he
said, ``the piece will always be evolving, because each
percussionist will always come up with new things to play, new
ideas, new sounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by a replica of Glennie's arsenal, he tinkered with a
variety of atmospheric sounds he imagined that his alien muse might
have brought along on her trip to this planet. He imagined other,
less obvious things as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that Leonard Slatkin's parents had played inHollywood
movie scores of the 1950s, and they most certainly played some of
those science-fiction scores. I love that sound of trilling
strings, and I wanted to evoke that.''
</P>
<P>
   For Glennie, the composer's embrace of performance-theater
issues within the framework of symphonic music has long held an
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not at all afraid to display aspects of his life through
music which have been of influence to him,'' she said by e-mail.
``He has a distinct musical voice from which we can always expect
an element of surprise. I have to be a fan of a composer's work in
order to ask them to write a piece for me, as it was in Michael's
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to play a character, and this is a strong element in
the concerto. I am an alien encountering all things `earthy'
through my many `alien' instruments.''
</P>
<P>
   Next month, another of Daugherty's cultural compilations will
begin to take shape when the Detroit Symphony Orchestra, of which
he is composer in residence, gives the premiere of ``Rosa Parks
Boulevard,'' a tribute to the civil-rights legend, and the first
segment of ``Motor City Triptych,'' commissioned for the city's
tricentennial in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
