<HEADLINE>
TREASURIES BOOSTED BY U.S. NOTE AUCTION, DOWNTURN IN STOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Prices of Treasury securities were up sharply
Wednesday, lifted by a successful government note auction and steep
losses in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury sold $8 billion new 10-year notes, an auction
market participants said was in line with expectations. The notes
were awarded at a price to yield 6.475 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In when-issued trading leading up to the sale, the notes were
being offered at a price to yield 6.48 percent, down from 6.52 the
previous day. The actively traded 10-year bond was yielding 6.42
percent Wednesday, down from 6.52 percent Tuesday. Its price, which
moves in the opposite direction, increased 23/32, to 100 18/32.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year Treasury bond was up 26/32, to 101
13/32. The bond's yield fell to 6.15 percent from 6.21 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Rupert, economist at Standard &AMP; Poor's MMS, a market
research and analysis firm, said ``the weakness in equities gave a
boost to Treasuries.''
</P>
<P>
   With most participants anticipating a half-percentage point
tightening next week by the Federal Reserve, Rupert said, the
market would quickly turn its speculation to the June and August
meeting. A tame Consumer Price Index report next Tuesday could
diminish thoughts of a similar increase in June.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Cheung, vice president, Asset Management
Department/Fixed-Income Division of Wilmington Trust in Wilmington,
Del., said the bond market had incorporated an aggressive Fed move
into its rate structure. ``Equities have pretty well passed the
height of earnings releases and are likely to seek a trading range
while waiting for the Fed to hand out its next batch of medicine,''
Cheung said. ``We will just have to wait to see if it is a single
dose or a double shot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
