<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1186 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-BIRDS-HUMANMUSIC-COX     05-10 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIRDS-HUMANMUSIC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wild Georgia
 &HT;    Noteworthy feat: Birds' songs quite sophisticated
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frogs croak. Dogs bark. Wolves howl. But birds sing.
</P>
<P>
   When songbirds chirp, trill and warble, we call it singing.
While some scientists argue whether birds' ``songs'' are true
music, many others believe that studies of songbirds can contribute
to the understanding of the origins of human music and its
evolution. To this end, biologists and musicologists are
collaborating in a relatively new field called biomusicology.
Birds' music, they note, lies very close to counterparts in the
music of people.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, ornithologists have noted birdsongs pitched to the
same musical scales used by people. The wood thrush, a native of
Georgia, can conform to the familiar Western diatonic scale; the
hermit thrush, which winters in Georgia, may sing with the
pentatonic scale of traditional Asian music, according to research
by Luis Baptista of the California Academy of Sciences in San
Francisco. In fact, such musical phenomena as the borrowing of
melodies, singing in duets or duels, and passing down traditions
through families from generation to generation also show up in
birds, Baptista reports.
</P>
<P>
   Some species may even compose in sonata form. Another Georgia
native, the song sparrow, for example, ``belts out one of its
themes, equivalent to a sonata's opening exposition, then fiddles
with it a bit here and there much the same way a non-feathered
composer develops a theme,'' says a report in Science News. ``The
sparrow eventually burbles the original theme again, a version of a
sonata's final recapitulation.''
</P>
<P>
   Spring songs
</P>
<P>
   Ornithologists Georgann Schmalz of Fernbank Science Center and
Emily Jo Williams of the Department of Natural Resources are
leading a series of ``birding boot camps'' around the state this
month to help birders recognize birds by their song alone. The
hard-to-master skill is needed to help conduct a breeding bird
survey in the state this month. Some bird songs and calls, however,
may be easy to remember by using sound-alike phrases of mnemomics
and phonetics. Some examples:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Parula warbler: ``zeeee-up,'' buzzy ascending notes tipping
over at the end.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Common yellowthroat: ``witchety, witchety, witchety.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Prothonotary warbler: ``zweet, zweet, zweet.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Painted bunting: a cheery whistle, no mnemonic.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Yellow-breasted chat: a buzzy buzz, no mnemonic.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Black and white warbler: ``wheezy, wheezy, wheezy,'' sounds
like a squeaky metal wheel.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Yellow warbler: ``sweet, sweet, sweet, I'm so sweet.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tufted titmouse: ``peter, peter, peter.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Robin: ``cheer up, cheerily, cheerily.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  White-throated sparrow: ``poor Sam Peabody, Peabody,
Peabody.''
</P>
<P>
   Field notes
</P>
<P>
   Reports of first-time backyard sightings of rose-breasted
grosbeaks, beautiful songbirds that migrate through Georgia this
time of year, are pouring in.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley McCormack: ``We have lived in our house in Stone
Mountain 25 years. This year we have had rose-breasted grosbeaks
that we have never had before.'' Julie Warner of Gwinnett: ``I
don't know how common they are, but in the 3.5 years I've lived
here, this is the first time I've seen them.'' Linda Lee of
Lilburn: ``Today was the first time I had ever seen a rose-breasted
grosbeak. He was on our platform feeder eating until a blue jay
scared him away.''
</P>
<P>
   In the sky
</P>
<P>
   The moon is in first-quarter phase, so look for it in the south
as it gets dark, says Fernbank astronomer David Dundee. None of the
planets are visible this week because they all appear too close to
the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Seabrook, , is the Atlanta Journal-Consitution writer on
nature and the environment. His column appears weekly. E-mail him
at cseabrook(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
