<HEADLINE>
GYMNASTICS BODY PLANS TOUGHER OLYMPIC SELECTION PROCEDURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ USA Gymnastics will choose its Olympic team more
subjectively than ever this summer to make sure the best athletes
make it to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for us to play by the same rules as the rest of the
world,'' said federation president Bob Colarossi Wednesday after
the selection procedures had been released.
</P>
<P>
   That means the women's committee can choose any six gymnasts,
regardless of the results of the July nationals in St. Louis and
the August trials in Boston. And the men's committee can name
four-time US champion Blaine Wilson even if he misses both
nationals and trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, the team we put on the floor will be the team that
gives the US the best chance to medal at the Olympic Games,'' said
Colarossi. ``End of story. That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other federations such as track and field and swimming,
which pick their Olympic squads at one-shot trials, USA Gymnastics
traditionally has opted for a more flexible process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we're a subjective sport, we're not about the first
person to touch the wall or cross the wire,'' said Colarossi.
</P>
<P>
   Although the top three men (and almost certainly the top three
women) from the combined nationals/trials standings are guaranteed
tickets to Sydney in September, the federation still wants wiggle
room in case a top star can't compete in July or August. And
because international rules allow for one-event performers, USA
Gymnastics may decide to bypass an all-arounder to choose a
specialist who can produce a medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be able to adapt to this, and select a team that
will be competitive,'' said Colarossi.
</P>
<P>
   However, the federation has tightened entry requirements for the
nationals, which count for 40 percent of the score. Except for
members of last year's world team, every gymnast must qualify at
preliminary events. That means members of the 1996 team such as
Shannon Miller and Dominique Moceanu, who've been struggling to
regain gold-medal form after lengthy layoffs, will have to place
well at the US Classic in Tulsa, Okla., in early July to make it to
St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike last time, when Miller and Moceanu were allowed to
use their scores from nationals and skip the trials, gymnasts now
must compete at both events to guarantee spots. The one exception
is Wilson, who missed a world all-around medal by .001 points last
year but is coming off shoulder surgery. If he's injured or ill
this summer, he can petition directly to Olympus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did that for Blaine because of what happened to Dan Hayden
in 1988,'' said Colarossi.
</P>
<P>
   Hayden, clearly the top US male that year, had to compete
injured at the trials and missed making the team, which finished
11th in Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   Though the selection procedures say only that the top three
women will be ``considered'' for guaranteed spots, national team
coordinator Bela Karolyi said it was ``highly, highly, highly
unlikely'' they wouldn't get them.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the men's and women's teams will be chosen by
committee shortly after the final trials events.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not leave that arena without naming the US Olympic
team,'' promised Karolyi.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 1818EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
