<SLUG> BC-MACHINE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE LOVE MACHINE': SEX, LIES AND CYBERSPACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Easily the most unpleasant character in ``The Love Machine,''
Gordon Eriksen's malicious satire of cybersex, is the movie's pushy
prime mover, Becca Campbell (Marlene Forte), a fictional
documentary filmmaker who doesn't know the meaning of the word
boundary. Nosy, bullying, self-righteous and duplicitous, Becca is
so intimidating to the people she interviews in the name of truth
that it's a wonder any of them put up with her for more than five
minutes, let alone come back for more.
</P>
<P>
   Those unlucky people, all connected with New York University,
share something else. They lead secret erotic lives that they
flaunt on personal links connected to a Web site,
The-Love-Machine.com, set up as a prank by a cynical student
operating out of a science lab.
</P>
<P>
   The worst-behaved character is Julio (Gary Perez), a married
professor of Latin American studies who brazenly advertises himself
as a stud and exhibits nude pictures of himself and two dozen of
his student conquests. The most inexplicable behavior belongs to
Akira (Jun Suenaga), a Japanese student whose Web site shows
pictures of him and his gay roommate, Javier (Al Rodriguez),
embracing, even though Akira vehemently denies his homosexuality
when confronted with the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Shino (Tomo Omori) and her boyfriend, Mike (Will Keenan), are
exhibitionists who troll the Internet looking to fill out a menage
a trois. Beverly, a middle-aged librarian, publishes an explicit
diary of her (possibly imaginary) affairs with two much younger
men. Chip (Chip Garner), who is gay and black, is looking for a
boyfriend but has a finicky list of qualifications that practically
ensure his quest will be futile.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Love Machine,'' which opens Thursday, is so well acted
that in certain scenes it could pass as an actual documentary. Its
fatal flaw is not its execution but its premise. The movie begins
with the ludicrous assumption that the cyberspace alter egos of
these characters, most of whom reveal their faces (and a great deal
more), are super-secret identities that bring their owners deep
shame. When Becca first interviews them under false pretenses, they
are unaware that she knows of their alter egos, and every one of
them blithely dismisses the idea of making erotic connections via
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Our intrepid documentarian, however, has not only visited her
subjects' racy Web sites, she has surreptitiously trailed them with
a camera crew to uncover their secret lives. Exuding hostility and
contempt, she bluntly confronts first Julio, who threatens legal
action, and then his wife, Cecilia (Mariana Carreno), with evidence
of Julio's infidelities. She also takes it upon herself to inform
Akira's fiancee, Kyoko (Kayoko Takahashi), of her boyfriend's
homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   The most far-fetched assumption is that a deeply closeted gay
man, terrified of discovery by his strait-laced family, would allow
any compromising pictures of himself to be circulated. In real
life, moreover, people, especially those with exhibitionistic
tendencies, are much more likely to boast about their sexual
adventures in cyberspace than to try to conceal them. ``The Love
Machine'' is a nasty (if titillating) little film whose notions
about cybersex, shame and today's erotic climate are way off base.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE LOVE MACHINE'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Gordon Eriksen; director of photography,
Hiro Wakiya; edited by Michael J. Dominico; art direction, Carveth
Martin; produced by Steven G. Menkin; a Crystal Pictures
presentation of an Olympia Pictures production.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Marlene Forte (Becca), Gary Perez (Julio), Tomo Omori
(Shino), Jun Suenaga (Akira), Elizabeth Wunsch (Beverly), Chip
Garner (Chip), John Chidiac (Marcus), Will Keenan (Mike), Mariana
Carreno (Cecilia), Kayoko Takahashi (Kyoko) and Al Rodriguez
(Javier).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 83 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This film is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
