<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1190 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT11-COX     05-10 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT CRAFTS ITS OWN ANTITRUST REMEDY
 &HT;    680&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Responding to a federal judge's order, Microsoft
Corp. on Wednesday rejected calls for a breakup and instead offered
to impose curbs on its business practices that it claimed ``fully
redresses the antitrust violations found by the court.''
</P>
<P>
   In its filing, announced after the close of the major financial
markets, Microsoft called on U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson to summarily dismiss a plan crafted by the Justice
Department and 17 states.
</P>
<P>
   That April 28 proposal would cleave the software giant into two
firms. One would market Windows operating system used by nearly 90
percent of personal computers, while the other would sell
applications products, such as Word and Internet Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   But if the judge wants to weigh the government's breakup
proposal, then Microsoft said it would need six more months to
prepare its defense, to be followed by ``a full trial on relief''
to begin Dec. 2 in Jackson's courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   At a cable industry convention earlier Wednesday in New Orleans,
Microsoft chief executive officer Steve Ballmer declared, ``Our
company will not be broken up. It will not happen.''
</P>
<P>
   In offering its own remedies to correct what Jackson found last
month to be grossly illegal conduct, Microsoft said it was willing
to stop displaying the Internet Explorer browser icon on the
Windows desktop.
</P>
<P>
   The company would also would let computer makers prominently
feature any other software, including products from Microsoft
rivals, on the desktop.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an enormous amount of flexibility (for computer
makers) and a very large concession by Microsoft,'' Bill Neukom,
Microsoft's top lawyer, said in a conference call with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft proposed a sliding schedule of further court dates,
each one linked to how far Jackson was willing to go in dealing
with the government's proposed remedies.
</P>
<P>
   The company argued that the ``need for deliberate procedures is
especially strong because much of the intellectual property the
government seeks to confiscate relates to products and
technologies, such as Windows 2000, that were not even mentioned at
trial.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Court intends to consider such draconian relief,
Microsoft is entitled to address these new issues fully and
deliberately,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   Under a court-imposed timetable, a reply from the government is
due May 17. Jackson will hold an initial remedy hearing May 24.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's proposals were part of a two-pronged legal strategy
by Microsoft. On the one hand, the company offers a remedy plan
that deals with the court's finding that it broke the law, while on
the other hand preparing a legal appeal that claims it did nothing
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Neukom said that even if Jackson adopted the Microsoft plan to
the letter and rejected all the government's proposals for both
interim and long-term relief, the company would still ``consider''
filing an appeal to stay his order.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has invited the court to destroy or hobble an
American company that is a model of success in the high technology
arena, and to do so explicitly to reshape the single most
productive and envied industry in the United States,'' the six-part
Microsoft filing said.
</P>
<P>
   In a landmark antitrust ruling issued April 3 after months of
settlement talks collapsed, Jackson held that Microsoft had
illegally abused its monopoly powers in ways that harmed consumers
and throttled its competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said that ``despite the strongly disapproving language
used by the court in certain portions of its findings of fact and
conclusions of law, the antitrust violations actually found by the
court are not sufficiently broad to warrant the drastic relief
requested by the government.''
</P>
<P>
   It added, ``In stark contrast to the relief sought in its
complaint, the government seeks to rip apart the company that until
recently had the largest market capitalization in the world _ an
extreme remedy not even (originally) hinted at. ... The law and the
facts do not support such a radical step.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The formula that Microsoft submitted to Jackson on Wednesday
went a good deal further than a negotiated consent decree
settlement that would have been acceptable to the Justice
Department officials two years ago, on the weekend before the
government filed its landmark suit. Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates
rejected that deal.
</P>
<P>
   But the new plan did not go as far as its final offer in
settlement talks that failed shortly before Jackson issued his
decision.
</P>
<P>
   The company's offer sounds similar to its 1995 consent
agreement, said Ken Wasch, president of the Software and
Information Industry Association. The Justice Department launched
the current antitrust case after claiming Microsoft violated that
accord.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft is trying to turn back the clock to 1995 and say,
'OK, we can live with the consent agreement,' `` said Wasch, who
supports a breakup. ``It's the antitrust equivalent of 'no TV for a
week.' ``
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: microsoft.com/presspass/trial/
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
