<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1193 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-EXAMINER-SALE-1STLD-W     05-10 1356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXAMINER-SALE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     EX-JUDGE APPOINTED TO REVIEW SAN FRANCISCO EXAMINER'S EDITORIAL
INTEGRITY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: Updates and edits throughout.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SETH ROSENFELD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Hearst Corp. appointed a former federal
judge Wednesday to review the editorial policies of The San
Francisco Examiner as a result of testimony by the paper's former
publisher that he offered Mayor Willie Brown favorable editorial
treatment in exchange for the mayor's support of Hearst's plan to
buy the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Charles B. Renfrew of San Francisco will lead the `` internal
review'' and will set the scope and duration of the inquiry, Hearst
spokeswoman Debra Shriver said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Renfrew was a U.S. District judge in Northern California from
1972 to 1980. From 1980 to 1981 he served as deputy U.S. attorney
general. In 1983, he became a vice president of Chevron Corp. in
charge of legal affairs, and in 1984 he became a Chevron director.
</P>
<P>
   His current law practice focuses on alternative dispute
resolution and internal corporate investigations, Hearst said.
</P>
<P>
   During testimony last week, Timothy O. White said he offered the
deal to the mayor on Aug. 30. White later disavowed the testimony
in a statement Hearst sent to the media.
</P>
<P>
   Examiner Executive Editor Phil Bronstein, who said he was at the
meeting between White and Brown, said White made no such offer, and
denied that the newspaper's opinion pages were improperly slanted
in Brown's favor.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst suspended White after his testimony, and appointed George
Irish, president of Hearst newspapers, as acting publisher of The
Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   White's testimony came during a trial in federal court to decide
whether Hearst can buy the Chronicle for $660 million and pay a
local publisher to take the Examiner off its hands. Former mayoral
candidate Clint Reilly is trying to persuade a judge to block the
Chronicle purchase as a violation of antitrust law.
</P>
<P>
   Irish, responding to a petition signed by 80 Chronicle employees
expressing ethical concerns over White's testimony, said in a
letter Tuesday, ``Unequivocally, any practices that compromise
editorial independence or integrity will not be tolerated in the
newsrooms of any of our newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said Hearst valued and respected White.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was our confidence in his abilities that caused us to
promote him to the position of publisher and editor of the San
Francisco Examiner and we regret deeply the circumstance in which
he and we find ourselves,'' the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   It will be up to Renfrew to review ``the correctness of White's
statements,'' it added.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be unlimited access to any and all employees and
any and all documents,'' James Asher, the chief legal officer for
development of the Hearst Corp., told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Renfrew, 71, a graduate of Princeton University and the
University of Michigan Law School, spent almost two decades as an
associate and partner at the Pillsbury, Madison &AMP; Sutro law firm in
San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   A Detroit native, he served in the Navy from 1946 to 1948 and in
the U.S. Army in 1952 and 1953.
</P>
<P>
   He was nominated to the federal bench by Republican President
Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   At Chevron, he was involved in negotiations over a $77 million
settlement with four states, California, Washington, Oregon and
Arizona, in a lawsuit accusing Chevron, Mobil Corp. and Shell Oil
Corp. of gasoline price-fixing.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993 he joined the San Francisco office of the law firm of
LeBoeuf, Lamb, Leiby &AMP; MacRae, concentrating on commercial
litigation as well as alternative dispute resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Renfrew has also served as panelist in disputes over legal fees
in major court cases. He is a member of an arbitration panel
appointed to decide how much to pay the lawyers who represented 46
states in a $206 billion settlement with the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the trial on Reilly's suit continued Wednesday before
U.S. District Judge Vaughn R. Walker.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly, who unsuccessfully bid for The Examiner, contends
Hearst's proposed purchase of the Chronicle will result in an
illegal monopoly in which Hearst owns the only major metropolitan
daily newspaper in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly claims Hearst's plan to sell The Examiner to local
publisher Ted Fang and his family, and to give them a subsidy of up
to $66 million over three years, is a sham meant to facilitate
Hearst's purchase of the Chronicle. He contends the subsidy is
insufficient to run a viable competitor to Hearst's Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst disputes Reilly's contentions. The Fangs also deny their
deal with Hearst is a sham. They have said their Examiner would
compete with Hearst's Chronicle for readers and advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's testimony focused on one of Reilly's newspaper
consultants, Michael Weaver. Weaver testified that The Examiner
would lose $20 million to $50 million a year if it did not have its
profit-sharing agreement with the larger Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly had been expected to testify Wednesday as a key witness,
but his lawyer, Joseph M. Alioto, said he would not call his client
to the stand.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Reilly consultant J. Scott Schmidt, a former
president of Thomson Newspapers West, which owned several daily and
weekly papers in California, testified that Hearst's subsidy was
not enough to support a ``worthy competitor'' to the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt said it would take a subsidy of at least $50 million a
year for three to five years. And, he testified, the Fangs would
have to boost The Examiner's current daily circulation of 108,968
to about 300,000 to attract enough advertising to finance a
competitive paper. The Chronicle's circulation is 465,535.
</P>
<P>
   In his bid for The Examiner, Reilly sought a $200 million
subsidy from Hearst over six years, according to court documents.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination by Christopher Hockett, an attorney for
the Fangs, Schmidt acknowledged that he had no information about
the Fangs' plans for publishing The Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   He also admitted making math errors that resulted in his
over-estimating some annual costs by $28 million of publishing The
Examiner, though he said he stood by his overall conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto has said he may call Irish to testify about what he knew
of White's talks with Brown.
</P>
<P>
   White sent Irish two e-mails about conversations he'd had with
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 30, 1999, White said he and Bronstein had had lunch with
Brown that day, and, ``I asked Willie how I was going to justify to
my superiors in New York wanting to support him and cooperate with
him when he was seeming to go out of his way to make our lives
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown was opposing Hearst's initial plan to buy the Chronicle
and close The Examiner if no buyer for it could be found.
</P>
<P>
   In court on May 1, Alioto asked White, ``Is it not correct that
you were in fact intending to convey to Mayor Brown that his
support for Hearst's proposed acquisition of the Chronicle would
result in more favorable treatment for him in The Examiner?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' White replied, adding, ``That wouldn't affect the
journalism side. It would affect the editorial side.''
</P>
<P>
   White later said he was tired and confused by Alioto's
questioning.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Bennack, Hearst's president, also is expected to testify
at some point in the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1965, The Examiner and the Chronicle have had a joint
operating agreement to share combined revenue and costs of
printing, advertising and circulation. They split the remainder,
with each paying the costs of its independent editorial staffs.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was set to expire in 2005, but Chronicle
Publishing Co. decided to sell the Chronicle to Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   The trial on Reilly's suit is the nation's first to consider
whether early termination of a joint operating agreement violates
the 1970 Newspaper Preservation Act, which permits the agreements
as exemptions to antitrust laws. The act was meant to keep alive
newspapers that might otherwise fail, so communities could benefit
from multiple editorial voices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
