<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1194 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BROWN-DANCE-REVIEW-AR     05-10 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-DANCE-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT TAKES TWO TO JITTERBUG, SOMETIMES MORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK_ Trisha Brown's new jazz-inspired dance piece is a
beauty, a perfect blend of the vernacular and the abstract. The
work, ``Rapture to Leon James,'' received its New York premiere on
Tuesday night when the Trisha Brown Dance Company opened its second
and final week at the Joyce Theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canto/Pianto,'' a revised suite of dances from Brown's staging
of the Monteverdi opera ``Orfeo,'' was also seen on a program that
included ``Locus,'' a solo, and ``For M.G.: The Movie,'' an oddly
private tribute by Brown to Michel Guy, who died in 1990; he
admired her work before and after he was France's culture minister.
The last two pieces exhibit a Brown trademark: too many ideas
behind each dance that the choreographer does not share with the
audience. A program note can provide a clue, but more often than
not the deliberately illogical can look merely arbitrary. ``For
M.G'' is hard going, but in ``Locus'' Brown seduces the viewer with
the quality of her performance.
</P>
<P>
   In this solo in silence, the movement (a long phrase including a
little twist of the torso, a hand lifting a foot, a forward bend
from the waist toward invisible corners) is less important than its
contrast between the fluid and the angular. One doesn't really have
to know that Brown once saw herself inside an imaginary cube and
that the locus of the title refers to more than one specific point
within that cube.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly one doesn't have to worry about concepts in ``Rapture
to Leon James,'' in which Brown was inspired by a film featuring
James, who was a star of the Lindy Hoppers at the Savoy Hotel in
Harlem and who died in 1970 It is not that ideas, especially about
structure or distillation of social dances, are absent. It is that
the theatricality of a polished image takes over, making the
choreography accessible on several planes.
</P>
<P>
   The piece becomes an ode to jazz as music, dance and social
activity. The fine score by Dave Douglas complements the
choreography, too contemporary to turn to a literal interpretation
of swing music. Terry Winters' wonderful set, a tower of golden
disks, recalls cymbals or records. The dancing refers to
jitterbugging, the Charleston and lines in which Lindy Hoppers
would follow a leader. Yet like the score and the decor, the
dancing evokes the real thing without depicting it.
</P>
<P>
   Especially startling and effective is the way Brown adapts her
usual high-flying system of partnering to an image of swing
dancing. Kathleen Fisher and Keith Thompson's duet may recall
jitterbuggers' tosses and throws. Yet all the shapes are geometric
(a woman wrapped around a man's body with legs held out in V
formation). Mondrian's ``Broadway Boogie Woogie'' comes to mind.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Tipton has outdone herself with the lighting, changing
the backdrop's colors. Jazz is hot or cool, and Tipton's palette
from fuchsia to turquoise creates the aura of shifting energy that
brings into relief the gray-white-black tones of the costumes. The
whole work gleams.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's brilliant conceit is that it takes two to jitterbug, and
the choreography is built upon pairs of dancers who rarely touch.
Two women, Brandi Norton and Fisher, set the pace, swiveling
torsos, swinging arms and extending legs. They dance in unison but
are apart, down to every waddle and pelvic thrust impelled by the
percussion.
</P>
<P>
   The melody on the brass instruments expands the dance. Thompson
and Stacy Matthew Spence shadowbox wittily across the stage, and
Thompson is superb when he leads a group: the image is of
improvisation, real or simulated. ``Rapture'' is about a community,
but the dancers, including Mariah Maloney, Seth Parker, Todd Stone,
Katrina Thompson and Abigail Yager, stand out as spirited
individuals. ``Rapture'' has legs.
</P>
<P>
   The music and choreography were commissioned by the American
Dance Festival and the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing
Arts through their Doris Duke Awards for Dance and Jazz Music
Collaborations.
</P>
<P>
   The music was played live by Douglas, on trumpet, and his
musicians: Greg Tardy, tenor saxophonist; Greg Cohen, bassist; and
Susie Ibarra, percussionist.
</P>
<P>
   As for ``Canto/Pianto,'' its four sections (``The Wedding,''
``The Message,'' ``Journey to the Underworld,'' ``The Death of
Orfeo'') offer a compressed version of the dramatic action that
Brown directed in Monteverdi's opera. The full production was seen
at the Brooklyn Academy of Music last year, but this is the first
time the suite of dances from the opera has been performed in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Although the choreography is not literal, what looks like pure
movement is often combined with heightened gesture. At times a
dancer substituting for a singer mouths the words heard on a
recording. The group sections focus on jumbles of dancers who reel
off lines in cumulative patterns. Even more effective is the use of
frozen tension, as in the underworld, symbolized by four men in
slow motion. They line up, forming a wall with Fisher, standing in
beautiful stillness to one side.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
