<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-JESUS-NYTR </SLUG>
  
 CBS's `JESUS' MINISERIES SHOULD APPEAL TO ALL  
 By JAY HANDELMAN   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Religion and television often are awkward companions, either
piously observant or discomfortingly distant in an effort to avoid
offending anyone.
</P>
<P>
   But they fit well together in CBS' ``Jesus,'' a four-hour
miniseries that airs at 9 p.m. Sunday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Those who are followers of Jesus' teachings will find much to
admire and those who come from other religious, or non-religious
backgrounds will find a fascinating story that is both involving
and educational.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Sisto, a rising young actor best known for the films
``Clueless'' and ``White Squall'' and last season's ``The '60s,''
is compelling as Jesus, who carries himself with a sense of honor,
but also a touch of cockiness, as if he thrives on the awe he
inspires with his ``miracles,'' which his performance seems to
suggest are nothing but magic tricks to get people to pay attention
to him.
</P>
<P>
   The film, which was shot primarily in Morocco and partly in
Malta, has a lush look, giving the miniseries a sense of quality
and importance.
</P>
<P>
   The story begins in a slightly fragmented style with the death
of Joseph, which prompts flashbacks to playful times as Mary and
Joseph deal with the realization of their son's birth. But Jesus
never loses his playful attitude, flirting with Mary of Bethany and
dancing at celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   The film is filled with dramatic moments, heightened to just the
right level by Roger Young and composer Patrick Williams. That's
never more true than in a near-climatic scene between Jesus and
Satan, played with power and a persuasive argumentative style by
Jeroen Krabbe.
</P>
<P>
   Young has put together a superb cast that includes Jacqueline
Bisset as a radiant and supportive Mary, Gary Oldman as the Roman
governor Pontius Pilate, Christian Kohlund as the pious-but-weak
religious leader Caiaphas, and particularly G.W. Bailey in the
fictional role of Livio, a conniving adviser and informant to
Pilate.
</P>
<P>
   In a case where other roles can overwhelm an actor, it is
difficult to watch ``Will &AMP; Grace'' star Debra Messing as Mary
Magdalene without expecting a punch line, but she does convey some
tenderness. And Armin Mueller-Stahl is all but wasted in the brief
role of Joseph.
</P>
<P>
   The film, utilizing a team of historical and biblical advisers,
presents its story in a way that should interest some and move
other viewers, without offending anyone, aside from those with the
strictest or most focused interpretations of the Bible. Like ``The
Ten Commandments,'' this ``Jesus'' could become a perennial
presence on television.
</P>
<P>
   (The Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla., is a member of The New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 1827EDT &QL; 
