A1199 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-UNILEVER-EARNINGS-NYT     05-10 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNILEVER-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNILEVER'S FIRST QUARTER PROFITS RISE 12 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Unilever, the food-to-detergents consumer goods giant
that is trying to buy Bestfoods for $18.3 billion, said Wednesday
that its first-quarter operating profit rose 12 percent in what the
company depicted as a first victory in an ambitious program to cut
costs.
</P>
<P>
   The stock price of Unilever, a British-Dutch company based in
London and Rotterdam, had fallen sharply when the bid was announced
on May 3. It strengthened Wednesday on the earnings news, with the
British shares closing up 5.3 percent at 4.0375 pounds, or $6.12,
and the Dutch shares up 7.2 percent at 52.35 euros, or $48.09.
</P>
<P>
   Bestfoods, of Englewood Cliffs, N.J., has rejected the Unilever
bid and is said by analysts to be seeking a higher offer than
Unilever's $66 a share.
</P>
<P>
   The improvement in Unilever's stock price does not directly
affect the all-cash bid for Bestfoods, the parent company of
supermarket brands that include Knorr soups, Hellman's mayonnaise
and Dove soap. But Unilever's earnings performance offered what
analysts said was evidence that a $5 billion, five-year program
announced in February is showing results.
</P>
<P>
   The cost-cutting measures include a plan to winnow Unilever's
1,600 brands to 400, close 100 factories and reduce the global work
force of 250,000 by 10 percent. Wednesday's figures, said David
Lang, an analyst at Investec Henderson Crosthwaite, ``reflect the
success they are having in focusing on major brands.''
</P>
<P>
   The increase in profit, which surpassed analysts' expectations,
came without a strong gain in sales, indicating the effects of cost
cutting. The company said profit from operations rose to 716
million euros, or $659 million, compared with 640 million euros in
the period a year earlier. The figures were based on exchange rates
in the first quarter, lifted in part by the euro's weakness against
the dollar. Dollar sales in the United States account for about
one-fifth of Unilever's revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Unilever's rationale in bidding for Bestfoods is to
strengthen its position in both the United States and in emerging
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Even without Bestfoods, Unilever has been pursuing an aggressive
strategy of acquisitions, buying Ben &AMP; Jerry's for $326 million and
Slim-Fast for $2.6 billion last month as part of what it says is an
effort to concentrate on high-growth top brands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our strategy of focusing resources on leading brands is on
track,'' the company's co-chairmen, Antony Burgmans and Niall
Fitzgerald, said in a statement. ``We are managing the migration to
a faster-growth portfolio without endangering our profitability.''
</P>
<P>
   They made no direct reference to the Bestfoods bid, which, a
company spokesman said, ``seems to be at a bit of an impasse.'' But
in a presentation to analysts, Unilever said it thought it had
offered a fair price, and a company spokesman said Unilever
believed there was a ``substantial role'' for Bestfoods managers in
a combined company.
</P>
<P>
   In describing the benefits of the proposed deal, the company
said the combination was like ``marrying the girl next door.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's figures showed Unilever's cost cutting to be
producing more notable financial results than similar measures at
the rival Procter &AMP; Gamble, which last month reported its first
drop in quarterly earnings in nine years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
