<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Thursday, May 10 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Microsoft Corp. delivered its
formal response in federal court to the remedy proposal from the
Justice Department and 17 states asking that the company be broken
into two parts. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   NY-GIULIANI-WIFE (New York) _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani announced
Wednesday that he was separating from his wife, Donna Hanover. He
said that as he battles prostate cancer he will need Judith Nathan,
the woman he describes as a ``very good'' friend, ``more now than
maybe I did before.'' Afterward, Hanover summoned reporters and
said the marriage had been strained for years, and alluded to an
earlier relationship that the mayor had with an unnamed staff
member. (Summary from wires) By Elizabeth Bumiller.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT11.
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE-U.N. (United Nations) _ With its political options
all but exhausted, the United Nations on Wednesday ordered its
peacekeeping troops in Sierra Leone to take up defensive positions
and prepare for a pitched battle against the rebel fighters
advancing toward the capital, Freetown. ``We'll do what we have to
do to defend ourselves and the government,'' the U.N. spokesman,
Fred Eckhard, said. ``We hope it won't come to a pitched battle,
but we are preparing for one.'' By Christopher S. Wren.
</P>
<P>
   (Early version has moved)
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ The federal government on
Wednesday settled a two-year antitrust case against the nation's
five largest music companies, which officials said uncovered
illegal marketing agreements that significantly inflated the prices
of compact discs, resulting in overcharges to consumers of an
estimated $500 million over the last four years. By Stephen
Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ARMS (Beijing) _ China's chief arms negotiator said
Wednesday that an American proposal to build an anti-missile
defensive shield posed an unacceptable threat to China's security
and could force it to significantly expand its own nuclear forces
in response. The Chinese find it hard to believe American claims
that the proposed ``national missile defense'' is only intended to
counter threats from small rogue states like North Korea, said the
official, Sha Zukang, in an interview. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   ILOVEYOU-VIRUS (Manila, Philippines) _ Officials investigating a
malicious program that disrupted computer systems worldwide said
Wednesday that they were looking for a computer student who
recently wrote a thesis proposal for a program with similar
elements. The student, who appears to have gone into hiding, is
Onel de Guzman, 23, who lived in the same apartment in Manila as a
man and a woman named on Monday as suspects in the case. When de
Guzman presented his proposal in February, a thesis reviewer at his
computer college rejected it, noting: ``This is illegal'' and ``We
do not produce burglars.'' By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   (Early version has moved)
</P>
