 &HT;    HEADLINE HERE IN ALL CAPS(a) 
 &HT;    (RETRANSMITTING FOR THOSE WHO MAY HAVE MISSED ITDuplication
warning: MOVING IN ``E'' and ``L'' ategories.) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are reviews of a Website and some current magazines:
</P>
<P>
   WEBSITE
</P>
<P>
   BIRDWatcher Report
</P>
<P>
   http://www.phxskyharbor.com/skyharbr/ava_enth/birdwatcher.html
</P>
<P>
   If you love to fly or just like to watch the planes, the
Birdwatcher Report is for you.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Jones, an aviation enthusiast who works for the city
Aviation Department, compiles the monthly report.
</P>
<P>
   Jones spends his spare time watching and photographing planes
that fly in and out of Phoenix Sky Harbor International Airport. He
researches the aircraft, and then writes the Birdwatcher report for
the Aviation Department newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   This month's issue include a report on the plane that brought
former Phoenix Suns guard Dan Majerle to the Valley as a member of
the Miami Heat (a former Malaysian Air System Boeing 727-212.)
</P>
<P>
   There are also photos of different planes at satellite airports
around the Valley, from a Chinese-built copy of a MiG trainer at
Deer Valley Airport to a ``forlorn DC-7'' sitting at Phoenix
Goodyear.
</P>
<P>
   The site is linked off the main Sky Harbor page
(http://www.phxskyharbor.com/skyharbr/index.html), which has plenty
more information about the airport.
</P>
<P>
   To send Jones a message, e-mail him at JetblastAZ(a)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   MAGAZINE REVIEWS:
</P>
<P>
   ``AUDOBON''
</P>
<P>
   We always thought the skull-and-crossbones label was enough, but
that was before we read (beginitalic)Audubon(enditalic), which has
learned that certain pesticides can be harmful if swallowed.
Cheerfully titled ``The Killer in Your Yard,'' the article offer
alternatives to soaking you lawn in DDT. There is a Big Stupid
Chart that looks toxic itself. After all, it is painted silver.
There is a well-done piece on new diseases that are cropping up in
the ocean, infecting coral reefs, seals, turtles, dolphins and many
other aquatic creatures. Experts believe that the combination of
pollution and global warming are tipping the scales in favor of
``underwater killers'' - bacteria, viruses, parasites and toxic
algae. Depressing, but informative. To lighten your spirits, the
magazine offers a guide to ``weekends in wilderness - pretty places
you can visit that are only a short drive from the city.'' Of
course, to Audubon, a short drive is like four hours. So fill 'er
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``GEORGE''
</P>
<P>
   If you stopped looking at this magazine somewhere along the way,
give it a second chance this month. It's been redesigned, and this
is the first issue to bear the stamp of its new editor, Frank
Lalli. It also comes out firing, with a fascinating excerpt from
the autobiography of feminist Betty Friedan, who reveals that her
husband physically abused her. The magazine, which has separate
covers for newsstand and subscriber sales, leads with a story about
Elian Gonzalez, and though you might be sick of that cute little
Cuban boy, this story actually tells the tale of three people who
survived the shipwreck and 11 others who died. My favorite article
is a piece by Jon Stewart, host of (beginitalic)The Daily
Show(enditalic), who is quietly becoming the funniest man on
television. Who else could get away with having Bob Dole as a
sideman?
</P>
<P>
   ``NEW YORKER''
</P>
<P>
   Offers some interesting slice-of-life features on jobs, all told
in the first person. One is the tale of a street vendor who sells
coffee and doughnuts off a cart in lower Manhattan. He hits the
street at 5 a.m. and has to deal with hostile yuppies all day long.
``The worst thing is the customers, almost all of whom are
appallingly hateful, horrible people.''' Hmmm. In New York? Naaa.
Another chronicles the exploits of a basketball coach at a Catholic
school who admits he breaks all sorts of rules recruiting players
and everyone looks the other way. (The school is not named). ``It's
what you have to do to win,'' he explains. Another longer article
follows a car salesman from his first day to his first big sale. In
between, there's some pretty funny stuff, including the inside
chitchat between the sales people. In the end, he ends up -
surprise! - disillusioned and bitter. You'd think a story like that
would have a happy ending, like ``Forrest Gump.''
</P>
<P>
   ``PRIORITIES''
</P>
<P>
   Provides your daily dose of affirmation. To buy a magazine that
is subtitled ``The Journal of Professional and Personal Success,''
you just have to be something special. They offer a lightweight
feature on former Phoenix Suns Coach Danny Ainge, who gave up one
of the glitziest jobs in the world to spend time with his family.
Oh yeah, and travel around and broadcast games for TNT. Also
features a cover story on uber-director Steven Spielberg, which
apparently was written without actually talking to him. There are
some canned quotes from press releases, and an interview with
Spielberg's wife, actress Kate Capshaw, but no close encounters
with his E.T.-ness. They do, however, have a nice publicity still
of Spielberg sitting next to a dinosaur foot. In the self-help
category, there is a piece on how to survive a downsizing, and
another on how to work at your computer without contracting the
dreaded repetitive-stress injury. By the way, who took my chair?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 1849EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
