<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1230 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-ELIAN-KIDS-COX     05-10 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-KIDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Youngsters show little grasp of issues facing Cuban boy
 &HT;    By Mark Bixler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Three grown men in long black robes will rely on their
collective legal wisdom to decide whether a 6-year-old boy can ask
for political asylum.
</P>
<P>
   For what it matters, most kids that age in metro Atlanta don't
know what political asylum is.
</P>
<P>
   They can't even spell it.
</P>
<P>
   The topic comes up because the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals in
downtown Atlanta is to hear argument today in the case of Elian
Gonzalez, the 6-year-old whose mom drowned while trying to bring
him here from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Fishermen found Elian on an inner tube in the ocean last fall.
His dad wants to take Elian back to Cuba, but the boy applied for
political asylum while living with relatives in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   First-graders at Holy Innocents' Episcopal School in Sandy
Springs have heard about the case on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``A fisherman found him,'' one boy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No! It was a dolphin!'' another said.
</P>
<P>
   Since Elian is a first-grader just like them, and since he
signed an eight-page application for asylum that comes with 12
pages of instructions, it seemed natural to ask them if they know
what ``political asylum'' means.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's somebody being nice to somebody,'' said Mitchell
Tucker, 7, as he crumpled and uncrumpled a pale white Dixie cup
with a design of light pink and yellow flowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it stealing?'' one asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talking?'' asked another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I forget what political means,'' said Christine Georgakokos,
7.
</P>
<P>
   Megan Ernst, a girl with short, dark hair and round glasses,
shot her right hand up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's being nice to somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmm.
</P>
<P>
   ``These questions are, like, for high schoolers,'' Megan said,
staring down at the grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask me a sports question,'' Mitchell said, still crumpling his
Dixie cup.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of his classmates sat under a tree near the playground
Tuesday afternoon to answer tough questions about refugees and
asylum and persecution. They snapped twigs and picked one blade of
grass after another.
</P>
<P>
   First-grader Charlie Stroman craned his neck toward the
playground while the boy beside him, Addison Baitcher, tried to
crack the asylum riddle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm missing art,'' Charlie said.
</P>
<P>
   Seconds passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my God!'' Charlie said. ``We're missing art for sure!''
</P>
<P>
   The federal government gives asylum to people fleeing
persecution suffered because of their race, religion, nationality,
membership in a social group or public opinion. So what does
persecution mean?
</P>
<P>
   ``They're like punching you and stuff and they take them to jail
and put them in the electric chair,'' Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ooo! I know! I know!'' Charlie said. ``I'm serious!''
</P>
<P>
   It's kind of like going to jail, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Six hours later and 45 miles away, the youngsters on the White
Sox T-ball team of the McDonough Youth Association wrestled
uneasily with the questions and arrived at similarly vague
conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Brett McDevitt, a 5-year-old who would rather have been on the
swing set, answered questions patiently in dusty cleats, a white
uniform with black pinstripes and an oversized black baseball cap
that said ``Sox'' just like the ones in the Major Leagues. When
asked to define political asylum, he volunteered a half-hearted
response.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leaf?''
</P>
<P>
   His mom, Bonnie McDevitt, said Brett can make decisions about
what to order in a restaurant _ it's usually a toss-up between a
hot dog or chicken _ but not much else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they act on impulse,'' she said of kids his age.
</P>
<P>
   Brett crossed his arms across his chest and narrowed his eyes
when asked a typical question _ Question 3 of Part D _ of Form
I-589, the Application for Asylum and for Withholding of Removal,
the very same form that Elian signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you, your spouse, your child(ren) or your parents ever
filed for, been processed for or been granted or denied refugee
status or asylum by any other country?''
</P>
<P>
   Brett didn't understand the question, but said an older kid
might.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Thomas Lavergne, a baseball player who was at George C.
Alexander Memorial Park on Tuesday evening and who, at 9, is a full
three years older than Elian. Did he know what the government was
asking in Question 3 of Part D?
</P>
<P>
   ``How my family is run?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas on political asylum:
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never heard of that word.''
</P>
<P>
   On the meaning of persecution:
</P>
<P>
   ``It just flew out of my head.''
</P>
<P>
   One 6-year-old at the park thought Cuba was ``a kind of musical
instrument.'' Another 6-year-old, Matthew Davis, thought the name
``Elian Gonzalez'' sounded familiar.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's close to Speedy Gonzalez,'' he said, chomping bubble
gum before a game against the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Most in children were eager to please when asked to spell
``asylum.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I-C-L-M-E,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A-S-I-G-H-T-H-E-M,'' said Ben Hart, 6.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Rodden-Bayo, an 8-year-old whose mom came here from Cuba
when she was 2, came a little closer when he spelled ``asylum'' as
``A-S-C-L-I-M-E.'' He said he's heard the words ``political
asylum'' and ``persecution'' on television but does not know
exactly what they mean.
</P>
<P>
   He knows who Elian Gonzalez is, though, and he thinks the
government should let him stay because Cuba is a dangerous place
with an awful human rights record.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better in the United States than it is in Cuba,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   His mom, Lourdes Bayo, said she thinks her son was ``mature
enough'' at age 6 ``to know where he wanted to live.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Children might not understand'' legal terms like asylum or
persecution, she said, ``but they understand how they feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the big issue here is that the media is making it seem
like children cannot make their own decision,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kids do not make the decisions in Justin Ray's house. He's a shy
5-year-old who was at the park in McDonough to watch his brother
Cordero play first base for the White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes as he spoke, Justin stuck the index finger of his
right hand in his mouth. Alternately, he would raise up both arms
and tug his ears up to look like Dr. Spock.
</P>
<P>
   Justin said he likes green beans, mashed potatoes and fried
chicken but does not choose what or when to eat. He said only kids
who are 10 years old can make those kinds of decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe they have to be 25.
</P>
<P>
   Or 40.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
