<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-KIDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Youngsters show little grasp of issues facing Cuban boy
 &HT;    By Mark Bixler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Three grown men in long black robes will rely on their
collective legal wisdom to decide whether a 6-year-old boy can ask
for political asylum.
</P>
<P>
   For what it matters, most kids that age in metro Atlanta don't
know what political asylum is.
</P>
<P>
   They can't even spell it.
</P>
<P>
   The topic comes up because the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals in
downtown Atlanta is to hear argument today in the case of Elian
Gonzalez, the 6-year-old whose mom drowned while trying to bring
him here from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Fishermen found Elian on an inner tube in the ocean last fall.
His dad wants to take Elian back to Cuba, but the boy applied for
political asylum while living with relatives in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   First-graders at Holy Innocents' Episcopal School in Sandy
Springs have heard about the case on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``A fisherman found him,'' one boy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No! It was a dolphin!'' another said.
</P>
<P>
   Since Elian is a first-grader just like them, and since he
signed an eight-page application for asylum that comes with 12
pages of instructions, it seemed natural to ask them if they know
what ``political asylum'' means.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's somebody being nice to somebody,'' said Mitchell
Tucker, 7, as he crumpled and uncrumpled a pale white Dixie cup
with a design of light pink and yellow flowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it stealing?'' one asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talking?'' asked another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I forget what political means,'' said Christine Georgakokos,
7.
</P>
<P>
   Megan Ernst, a girl with short, dark hair and round glasses,
shot her right hand up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's being nice to somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmm.
</P>
<P>
   ``These questions are, like, for high schoolers,'' Megan said,
staring down at the grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask me a sports question,'' Mitchell said, still crumpling his
Dixie cup.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of his classmates sat under a tree near the playground
Tuesday afternoon to answer tough questions about refugees and
asylum and persecution. They snapped twigs and picked one blade of
grass after another.
</P>
<P>
   First-grader Charlie Stroman craned his neck toward the
playground while the boy beside him, Addison Baitcher, tried to
