<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1232 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-BBN-ROCKER-HNS &LR;      05-10 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROCKER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ATLANTA FANS SHOW WHAT REALLY MATTERS TO THEM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEVE CAMPBELL   
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They finally got around to booing John Rocker in Atlanta the
other night.
</P>
<P>
   Not because Rocker's sentiments had just been translated from
Der Fuhrer's German to the King's English.
</P>
<P>
   Not because Atlanta Braves fans came down with a case of
collective conscience.
</P>
<P>
   Not because the citizens of Atlanta decided that _ upon sober or
merely semi-inebriated reflection _ they will not in any way
endorse a bigot and a boor and a bonehead.
</P>
<P>
   Not because the Braves' bullpen stopper is such a rock head that
the only way he can keep his foot out of his mouth is by refusing
to comment publicly on anything.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, parents who expect sports to send society nothing but
wholesome messages. Sorry, kids. Sorry, minority groups. Sorry,
unwed mothers. Sorry, gays. Sorry, New Yorkers. Sorry, everybody
who doesn't consider wearing a white sheet over the head the
highest form of fashion. There is no feel-good ending in sight to
the Rocker saga.
</P>
<P>
   They finally got around to booing John Rocker in Atlanta the
other night for one reason and one reason only.
</P>
<P>
   Brought in to protect a ninth-inning lead, Rocker provided the
sort of relief that rat poison would give to an upset stomach.
</P>
<P>
   When Rocker entered the game against the Philadelphia Phillies
with a 4-1 lead Friday night, a crowd of 40,174 gave him a standing
ovation. Rocker preened and he posed, basking in the adulation from
the same fans who gave him a standing ovation upon his return from
a two-week suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Then Scott Rolen hit a home run. Then the Phillies hit two
singles, followed by a one-out triple, followed by a two-out single
to put the visitors in the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, Rocker went from Atlanta hero to zero.
</P>
<P>
   Boo!!! Boo!!! Boo!!!
</P>
<P>
   Not because Rocker is a smug, contemptible, hateful excuse for a
human being. Not because Rocker is the one who made all the hateful
and insensitive remarks to a magazine reporter, yet blames
everybody but himself for the resulting fallout. Not because Rocker
smirkingly takes the cheers, autograph requests and signs of
support as proof that he is a man of the people.
</P>
<P>
   Booo!!! Boo!!! Boo!!!
</P>
<P>
   Because Rocker frittered away Braves starting pitcher Tom
Glavine's night of work. Because in less than an inning, Rocker's
earned run average shot from 0.96 to 4.50.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever some rogue athlete returns after punishment _ usually
of the slap-on-a-wrist variety _ for some misdeed, people wonder
aloud about ``the message'' it sends. You want to know the message
that gets sent day after day, week after week, year after year? The
message is that, like it or not, double standards exist.
</P>
<P>
   Always have. Always will. The higher on the food chain that
somebody is, the less the chance of paying retail prices for
misdeeds. Star athletes, likewise, get consideration that lesser
lights don't. It's just that when a star athlete is involved, the
world insists on watching and weighing in on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Where are the worries about the message sent when Robert Downey
Jr. squeezes movie gigs in between trips to prison and drug rehab?
Where is the concern about the message kids get when Sean ``Puff
Daddy'' Combs gets busted on gun-possession charges? Where are the
calls for action when Whitney Houston spaces out during a Grammy
Awards gig and gets pulled out of an Academy Awards performance
because of erratic behavior?
</P>
<P>
   But when Darryl Strawberry flunks a drug test, when Mark Chmura
gets arrested on charges of having sex with a teenager, when
Latrell Sprewell wraps his hands around a coach's throat, the
message being sent becomes a major concern. People get
sanctimonious about out-of-control athletes, right up to the moment
one of those public enemies joins their team.
</P>
<P>
   To most of the country, Sprewell is still the rebel without a
conscience who tried to choke his boss. To New York Knicks fans,
he's the beloved ``Spreeeeee'' who gives the team at least a hope
and a prayer of winning a championship.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the public support that Rocker receives undoubtedly is a
backlash against the overreaction to his remarks. Rocker has
created more of a stir for being a blowhard than NFL players Rae
Curruth and Ray Lewis did for getting charged with murder. Just
because Rocker's words got blown out of proportion doesn't give him
some sort of moral high ground. His petulance, his inability to say
or do anything conciliatory, speak loudest of all.
</P>
<P>
   About the only smart thing Rocker has done since breaking out
his World Wrestling Federation act is to adopt a no-comment policy
on all matters. Otherwise, Braves management would live in mortal
fear of interviews like this:
</P>
<P>
   Blow-dried TV guy: ``So, John, what kind of pitch did he hit?''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker: ``I threw a !%!! fastball to that !!&AMP;!! guy, who looks
like a !!X%%! foreigner, if you ask me.''
</P>
<P>
   They booed John Rocker in his home park the other night, and it
was as unsatisfying as it was overdue. They booed him for the
emptiest of reasons, these same Atlanta Braves fans who stood and
cheered his arrival.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for a happy ending, then the best hope is that
Rocker's karma comes back to him full-force, rendering his left arm
as lame as his brain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 1904EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000510.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1233 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-(TRIM     05-10 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBERAL ECONOMICS EXPERT IS APPOINTED RUSSIA'S PRIME MINISTER 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Vladimir Putin on Wednesday named as prime
minister a chief foreign-debt negotiator and a liberal economics
expert. The long predicted move, some experts said, bodes well for
efforts to tame Russia's feral style of capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   That view was bolstered by a separate report Wednesday that
Putin might abolish the Fuel and Energy Ministry as he reorganizes
the cabinet. The immensely powerful agency has often been attacked
as a seat of corruption and a brake on capitalist reforms.
</P>
<P>
   The new prime minister, Mikhail M. Kasyanov, has been first
deputy prime minister, then the government's No. 2 post, since
Putin became acting president in January. He frequently stood in
for Putin as the acting president campaigned for the full four-year
term that he won in elections in March.
</P>
<P>
   But Kasyanov, 42, is best known as the pragmatic and savvy
negotiator who persuaded private Western creditors in February to
agree to a reduction of nearly $32 billion in Russian debt.
</P>
<P>
   The creditors, known as the London Club, agreed after months of
talks to accept bonds worth as little as 62.5 cents for every
dollar owed them. That now seems an exceptionally good deal for
Russia, which was _ and is _ reaping an unexpectedly large income
from a rebounding economy and exports of high-price oil.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Klaus Regling, who negotiated with Kasyanov as the German
Finance Ministry's chief international officer in the 1990s, called
him an extremely tough bargainer who won the respect not just of
the Germans, but also of the Americans in the Treasury Department,
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he signed off on something, you knew it was really a done
deal,'' said Regling, now a finance expert in London. ``There are
always all these advisers around. But he didn't need that. You
could really do it with just two persons in the room.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The nomination of Kasyanov, a tall, beefy man with a gravely
voice and a crushing handshake, goes to the lower house of
Parliament, the Duma, which plans a vote next Wednesday. The
speaker, Gennady Seleznyov, a Communist, predicted that Kasyanov
would be confirmed easily, even though the Communists have serious
questions about the Kremlin's economic bent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Duma members are not allergic to Kasyanov,'' Seleznyov
said.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus among Russian experts was that Kasyanov would
continue to have a strong hand in fiscal policy, pushing for a
streamlining of tax and regulatory codes.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Budget Committee in Parliament, Alexander
Zhukov, said in a radio interview the government was preparing
``drastic changes to some of the main taxes,'' including the income
and excise taxes and the payroll tax for welfare funds, which could
change the landscape of the budget and economy.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the semi-official Interfax news service quoted a
government source as having said Putin is considering eliminating
several cabinet-level agencies, including the Economics and the
Fuel and Energy ministries. Their duties would be folded into the
Finance Ministry and other departments.
</P>
<P>
   The Fuel and Energy Ministry has been marked by liberals as a
test of Putin's willingness to confront entrenched interests.
</P>
<P>
   Although much of the oil industry is in private hands, natural
gas remains more or less a government monopoly. And the ministry
wields enormous influence _ much of it for the benefit of special
interests, critics say _ through its control of pipelines and the
pricing of oil products.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the critics have demanded the ouster of Energy
Minister Victor Kalyuzhny, who they say has imposed new production
quotas and tariffs that insiders can easily manipulate.
</P>
<P>
   Kasyanov hedged when asked about a cabinet shake-up. ``It is
necessary to make some adjustments in the structure of the federal
organs of power,'' he said, adding that those changes ``will not be
global ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Some express doubts _ similar to those expressed about Putin _
as to whether Kasyanov is willing to free Russia's economy from the
grip of the financial-industrial combines which now dominate
several industries and their government regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Russia's racier muckraking newspapers have dubbed
Kasyanov ``Misha Two Percent,'' charging that as Russia's finance
minister, he gave well-connected bankers inside information about
terms for the resale of old Soviet-era debts. Kasyanov has flatly
denied that.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Like Putin, Kasyanov is also pegged by Moscow's rumor mill as
close to two tycoons, Boris A. Berezovsky and Roman Abramovich, who
have amassed huge stakes in Russia's oil, metals and media
industries. Already this year, the two have cornered 70 percent of
Russia's aluminum industry with the blessing of the government.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky and Abramovich both raised eyebrows by showing up at
invitation-only events surrounding Putin's inauguration on Sunday.
One of the best-known liberals of President Boris Yeltsin's regime,
Boris Nemtsov, warned this spring that Kasyanov's elevation to
prime minister would mean a continuation of the robber-baron
capitalism that helped ruin the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Kasyanov also scoffs at that. ``I don't have any concrete ties
to any particular financial-industrial group. I maintain contacts
with everybody,'' he said at an April news conference. ``I meet
with Berezovsky very rarely - perhaps once every six months.''
</P>
<P>
   And in fact, Kasyanov is credited with supporting a one-third
increase in oil-export taxes and a requirement that oil companies
pay their taxes in cash rather than through barter _ two measures
opposed by the so-called oligarchs.
</P>
<P>
   He rose the hard way. A graduate of the Moscow Automobile and
Road College, he worked at the old Soviet central planning
committee before switching, with the Russian government, to a
free-market economic philosophy after the Soviet Union died in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   Kasyanov spent two years at the economics ministry before
joining Yeltsin's finance ministry where he held several posts
before being finance minister. Under Putin, he kept that title and
added the post of first deputy prime minister, the job he held
until Wednesday's announcement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
