<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELEPHONE-TAX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HOUSE REPUBLICAN LEADERS ATTACK PHONE TAXES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AUSTIN ZALKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republican leaders announced Wednesday they
will try to abolish the federal excise tax on telephone calls, a
move they said would allow more Americans access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the GOP leaders said at a news conference on Capitol
Hill that removing the tax would make dial-up Internet connections
less expensive.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Richard Armey, R-Texas, said that when the
House votes next week on the phone-tax issue, it will be taking
steps to ``permanently ban government access charges on the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the current federal 3 percent tax on long-distance
phone calls and 2.7 percent tax on local calls, Armey said,
``That's the biggest problem we have for equal access to the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   He called the federal phone taxes, which raise more than $5
billion a year for the U.S. treasury, unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   Another Republican, Rep. Bob Goodlatte of Virginia, who
co-chairs the Congressional Internet Caucus, also said taxing phone
calls hinders Internet access. He added that such levies are among
the ``most unfair, regressive taxes.'' Like other sales taxes,
phone taxes require poor people to pay the same rate as wealthier
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the lower-income person, (the phone tax) is the most
unfair charge of all,'' Goodlatte said.
</P>
<P>
   Armey and Goodlatte spoke before the House voted Wednesday to
extend the ban on taxing sales over the Internet until 2006. The
current moratorium will expire in October 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Harvey, a spokeswoman for House Minority Leader Richard
Gephardt, D-Mo., said he had proposed phasing out the telephone tax
in a recent speech but had no position on whether it should be
eliminated immediately.
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
dart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
