<HEADER>
A1235 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-BOB-DANZIG-HNS &LR;      05-10 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOB-DANZIG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ADVANCE MAN FOR HEAVENLY MESSENGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CECILE S. HOLMES   
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ He's completely comfortable talking about the
metaphysical,
</P>
<P>
   but Robert J. ``Bob'' Danzig never expected to become an advance
man for
</P>
<P>
   those winged messengers people call angels.
</P>
<P>
   Danzig, 66, left his post running Hearst Newspapers two years
ago to
</P>
<P>
   become a motivational speaker and author. In his new book,
``Angel
</P>
<P>
   Threads'' (Frederick Fell Publishers Inc., $14.95), he recounts
stories
</P>
<P>
   from his life and others' lives.
</P>
<P>
   The tales show how life journeys can be reshaped by ``angels.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean all of these angels are actual messengers from
heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Many are angelic people, like the fellow hospital patient who
reached
</P>
<P>
   out to Danzig after he had a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   Life is like a tapestry, woven with diverse people, places and
</P>
<P>
   experiences, Danzig said May 3 during a talk for the Houston
Food Bank
</P>
<P>
   Humanitarian Award Luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thread that you who are connected to this food bank share
is you
</P>
<P>
   share the power of the thread of inspiration,'' he said.
``Someone was a
</P>
<P>
   thread of inspiration in your tapestry, and you are to others.
You share
</P>
<P>
   that. You also share the power to excite.''
</P>
<P>
   Danzig avoided a formal address from the podium. Instead,he
shucked
</P>
<P>
   his jacket and spoke in his shirtsleeves and suspenders, walking
among
</P>
<P>
   the round tables in the Westin Galleria Hotel ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   He joked, pausing once to admire a woman's hat. He poked fun at
himself,
</P>
<P>
   then turned serious, jabbing the air to make important points as
500
</P>
<P>
   people listened.
</P>
<P>
   He told how a social worker helped him believe in his own worth
when he
</P>
<P>
   was a youngster and how his first boss gave him confidence when
she told
</P>
<P>
   him, ``You are full of promise'' when he was a newspaper copy
boy.
</P>
<P>
   For Danzig, life's tapestry is enriched by multicolored-threads,
</P>
<P>
   especially influence from people ``with the qualities'' of
angels.He
</P>
<P>
   decided to write his current book after meeting people whotold
him of
</P>
<P>
   their encounters with angels and realizing keyinfluences in his
own
</P>
<P>
   life tapestry.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, one man's story describes a visible, 8-foot angel.
``With
</P>
<P>
   others, it (the concept of angels) is more a notion of what it
might be
</P>
<P>
   like to describe love,'' Danzig said.
</P>
<P>
   He understands the skepticism such ideas provoke. But he remains
</P>
<P>
   grateful for the angellike people who have crossed his path and
</P>
<P>
   influenced his destiny.
</P>
<P>
   Danzig began his work with Hearst as an office boy at the Albany
Times
</P>
<P>
   Union when he was only 16. Reared in five foster homes after his
parents
</P>
<P>
   divorced when he was 2, Danzig served in the U.S. Navy and then
attended
</P>
<P>
   college at night.
</P>
<P>
   His career with Hearst spanned 46 years. In 1969, he was named
publisher
</P>
<P>
   of Hearst's Albany, N.Y., Capital Newspapers. He became head of
the
</P>
<P>
   company's Newspaper Group in 1977, holding that position for
more than
</P>
<P>
   two decades.
</P>
<P>
   He became an industry leader, serving such groups as the
Newspaper
</P>
<P>
   Association of America and the American Press Institute.
</P>
<P>
   He left newspapers for public speaking and writing because he
wanted to
</P>
<P>
   share his ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea if I could write a book, if I could become a
successful
</P>
<P>
   speaker, if I could connect with a university,'' he said in an
</P>
<P>
   interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``In each case, someone had crossed my path with some knowledge
of how to
</P>
<P>
   write a book, how to become a successful speaker, how to connect
with a
</P>
<P>
   university.
</P>
<P>
   ``In each case, all I did was accept the gift they offered me
and explore
</P>
<P>
   that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Danzig now teaches the ``Confidence Course'' at New School
University in
</P>
<P>
   New York. He has written two other books, ``The Leader Within
You'' and
</P>
<P>
   ``Vitamins for the Spirit,'' and is planning a fourth book. With
his wife,
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Brady-Danzig, a lyric soprano, he set up a private
charity.
</P>
<P>
   Danzig donates all speaking fees and book royalties to the
charity.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a great yearning among people for the softer values
of life,''
</P>
<P>
   he said. ``It has less to do with religiosity or religion than
it does
</P>
<P>
   with feeding or sharing one's spirit. There is a profound
spirituality
</P>
<P>
   out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a guy who's run a huge, multimillion-dollar corporation
come to
</P>
<P>
   talk to them has lubricated my audience,'' he said. ``That opens
doors. If
</P>
<P>
   I was an Episcopal priest, it might be different. When I'm done,
there
</P>
<P>
   are people lined up to hug me. They're not really hugging Bob
Danzig;
</P>
<P>
   they're hugging the idea of insights to nurture and nourish
their
</P>
<P>
   spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Danzig's book is full of such insights, offering stories of
people who
</P>
<P>
   nurtured others or were befriended by other nurturing souls.
</P>
<P>
   Danzig firmly believes people can learn from ``angels,'' whether
they
</P>
<P>
   understand those messengers as actual winged envoys from heaven,
or more
</P>
<P>
   as people or experience that helped open new possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things that open the possibility of love, relationship
and
</P>
<P>
   sharing are so often triggered by some event we didn't plan,''
Danzig
</P>
<P>
   said.
</P>
<P>
   Such experiences might be called coincidences, but Danzig says
they are
</P>
<P>
   permeated with a ``spirit force'' more significant than
happenstance.
</P>
<P>
   Such experiences teach us that ``we are not alone,'' Danzig
said. ``There
</P>
<P>
   are either persons, events or circumstances that surround and
guide our
</P>
<P>
   lives. All of them have some spirit component.''
</P>
<P>
   But has he ever seen a real angel?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think in terms of the physical,'' Danzig said in an
interview
</P>
<P>
   after his Houston speech. ``I think in terms of the spiritual.
Every
</P>
<P>
   person I've talked about here is angellike.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
