<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1236 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SAFRICA-MARKETS-ART-9     05-10 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-MARKETS-ART-940(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPING TO ATTRACT FOREIGN MONEY, SOUTH AFRICA CRACKS DOWN ON
INSIDER TRADING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By HENRI E. CAUVIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ For years, the Johannesburg Stock
Exchange was nearly as notorious among international financiers as
the country itself was among human rights advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated from the world, apartheid-era South Africa learned to
play by its own rules, its financial markets evolving into an
insular, incestuous morass where insider trading was a key part of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a decade after the country began a political
transformation, South Africa's market has found that it, too, must
change. Backed by a new law, regulators have taken aim at insider
traders.
</P>
<P>
   In the first year under the new law, the market has won six
settlements totaling almost 2.2 million rand ($320,000), and more
important, they say, they have sounded a new opening bell here in
the financial capital of Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want people to be scared,'' said Peter Redman, a former
broker and stock exchange chairman who is now a senior surveillance
official for the exchange, ``so that they just don't do this sort
of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The regulators are, by their own admission, a long way from that
point, but they are pressing ahead, knowing that much is at stake.
Indeed, for South Africa's financial sector and the stock exchange
in particular, few matters are more pressing. The country is slowly
rebuilding its economy, and it craves the foreign investment a
thriving stock exchange could bring. Emerging markets like South
Africa, Brazil and South Korea are hot, and as a barrier to
investment, national borders are fast becoming obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   What remains an obstacle here and in many other emerging
markets, though, is the fear of being bamboozled. Foreign investors
want to know that they are trading on a level playing field, that
they have access to the same company information that local
investors do.
</P>
<P>
   It is a concern that South Africa's chief insider trading
enforcer, Rob Barrow, has heard all too often from people with
money to invest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them have made it very clear to me that they resist
coming into the South African market, sometimes with substantial
money, or money that would be substantial to us and our economy
because they've been here before and believe they've been taken to
the cleaners,'' said Barrow, chairman of the country's newly formed
Insider Trading Directorate. ``That, of course, is the perception
we are trying to change.''
</P>
<P>
   The Johannesburg Stock Exchange's trading volume increased
nearly ninefold, from 5.2 billion shares at the end of 1995, to
43.1 billion at the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Insider trading _ trading on nonpublic information that could
affect a stock's price _ was never much of a secret here. And for
decades, under the Companies Act, it was a criminal offense. But it
was impossible to prosecute. The charges were hard to prove beyond
a reasonable doubt, and prosecutors were frequently ill equipped to
handle such complicated cases. So the accusations hardly ever saw
the inside of a courtroom. Not once, in fact, did South Africa ever
win an insider trading conviction under the old law.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Insider Trading Act enacted last year, however,
insider trading not only became a criminal offense but a civil one,
too. In a civil proceeding, the standard of proof is not as high,
and that has opened a new door for the authorities here.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the authorities say, they hope to send someone to
prison for insider trading. But after years of seeing no results,
at least they have, in the civil settlements won so far, something
to show for their work.
</P>
<P>
   In the largest settlement, won late last year, Ron Sackstein,
chief executive of I-Fusion Holdings, a local information
technology company, paid just over a million rand, or about
$160,000, to settle insider trading accusations against him.
</P>
<P>
   While most agree that the civil actions are a measure of
progress, sentiment is split on whether settlements are enough to
discourage dishonest traders. In some cases, the terms have allowed
those accused to remain unidentified.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shouldn't really just be a civil action,'' said Ian
McMillan, chief investment officer for Fleming Asset Management in
Cape Town. ``It should be more serious. If your penalty is just a
monetary one, the incentive is there to try it because maybe you
can make more than they'll take.''
</P>
<P>
   John Pott, the southern Africa representative for the
International Finance Corp., a unit of the World Bank, said he,
too, would like to see an even more aggressive approach by
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the question in investors' minds still is are the
deterrents of a sufficient magnitude,'' said Pott, who said his
agency had about $100 million in investments here. ``I guess that
is our concern, and we would hope that they would go one step
further toward how the SEC deals with the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   But South Africa, swamped by every sort of crime and struggling
to remake its apartheid-era system of law enforcement, has nothing
like the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission's army of
investigators and prosecutors with the skills and resources to turn
complicated, painstaking investigations into coherent, viable
prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   So as South Africans see it, they are doing the next best thing,
said Nicky Newton-King, the stock exchange's legal counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Around the world, what is happening with white-collar crime is
people are moving to civil remedies because very few courts and
prosecutors have the technical skills to actually get behind this
sort of contravention,'' she said. ``If what you can do is take the
profit out of the crime for the guys that are doing it and you can
stop and make them think, then I think you've been successful.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, even giving potential insider traders pause is seen as a
step forward in South Africa, where history helped instill insider
trading into the ethos of a business establishment dominated by the
white minority. Dodging trade sanctions demanded a certain
creativity. Forged certificates of origin for products made here
were commonplace, and in one form or another, that sort of scheming
took hold in quite a few corners of the business sector. There was
``a culture of insider trading,'' Redman said.
</P>
<P>
   And the structure of corporate ownership and management that
evolved, mostly out of necessity, during the era of sanctions only
encouraged the sort of misbehavior the country is now trying to
stamp out. With little foreign investment and ownership, the
biggest South African businesses became nests of complex cross
holdings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a concentration of power,'' said Bill Urmson, the
stock exchange's director of surveillance. ``And an awful lot of
information was flowing into those very few citadels of power,
which made the opportunity for insider trading more severe.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, securities regulators and market administrators are trying
to teach companies how to conduct themselves in this new, open
environment. Guidelines about who disseminates information, who
gets information and when are more common.
</P>
<P>
   It is a work in progress, to be sure. In March, in the latest
move toward a more transparent corporate culture, the stock
exchange announced plans to require directors to disclose dealings
in their companies' shares promptly. Such requirements are standard
in the world's biggest markets, and adopting them here would be
another step toward bringing the stock exchange in line with its
more reputable counterparts in New York, London and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The changes are not only in South Africa. International
investors, enchanted by the promise of emerging markets, have
pressed for change from South America to Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Globalization of markets demands globalization of
regulation,'' said Miroslaw Kachniewski, a Polish securities
regulator who heads an international committee examining
enforcement in emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
   The committee, part of the International Organization of
Securities Commissions, is scheduled to present a report at that
organization's annual meeting, which starts this weekend in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Putting all the world's securities regulators on the same page,
as far as what constitutes insider trading and what the appropriate
response is, is the ultimate objective of Kachniewski and his
committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of regulators are aware,'' he said in a
phone interview from Warsaw. ``However, there are some
jurisdictions where insider trading is not a criminal offense, and
I hope our research will help give regulators the information they
need to convince their governments that changes are necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, South Africa is not that far behind compared with
efforts in developing nations. ``I think among emerging markets,
and certainly in Africa, they are ahead of the pack,'' Pott said.
</P>
<P>
   But Barrow, the insider-trading enforcer, knows he will be
judged, not on his success in winning legal battles but on the
market's success in winning over wary investors. ``You can only
judge the success on the perception of the Johannesburg Stock
Exchange, that the JSE is a market with sufficient integrity that
anyone can trade on it,'' he said. ``I think we are well on our way
to getting there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 1911EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000510.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1239 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ILOVEYOU-VIRUS-1STLD-     05-10 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ILOVEYOU-VIRUS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-840&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRUS MAY BE BASED ON UNIVERSITY THESIS PROPOSAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to add background and restructure: adds new 4th graf that
explains how virus worked; moves up 1st comment by
Pagulayan;reworks graf following that comment to smooth
transition;deletes orig 12th, 13th, 15th grafs, bgng `Luis
Pagulayan...' and adds 3 new grafs with background, bgng `Buen's
and Onel de Guzman's...;restructures orig. 16th graf to smooth
transition;deletes 3 last grafs of original _ updated reporting
from Washington now appears separately as ILOVEYOU-VIRUS-U.S.) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANILA, Philippines _ Officials investigating a malicious
program that disrupted computer systems around the world said
Wednesday that they were looking for a young computer student who
recently wrote a thesis proposal with elements that were similar to
a virus that has disabled e-mail systems around the world in recent
days.
</P>
<P>
   The student, who appears to have gone into hiding, is Onel de
Guzman, 23, who lived in the same apartment in Manila as a man and
woman who were first named on Monday as suspects.
</P>
<P>
   When de Guzman presented his proposal in February, a thesis
reviewer at his computer college noted on it: ``This is illegal''
and ``We do not produce burglars.''
</P>
<P>
   The program released last week, a hybrid of varieties known as
viruses and worms, ricocheted around the world as an attachment to
e-mail messages with the subject line ``I Love You.'' Opening the
attachment activated the program, which then sent itself along to
addresses found in the victim's e-mail software. In addition, the
program tried to fetch additional software from a Philippine Web
site that could pilfer passwords from the user's computer.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the college, AMA Computer College, said a second
student, Michael Buen, had written a software program that might
have been combined with de Guzman's work to create the virus. The
officials said he, too, had gone into hiding.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thesis proposal, though not illegal per se, could be used
as part of the structure of the current virus,'' said Luis
Pagulayan, the college's general counsel.He said subpoenas were
being issued by the National Bureau of Investigation for both
students, although investigators have not formally named them as
suspects. The bureau is continuing to investigate the couple,
Reomel Ramones and Irene de Guzman, whose apartment was raided on
Monday. Irene de Guzman is Onel de Guzman's older sister.
</P>
<P>
   Ramones and Irene de Guzman were initially named as suspects
when investigators traced the virus to a computer in their
apartment, but when authorities raided the apartment on Monday the
computer had been removed. Ramones was detained, but Irene de
Guzman disappeared after promising to surrender to authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Secretary Artemio Tuquero said Wednesday that Ramones,
who was held overnight Monday at the National Bureau of
Investigation and who will face charges on May 19, may have been a
``fall guy'' but that it was too soon to drop charges against him.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel Abad, executive vice president of the college, said of
Onel de Guzman: ``We are not saying he is a suspect. If ever we
found something about the thesis, it could only be a circumstantial
lead. We do not know whether he did develop this as a virus.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it was his impression that if the two students were
involved in creating the virus their intention was to steal and use
passwords, not to spread destruction through the world's computer
systems.
</P>
<P>
   According to local news reports, both students were members of
an underground campus group called GRAMMERSoft, which did
programming work for hire and also wrote and sold thesis projects
to other students. But college officials said they could not
confirm that the two were members.
</P>
<P>
   Abad said he had asked teachers what they recalled about Onel de
Guzman. ``He's the quiet type,'' Abad said. ``He's an average
student, although in some subjects he is getting very high grades.
In our grading system, 1 is the highest and 5 is failing. In one
subject, in Assembly Language, he got a 1. It's a pretty hard
subject, and he got a flat 1 on it. And on other computer subjects
he got a 1.5, a 1.25.''
</P>
<P>
   Buen's and Onel de Guzman's names surfaced over the weekend when
computer security researchers in the United States and Sweden found
that one component of the rogue program closely resembled
password-stealing programs discovered in recent months by U.S.
anti-virus researchers.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier programs contained both a list of names and
references to the Philippine computer college and the GRAMMERsoft
group. Buen's name appeared in a brief resume, and de Guzman was on
an extended list of names inserted in the program, perhaps as
references.
</P>
<P>
   Pagulayan, the college's general counsel, said the two were
among 10 possible suspects on a list given to Philippine
investigators by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   He said the name of Onel de Guzman immediately rang a bell at
the school because, although many thesis proposals are rejected,
his was turned down because ``it was contrary to law, dealing with
hacking, dealing with a virus. That is not something that happens
every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Abad said Buen's thesis, which was accepted and which led to his
graduation from the school last Friday, contained information that
could be used to create multiple copies of computer files.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you merge both programs you can come up with this virus,''
said Karim Bangcola, senior vice president of the college.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Onel de Guzman's proposal, which was titled ``E-mail Password
Sender Trojan,'' was never developed into a full-fledged thesis,
and he did not graduate as scheduled last week.
</P>
<P>
   In the proposal, which was obtained by The Associated Press, he
wrote that his software ``will be helpful to a lot of people,
especially Internet users, to get Windows passwords such as
Internet accounts to spend more time on the Internet without
paying.''
</P>
<P>
   He also wrote: ``We spend a lot of money to pay for accounts for
only using a couple of hours. So this program is the main solution.
Use it to steal and retrieve Internet accounts of the victim's
computer.''
</P>
<P>
   Explaining why the thesis proposal was rejected, Abad said: ``It
carried a feature that could enable the software to steal
passwords. And there's a recipient and it will steal the
recipient's password and all the other names in the recipient's
address book.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, all the names in that address book will be
sent new e-mails automatically, and exponentially again you will
get the e-mails and Internet accounts of these people,'' he said.
``We saw that to be very illegal and very immoral, and so we
disapproved the thesis proposal. It never got developed within
AMA.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
