<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ILOVEYOU-VIRUS-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRUS CAUSED MORE DAMAGE THAN PAST COMPUTER VANDALISM 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A computer security expert told a U.S.
congressional panel in Washington on Wednesday that the ``I Love
You'' program had caused far more widespread damage than similar
episodes in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The expert, Peter S. Tippett of ICSA.net in Reston, Va., said a
preliminary survey by his company indicates 98 percent of
businesses in North America received the email, and 65 percent had
computers infected by the attached virus. In contrast, he said, a
program known as Melissa that spread in similar fashion last year
reached only 20 percent of the companies in North America and 10
percent were infected.
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide, Tippett estimated, the ``I Love You'' program caused
$3 billion in damages and lost time. Lloyd's of London has
estimated it will ultimately cost more than $15 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
