<HEADER>
A1246 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-RENO-AFRICA-NYTS     05-10 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-RENO-AFRICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR IS BETTER THAN SIERRA LEONE'S PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for use in papers of Thursday, May 11)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by OPED clients. Nonsubscribers can use this
article only by special arrangement. For purchase information, see
end of text. 
 By WILLIAM RENO    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EVANSTON, Ill. _ Sometimes it is better to wage war than to
agree to an unstable and unworkable peace, a proposition that the
current crisis in Sierra Leone bears out.
</P>
<P>
   A peace agreement signed in July 1999 was supposed to help
rebuild Sierra Leone by installing a coalition government, composed
of the current president, Ahmad Tejan Kabbah, and Foday Sankoh, the
ruthless leader of the main rebel group.
</P>
<P>
   Under the accord, Sankoh became a vice president and
commissioner of diamond resources, the country's main source of
income. Three of his lieutenants became ministers of government.
All were offered a blanket amnesty for past crimes. In exchange,
U.N. peacekeepers were to take the weapons of all combatants.
Instead, the rebels have captured and disarmed 500 peacekeepers,
and the country is in chaos once again.
</P>
<P>
   This agreement failed for several related reasons. It mistakenly
assumed that the rebels were interested in peace, let alone had an
interest in real governing. It assumed that there was a civil war,
and treated Sankoh as a legitimate champion of the rural poor,
whose interests he claimed to represent. In reality, Sankoh was
interested only in taking advantage of a corrupt state that had
collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   So, from the rebels' point of view, why have peace when it is
the absence of law and order that enables one to loot? Why let
peacekeeping troops enter the country's diamond mining area if one
is profiting from the sale of these riches on the black market?
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the rebels never had any intention of honoring the
peace accord; they were only interested in waging war and looting
the country. The United Nations, so reflexively attached to the
mantra of peace at any price, sent peacekeeping troops when there
was no peace to keep.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations and the State Department, which helped
negotiate the peace accord, should have known better. As recently
as March 1999, the U.N. Security Council threatened to prosecute
Sankoh for war crimes. Earlier, a State Department report on Sierra
Leone noted the discovery of civilian mass graves in areas where
the rebels had attacked.
</P>
<P>
   Why would the United Nations and the United States agree to a
power-sharing agreement with Sankoh, whose forces have killed,
raped and maimed tens of thousands of men, women and even children?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is quite simple and found in President Clinton's
statement during his April 1999 visit to Rwanda, when he lamented
the lack of U.S. action to stop the genocide there. After this
speech, the Clinton administration wanted to show that it cared
about human rights in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The peace accord was quick and cheap, but doomed. Let us hope
that the West now recognizes this _ and doesn't opt for a second
try at an accord. In the last few days Olusegun Obasanjo, the
Nigerian president, has agreed to send his country's soldiers back
to Sierra Leone, provided the West pays their costs. Not only
should these soldiers be better equipped and trained, they and
Kabbah's forces must also have the ability to fight back _ in
effect, waging war against the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   This is the best solution _ because unlike the West, Nigeria has
national interests at stake. Trouble anywhere in West Africa is a
threat to its stability. And Nigeria might recognize what the West
hasn't _ that peace in the region can only be won through war.
</P>
<P>
   (William Reno, who teaches political science at Northwestern, is
the author of ``Warlord Politics and African States.'')
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the OPED
package and other features. &QL;
</P>
