<P>
   U.S.-ARMS (Washington) _ Administration officials discuss arms
policy in advance of President Clinton's trip to Moscow. By Eric
Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SHANGHAI-NOVELIST (Shanghai, China) _ Zhou Weihui had gathered
her friends and acquaintances on a veranda overlooking this city's
famous 1930s-era waterfront, ostensibly to say goodbye to society
for a while. She wanted to drop out of sight, she said, because she
was under too much pressure from China's formidable propaganda
machine, which was busy trashing her best-selling novel, ``Shanghai
Baby.'' Already, her publisher had destroyed the page proofs and
all of the books in stock, arguing _ after having sold at least
80,000 copies _ that the novel was in poor taste and that Zhou, 27,
was too outlandish. By Craig S. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Washington) _ President Clinton has stressed for
months that Congress must grant permanent trading rights for China
or risk damage to the competitiveness of U.S. companies and
threaten relations with the world's most populous nation. But not
unlike other high-profile trade votes, this one involves a host of
issues that are purely local. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-U.S. (Washington) _ President Clinton, in the face of
strong opposition from the U.S. pharmaceutical industry, on
Wednesday issued an executive order to make AIDS drugs available
far more cheaply throughout sub-Saharan Africa. The order declares
that the U.S. government will not seek to interfere with countries
in that region that may violate U.S. patent law in order to provide
AIDS drugs at lower prices. The language of the executive order is
nearly identical to an amendment that was deleted at the behest of
the drug industry from an African trade bill that Congress is
considering this week. The order issued by President Clinton
essentially extended to most of Africa a special arrangement
provided last year to South Africa. By Neil A. Lewis. (725 words)
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-GUARDS (Maden, Turkey) _ Sipping tea in the sun and
looking down from their clay bunker at a placid field full of
wildflowers, Irfan Ozay and his cousin Remzi should be happy. With
their help and that of 95,000 other village guards, the Turkish
army has finally won its war against Kurdish rebels. But like many
other village guards, the Ozay cousins are worried and becoming
angry. They fear they will soon be cashiered and find themselves
without jobs or prospects. What to do with these village guards is
one of the most urgent questions that suddenly confront Turkey now
that peace has broken out. By Stephen Kinzer. (850 words)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
