<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-OLDCITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVING ZEUGMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Zeugma should be saved. The site of two ancient cities is about
to be drowned. A dam across the Euphrates river will create an
artificial lake to meet the demand for hydroelectric power for
southeastern Turkey. But the dammed waters will flood much of
Zeugma in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In a do-or-die version of television's ``Antiques Roadshow,''
archeologists are scrambling to save as many artifacts as they can,
including still-vibrant mosaics from the second or third century.
Of course, instead of hunting in grandma's attic, these
archeologists are hunting in civilization's basement for pieces of
human identity.
</P>
<P>
   The area was a prime place to cross the Euphrates. Through time
Assyrians, Romans, and Greeks lived there. Later, Arabs, Turks,
Crusaders, and Kurds fought over the area. In the Middle Ages,
Zeugma was forgotten as the main crossing over the Euphrates moved
downstream.
</P>
<P>
   One might wish for a Poseidon or Zeus to protect the site or a
Moses to hold back the water. A less epic but simpler approach is
available to the Turkish government: Delay the dam project for a
few months so archeologists can complete more of their rescue.
</P>
<P>
   Zeugma _ whatever its fate _ should become a vivid cautionary
tale for the preservation community. That the site existed and the
dam was coming were known facts. Researchers attracted funds and
other support from the French and Turkish governments as well as
from private companies to excavate and map the area, but that
wasn't enough to beat the racing clock of progress.
</P>
<P>
   What happens the next time a site is threatened? One wise step
would be to build larger coalitions of interest. In addition to
government and industry, more museums and universities could be
pulled in to keep track both of significant sites and potential
threats posed by development projects.
</P>
<P>
   Time steals a great deal, turning cities to rubble, paper to
dust, and people _ if they're lucky _ into memories. This rush of
years cannot be stopped. But at Zeugma the rush of water could be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 1939EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000510.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1261 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-SIERRA-BOS &LR;      05-10 0372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-SIERRA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUNDER IN WEST AFRICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In peacekeeping as in war, the faster a blunder is acknowledged,
the sooner it may be corrected. That is the harsh moral of the
civil war that has revived this month in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   The attention of the outside world has been drawn to the plight
of United Nations peacekeepers who were sent to the West African
nation to supervise a peace agreement that existed only on paper.
This week, 498 of the poorly trained and lightly armed
blue-helmeted UN troops were taken hostage by the forces of local
warlord Foday Sankoh, a glorified diamond thief who muscled his way
into a power-sharing peace treaty last July.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh's fighters became infamous for their practice of hacking
off the hands and arms of citizens who defied the warlord by voting
for Sierra Leone's President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah. Despite such
sadistic methods, Sankoh persuaded Washington, London, and the rest
of the outside world to grant him eight ministers in a coalition
government and a complete pardon for all his crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The great powers behind the illusory peace treaty of last July
blundered in trusting Sankoh to keep his promises after a West
African armed force that had been keeping the peace withdrew from
Sierra Leone this month. Equally foolish was their unfounded
assumption that a few thousand UN peacekeepers might be able to
protect themselves, much less the preyed-upon population of Sierra
Leone.
</P>
<P>
   Since there is no stomach for a full-scale intervention by any
of the permanent members of the Security Council, the next best
thing is for the rich and powerful nations _ those that wish to
make good their blunders _ to subsidize the return of a bigger and
better armed version of the West African forces that had kept the
peace in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   A crucial error, not to be repeated this time, was the naive
belief that a criminal like Sankoh could be placated in a
power-sharing government. The blue helmets of the UN can help only
if there is a peace to keep. Where there is no peace, well-meaning
outsiders must choose a side to take or stay out of a civil war
like Sierra Leone's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
