<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1263 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-N     05-10 1321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK UP TO BEAT THE BUG 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This column contains all the antivirus software necessary to
protect your computer from the ``I Love You'' worm virus and its
many mutant variations. All you have to do is double-click on the
following paragraph by tapping the paper twice with your finger,
and then press the finger as firmly as possible against your
forehead while reciting aloud:
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not open any e-mail attachment, even if it comes from
someone I know, unless I am absolutely certain it does not contain
a virus.''
</P>
<P>
   There, that was easy. Sorry about the ink smudge on your
forehead. Along with your backup files, you are now protected
against the inevitable next wave of Love Bug copycat viruses.
</P>
<P>
   You do have a current backup, don't you?
</P>
<P>
   It is not a question of whether you will need a backup someday,
but rather of question of when. A hard disk can fail. A thief can
carry off your PC. You can absent-mindedly leave your laptop on the
train. Fire. Flood. Termites. You never know. ``When'' is going to
come sooner than you think, because computer viruses could soon be
rampant on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   No computer connected to the Internet should be without an
up-to-date antivirus program. But be careful. Some of the new
viruses are script-based and are harder to catch. Even a recent
antivirus program can be vulnerable to new forms of attack.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the most important thing you can do is to get in the
habit of backing up your important files. Then, if the worst
happens, the worst won't happen.
</P>
<P>
   All Windows-based computers come with an integrated backup
utility _ the sort of application Microsoft added to the operating
system before the Justice Department started getting excited about
such things _ but that has not stopped at least a dozen companies
from offering backup utilities of their own.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days the main backup media were floppy disks and
tapes. Today the home computer owner has many options, including
floppies, Zips, CD-RW drives and even Internet-based remote storage
systems.
</P>
<P>
   The actual software and hardware tools for backing up a hard
drive will be discussed here next week. But the general philosophy
of backup deserves attention first, because it does not matter what
kind of backup software or hardware you have if you do not use it.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Weafer of the Symantec Antivirus Research Center spends
most of his time thinking of ways to prevent viruses from getting
into computers in the first place, but he also stresses that a
reliable backup plan is essential to computer security. The key
points to keep in mind, he said, are the following:
</P>
<P>
   _ The backup process has to be easy.
</P>
<P>
   _ It has to be regular.
</P>
<P>
   _ The backup files have to be stored away from the computer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Backup software must be tested periodically, before it is
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Many people avoid contemplating the horror of losing weeks',
months' or even years' worth of data. As Samuel Johnson said,
``Nothing focuses the mind as sharply as the news that one will be
executed in a few days.'' Pretend that a virus will execute your
computer tomorrow at dawn. Are you focused?
</P>
<P>
   The best backup strategy is the one that you will use the most.
If the process is too complicated, the temptation will be to skip
it.
</P>
<P>
   Nurture the discipline to make a backup schedule and stick to
it. Decide how much work you can afford to lose. A week's worth?
Then schedule a backup session once a week, and make it a ritual.
</P>
<P>
   Do not store the backup files on the same computer, or even in
the same room, with the original files. The best strategy is to
keep at least one full backup of your files in some other place,
just in case. It is more work, and you will be lucky if it is
wasted effort, but it is prudent to make at least two copies of
each backup. Keep one locally, and entrust the other to someone off
site.
</P>
<P>
   When a patient asks a dentist, ``Do I have to floss all my
teeth?'' the dentist usually responds, ``No, only the ones you want
to keep.'' The same holds true for backing up computer files. Back
up only the ones you would hate to lose.
</P>
<P>
   You do not need to back up the actual application programs,
assuming you have a legal copy of the software and kept the
original disks as you were supposed to do. If you were using a
bootlegged copy of the application, viruses can be seen as cosmic
retribution.
</P>
<P>
   Do not neglect the final step: Test your backup system. Try to
reinstall the backup files.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago I diligently made sets of backup disks using a popular
backup program. When the day of reckoning finally came, the result
of a failed hard disk, the backup program informed me that it could
not decompress the files it had compressed. My backups were in
vain.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of a virus, do not try to reload your backup files
on the infected computer until you are positive that it has been
thoroughly disinfected and protected. If the virus is still lurking
on the system, it will corrupt the backup disks immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The ``I Love You'' virus, also known as the Love Bug or the Love
Letter worm, infected tens of thousands of Windows-based computers
around the world in the past week. If you have not received one of
those love letters, please do not feel unloved. There is nothing
affectionate about the virus.
</P>
<P>
   Reading the poisoned e-mail is harmless, but opening the
attached file leads to heartbreak, or at least heartburn. Once
unleashed, the virus burrows into the roots of the PC, where it
tries to steal passwords and return them to an e-mail address in
the Philippines. Meanwhile, it rummages though the victim's
Microsoft Outlook address book and sends a copy of itself to
everyone listed there. That is why the virus files appeared to come
from friends and acquaintances, and why they quickly clogged
computer systems around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The virus does some immediate damage, too. It hides the victim's
MP3 music files, which is annoying, but it also trashes any JPEG
graphics files it finds by overwriting them. While the music files
often can be recovered, digital photos and graphics are typically
lost.
</P>
<P>
   On the bright side, however, it probably destroyed a significant
portion of the world's reservoirs of digital pornography and
bootlegged Metallica music files.
</P>
<P>
   There is absolutely no evidence to suggest that these latest
viruses were deliberately released into the wild by law enforcement
agencies, the music industry or the makers of antivirus software,
although a cynical paranoiac might note that each benefited
immensely from the rapid spread of the viruses over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Collections of MP3 music files are clogging computer systems on
college campuses around the world. The record industry and some
musicians like the heavy-metal band Metallica are upset that
pirates are trading MP3 recordings of their music over the Internet
without paying royalties. The release of a global MP3-killer virus
as a tactical weapon would have a much more immediate effect than
lawsuits in destabilizing the file format, which has no facility
for copyright management.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, there are vast collections of innocent, perfectly
legal JPEG graphics files on computers around the world, but the
same file format is popular for distributing pornography over the
Internet. A virus designed to attack specific file formats, or to
search for and destroy files containing certain keywords, could be
an interesting tool for law enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, the Love Bug virus merely hides the MP3 files,
making them invisible. Before you despair over losing all the MP3
files you have lovingly collected over the last year or two, go
into Windows, click on My Computer, click View, click Folder
Options, click View and check ``show hidden files.'' Chances are
your Metallica files are still there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
