<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1270 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-VIRTUAL-ORCHESTRA     05-10 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-VIRTUAL-ORCHESTRA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE THEATER, ORCHESTRA PITS ARE FILLED IN WITH DIGITAL MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By ANNE EISENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ No orchestra members will be in the pit riffling
through their scores and checking their instruments when the
curtain rises Thursday night on the New York City Technical College
revival of ``Evita.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because 35 loudspeakers have replaced them, arranged in
front of the audience where an orchestra once sat.
</P>
<P>
   It is those speakers, connected to a computer fully stocked with
the digitally sampled sounds of a range of orchestral instruments,
that will pour forth the accompaniment to ``Don't Cry for Me,
Argentina'' as Evita sings her sad farewell from the stage. Welcome
to the virtual orchestra, the group that always plays on pitch and
never calls for a coffee break.
</P>
<P>
   So while Argentina may restrain its tears, future musicians in
the audience may well weep, when they realize what this show and
others like it could mean for their job prospects. Only the singers
and actors in this production are human. The orchestra that
accompanies them is digital.
</P>
<P>
   Controlling the digital orchestra _ not from the podium but from
a computer console _ will be David B. Smith, co-creator of the
system and an assistant professor at New York City Technical
College, which is sponsoring the performance.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, once a violinist himself, does not see his 100 percent
simulated symphony orchestra as a threat to his former colleagues.
``We're not driving musicians out of business,'' he said. ``Our
purpose is to support touring groups and small ensembles that
otherwise can't afford an orchestra.''
</P>
<P>
   At this week's performances of ``Evita,'' at Klitgord Auditorium
in Brooklyn, Smith will probably be found sitting near the stage
with the score at hand; he prefers a printed version to the
electronic one his computer can readily display. ``I check the
score,'' he said, ``but mainly I'm looking at the conductor and the
singers.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith will be watching to make sure that the music he is cueing
keeps time with the musicians on the stage, neither getting ahead
of them nor lagging behind.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, he will tap out a rhythm on a keyboard, the rate of
which will tell the computer whether to speed up or slow down its
music. At a rehearsal, he watched both the conductor and singers
closely, constantly varying his electronic rhythm in response to
the conductor's baton with a rubato that even Puccini, a master of
the slow and fast, might envy.
</P>
<P>
   The speakers that emit the sound of an orchestra are arranged in
a semicircle just below the stage, with one speaker dedicated to
each instrument. The string section _ once wooden violas, violins
and cellos _ has been replaced by 16 high-tech flat-panel speakers
positioned on metal stands that put them at about nose level.
</P>
<P>
   ``The celli are the big ones,'' Smith said, pointing to the
largest of the speakers, rectangles about the size of a movie
poster. ``They are bigger because they have to get down two octaves
below middle C, in the 60-hertz range.''
</P>
<P>
   The harpsichord that is heard in Evita's death scene shares a
speaker with a piano. Other speakers are reserved for instruments
like the French horn, the oboe, the clarinet and the harp, as well
as for the occasional gong and log drum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sample every single pitch and articulation, either live or
on CD,'' said Frederick Bianchi, co-creator of the system and an
associate professor and director of computer music at Worcester
Polytechnic Institute. ``For instance, we have literally 8,000 or
9,000 samples of the violin created and stored.'' Bianchi is even
careful to separate upbow and downbow strokes for all the stringed
instruments being sampled.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and Bianchi have spent 15 years developing their musical
system. ``We've had 2,000 performances and never a crash,'' Bianchi
said. ``Of course, we also provide a backup system just in case,
but the primary system has yet to fail.''
</P>
<P>
   Their company, Realtime Music Solutions, offers to music
directors the digitally sampled sounds, sequencing software and
show files that contain the information to perform a particular
score. One of the systems is currently on the road with a tour of
``Annie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The score is for 30 players,'' Smith said. ``The tour has
seven people, so we supplied the other 23 instruments.''
</P>
<P>
   Synthesizers are nothing new in orchestra pits, of course.
Despite the best efforts of unions, they have been making steady
inroads there during the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   Evan Johnson, a violinist who plays in the ``Beauty and the
Beast'' orchestra on Broadway, opposes their incursion. He and the
show's four other violinists have their sound filled out by a
synthesizer at every performance. ``First they take away 10 of our
15 violins,'' Johnson said, ``and then add a synthesizer, but it's
not the sound of live people.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said that virtually all Broadway pits had synthesizers.
``I don't understand how any self-respecting artistic director
could continue the process toward more and more synthesized
music,'' he said. ``The essence of live theater is live performers.
You don't go to a baseball game to see robots.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith and Bianchi, in contrast, are eager to make digitally
sampled music available to an ever increasing audience. They
particularly want to help smaller groups, like high school
musicians who want to put on a play but don't have enough players
for a full orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not saying, `Get rid of the orchestra,''' Bianchi said.
``We can make your seven people better. We want to enhance, not
replace.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the programs offered many advantages. ``There are
lots of sequencing programs, but ours is tempo agile,'' he said.
``That means the person performing the virtual orchestra has the
ability to mold the music in real time, slowing down or speeding up
with real expression.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the equipment for the performance of ``Evita'' was
purchased through a grant from the Alfred P. Sloan Foundation,
which is financing a program in new sound technology at the
college, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The technical support staff for the performances of ``Evita'' is
composed almost entirely of students training in New York City
Technical College's stage technology program, preparing for the
increasingly high-tech world of backstage theater. Some of the
singers are professionals, others are college students.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 1947EDT &QL; 
