<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1271 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ELIAN-MIAMI-COX     05-10 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-MIAMI-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miami's angry turmoil over Elian echoes 1960s Havana
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vacations are supposed to be fun.
</P>
<P>
   But last week when I returned to the city I have always
considered home to see relatives and frolic in the Atlantic Ocean,
my emotions were a grab bag of sadness, anger and regret.
</P>
<P>
   After living in Atlanta for the past 2 1/2 years, I returned to
Miami, the place where I was raised. My parents and I _ a
3-month-old infant at the time _ moved there in October 1960 after
leaving a turbulent Havana, Cuba, in the throes of Fidel Castro's
communism.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Miami is almost no different, mired in its own ugly episode
of hatred and rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   The beautiful city is torn and raw, a place where politicians
are raging, where friends are bickering and where brothers, sisters
and cousins have turned their backs on each other because they
refuse to accept one another's views.
</P>
<P>
   It's all about a 6-year-old Cuban boy who innocently landed on
U.S. shores after his mother, stepfather and nine other people died
at sea when the small motorboat they used to escape Cuba capsized.
The verbal wars also are about the aging Castro, who after 40 years
in power in the island nation, is still pushing the buttons of
Miami's Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   We all know the saga of young Elian Gonzalez and the history of
the 73-year-old dictator.
</P>
<P>
   But the emotional destruction left in Miami after federal agents
seized Elian from the home of his relatives April 22 is worse than
any hurricane the city has ever weathered.
</P>
<P>
   Natural disasters tend to unite a community. The wake left by
this child's plight has destroyed this one.
</P>
<P>
   Driving through the city's Little Havana section last week, my
mother and I could not help but struggle with the knots in our
throats. My mother, in her early 20s when she left Havana, began to
cry. The scene before her was jarring. Cuban flags of every size
flew from the windows of homes and businesses. They flew from cars,
trucks and SUVs driven by both young and old. Signs bemoaning
Elian's departure were posted everywhere and anywhere room would
permit. Most of the signs screamed angry words at President Clinton
and Attorney General Janet Reno. The hatred was palpable as we
rolled though the streets in our tiny rental car.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is so awful,'' my mother said to me in Spanish as we
turned onto a street where a man sold Elian T-shirts from a rickety
wooden cart. ``The story of this little boy, these signs, all the
hatred on the Cuban radio stations and on TV, it's the history of
our country unfolding right in front of us. It's always been so
tormented.''
</P>
<P>
   Both of us gulped when we spotted the shiny black ribbons tied
to every chain link fence in the row of houses across the street
from the tiny home where Elian stayed for five months. The front
yard of the home of Lazaro Gonzalez _ Elian's great uncle _ is
jammed with bouquets of wilting flowers and stuffed animals stained
by mud and rain; the wooden swing set where the world watched the
charming boy play daily, was depressing in the punishing Florida
sun, quiet and empty.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of neighbors stood in front of their homes, their
faces blank. One man sat in a small lawn chair in the middle of the
street in front of the Gonzalez home. He held a Cuban flag in his
left hand as he staged a silent vigil for who knows what.
</P>
<P>
   We stayed at my aunt's house in Coral Gables, just west of
Miami. Nightly we were treated to the constant banter of
commentators bashing the U.S. government on Spanish-language radio.
My aunt and her husband, both staunch anti-Castro Cubans, had very
definite opinions of how things should have played out in the Elian
situation. While we understand their feelings and support their
anti-Communist sentiments, there were some things we disagreed
with.
</P>
<P>
   But for the first time ever, neither my mother nor I dared to
air our views. Our relatives would have harshly criticized us for
opposing them. We would have argued and it would have gotten ugly.
This was a first for me, a normally outspoken woman.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, we met a man at a friend's house. His name is
Jorge Vasquez. He told us this ugly situation would pit friend
against friend, neighbor against neighbor: ``People are fighting
over this. It's one of the worst things that has ever happened to
Miami.'' On April 28, more than 80,000 Cuban-Americans marched in
Little Havana in a peaceful protest decrying the federal raid that
took Elian. There were angry words. There was mockery of Clinton,
Reno and Castro. But mostly there was resignation. A few miles
south, 2,500 Anglos held their own protest against the
Cuban-American community along U.S. 1. A small plane flew above the
demonstrators with a banner that read: ``One down, 800,000 more to
go.'' The sign referred to Elian and the 800,000 Cuban-Americans
who live in Dade County. A man dragged a Cuban flag on the street.
</P>
<P>
   That made me angry. Never before had I felt so Cuban as at that
very moment. Why did this man drag the flag of my country? In all
the years I had lived in Miami, I had never seen such turmoil. As a
journalist, I had covered riots in Miami, but never had I seen
people so torn apart. Now I know why the man with the distant look
on his face keeps his silent vigil in front of the Gonzalez home in
Little Havana. He stares at Elian's empty swing set and jungle gym
and wonders if Miami will ever be at peace again.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 1948EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
