<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1272 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-DNA-FREEDOM-BOS &LR;      05-10 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNA-FREEDOM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DNA TEST FREES INNOCENT MAN JAILED 10 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He cried the first night the prison doors closed behind
him.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote poetry and short stories to help pass the decade he
spent behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   Then, three years ago, Neil J. Miller made a request that
changed his life. Adamant that he had not committed the crime for
which he was serving 10 to 25 years in jail, he asked a lawyer if
genetic testing might free him.
</P>
<P>
   It did.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, with a dozen jubilant friends and family members
gathered around him, many offering public prayers of thanks, Miller
walked out of a courthouse, freed by sophisticated DNA testing that
wasn't available when he was convicted of raping and robbing an
Emerson College student in her apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Praise be to God,'' Miller, now 33, said in a hallway in
Suffolk Superior Court shortly after his release was announced.
``Praise be to God.''
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by attorneys for the New York-based Innocence Project,
which helped exonerate him, Miller insisted that he harbored no
resentment despite spending the past decade behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't hate nobody,'' he said. ``I don't hold no animosity
toward anybody. But I hope I can move on, the victim can move on,
and everybody else can move on.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Miller was convicted of the aggravated rape and armed
robbery of the 19-year-old student, who identified him from a
photograph, and later in person, as the man who had assaulted her
in her apartment on August 24, 1989.
</P>
<P>
   But with the aid of DNA testing coordinated by the Innocence
Project, based at the Benjamin Cardozo School of Law, Miller was
able to prove that he was not the source of semen found on the
victim's bed and body.
</P>
<P>
   Informed of the newly discovered evidence, the Suffolk County
District Attorney's Office and Boston Police acknowledged Miller's
innocence and arranged for his release.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's exoneration marks the third time in the past year that
men convicted of crimes in Suffolk County have been freed, although
Miller is the only one of the three freed as a result of DNA
testing.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, however, Marvin Mitchell was released from prison after
DNA tests showed he was not the man who had raped a 12-year-old
girl abducted from a bus stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Miller spent ten years in prison for a crime he didn't
commit,'' said Innocence Project co-director Peter Neufeld, who
called Miller's imprisonment ``a disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Neufeld praised prosecutors for cooperating with efforts to free
Miller. But he had harsh words for the criminal process that
resulted in Miller's wrongful conviction.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, he questioned prosecutors' reliance on
cross-racial identification, citing statistics that indicate that
people have difficulty identifying someone of another race.
</P>
<P>
   Miller is black and the victim is white.
</P>
<P>
   ``The machinery of this justice system is unfortunately very
broken at the moment,'' Neufeld said, ``and is going to need some
serious reform.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Neufeld, Miller is the 65th person in the United
States to have been unjustly convicted and later cleared by DNA
testing, and the second in Boston. Of those 65, Neufeld noted,
eight were on death row.
</P>
<P>
   As Miller was released, he was surrounded by a circle of friends
and family, including one woman who videotaped the long-awaited
reunion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is beyond words,'' said Glynnada Hayes-John, Miller's
cousin. ``I mean, he's been locked up for ten years and you can't
get that back. But we're going to make the most of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy,'' added Miller, who plans to live temporarily with
his sister in Boston until he saves enough money for a place of his
own, ``but I'm also nervous and scared.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
