<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1273 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-ONLINE-SURVEY-NYT     05-10 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-SURVEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY FINDS INTERNET OF SOCIAL BENEFIT TO USERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By REBECCA FAIRLEY RANEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although Internet use has become associated more and more with
social isolation, some researchers are finding that the opposite
may be true.
</P>
<P>
   According to a study released on Wednesday by the Pew Internet
and American Life Project, a research center in Washington, more
than half of Internet users found that e-mail was strengthening
their family ties. And Internet users in the study reported far
more offline social contact than non-users. Women in particular
said they found e-mail very useful in keeping in touch with friends
and family.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that Internet users have a more robust social
network than non-Internet users,'' said Lee Rainie, director of the
project. ``There doesn't seem like there's any diminution of social
networks because people are spending a lot of time online.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet users in the study were far more likely to report that
they had a significant network of relatives and friends to call on
in time of need. Nearly half of Internet users reported that they
had a social network, but only 38 percent of non-users did. The
more years respondents had been going online, the more likely they
were to report that they had a social network.
</P>
<P>
   And although 8 percent of Internet users said they were socially
isolated, far more non-users _ 18 percent _ reported that they had
either no one or hardly anyone to turn to. On the subject of
offline, real-world contact, nearly 75 percent of Internet users
said they had visited family or friends the day before they were
asked the question, but only 61 percent of non-Internet users said
they had made such visits.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone survey was conducted from March 1 through March
31. Interviews were conducted with 3,533 adults, and 1,690 of those
were Internet users. The sampling error was plus or minus 2.5
percentage points for the full sample, and plus or minus 3
percentage points for data about the Internet users.
</P>
<P>
   These conclusions seem to contradict the findings of a study
released in February by the Stanford Institute for the Quantitative
Study of Society, but the studies took very different approaches.
</P>
<P>
   In that study, the researcher, Prof. Norman Nie, concluded that
the Internet contributed to social alienation. Because people were
spending more time on the Internet, his findings showed, they were
spending less time in social endeavors. The study found that 8
percent of regular Internet users attended fewer social events and
that 59 percent of regular users said they watched less television
as a result of time spent online. Thirteen percent said they spent
less time with friends and family.
</P>
<P>
   For the Stanford study, subjects were asked how much time they
spent on various activities, including time online, but were not
asked how they felt about their online communication. The Pew study
asked about the quality of their online communication and whether
subjects felt that it had improved their relationships, but the
study did not ask how much time they spent on activities online and
offline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are measuring communication and contact among people,
e-mail being an important component of that communication and
connection,'' said Rainie, director of the Pew study. The Stanford
study's conclusions, he said, were based on ``a value judgment that
any kind of conversational contact was more socially valuable than
other types of contact.'' The study distinguished between e-mail,
telephone conversations and face-to-face visits.
</P>
<P>
   Nie, the researcher on the Stanford study, said that if he had
to do it over, he would ask how people felt about the quality of
their Internet communication. However, he said, ``that's not
something survey research is particularly good at.'' Such questions
would be more appropriate for a psychologist's couch, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was convinced that e-mail communication was not as
valuable as face-to-face interaction. For example, he said, some of
his relatives had recently sent e-mail from every port while
touring the world on a sailboat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was wonderful to hear about their exciting tales,'' Nie
said, ``but it had none of the emotional quality of spending an
evening with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The different conclusions of the studies could signal the
beginning of a stream of seemingly contradictory studies about the
Internet. Bruce Bimber, director of the Center for Information
Technology and Society at the University of California at Santa
Barbara, said the contrast between the two studies showed that the
Internet had become too diverse to examine as a singular
phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers discovered the same thing about television in past
years. Though studies of television viewing showed that the
audience was less engaged in society, those who watched public
television were more engaged. The same may be true for segments of
the Internet-using population, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to stop thinking about the Internet as a single entity
with a single effect,'' Bimber said. ``It's going to take several
more years before the research has a standard set of measures.
Before we do that, we're going to get pieces of the puzzle that
don't necessarily fit together but aren't contradictory.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pew study produced separate data for men and women with some
clear differences. The study reported that about 9 million women
had gone online for the first time in the last six months, a number
that comprises about one-tenth of all women in the United States.
For the first time, women make up half the Internet population.
</P>
<P>
   Women, the study found, are more likely than men to say that
e-mail has improved relationships with family and friends. Nearly
60 percent of women said they found e-mail very useful for
communicating with family members, but only 44 percent of men said
so.
</P>
<P>
   The study showed little evidence that time on the Internet
prevents people from communicating in other ways. For example,
parents and children who exchange e-mail said they talked on the
phone just as often. More than 75 percent said they talked on the
phone at least once a week and sent e-mail just as much.
</P>
<P>
   They did not deride the use of e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're asking people to judge the value of that contact, and
they're reporting that they value that contact,'' Rainie said.
``They felt there were improvements and a greater volume of
communication. You can make the case that that's a social
benefit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
