<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-FORECAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSY HURRICANE SEASON FORECAST; EXPERTS CALL PREPARATION CRUCIAL
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Weather forecasters for the federal government said
Wednesday that residents along the East Coast and in the Caribbean
should prepare for a particularly active hurricane season this
year, with stronger and longer-lasting storms.
</P>
<P>
   The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration expects an
``above average'' hurricane season. Eleven or more tropical storms
have been predicted, with seven developing into hurricanes; three
or more will be major hurricanes, officials said. (A major
hurricane reaches maximum sustained winds of more than 110 mph.)
</P>
<P>
   D. James Baker, the under secretary for oceans and atmosphere at
the Department of Commerce, said that La Nina, which is defined by
cooler than average temperatures in the central and eastern
tropical Pacific, continues to a have significant influence on
weather conditions and hurricane forecasts. The current forecast
suggests that La Nina will fade by August.
</P>
<P>
   ``During last year's hurricane season,'' Baker said, ``La Nina
was bold, and clearly defined, and gave forecasters more
certainty.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the remnants of La Nina, combined with other weather
patterns including warmer than normal Atlantic Ocean temperatures,
will ``affect hurricane activity over very long time scales.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker said the conditions are ``ripe for hurricane activity.''
</P>
<P>
   La Nina, which has dominated global weather patterns for the
last two years, is responsible also for worsening drought
conditions in the Midwest and South, weather officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Warm conditions have arrived early this year along the East
Coast, with record high temperatures in some places. And rainfall
has been inconsistent in the last few months, depleting soil
moisture in a swath of states throughout the South and Midwest,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The drought will ``get worse before it gets better,'' said John
Kelly, assistant administrator at the oceanic and atmospheric
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Improvements in forecast technology are helping meteorologists
track storms, but hurricanes and tropical storms wreak havoc every
year along coastal regions. Last year, five hurricanes struck
mainland United States, killing 60 people, according to the oceanic
administration.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane season runs from June 1 to Nov. 30. During the
peak months _ August to October _ many of the storms begin over the
tropical Atlantic Ocean and move toward the Caribbean Islands or
the coastal United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential for economic catastrophe in coastal cities and
towns has increased dramatically in recent years because more and
more people are moving to the coasts,'' said Secretary of Commerce
William Daley, who oversees the oceanic and atmospheric
administration. ``It is imperative that local residents and
businesses be prepared to protect themselves and their property.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
