<HEADER>
A1279 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-CHIPS-COX     05-10 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHIPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chips are hot stuff these days
 &HT;    By Kirk Ladendorf
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chip company stocks may have been hammered on Wednesday, but the
sell-off is anything but indicative of the state of the
semiconductor industry.
</P>
<P>
   Chips are hot stuff these days, and many of the companies that
make them have embarked on expensive campaigns to build and equip
factories to keep pace with demand.
</P>
<P>
   Chips used in wireless phones and equipment and Internet-related
networking gear are the hottest chips going today, but demand is
strong in all sectors of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, semiconductor makers are feeling the effects
of their decision to slow down spending on factories and equipment
during the industry's three-year slump that began in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they are scrambling like mad to add capacity,'' said
George Burns, an analyst with Strategic Marketing Associates in
Santa Cruz, Calif., which tracks the chip industry's factory
investment. ``This is a boom-and-bust industry and right now, we're
in the boom.''
</P>
<P>
   Around Austin, which is second only to Silicon Valley in its
concentration of chip companies, the effects aren't hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola Inc. workers in East Austin have been working for weeks
to install dozens of pieces of advanced manufacturing equipment
into MOS 13, the company's most advanced chip factory. It also is
expanding its other two local factories.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola will spend more than $400 million at MOS 13, the bulk
of $600 million its spending at all three of its Austin chip
factories this year. The expansion push is part of Motorola's $2.6
billion worldwide spending plan worldwide to boost chip production
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola's aggressive expansion plans are just a small part of
the record $55 billion that chip makers expect to spend on
factories and equipment this year in response to the sudden strong
surge in demand for chips.
</P>
<P>
   The big expansion plans by Motorola and other chip makers has
meant money in the coffers of Applied Materials Inc., which on
Wednesday reported record earnings, sales, new orders and
backlogged orders for the quarter ended April 30.
</P>
<P>
   Applied, which announced heavy layoffs less than two years ago,
now is making chip equipment in Austin almost around the clock. The
company has 4,500 workers in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Intel Corp., the chip industry's largest player, plans to spend
$6 billion this year on new factory capacity designed meet
continued strong demand for its Pentium processors. Intel also
plans to spend $100 million over the next year to build and equip a
new chip design center in downtown Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's main rival, Advanced Micro Devices Inc., does almost all
of its domestic manufacturing in Austin and employs some 4,500
people locally. It has budgeted $700 million on capital spending
this year, with most of that money targeted for its new factory
Dresden, Germany, which expects to ship its first commercial
products in June.
</P>
<P>
   AMD's management also is talking with partner Fujitsu Ltd. in
Japan about adding to their Japanese joint venture manufacturing
operation for non-volatile flash memories, which are used in
wireless phones and other devices.
</P>
<P>
   AMD won't disclose how much it is spending in Austin this year,
but the company said it continues to add equipment to Fab 25 as its
shifts production from its older K6-2 processors to its more
advanced Athlon chips. Samsung Austin Semiconductor will spend
another $200 million this year on advanced manufacturing equipment
that will allow its Austin factory _ its only domestic
manufacturing plant _ to make more advanced memory chips.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cypress Semiconductor Corp. plans to add 10 percent
to the capacity of its Round Rock manufacturing plant, but the
company still has no plans this year to start again building the
major chip factory project there that it canceled in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cypress is trying very hard not to get caught up in this mass
building hysteria to add capacity,'' said spokesman Joe McCarthy.
The company does plan to build the unfinished project in Round Rock
sometime in the future, he added.
</P>
<P>
   At Motorola, the Austin expansion is part of a company-wide push
to boost manufacturing capacity by 30 percent this year from its
worldwide chip sales of more than $7 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are aggressively going after business,'' said Bill Walker,
Motorola's top executive for chip manufacturing. ``You have to take
advantage of it while the business is there. You've got to keep
building.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker said Motorola's expansion should create 400 to 500 new
manufacturing jobs in Austin this year. Despite those new jobs, the
company said its Austin employment remains at about 10,000 _ the
same level as four years ago. The company prefers to round its
local employment figures to the nearest 1,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola also will close its 25-year-old MOS 3 factory in East
Austin this year. The factory, which makes chips from small 4-inch
diameter silicon wafers, is no longer considered to be competitive,
Walker said. Workers will be transferred to the company's other
factories in the Austin area.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman explained that even though the company is hiring
workers, work force attrition helps keep its total employment close
to 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Does the current expansion in the chip business mean chip makers
will have too much capacity for their own good in the near future?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, industry analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the semiconductor industry and, of course, they are
going to overdo it,'' said Burns, the analyst. ``We have a year and
a half before we see a slump in equipment spending.''
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Kirk Ladendorf at kladendorf(at)statesman.com or
445-3622.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
