u a BC-JONBENET-COX     05-10 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JONBENET-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ramseys sue book publishers
 &HT;    By Andrea Ball
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ John and Patsy Ramsey sued a Fredericksburg
publisher and two Travis County businessmen for $11.7 million,
claiming their book wrongly called the Ramsey's 13-year-old son a
murderer.
</P>
<P>
   Windsor House Publishing Group is accused of libeling Burke
Ramsey in its book, ``A Little Girl's Dream? A JonBenet Ramsey
Story.'' The book claims Burke sexually molested and killed his
6-year-old sister JonBenet in 1996. He was 9 at the time of the
murder.
</P>
<P>
   The Ramseys call the book malicious, negligent and false in the
lawsuit filed late Tuesday in Travis County District Court _ one of
several filed nationwide in defense of Burke.
</P>
<P>
   But Dwight Wallington, owner of Windsor House and the book's
author, isn't backing off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad they're suing us,'' said Wallington, whose company
was in Austin when the book was published in 1998. ``I welcome it.
Now we can get at the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   The suits also names Travis County residents Peter Des Camps and
James Conn of Windsor-Golf Distribution, a now-defunct holding
company involved with financing the book. ``We are investigating
the claims in the lawsuit and will issue a statement later,'' Des
Camps said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit also names Eleanor Von Duyke, a beauty pageant
organizer listed as the book's co-author. The book was to be an
account of Von Duyke's experience in the pageant industry, but the
focus later shifted to JonBenet, Wallington said.
</P>
<P>
   Von Duyke, whom Wallington said was angered by the final version
of the book, could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   JonBenet was found beaten and strangled Dec. 26, 1996 in the
basement of her parents' home in Boulder, Colo. Police have said
Burke is not a suspect but that John and Patsy Ramsey remain
``under an umbrella of suspicion.''
</P>
<P>
   Since her death, the blonde JonBenet has been the subject of
countless books, tabloid covers and television shows. Amateur and
professional sleuths continue to publicly speculate on the little
girl's grisly fate.
</P>
<P>
   Wallington, who said he worked on the book for five months,
theorizes that Burke habitually molested JonBenet and accidentally
killed her that December night. The Ramsey's dispute the
allegation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Burke Ramsey was a happy, normal 9-year-old boy prior to his
sister's murder,'' the lawsuit reads. ``He did not engage in sexual
molestation or abuse of his little sister JonBenet. He is not a
chronic liar as the defendants have claimed. And, most important of
all, Burke Ramsey did not kill his younger sister.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit is one of a string of libel suits filed by the
Ramseys in defense of their son. On Monday, they sued the New York
Post and Time Warner for $4 million each, and several other
lawsuits are pending, said Lin Wood, the Ramsey's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Wood said Burke has seen the tabloid headlines, and the family
fears that he will be emotionally scarred by the accusations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He, fortunately, has a young person's God-given defenses,''
Wood said from his Atlanta office. ``Everything is fine right now.
But this could hurt him down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallington stands by his book.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did I do this to bother Burke Ramsey? No,'' Wallington said.
``Did I do it to get to the truth? Absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Ball at aball(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
