<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-TRAVEL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWNLOAD TRAVEL PLANS AND INFORMATION ON A HANDHELD DEVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By JOE HUTSKO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whether your travels take you to another city or another
continent, it helps to know something about your destination: where
to eat, where to stay or what to see. In the past, that meant
taking along travel or restaurant guides and a pocket diary for
keeping track of travel arrangements, appointments, reservations,
torn pages from directories, maps and other bits of travel-related
data.
</P>
<P>
   Now you can carry all that information on a computer. Although a
laptop can make a handy travel companion, the smaller, handheld
personal digital assistants are even more convenient.
</P>
<P>
   With pocket-size handhelds, there are basically two choices:
devices running the Palm operating system, like Palm's own
handhelds or the Handspring Visor, and those from Casio, Compaq and
Hewlett-Packard, which use Microsoft's Windows CE operating system
or its newer, more capable successor, Pocket PC. Just as the Palm
camp has a lead of many millions of units over the Microsoft
faction, Palm and its cousins also have the edge in travel
products.
</P>
<P>
   There is a lot of travel information available for handhelds,
which is useful even if your idea of traveling involves nothing
more than a trip to a new neighborhood in search of an exotic meal.
The publishers of popular travel and entertainment guidebooks have
a presence on the Web, and some have adapted their products to the
handheld market. From Fodor's to Frommer's, Lonely Planet to Zagat,
the guides served up by these brand names for online or handheld
use generally match their printed counterparts in tone, style and
content.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers loyal to any of the guides can visit their Web sites
for products, services and online addendums to the printed
editions. Users must pay to download some information, but all
offer some free online-based services and listings that can be
saved to a PDA as a text file or Web page.
</P>
<P>
   Downloadable guides vary in depth and price. Zagat restaurant
guides for Palm devices, for instance, are published by Landware
for $29.95 for the first city and $14.95 for each additional city.
Also for Palm-based devices are the Weissmann City Profiles guides,
published by Aramis and priced at $59.95 for a package of major
cities in either the United States or Europe. Information about
individual cities can also be downloaded for $12.95 each.
</P>
<P>
   More in tune with modern trekkers are the Web-based upstarts
that are challenging the old hands with innovative services. The
goods and services they offer are free to subscribers; advertising
is the source of their revenue.
</P>
<P>
   A leader in the handheld information-on-the-go trade is AvantGo,
which runs on both Palm and Windows CE and Pocket PC devices.
Gaining access to the software and services requires registering
with the site, then downloading the information to a PDA. AvantGo
organizes the available Web sites, called channels, by categories.
For travelers, the City/Regional and Travel categories are most
useful.
</P>
<P>
   Choices in these categories are many and far-reaching, including
a version of the popular CitySearch.com service, which gives a
rundown of what is going on in most United States (and some
foreign) cities. The information includes live shows and movies,
restaurants, nightclubs and other recreation and events. Other
AvantGo travel channels include a mapping program for getting from
Point A to Point B, and RestaurantRow-.com, which organizes
restaurants based on ZIP code and will even phone or mail in a
reservation on your behalf through the channel's concierge service.
</P>
<P>
   After the user picks channels of interest, the AvantGo site
plucks the desired bits of information from the partners (including
The New York Times) that are the sources of material. That data is
transferred to the handheld the next time the user runs Palm's
HotSync program or Microsoft's ActiveSync on Pocket PC's.
ActiveSync can also be set to update the handheld constantly as
long as it is in its cradle, connected to the computer.
</P>
<P>
   Both Pocket PC and Palm users may also choose to turn any Web
page into a custom channel. The Pocket PC approach is a one-step
process, requiring only a click of the Create Mobile Favorite menu
in Internet Explorer to send the page to the device the next time
it is synchronized. Palm users use AvantGo to accomplish the same
thing, with an extra step thrown in: they choose how often to
update each page _ at every sync, only once or once a week. AvantGo
for the Pocket PC works the same way.
</P>
<P>
   A compelling new city guide for Palm devices is Vindigo, which,
unlike AvantGo's wide-reaching selection of channels, focuses on
eating, shopping and playing. The service looks only at New York,
although the company says it expects to offer information for other
cities by summer. The Vindigo program gets its information from New
York Today, which is owned by The New York Times Co.
</P>
<P>
   Tap in a location, and Vindigo arranges your options
accordingly, relative to the closest cross-streets. Listings can
also be browsed by neighborhood, and many are accompanied by a
brief review. The program automatically generates walking
directions to get you where you want to go by the most direct
route. The company said it was exploring other platforms, which
means Pocket PC.
</P>
<P>
   For those who want to be connected anywhere, anytime, Palm sells
the Palm VII, a wireless device that gives the user access to the
Palm.Net service, which offers live Web clippings of specific,
tailored information (as opposed to the actual Web sites
themselves). The Palm.Net site's Web clipping applications for
travelers include flight schedules and tracking for major airlines,
traffic coverage and directions, Fodor's and Frommer's guidebooks,
a gas station finder and weather reports.
</P>
<P>
   Palm.Net's Web-clipping service has been criticized for being
too expensive. The basic service is $9.99 a month for 50 kilobytes
of data (about 150 Palm VII screens), an extended plan is $24.99 a
month for 150 kilobytes, and a volume plan is $39.99 for 300
kilobytes. Each plan charges 20 cents a kilobyte if the data limits
are exceeded.
</P>
<P>
   Palm.Net and other vendors are coming up with improvements that
make the Palm VII more useful. For example, PalmNet's new unlimited
plan, for $44.99 a month, lets users clip to their hearts' content.
While Palm.Net's e-mail lets subscribers check only their Palm.Net
e-mail accounts, ThinAir software by ThinAirApps allows the Palm
VII to check e-mail accounts at most other places.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
