<SLUG> BC-U.N.-AFRICA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO PROGRESS SEEN IN ETHIOPIA-ERITREA PEACE EFFORT
</HEADLINE>
  By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASMARA, Eritrea _ A seven-member U.N. Security Council
delegation ended a weeklong trip to Africa unable to persuade the
leaders of Eritrea and Ethiopia to stop preparing for war and to
return instead to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   Within the next few days, the diplomats said, they expect to
begin discussing what steps the Security Council can take to put
more pressure on Prime Minister Meles Zenawi of Ethiopia and
President Isais Afwerki of Eritrea to pull back from battle over a
disputed border.
</P>
<P>
   The ambassadors, from the United States, Britain, France, Mali,
Namibia, the Netherlands and Tunisia, left a series of meetings
with the Eritrean and Ethiopian leaders disappointed to varying
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the delegates cited lack of concern shown by the
countries' leaders, both former guerrillas, when asked to consider
the human consequences of a war that the diplomats unanimously call
``senseless.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither of these two has a sleepless night over this,'' an
ambassador said of Meles and Isais, who had in recent years been
held up as positive examples of a new generation of pragmatic
African politicians.
</P>
<P>
   As leaders of separate nationalist rebel movements that fought
the Ethiopian government for three decades, they were once in
alliance. War broke out between them unexpectedly in 1998, years
after Meles had become prime minister of Ethiopia, and Isais had
successfully seceded to form the independent nation of Eritrea,
taking with him the only Red Sea port at Assab.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference at Asmara airport Wednesday, Richard
Holbrooke, the U.S. representative at the United Nations and the
leader of the delegation, was asked whether Meles and Isais had
decided to go to war and whether any admonition from the Security
Council would make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only say, with great reluctance and foreboding, that the
welfare of the peoples of this region does not receive the priority
that we think it should in the determination of this issue,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The delegation's unusual field trip ended with questions still
hanging over agreements with several other African nations,
specifically those involved in the war in Congo, the former Zaire.
One agreement, with the President Laurent Kabila of Congo is to
open the way for the eventual stationing of U. N. peacekeeping
troops in the country.
</P>
<P>
   After the unraveling last week of a U.N. peacekeeping mission in
Sierra Leone, council members say that they are more determined
than ever to see that a mission to Congo is deployed carefully and
commanded effectively.
</P>
<P>
   The mission in Sierra Leone has been criticized as being below
strength and poorly commanded by an Indian general, Vijay Kumar
Jetley. The mission intended for Congo is smaller than that in
Sierra Leone, though Congo is many times larger.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council delegation, which began its trip on May 3
in Brussels, visited not only Congo, but also Zambia, where a Congo
peace accord was signed almost a year ago; Zimbabwe, which supports
Kabila with troops; and Rwanda and Uganda, two nations that once
supported Kabila but are now fighting him with their troops and
through rebel groups.
</P>
<P>
   The envoys said that most of the leaders they met want to get
out of the Congo war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 2007EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
