<P>
   POLITICS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-HEALTH-CARE (Davenport, Iowa) _ Republican George W. Bush
proposes tax incentives for the elderly to buy health-care
insurance and financial relief for people who care for a parent or
other elderly relative at home. The plans were fueled by statistics
showing that half of older women and one-third of older men are
likely to need nursing home care. BY CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CALIFORNIA (Washington) _ Because California and its
critical electoral votes remain very much in play, both Vice
President Al Gore and Republican George W. Bush are spending lots
of time and money there. Bush went last week, and this week, the
vice president hits Los Angeles in a swing of the South and West
that also includes fund-raisers in Little Rock, Dallas and
Portland. BY BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-AIDS (Washington) _ President Clinton, circumventing
Congress, issues an executive order allowing Africa to import and
produce generic AIDS drugs. A similar measure, opposed by major
drug companies that produce expensive brand-name AIDS medicines,
was recently blocked by lawmakers. By JUDY HOLLAND. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANES (Washington) _ Residents along the Gulf Coast should
brace for more hurricanes than average this season _ possibly seven
or more _ according to a forecast issued by the National Weather
Service. By PHILIP CAUTHON.
</P>
<P>
   TELEPHONE-TAX (Washington) _ House Republican leaders announce
they will try to abolish the federal excise tax on telephone lines,
which they say would make it easier for people to access the
Internet. By AUSTIN ZALKIN. (Already filed.) (Also filed in the
Financial ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RAILROAD-KILLER (Houston) _ The doctor who diagnosed Angel
Maturino Resendiz as paranoid schizophrenic testifies that the
admitted serial killer believed he was following God's will when he
killed nine people in three states. Maturino Resendiz, 40, has
pleaded innocent by reason of insanity in the rape, bludgeoning and
stabbing of Houston-area physician Dr. Claudia Benton, who was
found dead in her home Dec. 18, 1998. He could face the death
penalty if convicted. By LISA TEACHEY.
</P>
<P>
   METHODISTS-GAYS (Cleveland, Ohio) _ More than 150 gay-rights
supporters _ including the grandson of Mahatma Gandhi and the
daughter of Martin Luther King _ are arrested outside a summit of
the United Methodist church in Cleveland. The demonstrators were
protesting the church's policies on homosexuals, which include
calling homosexuality ``incompatible with Christian teaching,''
prohibiting same-sex unions and barring the ordination of openly
gay members as clergy. By RICHARD VARA.
</P>
