<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1289 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-PRODUCT-TESTS-ART     05-10 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-PRODUCT-TESTS-ART-975-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACK IS PUT THROUGH THE WRINGER, SO YOU WON'T BE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By DANIEL SORID    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his 15 years on the job, Jack has been trapped in coal mines
and forced to lift and carry objects that could break his back, and
once while pregnant _ yes, pregnant _ was stuffed into a car to see
if he could fit behind the wheel and reach the pedals.
</P>
<P>
   Jack never complains, however, because Jack is a piece of
software, a virtual reality representation of a person who can take
on various forms _ like a bulky man or a pregnant woman _ then
operate within various environments and sometimes in concert with
other virtual humans.
</P>
<P>
   Developed at the University of Pennsylvania beginning in 1984,
Jack has spent more than a decade in the service of industry and
government, showing car manufacturers whether their designs can
accommodate a person of a certain size, or construction companies
whether a particular task might leave employees injured and
unproductive. He has even helped the U.S. military train soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of flesh and blood, Jack is made of computer code and
lives in a virtual world inside a video monitor. Jack _ named for
the child's toy, which resembles the axes of a three-dimensional
computer model _ can walk, avoid obstacles, reach and lift. But if
he cannot perform a certain task _ if an object is too heavy or out
of reach _ an image of the character will signal a problem,
sometimes by turning a body part a different color on a computer
screen. Jack rolls with the punches so that we don't have to.
</P>
<P>
   With a virtual reality helmet or a video screen, users of the
software can also see through Jack's eyes. In one instance, Jack
caused the John Deere tractor company to send a prototype back to
the drawing board after the company found that the design
obstructed Jack's view of the vehicle's blades.
</P>
<P>
   ``They went back and redesigned those parts of the tractor long
before it went into production and saved them an uncountable number
of dollars,'' said Prof. Norman Badler, director of the Center for
Human Modeling and Simulation at Penn. ``Once there's a production
line, you don't want to change the design.''
</P>
<P>
   Although many companies have developed human-looking digital
characters with limited capabilities, like the wide-eyed virtual
newscaster Ananova, several companies and universities have
developed ``intelligent'' virtual human beings that are programmed
to move and even respond like people.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual humans like Jack can be placed on a virtual battlefield,
in a simulated car interior or in any other environment that can be
created on a computer. The virtual human is then programmed to
perform a specific act _ like Jack reaching for the car's cigarette
lighter, which causes him to bump his head on the dashboard _ and
the results are displayed on Jack's image on a computer screen and
numerically on a printout. Designers can add realism to the
environment by importing graphics and special effects.
</P>
<P>
   Developers of this type of software are trying to imitate the
complexity of real people as closely as possible. Recently, more
sophisticated virtual humans have been programmed with
psychological traits to study how people might react in an
emergency, like a chemical fire or a riot.
</P>
<P>
   In one situation, a crowd of protesters, waving fists and
holding banners, walks down a city street. Each protester is
programmed with a mood and a personality, which determine reactions
to different events, like a knife being pulled or police firing a
shot. Watching these reactions over the entire crowd would show
authorities how best to maintain safety in various situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ultimate objective in creating realistic and believable
virtual actors is to build intelligent autonomous virtual humans
with adaptation, perception and memory,'' said Prof. Daniel
Thalmann, director of the Computer Graphics Lab at the Swiss
Federal Institute of Technology, in Lausanne. ``These actors should
be able to act freely and emotionally. Ideally, they should be
conscious and unpredictable.''
</P>
<P>
   The earliest virtual humans were developed in the 1960s. One of
their earliest applications was in testing an aircraft landing
procedure. In 1981 the U.S. government financed a project at the
University of Pennsylvania to develop a virtual human model for
engineering design studies. The software, a precursor to Jack,
demonstrated to NASA that the toilet system on the space shuttle
needed to be redesigned to accommodate larger astronauts.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1990s, Jack had become more realistic. ``You don't make
the brain smarter, you make the rest of the body smarter, getting
it to walk properly, use its arms and legs to reach properly at
steering wheels, pedals and knobs, lifting things properly,''
Badler said. ``Within the last 10 years the main emphasis of what
we've done has been on telling the model what to do rather than
showing it in excruciating detail what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   A more advanced Jack, for example, could be instructed through a
voice interface to take cover behind a vehicle, rather than have to
be programmed with the specific motions needed for that task. The
University of Pennsylvania's human modeling center, which still
uses the Jack software, is working on expanding Jack's ability to
respond to natural language commands.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Jack was sold to Transom Technologies, which was later
acquired by Engineering Animation, a company that specializes in
visual applications for engineering and manufacturing. Today the
company charges about $25,000 for the Jack software, according to
Ulrich Raschke, Engineering Animation's program manager for virtual
simulation. Developing a cast of characters, placing them in an
environment and assigning them tasks requires hours or days,
depending on complexity, Raschke said. The software, however, does
not require expensive computers and can run on a high-end PC.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Other companies have developed software similar to Jack. Boston
Dynamics specializes in virtual humans software for military and
law enforcement use. The software can train soldiers for ground
attacks, urban combat, biological warfare and medical emergencies.
In one application, the motions of a human soldier carrying a mock
weapon and running on a treadmill can be transferred to a virtual
counterpart running along a path, ready to attack.
</P>
<P>
   Training software that relies on virtual reality provides
several advantages over other training methods, including one
called branched video. A video with real actors plays on a screen
in front of a trainee who wields a gunlike device that is connected
to the video system. The actors in the video scene respond to the
actions of the trainee.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual systems provide real-time feedback to the participant
and are cheaper than branched video. And unlike branched video, in
which the number of scenes is limited, a virtual system can relay
specific responses to each of a participant's actions and thereby
introduce more variables into the scenario.
</P>
<P>
   In a checkpoint monitoring system being developed for the Navy,
trainees will control Jack with voice commands during
computer-guided emergencies, like a terrorist threat. The
simulation can be run over and over, with different results each
time. ``If you want to train a soldier at a checkpoint, you would
rather they encounter the bad situation in simulation rather than
in real life,'' Badler said.
</P>
<P>
   Although single virtual actors can help train individuals, some
organizations are using virtual humans in groups to try to model
crowd psychology. The Swiss Federal Institute of Technology, Matra
Systemes &AMP; Information of France and Britain's Scotland Yard are
working together on a system to simulate emergencies like a
chemical plant explosion or a riot. Individuals in the crowd are
programmed with personalities and moods, and react in different way
to the emergency. The system can help security agencies understand
how crowds react and how best to use police officers and other
emergency workers to keep order.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, the members of these virtual crowds would interact the
way humans do. But crude graphics and the limits of artificial
intelligence have kept interactions fairly basic. ``Human
expressions are very, very complicated,'' said Barbara Rothbaum, an
associate professor of psychiatry at the Emory University School of
Medicine, who is working on a project to use virtual reality
simulations to treat phobias in patients. ``We might make a
distinction between a genuine smile, a sinister smile and a
not-so-genuine smile. You're not going to make those distinctions
as a virtual human.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, fairly complicated applications like crowd control are
useful even with the current state of the technology. ``Think about
cartoons,'' Rothbaum said, ``and how they relay a lot of
information in really fairly simple lines: the direction of the
eyebrows, the direction of the shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   While some systems can cost thousands of dollars, spending $50
at the video game store can give regular computer users a chance to
interact with their virtual counterparts. The Sims, a popular game
from Electronic Arts, has impressed the researchers with its
realistic human characters who interact with family and friends.
Badler is purchasing a copy for his lab, to try to link it with his
advanced systems.
</P>
<P>
   That home computer users can interact with believable virtual
humans on their PCs is a testament to how advances in computing
power might propel virtual humans into many more aspects of
production, training and entertainment. The next logical step might
be to find people modeling a whole range of actions _ traveling,
business, sleeping _ with virtual humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can imagine going onto the Web with an avatar that looks
very much like yourself and going into chat rooms and basically
presenting yourself virtually on the Web and controlling
yourself,'' said Raschke of Engineering Animation. ``You can really
expand this out to the whole range of what humans are involved
with. Let your imagination go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 2012EDT &QL; 
