u p BC-BUSH-TAXES-NYT     05-10 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-TAXES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH PROPOSES TAX BREAKS TO COVER LONG-TERM CARE
</HEADLINE>
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVENPORT, Iowa _ Gov. George W. Bush proposed a set of tax
breaks Wednesday to encourage more people to purchase long-term
care insurance and to ease the financial burden on people looking
after ailing relatives at home.
</P>
<P>
   Under Bush's plan, which anticipates the fast-growing number of
older Americans, people of any age who buy insurance for the kind
of extended nursing-home stays not covered by other policies or by
Medicare could fully deduct the annual premium from their taxes,
whether they itemize deductions or not.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, people with aging dependents at home could claim
an extra exemption, which would amount to a nonitemized deduction
of about $2,750.
</P>
<P>
   ``To many of our seniors, illness can be a path to financial
ruin, and this is one of the greatest fears of retirement and our
nation must address it as we head into the 21st century,'' Bush
told a group of about 80 at a nursing home here.
</P>
<P>
   ``This cost can undermine the whole idea of security in
retirement,'' he added. ``It's time for many Americans to prepare _
prepare for peace-of-mind insurance. It must become a central part
of retirement planning in America.`
</P>
<P>
   The scope and expense of Bush's proposal was modest _ it would
cost $7.4 billion over five years _ and some critics said it would
make only the smallest of dents in a problem turning ever more
severe. But the plan represented Bush's attempt to demonstrate that
he was paying heed to health care and to senior citizens, an issue
and a voting block that could be decisive in the presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
   Bush seemed to take the dynamics of the electorate into full
account with remarks that aimed for a kind of political trifecta,
singling out and offering reassurances not only to elderly
Americans but also to members of the baby-boom generation and to
women. His message to baby boomers was that their anticipatory
qualms about retirement were foremost in his mind, while his nod to
women voters was his recognition that they typically shoulder most
of the responsibility for older relatives.
</P>
<P>
   But the elderly were arguably his most important audience,
because Vice President Al Gore has asserted that he has more
thoughtful and responsible ideas for both health care and Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was clearly trying to challenge that claim and intends to
follow Wednesday's proposals with a speech on Monday that will
outline his philosophy on changing Social Security and Medicare and
dealing with the high cost of prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The high stakes of the presidential candidates' jostling over
these issues was suggested by the fact the Gore campaign arranged
for reporters to talk on the phone Wednesday with U.S. Secretary of
Health and Human Services Donna Shalala.
</P>
<P>
   Shalala did not seem to be fully aware about what, exactly, Bush
was recommending, but she said that the plausibility of any and all
of his proposals was thrown into doubt by his call for a tax cut of
$483 billion over five years, which is much larger than the tax cut
Gore favors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way, given the size of his tax cut, that he can pay
for this,'' she said of Bush. ``It's an empty promise.''
</P>
<P>
   Shalala said that the Texas governor's financial incentives for
the purchase of long-term care insurance do nothing to address the
flaws of many of the policies on the market and that the exemption
that Bush would grant home caregivers was nowhere near as generous
as the $3,000 tax credit that the Clinton administration has
proposed and that Gore supports. The exemption, for someone in the
15 percent tax bracket, would amount to only a few hundred dollars
a year.
</P>
<P>
   Long-term care insurance, which fills a gap in what is provided
by private and corporate health care policies and Medicare, covers
the cost of an extended stay in a nursing home or assisted-living
center for people whose financial resources have not dwindled to
the point where they qualify for Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   According to figures provided by the Bush campaign, only about 5
percent of Americans now have such policies.
</P>
<P>
   An aide to Bush said that a 39-year-old would pay an annual
premium of about $358 for a policy that guaranteed two years of
nursing-home care and $507 for a policy that guaranteed five years;
a 64-year-old would pay about $1,265 for the two-year guarantee and
$1,709 for the five-year one. The older a person is when he or she
buys the policy, the more it costs.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 percent of Americans over the age of 65 have annual
incomes under $20,000, and Joshua M. Wiener, a principal research
associate at the Urban Institute in Washington, noted that these
people would be unable to afford such a policy even after Bush's
deduction, which would shave only a few hundred dollars off the
price.
</P>
<P>
   `This is basically for the upper-middle-class elderly,'' he said
of Bush's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's plan also sets no income ceiling for eligibility,
so that wealthy Americans in higher tax brackets would actually
save more on the policies than middle-class Americans, because the
tax deduction would be more valuable for them.
</P>
<P>
   But an aide to Bush said that the governor's plan was not
intended primarily for these people, many of whom have jobs that
already offer long-term care as a benefit and would not qualify for
the deduction.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush, citing figures for the looming rise in the number of
Americans over the age of 65, said it was important to put
mechanisms into place to encourage their financial security and to
decrease the number of them who will end up needing public money
and help.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 2013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
