<SLUG> BC-DELTA-DELAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Boeing strike delays delivery to Delta
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Initial delivery of Delta Air Lines' newest model jetliner has
been delayed two months because of the recent engineers' strike at
Boeing Co.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based airline had been scheduled to get its first
767-400 from Boeing by the end of this month. Deliveries now are
expected to begin at the end of July, when two of the planes will
arrive, Delta spokesman John Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   The 767-400 is a longer, ``stretched'' version of the 767, an
industry workhorse. Delta, the first airline to order the new
model, will use it mainly to replace aging L-1011s on high-volume
domestic flights.
</P>
<P>
   When 767-400s begin arriving, they'll make training runs for
several weeks. They'll start flying Florida and West Coast routes
this fall and fly to Hawaii by year's end, Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Deliveries of other models, such as the Boeing 737-800 and 757,
also are being pushed back several weeks by the effects of the
38-day strike, which ended in mid-March.
</P>
<P>
   As a consequence, Delta will keep flying some of its oldest
L-1011s and 727s a few months longer than planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will need to hold on to some of these aircraft to fly our
planned schedule,'' Delta's senior vice president-flight
operations, Dave Bushy, said in an update to employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, aircraft deliveries will be back on track in the
September-October time frame,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Delta is taking delivery of new planes at a rate of about one a
week under a massive 1997 order that made Boeing its exclusive
supplier. The airline expects to take delivery of 60 over the next
12 months.
</P>
<P>
   The 767-400, which Delta chose over the Airbus A330 as its new
domestic widebody, will carry about 287 passengers in a two-class
configuration, versus 252 for the 767-300 Delta now flies.
</P>
<P>
   It is 21 feet longer and has an extended wingspan, new landing
gear and upgraded cockpit instruments, as well as a remodeled cabin
interior based on the Boeing 777 cabin.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 2017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
