<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1296 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DOW-CONCERN-COX     05-10 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-CONCERN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Investors feel the heat of Fed's inflation policy
 &HT;    By David McNaughton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investors can run _ as they did Wednesday _ but they can't hide
from the Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has dawned on many investors that the Fed might not be near
the end of the tunnel on potential rate increases,'' said Atlanta
money manager Phillip M. Larkins of Legacy South.
</P>
<P>
   There now are expectations the Fed will raise short-term rates
by another 1 percentage point this year, which would take the prime
rate to 10 percent, what First Union economist Mark Vitner
considers a psychologically important level. The prime, a benchmark
for some business and consumer loans, hasn't been that high since
1990.
</P>
<P>
   Concern about how much higher interest rates will go apparently
contributed to Wednesday's slide in the stock market, while bond
prices rose as their appeal increased. Higher rates not only reduce
profits, but they make investors less willing to buy stocks trading
at high prices relative to earnings prospects.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite, also hurt again by worries about the
outlook for Cisco Systems, lost 200 points and 5.6 percent. The Dow
Jones industrial average shed almost 170 points, or 1.6 percent.
Investors are not likely to feel any more at ease today, according
to Vitner. He expects the Commerce Department to report
stronger-than-expected retail sales for April. Most analysts are
looking for an increase of about 0.5 percent. Vitner said he
wouldn't be surprised to see a gain of 0.5 percent to 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the message will be the economy is still way too
strong for the Fed's liking,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Better news, however, may come with Friday's Producer Price
Index and Tuesday's Consumer Price Index, due the same day the Fed
meets to consider what to do about interest rates. Economists
expect the producer index to show a decline for April because of
lower energy costs. Vitner anticipates the CPI will be unchanged or
down, while the number excluding energy and food will be up no more
than 0.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While that's likely to raise questions in some quarters about
how severely the Fed should tighten credit, Vitner said, it
probably won't slow the Fed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Fed would like to do a little more than people
think is needed and reinforce the credibility they have built up as
inflation fighters,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   How much is too much is starting to be debated outside the Fed.
With the economy as strong as it is, Vitner thinks the Fed would
have time to correct any error.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Fed has greater risk in not doing enough,'' added
Larkins. ``There are many investors who were not in the market 10
years ago. They don't understand the devastation inflation can do
to the financial markets.''
</P>
<P>
   The above-average gains of the last five years in the stock
market were due to low inflation, he said. ``We don't want to go
back to a 4 to 6 percent inflation,'' Larkins suggested. With
inflation in that range, investors could probably expect annual
stock market returns ``probably in the single digits.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
