<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1298 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-LEGAL-SITES-2TAKE     05-10 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-LEGAL-SITES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNTANGLING THE LEGAL MAZE BY SURFING THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By MARCI ALBOHER NUSBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You have had a bad week. Your landlord raised the rent without
notice. You had an accident with your new car just after you drove
it out of the dealership. Your spouse is threatening divorce. In a
wave of desperation and self-pity, you make your way to the
computer and find yourself cruising the Net. Suddenly, hope appears
in the form of a site that may help you learn about all these
troublesome legal issues in your life.
</P>
<P>
   While most of us never face that many disasters at once, we all
encounter times when it would be good to know more about the law _
at least enough to know if it's time to hire a professional. But
with do-it-yourself sites sprouting up as quickly as you can say
``billable hours,'' it's hard to know where to begin.
</P>
<P>
   There are currently about a dozen legal Web sites aimed at
nonlawyers and scores more presenting legal resources in a less
consumer-friendly manner. Many of these sites are still in their
infancy, so content and design are improving constantly.
</P>
<P>
   They generally follow a basic model: a legal encyclopedia with a
summary of each area of the law, links for more information and a
lawyer locator, searchable by city and area of practice. As a
lawyer and a consumer, I have looked at several of them and picked
out a few of the most interesting and authoritative sites.
</P>
<P>
   Nolo.com (www.nolo.com) is the online incarnation of Nolo Press,
the scrappy California publishing company dedicated to empowering
the layperson through access to legal information. If you arrive
with a particular query, chances are you will find an answer. If
you can't, pose a question to Auntie Nolo, described as a
``plainspoken, mostly patient soul.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a legal solution to your problem,'' the site says,
``Auntie will provide it. If what you need is a cup of tea, not a
subpoena duces tecum, she'll tell you whether one lump or two is
better.''
</P>
<P>
   The tone is characteristic of Nolo.com, which is both
comprehensive and quirky. It is so lighthearted that it makes
learning about the law fun.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a legal encyclopedia, which is perfect for those
times you hear a word like ``estoppel'' on ``Ally McBeal'' and
don't know what it means. Even at its most offbeat, the site keeps
its eye on the practical. (The article ``The Opposite of Marrying a
Millionaire _ Marrying a Debtor,'' in Auntie Nolo's debt and credit
section, may come in handy if the spouse who wants a divorce also
has a bundle of bills.) If you had to choose one site to take to a
desert island, this would be the one _ if you still had any legal
issues once you got there.
</P>
<P>
   If you prefer your information with a healthy dose of legal
news, law.com (www.law.com) is the place for you. It has the look
of a newspaper, which shouldn't come as a surprise since it has the
exclusive online rights to digital content from American Lawyer
Media, publisher of 22 legal newspapers and journals. Though
lawyers are the primary audience for law.com, consumers would be
wise to bookmark it to get links to the sites lawyers themselves
use for research. (For example, the site's extensive system of
links will lead you to Tenant.net, where you can review New York's
rent laws to see if your landlord's rent increase is legal).
</P>
<P>
   Interested in live advice? Try FreeAdvice.com
(www.freeadvice.com), where seven days a week (during specified
hours) you can have an online dialogue with a real live lawyer (or
in some instances, a real live recent law school graduate not yet
admitted to the bar). While it is reassuring to know that you are
communicating directly with someone, the answers are filled with
disclaimers and often give only a bit more information than the
site's summaries. If the chat leaves you unsatisfied, some of the
stock answers may meet your needs (in fact, the section Who Do I
Contact After an Auto Accident, under Accident Law, is the ideal
place to help you sort out your next steps in dealing with your
recent fender bender.)
</P>
<P>
   For a thorough introduction to the legal and judicial system and
top-notch advice for choosing, hiring and managing a lawyer
(including questions to ask during an interview), log on to FindLaw
(www.findlaw.com) and read through Courts and Legal Process and
Hiring a Lawyer, in the Consumer Center. The Small Business Center
is also worth a visit for its plain English guidance on everything
from business plans and finance to employment and insurance.
</P>
<P>
   If you know you need a lawyer but don't know where to find one,
look to lawyers.com (www.lawyers.com), the site of
Martindale-Hubbell, publisher of the leading print directory of law
firms and lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   As befits its heritage, this site shines in the lawyer-search
area with impressive profiles of firms and practitioners worldwide.
Another strong feature is Ask a Lawyer, where you can pose a
question to one of the site's experts. There is no promise that
your question will be selected (timely, short queries with broad
appeal have the best shot) but even if you don't get an answer,
archived questions like ``Will my used car be covered by the lemon
law?'' make for interesting reading.
</P>
<P>
   Also worthwhile for lawyer searching is Lawoffice.com
(www.lawoffice.com), the site of the veteran legal publisher West
Group. With a directory of more than one million legal
professionals, the site's listings are loaded with lawyers'
biographies, published works, representative cases and links to
firms' Web sites and e-mail addresses.
</P>
<P>
   For a distraction from your legal problems, drop in on
TheLAW.com's Strange but True, filled with legal trivia like the
Louisiana law making it illegal to shoot a bank teller with a water
pistol after robbing a bank.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Koch, the former New York City mayor, is a co-founder of the
site; clicking on Ed Koch's Chambers on the home page takes you to
his introduction to the site, where he invites users to send him
e-mail ``to tell me: How'm I doing?'' TheLAW.com offers celebrity
profiles, television and film reviews and an online courtroom. On
the serious side, the site has support groups and live chats with
social workers for those dealing with emotional issues like
adoption and employment discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   One legal task we all inevitably face is the drafting of a will.
To see how ordinary people and celebrities from Benjamin Franklin
to Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis handled theirs, find your way to
Wills on the Web (www.ca-probate.com/wills.htm), which displays
real wills from 1493 to the present. When you are ready to tackle
your own will, EstatePlanningLinks.com
(www.estateplanninglinks.com) answers everything from ``Why Have a
Will?'' to ``What to bring to your first meeting with an estate
planning attorney'' and has links to numerous self-help resources.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, if you are dissatisfied with Cliff Notes versions of
the law offered at some of the consumer sites, visit the Cornell
Law School's Legal Information Institute (www.law.cornell.edu),
probably the most expansive legal reference tool online. Useful
features include ``Law About ...'' (with links to every legal topic
imaginable), constitutions and codes, court opinions, law by source
or jurisdiction, and the American Legal Ethics Library (it's longer
than you think). The site is popular with lawyers and is equally
accessible to nonlawyers who would rather read statutes and
judicial opinions than simplified summaries.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Used properly, legal Web sites can enhance your understanding of
the law and from time to time may even convince you that a legal
issue isn't worth pursuing with a lawyer. When you do need a
lawyer, spending some time at one or more of these sites can help
you choose the right one, manage that person properly and know the
basics about the subject you are discussing.
</P>
<P>
   As to the rules governing online legal advice, there are no laws
that apply specifically to Web sites. The problems that might arise
for lawyers have to do primarily with advertising. If a site is
deemed to be advertising (as opposed to the publishing of free
information), the lawyers involved would be subject to laws
governing false advertising as well as bar association ethics
restrictions on advertising by lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   In the borderless land of the Web, lawyers could find themselves
in tangles with their bar associations about such things as whether
postings on lawyer referral services constitute advertising in a
state where a lawyer is not admitted to practice law.
</P>
<P>
   Even more delicate is the question of whether lawyers involved
with sites are engaging in the unauthorized practice of law by
offering online advice that is available in states where they are
not admitted to the bar. Though lawyers rely on lengthy
disclaimers, for now this is unchartered territory that is certain
to provide legal ethicists and the courts with ample fodder for a
new breed of cases.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, if online advice is deemed to be the practice of law
(an open question and one that all the disclaimers on the sites are
trying to rule out), a lawyer could commit malpractice by giving
advice that turned out to be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   For the person using the Web sites, reliance on online legal
advice has its dangers. These sites are not substitutes for
lawyers, and they are only as good as the information they contain
_ which could be out of date, oversimplified or just plain wrong.
If you get bad advice, you don't have a bar association available
to handle your complaint, as you would if you had been dealing with
a real lawyer. Above all, keep in mind that in the world of free
counsel, you may just get what you pay for.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 2021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
