<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1300 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-FORD-COX     05-10 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Zoo hosts Ford brass
 &HT;    By Russell Grantham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co.'s Hapeville plant could build about 50,000 more
cars annually when the Ford Taurus and Mercury Sable get makeovers
in a few years, said an industry analyst.
</P>
<P>
   But chances are Ford executives won't talk about plans for its
Atlanta-area plant when the Dearborn, Mich.-based company holds its
annual meeting today at Zoo Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't talk at all about future product,'' said Ford
spokeswoman Della DiPietro, who arrived in Atlanta on Wednesday for
the annual meeting, expected to attract about 500 shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting, Ford shareholders are expected to re-elect the
company's 13 directors, appoint PricewaterhouseCoopers LLP as its
accountant and vote on five shareholder proposals that Ford
management said it opposes.
</P>
<P>
   Two shareholder proposals _ one calling for employee directors
and another calling for independent directors on key committees _
appeared at Ford's 1999 annual meeting as well and garnered about 4
percent of shareholders' votes.
</P>
<P>
   Ford is holding its annual meeting in Atlanta this year, company
officials said, because the automaker alternates each year between
locales near its Detroit-area headquarters and cities where it has
assembly plants.
</P>
<P>
   But Ford's plans for the Hapeville plant are ``certainly not
something that the company is ready to talk about,'' said Alan
Baum, an analyst with IRN, an automotive research company in Grand
Rapids, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Both Georgia Gov. Roy Barnes and Illinois Gov. George Ryan have
reportedly lobbied Ford in recent months in a competition for new
or expanded auto plants in Chicago and Hapeville _ where Ford now
builds the Taurus and Sable _ to build a new line of sport-utility
vehicles or to consolidate Taurus and Sable production
</P>
<P>
   Based on contacts with Ford's suppliers, Baum said he expects
Ford to consolidate its Taurus production in Hapeville with its
2004 model year.
</P>
<P>
   Baum said he also expects Ford's Chicago plant to produce a
``tall wagon kind of thing'' for its Mercury division to replace
the Sable. Both vehicles will be based on Volvo's ``P2'' chassis to
save costs, he said. Ford bought Volvo's car operations last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of suppliers working on this program''
already, he said. ``Three years is not a long time for this sort of
development.''
</P>
<P>
   A Clayton County Chamber of Commerce official said in December
that a Ford expansion in Hapeville could mean 700 new jobs and $100
million in new investments.
</P>
<P>
   Shifting all Taurus production to the Hapeville plant would mean
Ford will probably have to expand the plant somewhat and cut its
Taurus fleet sales to taxi, rental and corporate customers, said
Baum.
</P>
<P>
   He projected the plant's production will jump from
240,000-250,000 units annually to 290,000. ``I think there would
probably be some brick and mortar'' expansion, he said, but ``not
many'' more jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But J.C. Phillips, president of United Auto Workers Local 882 at
the 2,500-employee Hapeville plant, said 500-1,000 new jobs would
probably result from such an expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants a product that will sell well, and we are
hoping to get the Taurus and Sable as long at it is made. It's a
good seller,'' he said. ``If we don't get this expansion, we'll get
a new vehicle,'' he added, but that might be the less desirable
outcome because the new vehicle might flop at dealerships.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
