A1301 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      05-10 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   RWANDA: BISHOP FACES EXECUTION
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Augustin Misago, on trial on genocide charges, received a
telegram from Pope John Paul II, who said he prayed for him to be
freed soon. Prosecutors asked the death penalty for the bishop, who
is accused of helping to plan the 1994 genocide in which about
800,000 Tutsi and moderate Hutu died. The church has been
criticized by survivors and rights groups for its silence during
the killings. Bishop Misago, 56, says he is the victim of a
political campaign against the church. A verdict is expected next
week.
</P>
<P>
   KENYA: CORRUPTION CHARGES
</P>
<P>
   A report by Parliament accused several prominent people, many
with close ties to President Daniel arap Moi, of corruption that
cost the nation hundreds of millions of dollars. Among them were
George Saitoti, whom Moi hand-picked as vice president, and
Nicholas Biwott, a presidential aide. The report also recommended
that Moi's son Philip be investigated for possibly evading taxes on
imported luxury cars. Moi was not named in the report.
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE: VOTE BOYCOTT CONSIDERED
</P>
<P>
   Faced with continuing attacks against his supporters, the leader
of the main opposition party, the Movement for Democratic Change,
said his party was considering boycotting coming parliamentary
elections. For weeks the party's president, Morgan Tsvangirai, has
vowed to carry on with his challenge to President Robert Mugabe and
the ruling party. But political violence, sometimes deadly, is
persisting, threatening to disrupt any voting.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: NATIONWIDE STRIKE
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of workers joined a one-day nationwide strike
protesting the high unemployment rate and the government policies
that labor unions believe are partly to blame for the shortage of
jobs. Organized by the Congress of South African Trade Unions, the
strike caused scattered service and production disruptions for some
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: DISCOUNTING THE DEAD
</P>
<P>
   The government passed an emergency decree to eliminate dead or
relocated voters from electoral lists, fearing that bloated rolls
would weaken the chances of reaching the 51 percent quorum
necessary for a deeply contested referendum set for May 21. But the
decree needs approval from both houses of Parliament within 60
days. Many members oppose the vote, which among other things seeks
to reform electoral laws at the expense of small parties. If either
house fails to support the decree, it would nullify the referendum,
regardless of its results.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: HOUSING REFUGEES
</P>
<P>
   The government is considering building two new detention centers
to house refugees whose asylum applications have failed and are
awaiting deportation. There are enough beds to house 900 asylum
seekers at a time, but the government wants to increase that to
about 2,900. More than 75,000 people have applied for asylum in the
past year; a backlog of 93,365 people are awaiting decisions.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   ECUADOR: TOP BRASS QUIT
</P>
<P>
   The heads of the navy and air force and the chairman of the
joint chiefs of staff have resigned, with local press reports
describing their action as a protest over a government plan to free
officers who took part in a coup in January. The coup leader, Gen.
Carlos Mendoza, is on trial with 117 mid-level officers also
involved in the overthrow of President Jamil Mahuad. But the new
president, Gustavo Noboa, has asked Congress to approve an amnesty
for the coup plotters.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: MINISTER RESIGNS
</P>
<P>
   Minister of the Interior Nestor Martinez has quit and been
replaced by a fellow member of the opposition Liberal Party rather
than face a congressional investigation that could have led to his
ouster. His departure came as President Andres Pastrana was
withdrawing his plan for a referendum in July on dissolving the
corruption-ridden Congress and replacing it with a new legislature.
The inquiry aimed at Martinez was seen as a warning to Pastrana not
to proceed with his plan.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: KIDNAPPER KINSMAN KIDNAPPED
</P>
<P>
   One of Mexico's cruelest kidnappers has suffered the abduction
of a nephew, for whom criminals are asking a $2 million ransom,
authorities told the newspaper Reforma. The 10-year-old victim is
the son of Aurelio Arizmendi, who is in prison charged with taking
part in 24 kidnappings carried out by a gang led by his brother.
The gang was known for cutting off its victims' ears.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: PRESIDENTIAL ALLY WINS
</P>
<P>
   Anibal Ibarra, a liberal ally of President Fernando de la Rua,
was elected mayor of Buenos Aires, promising to fight crime and
improve city services. Ibarra won only 49.1 percent of the vote but
averted a runoff when his closest competitor withdrew. His victory
was seen by political observers as a major help for the president,
whose policies have been slow to improve the economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 2023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
