<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1308 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-HAWKS-IZZO-COX     05-10 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS-IZZO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Offer goes to coach of NCAA champion
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hawks have offered their head coaching position to Tom Izzo
of NCAA champion Michigan State and expect a decision before the
end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Izzo, 45, received an offer thought to be worth more than $15
million over five years to replace Lenny Wilkens, who resigned
April 24 after seven years as Hawks coach.
</P>
<P>
   Izzo could not be reached for comment Wednesday. Hawks general
manager Pete Babcock said the team would not comment ``on any phase
of our coaching search.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks have, however, backed away from Isiah Thomas, who has
been informed of the offer to Izzo. Thomas is now interviewing with
another team, possibly the New Jersey Nets, who might be willing to
make him head coach and director of basketball operations.
</P>
<P>
   Izzo is thought to be considering the offer after getting his
third raise in as many years from Michigan State, where his new
deal is estimated to be as much as $1.1 million a year. Taking the
Hawks job make Izzo the second college coach _ former Kansas coach
Larry Brown is the other _ to win an NCAA title and leave the next
season for the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Izzo led Michigan State to a 32-7 record and the school's first
national title in 21 years last season and compiled a 120-48 record
in five seasons as head coach. And it's his loyalty to Michigan
State, where he has worked as an assistant and head coach since
1983, and the fact that all but three players return from the
national championship team that could make the decision to leave
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   If he accepted the job, however, he would inherit a team with a
young talent base - next season's team could have as many as seven
players 24 or younger - and a lottery pick in next month's NBA
draft. The fact that the Hawks have a youthful roster led team
management to search the college ranks for a replacement for
Wilkens, but several college coaches who have made the leap to the
NBA in recent years have not had much success.
</P>
<P>
   Former UNLV coach Jerry Tarkanian lasted 20 games before being
fired in San Antonio, ex-Massachusetts coach John Calipari was
72-112 in New Jersey before he was terminated, Rick Pitino is only
90-124 since leaving Kentucky to become president and coach of the
Boston Celtics and Tim Floyd is 30-102 in two seasons with the
Chicago Bulls after leaving Iowa State.
</P>
<P>
   Babcock, however, has been intrigued with college coaches. He
talked to Pitino in 1993 before hiring Lenny Wilkens. And in his
search for Wilkens' replacement he said he is looking for a
teacher, ``someone who enjoys working with young players, in
bringing them along.''
</P>
<P>
   Izzo apparently fits that description. His teams are tenacious
defenders, remarkably adaptable at a level where players are asked
to fit a system rather than having a system developed for the
talent on hand.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on Izzo, senior guard Mateen Cleaves said recently,
``A guy like myself, I fell in love with him. You could tell he was
a very hard worker and he really meant what he said.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves, injured much of last season, and swing man Morris
Peterson were the stars of the Michigan State's championship drive
and are projected as first-round picks in the June NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   Izzo is a native of Iron Mountain, Michigan, a high school
teammate and at Northern Michigan a roommate of four years with San
Francisco 49ers coach Steve Mariucci, who is his closest friend.
``We went through everything together,'' Mariucci has said. ``The
good times, the bad times. We know each other's secrets.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
