<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1310 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-BILL-ONLINE-ART-2     05-10 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-BILL-ONLINE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE MY BILLS, PLEASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(Eds.: Please note that the word AT in parentheses has been used in
the 13th graf instead of the symbol, which is non-transmittable to
some newspaper systems.) 
(ART ADV: NYT Photo 2 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROY FURCHGOTT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Susan MacTavish Best, a Webmaster in San Francisco, had a
routine for paying her bills. She let them collect in piles, then
dealt with them when the spirit moved her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am incredibly unorganized and always pay my bills late,''
MacTavish Best said. But she knew that she could not indulge her
penchant for disorganization and procrastination during a
three-month trek to India that began last September.
</P>
<P>
   Then she heard a radio advertisement promoting a bill
aggregater, a term that is coming into use to describe services
that receive customers' bills, display them online for their
customers to view and pay them from the customers' bank, savings or
investment accounts.
</P>
<P>
   MacTavish Best used the advertised service, Paytrust, while she
was away and continues to use it now, receiving an e-mail message
when each bill comes in. She can look at any bill online, but she
has told the service to pay some of them whether she looks at them
or not, provided they are below a figure she has set for each.
Other bills she reviews, then pays according to her old routine:
when the spirit moves her.
</P>
<P>
   ``They send reminders, `Bill due in three days,' `Bill due in
two days,' `Bill due today,''' MacTavish Best said. ``Then _ I am
so lazy _ I figure I'd better take care of it. I hit the link, and
it's paid.'' Despite toying with fate, she said, she has not
incurred a late fee since joining.
</P>
<P>
   Bill-paying services are a step toward the day when everyone
will receive and pay all their bills electronically. That day once
seemed a long way off, when the concept of electronic billing was
caught in a kind of economic Catch 22. Companies did not offer it
because they did not see customers lining up to sign on. Customers
did not sign on because there were no services offered. While
online banks and other Web-based services developed to offer bill
payments, most just write and mail checks in response to a
customer's request that a payment be sent to a particular place.
Few actually receive the bills for the customer.
</P>
<P>
   Aggregaters are taking the risk to develop the market. Firms
like Paytrust (www.paytrust.com), PayMyBills (www.paymybills.com)
and Cyberbills (www.statusfactory.com) arrange to receive a
client's bills, which they scan so clients can see them on the Web.
They then organize the bills and pay them as directed. The
companies charge users a monthly fee that ranges from $3.95 to
$29.95, depending upon the number of bills paid.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the fees, the companies are not yet making money.
Handling people's bills is expensive; an army of employees opens
envelopes by hand, puts the bills on a scanner and converts them
into digital images. The companies are calculating that if they can
deliver the customers, more merchants will automate the way they
send out bills and collect payments, and the cost to provide the
service will come down.
</P>
<P>
   That possibility is enticing enough that online financial
service providers like Quicken and portals like AOL say they plan
to offer bill aggregation before the end of the summer. Others,
like Spectrum EBP, a joint venture of Chase Manhattan, First Union
and Wells Fargo, are working to develop a closely related service
called bill presentment. In bill aggregation, paper bills are
mailed to agencies; in bill presentment, everything, even incoming
bills, is handled electronically.
</P>
<P>
   Bill services' customers, like MacTavish Best, can pay any bill
at any time from anywhere. ``I was in Delhi, and I couldn't
remember my password,'' MacTavish Best said, ``so I sent an e-mail
and got an immediate response. I was sitting there in the cafe and
we were e-mailing back and forth, having a conversation. There is a
12-hour difference so I was thinking, `It's like 4 in the
morning.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bill-paying services do have their critics. Because the services
need access to users' bank accounts, banks have raised privacy
concerns. Union Trust once filed suit against an aggregater,
Paytrust, to keep it from asking bank clients to share their online
identification and passwords.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they have an unscrupulous employee, they could execute a
trade, move your money, they could wipe you out,'' said Kellie
Scott, senior vice president and director of eChannels, the
e-commerce division of Union Trust. The suit was dropped, and now
many banks and aggregators are working together to establish safe
procedures for sharing information.
</P>
<P>
   As with any new technology service, there are glitches. When a
San Francisco public relations firm, pr(at)paiz.com, failed to put
the proper code on a bill a client wanted to pay through
PayMyBills, the firm never received the money. ``We called over
there, and the bill was just sitting there,'' said Damon Paiz, a
part-owner of the agency. ``They didn't try to call us to say our
bill was just sitting there. It was just very unprofessional.''
Since then, Paiz said, there have been no problems. A PayMyBills
spokesman said the company had added a research team to handle
payments for bills with incorrect codes.
</P>
<P>
   The sites are not completely seamless for consumers. There are
only about 30 companies _ most of them utilities and phone
companies _ that accept electronic payments, so to pay any other
bill, the user must authorize the aggregater to make the payment at
least five days in advance to give it time to go through the mail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
