</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-CRISIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIERRA LEONE STRESSING UN ROLE, US POLICY IN AFRICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY AND JOE LAURIA AND  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The crisis in Sierra Leone is testing the
credibility of United Nations peacekeeping operations as well as
the Clinton administration's oft-expressed desire to more actively
help African nations, officials and analysts said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan, angry at the lack of help from
Western countries, said it was time for the more powerful nations
to assist the embattled UN force and help bring to safety 500 UN
peacekeepers held hostage in the West African nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had hoped that some of those with the capacity would go to
the assistance of those who are in there doing the bidding of the
Security Council and the UN,'' Annan said.
</P>
<P>
   But several US officials said Wednesday that the Clinton
administration would not budge from offering only logistical and
technical support.
</P>
<P>
   British officials also said they would not provide combat
troops, although 800 paratroopers who have arrived in Sierra Leone
have provided some assistance to UN troops as they help evacuate
British citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Annan said the British troops were ``helpful,'' adding, ``at
least they have moved, they have done something, even though the
initial objective was to evacuate British and other nationals.''
</P>
<P>
   UN senior officials had low expectations that the United States
would risk the lives of American troops in Sierra Leone, based on
the 1993 peacekeeping fiasco in Somalia that resulted in the deaths
of 18 American soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Clinton administration putting much greater
emphasis on Africa in the past two years _ President Clinton cited
what he saw as an ``African renaissance,'' several special envoys
have been shuttling to defuse conflicts and a new $260 million
effort has begun to fight the devastating spread of AIDS _ Annan
and other UN officials had expected a more invigorated US response
to the Sierra Leone crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have liked to see some of the governments with
capacity, with good armies and well-trained soldiers, to
participate,'' Annan said. ``But they are not running to forward to
contribute to this force. We have to take the forces we get.''
</P>
<P>
   But US officials said Wednesday that they did not want to risk
the lives of troops in an area of the world where America has few
national security interests. While intervention on humanitarian,
moral and ethical grounds could be argued, those officials said,
national security interests overrode all other considerations.
Wednesday, UN Ambassador Richard Holbrooke wrapped up an
unsuccessful attempt to quell tensions in two other African
hotspots: Congo and along the Ethiopia-Eritrea border.
</P>
<P>
   Of Sierra Leone, one US senior official said on condition of
anonymity: ``We want to make sure this stays a UN challenge and not
a US national challenge. We will be supportive diplomatically and
help airlift other troops, but we have to be very sensitive to what
we are already doing in Bosnia and Kosovo and not overstretch
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are encouraging allies to help, especially allies who used
to colonial masters in these places, like the British,'' the US
official said.
</P>
<P>
   British troops had begun ferrying UN peacekeepers to dug-in
positions at the entrances to the capital of Freetown, ``where they
are anticipating the worst,'' said UN spokesman Fred Eckhard.
Rebels were advancing toward the capital as night fell.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary-general still holds some hope that the British
troops will remain after the evacuations of British and European
nationals are completed. ``They are saying they will leave after
the evacuation is over, but let's see,'' said a UN official, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   A British official in New York acknowledged that his country is
sensitive to the appearance of soldiers leaving while Freetown was
under attack. ``People in London do fully understand the importance
of signals which is why they are deliberately leaving that question
open,'' said the diplomat. ``No one is saying, coming next weekend
we are all out, fend for yourselves boys.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, additional reinforcements may not arrive until
late this month. UN officials are trying to get 3,000 additional UN
peacekeepers from Bangladesh, Jordan and India to Sierra Leone, but
the earliest possible arrival is May 21 and could be much later, a
UN official said.
</P>
<P>
   And regional West African defense ministers will meet on May 17
to decide whether to send a force of 1,600 Nigerian combat troops.
But Annan does not believe that force would be able to defend the
capital from rebel forces because of its lack of experience and
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   As the conflict worsens, more questions have arisen on the
future of UN peacekeeping operations.
</P>
<P>
   David Welsh, a senior State Department official, told the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee Wednesday the Sierra Leone disaster has
shaken the confidence of such UN missions. He believed it would
cause ``more introspection about what these missions are designed
to accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The UN's credibility is right on the line now,'' said Carol J.
Lancaster, a Georgetown University professor and former Clinton
administration official. ``This whole incident in Sierra Leone
makes the UN look not just powerless but a victim as well.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the Clinton administration's decision not to become
more involved in the crisis shows there are ``limits to their
interests in Africa, an unwillingness to apply a rhetorical policy
of greater engagement to situations involving conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   A second UN official, also asking not to be identified, said
that the blame should not rest with his organization, but rather on
member states that are unwilling to fund peacekeeping operations.
He said the Sierra Leone operation, for instance, was only at 8,000
troops instead a planned 11,000 because of a lack of money.
</P>
<P>
   The official also said that the UN force had made much progress
until the rebel offensive. ``We managed to get UN troops in every
part of Sierra Leone except the heartland of the diamond mining
area in eastern Sierra Leone, which is controlled by rebel
elements. When they saw that, and they new disarmament camps coming
and soldiers turning in their weapons, they decided to try to
derail the whole process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Donnelly reported from Washington; Lauria from the United Nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 2034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000510.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1312 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-BILL-ONLINE-2NDTA     05-10 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-BILL-ONLINE-2NDTAKE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: the mail.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   And although banks and bill-paying services are working on ways
to share information, few arrangements have been set up. Most
people who use an aggregater's services still have to visit their
banks' Web sites if they want to check their balances before they
approve a payment. ``I can't check my balances real time,'' said
Brad Winney, who banks with Citibank and pays bills through
Paytrust. ``I have to go to my banking application.'' Winney said
he was satisfied over all because he estimated that the service was
saving him more than $1,000 in late fees each year.
</P>
<P>
   Aggregaters and banks say they are trying to make it easier for
people to use bill-paying services. ``This is taking off faster
than anyone expected,'' said Scott, of Union Trust. ``I think it
will all be pretty seamless by the end of next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Signing up with a service is fairly simple and takes about an
hour overall. Most require a user to fill out an online form with
information like the billing address, the bank account number and a
password. Most then send a package in the mail with a form to sign
that will allow the aggregater to take money from an account at a
bank, savings and loan or brokerage. Most services allow multiple
accounts, and payments can be drawn from any of them.
</P>
<P>
   Paytrust has an accelerated sign-up system that lets users
download a permission form and fax it back. In a test, the form was
processed and the account activated online in about four hours.
Users can determine which bills are to be paid through the site.
The companies say they have a similar automated system to change
the address back if a client wants to go back to receiving bills at
home.
</P>
<P>
   To save the user keystrokes, sites have compiled lists with the
addresses and payment information for many banks and savings and
loans, credit card companies and insurance and mortgage companies;
those names can be added to a consumer's list with a few mouse
clicks.
</P>
<P>
   Paytrust notifies the companies sending bills that they should
send them directly to the site. Some sites require users to mail
change-of-address notices to billers, using stickers and envelopes
included in the sign-up packages, to tell them to send bills to the
aggregaters.
</P>
<P>
   The sites let users set up rules for paying each bill. For
instance, a user can tell the site to pay the phone bill
automatically on the 25th of each month if the amount due is less
than $100. If it is more, the system will alert the user, who will
then manually authorize a payment.
</P>
<P>
   Check writing is not limited to financial companies. People can
have checks sent to anyone by typing in the relevant information,
just as they would for online banking. ``That lets us be the 100
percent solution for your monthly bills,'' said Tom Lazaroff,
marketing director for PayMyBills.com. ``You can pay your gardener,
your dry cleaner, or send a check to Aunt Sally in Minnesota.''
</P>
<P>
   When a bill arrives, the user gets an e-mail notice. Reminders
are sent by e-mail for unpaid bills that nearing their due date. A
confirmation is sent by e-mail when a payment has been made. Check
information can be exported from the Web site into financial
management programs like Quicken and Microsoft Money, as well as
directly to spread sheets.
</P>
<P>
   The sites also archive payment information. Most said they would
keep two years' worth of records on hand. And at the end of each
year, the sites offer to sell clients their records on a CD. The
CDs have scans of all the bills, a summary of billing categories
and in some cases, feature a rudimentary ability to search for
specific bills or information. The CDs are usually priced at $15 to
$30.
</P>
<P>
   The sites are sometimes a little quirky. The Paytrust site could
not find an address for USAA Savings Bank, with USAA capitalized,
but it found the name when it was lowercased. Also, the site would
not allow two transactions in which the same amount was to go to
the same biller on the same day so a user could not make two car
payments with separate checks in one day.
</P>
<P>
   The services are popular with technophile ``early adopters,''
but they are still far from ubiquitous. Paytrust, which says it is
the largest of the aggregators, said it had 30,000 active members.
PayMyBills and Status Factory declined to cite customer numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Some potential customers may be concerned about security. ``I
was leery of Paytrust because you have to send to the bank letting
Paytrust take out money,'' Winney said. To calm those qualms,
Paytrust and PayMyBills are both insured by the Travellers
Insurance Group Safeweb program, which protects users against
unauthorized transactions up to $100,000. Status Factory, the
retail Web site of CyberBills, promises to refund twice the amount
of any loss to any customer using a 128-bit encrypted Web browser,
like recent versions of Netscape's Navigator or Microsoft's
Internet Explorer. The sites will also take care of any bills, and
any late fees, that are not paid on time because of their errors.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the sites offer one attractive and unadvertised
bonus: they handle those advertisements that are sent along with
your bills. ``They are shredded,'' Lazaroff said, ``and you don't
have to look at junk mail.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Users like to say that bill aggregation services cost less than
the stamps they used to mail out payments each month. That is not
quite true _ but it is close. Here is what some services charge:
</P>
<P>
   PAYTRUST: www.PayTrust.com
</P>
<P>
   Users can get started within hours. The cost is $8.95 a month
for 25 transactions, 50 cents for each additional transaction, and
an optional $14.95 for a year's financial records on a CD.
</P>
<P>
   PAYMYBILLS: www.PayMyBills.com
</P>
<P>
   Users not only pay their bills, they can also analyze their
spending habits, a big help when budgeting. PayMyBills charges
$8.95 for 25 transactions a month, 50 cents for each additional
transaction, and $24.95 for a year's financial records on a CD.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERBILLS: www.StatusFactory.com
</P>
<P>
   CyberBills offers double your money back for an unauthorized
transaction, provided you use a secure browser. It offers three
levels of service, starting at $3.50 a month for five transactions.
The mid-level service costs $8.95 for 30 transactions and 75 cents
for each additional transaction. Basic plan users who exceed five
transactions are automatically switched to the mid-level service.
The premium service is $29.95 a month for unlimited transactions. A
year-end CD is $49.50 for the low- and mid-level service, and free
with the premium service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
