<HEADLINE>
SIERRA LEONE STRESSING UN ROLE, US POLICY IN AFRICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY AND JOE LAURIA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The crisis in Sierra Leone is testing the
credibility of United Nations peacekeeping operations as well as
the Clinton administration's oft-expressed desire to more actively
help African nations, officials and analysts said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan, angry at the lack of help from
Western countries, said it was time for the more powerful nations
to assist the embattled UN force and help bring to safety 500 UN
peacekeepers held hostage in the West African nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had hoped that some of those with the capacity would go to
the assistance of those who are in there doing the bidding of the
Security Council and the UN,'' Annan said.
</P>
<P>
   But several US officials said Wednesday that the Clinton
administration would not budge from offering only logistical and
technical support.
</P>
<P>
   British officials also said they would not provide combat
troops, although 800 paratroopers who have arrived in Sierra Leone
have provided some assistance to UN troops as they help evacuate
British citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Annan said the British troops were ``helpful,'' adding, ``at
least they have moved, they have done something, even though the
initial objective was to evacuate British and other nationals.''
</P>
<P>
   UN senior officials had low expectations that the United States
would risk the lives of American troops in Sierra Leone, based on
the 1993 peacekeeping fiasco in Somalia that resulted in the deaths
of 18 American soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Clinton administration putting much greater
emphasis on Africa in the past two years _ President Clinton cited
what he saw as an ``African renaissance,'' several special envoys
have been shuttling to defuse conflicts and a new $260 million
effort has begun to fight the devastating spread of AIDS _ Annan
and other UN officials had expected a more invigorated US response
to the Sierra Leone crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have liked to see some of the governments with
capacity, with good armies and well-trained soldiers, to
participate,'' Annan said. ``But they are not running to forward to
contribute to this force. We have to take the forces we get.''
</P>
<P>
   But US officials said Wednesday that they did not want to risk
the lives of troops in an area of the world where America has few
national security interests. While intervention on humanitarian,
moral and ethical grounds could be argued, those officials said,
national security interests overrode all other considerations.
Wednesday, UN Ambassador Richard Holbrooke wrapped up an
unsuccessful attempt to quell tensions in two other African
hotspots: Congo and along the Ethiopia-Eritrea border.
</P>
<P>
   Of Sierra Leone, one US senior official said on condition of
anonymity: ``We want to make sure this stays a UN challenge and not
a US national challenge. We will be supportive diplomatically and
help airlift other troops, but we have to be very sensitive to what
we are already doing in Bosnia and Kosovo and not overstretch
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are encouraging allies to help, especially allies who used
to colonial masters in these places, like the British,'' the US
official said.
</P>
<P>
   British troops had begun ferrying UN peacekeepers to dug-in
positions at the entrances to the capital of Freetown, ``where they
are anticipating the worst,'' said UN spokesman Fred Eckhard.
Rebels were advancing toward the capital as night fell.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary-general still holds some hope that the British
troops will remain after the evacuations of British and European
nationals are completed. ``They are saying they will leave after
the evacuation is over, but let's see,'' said a UN official, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   A British official in New York acknowledged that his country is
sensitive to the appearance of soldiers leaving while Freetown was
under attack. ``People in London do fully understand the importance
of signals which is why they are deliberately leaving that question
open,'' said the diplomat. ``No one is saying, coming next weekend
we are all out, fend for yourselves boys.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, additional reinforcements may not arrive until
late this month. UN officials are trying to get 3,000 additional UN
peacekeepers from Bangladesh, Jordan and India to Sierra Leone, but
the earliest possible arrival is May 21 and could be much later, a
UN official said.
</P>
<P>
   And regional West African defense ministers will meet on May 17
to decide whether to send a force of 1,600 Nigerian combat troops.
But Annan does not believe that force would be able to defend the
capital from rebel forces because of its lack of experience and
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   As the conflict worsens, more questions have arisen on the
future of UN peacekeeping operations.
</P>
<P>
   David Welsh, a senior State Department official, told the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee Wednesday the Sierra Leone disaster has
shaken the confidence of such UN missions. He believed it would
cause ``more introspection about what these missions are designed
to accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The UN's credibility is right on the line now,'' said Carol J.
Lancaster, a Georgetown University professor and former Clinton
administration official. ``This whole incident in Sierra Leone
makes the UN look not just powerless but a victim as well.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the Clinton administration's decision not to become
more involved in the crisis shows there are ``limits to their
interests in Africa, an unwillingness to apply a rhetorical policy
of greater engagement to situations involving conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   A second UN official, also asking not to be identified, said
that the blame should not rest with his organization, but rather on
member states that are unwilling to fund peacekeeping operations.
He said the Sierra Leone operation, for instance, was only at 8,000
troops instead a planned 11,000 because of a lack of money.
</P>
<P>
   The official also said that the UN force had made much progress
until the rebel offensive. ``We managed to get UN troops in every
part of Sierra Leone except the heartland of the diamond mining
area in eastern Sierra Leone, which is controlled by rebel
elements. When they saw that, and they new disarmament camps coming
and soldiers turning in their weapons, they decided to try to
derail the whole process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Donnelly reported from Washington; Lauria from the United Nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
