<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME CONGRESSMAN LOOK FOR `POLITICAL COVER' ON CHINA TRADE VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Minn., Ill., Texas, Calif.)   By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There are 10,000 miles and not much trade between
China and the anthracite coal region of eastern Pennsylvania, but
for Paul Kanjorski, a House Democrat, the two are inseparable.
</P>
<P>
   Kanjorski said he told President Clinton and House Republican
leaders that he would support extending permanent trading rights to
China if they would offer ``assurances'' that his proposed tax
breaks to encourage investment in Pennsylvania's distressed coal
region will become law before Clinton leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very tough vote for me and these issues must come
together,'' Kanjorski said flatly this week. ``It's not a vote I'm
just going to throw away.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has stressed for months that Congress must grant China
permanent trading rights or risk damaging the competitiveness of
U.S. companies and relations with the world's most populous
country. But not unlike other high-profile trade votes, this one
also involves a host of issues that are purely local, like job
retraining and development aid.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials warned early this spring that
they could not dole out favors for votes, not at the end of
Clinton's term and with Republicans in control of Congress.
Commerce Secretary William Daley, who is leading the
administration's lobbying effort, said lawmakers must make a
straight choice or, as he put it, ``walk the plank.''
</P>
<P>
   But that has not stopped members of Congress from demanding life
preservers. With the Clinton administration still short of the 218
votes it needs in the House and with just two weeks left before the
scheduled vote, at least some of the Democrats and Republicans who
remain officially uncommitted want pet projects funded.
</P>
<P>
   The requests may be one reason that 30 lawmakers on both sides
of the aisle have been coy about how they will vote, a remarkably
large number of undecided members given that Congress has had to
choose whether to renew China's trade privileges annually for two
decades. The administration is now asking Congress to give up that
annual review, fulfilling a promise it made to Beijing last year
when it negotiated China's accession to join the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Several Democrats who represent districts with a heavy trade
union presence have been especially demanding. They argue that they
need some political cover to vote for a measure unions steadfastly
oppose. The administration, if not yet making firm commitments, is
at least listening, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industrial unions are vehement about this. They say
they'll picket me,'' said Rep. James Oberstar, a senior Minnesota
Democrat. ``I'll take the heat if I can get something done for the
people I represent.''
</P>
<P>
   Oberstar says he wants the administration to amend the Trade Act
of 1974 so that imports of steel slabs could be treated as a direct
threat to the taconite miners of northern Minnesota. With Russian
and Brazilian slabs flooding the market, Oberstar said, U.S. blast
furnaces no longer use as much taconite, a low-grade iron-ore, to
produce raw steel. Several thousands jobs are threatened, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they have something they really want,'' he says, referring
to the China trade bill. ``What I'm saying is that they bend the
damn law to serve the needs of these people who are hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   The requests for aid come as the administration and Republican
leaders in Congress are locked in a furious battle with opponents
of the China trade measure, including senior congressional
Democrats and politically powerful labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   The House majority whip, Tom DeLay, R- Texas, warned Wednesday
that he would have to engage in ``traditional hand-to-hand combat''
to round up enough Republican votes to pass the measure, dismissing
reports that his party already had 150 secure votes. Another
Republican leader said that a recent head count of House
Republicans found only 120 solid supporters, though administration
officials said they still expect at least another 20 Republicans to
vote in favor.
</P>
<P>
   The pendulum swung slightly in favor of opponents Wednesday when
Reps. David Phelps of Illinois and Gene Green of Texas, both
Democrats, declared they would vote no. The administration says
that it needs a minimum of 70 House Democrats to vote in favor and
that it remains 10 to 15 votes shy of that mark.
</P>
<P>
   Whips on both sides of the aisles have been publicly
discouraging their caucuses from using the close vote as a chance
to extract benefits for their home districts. Asked about
Republican pork barreling Wednesday, DeLay said sharply, ``We don't
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Robert Matsui, D-Calif., and his party's chief supporter of
the bill in the House, also urged lawmakers to make their decision
on the bill's merits.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't get cover from labor from a bridge project,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another of Clinton major trade priorities, the North American
Free Trade Agreement, which Congress approved in 1993, became a
political pinata when scores of lawmakers on both sides of the isle
demanded _ and often received _ benefits in exchange for their
votes, administration officials acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   The China trade measure is not NAFTA. It does not require that
the United States open its markets wider to imported goods, as
NAFTA did, and the congressional demands for district-by-district
benefits are much less intense this time, many people involved in
lobbying process said.
</P>
<P>
   But the lobbying, if less high profile, is hardly invisible.
Daley flew to Texas late last week to hear more about Rep. Ruben
Hinojosa's proposed Cross-Border Institute for Regional
Development, a business plan to create a Silicon Valley in
southeastern Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Daley and Hinojosa, a Democrat who has yet to say which way he
is voting on China trade, declined to comment on the trip. But a
congressional aide said that Hinojosa hopes that a public-private
partnership could bring high-tech businesses and jobs to the area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
