<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESERT-SLAYING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN WHO KILLED BEST FRIEND GETS TWO YEARS IN JAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, N.M. _ Calling Raffi Kodikian a person of good
character but bowing to his responsibility to the law, a judge
Wednesday decided that even a mercy killing does not excuse
Kodikian from prison.
</P>
<P>
   The two-year sentence Chief District Judge J.W. Forbes imposed
on Kodikian, 26, is far less than the 20-year term he could have
ordered for the murder of David Coughlin in Carlsbad Caverns
National Park.
</P>
<P>
   And although Kodikian will leave state prison a young man, the
questions and skepticism about what happened on the parched floor
of Rattlesnake Canyon during a four-day ordeal last August will
remain with him a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   There are questions from the Coughlin family, skepticism from
the park supervisor, even doubts from Kodikian himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one of us should have come out of that canyon, both of us
should have,'' Kodikian, of Boston, said at a press conference
after sentencing. ``I'll be spending the rest of my life trying to
justify what happened, and chances are I won't be able to.''
</P>
<P>
   But even in retrospect, Kodikian said, he believes he did the
right thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that anybody in my position who would turn their back
on their friend wouldn't have been deserving of coming out of that
canyon,'' Kodikian said.
</P>
<P>
   Kodikian, who accepted the sentence stoically, entered custody
at 5 p.m. after an emotional afternoon with family and friends.
Kodikian has said he stabbed Coughlin after his friend, dehydrated
and in severe pain, begged him for death.
</P>
<P>
   Kodikian ``does not pose a threat or danger to society,'' Forbes
said from the bench. But, he added, punishment ``serves the very
important purpose of preserving the rule of law that we all need to
have for an orderly society.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes imposed a sentence of 15 years with 13 years suspended.
With good behavior, Kodikian can reduce his sentence for
second-degree murder to 20 months, followed by five years'
probation.
</P>
<P>
   The Coughlin family, of Wellesley, Mass., did not attend the
three-day hearing. A family statement read Wednesday by prosecutor
Les Williams did not mention what punishment the Coughlins deemed
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can think of no reason why Raffi would have wished David
any harm or pain,'' wrote Robert P. Coughlin, the victim's father.
``Moreover, we cannot presume to know what transpired, or the
thoughts and emotions the two experienced during the days before
David's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be sure, we have questions. However, we find it difficult
to believe there was any malicious intent.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked what message he wished to send the Coughlin family,
Kodikian replied: ``They know how I feel about David, and how I
feel about them. I still love him _ always will.''
</P>
<P>
   Kodikian and Coughlin, 26, of Millis, Mass., had detoured to
Carlsbad Caverns National Park en route to California where
Coughlin had planned to persue graduate studies.
</P>
<P>
   Kodikian, who called the tragedy a ``lifelong sentence,'' said
he has often regretted being rescued.
</P>
<P>
   However, Kodikian said he is not troubled by lingering
skepticism over what happened in Rattlesnake Canyon. ``In America,
they're entitled to their opinion, but their opinion doesn't
concern me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both the prosecution and the defense pronounced themselves
satisfied with the punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Forbes ``couldn't have picked a fairer sentence to all
concerned,'' said Kodikian's attorney, Gary C. Mitchell, who urged
the court to spare his client any prison time. ``I think it shows a
great deal of mercy.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, the chief deputy district attorney, asked Forbes to
give Kodikian a severe sentence, but later said the judge's
decision was satisfactory. ``I can't say it was unjust,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even a longtime skeptic of Kodikian's version of events, Sheriff
A.M. ``Chunky'' Click, called the decision a fair one. ``I think it
was (just), with the mitigating circumstances in this case and the
testimony that came out,'' Click said.
</P>
<P>
   That testimony _ particularly Kodikian's gripping, emotional
account of the tragedy on the witness stand _ softened some of the
disbelief in this frontier city that two young, healthy men could
become hopelessly lost and driven to suicide while camping an
hour's hike from safety.
</P>
<P>
   But questions linger.
</P>
<P>
   Carlsbad Caverns park supervisor Mark Maciha, who tended to
Kodikian after his rescue, said Wednesday that Kodikian's account
will remain forever uncontradicted because the only other witness _
Coughlin _ is dead.
</P>
<P>
   Maciha has said he is baffled by, among several factors,
Kodikian's mental alertness when rescued and the campsite's
proximity to safety.
</P>
<P>
   In final arguments Wednesday, prosecutor Williams emphasized
that, even given the extreme conditions, taking Coughlin's life was
unjustifiable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where there is life, there is hope,'' Williams said slowly.
``David Coughlin would be alive today if Raffi Kodikian had not
killed him. . . . The law says you may not murder another person
just because you think it's in their best interest.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mitchell, the defense attorney, argued that another person's
best interest sometimes leads to drastic measures. Coughlin's death
was not a ``Kevorkian-like'' mercy killing, Mitchell said, but an
act of humanity akin to battlefield choices in which a comrade who
cannot be treated, or saved from the enemy, is sometimes killed to
end his pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justice can say to us that when there is no evil in the case _
none whatsover, none _ that we should seek mercy from the criminal
justice system,'' Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   After the hearing, Kodikian would not comment about the
sentence. But before he left a makeshift press room and prepared to
make a prison cell his home, he looked back _ and ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are a lot of lessons in this, but they are too
numerous to list here,'' he said. ``But I'll be spending the next
two years thinking about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
