<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCK PRICES DECLINE DEEPLY AMID INTEREST-RATE JITTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks dropped sharply Wednesday, led by a continued
sell-off in technology shares, as investors seemed to grow
increasingly worried about how high the Federal Reserve will raise
short-term interest rates to keep inflation in check.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index suffered the biggest of three
consecutive losses _ and its 11th biggest on record _ as the
technology-heavy gauge dropped 200.28 points, or 5.59 percent, to
3,384.73. The last time it closed lower was on April 14, when the
Nasdaq plummeted 9.7 percent to end its worst week ever.
</P>
<P>
   Issues like Intel, Cisco and Motorola were among the biggest
casualties but the latest downdraft, the sixth in seven sessions
for the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, spared almost no sector
of the market except for some household-name consumer stocks, a
handful of mining companies and the utility sector, a traditional
bear-market haven.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot more selling pressure in this market than is
generally perceived,'' said Richard E. Cripps, chief market
strategist at Legg Mason Wood Walker in Baltimore. ``It's not just
that buyers are staying away.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average lost 168.97 points, or 1.6
percent, to 10,367.78, with Intel, down 10 7/8, to 106 1/16,
accounting for about one-third of the slide. The company said 1
million of its computer motherboards are defective, and analysts
said the replacement cost could run into the hundreds of millions
of dollars. Hewlett-Packard, the second-biggest drag, shed 6 9/16,
to 126\.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, Cisco Systems, which reported slightly better than
expected quarterly results after the close of the market on
Tuesday, slumped 4\, to 58{, as investors focused on the company's
doubts about being able to get all the components it needs to set
up networks. And Motorola lost 18, to 86{, after a Salomon Smith
Barney analyst cut his rating, noting difficulties in getting
components for its cellular phones.
</P>
<P>
   The S&AMP;P 500 fell 29.09 points, or 2.06 percent, to 1,383.05. It
is now down 5.9 percent this year compared with losses of 9.8
percent for the Dow and 16.8 percent for Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trend has dramatically changed'' in recent weeks, said
Ronald Shear, chief executive of the Carlin Equities Group, a
trading-oriented firm heavily involved with Nasdaq stocks. ``The
market's very much afraid of several more rate increases'' by the
Fed, whose policy-making committee is to meet on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Shear said investors were also getting a whiff of inflation,
which implied at least modest doubt about the effectiveness of Fed
policy. Gold stocks did nothing, but some lesser metal companies
moved up. For example, Inco, the giant nickel producer, jumped 1
5/8, to 18 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Although the main gauges finished above their lowest levels of
the day, an afternoon comeback largely evaporated and the Nasdaq,
which had cut a 6.08 percent dive in half, retreated again toward
the close.
</P>
<P>
   And few seemed optimistic that the skid, which has lopped 33
percent off the Nasdaq since its high of 5,048.62 on March 10 has
run its course.
</P>
<P>
   Donald G. Berdine, chief investment officer at PNC Advisors in
Pittsburgh, said that he thought the Dow could decline an
additional 2 percent to 3 percent, the S&AMP;P 500 another 6 percent to
8 percent and that the Nasdaq could slide to 3,000 before the
market steadied and liquidity improved.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he was preparing for a resumption of rising prices
during the summer after the Fed has finished raising rates,
probably at its June 27 meeting. ``We're advising getting ready for
the second half, getting ready to buy'' stocks like regional banks,
Berdine said. He added that he would retain technology shares,
concentrating on infrastructure companies and avoiding those that
are purely Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Brokerage stocks were among the session's big losers, with
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter down 5, to 66[, Lehman Brothers and
Goldman Sachs down more than 4 each, to 78 and 81 7/16
respectively, and Merrill Lynch down 3\, to 100\.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors slumped 4 9/64, to 81 15/16, after a Merrill
Lynch analyst downgraded it, and AT&AMP;T Wireless eased 7/16, to 28
9/16, nearly a point below its initial offering price late last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the general gloom, some investors returned to such
brand-name standbys as Wal-Mart, up 3 11/16, to 56 11/16; SBC
Communications, up 2 13/16, to 45[; Coke, up 2 5/16, to 52 13/16,
and Exxon Mobil, up 2 1/16, to 81{. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
