<HEADER>
A1325 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-HURRICANE-COX     05-10 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More hurricanes enter state from south, west, study finds
 &HT;    By Eliot Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH _ Despite the traditional imagery of hurricanes
marching across the Atlantic Ocean, a new report shows more storms
have entered the Florida peninsula from the south and west than the
southeast,
</P>
<P>
   ``We're used to looking to the east,'' James Lushine,
warning-coordination meteorologist for the National Weather
Service's Miami office, told Wednesday's meeting of the Local
Emergency Management Network, a group of local emergency and
government officials.
</P>
<P>
   Lushine said his study found that storms from the south and west
were weaker but often provide no more than three days of lead time
before landfall, forcing a mad scramble to prepare and, if
necessary, evacuate. That was the case in 1999 with Irene, which
caught South Floridians off guard with near-hurricane force winds
and more than a foot of rain in places.
</P>
<P>
   Storms that cross the Atlantic usually provide up to 10 days of
lead time.
</P>
<P>
   Lushine said he found that 87 percent of storms from the south
and west were minimal to moderate storms, with top sustained winds
of up to 110 mph, while more than a third of the southeast storms
were major storms.
</P>
<P>
   He also found that the south and west storms usually occurred
early or late in the season, which runs from June 1 to November 30,
while southeastern storms historically came at the heart of the
season _ late August to mid-September _ and that the south and west
storms usually brought twice as much rain and spawned more
tornadoes but had lower storm surges than the southeast storms.
</P>
<P>
   Lushine's comments came the same day his bosses called for an
above-average season with the potential for stronger,
longer-lasting storms. At a Washington news briefing, National
Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration officials predicted at least
11 storms of at least tropical storm strength, with seven or more
becoming hurricanes and three or more of those becoming major
hurricanes. The historical average is 9.3 storms, 5.8 hurricanes
and 2.2 major hurricanes. Last year's hurricane season brought 12
storms, with five of them striking the U.S. mainland, killing at
least 60.
</P>
<P>
   NOAA Administrator D. James Baker cited the lingering effects of
the fading La Nina event, which cools surface temperatures in the
Pacific Ocean and increases the potential for storms; it is not
expected to vanish until August. He also cited a global circulation
pattern which reduces the wind shear that kills hurricanes as well
as a strong jet stream from Africa and warmer temperatures in the
Atlantic, both of which favor stronger storms.
</P>
<P>
   NOAA also formally announced that Max Mayfield, deputy director
of the National Hurricane Center and acting director since January,
will now head the center.
</P>
<P>
   EliotKleinberg(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
