<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1326 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-PHILLIPS-AUCTION-ART-     05-10 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILLIPS-AUCTION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATTY NEW IMAGE FOR THE `OTHER' AUCTION HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT7 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CHRISTOPHER MASON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``It's just as splendid as Sotheby's or Christie's,''
said Dan Klein, the international executive director of Phillips
auction house, exuding an air of proprietary triumph last week as
he toured the American Craft Museum at 40 W. 53rd St.
</P>
<P>
   Only 10 days earlier, the galleries were earthy shades of
orange, yellow and green. But the designer Bill Katz has
transformed the museum into a gleaming white showcase for artworks
from Phillips' spring sales.
</P>
<P>
   Passing multimillion-dollar canvases, Klein stopped to pose
before an Andy Warhol silkscreen that seemed prophetic: a giant
dollar sign.
</P>
<P>
   Long a distant third in the world auction stakes, Phillips has
rented the museum for three weeks, and lavished $1.3 million in
construction costs, sources said _ not counting design fees _ as
part of an ambitious attempt to give the company's fusty reputation
a swift, elegant facelift.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, in a setting newly glamorous with helium-filled
lanterns and Sharon Stone (supplying the celebrity quotient), Klein
will conduct the biggest sale in Phillips' 206-year history, an
auction of 31 Impressionist and modern works that may bring $80
million _ quite a leap from its total record sale of $3.6 million
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Coming at a time when the world's two leading auction houses,
Sotheby's and Christie's, are embroiled in an embarrassing
price-fixing scandal, Phillips, which is based in London, is
causing a considerable stir with its conspicuous and costly effort
to reinvent itself as an important player in New York. Richard
Feigen, a prominent New York art dealer, said: ``I think it's fine
to have a third force in the auction world. I just don't see how
they're going to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   One way is to create a couture image, which Phillips has done by
luring the art world's equivalent of beautiful models _ from
Cezanne, Renoir and Picasso to Damien Hirst; by making substantial
guarantees to sellers; and by buying at least 8 of 31 works
outright for resale, which is raising eyebrows. ``Spending so much
money, I can't see how they'd recoup it,'' Feigen said. ``Not even
if they had an impressive permanent space.''
</P>
<P>
   Cramped and rundown, Phillips' existing New York headquarters at
406 E. 79th St. has a single salesroom-cum-gallery that resembles
the auditorium of a cruelly underfinanced high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you can see why we had to get out of here to have an
Impressionist sale,'' Klein said, as he led this reporter on a
swift tour.
</P>
<P>
   The American Craft Museum's location gives Phillips a
sophisticated new image _ at least until the auction house leaves
on May 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's smart what they did, to rent this space and show these
paintings,'' said Laszlo von Vertes, a collector and former art
dealer visiting from Zurich, who was among the first to stop by
last Friday for a look at Phillips' wares before heading four
blocks south to do the same at Christie's. ``It's big competition
for Sotheby's and Christie's, which is good for the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Expectations for Phillips' chance for success are fueled by the
formidable resources of the man bankrolling it: Bernard Arnault,
the chairman of LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton, a $40 billion
behemoth. He bought Phillips last November for a bargain price of
$121.5 million and hopes to seize a chunk of Sotheby's and
Christie's turf. Together, Sotheby's and Christie's control most of
the $5 billion global fine art auction business. Igniting Arnault's
efforts is his noted rivalry with Francois Pinault, a French
department store magnate who triumphed over Arnault last year for
control of Gucci and who bought Christie's in 1998 for $1.2
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Apsis, a partner in the gallery C&AMP;M Arts on East 78th
Street and the former head of the Impressionist and modern art
department at Sotheby's, believes it is possible for Phillips to
claim some of Christie's and Sotheby's business. ``This is the
perfect time, because the market is in a state of flux,'' he said.
``And a lot of new collectors are entering the market.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Six months ago, I don't think anyone would have predicted that
Phillips would be this far along,'' he went on. ``They've made big
strides.''
</P>
<P>
   But such strides come at a price; many in the art world
commented on Phillips' recent tactics of promising the seller a
large fixed sum, no matter what the outcome at auction, just to get
the firepower to make the five coming sales seem impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Arnault, in town for the auctions, said, referring to his
rivals, ``We made some guarantees, as everyone did. ``It's a normal
game. I understand they're not happy to have lost these paintings,
that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   As to the cost of fixing up the museum, ``the premises needed
it,'' he said. ``And I think it's beautiful. Bill Katz did a
wonderful job. You know, we're used to this. It's what we do when
we have a fashion show in the group. We think it's important to
show the public the products we're going to sell in a nice way.''
</P>
<P>
   If the strategy works, noted Joe Helman, a well-known 57th
Street dealer, ``it's an inexpensive way to buy into the art
market.'' Spiffing up a museum and guaranteeing paintings is ``a
lot cheaper,'' he said, than buying Christie's or Sotheby's.
</P>
<P>
   Arnault tried that, too, last December, when he entered
negotiations with Alfred A. Taubman, Sotheby's former chairman and
still the controlling stockholder. But talks fell through, a former
Sotheby's executive close to Taubman said.
</P>
<P>
   The new Phillips venture, Klein admitted, ``is a leap of faith
by Arnault, and we've jumped off the cliff with him.''
</P>
<P>
   By a peculiar twist of fate, the star item in Thursday evening's
sale is Kasimir Malevich's ``Suprematist Composition,'' a rare
abstract geometric painting in black, red and white that until last
year had hung for 63 years at the Museum of Modern Art across the
street. Important Suprematist oil paintings by Malevich have been
virtually absent from the auction market since his death in 1935.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Phillips' prize pony being offered up Thursday night
as the final lot of the evening, some observers sounded a note of
concern. ``There are very few buyers out there for a Malevich,''
Feigen observed, though Apsis noted that this particular painting
``is exceptional.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz emphasized the painting's importance by allotting it a wall
of its own that was immediately visible as visitors entered from
the lobby. To alert passers-by, an enormous blown-up photograph of
the painting was placed in the museum's 53rd Street window, to the
chagrin of the Museum of Modern Art, which gave the painting back
to Malevich's 31 descendants last year in an amicable settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips is reported to have guaranteed $15 million to the
heirs, after a five-day negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence M. Kaye, a lawyer for the heirs, said, ``The family was
very impressed by the enthusiasm that Phillips showed.''
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual move, Phillips has declined to set an official
estimate on the painting, but art experts think it could fetch at
least $10 million, making it the most valuable work ever offered by
the auctioneer. (A Monet seascape, the previous record, sold in
1998 for $2.5 million.)
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
