<HEADER>
A1327 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-B     05-10 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT MAKES COUNTEROFFER TO STAVE OFF DIVISION OF COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Corp. urged a judge Wednesday to reject
the government plan to break the software giant into two pieces,
saying a far more moderate solution was appropriate for the
antitrust violations the judge said it had committed.
</P>
<P>
   Federal District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson ruled last month
that Microsoft competed unfairly in the software market, and he
asked the company and the government to suggest remedies.
</P>
<P>
   In its proposal Wednesday, Microsoft strongly opposed a proposal
from the US Justice Department and 17 states to sever Microsoft
into two companies: one that would make the Windows operating
system and one that would include Microsoft's Internet business and
its word-processing, spreadsheet and other so-called applications
software.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the company said, Jackson should bar Microsoft from
using its Windows monopoly as a cudgel to bully other companies.
For example, during a lengthy antitrust trial Microsoft was accused
of withholding technical information and rights to Windows from
companies that wanted to promote a Web browser made by Netscape
Communications Corp., rather than Microsoft's own Web browser.
Without the information and rights to Windows, most computer makers
cannot sell computers.
</P>
<P>
   The government said behavior like that allowed Microsoft to
crush rivals and dampen innovation in the software market, harming
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Under Microsoft's plan, computer makers would have more control
over the look of the Windows screen and the Internet sign-on
sequence. They could feature non-Microsoft products on the screen,
and even delete the icon that leads users to Microsoft's Web
browser.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft did not endorse a variety of other government
proposals, such as forcing it to charge a uniform price for
Windows. And it vigorously attacked the idea of a breakup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe there is no basis in this case for the government's
unprecedented breakup proposal, and we are hopeful that the Court
will dismiss this excessive demand immediately,'' Microsoft
Chairman Bill Gates said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   A breakup and other government proposals ``would have an
enormous and horrendous effect on every part of the mission of this
enterprise,'' Microsoft legal chief Bill Neukom told reporters.
``They would have a dramatic effect on other companies in this
industry and have a huge and negative effect on consumers... and I
think it's perfectly fair to say would have a very negative effect
on the economy of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department called Microsoft's proposal ``ineffective
and filled with loopholes,'' and said it would not prevent the
company from ``using its monopoly power in the future to engage in
the same kind of illegal behavior to crush new innovations.''
</P>
<P>
   Having overtaken the Netscape Web browser, critics say,
Microsoft now aims to use its Windows monopoly to push into the
market for Internet audio and video software, as well as the
software market for servers, or powerful computers that businesses
commonly use to run computer networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge has to look around the corner and see where they're
going to go next, and cut them off at the pass,'' said Mike Pettit,
president of a group of Microsoft rivals called Procomp. He called
Microsoft's proposal ``meaningless.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Microsoft's plan:
</P>
<P>
   -- Computer makers could promote and feature software made by
Microsoft rivals, such as the Netscape Web browser. The computer
makers also could display icons for non-Microsoft products on the
initial screen that computer-users first see, and they could delete
the icon for Microsoft's Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft would be barred from withholding its Windows operating
system from companies that took advantage of these freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling, Jackson has already found that Microsoft induced
computer makers to distribute Microsoft's Web browser rather than
the browser made by rival Netscape, which has been acquired by
America Online Inc. Jackson also found that Microsoft illegally
``tied'' its Web browser to Windows, when the two should be
separate products. Microsoft said its proposal addresses that
concern.
</P>
<P>
   -- Microsoft could not induce any company to limit its support
for Microsoft competitors in return for giving that company a
favored place on the Windows desktop screen, or otherwise using
Windows to promote the company. Jackson has already ruled that
Microsoft engaged in this kind of behavior.
</P>
<P>
   -- Microsoft would agree to give all software developers
``timely and complete access'' to technical information about
Windows upgrades, which is crucial for independent companies to
make Windows-compatible products.
</P>
<P>
   Other restrictions would address the charge that Microsoft tried
to hurt Apple Computer Corp. by threatening to drop its support for
Apple-compatible products unless Apple took actions favorable to
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   These restrictions would stay in effect until 2004, Microsoft
suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're proposing is pretty bland,'' said Thane Scott, an
antitrust specialist with the Boston law firm Palmer &AMP; Dodge, who
does not take sides in the case. ``This is a proposal to impose
very loose oversight over Microsoft. ... It's the minimum of what
any court would absolutely impose, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said that the government's breakup proposal was too
broad, and that it aimed to help Netscape's Web browser and Java,
made by Sun Microsystems, become rivals to Windows.
</P>
<P>
   However, Microsoft argued, the court never ruled that the
Netscape and Sun products would have successfully competed with
Windows even if Microsoft had not engaged in its anticompetitive
behavior. Therefore, the company said, the government was incorrect
in trying to create competition to Windows that might never have
existed under any circumstances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 2048EDT &QL; 
