<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1328 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-PHILLIPS-AUCTION-ART-     05-10 0411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILLIPS-AUCTION-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK: for $2.5 million.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Declining to discuss the heft of Phillips' guarantees and other
financial arrangements with consignors, Klein was more than eager
to show off the American Craft Museum, in its current, spiffed-up
condition.
</P>
<P>
   Just off the entrance, where giant canvases by Andy Warhol and
David Salle now hang in isolated splendor, the lobby was formerly
filled with a warren of counters and merchandise as part of the
museum's gift shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spatially, the museum is very beautiful, but like everyone's
life, it gets cluttered up after a while,'' said Katz, the
designer, who is known for the spare refinement of his work and for
his well-cultivated friendships with artists, including Jasper
Johns, Cy Twombly and Ellsworth Kelly, for whom he has designed
exhibitions. ``My goal always is to simplify and clarify,'' Katz
said. ``The idea is to draw attention to the art.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz was hired by Phillips in February, shortly after returning
from the Guggenheim Museum in Bilbao, where he installed Francesco
Clemente's current exhibition. ``It was all very quick,'' he said.
Lamps previously suspended at just-above-hairdo level in the lobby
were removed. Katz designed simple, interconnected white walls to
create intimately scaled spaces for viewing. He also lowered each
entryway and painted the recessed spaces dark gray.
</P>
<P>
   ``This way, your eye is not distracted from the experience of
viewing the paintings,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Plans called for installing 480 artworks for the separate shows,
each of which required new walls to be put in place overnight. Five
snappy catalogs, designed by Richard Pandiscio, celebrate the new
level of work Phillips is representing. Abigail Asher, a partner at
Guggenheim &AMP; Asher, art consultants, noted, ``They've certainly put
together catalogs unlike any other Phillips catalogs we've ever
seen before.''
</P>
<P>
   In another attempt to upgrade Phillips' image, Klein has been
searching for a new Manhattan headquarters. Until he finds
something, Klein said that Phillips may continue to hold auctions
twice a year at the American Craft Museum. ``It's all been very
wild and exciting,'' Klein said. ``Now we just have to sell the
pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's auction will begin to tell the tale. Tobias
Meyer, head of contemporary art for Sotheby's worldwide, threw down
the gauntlet. ``The question is,'' he said, ``how much is Arnault
prepared to lose?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
