<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-BIGDIG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVING FEES TO SUPPORT `BIG DIG' COST OVERRUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ All Massachusetts motorists will have to pay for the
``Big Dig's'' $2 billion cost overrun, as lawmakers agree to
maintain driving license and vehicle registration fees that had
once been scheduled to be phased out permanently, Beacon Hill
sources say.
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate negotiators believe the Registry fees are more
fair and less politically explosive than new bridge and
Massachusetts Turnpike tolls that were considered earlier this year
to cover the soaring costs of the $13.6 billion project. They have
agreed in principle to the plan after weeks of closed-door
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which is still being drafted, could be announced
Thursday, and is expected to pass the Legislature as soon as
Tuesday, just days before a May 19 federally imposed deadline. The
Federal Highway Administration has threatened to cut off financing
for the Central Artery renovation project by that date if
Massachusetts does not craft a sound financial scheme to cover the
overrun.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also uses this year's budget surplus, estimated at $650
million, to pay down high-interest debt, generating $690 million in
savings over the next five years that would go toward funding the
Central Artery/Tunnel project.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal also sets aside cash for the statewide road and
bridge program, which federal transportation officials have
insisted is necessary for Massachusetts to receieve money already
earmarked for the Central Artery.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Joseph C. Sullivan, a Democrat and co-chairman of
the Joint Committee on Transportation, declined to comment on
details of the plan, but said lawmakers do not want to test the
Congressional threats and are rushing to put the proposal into
legislative form so it could be voted on quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at closure by week's end,'' Sullivan said
``We're sensitive to the May 19 time frame. There would have to be
action next week in both branches. . . . We're working extra hard
at this.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan's Senate counterpart, Robert A. Havern III, a Democrat,
did not return calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   The registration fees would generate $55 million in annual
revenue, while license fees would produce about $45 million a year.
Combined, those funds could leverage $1.4 billion, enough to cover
most of what federal officials say is a $2 billion overrun.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the budget gap would be paid for through the $690
million savings reaped by using surplus funds to pay down
high-interest debt. It was unclear whether lawmakers would apply
that money directly toward construction or use it to borrow money
to cover the difference, although the latter option appeared the
most likely scenario, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   While federal authorities are insisting the Big Dig cannot
siphon funds from other highway projects in the state, using some
of the surplus for road and bridge repairs would help lawmakers
sell the license and registration fee plan to the public by arguing
that motorists will benefit.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, then-Governor William F. Weld issued an executive order
that provided for a one-time $30 ``lifetime'' fee to register a
car, with two-year renewals but no further charges. Previously, car
owners had to pay $30 every two years for a registration _ and will
again under this legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Weld also ordered that driving license renewal fees be lowered
from $33.75 to $2. That order was due to take effect this month.
</P>
<P>
   The plan will also include about $250 million combined from the
Turnpike Authority, which oversees the Big Dig, and Massport, which
controls Logan International Airport where access is being improved
by the addition of the project's Ted Williams Tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   The overrun package, including contingencies and funding for
other road and bridge work, could total more than $2 billion,
sources familiar with the discussions said.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate plans to pay for the overrun differed in
several ways. While both chambers called for keeping driver's
license fees, the Senate did not propose reinstating registration
fees but conceded the idea to the House under this compromise.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate and Governor Paul Cellucci wanted to use the surplus
to pay down debt and reap savings that could be used to leverage
lower-rate borrowing or be applied as cash. The House conceded this
idea to the Senate and governor.
</P>
<P>
   All told, the state is expected to receive about $500 million in
Federal Highway money for next fiscal year, which begins in
October. About $175 million of that would be earmarked for the Big
Dig.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has approved $8.55 billion, of which about $5 billion
has already been spent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
