<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1331 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      05-10 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: GIULIANI'S DECISION 
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB HERBERT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You could tell from the headlines, especially in the
tabloids, that something had to happen _ that, as Donna Hanover
said last week in an emotional appearance outside St. Patrick's
Cathedral, ``decisions'' had to be made.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, his own voice halting and at times trembling, Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani told reporters that he and Hanover were
considering a formal separation.
</P>
<P>
   That's one decision. Soon, I think, will come the decision to
abandon the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   In disclosing his plans to separate from Hanover, the mayor
said, ``I'm motivated by all the tremendous invasion of privacy
that's taken place in everyone's life _ my family, Judith Nathan's
family.''
</P>
<P>
   Nathan has been described by Giuliani as his ``very good
friend,'' and Wednesday he said, ``I'm going to need her more now
than maybe I did before.''
</P>
<P>
   I rooted for the longest time for a Senate race between Rudolph
Giuliani and Hillary Rodham Clinton. This was purely out of
self-interest. I make my living running around with a pocketful of
paper and a Bic pen, chasing stories. And I couldn't imagine a
story that would be more fun than all-out warfare between these two
huge, aggressive and controversial personalities.
</P>
<P>
   Way back in November 1998 I wrote: ``I have found nothing to
substantiate the rumors that Hillary Rodham Clinton is interested
in running for Moynihan's seat. But the idea of a Senate race
between Clinton and Rudolph Giuliani is such a splendid one that it
must be kept alive at all costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, the story has certainly been incredible. The real events
have trumped anything I might have imagined.
</P>
<P>
   But it has not been fun.
</P>
<P>
   You have to be very twisted indeed to get a kick out of public
figures coming down with cancer and the very public disintegration
of a marriage.
</P>
<P>
   The combat I imagined was of the political variety, Hillary
against Rudy, Democrat against Republican, one narcissist against
another.
</P>
<P>
   The dynamics changed radically two weeks ago when Giuliani
announced that he had been diagnosed with prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Just days later came stories in the tabloids about the mayor's
relationship with Nathan. The mayor acknowledged they were friends,
and that has been the hot topic ever since. The tabloids went into
overdrive. There were daily stories, with photos, about Nathan. The
history of the relationship was chronicled. Her wardrobe was
analyzed and re-analyzed. A media encampment was set up outside her
East Side high-rise. Other reporters and photographers were
dispatched to Hazleton, Pa., to get reactions from Nathan's
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday it was clear that the frenzy wasn't about to abate,
and top Republican officials were openly concerned about the effect
it was having on the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's response was to announce that he and Hanover would
pursue a formal separation. And Hanover called reporters to Gracie
Mansion where she spoke tearfully about problems that went back
several years.
</P>
<P>
   For these and other reasons, I don't see how Giuliani stays in
the Senate race. And I would expect his exit to come sooner rather
than later. Like most other observers, I doubt that he ever really
wanted to go to the Senate. He's a guy who likes to command.
</P>
<P>
   And while he has tried mightily to seem otherwise, he's also
human. And that means he is laboring beneath an almost unimaginable
load of physical and emotional stress. He is the mayor of the
nation's largest city. He is fighting the disease that killed his
father. His marriage has unraveled. The person he seems closest to
is being hounded day and night by the media, and that will only
grow worse. The prognosis he has received from his doctors is very
good, but the treatment is rough nevertheless, and it is likely, at
least to some extent, to be debilitating. And after going through
that, his immediate task would be to engage in a titanic, historic
battle for the Senate against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   I expect Giuliani to bow out of this race, regain his health,
settle the difficulties in his personal life and then come back,
renewed, to run in some future campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 2051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
