<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1333 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SIERRA-LEONE-ART-NYT &LR;      05-10 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-LEONE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS FLEE TO SIERRA LEONE CAPITAL AS WAR LOOMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also SIERRA-LEONE-U.N.) 
(ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUI JUNCTION, Sierra Leone _ Thousands of panicky men, women and
children fled toward the capital on Wednesday, carrying loads on
their heads or scrambling to board jammed buses, as fighting edged
closer to the capital.
</P>
<P>
   This junction, about 10 miles east of the center of the capital,
Freetown, was the scene of intense confusion on Wednesday morning.
As civilians streamed toward the capital, which remained under the
control of an embattled U.N. force, vehicles filled with
pro-government militiamen rumbled away from town, toward the
fighting with the Revolutionary United Front.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are expecting the rebels to come from the Waterloo
direction _ there is only one route,'' said Lt. Joseph Jalloh of
the Sierra Leone army. Waterloo is five miles away. ``We are trying
to stop them from coming to Freetown.''
</P>
<P>
   As the confusion intensified, the whereabouts of Foday Sankoh,
the leader of the Revolutionary United Front, remained unclear. His
absence complicates efforts to negotiate the release of 500 U.N.
peacekeepers and civilians being held by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have rapidly advanced westward toward the capital in
recent days. And the U.N. mission, whose mandate had been to keep
the peace as a neutral force, has essentially become allied with
the Sierra Leonean army and a militia known as the Kamajors to
stave off a rebel assault on Freetown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is now the goal of our force to preserve the stability and
peace in Freetown,'' said Bernard Miyet, the U.N. undersecretary
general for peacekeeping, at the end of a two-day visit to Sierra
Leone. ``It is our immediate priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Miyet said the United Nations was committed to staying in Sierra
Leone. ``I have not come here to shut down this operation,'' he
said. ``I have come to see how we can preserve peace for a
population that deserves peace.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the second time since the beginning of last year that
Freetown, at the western end of a peninsula in the Atlantic Ocean,
has faced a possible invasion. In a fierce attack in January 1999,
the Revolutionary United Front, then allied with ex-government
soldiers, pushed into the center of town, burning houses, raping
women and girls, killings thousands and hacking off the hands and
arms of hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   The advance of rebels with a brutal past has caused panic among
Sierra Leoneans. Since Tuesday, when U.N. peacekeepers abandoned
Masiaka, a junction town about 25 miles east of here, civilians
have been fleeing westward.
</P>
<P>
   The sight of thousands traveling by foot, bicycle and vehicle,
carrying clothes, gasoline containers, mattresses, and pots and
pans, appeared to have heightened fears in villages and towns as
they made their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the people from Waterloo are leaving,'' said Samuel
Fofanah, 25, a teacher at Peninsula Secondary School who left
Waterloo on his bicycle early on Wednesday morning. ``We heard
gunshots.''
</P>
<P>
   Those passing through Jui Junction included Abraham, 9, who was
as old as Sierra Leone's war. Abraham, whose hands were hacked off
by the Revolutionary United Front during an attack on Waterloo in
January 1999, was carrying a large nylon bag on his head, steadying
it with the stumps of his arms. He and his father had walked from
Waterloo on Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   James Kargbo, a 26-year-old high school student in Waterloo, had
fled to Freetown on Monday with most of his belongings. He was
trying to return on Wednesday to Waterloo, but then learned that
soldiers were no longer permitting civilians to travel east of
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I left behind many important items, like my books,'' Kargbo
said, as he sat on a flatbed pickup truck with a small radio glued
to his left ear. ``I am a student.''
</P>
<P>
   People who could afford it spent 500 Leones, or 25 cents, to buy
a seat in a bus or station wagon.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. Johnny Paul Koroma, the head of a junta that toppled
the government of President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah in 1997 but who is
now allied with him, claimed on a Freetown radio station that his
men had taken back Masiaka. The news, though, could not be
confirmed and did not halt the exodus toward the capital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
