<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1335 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-METHODISTS11-COX     05-10 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METHODISTS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UNITED METHODIST GENERAL CONFERENCE
 &HT;    Gay rights demonstrators are arrested before vote
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ More than 180 gay rights protesters, including at
least one United Methodist bishop, were arrested outside the
convention center here Wednesday in a carefully choreographed
demonstration aimed at delegates to the United Methodist General
Conference inside.
</P>
<P>
   The conference faces a vote later this week on whether to keep
church bans against ordaining sexually active gays and lesbians to
the ministry and performing same-sex unions. The conference
committee handling those issues has recommended that the
denomination maintain the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   Ten United Methodist bishops and several veterans of the civil
rights movement were among the 300-or-so who began to assemble at
dawn on a plaza above the entrance to the center. They marched
around the building, and then about half of them, in groups of 10
to 30, blocked the driveway leading from the main entrance.
</P>
<P>
   As each small band lined up across the roadway, Commander Jim
Davidson of the Cleveland police stepped forward, identified
himself and said, ``I am asking you to please disperse and allow
access to this facility.''
</P>
<P>
   When they did not move, he called up uniformed police officers
lining the driveway, in pairs of two, to lead them away. Many of
those arrested had already filled out sheets with their names,
addresses and Social Security numbers to speed up the process. As
each group moved away, another group quickly re-formed the human
blockade.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of counter-protesters not affiliated with the United
Methodist Church positioned themselves on a wall overlooking the
arrests. Chuck Spingola of Newark, Ohio, was one of them. In a
baseball cap and ``Thank God for AIDS'' T-shirt, he dangled a toy
made of two male dolls on an elastic band and yelled at the
protesters, ``The Bible says sodomizers should be stoned to
death.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, a group of people supporting the gay rights
demonstration sang ``Joy to the World'' and ``This Little Light of
Mine'' and cheered on each group who was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on the floor of the conference inside, about 50
visitors in the balcony stood to sing ``We Are Marching in the
Light of God,'' a Christian gay rights anthem. A few dozen
delegates sympathetic with the gay rights cause also stood beside
their tables on the floor where the conference was in session.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Whittemore, the certified public accountant from Hartwell,
Ga., who heads the North Georgia delegation said he and some other
Georgians knew little of what occurred outside. They came into the
convention center at 6:30 a.m. to meet with candidates for bishop
from the Southeast, ``and we've been working ever since,'' he said
late Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Whittemore said the United Methodist Church does not shut out
homosexuals. ``Our stance is that all people are of sacred worth
and all people are welcome at United Methodist Churches,'' he said.
``At the same time, we say a number of things are not acceptable.
We say homosexual practice is incompatible with our view.''
</P>
<P>
   As of late afternoon, many of the demonstrators who were
arrested remained in jail awaiting processing, according to Lt.
Sharon MacKay of the Cleveland Police Department. Those arrested
were charged with aggravated disorderly conduct, a misdemeanor, and
were fined about $180.
</P>
<P>
   United Methodist Bishop Joseph Sprague of northern Illinois was
one of those arrested. Before the demonstration, he said he had
asked himself, ``Where would Jesus Christ be today? Where would
Martin Luther King be today? Where would Mohandas Gandhi be
today?''
</P>
<P>
   Gandhi's grandson, Arun Gandhi, was in the first line of
protesters arrested. He is the founder of a center for nonviolence
in Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   King's daughter Yolanda, an actress living in Los Angeles,
marched but chose not to block the drive and be arrested because
she was hurrying back to Los Angeles for the premiere of
``Odessa,'' a film in which she stars.
</P>
<P>
   Although her father never specifically addressed the question of
homosexual rights, ``the fact is my father talked about the beloved
community, where all people receive respect and dignity,'' she said
before the march. ``That includes homosexuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
