<SLUG> BC-LA-EDWARDS-TRIMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERDICT SHAKES LOUISIANA'S CYNICISM A BIT 
</HEADLINE>
  By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Political corruption in Louisiana did not begin
with Edwin W. Edwards, and it presumably will not end with his
conviction Tuesday on federal racketeering, conspiracy and
extortion charges. But many Louisianians said Wednesday that they
took a certain measure of hope from the jury's firm declaration
that malfeasance would not be tolerated here the way it has been
since the era of Huey Long.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good old boy mentality has probably stuck here more than
in any other state,'' said Walt L. Nixon, a 46-year-old Website
designer who was taking a morning cigarette break outside the
Texaco building in downtown New Orleans. ``It's good to see that
things are being exposed.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon, a New Orleans native, said that the jury in the former
governor's case sent a clear message, and he predicted that some
Louisiana politicians might actually hear it. ``It'll be very slow
to come around,'' he said, ``but it is a start.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet there was a certain ambivalence in the reaction of many
here Wednesday. Some still expressed a measure of fondness for
Edwards because the four-term governor had done good things for the
state, they said, or simply because he had entertained them for so
long. Some squirmed at the notion that the government might put a
72-year-old man in jail for what could be the rest of his life. And
many said a single conviction, even of such a prominent defendant,
could not erode a wall of cynicism that has been built over
generations. (Even now, Edwards faces a second trial on unrelated
charges and the state's election commissioner and insurance
commissioner are under indictment.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a step in the right direction,'' said Paul A. Gauthreaux
Jr., a shipping company manager who was eating lunch on the New
Orleans Riverwalk along the Mississippi, ``but whether or not it'll
change anything, I doubt it. It's been going on for hundreds of
years and one little conviction's not going to make much of a
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   One day after the jury in Baton Rouge convicted him on 17 of the
26 counts in his indictment, Edwards was back in court Wednesday as
it considered whether he and three co-defendants would have to
forfeit illicitly gained assets. After several hours of
deliberation, the jury declared that the defendants would forfeit
$2.56 million of the $3.1 million sought by the government. U.S.
District Judge Frank Polozola will determine each defendant's
portion of that amount.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday afternoon, the jury found Edwards, his son Stephen,
and three associates guilty of multiple counts related to the
bidding for coveted state riverboat casino licenses, both during
Edwards' last term in office and after his departure in 1996. He
could receive a total of more than 200 years in prison and be fined
millions of dollars. Using evidence gleaned from wiretaps and
cooperating witnesses, prosecutors in the 17-week trial depicted a
criminal enterprise in which Edwards and his co-defendants demanded
payoffs from businessmen in exchange for the licenses.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards had evaded conviction twice in the 1980s, when he was
twice tried on charges of taking payoffs to help associates win
state hospital licenses. A first trial ended in a mistrial, a
second in acquittal. Those trials helped cement Louisiana's image
as a place where a certain level of corruption would be forgiven,
particularly if the offender was as charming as Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   But Eddie J. Jordan Jr., the U.S. attorney who oversaw Edwards'
prosecution, took pains Wednesday to declare those days over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we begin the process of reclaiming our state's great
name,'' he said in a news conference in Baton Rouge, after Polozola
lifted a ban on public comments by lawyers in the case. ``Today we
begin the process of restoring confidence in our state's democratic
institutions. Today we begin the process of removing the stain of
corruption that has ruined our state's ability and our state's
reputation as a great place to conduct business.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury's verdict, Jordan concluded, sent the message that
``corruption is not the Louisiana way.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Edwards seemed to make that point, saying his convictions
should be ``a reflection on me, not on the people of Louisiana.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Without making an explicit confession, he also contended that
his crimes bore no financial cost for the state. ``There isn't a
penny missing from the state treasury,'' he said. ``There are no
allegations and certainly no evidence that I at any time took
anything voluntarily from the people of this state.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan had a ready response. ``Never is it a victimless crime
when you have a person who has a reputation in state government for
being corrupt because the price we pay is an absence of business
opportunity in this state,'' he said. ``Businesses in their right
mind do not want to come to a state where they know that they will
be shaken down.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some Louisiana residents said that the state's reputation would
change only if a steady federal vigilance was maintained.
``Obviously the federal government is not in a position to mount
that kind of prosecution year after year,'' said Richard Ford, the
novelist, who has lived in New Orleans for 10 years. ``There has to
be a `no tolerance' rule.''
</P>
<P>
   But others said the verdicts should send a strong signal that
Louisiana politicians can no longer charm their way out of trouble.
``Hopefully, this will send the message that it's not funny
anymore,'' said Jim Brandt, president of the Public Affairs
Research Council of Louisiana.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It is a measure of this state's cynicism that many here
expressed surprise at the convictions even as they expressed
certainty about Edwards' guilt. Many also questioned whether he
would spend a day in jail, despite the toughness of the verdicts.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the convictions wiped away the disillusionment felt by
John Volz, the former U.S. attorney who failed twice to convict
Edwards in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really has sort of restored my faith in the ability of
Louisiana citizens to recognize outrageous conduct on the part of
its public officials,'' he said. ``It took 15 years, but justice
has been done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
