u e BC-NAILS-MUSIC-REVIEW-NY     05-10 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAILS-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NINE INCH NAILS': STILL DRAWING POWER FROM DESPAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   By JON PARELES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A man looks within himself and finds he has lost his
soul. He feels pointless, disgusted with his animal impulses,
bitter, furious. He turns to others, but they abuse him or betray
him. He examines authority and sees only cruelty and corruption; he
cannot feel any faith. He lashes out, but that brings no
satisfaction. He seeks oblivion, but stops short of suicide. In the
end he decides simply to endure. If life is purgatory, at least the
pain is real.
</P>
<P>
   No one is better than Trent Reznor at turning such desolate
nihilism into arena rock. Leading his band, Nine Inch Nails, at
Madison Square Garden on Tuesday night, Reznor used both brute
force and finesse to bring out the shadings of torment in his
songs.
</P>
<P>
   Nine Inch Nails became one of the most influential bands of the
1990s by adding melody to the jackbooted beat, dance-music
synthesizers and hard-rock guitars of industrial rock, while the
words shouted the secrets of adolescent angst.
</P>
<P>
   Reznor's persona was a sympathetic character at the center of
the onslaught, trying to stay honest even when the whole world was
lined up against him. While pop's mainstream is too busy boasting
and flirting to admit any insecurities, Reznor still knows where
they hide.
</P>
<P>
   His 1999 album, ``The Fragile'' (Nothing/Interscope), is a
meticulously arranged studio creation, and he did not try to
reproduce it from the stage. Instead he pared down most songs to
their blunt essentials: beats, keyboard riffs, power chords and his
voice, howling or gasping its bleak insights. Drum machines or
human muscle stomped a beat; synthesizers zapped out riffs; guitars
played power chords as unswerving as granite cliffs. There were
sudden, explosive crescendos and pockets of silence that were just
as startling.
</P>
<P>
   To reflect the stark power of the music, the musicians were
small figures in semidarkness, dwarfed by video screens and
scaffolding and surrounded by white lights that repeatedly blasted
the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Reznor has enough hard-riffing singalongs to fill an entire set.
But he also chose to play some of the more elaborate songs on ``The
Fragile,'' including ``La Mer'' and ``The Great Below,'' with a
long instrumental section. As majestic images of water and then
flames (by the video artist Bill Viola) played above the band, the
music built inexorably from a modest piano ostinato to a quiet
march, without the album's effects but with its suspense; a simple
drumbeat, long absent, entered like a thunderclap. It was art-rock
to rival Pink Floyd or the Cure.
</P>
<P>
   Reznor has not entirely given up on human fellowship.
Introducing the viciously mocking song that has been retitled
``Starsuckers Inc.'' for its release as a single, he said it was
about ``a friend,'' and then the friend it denounced, Marilyn
Manson, joined him onstage, publicly ending a long feud. ( Manson
has also directed the video clip for the song.) Nine Inch Nails
then backed Manson singing his own song, ``The Beautiful People'';
his growl and rasp sounded crude after Reznor's finely modulated
despair.
</P>
<P>
   But Reznor retained the last word, and it was solitary. Lighted
from below to make his eye sockets look hollow, he intoned
``Hurt,'' a catalog of self-loathing. But the song ended with a
quiet vow: ``If I could start again, I would find a way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
