<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1360 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-L.A.-YIDDISH-FESTIVAL     05-10 1296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-L.A.-YIDDISH-FESTIVAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A YIDDISH FESTIVAL STAKES A CLAIM IN LOS ANGELES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Conn., Mass., Neb., Canada, Argentina, Germany,
Israel, Mexico, France, Poland)   By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Nearly eight years ago, Aaron Paley and several
friends began a reading group in Yiddish, a language that he
learned from his parents while growing up in the San Fernando
Valley. By 1995 Paley, an arts festival organizer, decided to
create a daylong event celebrating Yiddish at a Jewish community
center in suburban Sherman Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expected a few hundred people, and 6,000 showed up,'' said
Paley, 42. ``It was a wake-up call to all of us that there was a
huge interest in Yiddish that had not been tapped. The language had
been marginalized. It wasn't taught. It was seen as kind of
nostalgic. There was no serious approach to Yiddish or Yiddish
culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to look back, we wanted to look forward. There
was something important to say today.''
</P>
<P>
   From those beginnings Paley helped create the largest festival
in the nation honoring Yiddish, the 1,000-year-old language of the
Jews of Eastern Europe. It is a language and, perhaps more
important, a culture that is viewed at the festival as
unsentimental, vibrant, emotional and alive.
</P>
<P>
   The festival, called ``Yiddishkayt Los Angeles,'' takes place
this year from Sunday to May 21 at theaters, museums and
synagogues. Its partners and sponsors range from the City of Los
Angeles and the Los Angeles Arts Commission to theaters and
schools.
</P>
<P>
   The festival is part of what seems to be a general resurgent
interest in Yiddish. In New Haven, Conn., the Yale Repertory Co. is
staging a student project, ``The People Versus `The God of
Vengeance,''' by Rebecca Taichman, who attends Yale Drama School.
The play is about a 1923 obscenity trial involving a Yiddish drama,
``The God of Vengeance,'' by Sholem Asch.
</P>
<P>
   Like Los Angeles, New York seems to be witnessing a Yiddish
revival. Pearl Gluck, director of literary programs at the Jewish
Community Center in Manhattan, said that summer programs and
Yiddish classes were proliferating around the city, and that poetry
readings, film series and music festivals involving Jewish culture
were now taking place, especially on the Lower East Side. ``There's
definitely a reattention to Yiddish and the culture around it,''
said Gluck, who will show parts of her film, ``Divan, (The
Couch),'' about her own Hasidic history, at the Los Angeles
festival.
</P>
<P>
   This festival is unusual for its Los Angeles-style blend of
tradition and artiness, including experimental dances with Yiddish
themes, klezmer music with modernist influences, and a performance
by a satirical comedian and juggler, Sara Felder, who grew up in
Brighton Beach, Brooklyn, without knowing too much Yiddish but who
took a crash course at Columbia University four years ago to
immerse herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't learn Yiddish, who will?'' asked Felder, 41, who
lives in San Francisco. ``If I don't preserve this culture, who
will do it?''
</P>
<P>
   Felder described herself, as she does in her act, as a
contemporary lesbian American Jewish juggler. ``It's my own niche,
and I'm proud of it,'' she said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly John Malashock, a choreographer who spent years
dancing with the Twyla Tharp Dance troupe in New York and has
worked with Lar Lubovitch, Anna Sokolow and Donald McKayle, has
created a dance called ``Blessings and Curses.'' The dance, about a
weaver, uses Yiddish and Sephardic folk songs, cantorial music and
contemporary classics. (Karen Hartman, a playwright, wrote the
story.)
</P>
<P>
   Malashock, who was raised in San Diego and Omaha, Neb., said
that he had grown up knowing only a handful of Yiddish words, but
that he deeply immersed himself in Jewish culture when his son,
Duncan, was studying for his bar mitzvah four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The work I'm now doing is rooted in Jewish culture, some of it
Yiddish culture, some of it Hebrew culture,'' said Malashock, 49.
``I grew up in a fairly secular atmosphere. Honestly, it wasn't hip
to identify yourself by religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet I have a longing _ and I think a lot of artists are the
same _ to go back and explore your background.''
</P>
<P>
   Isaac Bashevis Singer, the Nobel Prize-winning author who wrote
in Yiddish, once described it as perhaps the only language never
spoken by men in power. Once the lingua franca of Jews over most
parts of the world, Yiddish arose from a number of German dialects
in the ghettoes of Central Europe. Its essentially German
vocabulary has been broadened over the centuries with traces of
Hebrew, Slavic, Romanian and French.
</P>
<P>
   Prof. Eli Katz, who teaches Yiddish at the University of
California at Berkeley, said there had been a distinct revival of
interest in the language in recent years, and perhaps greater
interest in the culture of Eastern European Jews before the
Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   The high point of Yiddish, he said, occurred ironically and
tragically on the eve of the Holocaust, when it was spoken by
millions. At the same time a significant literature was being
created in cities like Warsaw, Vilnius and New York. Before
Germany's annihilation of 6 million Jews, Yiddish was the tongue of
more than 11 million people. Today, by to several accounts, Yiddish
is spoken by perhaps 4 million Jews, mostly in the United States,
Canada, Argentina, Israel, Mexico, France and several countries in
Eastern Europe. Many more understand words and phrases.
</P>
<P>
   Katz and several artists connected to the Los Angeles festival
said the revival of interest stemmed from such factors as nostalgia
and an effort to reclaim ethnic heritage often overlooked in past
generations' rush to assimilate.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles festival takes place in a polyglot city that
has, in comparison to New York, a smaller, although pronounced,
Jewish influence. There are 519,000 Jews in the Los Angeles area,
and 1.45 million Jews in New York, according to the 1999 American
Jewish Yearbook.
</P>
<P>
   Paley, who has worked in New York, and is founder and executive
director of Community Arts Resources, probably the pre-eminent
festival organizer in Los Angeles, said putting on such a festival
in New York would prove difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not the center of the Jewish world in this country,'' he
said. ``New York is.'' As a result, various old-line organizations
that have sought to perpetuate Yiddish, like the Workmen's Circle,
Yivo (the Yiddish Institute for Jewish Research) and The Forward, a
weekly newspaper, might want to involve themselves in such a
festival, he said. ``But there are issues of turf and issues of
politics, which we don't have in Los Angeles,'' said Paley.
``Sometimes it's more difficult to pull things off in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   The interplay of music is a dominant theme of the festival. One
klezmer group, Brave Old World, which has generated strong reviews
in recent years, mixes the traditional dance and wedding music of
Eastern European Jews with modern and original compositions.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Alpert, a vocalist and violinist with the group, grew up
in Los Angeles and Boston. He said the klezmer revival in the 1970s
and '80s came about after several decades in which it was simply
too painful for younger American-Jewish artists to explore their
European heritage because of the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a deliberate attempt to replace Yiddish identity in
particular with an identification with Israel and Israeli
culture,'' Alpert said. Perhaps Alex Haley's book ``Roots'' as well
as the movement among blacks seeking a national identity led Jews
in some ways to do the same, Alpert said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly, ethnicity and one's ethnic identity has become
hip,'' he said. ``Yiddish has become hip.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
