<SLUG> BC-NY-MAYOR-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI SAYS HE IS SEPARATING FROM HIS WIFE; EFFECT ON SENATE RACE
UNCLEAR
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos _ NYT11,13 _ are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make one-time purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani announced on Wednesday that he
was separating from his wife, Donna Hanover. He said that as he
battles prostate cancer he will need Judith Nathan, the woman he
describes as a ``very good'' friend, ``more now than maybe I did
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani did not say whether he would continue his race for the
U.S. Senate against Hillary Rodham Clinton, but he did say that his
political career was not at the moment his first concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really care about politics right now,'' Giuliani said.
``I'm thinking about my family, the people that I love and what can
be done that's honest and truthful and that protects them the best.
I'm not thinking about politics. Politics comes at least second,
maybe third, maybe fourth, somewhere else. It'll all work itself
out some way politically.''
</P>
<P>
   In an extraordinary news conference in Bryant Park, Giuliani
spoke at length to reporters about his relationships with his wife
and Nathan. He spoke in a soft voice with downcast eyes as he
tightly gripped both sides of the lectern. The mayor described his
emotional state as ``sad'' and then added, ``I feel terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Three hours later, Hanover appeared outside the gates of Gracie
Mansion and, with a wavering voice and tears in her eyes, said:
``Today's turn of events brings me great sadness. I had hoped to
keep this marriage together. For several years, it was difficult to
participate in Rudy's public life because of his relationship with
one staff member.''
</P>
<P>
   Joannie Danielides, Hanover's press secretary, said that Hanover
was referring to Cristyne F. Lategano, Giuliani's former
communications director who is now president of NYC &AMP; Company, the
city's tourism bureau. Friends of Hanover said on Wednesday that
she had described the relationship between her husband and Lategano
as ``intimate'' while Lategano worked at City Hall. The mayor has
denied having had a romantic relationship with Lategano, who left
City Hall last May and married Nicholas Nicholas, a sports writer,
in February.
</P>
<P>
   Hanover also said that ``beginning last May, I made a major
effort to bring us back together. Rudy and I re-established some of
our personal intimacy through the fall. At that point, he chose
another path. Rudy and I will now discuss the possibility of a
legal separation.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanover added that she and the couple's children, Andrew, 14,
and Caroline, 10, will continue to live at Gracie Mansion, the
mayor's official residence, ``for at least the next few months''
because of security concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Lategano issued this statement on Wednesday: ``I have no desire
to speculate why Donna Hanover decided to issue the statement that
she did. Understandably, this is a difficult time. I wish both the
mayor and Donna Hanover a successful resolution.'' Lategano added
that she was ``proud'' to have worked for Giuliani, and that he
``is and will continue to be one of the greatest mayors in our
city's history.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
