<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HOLLYPARK-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYLER BAZE CONTINUES FAMILY TRADITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Generally, teen-agers and race tracks don't
make a good mix.
</P>
<P>
   But, then there is Tyler Baze, a 17-year-old Monrovia resident,
who is making quite a name for himself at Hollywood Park.
</P>
<P>
   Baze, an apprentice rider, entered the week with seven wins,
just one behind leading rider Victor Espinoza. Needless to say for
a guy who won his first race just seven months ago, Baze is riding
high.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm working at it,'' he said. ``But this is a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   As it is with all aprentice jockeys, Baze is known in the jock's
room as the ``bug boy.'' And, while he takes his share of ribbing,
he also is getting some great advice from the nation's top jockeys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learn by watching different riders and listening to what the
older riders have to say,'' Baze said. ``Since i've only been
working at this for about a year, it's nice to be able to talk to
them too.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyler, a native of Washington state, isn't the first member of
the Baze family to take to racing. His uncle Gary Baze, was the
all-time leading jockey at now-defunct Longacres; second cousin
Russell baze is a member of the Hall of Fame and the top rider on
the Northern California circuit.
</P>
<P>
   The list goes on. His grandfather Carl Baze was a longtime
trainer in Washington. And, his great-grandmother was one of the
nation's first-ever female jockeys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in my family is in racing,'' Tyler Baze said. ``I
always thought I be small enough to carry on that tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   Six of Baze's seven wins have come in the saddle for trainer
John Sadler, who first used him in October at Oak Tree. After that
if was off to Turf Pasadise for some needed experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sent Tyler down to the minor leagues to get a little
seasoning,'' Sadler said. ``Now, he's a polished act.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadler also praised the young man's professionalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tyler's a throwback,'' Sadler said. ``He calls people sir and
madam and he is very respectful. He's a terrific hard-working kid.
</P>
<P>
   (BOX) Triple Crown season is a unique time at Hollywood Park.
Last year, jockey Chris Antley won the Kentucky Derby and was
beseiged with requests for interviews, autographs and endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   Things were no different for Sierra Madre resident Kent
Desormeaux Wednesday. The jockey, who had a beautiful ride aboard
Fusaichi Pegasus, was the center of attention every time he stepped
out of the jock's room.
</P>
<P>
   How long it will last is anybody's guess. But as long as
Fusaichi Pegasus wins, Desormeaux will be the man of the hour.
</P>
<P>
   (BOX) Tout Charmant will make her 2000 debut Sunday in the
Wilshire Handicap. Formerly trained by Bob Baffert, the filly is
now in the hands of Ron McAnally.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's working good, she looks good and she acts good,''
McAnally said. ``You'll never know if she's as good as she was when
Baffert had her, but this is a good place to start.''
</P>
<P>
   Other probables for the $100,000 Grade III Wilshire Handicap
include Penny Marie, Perfect Copy and Finally.
</P>
</TEXT>
