<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY STADIUM PROPOSAL APPROVED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH -- A proposal that would allow the Los Angeles Galaxy
soccer team to move from Pasadena to Cal State Dominguez Hills,
Wednesday earned approval from the California State University
Board of Trustees.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, which paves the way for a Galaxy move from the Rose
Bowl to a soccer complex in the South Bay, had been approved by the
board's committee on finance after a hearing Tuesday. The full
board accepted that approval.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, the Galaxy would develop a portion of the
campus, adding a 30,000 seat soccer stadium, a smaller tenis
stadium and a myriad of other improvements. The project is expected
to cost in the neighborhood of $85 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy hopes to take Wednesday's approval of the proposal to
attract the United States Soccer Federation. The Chicago-based
group is seeking bids on its plan to build a new soccer academy for
the United States men's and women's national soccer teams.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Leiweke, president of the Galaxy, said the state University
Board of Trustees' aproval was necessary before the Galaxy could
make their bid.
</P>
</TEXT>
