<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-FLAG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISTRUST FOILS SOUTH CAROLINA HOUSE'S EFFORT TO REMOVE DIVISIVE
BATTLE FLAG 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID FIRESTONE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ In a flurry of horse trading, members of the
South Carolina House of Representatives spent Wednesday desperately
searching for a plan that would move the Confederate battle flag
from atop the Statehouse and satisfy both flag supporters and their
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   But the profound mistrust and animosity between the two sides
kept any plan from mustering a majority, though by Wednesday
evening the House appeared to be moving toward a settlement on the
issue, though on a path with many turns.
</P>
<P>
   The most promising proposal, which seemed to have bipartisan
support at idday but later died on a vote of 82-35, would move the
flag from the dome to a Confederate memorial in front of the
Capitol and would also erect flagpoles bearing military banners to
honor soldiers who fell in four 20th-century wars. The plan called
for the Confederate flag to fly from the dome one day a year, on
Confederate Memorial Day, which by coincidence was Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The logic of the plan illustrated the body's desperation to
placate all sides in the debate. For those who consider the flag an
offensive symbol of white supremacy and a reminder of slavery, the
plan would have diluted the impact of having a single Confederate
battle flag at the entrance to the Capitol by putting it in a
historical context of honoring the soldiers of many other wars.
</P>
<P>
   For those who revere the flag as an emblem of honor to their
slain Confederate ancestors, the plan would confer at least a day's
worth of official legitimacy to the flag on Confederate Memorial
Day, which observes the date when Gen. Stonewall Jackson died.
</P>
<P>
   But hardliners on each side found those aspects unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``To fly that flag for a day, even for an hour, even for a
minute, is unacceptable to us,'' said Joseph Neal, a black Democrat
from Chester, who would have supported the plan if not for the
one-day-a-year provision. ``It is not a sovereign flag, and it is
an insult to people of color.''
</P>
<P>
   White Republicans who want to keep the flag on the dome picked
apart the plan from the other end of the spectrum, criticizing it
for not honoring soldiers in the Revolutionary War, or for being
vague on which flags symbolize certain wars. The Republican
majority leader, Rick Quinn, who supported the proposal, said it
had been hurt when black members compared the Confederate flag to a
swastika, and when demonstrators burned the flag in front of the
Capitol shortly after noon.
</P>
<P>
   There appeared to be about 5 or 6 black members who supported
the plan out of 26 in the House, along with the prominent local
bishop of the AME Church. But white moderates who were pushing the
plan were astonished that most black representatives objected to
the plan because of the single day a year the flag would spend on
the dome, particularly when most black officials supported the
circle of military flags.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get 364 days, and they get one,'' said Bob Sheheen, the
former Democratic speaker who is retiring later this year. ``I'm
asking them to give up all their days, and I'm asking you to make
that commitment for only one day. This amendment changes the
emphasis this state puts on the flag, and it says to our citizens
of color that we are going to view it more like you view it.''
</P>
<P>
   The failure of the plan left the House facing the compromise
reached by the State Senate, which appears unacceptable to the
black members. It would remove the flag from the dome and the two
chambers and put a smaller version in front of the Capitol on a
30-foot pole, the only flag in front of the building. Opponents
said the plan left the flag in far too prominent a position.
</P>
<P>
   The flag has been flying from the dome since 1962, and has
severely tainted the state's reputation for racial tolerance. A
national economic boycott of the state, being conducted by the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, has has
hurt the state's tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
