<SLUG> BC-HURRICANES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GULF COAST WARNED TO BRACE FOR MORE HURRICANES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By J.R. GONZALES 
and PHILIP CAUTHON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A major hurricane with 155 mph winds could leave 1,400
dead and 125,000 homeless along the Texas Gulf Coast, Harris County
Judge Robert Eckels said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Eckels, also the county's director of emergency management, said
115-mph winds could be felt as far north as Conroe, Texas _ about
100 miles from the coast. The area surrounding the Clear Creek area
of Houston, near the coast, would be under 22 feet of water, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   The estimates are part of a county study simulating what would
happen if a category-five hurricane passed through Houston. No such
hurricane has made landfall here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a big concern that when a big hurricane comes toward
this community, people will not take it seriously and will not
understand the impact,'' Eckels said at the 2000 Houston/Galveston
Hurricane Workshop in Pasadena, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, experts in Washington said Gulf Coast residents
should brace for more hurricanes than the average season, possibly
seven or more.
</P>
<P>
   The average season brings 9.3 tropical storms, 5.8 of hurricane
strength and 2.1 of intense hurricane strength.
</P>
<P>
   Tropical storms form and receive names when their circulating
winds reach 39 mph. They become hurricanes when their winds reach
74 mph and major hurricanes when winds reach 111 mph.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane season, which begins June 1 and ends Nov. 30,
likely will bring stronger and longer-lasting storms than usual,
including three or more ``major'' hurricanes with sustained winds
over 110 mph, said scientists at the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just about the number'' of storms, said Max Mayfield,
director of NOAA's National Hurricane Center. ``What really counts
is where they make landfall and how strong they are. Just one
hurricane over your community makes it a very bad year.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Weather Research Center in Houston and hurricane
expert William Gray at Colorado State University predicted a quiet
season.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pasadena workshop, experts addressed the possibility of a
storm similar to the 1900 Galveston hurricane, which killed an
estimated 8,000 people and remains the deadliest natural disaster
in America.
</P>
<P>
   Since that storm, Galveston has constructed a seawall and raised
the grade of the island. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``Think about all the people that have moved here,'' said Bill
Read, meteorologist in charge at the Houston-Galveston National
Weather Service. Read estimated as much as 30 percent of the
Houston area's population did not live here when Hurricane Alicia
made landfall in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last decade, no hurricanes and only three tropical
storms have affected the upper Texas coast. Many believe this
relative quiet will cause people to become more relaxed in their
hurricane preparations.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Landsea, meteorologist at the NOAA's Hurricane Research
Division, said in Pasadena that fault for much of the damage will
fall on residents instead of Mother Nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to call it a natural disaster,'' Landsea said.
``We help make them.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, NOAA officials expressed concern about a survey
that shows people in hurricane-prone regions are largely
ill-informed on the basics of hurricane preparation.
</P>
<P>
   For example, most people do not know that flooding causes the
majority of deaths during hurricanes and nearly half are unaware
that homeowner's insurance does not cover flood damage, according
to the May telephone survey of 1,037 people in several southern
states, including Texas.
</P>
<P>
   For more hurricane preparedness information, log on to the Web
site www.fema.gov/hu98/hurinfo.htm
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
