<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI SAYS HE IS SEPARATING FROM HIS WIFE; EFFECT ON SENATE RACE
UNCLEAR
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds note: resending with correct slug, 2nd Take added)   (See also NY-GIULIANI-ASSESS) 
(ART ADV: Photos _ NYT11,13 _ are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make one-time purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani announced on Wednesday that he
was separating from his wife, Donna Hanover. He said that as he
battles prostate cancer he will need Judith Nathan, the woman he
describes as a ``very good'' friend, ``more now than maybe I did
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani did not say whether he would continue his race for the
U.S. Senate against Hillary Rodham Clinton, but he did say that his
political career was not at the moment his first concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really care about politics right now,'' Giuliani said.
``I'm thinking about my family, the people that I love and what can
be done that's honest and truthful and that protects them the best.
I'm not thinking about politics. Politics comes at least second,
maybe third, maybe fourth, somewhere else. It'll all work itself
out some way politically.''
</P>
<P>
   In an extraordinary news conference in Bryant Park, Giuliani
spoke at length to reporters about his relationships with his wife
and Nathan. He spoke in a soft voice with downcast eyes as he
tightly gripped both sides of the lectern. The mayor described his
emotional state as ``sad'' and then added, ``I feel terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Three hours later, Hanover appeared outside the gates of Gracie
Mansion and, with a wavering voice and tears in her eyes, said:
``Today's turn of events brings me great sadness. I had hoped to
keep this marriage together. For several years, it was difficult to
participate in Rudy's public life because of his relationship with
one staff member.''
</P>
<P>
   Joannie Danielides, Hanover's press secretary, said that Hanover
was referring to Cristyne F. Lategano, Giuliani's former
communications director who is now president of NYC &AMP; Company, the
city's tourism bureau. Friends of Hanover said on Wednesday that
she had described the relationship between her husband and Lategano
as ``intimate'' while Lategano worked at City Hall. The mayor has
denied having had a romantic relationship with Lategano, who left
City Hall last May and married Nicholas Nicholas, a sports writer,
in February.
</P>
<P>
   Hanover also said that ``beginning last May, I made a major
effort to bring us back together. Rudy and I re-established some of
our personal intimacy through the fall. At that point, he chose
another path. Rudy and I will now discuss the possibility of a
legal separation.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanover added that she and the couple's children, Andrew, 14,
and Caroline, 10, will continue to live at Gracie Mansion, the
mayor's official residence, ``for at least the next few months''
because of security concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Lategano issued this statement on Wednesday: ``I have no desire
to speculate why Donna Hanover decided to issue the statement that
she did. Understandably, this is a difficult time. I wish both the
mayor and Donna Hanover a successful resolution.'' Lategano added
that she was ``proud'' to have worked for Giuliani, and that he
``is and will continue to be one of the greatest mayors in our
city's history.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani had no reaction to the statements of his wife and his
former aide as he left City Hall at 7:20 on Wednesday night for a
Senate fund-raiser in Westchester County. He also refused to answer
a question about whether he would withdraw from the race.
</P>
<P>
   Friends of Hanover said that although she and her husband had
talked in recent days about ending their 16-year marriage, Hanover
did not know that Giuliani was going to announce their planned
separation at his news conference. Friends said she learned of her
husband's remarks immediately after the conclusion of the news
conference, which was held on the outdoor balcony of The Bryant
Park Grill in midtown Manhattan. The friends described Hanover as
``distraught.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Giuliani's senior advisers said on Wednesday that the
mayor's announcement caught them by surprise, too, even though
Giuliani had made no secret of his estrangement from his wife over
the past few years and had announced last week that Nathan, 45, a
single mother and registered nurse who works for a pharmaceutical
company, was a ``very good friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Pictures of Giuliani and Nathan leaving a restaurant together
were first published on May 3 by The New York Post. Giuliani
announced that he had prostate cancer in an early, treatable form
on April 27.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether Giuliani had planned beforehand to
announce the possible separation at the news conference, or whether
he wandered into the remarks as reporters questioned him. Since the
mayor learned he has prostate cancer, he has become increasingly
personal and introspective in his news briefings.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday Giuliani had no official statement, and only began
to talk about his marriage after a reporter asked him for a
reaction to comments made on Tuesday by Joseph L. Bruno, the state
Senate majority leader. In a radio interview in Albany, Bruno urged
Giuliani to resolve his differences with Hanover.
</P>
<P>
   She first publicly addressed the issue in a hastily arranged
news conference outside St. Patrick's Cathedral last weekend,
saying that her husband and her marriage ``have been very precious
to me.'' Bruno added that he was concerned that Giuliani's personal
life would distract him from the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   In responding to the question about Bruno, Giuliani never did
say what he thought of the majority leader's remarks. Instead, he
said: ``This is very, very painful. For quite some time it's
probably been apparent that Donna and I lead in many ways
independent and separate lives. It's been a very painful road and
I'm hopeful that we'll be able to formalize that in an agreement
that protects our children, gives them all the security and all the
protection they deserve, and protects Donna.''
</P>
<P>
   When pressed by reporters about whether he meant a legal
separation, the mayor at first said he did not want to give
details. But when asked if his wife would move out of Gracie
Mansion, Giuliani at last used the word ``separation'' by
responding haltingly: ``Nobody, nobody, nobody is moving anywhere.
Everybody is secure and safe. What I said is that we should try to
work out a separation agreement. That's different.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There were only a small group of reporters and television
cameras present in a small space, and many were only a few feet
from the mayor. As Giuliani continued to talk at length about his
relationships with the two women, the briefing became an unusually
intimate confessional for a man who has until recently guarded most
aspects of his private life. At one point, Giuliani was asked if
the media had caused the damage in his public life.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' responded Giuliani, who has often blamed the media in
the past. ``The media makes the damage worse, it didn't cause the
damage. I take responsibility for everything that I've done. And
you have a right to ask me and then I have a right to answer or not
answer. And that's the way I think we can have a respectful
relationship with each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani also spoke warmly of both Nathan and Hanover. ``Judith
_ Judith Nathan is a very, very fine person,'' the mayor said.
``She's been a very good friend to me, before I had to deal with
the decisions that I have to make about my illness and what to do
about it, and I rely on her, and she helps me a great deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he turned his comments to his wife. ``Donna Hanover is a
wonderful woman,'' Giuliani said. ``And she's a wonderful mother.
She's someone that I respect tremendously. The fact that we've
grown independent, we've grown more separate over the years, who
knows why those things happen? But she is a very, very fine,
wonderful person, and she's an extraordinary mother and I have
tremendous respect for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what his emotional state was at that moment, Giuliani
responded: ``My emotional state is I'm very sad. And I feel
terrible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
