<SLUG> BC-GLF-NELSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WELL-RESTED TIGER WOODS RETURNS TO ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Tex. _ A little rest usually does Tiger Woods a lot of
good. In the past nine months, Woods has taken at least two weeks
off on five different occasions. Each time, Woods returned to
action by winning his next tournament.
</P>
<P>
   So after a four-week break, excuse Woods for feeling confident
about the GTE Byron Nelson Classic that begins here Thursday. Woods
has not competed since the Masters, spending his idle time fishing,
resting and preparing for an upcoming busy stretch that will lead
him into next month's U.S. Open. Feeling rejuvenated and
well-rested after Thursday's pro-am at the TPC of Las Colinas,
Woods said he was over the disappointment of finishing fifth in
last month's Masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at the Masters as a positive, actually,'' said Woods,
who has three victories and three second-place finishes in eight
starts this year. ``If you take away two bad holes on Thursday, I
had a pretty good tournament. To get myself back in contention at
the Masters with a chance to win Sunday, I'm pretty proud of that.
I shot the lowest score on the weekend, but I put myself behind on
Thursday.''
</P>
<P>
   Vijay Singh, who won the Masters, will be playing at the Byron
Nelson, part of a world-class field that will also include David
Duval, Hal Sutton, Davis Love III, Phil Mickelson, Nick Price, Jim
Furyk, Jesper Parnevik, Sergio Garcia and Justin Leonard. Loren
Roberts is the defending champion, winning last year after beating
Steve Pate in a playoff.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of Nelson, one of golf's greatest players who is
now 88, helps to make this tournament one of the most popular on
the PGA Tour. Nelson is still giving back to the game, and last
week he shared some of his wisdom with Leonard, who has been mired
in a yearlong slump.
</P>
<P>
   Although he is still ranked No. 18 in the world, Leonard does
not have a top 10 finish this year, and he has not won in more than
two years. Nelson noticed a flaw in Leonard's take-away, so Nelson
visited Leonard at his Dallas home and offered some technical
advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't been playing well enough to suit him, and rightly
so, because he has a lot of talent,'' Nelson said. ``I'd been
wanting to talk to him about it for quite a while. Whether or not
he plays worse or better, that's to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   The tournament is played on two courses Thursday and Friday _
Las Colinas and Cottonwood Valley, before plays shifts exclusively
to Las Colinas on the weekend. Cottonwood Valley is the easier of
the two courses, so any player who struggles there probably will
not win the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoot 70 at Cottonwood, and you're putting yourself behind the
8-ball pretty good,'' said Woods, who won the Byron Nelson in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   With a strong breeze of 15 to 20 miles an hour expected for
Thursday, it could be a difficult day for scoring. But Woods was
eager to end his vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I haven't played a tournament in four weeks,'' said
Woods, who will play in Germany next week, then compete in the
Memorial Tournament the following week. ``I'm pretty excited about
getting out there tomorrow. It's nice to hit a shot that really
matters. When you're home playing with your boys, you hit a bad
shot, it's not a big deal. Pick it up, go on to the next. This is a
little different.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
