<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Antitrust Case Settlement Could Lower Prices of CDs
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission settled an antitrust case against
the nation's five largest music companies that could result in
significant price cuts for compact discs. Officials said the
settlement completed a two-year investigation that found the
companies used illegal marketing agreements to end a price war,
inflate the prices of compact discs and sharply restrict the
ability of retailers to offer discounts. Agency officials estimated
that consumers were overcharged by $500 million over the last four
years.
</P>
<P>
   EBay Cancels Sale of a Painting
</P>
<P>
   EBay canceled the sale of a painting to a Dutch executive for
$135,805, contending that the seller, Kenneth A. Walton, had
violated its rules in a way that artificially inflated the sale
price. The company also suspended three accounts that Walton used
to trade art, accusing him of ``shill bidding,'' meaning that he
entered bids on his own sales.
</P>
<P>
   Dreyfus Settles Case for $3 Million
</P>
<P>
   Dreyfus agreed to pay $2.95 million to settle charges that it
failed to inform investors adequately about the risks of its
Aggressive Growth Fund and that the fund's early performance had
been manipulated by loading it with initial public offerings. In
addition, the fund's former manager, Michael L. Schonberg, agreed
to a nine-month suspension from the investment management business
and will pay a $50,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   House Votes to Extend Moratorium
</P>
<P>
   The House passed a bill to extend the current moratorium on new
Internet taxes until 2006. The moratorium forbids states from
trying to find new ways of taxing Internet use, like imposing taxes
on monthly access charges for Internet service providers. The
legislation does not directly address sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   From Secretary to Online Executive
</P>
<P>
   John W. Sidgmore, the vice chairman of WorldCom and chief of its
Uunet unit, has invested in and become chairman of eCommerce
Industries, a dot-com venture for the office supply industry
started by Paula Jagemann, his former secretary. The company
intends to announce that it has formed the first electronic
exchange to link office supply manufacturers, wholesalers and
retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Random House in Audio Book Deal
</P>
<P>
   Random House and Audible, an Internet audio company, have signed
an agreement to begin selling digitized audio books online, the
companies plan to announce Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Champion Shows Favor to a Suitor
</P>
<P>
   Champion International embraced a sweetened $7.3 billion
cash-and-stock bid from International Paper, starting a three-day
clock for UPM-Kymmene of Finland to raise its $6.8 billion cash
offer for Champion. The company said that its board had determined
that the International Paper bid was superior after both suitors
submitted revised offers. Shares of Champion rallied $6.4375, to
$72.375.
</P>
<P>
   Profit at Unilever Increases 12 Percent
</P>
<P>
   Unilever, the consumer goods giant that is trying to buy
Bestfoods for $18.3 billion, said that its first-quarter operating
profit rose 12 percent in what the company depicted as a first
victory in its effort to cut costs.
</P>
<P>
   Government Role in the Economy
</P>
<P>
   In the past, economic transformations were accompanied by
enormous increases in spending on education, transportation,
communications and, ultimately, technological research, much of it
undertaken or subsidized by the government. The government now has
a similar and crucial role to play in the new economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
