<SLUG> BC-METHODISTS-GAYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
180 GAY RIGHTS ACTIVISTS ARRESTED AT METHODIST CONFERENCE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICHARD VARA 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ More than 180 gay rights activists, including a
bishop, were arrested Wednesday protesting the United Methodist
Church's view that homosexual behavior is contrary to Christian
teachings.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates to the national church's General Conference will
consider several gay-related petitions, including one asking for
church blessings for same-sex unions and another allowing gays to
be ordained.
</P>
<P>
   Gay rights activists have been lobbying and demonstrating at the
national legislative assembly since it began May 2, hoping to
change the 8.5-million-member denomination's position defining
homosexual practices as ``incompatible with Christian teaching.''
The church also bans church blessing for gay unions and prohibits
practicing gays from ordination.
</P>
<P>
   Gay rights activists ratcheted up the pressure against church
policy Wednesday morning by holding a rally and march that resulted
in police arrests when protesters blocked a Cleveland Convention
Center roadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here to call the United Methodist Church to repentance,
to come away from its sin of bigotry, from its sin of exclusion and
injustice,'' said Jimmy Creech, a former minister who was defrocked
by the denomination last year for blessing a gay couple's union.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Mel White, a gay pastor who is a member of the
Universal Fellowship of Metropolitan Community Churches, asked
Methodists to withhold donations from churches that exclude gays
and contribute only to gay-friendly congregations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those churches that refuse us admission or that punish us when
we come must be shown lovingly that we love the United Methodist
Church,'' White said during the rally.
</P>
<P>
   About 300 protesters supported the demonstration, including
Yolanda King, eldest daughter of the late Martin Luther King Jr.,
Arun Gandhi, grandson of Mohandas Gandhi, and the Rev. James
Lawson, a former King colleague.
</P>
<P>
   Gandhi and Lawson, along with United Methodist Bishop C. Joseph
Sprague of Chicago, were arrested by Cleveland police after they
refused police orders to move from the roadway. King did not
participate in the blockage because she had to fly to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters, singing hymns as they took turns blocking the
roadway, politely complied with police arrest and were led away to
be booked and fined $100 each. Other demonstrators cheered and
applauded as each group of protesters was led away.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the convention center, about 100 gay rights protesters
stood in the balcony overlooking the conference floor and sang a
hymn prior to the start of delegates' worship. Several delegates
also stood in sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   But few delegates expect the church to change its stance
Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Scott Field of Chicago, who is coordinating lobbying
efforts of several United Methodist evangelical and conservative
groups and churches, said conservatives have been winning several
other issues and elections, indicating strong support for
traditional sex morality.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get a strong vote Thursday, I suspect the numbers of
those seeking change will decline over the next four years,'' Field
said. ``We view (the demonstration) as a last push at this General
Conference. For those who are activists for the gay and lesbian
agenda, they probably will have to make some decision about their
future within the denomination.''
</P>
<P>
   The demonstration overshadowed the appearance of Archbishop
George Carey, titular head of the world's 70-million Anglicans. He
was the first Anglican head to ever address the denomination.
</P>
<P>
   Methodism was founded by John Wesley, an Anglican priest in
Great Britain. But Anglican officials in the 18th century did not
approve of Wesley or his followers.
</P>
<P>
   Carey told delegates that church unity does not require
``uniformity and sameness.'' Delegates applauded when he stated
that he opposed it when ``one part of the (church) family believes
that they hold the truth and nobody else does.''
</P>
<P>
   The Anglican Church worldwide is also debating gay rights and
Carey has been trying to keep the denomination from splitting over
the issue of blessing of same-sex unions and ordination of gays.
</P>
<P>
   He urged that Christians unite in evangelism, social ministry
and other activities.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
