<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1414 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     05-10 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DON'T WORRY 'BOUT A THING 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Knicks fans worry. They like to worry.
</P>
<P>
   Correction: Knicks fans love to worry.
</P>
<P>
   Worry is the nature of the city. Worry defines every crevice of
city life where people's lives rest on such a fragile precipice
from the stock market to the Mets. Worry gives the city its pulse.
</P>
<P>
   When Knicks fans worry, the group neurosis starts at the top of
Manhattan and works its way down to the tip; it extends from
borough to borough.
</P>
<P>
   The fans come out of an enthralling come-from-behind victory
delightedly drained. They come out of a loss steaming, ready to
trade whoever the goat was in that particular game _ usually the
Ward-Childs backcourt. They groan whenever Patrick Ewing gets the
ball in the low post; erupt in cheers when he scores; throw up
their hands when he misses. All the time loving every minute.
</P>
<P>
   Knicks fans never did warm up to Pat Riley, although they
certainly appreciated his style. But Riley didn't worry, even at
times like this, when as Heat coach he has had good reason to worry
after his team squandered its home court advantage by losing Game 2
on Tuesday night. Riley never did worry. Not outwardly.
</P>
<P>
   Now Knicks fans like Jeff Van Gundy. He worries and wears worry
on his sleeve. Van Gundy seems to agonize over everything from a
sloppy possession to the fans' treatment of Charlie Ward, Chris
Childs and especially Ewing. But he realizes that the outbursts are
a manifestation of the fans' need to fret.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we got rid of everybody after Game 1 who people criticized
and had an opinion about, we'd have trotted out with three guys for
Game 2,'' Van Gundy said.
</P>
<P>
   Worry may be the pastime of Knicks fans. But this will be a
different kind of playoff spring for them: worry free.
</P>
<P>
   For the next 12 days _ from the end of the Miami series to the
conference championship _ most likely with Indiana _ Knicks fans
won't have a lot to worry about. For all the game-to-game
hand-wringing and analysis, the Knicks are better than the
one-dimensional, muscle-bound Heat, better than the aging Pacers.
Blasphemous, I know. But true.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks are better: better than the Heat, better than the
Pacers or the Sixers, better than last year's Knicks, who reached
the finals. These Knicks are balanced, rich in depth, rich in
scorers. This is a team that can have Sprewell and Houston mired in
shooting slumps simultaneously and still beat Miami in Miami _
comfortably.
</P>
<P>
   After practice Wednesday, Van Gundy said he told Houston and
Sprewell at halftime Tuesday night not to worry: They didn't have
to carry the weight of the world on their shoulders. Childs and
Ward could outplay Miami's backcourt with Tim Hardaway hobbled, the
Heat still doesn't have an answer for Marcus Camby and, at the
moment of truth, Ewing always seems good for a couple fools' points
against his protege, Alonzo Mourning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two shouldn't feel the burden of `If I don't get going,
we're not going to win,''' Van Gundy said. ``Lattrell is what _ 6
for 27? I don't want him to be worried so that it takes away from
the other parts of his game. He and Allan have to do the best
possible job they can, play the best possible basketball they can
and then deal with the result.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really worried about how to get them going. If a team
wants to commit two guys to one person, then that's going to open
up other things for other people, so other people are going to have
to step forward like Charlie did last night. Kurt did a good job,
and Marcus did a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   So, what does Van Gundy worry about? ``The overall mentality.
How we approach Game 3, corrections we need to make to give us a
chance to play better in Game 3. A writer will deal with an
individual story line; for me, the team is the story line: `How can
we win?'''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Johnson and Ewing spent the off day taking extra practice.
Johnson was at one end shooting free throws. Ewing was at the other
end shooting jumpers, flexing his knee, loosening his back. After
the workout, Ewing said wasn't worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about my back,'' he said. ``I'm able to play,
that's the bottom line. I'm not limping around like last year.'' Is
he hurting more than he's revealing?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not even worried about that, I'm ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   But what about the back? ``I'm tired of answering that _ don't
ask no more about my back.''
</P>
<P>
   Difficult as this may be, Knicks fans should not worry about
this series and the next. Relax. Enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   There will be plenty to worry about when the finals begin, come
June 2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 2152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
