<DOCNO> NYT20000510.0334 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1434 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-GIULIANI-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      05-10 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: SENATE RACE THROWN INTO CONFUSION BY GIULIANI'S
ANNOUNCEMENT
</HEADLINE>
   (See also NY-GIULIANI) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani was still the Republican
candidate for Senate on Wednesday night, even after Wednesday's
tumultuous turn of events. But state Republican leaders were
already turning their sights on two Republicans _ a Long Island
congressman and a wealthy Wall Street philanthropist _ to step into
the race in case Giuliani drops out of the contest with Hillary
Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   One of the potential candidates, Rep. Rick Lazio of Long Island,
spoke by telephone Wednesday evening with William Powers, the state
Republican chairman, to review the prospects of his entering the
race should Giuliani not run, Republican officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The second, Theodore J. Forstmann, a Wall Street investor who
personally financed a program to allow poor children to attend
private schools, was moving to set up meetings with Republican
leaders next week to discuss his own prospective candidacy, his
associates said.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden flurry of activity in what has until now been seen as
Giuliani's uncontested bid for the nomination came amid signs of
confusion and concern among party leaders struggling to keep
abreast of a rapid day of revelations about Giuliani and his
marriage to Donna Hanover.
</P>
<P>
   Although most Republicans offered public support for Giuliani,
insisting that the disclosures would not hurt his standing with
voters, there was clear evidence of concern over whether the mayor
would stay in the race and, if he did, whether he would be a
seriously weakened opponent to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   An hour after Giuliani announced that he and Donna Hanover were
seeking a separation, a senior New York Republican described it as
a favorable development, contending that it would put an end to
intensive coverage in the New York tabloids about his close
friendship with Judith Nathan, a pharmaceuticals executive. But 20
minutes after Hanover held her own news conference to say that
Giuliani had had ``a relationship'' with a staff member, the same
Republican called back to retract the statement: ``My quote no
longer stands _ even on an anonymous basis.''
</P>
<P>
   And Guy Molinari, the Staten Island borough president and
typically one of Giuliani's most loyal defenders, declined a
request for an interview on Wednesday to discuss this latest
episode in the mayor's political life.
</P>
<P>
   In a day of almost unheard-of turmoil in the New York Republican
Party, Lazio and Forstmann moved gingerly to position themselves in
the event that Giuliani dropped out, without, their aides said,
doing anything to appear as if they were taking ungraceful
advantage of Giuliani's difficulties. Aides to both men said they
would enter the race only if Giuliani dropped out.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's aides said that Giuliani had not made a final
decision about his future, though his own associates _ who were
caught off guard by Giuliani's announcement _ described themselves
as increasingly pessimistic that Giuliani would make the race.
</P>
<P>
   When Giuliani announced last week that he had prostate cancer,
he said that he hoped to make a decision about whether he would
stay in the race, based on his treatment, by the middle of May.
Some Republicans, concerned that the disclosures about Giuliani's
personal life could make him a weaker candidate, said on Wednesday
that they hoped Giuliani would not drag out his decision if he
intended to abandon the race.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican convention is May 30. But time is pressing for
the Republican Party, because Lazio and Forstmann are both unknown
and inexperienced candidates, and thus could find themselves
disadvantaged in a race with Clinton, who has spent nearly a year
on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio would also have to move to raise money to finance the
campaign, a particularly urgent need in order to pay for television
advertisements to present himself to voters.
</P>
<P>
   An aide to Forstmann said he was prepared to finance his own
race. One senior Republican said that Forstmann's wealth, and his
asserted interest in paying for his own campaign, was one of his
great potential assets. That said, there is an established history
of wealthy people's running for office for the first time and
failing.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio had, with the tacit support of Gov. George Pataki,
threatened to run a primary against Giuliani for the Republican
nomination last fall. He backed off, reluctantly, in response to
pressure from Republicans who saw Giuliani as the party's strongest
candidate. Through a spokesman, Lazio clearly signaled his
continuing interest in the race on Wednesday night, but said, ``I
shall take no action regarding the U.S. Senate race until the mayor
announces his decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has been mentioned by Republicans as the strongest
potential replacement, given his statewide recognition, popularity
and fund-raising ability. But his advisers repeated on Wednesday
that the two-term governor had no interest in serving in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   It was a day of dark humor at Giuliani's campaign headquarters,
where aides, at once giddy and gloomy, relied on television and
newspaper reporters to track developments in their candidate's
life. Across the state, Republican supporters of Giuliani argued
that developments in the mayor's personal life would have no
bearing on the campaign, and that the announcement of the
separation would remove the issue of Giuliani's marriage from the
table.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should go full steam ahead,'' said State Sen. Roy Goodman,
the Manhattan Republican leader. ``I do not think it will affect
the political picture at all. It's strictly a personal matter.''
</P>
<P>
   But some Republicans warned that the disclosures about
Giuliani's personal life would raise questions about him among
conservative, upstate and female voters, doubts that he could not
afford in a race that polls show to be very close.
</P>
<P>
   One of Giuliani's advisers said on Wednesday night that the
latest news could be an advantage, by presenting the mayor as human
and candid. But many Republicans described that argument as wishful
thinking at best.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of this helps,'' said Nelson Warfield, who was the
spokesman for Bob Dole's presidential campaign in 1996, and who has
has been a frequent critic of Giuliani. ``It's mere happy talk to
suggest it humanizes him. Nobody needs to be humanized this way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
