<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADLITTLE-SPINOFF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE PLANS SPINOFF OF TECH UNITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arthur D. Little Inc., the 114-year-old management consulting
pioneer, stepped squarely into the Internet age Wednesday as it
announced plans to spin off its technology-based divisions into a
publicly traded company.
</P>
<P>
   Named C-Quential Inc., the new firm consists of Arthur D.
Little's telecommunications, information technology, media and
electronics units, which the parent company refers to as its TIME
group.
</P>
<P>
   In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, Little
said it hopes to raise up to $150 million in an initial public
offering. Part of the proceeds would be used to retire $70 million
in debt, the filing said.
</P>
<P>
   The company said the four existing technology consulting units
had combined net income of $10.8 million last year on $106.6
million in revenues. C-Quential's headquarters will remain in
Cambridge, Mass., but about 90 percent of its more than 250
employees work in offices in 21 countries.
</P>
<P>
   With its move, Little joins scores of other companies that have
spun off technology-based units of their organizations in recent
months.
</P>
<P>
   According to Securities Data Publishing Co. of New York, 39
technology-based initial public offerings have raised a total of
$11 billion for their sponsors since the beginning of 1999. Several
of those proved lucrative for investors, but others were a flop,
with shares later tumbling below initial prices.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Holmes, founder of IPOpros.com Inc. of Boulder, Colo., said
recent market volatility makes it difficult to predict investor
interest in C-Quential, which probably won't be able to begin
offering shares for at least 60 days while the SEC reviews its
prospectus.
</P>
<P>
   A Little spokesman said the company was advised by lawyers to
not elaborate on its filings because such comments could be seen as
improper promotion of the upcoming offering.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolf Fischer, 43, a Little vice president since 1995 and
formerly an executive with telecommunications companies in Europe,
was identified as C-Quential's president and chief executive.
Lorenzo C. Madrid, 49, president and chief executive of Little
since last July, is C-Quential's board chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications and electronics clients that C-Quential is
inheriting from its parent include KPN Telecom, Mannesmann AG,
Orange PLC, Samsung Group, and Siemns AG. Sixty percent of the TIME
group's revenues last year were from European clients.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur D. Little was founded in 1886 and, while once publicly
traded, has been privately held since 1988, following an aborted
hostile takeover bid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 2158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
