<SLUG> BC-SRILANKA-REBELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SRI LANKAN REBELS RENEW ASSAULT ON KEY NORTHERN CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also SRILANKA-CENSOR) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two days after the Sri Lankan government rejected a cease-fire
offer, separatist rebels went back on the offensive Wednesday in an
early morning assault, striving to take back the Jaffna peninsula
at the northern tip of Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
   After a week's lull in fighting, the rebels said in a statement
from their London office that their latest assault had brought them
within two miles of city of Jaffna, the cultural capital of the
Tamil-dominated north.
</P>
<P>
   The government confirmed that the rebels began a strong assault
at 3 a.m. and broke through ``a few gaps in the army defenses.''
But it spoke of ``a large number of casualties among the
attackers.'' The rebels are known as the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam. They have been fighting for a separate homeland for the
Hindu Tamil minority since 1983.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels controlled Jaffna from 1990 to 1995, but the
government reclaimed it in December 1995 and has held it since.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the Tigers have scored a series of gains. They
have taken control of large chunks of territory in the sparsely
populated, jungle area of Wanni south of the Jaffna peninsula. And
on April 22, they overran the government's heavily fortified
military base at Elephant Pass, which connects Jaffna to the
mainland, and another base a week later.
</P>
</TEXT>
