<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIT-ENTREPRENEUR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAIR'S DNA DYE WINS PRESIGIOUS MIT AWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Toiling in MIT's labs, two students created a
dye that makes DNA visible to the naked eye. And Wednesday night
they took a step onto center stage, winning the sought-after $50K
MIT Entrepreneurship Competition.
</P>
<P>
   Held by MIT's Sloan School of Management, the contest helps
teaches students about creating a successful business. In the
process, it also has helped launchseveral hot start-ups, including
Akamai Technologies Inc. and Direct Hit Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Akamai, a finalist in 1998, saw its shares soar after its
initial public offering last fall. The Cambridge company, which
transmits Internet content and analyzes online traffic, now boasts
a market capitalization of $7.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Search software developed by Direct Hit, a cowinner two years
ago, turned out to be another company's desire. Earlier this year,
Ask Jeeves Inc. paid more than $500 million for the Wellesley firm.
</P>
<P>
   This year's winners were two Massachusetts Institute of
Technology biochemistry students, Zoran Zdraveski and Susan Bevers,
and an entrepreneur named Kiril Alexandrov. Their team, called
EyeGen, was among 206 groups competing for the award.
</P>
<P>
   EyeGen's products, EyeGenRad, is described as a safer, less
costly means of viewing DNA for scientific analysis. EyeGen
estimates its market at more than $15 billion annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since DNA manipulation is at the core of most genomic,
medical, and biotech research _ EyeGenRad has broad application,''
the team said in a description.
</P>
<P>
   Runners-up included Centrata, a developer of software allowing
computer owners to sell their unused computer resources to create a
large network. Another winner was Mazu Networks, which hopes to
provide customer management and billing for application service
providers.
</P>
<P>
   EyeGen will pocket $30,000, and the two runners-up will each
receive cash prizes of $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Participants know how crucial the recognition is to their
business plans. The MIT awards have become known as one of the best
campus-generated launching pads for businesses, and venture
capitalists watch it closely. At a time when start-ups are
desperate for attention, the contest's winners can bask in the the
spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Friday evening, I call the finalists,'' said lead organizer
and business school student Heather Wilding. ``The first reaction
is silence. And then they say, `Oh my God.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Leighton, cofounder of Akamai, says the critiques during the
long awards process, which takes several months, helped the company
fine-tune its strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were noticing where we were deficient,'' Leighton said.
``It was a learning experience for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 2201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
