<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1443 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CANCER-DRUG-BOS &LR;      05-10 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-DRUG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANCER DRUG FALLS BELOW EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Endostatin, the highly touted potential cancer treatment whose
first human trials are being avidly followed by thousands of
hopeful cancer patients, has yet to show dramatic benefits after
seven months of safety testing, according to a senior government
research official.
</P>
<P>
   Endostatin, discovered by Dr. Judah Folkman and colleagues at
Children's Hospital in Boston, is one of the most talked-about
potential cancer treatments in years. It has been hailed as a
possible cure by no less a luminary than James Watson, who won a
Nobel Prize for his pioneering genetic research.
</P>
<P>
   While endostatin may yet prove effective, the official's
statement contradicts persistent Internet rumors that the drug has
made impressive gains against tumors in one or more of about 45
patients in the three Phase I trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not aware of any major clinical response to date,'' said
Dr. James Pluda, a senior investigator at the National Cancer
Institute, which is overseeing two of the three trials, one of them
in Boston at Dana-Farber Partners Cancer Care.
</P>
<P>
   Pluda's comments followed other disappointing news for the
research, as word leaked out that one patient had to be dropped
from the endostatin trial because his tumor had continued to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Killian, a robust and optimistic Chicagoan with advanced
colon cancer, suffered a setback this week when tests at the
University of Wisconsin in Madison showed that his liver cancer had
enlarged by 70 percent while on the drug. Under the research rules,
a cancer that has grown by 50 percent or more makes the patient no
longer eligible for the drug.
</P>
<P>
   A number of other patients have dropped out of the trials, but
researchers will not say how many.
</P>
<P>
   Killian said in a telephone interview that he felt well, and
that believes the drug was keeping the cancer at bay, but Dr. James
Thomas, the head of the Wisconsin trials, told Killian that he had
no choice but to stop the endostatin treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were lots of tears,'' said Killian. ``I`m 42 years old,
and I have an 8-year-old daughter who's crying at school because
her dad's out of the endostatin trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Arguing that a higher dose of endostatin might save his life,
Killian, his wife, Lori, and dozens of supporters who have followed
his case on the Internet have launched a campaign to have him
reinstated at a higher dose. Killian appealed directly to Folkman,
in whose laboratory at Children's Hospital the tumor-killing
protein was discovered.
</P>
<P>
   However, Folkman could not help Killian; he instead advised him
on what other regimens he could try. Folkman has no direct control
over the trials, which are being sponsored by the National Cancer
Institute in Wisconsin and by the M.D. Anderson Cancer Institute in
Houston, and in Boston by EntreMed Inc., which developed the drug.
</P>
<P>
   New drugs are tested in three phases, the earliest of which is
solely to determine whether they are safe. In Phase 1, the initial
doses are very conservative and often too low to be effective; the
doses are increased in successive small groups of patients until
the side effects become intolerable.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Phase 1 trials are far from conclusive, rumors have
abounded on Internet bulletin boards, particularly among investors
in EntreMed, that endostatin was working. And even though no
results have been published yet, seemingly positive comments by
researchers in the trial have fueled the belief that the trials are
going well.
</P>
<P>
   Killian, one of the few patients to speak publicly about the
trials, was a true believer in the drug. Nearly every day, he drove
four hours to and from Madison to receive the one-hour infusion of
endostatin, which is known as an angiogenesis inhibitor. It is a
natural protein made in the body that, when tested in animals,
destroyed the blood supply of growing tumors and shrank them until
they were invisible.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the cancer had spread from his colon to his liver
and lungs, Killian said that since he started taking endostatin in
January he has felt better than he had in two years. He continued
to golf and play with a rock band, and came to believe the drug was
working.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers for the endostatin trial are assigned at random to
the varying dose levels: Killian's supporters say that because he
was assigned to a relatively low dose, he should have a chance to
try a higher dose, on the assumption that it would be more
effective.
</P>
<P>
   But Pluda of the cancer institute threw cold water on the
assumption that Killian's tumor might shrink if he got a higher
dose. He said:
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had evidence at this point that we were having a
significant clinical effect'' at higher doses, ``and that the
higher doses were safe to give to someone who had received a
substantial amount of drug already, I'd feel bad and we would
probably try to do something. But I don't have any such evidence as
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Bioethicists said that volunteers for Phase I trials must
understand that the tests are only for safety and are not supposed
to be therapeutic. But one expert, Dr. David Rothman of the
Columbia University School of Medicine, sympathized with Killian,
arguing that Phase 1 trials are increasingly seen by patients as a
long-shot chance for a cure.
</P>
<P>
   Rothman added that some ethicists have become increasingly
uncomfortable with the very low doses of drugs given volunteers in
Phase I trials. He said the patient do not always understand that
they're getting too little of the drug to benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Understandably,'' Rothman said, ``the patient would like to
have access to an increased dose.''
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of the research trial say it's too early to make any
official report. Until now, they have only said informally that
endostatin appears to have little toxicity and has shown some
``biological activity.'' That suggests that the drug is working as
it is supposed to on molecules and cells in the body, but it does
not mean it is halting the cancer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 2203EDT &QL; 
