<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-MARLINS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marlins outlast Braves
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Miami _ The Marlins came after Tom Glavine at Pro Player Stadium
on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   They welcomed him to South Florida and, ignoring the fact that
he is riding one of the best runs of his career, beat him 5-3 with
some help from poor Braves defense, poor Braves baserunning and
decent hitting of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine, who's been the best pitcher in baseball this side of
Randy Johnson and Pedro Martinez this season, lost for the first
time since last September against the Giants. He gave up a
season-high five runs and a season-high nine hits to fall to 6-11
against the Marlins in his career, 2-8 at Pro Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   He has not won in Miam since May 3, 1995, dating back six
starts.
</P>
<P>
   Not Glavine's new cut fastball, his 5-0 record, his sterling
1.73 ERA or his own RBI hit seemed to bother the Marlins. Certainly
the usual suspect, Marlins catcher Mike Redmond, wasn't bothered.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond entered the game hitting .750 against Glavine (9-for-12)
in his career and went to work raising the average with a pair of
infield hits in his first two at-bats. His hit in the third inning,
which should have been ruled an error on Chipper Jones, started a
two-run rally where the Braves defense hurt Glavine.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Bonilla misplayed a Cliff Floyd liner to left which should
have ended the inning but instead was ruled a two-run double and
gave the Marlins their first lead at 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine could only smile in the fourth inning when Redmond
grounded a ball off Glavine's foot for another hit. But by the
sixth inning, he wasn't laughing anymore. By then, the Braves'
offense was letting him down.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves had the bases loaded with nobody out and the heart of
the order due up in Chipper Jones, Andres Galarraga and Brian
Jordan on a rally Glavine started with a walk. But Jones sent a
first-pitch fly ball to former Brave Danny Bautista in right field,
which wasn't deep enough to prompt Glavine to take off from third
base. That didn't stop Andruw Jones from taking off from second,
which sent the Braves baserunners into confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Before it was over, Glavine had gotten thrown out on his way
home for a double play, and Andres Galarraga followed with an
inning-ending groundout to short.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine proceeded to surrender his second home run of the game _
to Preston Wilson, who's leading baseball in strikeouts _ in the
bottom of the sixth inning, allowing the Marlins to take a 4-2
lead. Glavine allowed two home runs in his seven innings after
allowing only one in the first 52 innings of his 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
