<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, MAY 11
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-CARDINAL-OCONNOR-OBIT-NYT (moved on Wednesday, May 3)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of Cardinal John O'Connor sent by the New York
Times News Service on Wednesday, May 3, misstated his birth date.
It was Jan. 15, 1920, not Jan. 20.
</P>
<P>
   BC-INTERNET-BATTLEGROUND-NYT (moved on Tuesday, May 9)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on A Tuesday, May 9,
about new software that poses a challenge to copyright protection
referred imprecisely to the role of Talal G. Shamoon in the Secure
Digital Music Initiative, an anti-piracy effort backed by the
consumer electronics and technology industries. He is the head of a
working group, not of the overall effort.
</P>
<P>
   BC-LA-POLICE-NYT (moved on Monday, May 8)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, May 8,
about a federal investigation into accusations of misconduct and
civil rights violations by the Los Angeles Police Department
referred imprecisely to the grounds of a lawsuit the Justice
Department has threatened to bring if the city does not change
training and procedures. The suit would assert a pattern and
practice of police misconduct. The Justice Department is still
reviewing accusations of racial discrimination and has made no
conclusion on that issue.
</P>
<P>
   BC-COMPUTER-BRIEFS-NYT (moved on Sunday, May 6)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, May 6,
about a new electronic commerce business led by Dennis Hayes cited
his pioneering technology work incorrectly. Although Hayes
developed the modem that became the standard for personal computers
in 1978, the first devices that enabled computers to communicate
over telephone lines were developed in the late 1950's.
</P>
<P>
   BC-ROME-ACADEMY-NYT (moved on Sunday, May 6)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, May 6,
about the Rome Prize Competition in the arts and humanities,
administered by the American Academy in Rome, omitted one winner.
She is Wendy Heller, assistant professor of music at Princeton, who
received the Mellon Post-Doctoral Research Fellowship.
</P>
<P>
   BC-TAVENER-MUSIC-NYT (moved on Wednesday, May 3)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, May 3,
about the composer Sir John Tavener misstated the name of a
performing group in a retrospective of his work at the Church of
St. Ignatius Loyola in Manhattan. It was the Flux Quartet, not the
Flux Ensemble.
</P>
</TEXT>
