r e BC-TV-RATEDX-REVIEW-SFCH     05-10 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-RATEDX-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S SHOWTIME FOR PORN BROTHERS' SLEAZY TALE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Step right into the Showtime tent and see movie star Charlie
Sheen snort coke, grope naked women and abuse firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, these forbidden sights have been restricted to
Sheen's closest associates in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   But ``No Limits'' is the Showtime mantra, and Showtime delivers
the sordid goods in ``Rated X,'' a movie about San Francisco porn
princes Jim and Artie Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Sheen plays younger brother Artie, shot dead by Jim nine years
ago in Artie's home in Corte Madera, Calif., north of San
Francisco. The movie's extra hook is that Sheen's older brother,
Emilio Estevez, co-stars as Jim Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Estevez directed Saturday's cable movie, too, helping to ensure
that ``Rated X'' is a voyeur's delight all around. It's also
violent, depressing and ultimately pointless.
</P>
<P>
   But don't let that get in the way of a bad time.
</P>
<P>
   The boys learn from their father (Terry O'Quinn) that a gun is
useful in settling disputes and later manage to learn for
themselves that sex sells. A potent combo.
</P>
<P>
   Still another element in the Mitchell brothers' lifestyle is a
shared fondness for drugs, starting with pot and moving along to
cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Here's Party Artie, snorting yet another line of white powder:
``Just say `Yes!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Based on a book by David McCumber, the movie presents Artie as
the creative half of the team and Jim as the saner businessman.
</P>
<P>
   Artie dreams up ``Behind the Green Door'' but is incapable of
directing the skin flick that clinches the brothers' porn
reputation. Artie foresees the home video porn revolution. Artie
concocts the idea of converting the O'Farrell Theatre into a sex
emporium with live performers.
</P>
<P>
   Artie has other artieful ideas: ``Let's make a flick about a
jail. It's just for girls. Now the lady that runs the joint is
nasty, a real maniac. She doesn't let the girls wear any clothes.
We'll set it against the Roman Empire ...''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure, but I think I might have seen the expurgated
version late one night. On Showtime, probably.
</P>
<P>
   And it's Artie who rips into the deepest, darkest paranoia as
his wives leave him and the trail of coke extends for miles.
</P>
<P>
   It is a real contest, though. Jim gives him a run for it, until
he jets to Cape Cod for a little self-detox under the care of
Artie's ex-wife Meredith (Megan Ward). Then he comes back to San
Francisco to try to clean up Artie _ a battle to the bloody finish.
</P>
<P>
   The least convincing part of the film is the bald pates of Sheen
and Estevez _ they say they shaved their heads for the roles. The
rest of it rings pretty much true, though as a director Estevez
seems unsure what he wants us to feel about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rated X'' is either an unamusing satire or a predictable Cain
and Abel tale with a particularly tawdry backdrop. The film seems
to waver uncomfortably and indecisively between the two before its
descent into tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Sheen's own experience with most of the vices in the film is a
dark inducement, and there's a kind of a slugger's punch behind his
more explosive scenes. You can't help but wonder how, or if,
Estevez tried to intervene with his own brother as Jim Mitchell
does here. In any case, Sheen now purports to be straight if not
narrow.
</P>
<P>
   The movie abounds with bare flesh _ none of it belonging to
Martin Sheen's boys _ and simulated sex, along with raw language
and ultimately violence.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't exactly live down to its name. ``Rated X''
carries an ``R'' rating from the Motion Picture Association of
America, not an ``X.'' They'd yawn at the O'Farrell Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
