</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CALIFORNIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA IS CRUCIAL TO GORE'S WHITE HOUSE HOPES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   (Undated) For decades Americans have headed to California to
seek their fame and fortune. So it's not surprising that the
presidential candidates have been traveling west in their quest to
win the top political prize.
</P>
<P>
   For Democratic contender Al Gore, who was scheduled to fly to
Los Angeles late Wednesday evening after attending a party
fund-raiser in Dallas, the need to do well in the Golden State is
paramount if he hopes to occupy the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts say that it will be virtually impossible for Gore
to win the presidency without capturing the most populous state,
since his Republican rival, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, almost
certainly will take his home state and will likely win Florida and
most other southern states.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's planned daylong visit to the Elizabeth Learning Center, a
predominantly Hispanic school in Cudahy, Calif., is intended to
underscore his interest in education, a top voter priority, as well
as help him with one of the state's fastest growing ethnic
populations.
</P>
<P>
   Later he will tap the state's wealth at a Democratic party
fund-raiser, before flying to Oregon on Friday to hold a town hall
meeting with undecided voters.
</P>
<P>
   While California has increasingly trended Democratic over the
past decade and handed President Clinton victories in his two
successful presidential bids, the vice president cannot take the
diverse state for granted.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has so far indicated that he is not ready to concede
this fertile electoral vote ground, has visited the state
frequently to woo the high tech millionaires of Silicon Valley in
the north as well as the Hispanic community in the south.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts say they are unsure whether Bush really
intends to devote the enormous sums of money needed to win a
sprawling state where expensive television ads are often the only
way to reach large groups of voters.
</P>
<P>
   They speculate that the governor's strategy may be to spend
enough time in California to force Gore to spend more of his
limited resources in the state rather than in more competitive
battleground states such as Michigan or Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can keep Gore in California protecting his base and
not spending resources in the Midwest, that could be a strategic
move,'' said Michael Latner, a project manager at the Field Poll,
which conducts statewide surveys.
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign spokesman Chris Lehane said that Gore's frequent
trips to California were not in response to Bush's forays into the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Lehane noted that Gore has visited the state more than 70 times
in his 7{ years as vice president.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to gauge how the candidates are doing in
California since the state's most respected independent polling
organizations, such as the Field Poll, have not conducted surveys
since the March primary. However, on Wednesday the New Hampshire
based-American Research Group released a poll of likely California
voters that showed Gore leading Bush 50 percent to 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Field Poll's Latner said his analysis of the primary results
showed that Bush has made inroads among white women, who slightly
favored the Texas governor over Gore. But despite his persistent
effort to woo Hispanic voters, Bush still garnered only 17 percent
of that group's vote compared to 58 percent for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Bush has the difficult task of overcoming the Hispanic
distrust of Republicans that stems from the anti-immigrant campaign
waged by former GOP Gov. Pete Wilson. Bush has tried to distance
himself from the former governor and stressed his amiable
relationship with Hispanics in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is doing some stuff right. But I think there is still
some skepticism that must be overcome,'' said Sherry Bebitch Jeffe,
a political analyst at the Claremont Graduate Schools in southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, with six months until the November election, Jeffe
and others say that it is too early to get accurate readings of the
state's political temperature.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
