   The following photo, originally transmitted on Tuesday, May 14,
was retransmitted today to correct the name of the woman:
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) MALVERN, Pa. -- May 9, 2000 -- SUB-SNAPSHOT-WORKPLACE-2
-- Office workers everywhere put up photos in their workspace that
helps define who they are and what motivates them. Monique Hauser,
a client service representative at the Vanguard Group, a mutual
fund company, stands over photos of several heartthrobs in her
cubicle including 10 identical images of the soap opera actor Scott
Reeves which she uses as her screen-saver. Reeves provides her with
``motivation,'' she says. (Salvatore DiMarco Jr./The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- May 10, 2000 -- RAC-UNSER -- Last November,
Al Unser Jr. defected from Championship Auto Racing Teams to Indy
Racing - and its jewel, the Indianapolis 500 - to sign with Galles
ECR Racing. ``There's been a hole in my heart ever since,'' Al
Unser Jr. said of having shutting himself out from the Indianapolis
500. (Jack Manning/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) UNDATED -- May 10, 2000 -- U.S.-ARMS -- The Pentagon is
assessing the risk to national security of shrinking the nation's
nuclear arsenal to 2,000 warheads under an arms-reduction treaty
with Russia, a major step that could help President Clinton broker
a arms-control and missile-defense accord with Moscow before he
leaves office, administration officials say. Minuteman
Intercontinental Ballistic Missiles during testing in 1997.
(Boeing/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) WASHINGTON -- May 10, 2000 -- SECURITY-LAPSES -- The
State Department suffers from a systemic failure to protect secrets
that is longstanding and far broader than the recent series of
lapses publicly denounced by Secretary of State Madeleine K.
Albright, according to a range of administration officials. Trucks
block the driveway to the State Department during increased
security following the bombing of targets by U.S. forces in
Afghanistan and Sudan in 1998. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) UNDATED -- May 10, 2000 -- SCHIFF-NABOKOV -- Stacy
Schiff won the Pulitzer for biography for her book about the
marriage of Vera Nabokov - the wife of Vladimir Nabokov, who during
their 52-year marriage served as her husband's agent, editor,
secretary and chauffeur. Why did Schiff not write about the
creative partner? ``I thought that she was the creative one to some
extent,'' said Schiff, 39. ``I suppose my thesis was the minor
player was going to be very revealing of the major player.'' (Dith
Pran/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) WASHINGTON -- May 10, 2000 -- MUSIC-ANTITRUST -- Robert
Pitofsky, left, chairman of the Federal Trade Commission,
commenting on an announced settlement of an antitrust case against
the nation's five largest music companies at FTC headquarters
Wednesday in Washington. Pitofsky said the settlement should result
in significant price cuts for compact discs. With him at the press
conference was Richard Parker, director of the bureau of
competition at the FTC. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) WASHINGTON -- May 10, 2000 -- ILOVEYOU-VIRUS -- Peter S.
Tippett of ICSA.net in Reston, Va., told a Congressional panel
Wednesday that the ``I Love You'' computer virus had caused far
more widespread damage than similar episodes in the past. Officials
investigating the malicious program that disrupted computer systems
worldwide said Wednesday that they were looking for a 23-year-old
computer student named Onel de Guzman, who recently wrote a thesis
proposal for a program with similar elements. (Stephen Crowley/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) ATLANTA -- May 10, 2000 -- SHOPPING-DESTINATION-COX --
Atlanta's Little Five Points is funky, friendly and brimming with
fun spots. The space that now houses Home Store Futon Gallery was
for years a Piggly Wiggly, then an A&AMP;P and more recently Sevananda
Natural Foods Market. (Sabine Morrow/Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) WASHINGTON -- May 10, 2000 -- MOMS-MARCH -- Organizers
of the Million Mom March for ``sensible gun control'' predicted
Wednesday that at least 150,000 mothers and their allies will
descend on the nation's capital on Sunday, with many others at
similar rallies in 67 towns and cities. Debbye Kelley-Watson,
right, embraces a supporter during a survey of site on the Mall
where the march will take place. (Stephen Crowley/The New York
Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) ATLANTA -- May 10, 2000 -- BUYERS-EDGE-COX -- Grocery
shopping may never be the same now that Webvan.com has brought the
supermarket to Atlanta's doorstep. The dot-com delivery service
officially began rolling out meat, potatoes and more from its
warehouse to kitchen counters May 1. Making deliveries on the first
day of Webvan's test run, Joe Gilbert handed Donna Kibler her
receipt after unloading her groceries. (Parker C. Smith/Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) WACO, Texas -- May 10, 2000 -- COUPON-LADY-COX -- ``My
grandmother used to say, 'If you keep your fist closed, you can't
receive any blessings and you can't give anything out,'' said
Jacklynn Adams, 46, who, besides being a cashier at the H-E-B here,
is ``the coupon lady,'' doling them out from a zipper pouch she
keeps next to the register. ``I've been in the grocery store
business for 26 years, and I've never had (an employee) that
excited, that energetic,'' said H-E-B store manager Brent Ackors.
``It's not normal. It's not anywhere close to normal.'' (Kelly
Lemons/Cox News Service)
