   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- May 10, 2000 -- NY-VIOLIN-LESSON -- Master
violinist Isaac Stern teaches some finer points of his craft to
superintendents of the New York City Board of Education, Wednesday.
Harold Levy, the board's interim chancellor, set up the class as
part of what Levy describes as an effort to raise the intellectual
awareness of the board. (Librado Romero/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- May 10, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 14 --
WOODY-ALLEN-DIALOGUE -- Woody Allen and Juliet Taylor, his casting
director, at his Manhattan office. Sometimes, Allen says, the right
actor walks in and is perfect for a part. ``I find it's easier to
get what I want from a guy who's 90 percent right as the character
and can act a little than from a guy who's not as right and who's a
great actor,'' he said. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- May 10, 2000 -- NY-MAYOR-2 -- Donna Hanover
speaks to reporters about her relationship with her husband, Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani of New York, Wednesday. Earlier Giuliani said that
he and his wife are discussing a formal separation. The mayor and
Hanover, an actress and television personality, have been married
16 years. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) UNDATED -- May 10, 2000 -- EGAN-MASS -- Bishop Edward
Egan, a leading candidate to become archbishop of New York, during
a Mass in honor of two longtime parish priests, Wednesday.
O'Connor, who had been archbishop since 1984, died last week and
was buried Monday. Official word of his successor comes from the
Vatican. (Richard Perry/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- May 10, 2000 -- NY-MAYOR -- Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani kissed his daughter, Caroline, as his wife Donna Hanover,
watched after delivering his inauguration speech at City Hall in
January, 1998. Giuliani said Wednesday that he and his wife are
discussing a formal separation. The mayor and Hanover, an actress
and television personality, have been married 16 years. (Fred R.
Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) ROXBURY, Mass. -- May 10, 2000 -- AUTHOR-TOURE-BOS --
Askia Toure's new book, ``Dawnsong! The Epic Memory of Askia
Toure,'' a book of poetry, was released in March. Toure calls the
work, which eulogizes such jazz greats as SRa and John Coltrane as
often as it teaches about ancient African civilization, an attempt
to ``restore our imagery, our archetypes, and our history'' in a
country where Africa's story is often ignored. Toure in front of a
statue at Roxbury Community College where he spoke to students
recenlty. (Wendy Maeda/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEWTON, Mass. -- May 10, 2000 -- WORKING-MILLIONAIRES-BOS
-- Susan Bailis could have retired after selling a company she
co-owned for $100 million. Instead, she and her partner eventually
formed a small company that operates a number of elder care
ventures. ``I never, even for a moment, considered not working,''
Bailis says firmly. adding, ``Work provides a structure to my
life.'' (Suzanne Kreiter/The Boston Globe) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) ENGLEWOOD, N.J. -- May 10, 2000 -- RETIREES-STOCK -- With
plenty of time to worry about how their money is doing and with
less time in their lives to recover from major investment mistakes,
older investors are becoming increasingly agitated as market
volatility insinuates itself into their daily lives, several
experts said. Hank Citron, a retired history professor, keeps his
television set turned on to CNBC and his computer online to Morgan
Stanley. (Norman Y. Lono/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- May 10, 2000 -- PHILLIPS-AUCTION -- Long a
distant third in the world auction stakes, Phillips has rented the
American Craft Museum, just opposite the Museum of Modern Art, for
three weeks for $100,000 and has lavished $1.3 million in
construction costs. The endeavor is part of an ambitious attempt to
give the company's fusty reputation an elegant facelift for its
biggest sale in its 206- year history; scheduled for Thursday.
Interior and exterior views of the site rented by Phillips.
(Frances Roberts/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- May 10, 2000 -- BETTY-FRIEDAN-2 -- In 1963,
Betty Friedan, the combative writer and activist, inspired a social
revolution for women with ``The Feminine Mystique,'' in which she
debunked the myth of the postwar woman, that docile soul who tended
home and hearth while happily forgoing her own ambitions and
interests. Her history makes it hard to imagine she is much of a
homebody. A love seat bought for $35 and a chair for $7.50 fill
Betty Friedan's Washington apartment. (Susana Raab/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- May 10, 2000 -- BETTY-FRIEDAN-1 -- In 1963,
Betty Friedan, the combative writer and activist, inspired a social
revolution for women with ``The Feminine Mystique,'' in which she
debunked the myth of the postwar woman, that docile soul who tended
home and hearth while happily forgoing her own ambitions and
interests. Recently she finished her sixth book, and first memoir,
``Life So Far.'' Friedan in her Washington Apartment. (Susana
Raab/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) PHILADELPHIA -- May 10, 2000 -- CIR-PRODUCT-TESTS-2 --
Using simulated humans, the most well-known of which is called
Jack, designers and engineers have been able to better test
products from tractors to car trunks. Jack, at top, is used to test
the drivers visibility while using a tractor in reverse. Below, a
simulation allows designers to check the proper distance between a
truck driver's hand and a mirror during adjustment. (The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) PHILADELPHIA -- May 10, 2000 -- CIR-PRODUCT-TESTS --
Using simulated humans, the most well-known of which is called
Jack, designers and engineers have been able to better test
products from tractors to car trunks. Jack was developed by Norman
Badler, of the Center for Human Modeling and Simulation at
University of Pennsylvania, posing next to a statue of Benjamin
Franklin. (Michael Branscom/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) PHILADELPHIA -- May 10, 2000 -- CIR-PRODUCT-TESTS --
Using simulated humans, the most well-known of which is called
Jack, designers and engineers have been able to better test
products from tractors to car trunks. Jack was developed by Norman
Badler, of the Center for Human Modeling and Simulation at
University of Pennsylvania, posing next to a statue of Benjamin
Franklin. (Michael Branscom/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- May 10, 2000 -- CIR-BILL-ONLINE -- Bill-paying
services are a step toward the day when everyone will receive and
pay all their bills electronically. Online financial service
providers like Quicken and portals like AOL say they plan to offer
bill aggregation before the end of the summer. (Tony Cenicola/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WASHINGTON -- May 10, 2000 -- CLINTON-MEDICARE --
President Clinton laughs at a comment made by Betty Dizik during an
event in the Rose Garden where Clinton and Democratic leaders
unveiled their Medicare prescription drug benefits plan. Dizik, a
73-year-old widow who spoke about the problems she faces in
purchasing the medications she needs, drew a laugh after telling
the president she'd vote for him a third time. (Paul Hosefros/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
