<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-HEALTHCARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH PROPOSES TAX BREAKS FOR LONG-TERM CARE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVENPORT, Iowa _ Highlighting an issue of increasing importance
to his own generation, the baby boomers, Texas Gov. George W. Bush
on Wednesday proposed new tax breaks to ease the cost of long-term
health care.
</P>
<P>
   The presumptive Republican presidential nominee proposed that
private insurance premiums for long-term care be fully deductible
on federal income taxes, and he advocated personal tax exemptions
for people who care for relatives in their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign estimated that the new breaks, which would be
available to people of all income levels, would cost $7.4 billion
over five years. The changes are designed, the campaign said, to
help address a growing health-care need for older Americans that
will become even more critical as large numbers of baby boomers
start retiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``For too many seniors, illness can be the path to financial
ruin,'' Bush said during a visit to the Ridgecrest Village
retirement center in Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Bush campaign, the number of Americans age 65
or older is expected to reach nearly 70 million by 2030, when the
last of the baby boomers reach retirement. Meanwhile, life
expectancy and health-care costs are increasing.
</P>
<P>
   Bush staffers said most Americans mistakenly believe that their
long-term care needs are covered by their existing health insurance
plans or by Medicare. But most private health insurance policies
don't cover long-term care, and Medicare covers only short-term,
skilled nursing home care following hospitalization. Medicare also
limits home-care coverage to those needing rehabilitative services
or physical therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Only 5 percent of long-term-care costs are paid from private
insurance, according to Bush staffers. Most of the costs are borne
by Medicaid program, which finances care for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said he would encourage more people to purchase the
necessary insurance _ and relieve a growing burden on Medicaid _
with the new deduction.
</P>
<P>
   Under Bush's plan, the full cost of the premiums would be
deductible from taxable income, even for taxpayers who don't
itemize. Taxpayers who itemize could also claim the deduction even
if their medical expenses didn't total more than 7.5 percent of
adjusted gross income, as required under current law.
</P>
<P>
   The only people who would be ineligible for the deduction would
be those who already receive employer-subsidized long-term-care
coverage. The deduction would cost $5.1 billion over five years,
the Bush campaign said.
</P>
<P>
   At an additional estimated cost of $2.3 billion over five years,
Bush would give personal exemptions to people who care for their
elderly parents or other relatives at home. Each exemption is now
worth $2,750 against taxable income.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said a growing number of Americans are caring for elderly
relatives in their homes, a practice that he wants to encourage.
</P>
<P>
   Although relatively few people have private long-term health
care coverage, the Bush campaign said those policies, even without
the governor's proposed tax deduction, already cost much less than
a nursing home stay.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why Bush didn't put income limits on his proposed tax
breaks, spokeswoman Karen Hughes replied that the long-term
health-care burden ``affects a lot of higher income people as well
as lower income.``
</P>
<P>
   Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala responded to
the Bush proposal for the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our major disagreement is that it's not paid for,'' Shalala
said.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign of Vice President Al Gore, the presumptive
Democratic nominee, issued a ``fact sheet'' charging that Bush has
not made health care a priority during his tenure as governor of
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   And the Gore campaign touted the administration's own plan,
which includes a $3,000 tax credit to assist individuals with
long-term care needs or their families.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
