<HEADLINE>
IT'S A CONSPIRACY AGAINST THE STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ I don't even pretend to know what it takes
to be the best coach in the NHL. What I do know is that Stars coach
Ken Hitchcock never deserved the award more than he does this
season. And in the infinite wisdom of those who decide these
things, he's not even among the league's three finalists.
</P>
<P>
   Makes me wonder _ and not for the first time _ what it is the
NHL has against the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   They wear these nice snazzy uniforms. For two years running they
owned the President's Trophy. They have a rich owner who doesn't
mind spending money and who will soon move his team into a
state-of-the-art arena. They won ``the most coveted trophy in
sports,'' the Stanley Cup (hmmm, maybe it's that dent they put in
it).
</P>
<P>
   So seriously, what does it take to get a little respect around
here, for crying out loud?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, sure. Go ahead and shrug this off as the ignorant whining of
a provincial sportswriter who still thinks icing is what you put on
a birthday cake. But I'm telling you, there's a conspiracy going on
here and I, for one, am sick and tired of it.
</P>
<P>
   The only place the Stars seem to be getting respect for winning
the Stanley Cup last season is in the list of finalists for most of
the league's esteemed award categories. None are included, which
can lead to only one conclusion: they have reached the enviable
level of being completely taken for granted.
</P>
<P>
   There's no Mike Modano among the finalists for the Hart Trophy
as the league MVP, though he may well be on his way to the Conn
Smythe Trophy in the playoffs. No Derian Hatcher or Richard
Matvichuk on the list for the Norris Memorial Trophy, honoring the
best defenseman, though Colorado coach Bob Hartley has already
nominated Matvichuk for the Jack Ripper Award, given to the player
who ... well, you get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   No Modano among the finalists for the Selke Trophy. No Ed
Belfour competing for the Vezina Trophy (what, no jailbirds
allowed?) as the league's best goalie, though you'll have to look
long and hard to find a better one in these playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   So if the Stars don't have any individual stars worthy of a
junior partnership in the law firm of Hart, Norris, Selke and
Vezina, that must mean the system is the answer, right? It's a
``team'' thing.
</P>
<P>
   Which gets me back to coaching.
</P>
<P>
   How in the name of Jack Adams _ the guy the award is named after
_ can Hitchcock not be among the three finalists as coach of the
year? He doesn't have a single player good enough, according to the
league, to make the list of finalists for individual awards yet _
knock, knock _ here the Stars are again, in the conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock didn't win the award last year, despite taking his
team to the Cup, and he won't win it this year, though he has never
coached better than he did this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you spend two years playing pretty much maxed out, like
we did the last two years, and you get everything out of every
player and everything out of your group, and you're dominating at
times, then suddenly you get challenged with all the things we got
challenged with this year, it really makes you decide whether you
like just winning or whether you really enjoy coaching,'' Hitchcock
said yesterday after a light Stars practice in preparation for
Saturday night's playoff series opener with the Avalanche.
``Everybody assumes that the two are connected, but they're really
not.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to go back and teach and you have to make
consequences a new factor; you have to develop a new level of
patience; you have to maneuver around to win games rather than
dominate; you have to be willing to get your team back on the horse
and fly again. There are a lot of things you have to do that are
pure coaching and teaching as opposed to saying, `Well, we're going
to win today; I just want to win.' ''
</P>
<P>
   This, by far, was Hitchcock's most difficult season as the
Stars' coach, perhaps his most challenging season in coaching,
period. He knew it wouldn't be easy, but he had no idea how rocky
it would get at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``The downside of winning came flying out about a month into the
season,'' Hitchcock said. ``Lost friends, the route's too long, the
mountain's too high ... you name it. I found we were carrying so
much baggage with us and we had to eliminate it. We had to narrow
our focus and stop looking any more than 24 hours ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the real challenge. We had to find a way as a group,
the players and coaches and everybody, to enjoy the daily struggle
and not worry about the end of the road or how we were going to get
there.''
</P>
<P>
   As often happens, challenge became a voyage of discovery. The
coach and the players learned more about themselves and what they
could not only endure, but overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to ask yourself again, `Do you really like coaching?
Do you really like what you wanted to do when you first started
out?' Because, guess what, things aren't going to be easy this
year, and it's not going to be the smooth ride that you had the
last couple of years. You're not going to have all of these nice,
easy situations that have been there for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock reacted to his team's struggles by becoming a
stronger, better coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found what frustrated me early in the season invigorated me
later on,'' he said. ``I learned why I liked coaching. I learned
again that I love to teach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been more pure coaching. There hasn't been the garbage
that goes with proving anything. It's been pure. It's why you get
in this business.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the greatest coaching performance seen around here since,
well, one Jimmy Johnson left town.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad the NHL didn't notice.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
