<HEADLINE>
EAGER STARS HAVE NO LOVE FOR LENGTHY LAYOFFS IN PLAYOFFS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING _ Tina Turner had a hit with ``What's Love Got To Do With
It?''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, a better question is what's Turner got to do with the
Western Conference finals? The answer is everything, and there
certainly wasn't a lot of love in the Stars' locker room yesterday
because of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's completely stupid,'' Stars center Guy Carbonneau said of
the playoff schedule that has Game 2 between the Stars and Colorado
Avalanche scheduled for Monday in Dallas while Game 3 isn't until
Friday in Denver. ``It's a country club. You get five days between
games now so you can rest. You don't need depth anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   If Carbonneau, who at 40 wants all the rest he can get, didn't
like it, you can imagine what the rest of the Stars were saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``It think it's stupid,'' Stars captain Derian Hatcher said,
repeating the phrase of the day. ``Why can't we play? Why can't we
start the series \Rtoday\S? I didn't even ask, to be honest. I just
want to know who set it up ... It doesn't make sense to me.''
</P>
<P>
   He has questions. We have answers.
</P>
<P>
   The layoff between Games 2 and 3 is because Turner has a concert
scheduled for Wednesday at the Pepsi Center in Denver. They
wouldn't be able to get the ice ready for a game on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   So why didn't they start the series on Friday with Game 2 on
Sunday? The answer is television. ABC wanted to show both the
Eastern and Western Conference finals in their Sunday afternoon
slot. When the Philadelphia Flyers won on Tuesday, setting up a
matchup between them and the New Jersey Devils, the network decided
to begin with that TV-wealthy matchup for their first Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's what we were delivered and that's what we'll
do,'' Stars general manager Bob Gainey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can look at it two ways, either the break between series
is too long or not long enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars wrapped up their second-round series against San Jose
Sunday, meaning they will play two games in 11 days.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite the long, grueling NHL playoffs we so often hear
about. Grueling? Not exactly.
</P>
<P>
   Long? Definitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the talk about trying to make it shorter? Right.'' Hatcher
said. ``It seems like they are trying to stretch it out as long as
possible. Instead of trying to make it shorter, they are doing the
opposite.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
