(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Rick Helling was able to do his side work
yesterday despite a swollen right hand, and he should be able to
make his scheduled start Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw all my pitches,'' Helling said. ``It wasn't like
pinpoint control, but I was able to throw them all. It felt kind of
funny, because my fingers are still swollen.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling was hit on the hand by a line drive off the bat of
Seattle catcher Tom Lampkin in the second inning Monday and had to
leave the game by the sixth. Although the hand was still swollen
yesterday, the injury had improved enough to allow him to flex his
fingers and do his side work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be very surprised if I couldn't go Saturday,'' Helling
said.
</P>
<P>
   If Helling needs an extra day, he could switch places in the
rotation with Esteban Loaiza. The Mariners knocked Loaiza out in
the third inning after 62 pitches Tuesday, and manager Johnny Oates
said he could come back a day early because of the low pitch count.
 &QL; 
Ready for rehab
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Frank Catalanotto, on the disabled list since
April 22 because of a pulled left groin muscle, is ready to begin a
rehabilitation assignment with Triple-A Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited to get going,'' said Catalanotto, who has played
only nine games. ``I've been pulling my hair out. I'm bored
stiff.''
</P>
<P>
   Catalanotto plans to work out with the RedHawks today, when the
Rangers leave for a four-game road trip to Anaheim. He said he will
be the designated hitter tomorrow and play the field Saturday and
Sunday. Barring setbacks, he would be ready to be activated when
the Rangers return home Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to make sure everything's OK,'' he said. ``I don't
care if I go 0-for-12 with 12 strikeouts, just as long as my
groin's OK.''  &QL; 
Venafro improving
</P>
<P>
   Left-handed reliever Mike Venafro's shutout inning against the
Mariners on Tuesday extended his scoreless streak to four innings
over six appearances. His ERA is down to 4.22.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's getting there,'' Johnny Oates said. ``There's a little
more movement on the ball, a little more life to it.''
\Nsubheds:Mateo extends streak With a fourth-inning single, center
fielder Ruben Mateo extended his hitting streak to 14 games, the
longest by a Ranger this season and the third-longest streak ever
by a Rangers rookie.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Browne (1987) and George Wright (1982) had 15-game streaks
as rookies. Browne hit .317 in his streak, and Wright hit .367.
Mateo is batting .431 in his.  &QL; 
Rangers vs. Angels
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers conclude their first round of games against AL West
opponents with a four-game series at Anaheim beginning tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were 6-6 against the Angels last season, going 3-3
at The Ballpark and Edison Field. Each team scored 74 runs.
</P>
<P>
   Angels pitcher Ken Hill went on the disabled list after
straining a muscle in the right side of his rib cage Tuesday. Mike
Fyhrie was promoted from the minors, and is scheduled to pitch
against the Rangers on Sunday. Rookie Ramon Ortiz, who had been
scheduled to pitch Saturday, was demoted to Triple-A Edmonton
yesterday and replaced by Jarrod Washburn.  &QL; 
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Rodriguez's day off lasted 71/2 innings, until he hit for
Scarborough Green with two outs in the eighth inning. He doubled,
improving to 2-for-2 with a homer and double as a pinch hitter this
season. He has a career .414 average (14-for-34) as a pinch hitter.
Rangers pinch hitters are 6-for-9 with three walks this season.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Oates showed confidence in rookie third baseman Mike
Lamb, allowing the left-handed batter to hit against lefty reliever
Arthur Rhodes in the eighth inning. Lamb singled, his second hit of
the game, and improved his average to .288.
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Sierra is making the most of his opportunity with Triple-A
Oklahoma, batting .382 with two home runs and 12 runs batted in. He
drove in the winning run in the ninth inning of the RedHawks' 3-2
victory against Omaha on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Minor-league catcher Cesar King, who was designated for
assignment when the Rangers added Scarborough Green to the 40-man
roster, was claimed by the Philadelphia Phillies and optioned to
their Triple-A club.
nn
</P>
