<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTOR-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
Werner swats rumor
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Texas Motorplex in Ennis and Houston Raceway Park in Baytown
both would lose one of their two NHRA events in 2001, according to
one Silly Season version of the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   An industry source said the Motorplex would lose its spring race
and HRP would surrender its fall date to allow the National Hot Rod
Association to book second events at the state-of-the-art Route 66
Raceway in Joliet, Ill., and The Strip at Las Vegas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Elon Werner, general manager of the Motorplex, said he has
received no indication from NHRA president Tom Compton that the
fourth annual Castrol Nationals scheduled for the first time on
Memorial Day weekend (May 25-28) will be the event's last hurrah.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not heard that at all,'' Werner said. ``And I would be
very surprised, in that the Castrol Nationals is a growing event.
First, our ticket sales are up almost 10 percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Second, our sponsors _ Castrol and O'Reilly Auto Parts _ the
Dallas-Fort Worth market is huge for them. NHRA is very concerned
about branding and strengthening their sponsor position, so that
would go against their philosophy. Third, this event makes NHRA a
lot of money. I'm very confident we'll continue to have two NHRA
events at the Motorplex.''
</P>
<P>
   Compton could not be reached for comment yesterday on a schedule
the NHRA reportedly plans to unveil around June 1.  &QL; 
Night race preferred
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Gossage is lobbying for the next NASCAR race at Texas
Motor Speedway to be a nighttime event.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, that's preferably a Winston Cup race,'' said
Gossage, TMS executive vice president and general manager. ``But if
it's a Busch race or whatever ... my preference is a night race.''
</P>
<P>
   Gossage said he pitched the idea of a stand-alone Busch night
race to Mike Helton, NASCAR's senior vice president and chief
operating officer, during the race weekend here in April. Helton
announced on Monday that new tracks in the Kansas City and Chicago
markets would be added to the Cup schedule in 2001, again denying
TMS of a coveted second race in NASCAR's premier series.
</P>
<P>
   That suddenly has made the idea of a second Busch race here even
more attractive.
</P>
<P>
   ``My desire there is that it be a night race,'' Gossage said,
``and we talked about how much fun that would be and how big a
crowd we could draw. I think it could be something NASCAR could
point towards _ a stand-alone Busch Series event, and they draw a
monster crowd in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Gossage said he prefers a late-summer or early fall date for a
second BGN race. Unless, of course, NASCAR decides to grant TMS a
second Cup race at night.  &QL; 
F1 tickets sell well
</P>
<P>
   Reserved seats in all grandstand areas for the inaugural U.S.
Grand Prix at Indianapolis Formula One race have been sold. But
general admission tickets remain available for all three days of
the event (Sept. 22-24) at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway. For
ticket information, call (317) 484-6700.
</P>
<P>
   The race's start has been moved up an hour, to 1 p.m. CDT.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
