<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-LEONE-U.N.-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. PEACEKEEPERS PREPARE FOR CLASHES WITH REBELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Complete writethru for updates, revisions; ADDS 600 words; Now
moving in 2 takes) 
By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ With its political options in Sierra Leone all
but exhausted, the United Nations reluctantly ordered peacekeeping
troops there Wednesday to take up defensive positions and prepare
to fight rebels advancing toward the capital, Freetown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll do what we have to do to defend ourselves and the
government,'' the U.N. spokesman, Fred Eckhard, said here
Wednesday. ``We hope it won't come to a pitched battle, but we are
preparing for one.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the peacekeepers, who number more than 8,000, had been
consolidated around Freetown and were digging in at the entrances
to the capital.
</P>
<P>
   The lightly armed soldiers, who came to Sierra Leone to help the
United Nations carry out a peace agreement signed last July between
the government and the Revolutionary United Front, are not
configured or equipped for conventional combat. Now the
peacekeepers have been told to assume a role they did not expect to
take on, lacking tanks, artillery and helicopter gunships.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials said they still know little or nothing about the
whereabouts and condition of about 500 peacekeeping troops who were
taken hostage by the rebels early last week _ the incident that
precipitated the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
   One detachment of 208 Zambian soldiers, who were captured
together with their armored personnel carriers, was reported to
have been taken to Koidu, a rebel stronghold in eastern Sierra
Leone. There was no word on the fate of another contingent of 200
Zambians who disappeared later. Attempts to deliver food and other
supplies to the captured peacekeepers have largely been thwarted.
The United Nations has not specified the nationalities of the other
hostages.
</P>
<P>
   President Charles Taylor of Liberia, who is close to the Sierra
Leone rebel leader, Foday Sankoh, has been asked to win the
peacekeepers' freedom, but so far has won only the release of a
Russian helicopter crew and two passengers. Sankoh himself has been
missing since protests outside his home in Freetown erupted into
gunfire on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations does not know the size or exact locations of
the rebel force, which are thought to control about half the
countryside. The rebels are armed with assault rifles and side
arms. When the peace accord was reached last year, there were some
45,000 combatants, on all sides.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials said that a handful of peacekeepers have been
killed and others have been wounded. The dead include Nigerian
troops caught in a cross-fire between government troops and rebels
at Rogberi last weekend, when a government helicopter accidentally
fired rockets at the Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolutionary United Front, Sankoh's rebel organization, has
set no conditions for freeing the captured peacekeepers. Sankoh has
denied that his forces held any peacekeepers, and his disappearance
has left the United Nations with no one to approach directly for
their release.
</P>
<P>
   The 13 armored personnel carriers that the rebels took from the
Zambians have been painted black and have been seen moving with the
rebels, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   With Sierra Leone sliding back into war, Eckhard said the United
Nations would no longer report the movements of its troops or
clashes with the rebels, who are already engaged against government
forces.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary-General Kofi Annan's strategy has been to shore up the
U.N. military presence in Sierra Leone sufficiently to deter the
rebels while he seeks a political solution salvaging the peace
accord.
</P>
<P>
   At the U.N. headquarters, where the mood was somber Wednesday,
officials met with diplomats from Jordan, India and Bangladesh to
discuss how to speed up the arrival in Sierra Leone of three
infantry battalions that these countries had pledged for next
month.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, Russia, Canada and the Netherlands have
offered to supply aircraft to ferry the new troops into Sierra
Leone. But the United States is limiting the carrying capacity of
its transport planes and proposes charging the United Nations as
much as or more than commercial air carriers would charge,
diplomats complained. The other countries are considering carrying
the troops for nothing or at cost.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of new troops would lift the U.N. mission's military
strength in Sierra Leone close to the authorized ceiling of 11,700,
from the 8,936 reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But officials said that airlifts could not begin for at least 10
days and would not be completed before the end of May. It was
unclear how much equipment the new soldiers would bring with them.
</P>
<P>
   Annan has received no response to his appeal for a well-equipped
rapid reaction force. The mission has been criticized for the ease
with which the rebels were able to overwhelm and detain U.N.
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best peacekeeper is a well-trained soldier,'' Annan said
Wednesday when asked about the quality of troops sent to Sierra
Leone. ``And we would have liked to see some of the governments
with capacity _ with good armies and well-trained soldiers _ to
participate. But they are not running forward to contribute to this
force. So we have to take the forces we get.''
</P>
<P>
   The secretary-general seemed to allude to the United States and
European powers when he said he hoped that strong countries ``would
go to the assistance of those who are in there doing their bidding
for the Security Council and the U.N.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has ruled out putting U.S. troops on
the ground in Sierra Leone. But Wednesday, Annan expressed thanks
for a British force of more than 800 paratroopers, which has
secured the airport at Lungi, outside Freetown, freeing up U.N.
soldiers to help defend the capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``The British presence has been helpful,'' Annan said. ``They
have done something, even though the initial objective was to
evacuate British and other nationals.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 2252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
