<SLUG> BC-CAR-STURBIN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAY'S RADAR GUN LOCKED IN ON INDY 500
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The most unforgettable mile of Greg Ray's
1999 championship season was not completed during the Indianapolis
500.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was it recorded at Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth, where
Ray clinched the Indy Racing League driver's title in the
season-ending Mall.com 500 on Oct. 17.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later, after a long day made even longer by a rain
delay and a full race and a championship celebration with his
hometown fans, Ray climbed into his Corvette and began the drive
home to Plano. Working his way through traffic in Trophy Club, Ray
was pulled over by a policeman on a motorcycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The officer asked me if I was in a hurry,'' Ray recounted
yesterday afternoon in The Speedway Club at TMS. ``I said no, but I
had had a long day at the Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Oh, what do you do out there?' I said, `I race
Indy-cars,' and he acted like he didn't understand. I had a big
stack of autograph cards with my race car on it next to me, and I
showed it to him. And he kinda looked at it and goes, `I'm a NASCAR
fan.' And he gave me a ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, that was funny.''
</P>
<P>
   It got even funnier for Ray later during his now annual Indy 500
sendoff luncheon yesterday. Ray was working his way through another
memoir when Trophy Club-Westlake motorcycle patrolman Larry Fischer
fired up his Harley-Davidson Road King ``cop bike'' at the back of
the elaborate ballroom and drove up to the dais being shared by Ray
and Eddie Gossage, TMS executive vice president and general
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Patrolman Fischer _ who made it clear to the audience that he
was not the officer who had ticketed Ray last fall _ nevertheless
reminded Ray to obey the speed limits around here. But in case he
ever got into a jam again, Fischer presented Ray with a genuine
plastic Junior Patrolman Badge _ guaranteed to give the next
officer who pulls him over a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   And another ticket for Ray.
</P>
<P>
   He has had a lot of fun living down the incident, which Ray said
received play as a ``brite'' in newspapers around the country and,
of course, was aired with fanfare on ``RPM 2Night''.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I can see, it was a pretty good piece of media,''
Ray said. ``And it was one of my competitors, Sam Schmidt, who
said: `I'm sure Greg didn't get a speeding ticket. He's just really
good at working PR.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ray, 33, is even better at standing on the accelerator of his
race car, which is the game plan when practice for the 84th Indy
500 begins on Saturday. Pole qualifications are scheduled May 20
for a race that will be run on May 28. Each of those days has been
circled on the Team Menard-Conseco calendar in Gasoline Alley.
Ray's best result in the season's first three races has been his
ninth-place run at Las Vegas Motor Speedway last month.
</P>
<P>
   A three-time winner in 1999, Ray started out 1999 in a similar
funk before showing up at the 2.5-mile Indianapolis Motor Speedway
with the Dallara-Aurora to beat. Ray was, in fact, leading the race
past halfway when his in-car radio failed, and he collided with the
car driven by Mark Dismore on pit road.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that has never been funny, although Ray has learned to deal
with the disappointment during the past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't haunt me,'' Ray said, ``but it's very bizarre to
watch a video clip of the Indy 500 and see Kenny Brack win. We were
the team. We had the car, all month long and during the race, to
win that race. And that's really our mental state now. I mean, we
expect to go there and _ not to be taken the wrong way _ but we'll
be disappointed if we're not on pole.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll disappointed if we don't win.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Ray plans to leave for Indy tonight in his
Corvette. The trip is approximately 850 miles and will require two
pit stops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to tell you how long it's going to take me,''
Ray said, after Patrolman Fischer and his Harley had split. ``But
it'll take me a little less than the average driver.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
