<SLUG> BC-GLF-NELSON-COTTONWOOD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLFER HOPING FOR COTTONWOOD BINGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Based on feedback from players, the jury is out
on whether scores will soar at the GTE Byron Nelson Classic because
of off-season course changes on the TPC at Las Colinas layout.
</P>
<P>
   Tournament officials, including the event's namesake, have
predicted a bump of anywhere from 0.30 to a full stroke per day in
the TPC scoring average by the time the final putt falls in the
final round Sunday. If so, several golfers agree they'll need to
make more than their usual allotment of birdies during their lone
trip around Cottonwood Valley Golf Course.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally the easier of the two courses used during Nelson
week, the Cottonwood course will be played by half the golfers in
the 156-player field today in the opening round. The ones who
emerge on Sunday's leader board, said defending champ Loren
Roberts, will be the ones who make the most of their opportunity at
Cottonwood, which statistically plays a stroke easier than TPC.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the TPC course, where touring pros will be greeted by
longer tees, more bunkers, 781 new trees and enlarged greens, there
were no course tweaks at Cottonwood during the off-season. If
scores rise as expected on the TPC course, Roberts said that places
a greater premium on shattering par at Cottonwood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it does,'' Roberts said. ``You need to put up a good
score over there if you're going to challenge, especially if it's
windy. That's a golf course that's very playable in the wind.
Effectively, the par over there is 3- or 4-under.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick Price, the 1991 Nelson champ, goes even further.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always feel if you don't shoot 5- or 6-under at
Cottonwood, you're giving up strokes to the field,'' said Price,
who blitzed the course with an opening 63 last year en route to a
12th-place finish. ``You can't win the tournament there. But you
can sure lose it, if you don't shoot a really good round. You can't
shoot a 70 and expect to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   In the five years the Nelson has used its two-course system, no
winner has shot worse than 68 _ 2-under par _ in his lone round at
Cottonwood. Three of the five champions (Tiger Woods, Phil
Mickelson, Ernie Els) posted their lowest scores of the tournament
at Cottonwood. When Els won in 1995, his cumulative score on the
TPC course was only third-best among Nelson competitors. But he won
by three strokes on the strength of a course-record 61 fired at
Cottonwood.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts and John Cook, the past two Nelson winners, actually
fared better during rounds at TPC. But Roberts said the key to
contending, especially in windy conditions, remains making the most
of the time spent at Cottonwood. Harrison Frazar, a Dallas native,
concurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you happen to catch TPC on a windy day, and Cottonwood on a
calm day, you've got a huge advantage over the person who has it
reversed,'' Frazar said.
</P>
<P>
   Others are less convinced. Mickelson, the 1996 Nelson champ,
said the bulk of a player's work during Nelson week still must be
done at TPC.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where you get 75 percent of your score,'' Mickelson
said. ``It's important to have a good round at Cottonwood, but I
don't think it's imperative that you go extremely low. I do agree
you can shoot yourself out of this tournament with a bad round at
Cottonwood. Absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the course changes, players remain curious about what
awaits them at TPC. Most point to longer tee boxes at No. 6 and No.
15, as well as a reconfigured 10th hole _ which features a larger
green and new greenside bunkers _ as the places where scores will
climb, as tournament officials envision.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said yesterday that he expects scoring to be affected by
roughly three-fourths of a stroke per day on the TPC layout. Frazar
pointed to the additional length at No. 15, which creates a
475-yard par-4 that usually plays into the wind, as ``a big
change'' in the estimation of competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, the 1997 champ, identified No. 10 as the revamped hole
that caught his eye. The tee box has been shifted 50 yards to the
left, forcing players to drive over a canal. In addition, four new
fairway bunkers have been added. Woods said a playing partner found
one during yesterday's pro-am round.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a guy almost bury a ball in the bunker with a driver.
That's not easy to do,'' Woods said. ``Obviously, they didn't pack
it down. You hit the ball in one of those bunkers, it's a true
penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   But not as damaging, in the overall scheme of Nelson week, as a
poor round at Cottonwood.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go out there and shoot a 70 at Cottonwood, you're
putting yourself behind the 8-ball pretty good,'' Woods said. ``If
you don't play well there, you're going to get left behind.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
