<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-OLIVER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLIVER IMPROVING, BUT WINLESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By NATHAN SANDERS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Good outing, bad outing ... for Darren
Oliver, it doesn't seem to make a difference. The outcome usually
winds up the same:
</P>
<P>
   No decision.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver made his seventh start of the season for the Rangers
yesterday afternoon, pitching seven strong innings before leaving
with a 5-3 lead. His reward was his fifth no-decision of the year
as reliever Tim Crabtree failed to hold the lead in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   David Segui's two-run home run in the bottom of the ninth turned
a 6-5 deficit into a 7-6 victory against Seattle, but it came too
late to give Oliver his first victory. The left-hander is 0-2 with
a 5.19 earned-run average.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, when you go out there and pitch well you would like
to get something to show for it,'' Oliver said. ``But we won as a
team, so that's the bottom line. It would be different if we lost
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver has made progress in spite of his winless record. Since
opening the season with a 7.45 ERA in his first two games, Oliver
has recorded a 4.54 ERA in his past five outings. The pendulum has
swung both ways in that span, but it never stops in his victory
column.
</P>
<P>
   On April 17 against the New York Yankees, he took a no-hitter
into the seventh inning ... and had a no-decision in a 5-4 loss. On
Friday, he allowed five runs against Oakland and lasted only five
innings ... and had a no-decision in a 17-16 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Oliver allowed three earned runs _ two of which came
on solo home runs by Edgar Martinez and Alex Rodriguez _ and showed
good command of his changeup, slider and fastball. But it wasn't
enough to bring him his first victory since he beat San Diego while
with the St. Louis Cardinals on Sept. 29, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't think about it,'' Rangers pitching coach Dick Bosman
said. ``You get frustrated, I know, and he's pitching pretty darn
good; but you can't carry that frustration with you the next time.
Frustration only leads to trying to overdo things, and overdoing
things only leads to less consistency. ... It's a battle within
more than anything else; it really is.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver is still fighting that battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really out of my control,'' Oliver said. ``All I can do
is go out there and keep pitching and keep grinding and hopefully
when the wins come, they will come in bunches.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
