<SLUG> BC-LEE-NUKE-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE DEPT. REPLACES TOP PROSECUTOR IN NUCLEAR SECRETS CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In a sign of possible turmoil in a highly
sensitive criminal case, the Justice Department has decided to
replace at a critical moment the top prosecutor in its case against
a scientist charged with mishandling nuclear weapon secrets at the
Los Alamos National Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Chavez, a spokesman for the U.S. attorney's office in
Albuquerque, N.M., where the case is being handled, said the
Justice Department had decided to send a prosecutor from Washington
to take control of the case from Bob Gorence, an assistant U.S.
attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez said Gorence, an experienced prosecutor who has pursued
the case aggressively from its start last year, would remain ``a
key member of the team'' handling the case against Wen Ho Lee, who
was charged with illegally downloading top secret data on nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of the computer tapes on which Lee downloaded the data
have disappeared, and the government has charged that he intended
to provide the information to a foreign government, China.
</P>
<P>
   Lee has vigorously denied the charges and has said he believes
he was unfairly singled out for prosecution because he is
Chinese-American. Asian-Americans have come together to offer
support, and have contended that he is a victim of racial
discrimination. Although Lee has not been charged with espionage,
he is being held under extraordinarily tight security and was twice
denied bail.
</P>
<P>
   The change in prosecutors is surprising, in part, because it
comes at a particularly sensitive time, when the defense and the
government are expected to battle over how much nuclear weapon
information can be submitted in the trial. The timing of the change
heartened the defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is good news for Dr. Lee, as Mr. Gorence was an
experienced prosecutor,'' said Mark Holscher, one of Lee's lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Gorence would not comment.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is not scheduled until November, but the defense has
already filed motions to introduce at trial all of the information
Lee is said to have downloaded, and the request is expected to be
argued in court in the next couple of months. The judge's decision
could be pivotal to the outcome of the trial, and the government's
argument now might be handled by someone relatively new to a case
that involves abstruse issues of nuclear technology as well as
national security.
</P>
<P>
   If the judge rules that the information should be admitted, the
government must decide whether to comply. The government has
already argued that the information contains ``the crown jewels''
of the U.S. nuclear arsenal and that releasing it would compromise
the country's national security. But if it refuses to release the
information, it will probably have to drop the charges against Lee.
</P>
<P>
   If the judge rejects Lee's request, it could weaken his defense,
which his lawyers have said rests on his claims that most of the
data was already in the public realm, that by itself it was not
enough to design a bomb and that it was not that useful without a
variety of manuals and other tools not generally available.
</P>
<P>
   Gorence has worked in the U.S. attorney's office for 14 years.
Six years ago he handed in his resignation with plans to start a
criminal defense practice. But he withdrew the letter after John
Kelly, who was then the U.S. attorney, made him his first
assistant, the person who effectively runs the office.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly left to run for Congress several months ago and Gorence
was named the acting U.S. attorney. But he was ultimately passed
over and the Justice Department nominated another attorney in the
office, Norman Bay, for the top job. Bay then replaced Gorence as
first assistant.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether any of these factors came to play in the
decision to replace Gorence as the lead prosecutor, or even whether
Gorence will remain with the U.S. attorney's office. But the
defense lawyers made it clear that they would not tolerate any
delays in the proceedings, and that they would fight for the
ability to use at his trial all the data Lee is accused of
illegally downloading.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 2253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
