<SLUG> BC-ARMY-HARASSMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMY INQUIRY SUBSTANTIATES GENERAL'S HARASSMENT CLAIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (This is an added starter on Page 1)  
 By CHRISTOPHER MARQUIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. Army's inspector general has concluded
that the service's highest-ranking female officer was a victim of
inappropriate sexual advances from another Army general, Defense
Department officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry substantiated the claim of Lt. Gen. Claudia J.
Kennedy, whose career is often cited as an example of the
opportunities for women in uniform, that Gen. Larry G. Smith
touched her inappropriately and tried to kiss her in her office at
the Pentagon in 1996, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The case, the first instance of a sexual harassment case lodged
against one Army general by another, is a serious embarrassment for
the Army, which like the other armed services has been roiled by
sexual scandals. Kennedy's allegation proved explosive among senior
Army officers and resulted in a charge against her _ later
dismissed _ of personal misconduct. The conclusions in the
inspector general's report were first reported in The Washington
Post.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy filed a formal complaint last August after the Army
announced that Smith had been appointed deputy inspector general.
</P>
<P>
   Although Kennedy, the Army's first woman to earn three stars,
did not formally report the 1996 incident for nearly three years,
investigators validated her claim through interviews with friends
and peers with whom she spoke after the event.
</P>
<P>
   An Army spokesman had no immediate comment on the results of the
inspection.
</P>
<P>
   Officials cautioned that the disciplinary process against Smith
is far from over. The Army inspector general is preparing to send
his findings to the Army's vice chief of staff, Gen. John Keane,
who must then issue his own finding. Smith then has a right to
rebuttal before the vice chief makes his conclusive finding.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who never took over the post as deputy inspector general,
is expected to be forced to retire soon. He is not expected to face
a court-martial because Army officials do not consider that the
incident merits prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Smith could not be reached for comment late Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   While the Army's inspector general, Lt. Gen. Michael W.
Ackerman, has led the inquiry, the clash between two generals was
deemed sufficiently high-profile to invite oversight by the
Pentagon's inspector general, who may ultimately be called upon to
determine any actions taken against Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, 52, is one of only three women in the military who are
three-star officers, out of a total of 116 officers who hold the
rank in the Army, Navy, Air Force and Marines.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, who recently announced that she would retire later this
year, had been deputy chief of staff for intelligence before her
promotion to lieutenant general in May 1997.
</P>
<P>
   She has refused to discuss publicly her allegations of sexual
harassment. In interviews after her promotion to lieutenant
general, however, she said she had experienced sexual harassment in
her career. In an interview with ABC News in 1997, she said she had
dealt with the incident ``individually.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the important thing about it is that early in my
career, what I did was I dealt with it individually,'' she said.
``My approach was to turn it over to my boss. And I was very
impressed with the way it was handled.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Pentagon officers have sought to portray the
overwhelmingly male-dominated military as more open than ever to
women, even at the highest ranks, while insisting that sexual
harassment would never be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's case obviously undercut that impression, as did
investigations of two other male generals who were demoted for
having had adulterous affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen. John J. Maher 3rd was demoted two ranks and forced to
retire last November after having affairs with the wives of two
subordinate officers. Maj. Gen. David Hale was demoted one rank and
fined after pleading guilty to eight counts of misconduct stemming
from affairs he had with the wives of four subordinate officers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 2257EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000510.0367 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
