u i BC-TURKEY-GUARDS-NYT &LR;      05-10 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-GUARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURKEY'S VILLAGE GUARDS WORRY ABOUT THEIR FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN KINZER   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADEN, Turkey _ Sipping tea in the sun and looking down from
their clay bunker at a placid field full of wildflowers, Irfan Ozay
and his cousin Remzi should be happy. With their help and that of
95,000 other village guards, the Turkish army has finally won its
war against Kurdish rebels.
</P>
<P>
   But like many other village guards, the Ozay cousins are worried
and becoming angry. They fear they will soon be demobilized and
find themselves without jobs or prospects. What to do with these
village guards is one of the most urgent questions that suddenly
confront Turkey now that peace has broken out.
</P>
<P>
   The Kurdish rebel leader, Abdullah Ocalan, was captured last
year and remains in a Turkish prison under sentence of death. At
his trial he said he now favors peaceful change, and asked his
guerrillas to stop fighting. Nearly all have done so.
</P>
<P>
   With no war, there is no need for village guards. Yet these
guards, who served as the first line of defense against the
guerrillas, have spent years carrying rifles. Many have become
accustomed to rough lives. Some have even been convicted of using
their quasi-military authority to commit crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The village guards around here will be peaceful, but I can
think of other places where they might start trouble or form
gangs,'' Irfan Ozay mused from his hilltop perch near Maden, which
overlooks a strategic highway 765 miles east of Istanbul. ``The
state needs to come up with a solution for us. Otherwise a lot of
people will be upset, and that's dangerous for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked in hard conditions for years,'' Ozay said. ``Now it
turns out we don't have any insurance or pension or any other kind
of rights. That's not fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Ozay is a veteran of eight years as a village guard, he
is just 26 years old and still has a few sheep from which he might
build up a herd. His cousin, though, is 40 and has nowhere to
start. ``I realize they don't need us any more, but I don't have
any business or land to go back to,'' Remzi Ozay said. ``What do
they expect me to do?''
</P>
<P>
   The village guard system was conceived more than a decade ago as
the Kurdish rebellion was intensifying. Many of its members
rendered invaluable service because they knew this region and its
people far more intimately than the army.
</P>
<P>
   This system also became a source of bitterness. Some village
guards drifted into corruption, others abused civilians. In some
villages the army forced men to become guards, imprisoning those
who refused.
</P>
<P>
   But no one doubts that village guards played a significant role
in the army's 15-year campaign to assert control of Turkey's rugged
eastern mountains. Now they want their government to show its
gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   Families in this part of Turkey are large, and by one estimate a
total of one million people here rely on salaries paid to the
95,000 village guards. The base salary is the equivalent of just
$115 per month, but in a region where war has brought almost all
productive activity to a halt, that is a valuable sum.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish officials and foreign diplomats have begun to worry that
if these salaries are suddenly cut off and nothing replaces them,
some unhappy veterans might grab their weapons and take to the
hills.
</P>
<P>
   One senior member of Parliament, Salih Yildirim, has proposed
that village guards over the age of 55 be allowed to retire with
benefits. Younger ones, he said, should either be offered jobs as
security guards or helped to find work as farmers or herders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem involves a great number of people,'' Yildirim
said. ``We must integrate these people into the region's economy.''
</P>
<P>
   But unfortunately no real economy exists in eastern Turkey.
Before the war most people here used to herd livestock on remote
mountains, but for years the army has forbidden them to enter the
highlands. Many live as impoverished refugees in swollen cities.
</P>
<P>
   All of this strikes hard at men like the two cousins who have
spent years standing watch outside their lonesome bunker here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were hired to help the state destroy an enemy and win a
war,'' Remzi Ozay reasoned. ``We succeeded. So why are we being
thrown away like this?''
</P>
<P>
   His younger cousin, however, believes things will work out in
the end. ``They'll find a solution for us,'' he said. ``If no one
else does, the army will. They have to. They know the danger if
they just cut us off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
