<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1479 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-NOVELIST-1STLD-     05-10 1295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-NOVELIST-1STLD-WRITETHRU-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEX, LUST, DRUGS: YOUNG WOMAN'S NOVEL IS TOO MUCH FOR CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS 3rd graf to clarify that bureau is local not national; 5th
graf to change `on the Internet' to `to read on the Internet', as
opposed to buying-selling on Internet; 11th graf to describe sexual
taboos in more detail) 
 By CRAIG S. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ Zhou Weihui, dressed in a traditional black
silk Chinese dress slit to mid-thigh, had gathered her friends and
acquaintances on a veranda overlooking this city's famous 1930s-era
waterfront, ostensibly to say goodbye to society for a while. She
wanted to drop out of sight, she said, because she was under too
much pressure from China's propaganda machine, which was busy
trashing her best-selling novel, ``Shanghai Baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, Zhou's publisher had destroyed the page proofs and all
of the books in stock, arguing _ after having sold at least 80,000
copies _ that the novel was in poor taste and that Zhou, 27, was
too outlandish.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Beijing's city Press and Publication Bureau raided a
book fair in the capital and confiscated dozens of copies. And tens
of thousands more copies are being destroyed around the country
while the state media denounce Zhou as ``decadent, debauched and a
slave of foreign culture.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Shanghai Baby'' tells the story of Coco, a 25-year-old
waitress who falls in love with a tall and handsome but impotent
and drug-addicted man named Tian Tian. She moves in with him, and
later begins an affair with a married German. ``One is for love,
the other is for lust,'' Zhou explained on the Shanghai veranda, a
cigarette fixed between her silver-nailed fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands, perhaps hundreds of thousands, of young
Chinese have bought the book, making Weihui, as she prefers to be
called, a national phenomenon. She is the country's most popular
writer since Wang Shuo, whose late-1980s writings about Beijing's
disaffected youth became so popular that the books are now
available to read on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Few other contemporary Chinese writers come close. ``Shanghai
Baby'' has gone through six printings since it was first published
last September, and several pirated editions are circulating around
China. A newspaper in Guangzhou even serialized the book, but
published only half before it was forced to stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all right to hold some book signings and other
promotional activities, but things should be done to a moderate and
proper degree,'' said An Boshun, Zhou's editor at Chunfeng
Literature and Art Publishing House, in a state-run newspaper last
week. In other words, Weihui has become too popular _ a strange
thing for a publisher to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   An, who has published a series of novels by the country's ``new,
new generation'' of writers, was slightly more forthcoming in a
phone call. ``It's an ideological matter,'' he said, declining to
discuss the matter further.
</P>
<P>
   Weihui's writing, and that of a handful of similar women of her
generation, has set off a debate about what is literature in a
country with a literary tradition stretching back thousands of
years and where belles-lettres have often been considered
politically suspect. Destroying books that challenge the state's
worldview occurred as early as 213 B.C., when Emperor Qin Shi
Huangdi burned all the books in the realm in an attempt to unify
people's thought. China's current government has periodically
resorted to similar, if less thorough, acts.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a People's Daily editorial reminded readers that
literature ``is a temple of holiness,'' and said that ``these
pretty women writers, who have split from the solid foundation of
Chinese creative writing and the rich historic and cultural
background of Chinese literature, who know a smattering of
Marguerite Duras and Henry Miller and dare jump onto the stage to
do a striptease, will eventually feel ashamed of themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The book touches on many social issues long taboo in Chinese
litera- ture, from female masturbation to homosexuality. It
includes graphic, if sensitive, descriptions of sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``I strip to my bra and panties in the humid, night breeze from
the Huangpu River. I hope this scene will stimulate Tian Tian. I
continue, like a stripper. `Have a try. Come to me, like a real
lover, honey. Give it a try'.''
</P>
<P>
   Coco's impotent lover eventually dies of a heroin overdose and
her German lover returns to his homeland, leaving her bereft in a
city of vanity and desire.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The book is one of the first in China to portray Weihui's
generation of urban women, born in the 1970s, as they search for
moral grounding in a country of shifting values. In many ways, her
age group's dislocation from China's traditional culture is
reminiscent of the generation gap that characterized the West in
the 1960s _ an era that Weihui evokes with references in her book
to Allen Ginsberg, Bob Dylan, the Beatles and others.
</P>
<P>
   Weihui sees herself as a feminist helping her generation of
women understand themselves. ``This is the first book to tell young
modern girls how to face sex,'' Weihui says. ``I just write the
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   But the truth has always been difficult for China's cultural
mandarins to handle. Nearly two decades ago, China banned the
writings of another woman, Dai Houying, whose novel ``People, Oh
People!'' was among the first books to explore people's emotions
during the Cultural Revolution. Dai's writings, which are now back
in print, were deemed too frank at the time.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   If indeed Weihui was going into seclusion, she was doing it with
as much fanfare as she could muster. She fox-trotted on the veranda
with a spiky-haired woman in a sleeveless blue top as a film crew
and several photographers gyrated around her, recording the moment.
</P>
<P>
   The party felt staged _ the guests were an odd mix of ages and
backgrounds, including the young man who applied her makeup. A tray
of sliced French bread was drying out on a table next to a platter
of coarse cakes covered with whipped nondairy cream. Waitresses in
red skirts, white shirts and limp bow ties served tepid beer, Coke
and red wine. The Lennon Sisters warbled from floor speakers, ``One
day a little girl, the next day a lady,'' in an off-target attempt
to create an atmosphere befitting Weihui's dress and the prewar
bank buildings behind her.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the film crew was working on a documentary that,
combined with a dramatization of Weihui's works, will be sold on
video disk together with her next book, ``Evil Pearl,'' a tragic
story about a woman of Shanghai's demimonde. ``It's about how
desire leads to destruction,'' Weihui said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Weihui is the daughter of an army officer and spent three years
of her childhood living in an army-occupied temple from which the
monks had been expelled during the chaotic Cultural Revolution. She
studied literature at Shanghai's prestigious Fudan University and
has written four previous books: ``The Shriek of the Butterfly,''
``Virgin in the Water,'' ``Crazy Like Weihui'' and ``Desire
Pistol.'' She hopes to publish ``Shanghai Baby'' in Taiwan, Japan
and France.
</P>
<P>
   Off-camera, she exudes an impersonal affability. ``I think I'm
an elegant person,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the evening, she headed home to her mother,
clutching a red silk handbag and a small black cell phone that rang
steadily at 15-minute intervals. Despite her bold stance, the
mounting criticism was taking its toll, touching, perhaps, the
filial emotions of a more tradition-bound woman deep inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I don't know who is right,'' she said. ``Maybe I am
wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
