<HEADLINE>
GROUP WILL PERSIST WITH COKE BOYCOTT 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A group led by a former Coca-Cola benefits manager
said Wednesday that it would press on with a boycott against the
company despite a lack of support from major civil rights
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The former benefits manager, Larry Jones, said that his group,
the Committee for Corporate Justice, which includes some former and
current Coca-Cola employees, will ask Atlanta businesses and
churches to remove Coke vending machines and will distribute
literature at local transit stations. The boycott will then extend
to other major markets, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The group is demanding that the company change what the group
contends is discriminatory treatment of black employees.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who is not among the plaintiffs in the suit, announced
the boycott at the company's annual meeting in Wilmington, Del., on
April 19; Coca-Cola says the action has not had a discernible
impact.
</P>
</TEXT>
