<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OFFICE-SUPPLY-ONLINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN STAGES, THE BOSS' SECRETARY BECOMES A DOT-COM EXECUTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH SCHIESEL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internet revolution has allowed people with unconventional
professional backgrounds to become far more successful far more
quickly than they may have in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes a new way to become a budding cyberspace entrepreneur:
start out as John Sidgmore's secretary. At least it seems to be
working for Paula Jagemann, 34.
</P>
<P>
   Sidgmore, 49, is vice chairman of WorldCom and chief of its
Uunet unit. He has invested in and become chairman of Jagemann's
dot-com venture for the office supply industry, eCommerce
Industries, based in Tysons Corner, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the company, which prefers to be known as ECI2,
intends to announce that it has formed the first electronic
exchange to link office supply manufacturers, wholesalers and
retailers. It also plans to announce the acquisition of two small
private software companies for about $15 million in cash and stock.
</P>
<P>
   The stock of ECI2 has value because the company is also set to
announce a $40 million round of financing from two venture capital
firms, Accel Partners and New Enterprise Associates. One reason
such prominent firms have agreed to invest in ECI2 may be that its
board includes Mory Ejabat, former chief executive of Ascend
Communications, and Dan Rosen, Microsoft's general manager for
Internet research. And perhaps the reason such prominent technology
executives have joined ECI2 's board is Sidgmore. ``Our mission in
life,'' he said, ``is to automate the 15,000 little independent
guys in the office supply business so they can win against the
goliaths like Staples.''
</P>
<P>
   Jagemann, chief executive of ECI2 , added, ``We have the first
electronic platform to really bring the independent dealers up to
speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Sidgmore has had faith in Jagemann for a long time. In 1989, she
became his secretary when he was chief executive of Intelicom
Solutions, a software company. Sidgmore aided her move into
Intelicom's marketing department. She followed him to Uunet a few
years later, where she headed public and investor relations.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Sidgmore is in a somewhat unusual position as chairman of
one of his own customers. ECI2 buys most of its data communications
services from Uunet. But so far, Sidgmore and Bernard J. Ebbers,
WorldCom's chairman, think the arrangement is working.
</P>
<P>
   ``These start-ups are really forging new ground,'' Sidgmore
said, ``and I have felt for awhile, and Bernie agrees, that getting
in the middle of this could be important to WorldCom. And it keeps
me fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 2306EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
