<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-BOOKS-ONLINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANDOM HOUSE AND AUDIBLE INC. AGREE TO SELL DIGITIZED AUDIO BOOKS
ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas)  By DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Random House, the nation's top trade publisher of
popular books, and Audible Inc., an Internet audio company, have
signed an agreement to begin selling digitized audio books online,
the companies plan to announce Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance will create a new imprint, called Random House
Audible, that will try to convince consumers to download audio
material _ ranging from existing Random House books to historical
material such as speeches to new, specialized content like business
books _ from the Web. Listeners would then listen to the books on
their computer or a portable device like an MP3 player.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement marks the first time that a publisher will sell
new audio material through the Web, rather than offering existing
audio books in a digital form as well, said Paul Rush, the
president of both the Audio Publishers Association and Earful of
Books, a Dallas-based chain of stores that sell books on tape.
Random House Audible will be able to release audio books more
quickly _ to respond to a news event, for example _ and will likely
inspire similar moves by other publishers, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``For our industry, it is a major event,'' Rush said.
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Frost, president of Random House's audio publishing group,
said the new imprint will focus on material with a narrower
audience than the company's current list of audio titles. That list
includes books by John Grisham and Danielle Steele and J.K.
Rowling's Harry Potter series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our programming doesn't have to support two inches on a shelf
in a bookstore anymore,'' Frost said.
</P>
<P>
   The new imprint could also serialize books more easily than the
existing audio division, which is Random House's fastest-growing
group, Frost said. For example, Random House Audible would not have
had to wait to release Grisham's recent serialized novel until all
of the chapters had been published, said Jonathan Korzen, a
spokesman for Audible. Books that sell particularly well over the
Web may later be sold as tapes and compacts discs, Korzen said.
</P>
<P>
   The companies expect to sell their first digitized audio book
this summer. The books will typically cost about 20 percent less
than audio books available on tape or CDs, Frost said.
</P>
<P>
   The new kind of books will not be as easy to listen to as the
old version, however. After downloading a book from the Internet,
people will be able to listen to it on their desktop computer, on a
hand-held computer run with Microsoft software or the Diamond
Multimedia Rio MP3 player. But Audible will encrypt the audio
material so that consumers cannot listen to it on a tape player, CD
player or the most popular brand of hand-held computers, 3Com's
Palm, Korzen said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 2309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000510.0373 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1618 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-IOPENER-AD-COLUMN-NYT     05-10 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOPENER-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW NET DEVICE EASY TO USE, BUT SELLING IT NOT AS SIMPLE 
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Texas)  By COURTNEY KANE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is rare in the world of high-technology gadgets to have the
luxury of introducing a product without the concern of immediate
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Netpliance Inc., the maker of the i-Opener _ a simple,
inexpensive device that provides Internet and e-mail access without
a personal computer _ finds itself in such a position, at least for
a little while. So, to take advantage of a wide open marketplace,
the company is introducing a marketing campaign before the battles
begin for dominance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just trying to maximize our first-mover advantage,''
said Bill Cobb, general manager for consumer sales at Netpliance,
which is based in Austin, Texas ``We're not going to worry about
the competition right now. We're just focused on getting our
message out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting the message out and explaining the product are the
second phase of the company's marketing plan after introducing the
device during the Super Bowl. A $13 million campaign, consisting
primarily of print and direct mail, is the first work from BBDO New
York, part of the BBDO Worldwide unit of the Omnicom Group, since
that agency was named to handle the account in February.
</P>
<P>
   As Internet use continues to extend beyond the desktop to
kitchen countertops, there are still plenty of people overwhelmed
by the complexity of even turning on a computer. The i-Opener
appliance and service, which is focused on computer novices 40 and
older, is as easy to use as a microwave. Users can take it out of
the box, plug it in, push a couple of buttons and surf the Web.
</P>
<P>
   But it is less simple to market a consumer-friendly Internet
device to those who have technology phobia. One way, Netpliance and
its agency decided, is to position it as a gift.
</P>
<P>
   One leg of the new campaign is centered on Mother's Day and
Father's Day celebrations. Emotional holidays like those are a
sensible time for marketers to start the communication to find
customers because people are already in the market to buy gifts.
</P>
<P>
   The i-Opener now sells for $99 plus a $21.95 monthly fee to
connect to its Internet service. The device, whose price is
scheduled to rise to $199 after Father's Day, is primarily sold
through the company's call centers or on its Web site, with retail
distribution at stores like Circuit City.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, the i-Opener has the advantage of being the
trailblazer in the Internet appliance category in what some people
are calling the post-PC era. But a host of competitors, including
Compaq, Gateway and IBM, are preparing to offer Internet-only
terminals by summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we have the marketplace to ourselves,'' said Lynne
Seid, who heads the Netpliance account at BBDO New York as
executive vice president and managing director. ``In fact, we are
trying to create our own Christmas now.''
</P>
<P>
   New technology products are traditionally pitched heavily in the
fourth quarter around Christmas, where there tends to be a plethora
of ads from marketers eager to stimulate sales. Netpliance's goals
for the second quarter are to explain the product simply, identify
the best media for the target audience and gain subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   The i-Opener first came on the ad scene in January with what was
meant to be a big splash during Super Bowl XXXIV, but the
commercial ended up getting lost in the blur of dot-com ads.
Although that commercial was amusing and the message was clear, a
month later Netpliance ended up shifting its account to BBDO New
York from McGarrah/Jessee, a small shop in Austin that created the
Super Bowl ad.
</P>
<P>
   Cobb, who joined Netpliance in February, attributed that shift
to his familiarity with BBDO New York from working with that agency
in his previous posts at the Pepsi-Cola Co. unit of PepsiCo and
Tricon Global Restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``McGarrah/Jessee is a fine branding agency, and they got us to
a certain level, but the capability of BBDO as an ad agency and the
additional agency services is so much wider,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cobb noted: ``Phase One of the campaign was really just trying
to get in the game. Now we are in the educational phase.''
</P>
<P>
   From a visual standpoint, the new ads are staid and lack
pizzazz, but BBDO hasn't lost its touch. It's all part of its plan
to speak to its audience in a no-nonsense manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's purposely not edgy like a lot of dot-com advertising you
see,'' Seid said. ``The whole purpose was to look open, accessible
and very plain-spoken and simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not trying to be indirect or cute,'' she added with a
chuckle. ``We are trying to be engaging. Obviously, we are in the
advertising business.''
</P>
<P>
   Two ads with a Mother's Day theme feature a shot of the i-Opener
accompanied by the phrase, ``Introducing i-Opener.'' One headline
reads, ``If you want your mom to stop calling, buy her an
i-Opener.'' A second ad's headline reads, ``Remind your mom why
you're her favorite.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other general advertisements speaking directly to potential
users will run between the two holidays. One headline reads, ``Meet
i-Opener, your soon-to-be significant other.'' Another reads, ``Who
says you can't get through to your kids.'' Each ad elaborates on
the product, provides a toll-free order number and gives the
address of the company's Web site, www.netpliance.com.
</P>
<P>
   Although the ads lack a tagline or some kind of catch phrase,
the unifying factor, besides the stark look in general, is that
they are ``selling an experience,'' Seid said.
</P>
<P>
   For the educational phase of the campaign, the company and
agency decided to leave television out of the mix. That is unusual
because BBDO is known for its lavish television campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot to ask a 30-second commercial to do,'' Seid said,
``in terms of educating a consumer, also having some stopping power
and also registering the basic information so they can respond to
the ad.''
</P>
<P>
   Print, in general, allows companies to focus on their audiences
more precisely. Some of the publications in which i-Opener ads
began running earlier this month include Entertainment Weekly,
People, Time, TV Guide, The New York Times and The Wall Street
Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Future marketing plans for the i-Opener were not disclosed. ``As
we approach a more competitive environment and have lots of
competitors spending a lot of money, we will be looking at what we
will be doing next,'' Seid said.
</P>
<P>
   Being one of the first Net appliances doesn't come without
pitfalls. An engineer recently posted on a Web site instructions
for tweaking the i-Opener hardware so that it could work as a
full-fledged PC. Since then, said Munira Fareed, the marketing
director at Netpliance, the company closed the loophole that
allowed people to make the changes.
</P>
<P>
   But the company can learn from the skills of the ``modifier.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we can get some great R&AMP;D from this,'' Cobb said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 2311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
