<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1622 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NYC-COL-GIULIANI-NYT &LR;      05-10 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-COL-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC COLUMN: WHEN PUBLIC AND PRIVATE COMMINGLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOYCE PURNICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The continuing drama of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's
increasingly public private life is nothing short of astonishing.
</P>
<P>
   What to make of his charged confessional Wednesday at a news
conference in Bryant Park, where, in an emotional, halting voice,
he announced he was seeking a separation from his wife, Donna
Hanover. The mayor spoke most kindly of her. And then, in the next
breath, he conceded how much he needed his recently acknowledged
``very good friend,'' Judith Nathan, in his life _ especially given
his recent diagnosis of prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Visibly shaken, the mayor said the marital estrangement was
``painful, very painful,'' and added that he and Hanover had been
leading separate lives for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   As if that wasn't enough for one day, a few hours later an
equally distraught Hanover held her own news conference to confirm
the impending marital separation and to say that her marriage had
been troubled pre-Nathan because of her husband's relationship with
a ``staff member,'' a reference to the mayor's former
communications director, Cristyne Lategano, said Hanover's
spokeswoman, Joannie Danielides. She and the mayor were long the
center of rumors about their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Lategano, now president of the city's tourism bureau, said that
she did not want to speculate about Hanover's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   The events of the last two weeks, beginning with the mayor's
announcement about his cancer, defy characterization. Clearly he,
his wife, and Nathan are under great stress.
</P>
<P>
   Dealing with cancer is one thing; as noted in this space last
week, most people with treatable cancers want to continue with
their pre-diagnosis lives, and do. But dealing with affairs of the
heart _ in the public eye _ is decidedly more complicated. The
mayor said he wasn't thinking about politics. But everyone else is,
and the obvious question is whether the mayor can survive this
curious, uncomfortable exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Is even New York ready for a candidate who acknowledges
adultery, is accused by his wife of another affair, and brazenly
parades his relationship for months, taking Nathan to public event
after public event, from the St. Patrick's Day Parade to community
meetings?
</P>
<P>
   Many would like to live in a world where public figures were
judged on their public records, not their private conduct. The
public is more open-minded than ever; Bill Clinton's popularity
survived Monica Lewinsky and impeachment. But he was already well
liked. Polls show that even some of Giuliani's supporters have
reservations about his pugnacious temperament _ the tough,
self-righteous image of his own making. Paradoxically, he has never
appeared more vulnerable than he did Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   He has nurtured a harsh reputation throughout his career,
insisting that the public accept his style and values and
succeeding on his own terms much more often than failing. His
unorthodox politics and his stubborn defiance have been his
political identity and strength.
</P>
<P>
   But how does the fierce, moralistic mayor jibe with the married
father of two openly defying classic public morals? The two
personas are in blatant conflict.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to believe that Giuliani really thinks this will
not hurt him. .
</P>
<P>
   But it was just as hard to believe that he blamed Patrick
Dorismond _ an unarmed black man killed in an altercation with
police officers _ for his death; that he didn't care what the press
thought of him; that he let the Lategano rumors hover for years.
</P>
<P>
   Most New Yorkers were offended, but this mayor nonetheless
insisted on punishing the Brooklyn Museum of Art for exhibiting
works he found morally offensive by attempting to deny them city
money. He tried to revise the city charter just to prevent a
politician he disliked _ Mark Green, the public advocate _ from
succeeding him should he move on to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, this is one headstrong man whose every fiber
says, you'll do it my way. That has led to a most remarkable series
of policies and incidents, of which this is surely the most
astounding.
</P>
<P>
   And it will not go away. This is one of those political
phenomena that develop a life of their own. It will get messier. If
there are more peccadilloes to be revealed, they will be. That's
how it works.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, perhaps impelled to go public about his life by a
reminder of his mortality, could triumph. If he does, he will have
changed the course of politics here and maybe across the land.
</P>
<P>
   If he fails, it is hard to see how he could not have committed
political suicide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
