<HEADER>
A1632 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SCHIFF-NABOKOV-ART-NY     05-10 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHIFF-NABOKOV-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIOGRAPHER PEERS, BRIEFLY, AT HER OWN LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., Canada) (ART ADV: Photo NYT27 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOYCE WADLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sleep-deprived _ that's the disclaimer Stacy Schiff,
who's won the Pulitzer for biography, throws over her interview.
She spent five years on her book about the marriage of Vera
Nabokov, but what's concerning her now is her own domestic life.
</P>
<P>
   The new baby is 2 weeks old and nursing, her 7-year-old daughter
has a strep throat, the 8-year-old son's birthday party is coming
up _ ever put together a child's birthday party? _ Schiff, a
breakneck New York speed talker, is saying. Would you like to come
over Saturday and take a shot? She doubts she'll make any sense.
</P>
<P>
   Still, hit her with that annoying question after the nanny
brings coffee into the living room with the piano and the old-money
space: heck of an apartment, off Park, in the 60s. How many rooms?
(Subtext: are you loaded? Schiff will protect herself pretty well.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We have enough to lodge our children.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, c'mon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half the people we know think we have too few bedrooms; half
think we have too many bedrooms.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, finally, charming, for Schiff is very charming: ``Do we
have to go into that?''
</P>
<P>
   You know the scene in ``The Princess Bride'' where two manic
swordsmen go at each other, taking a breather once in a while to
discuss technique? This is how it is when a reporter sits down with
a biographer who is wary of giving it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too boring.'' ``Truly boring.'' Those are the words Schiff,
39, uses when you look into certain parts of her life: the medical
condition that compelled her to remain in bed for her latest
pregnancy; her finances.
</P>
<P>
   She also interviews the interviewer and compares notes: how
about the guilt-provoking pause _ that one work for you? Don't you
just hate it when you have to go back because you've missed the big
question?
</P>
<P>
   She is more forthcoming on Vera Nabokov, the wife of Vladimir
Nabokov, who during their 52-year marriage served as her husband's
agent, editor, secretary and chauffeur.
</P>
<P>
   Why did Schiff, who had previously written a biography of the
French aviator and writer Antoine de Saint-Exupery, not write about
the creative partner?
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that she was the creative one to some extent,'' Ms.
Schiff says. ``I suppose my thesis was the minor player was going
to be very revealing of the major player. I'm trying to remember if
Mrs. Dostoyevsky said to Mrs. Tolstoy or it was the other way
around that a person's character is never so much revealed as in
his day-to-day life at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is what is interesting about Schiff's life at home: the
absence of a husband. She has one, Marc de La Bruyere, a real
estate developer in Edmonton, Alberta. He spends, in what Schiff
cheerfully calls her bizarre life, about 10 days a month in New
York. In the summer and on school holidays, Schiff and the children
join him in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live here; he lives most of the time in Edmonton,'' Schiff
says. ``You might want to ask why.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ever try to leave New York?'' Schiff says in an escalating
comic riff. ``I did once. I lasted about a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always had these great excuses: My agent is five blocks
away. The kids go to school here. It's very cold there. It's really
dark, at the end of the world. Like the Arctic Circle.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time for the nanny to bring in the baby to nurse, and while we
courteously avert our eyes, Schiff's background:
</P>
<P>
   Despite the swank apartment, she is not a member of the powerful
and rich New York Schiff family. She comes from the small mill town
of Adams, Mass. Her mother taught at North Adams State College, and
her father owned a clothing store in the Berkshires. They were one
of three Jewish families in the county. ``Looking back, I think it
was just a little alienating,'' Schiff says. ``Why do you think I'm
always writing about refugees, people out of sync?''
</P>
<P>
   Schiff describes herself as ``an obstreperous child.'' When her
parents tried to get her into boarding schools, she intentionally
fell asleep in the car and would not leave. Later, she graduated
from Phillips Andover Academy, then Williams College. She came to
New York and worked as a book editor. The next book project will be
Ben Franklin, the Paris years.
</P>
<P>
   End of visit. A few hours later one realizes there is, in this
interview, one of those awful enormous holes: the wife Tolstoy or
Dostoyevsky has said that domestic life reveals character. What
does Schiff's unconventional domestic life reveal?
</P>
<P>
   Schiff, phone in hand, nursing the newborn, takes a pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll let you do this one,'' she says. ``You could say I was
ultra culpable; you could say I was the poor neglected party. I
seem to be the poor neglected party. Marc is coming back _ did I
mention that?''
</P>
<P>
   But meanwhile, not counting the nanny, she is alone with three
young children, one of whom is a 2-week-old. ``Don't think that
didn't get into the conversation,'' Schiff says. `` `Darling,
everyone has strep, and the one that doesn't have strep is 2 weeks
old.'''
</P>
<P>
   Character, Schiff. What does this reveal?
</P>
<P>
   ``You could say you have two stubborn people here. You could say
there is a certain resistance to giving up one's identity. Have you
ever been married? Had that thing of someone calling you by a name
not your own? It's unsettling. It's like a fictitious person.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
