<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-FLAG-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPROMISE WOULD REMOVE CONFEDERATE FLAG FROM S.C. STATEHOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: LEADS with Representatives reaching compromise; 2nd take to
follow.) 
By DAVID FIRESTONE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ The battle flag of the Confederacy, which has
divided South Carolina from its perch atop the statehouse since
1962, will come off the dome on July 1, under a tentative
compromise reached late Wednesday night by the state House of
Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, which has already been approved with minor differences
by the Senate, calls for a smaller, square version of the flag to
be placed on a flagpole near the front of the Capitol, adjacent to
a Confederate soldiers' memorial. House leaders and senators
predicted few difficulties in ironing out the differences, and Gov.
Jim Hodges has said he will sign the bill.
</P>
<P>
   But the bill will by no means end the racial acrimony that
created such pressure for a compromise in the first place. Only
three of 26 black members of the House voted for the bill, and many
denounced it furiously as a plan that would make the flag an even
more prominent feature of the state's official landscape. The
NAACP, which has been conducting a national economic boycott of the
state to get the flag removed, has said the plan is unacceptable,
and has vowed to continue the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Once the flag comes off the dome and out of the spotlight,
however, it is unclear how effective the boycott, which has hurt
the state's tourism industry, will be. The NAACP had originally
said the boycott would continue until the flag was lowered from the
dome, and its opponents are now accusing it of changing its goals
because the group was not a participant in the compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the flag's longtime supporters said the move was a
historic step forward for the state, which saw its reputation
severely tarnished by the flag's presence in such a prominent
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a defining moment for our state, a giant step
forward,'' said David Wilkins, the speaker of the House, who had
pushed hard for a compromise.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
