A1637 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-RAILYARD-KILLER-HNS &LR;      05-10 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAILYARD-KILLER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAILYARD SUSPECT THOUGHT HE WAS `HALF ANGEL, HALF MAN,' EXPERT
SAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LISA TEACHEY 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ An expert called by the defense testified Wednesday
that Angel Maturino Resendiz is a paranoid schizophrenic with
religious delusions who believed he was ``half angel, half man''
when evil forces sent him on his cross-country killing rampage.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendiz, 40, has admitted to the December 1998 slaying
and rape of Dr. Claudia Benton at her West University home near
Houston, as well as brutally killing five other people in Texas,
two in Illinois and one in Kentucky over a two-year period.
</P>
<P>
   He has pleaded not guilty by reason of insanity to capital
murder in Benton's death. Under Texas law, a jury can only find
someone legally insane if he had a severe mental disorder and could
not tell right from wrong when the crime was committed.
</P>
<P>
   The state rested its case against Maturino Resendiz on Tuesday
after linking the railcar-hopping transient to the Benton case
through fingerprints, DNA and stolen items recovered from his home
in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys began Wednesday by questioning Dr. Larry
Pollack, a Houston neuropsychologist they hired to examine Maturino
Resendiz in the Harris County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   Pollock's testimony and intense cross-examination by prosecutor
Lyn McClellan was followed by the testimony of four of Maturino
Resendiz's siblings about their brother's troubled childhood and
bizarre beliefs as a young man in which he likened himself to a
biblical prophet.
</P>
<P>
   Pollock, who examined Maturino Resendiz for three days in
October, said the Mexican national was schizophrenic, but tests did
not prove he was a psychopath.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man is extremely paranoid,'' Pollock said. ``He believes
things about the world that are unverifiable to anyone else ... he
has a crazy delusional perception of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Schizophrenia is a mental disorder causing delusions and
irrational thinking. A psychopath has no conscience.
</P>
<P>
   Tests determined Maturino Resendiz has an above-average IQ,
Pollock said, but a neurological exam found a brain impairment that
could explain why he suffered from confused, disorganized logic.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of his heinous acts, Pollock said, Maturino Resendiz
was likable, even when he went into wild, unsolicited diatribes on
politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you didn't know what we know about him, you'd have thought
he was a very nice man,'' Pollock said. ``He was a very nice person
when he talked about his daughter, in a crazy way.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollock also said Maturino Resendiz thought he could cause
earthquakes, floods and explosions, believed he eluded authorities
by making himself invisible and traveled in his sleep from his jail
cell to visit his wife.
</P>
<P>
   When he surrendered to Texas Rangers at the Mexican border in
July, he knew he would be executed, Pollock said. But he believed
his death would cause everyone involved, including the judge and
jurors, to die, then he would be resurrected because he was
immortal.
</P>
<P>
   When he killed, Maturino Resendiz believed he was an angel
following God's will, Pollock said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was something at the time he was near those homes that
triggered him,'' Pollock said. ``I don't know what those things
were. ... He was overwhelmed by a sense of evil. His mission was to
destroy them.''
</P>
<P>
   But McClellan countered by asking if those same evil forces had
also told him to rape his dead or dying victims or steal valuables
from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He felt an evil force pulling him into these homes and
directing him to people who were evil and deserved to be dead, and
as an angel of God he was doing God's will,'' Pollock said, adding
the sexual assaults were ``bizarre behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   When McClellan asked how Maturino Resendiz could claim to be
guided simultaneously by evil forces and God's will, Pollock said
paranoid schizophrenics often exhibit contradictory behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're trying to make it logical, and this is one of the most
illogical diseases known to mankind,'' Pollock said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Or,'' McClellan responded, ``it's the most illogical
explanation someone has come up with.''
</P>
<P>
   He asked if Maturino Resendiz could be using schizophrenia as a
cover for violent anti-social behavior and really did know right
from wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew society may judge him as wrong,'' Pollock said, ``but
in his heart he knows he was right.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
