r f BC-GERMANY-REAGANOMICS-W     05-10 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-REAGANOMICS-WORTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETOOLING THE OLD `GERMAN MODEL' ECONOMY  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Business Editors)   (This 600-word ``separate-buy'' financial story is from the May
2000 issue of ``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this article, it must
be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been double-filed _ into the ``a''
general news and ``f'' financial news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By TODD G. BUCHHOLZ  
 c.2000 Worth Magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   When Bill Clinton campaigned for the U.S. presidency in 1992, he
applauded the ``German model,'' highlighting the intimate links
between banks, unions, corporations, and government.
</P>
<P>
   But, after Clinton moved into the White House, he soon learned
that the German economic model was falling apart, and that the U.S.
economy was in fact far healthier and sturdier than Germany's.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992, America's robust economy has created millions of new
jobs, while Germans have sat around in their lederhosen waiting for
their own economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Now Clinton travels the globe bragging about the ``American
model'' of open markets, aggressive competition, and tight fiscal
budgets.
</P>
<P>
   But Germany may be getting its economic house in order. After
years of painfully high unemployment, the country is creating jobs.
The jobless rate has been falling the past two years, down to 10.1
percent recently from a peak of 11.8 percent in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Although that is still ridiculously high when compared with the
4 percent jobless rate in the U.S. and U.K., it's still progress.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the German stock market has caught more than a
whiff of optimism. Its benchmark DAX index leaped 39 percent in
1999 and was up 10.1 percent during the first seven weeks of this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics will point out that the euro has skidded during the
past year, losing some 16 percent of its value against the U.S.
dollar. Clearly, European leaders and central bankers haven't quite
earned the respect of world financial markets, but a cheaper euro
has been great for German exporters.
</P>
<P>
   The big electronics firm Siemens can compete much better against
Motorola and IBM if it is charging lower prices. And those swank
new Mercedes-Benz cars look less expensive to Americans when
they're being built by German workers paid in euros.
</P>
<P>
   There's more to the German rebound than its cheap currency.
Ironically, what's driving the recovery is the breakdown of the
German model of cozy relations among the country's industrial
giants, banks, and insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, every major company seemed to own a piece of each
other, in a ``you scratch my back, I'll scratch yours'' system,
with the same 60-year-old men sitting on every important board of
directors.
</P>
<P>
   While this world of complex cross-holdings kept matters
peaceful, it hindered the intense competition that drives
innovation. Mergers, takeovers, and shareholder rebellions were far
too rare.
</P>
<P>
   If a company needed money to build a new factory, it would just
go to its affiliate bank for a loan. No need to borrow from the
bond market or issue public stock; heaven forbid _ that would
require justifying its finances to the public. And shareholders
came last. More important were executive perks and union support.
</P>
<P>
   In a millennial twist, it is the left-wing government of
Chancellor Gerhard Schroder that is now dragging German businesses
into the Western world of heated competition.
</P>
<P>
   His Social Democrat Party, in a coalition with the
pro-environment Green Party, is slashing corporate capital-gains
taxes to encourage firms to spin off their cross-holdings without
having to pay punitive taxes. In addition, Schroder's government
proposes to slash individual income taxes, even for the wealthiest
Germans.
</P>
<P>
   With a cheap currency and a bonanza of tax cuts, the German
economy should grow at least 3 percent in 2000. This is
Reaganomics, twenty years after Reagan, albeit with a leftist tilt.
</P>
<P>
   For Germans, the 21st century is getting off to a strange but
promising start. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Contributing editor Todd G. Buchholz, president of
Victoria Capital, is the author of ``Market Shock.'') &LR;  &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
