<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY BRACES FOR SHAKEUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Six of Luis Hernandez's Galaxy jerseys are
already waiting for him in the team's Rose Bowl locker room, and
Major League Soccer is expected to announce later this week that it
has signed a transfer agreement with the Mexican club team Tigres
for Hernandez's services.
</P>
<P>
   But the news isn't all good for the Galaxy. Team officials told
Clint Mathis, Joey Franchino and Roy Myers at Wednesday's practice
that they will be sent to other teams in order to make the deal
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will definitely be a transition period with the players
leaving on behalf of acquiring Hernandez,'' said Galaxy defender
Paul Caligiuri. ``To acquire a top star like Hernandez in his prime
and with his goal-scoring abilities is definitely a bonus for the
league and this team but it did come with a cost.''
</P>
<P>
   MLS executive vice president Ivan Gazidis refused to comment,
but Galaxy head coach Sigi Schmid admitted it is all but done. ``We
sort of informed them of what's supposed to happen if everything
finalizes itself,'' said Schmid of the three players.
</P>
<P>
   If Hernandez, Mexico's top striker and contributor during the
1998 World Cup in France, signs today or Friday, he could be in
uniform for the Galaxy's game in Dallas on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis and Franchino said their goodbyes to teammates.
Franchino, 23, a graduate of Damien High School in La Verne, said
he would go to the New England Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis, 23, is having an all-star year (three goals and an
assist) after signing a multi-year contract with the league last
month. He said he would go to the New York/New Jersey MetroStars,
where he will be reunited with former Galaxy coach Octavio
Zambrano.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear where Myers is heading but the Galaxy will have
to release the 31-year-old midfielder. Myers will likely be
reassigned to another team as a foreign allocation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I was told I will go to New England,'' said Franchino,
the most emotional of the three. ``I'm pretty sure this is my last
practice. The toughest part is walking out of here because I've
been with these guys for three years and they're good people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They way I look at it, this is an opportunity to further my
career,'' said Mathis. ``New York hasn't been doing as well as they
hoped, so if this happens, hopefully I can help turn them around.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, an international star with his recognizable long
flowing blonde hair, is Mexico's most marketable and talented
player. Only 31, ``El Matador,'' as he's known in Mexico, will
attract a large Mexican contingent to the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The big question for the Galaxy, however, is how will this
affect the team. Hernandez will replace Mathis on the front line
and team with Cobi Jones. UCLA rookie standout Sasha Victorine will
step in for Myers as an attacking midfielder. And Caligiuri will
replace Franchino as the team's outside left back.
</P>
<P>
   The starting lineup doesn't look like it will suffer, but the
Galaxy's strength has been its depth, which now will be tested.
When one factors in that Carlos Hermosillo left the team after the
1999 season, leaving a foreign allocation spot for Hernandez, it
looks on paper like the Galaxy is giving up four players to get
Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   This is a situation the Galaxy has wrestled with. Basically, MLS
told the Galaxy it was pursuing Hernandez and that when a deal was
finalized, the Galaxy would have to make three players available.
That was the only way to free up salary cap space and move Los
Angeles ahead of San Jose and New England to get the next foreign
allocation.
</P>
</TEXT>
