r f BC-IBC-POSSIBILITIES-KAN     05-10 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IBC-POSSIBILITIES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERSTATE BAKERIES REIMPLEMENTS POISON PILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Interstate Bakeries Corp.'s on-again, off-again poison pill is
back on again.
</P>
<P>
   The company reimplemented a so-called shareholders rights plan
Tuesday, eight months after one was first put in place and about
three months after it was dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Interstate dissolved its first poison pill after several months
of fruitless discussions with Ralston Purina Corp., which owns
about 40 percent of Interstate's stock. Ralston Purina got the big
stake in Interstate when it sold Continental Baking Co. to
Interstate five years ago in a stock and cash deal.
</P>
<P>
   Interstate originally implemented a poison pill amid rumblings
on Wall Street that a competitor might pursue the company. Such
plans are designed to make it difficult for outside interests to
take over a company.
</P>
<P>
   The company was particularly vulnerable after its stock price
took a big one-day hit in October 1998, after Interstate warned
that earnings were going to fall short of analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The stock never recovered, and continued to go down as the
company experienced more problems, including more missed earnings
targets, operating problems at a new plant, an eight-day Teamsters
strike that took product off shelves in a wide swath of the
Northeast and higher fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding Interstate's depressed stock price was a provision
that Ralston Purina had to reduce its stake in Interstate from
almost 40 percent to less than 15 percent by Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Ralston Purina balked at having to sell so much of its stock
when Interstate's stock price was so low. As a result, the two
returned to the table and worked out an agreement whereby Ralston
Purina would reduce its holdings in Interstate over a much longer
period in hopes that Interstate's stock price would rise.
Interstate has the right of first refusal on all Ralston Purina
shares.
</P>
<P>
   The new poison pill, like the first one, is triggered if someone
buys 15 percent or more of Interstate's stock and makes a tender
offer. If that happens, each existing shareholder except the group
making the offer has the right to receive one share of preferred
stock for each share of common stock already owned.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether the new plan had any substantial
differences from the original poison pill.
</P>
<P>
   All of Interstate's top management, including Chairman Charles
Sullivan, was out of town and could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Ralston Purina said he could not comment on the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell Pinheiro, an analyst with Janney Montgomery Scott, said
Interstate clearly continued to feel exposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, they feel the value of this company is a lot
higher, even more than perhaps a premium a hostile player would pay
for the company,'' Pinheiro said.
</P>
<P>
   The poison pill would not stop a suitor from pursuing
Interstate, but would force it to deal directly with the company's
board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   In a news release, Sullivan said: ``The (plan is) designed to
assure that all of IBC's shareholders receive fair and equal
treatment in the event of any proposed takeover of the company and
to guard against partial tender offers, squeeze-outs, open market
accumulations and other abusive tactics to gain control of IBC
without paying all shareholders a more equitable value.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinheiro said the one name he heard bandied about as a possible
suitor was Bimbo Bakeries US, the U.S. division of the largest
baking company in Mexico. The company has a small presence in the
United States, but would like to have a larger one.
</P>
<P>
   Another scenario is that Sullivan and other top management could
take the company private.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the company's top managers and directors have been
actively buying Interstate stock, including Sullivan, President
Michael Kafoure, and Vice President and Controller John McKenny.
</P>
<P>
   Interstate's stock is trading around $14. If a group of managers
made a leveraged buyout, they probably would pay somewhere around
$22 a share, Pinheiro said. That would give Interstate a takeout
price of about $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're generating about $150 million each year in free cash
flow, so that would give them enough to service the debt, although
they probably wouldn't want to leverage it that much,'' Pinheiro
said.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, he said, Interstate could bring in a partner.
Ralston, which already owns a huge chunk of Interstate, would be
the most logical one, Pinheiro said.
</P>
<P>
   And what would be the motivation for going private?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, first the dislike of being a public company,'' Pinheiro
said. ``I don't think Chuck Sullivan likes being a public company
too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my view, going private is a possibility, but one that seems
to be driven by frustration of the stock price and the fickle
nature of Wall Street and not driven perhaps by strategic
thinking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 2321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000510.0388 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1645 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MICROSOFT--BREAKUP-SF     05-10 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT--BREAKUP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT REJECTS BREAKUP PLAN  &HT;     BY HENRY NORR
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Conceding almost nothing in the government's antitrust case,
Microsoft yesterday adamantly rejected not only the idea of
breaking it in two but also the restrictions on its conduct
proposed by the Department of Justice two weeks ago.
<P>
   The software Goliath offered its own list of alternative
remedies, including changes to its business practices that would
give PC-makers more freedom to customize their products. But Bill
Neukom, Microsoft's chief lawyer, reserved the company's right to
appeal the final judgment even if Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson
agrees to its proposals to the letter.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, Microsoft called on the judge to dismiss the
government's bid to break it into separate companies. Calling the
demand ``unprecedented,'' ``unwarranted'' and ``punitive,'' the
company argued that would have ``horrendous'' effects on consumers,
the computer industry and the American economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our company will not be broken up,'' declared Microsoft Chief
Executive Officer Steve Ballmer. ``It will not happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department, supported by 17 state attorneys general,
had proposed splitting Microsoft into two companies, one based on
the Windows operating-system business and the other taking over the
remaining Microsoft products, including its Internet Explorer Web
browser and its popular Office application suite.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs also proposed ``conduct remedies,'' including a
requirement that Microsoft allow other companies to examine the
``source code,'' or programming instructions, underlying Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft flatly rejected the request. Ballmer said in a
statement that ``the government's so-called conduct and disclosure
remedies are just as damaging to the company and just as bad for
consumers as their breakup demand.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of the six documents Microsoft filed yesterday in
response to the government proposals, it declared that the
disclosure proposal ``would constitute a wholesale confiscation of
Microsoft's intellectual property _ the company's crown jewels.''
</P>
<P>
   What the software company did offer was a list of changes to its
business practices that it said would correct the abuses Jackson
found in earlier rulings. In April, Jackson ruled that Microsoft
had used its monopoly position in the operating systems' market to
stifle innovation and hurt consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Under its plan, the company would agree:
</P>
<P>
   _To allow PC manufacturers to delete the Internet Explorer icon
from the Windows desktop and Start menu, to make a non-Microsoft
browser the default program for Web access, to display icons for
non-Microsoft programs and to offer their own Internet sign-up
routine when the computer is first turned on.
</P>
<P>
   _Not to enter into contracts to promote any product or service
in exchange for the other party agreeing to limit distribution of
non-Microsoft programs.
</P>
<P>
   _To disclose equally to all software developers timely and
complete access to technical information, and not to condition such
disclosures on developers agreeing not to create products for
computing platforms that compete with Microsoft's.
</P>
<P>
   _Not to withhold Microsoft programs for other platforms in order
to force the vendor of the competing platform to limit its product
plans. That restriction, however, would apply only to Microsoft
programs ``ready for commercial release,'' not to any that might be
under consideration or development.
</P>
<P>
   _Not to raise prices on the previous version of Windows after it
releases a major upgrade. In the past, Microsoft has raised the
price of earlier versions to push PC manufacturers and users to
adopt its new releases.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of MICROSOF (78159 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``We think these proposals are incorrect both as to the facts of
the case and appropriate remedies,'' said California Attorney
General Bill Lockyer, one of the plaintiffs in the case. ``We
continue to see Microsoft saying they really didn't do anything
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly settlement `lite,''' said Richard Gilbert, a
professor at the University of California at Berkeley, who served
as chief economist of the Justice Department's antitrust division
earlier in the Clinton administration. ``There's not a lot here
that Microsoft hasn't already agreed not to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there's a gulf, a very large gulf, between the
government's proposals and these,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But William Kovacic, an antitrust expert at George Washington
University in Washington, D.C., said Microsoft's proposal ``does
address a number of the judge's specific concerns'' as reflected in
Jackson's courtroom comments, findings of fact and conclusions of
law.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was wise for Microsoft to offer these proposals,'' Kovacic
said. ``It's a way to focus attention on the conduct issues, as
opposed to a breakup.''
</P>
<P>
   Rich Gray, founder and principal of Outside General Counsel in
Menlo Park, said he found Microsoft's brief against the
government's breakup proposal much stronger than he'd expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``After reading their brief I'm pretty persuaded that even if
they can't persuade Judge Jackson on the breakup remedy, they are
very likely to win that issue on appeal,'' Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Miller, a San Francisco antitrust attorney who served as the
lead counsel in the Justice Department's 1994 case against
Microsoft, said that Microsoft's proposal overlaps with the
government's concerns about its conduct. ``In that sense,'' he
said, ``there is certainly some common ground now. The question is
whether that common ground is broad enough to satisfy the
Department of Justice and the states.''
</P>
<P>
   ``From all indications, it isn't,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the judge decides Microsoft's concessions would
effectively prevent the kinds of abuses he has found in its past
behavior, according to Miller, he might not consider them adequate
remedies. Supreme Court precedents, he said, clearly establish that
a judge who has found violations of the Sherman Anti-Trust Act can
not only prohibit the conduct that violates the law, but also take
measures to restore competition in the affected markets and ``fence
in'' the monopolist so it can't commit other violations in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Judge Jackson has offered few clues at to the remedies
he considers appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs will respond next Wednesday to Microsoft's latest
filings. An open hearing on possible remedies is scheduled for May
24.
</P>
<P>
   If the judge were to accept its proposals, Microsoft attorney
Neukom said in a post-filing press conference, the case could be
settled as early as this month _ unless, of course, Microsoft were
to appeal even that outcome.
</P>
<P>
   If the judge is considering farther-reaching remedies, Microsoft
said in its filings yesterday, he should change the schedule to
allow it more time to prepare for the next phase of the case.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the company said, it should have until December 4
to prepare if the judge is considering breaking it up. If he
rejects that idea but entertains the possibility of requiring it to
disclose its source code, Microsoft would need until October 2 to
prepare, according to the filing.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's proposal includes an offer to pay attorneys' fees
for the 19 states that were plaintiffs in the case, but apparently
not to cover the Justice Department's costs.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of MICROSOF (78159 ) &QL; 
