<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVE EMPLOYEES WHAT THEY WANT, AND THEY'LL STICK AROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Well, knock me over with a feather.
Organizations that offer the most sought-after employee benefits
are the most effective at getting and keeping employees.
</P>
<P>
   Management consultants Bud Burgess and Don Feltham kept hearing
a plea from their Kansas City area clients: Help me recruit and
retain good workers.
</P>
<P>
   They knew there was no silver bullet. Still, they reasoned,
there are places right here where the annual staff turnover rate is
below the national 15 percent to 20 percent norm. What do they do
that others don't?
</P>
<P>
   The Burgess &AMP; Associates crew worked up a survey this spring,
mailed it to nearly 400 area businesses, got 65 responses and
picked apart the returns. The conclusion:
</P>
<P>
   ``Low-turnover organizations are doing a better job than
high-turnover organizations of providing what their existing
workers want,'' Feltham said.
</P>
<P>
   The consultants were not shocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The low-turnover places really take care of the people they
have working for them now. They know their people talk. They know
their existing people are their best referral agents,'' Burgess
said. (They define low turnover as an annual rate of 12 percent or
less.)
</P>
<P>
   The low-turnover organizations said flexible scheduling was
their most effective benefit. Also, in the cafeteria of employee
benefit offerings, the lowest-turnover companies put more on the
buffet.
</P>
<P>
   Out of 46 recruitment and retention tactics in the poll, the
typical low-turnover company offered 60 percent to 70 percent of
the benefits choices. The typical high-turnover company used only
30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   After massaging the data, the consultants came close to assaying
that magic bullet for getting and keeping workers. Some
ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   - Flexible scheduling.
</P>
<P>
   - Referral bonuses for employees who recommend new hires.
</P>
<P>
   - Subsidized transportation and parking.
</P>
<P>
   - Casual dress code.
</P>
<P>
   - Liberal internal job-posting and job-changing policies.
</P>
<P>
   - Job-offer decisions made (and revealed) after the applicant's
first visit.
</P>
<P>
   - Subsidized health care.
</P>
<P>
   The local findings dovetail with national results. Hewitt
Associates, the nation's largest employee benefits consulting firm,
surveyed 1,020 major U.S. employers last year.
</P>
<P>
   To ``remain competitive in today's war for talent,'' employers
must ``offer attractive benefits that enable employees to better
balance their work and personal lives,'' Hewitt concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Benefits listed were flexible scheduling; child- and elder-care
assistance; adoption benefits; on-site concierge, banking, dry
cleaning and travel services; discount purchases; casual dress;
financial advice programs; professional growth and training,
including tuition reimbursement and on- and off-site seminars; and
liberal family- and medical-leave policies.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, those are big-company kinds of benefits. But all
employers need to understand the competitive employment market.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a question of whether employers can afford such
benefits; it's whether their competitors can _ and whether they can
afford not to.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
