<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1648 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-HOTELS--SFCHRON &LR;      05-10 2367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOTELS--SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOTELS FOR THE MENTALLY ILL 
 &HT;     BY DAVID LAZARUS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You probably wouldn't give Lawrence a second glance.
</P>
<P>
   He keeps to himself as he goes about his business, attending
classes in African American history at City College of San
Francisco, walking to school from his little room in the
downtrodden Graystone Hotel on Geary Street.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence seldom speaks to other students. He does not interact
with other hotel residents. ``I'm pretty withdrawn'' is his
explanation for his behavior.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Lawrence is a product of both modern medicine _ his
schizophrenia controlled by daily doses of anti-psychotics and mood
stabilizers _ and the latest thinking on how a city can better
handle the heaviest users of its mental health system by getting
them out of institutions and into the community.
</P>
<P>
   Financially, the experimental program begun by San Francisco in
1997 is a glowing success. The annual cost of housing and treating
the 400 mentally ill individuals brought most frequently to San
Francisco General Hospital has dropped from about $24 million to $8
million.
</P>
<P>
   That success may now make the so-called Program for Assertive
Community Treatment, or PACT, the city's best bet for managing its
population of mentally ill residents as cutbacks loom at San
Francisco General. A city budget shortage could soon lead to
elimination of 21 of the 87 beds in the hospital's psychiatric
ward.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the clear monetary benefits of PACT, the reality of
the program is that Lawrence and people like him are the exception.
For most participants, days are spent in an unsupervised pursuit of
spare change and cheap drugs, and few have shown a willingness or
ability to play a more active role in society.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, you hope you've gained one inch in the
long road toward bringing these people back into society _ one
little inch,'' said John Mitchell, a registered nurse at Community
Focus, the largest of three PACT projects in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Run by the University of California at San Francisco, Community
Focus accounts for half of the 400 people in the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating,'' Mitchell said. ``In many cases, the most
we can expect is that they'll have a roof over their head and three
meals a day and be clothed. And that's progress.''
</P>
<P>
   A morning spent with Mitchell as he made his rounds of
Tenderloin hotels illustrated the difficulty of the job as well the
pluses and minuses of housing the city's mentally ill in downtown
residential hotels.
</P>
<P>
   He began just after 8 a.m. at the Graystone, where two clients,
Clinton and Donald, were waiting outside for their daily medication
and, more important, envelopes containing the few dollars that
would be their spending money for the day.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Quieting Interior Voices
</P>
<P>
   Clinton received 13 pills in a rainbow of colors _ a
pharmaceutical cocktail to keep him calm, rational and undisturbed
by the voices in his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to sleep after I take them,'' he said after swallowing
all the pills in one big gulp. ``I like sleeping during the day.
I'm up all night.''
</P>
<P>
   After running a comb through Donald's hair to check for head
lice, Mitchell proceeded past the Graystone's ``No visitors'' sign
and into the hotel, where dark, foul-smelling rooms go for about
$500 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Fred in Room 608 told Mitchell that he would not be taking his
medication that day because he was fasting ``for religious
reasons.'' Mitchell, as per PACT rules, did not argue the point,
handing Fred his pills for later, along with his money.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always got a reason,'' Mitchell said as he headed down
the hallway. ``He's manic depressive, and manic depressives don't
like medicine because it brings them off their high.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred would be up most of the night, Mitchell predicted,
``getting louder and louder.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of HOTELS10 (35664 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; sh1  &LR; Another Hotel to Cover
</P>
<P>
   He went quickly through the other rooms on his list and then
headed over to the Columbia Hotel at the corner of O'Farrell and
Taylor streets. Henry in Room 612 had the window closed and
curtains drawn as he chain-smoked in a wooden chair by the bed.
</P>
<P>
   As Henry swallowed his pills, Mitchell quietly explained that
Henry, a manic depressive, had been born into money but had
squandered his family's fortune on call girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lived my whole life in San Francisco,'' Henry said
bitterly. ``I hate this city. It hasn't done anything for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the hall, Mitchell doled out medicine and money to Willie,
a flirtatious transvestite whose room was covered floor to ceiling
with magazine pictures of men and women in suggestive poses.
</P>
<P>
   Willie is one of the few in the program with an activity outside
the hotel. He serves as an assistant to the art therapist at
Mitchell's clinic on Market Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't for us working with him real hard, he'd be in a
hospital 12 months a year,'' Mitchell said. ``He's one of our
success stories.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Program Created in 1972
</P>
<P>
   Versions of PACT have been around for nearly three decades,
since the idea was first introduced in Madison, Wis., in 1972. San
Francisco's version is also known in bureaucratic circles as the
Single Point of Responsibility program.
</P>
<P>
   The basic concept is simple: Hospitalization costs can go down
and quality of life for patients can go up by moving the mentally
ill out of institutions and back into society, where they will be
attended to on a daily basis by nurses and social workers.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Wisconsin, PACT-type initiatives have been adopted in
Delaware, Idaho, Michigan, Rhode Island and Texas. Pilot programs
are under way in Hawaii, Massachusetts, Minnesota and Virginia, as
well as in California.
</P>
<P>
   The National Alliance for the Mentally Ill, a leading advocacy
group, is pushing for every state to adopt the PACT system by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``The research by and large shows that the PACT model can reduce
hospitalization,'' said Dr. Robert Okin, chief of psychiatry at San
Francisco General Hospital. ``It has the capacity to stabilize
patients in the community.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Miracle Cures Not Expected
</P>
<P>
   ``Stabilize'' _ that is the key word here. No one expects
miracle cures or even that a majority of PACT participants will
become functioning members of society.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the program is designed to place patients on something
close to an even keel, to get them to take their medication each
day and, through a long-term relationship with caregivers, to
address the more excessive aspects of their disorders.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, though, PACT participants _ the program is
voluntary _ frequently withdraw into their hotel rooms, emerging
onto the street only to panhandle or buy drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the PACT model, the client's wishes are incorporated into
the plan,'' said Bea Stephens, executive director of San
Francisco's Westside Community Mental Health Center, which also has
a PACT contract with the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a clinician, I may think a client needs a more supervised
environment,'' she said. ``But the client may choose to have more
independence.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Addiction Common
</P>
<P>
   Not coincidentally, Stephens said, as many as 60 percent of
participants in Westside's PACT have ``addiction issues.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the most singular barrier we have to
integrating enrollees into the community,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Community Focus' Mitchell also observed that drug use is
prevalent among PACT participants and that many turn to panhandling
or prostitution to support their habits.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of HOTELS10 (35664 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``It's a lifestyle of choice,'' he said. ``They do a little
panhandling, get a little disability money, and the streets are
their kingdom.''
</P>
<P>
   The burnout is evident in Mitchell's eyes _ a fairly common
consequence for those who make a living by treating the mentally
ill. He said he was willing to speak candidly about PACT only
because he will be leaving the program soon to look after his
father, who has cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better to have these people in the community,'' Mitchell
said. ``But not all of them. Some people need four walls and a
locked door.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Fewer Hospital Beds
</P>
<P>
   There are fewer walls and doors available, though. The state
hospital in Napa County now accepts only a handful of patients from
San Francisco. San Francisco General, meanwhile, could end up with
just 66 beds in its four dormitorylike psychiatric wards, which
divide patients along ethnic, gender or cultural lines.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere in the San Francisco General wards is
surprisingly quiet _ it is no ``Cuckoo's Nest'' _ but there is also
the general sense of ennui among inhabitants that comes with being
shut inside for weeks at a time.
</P>
<P>
   So great is demand for space in the wards that the hospital
turns away as many as 100 people a month brought in by police for
being a threat to themselves or others.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital's Okin was frank about where the mentally ill can
end up: an institution, jail, the street or PACT.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point,'' he said, ``society has to make the decision
about what it's going to do with its most disabled, least
functional members.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; San Francisco a Magnet
</P>
<P>
   And San Francisco, with its gentle climate and relatively
generous social-support network, will remain a magnet for such
people, placing an ever-growing burden on the city's resources,
Okin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the federal government abandons people who are the
most disadvantaged and disturbed, those parts of society that are
most humane will inadvertently be asked to shoulder the greatest
share of the burden,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest wild card for PACT's future in San Francisco is the
residential hotels. Although city ordinances bar most such hotels
from being converted to other uses, the stock of available rooms is
limited, and few restrictions prevent owners from raising rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rates will be what the market will bear,'' said Sam Patel,
owner of the Mission Hotel and co-manager of two other downtown
hotels.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, he said, this means most residential hotel
occupants pay between $100 and $150 a week for their rooms. But as
downtown property values continue to rise, Patel said, it is likely
that these rates will increase.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Housing a Major Need
</P>
<P>
   ``The Achilles' heel of the program is how many people it can
accommodate,'' said Steven Segal, director of mental health
research for the School of Social Welfare at the University of
California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to see how the housing stock will keep pace with
need,'' said Marc Trotz, director of housing development for the
San Francisco Department of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rising rents in San Francisco are a threat to any
low-income person,'' he said. ``It's a unique challenge to anyone
working with poor people in this town.''
</P>
<P>
   For PACT, this challenge is exacerbated by the fact that it must
compete for limited space in the residential hotels with other city
programs for homeless and low-income people.
</P>
<P>
   To make more rooms available, the city has taken the unusual
step of leasing six residential hotels in the past year, including
two leased through the Department of Public Health, which oversees
PACT.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Rising Rent at Private Hotels
</P>
<P>
   But most PACT participants continue to be housed in privately
run hotels and, in some cases, already are seeing most of their
monthly $700 disability checks go to pay the rent.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 3 of HOTELS10 (35664 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``We're quite worried about how the housing market will affect
clients' lives,'' said Joanne Wile, director of Community Focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you exactly what's going to happen,'' said Randy
Shaw, director of the Tenderloin Housing Clinic, a grassroots
organization. ``The city's going to have to further subsidize the
rents.''
</P>
<P>
   This will place more pressure on PACT initiatives to maintain
political backing from the mayor's office and the Board of
Supervisors, advocates say.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Issues Raised by Violent Acts
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it will take only one violent incident
involving a PACT participant for questions to be raised about
housing those with the greatest tendency for errant behavior in the
community instead of at institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the economies _ it's cheaper to have these people
at hotels,'' Shaw said. ``But they shouldn't be in hotels. They
should be in hospitals.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the case, many now agree, with Hollis Owens, who was
arrested in connection with the beating of a Vallejo man in San
Francisco's Portsmouth Square last December.
</P>
<P>
   While Owens, who had a criminal history of assaults going back
15 years, was not in PACT, he was in a similar program run by the
Department of Public Health called Citywide Case Management.
</P>
<P>
   Citywide shares offices with Community Focus and is also
administered by UC San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving a drink of vodka from Ramon Calderon, who
apparently made a habit of befriending street people, Owens
suddenly flew into a rage and struck Calderon on the head with a
stick. Calderon later fell into a coma and was declared legally
dead at Marin General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Owens, originally charged with murder, eventually pleaded guilty
to voluntary manslaughter and was sentenced Monday to eight years
in state prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will happen again,'' said Community Focus' Mitchell.
``There are enough people just like this guy that we work with as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco General's Okin disputed the suggestion that PACT
clients pose a greater danger to the community. ``I think we have
increased the security of the community through this program,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Mitchell, who works with PACT clients day in and day out,
warned against complacency.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are these people out in the community,'' he said.
``Caseworkers are trying to make them safe and civil, but we're
having a hell of a time doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Funding for PACT runs out next month. Linda Wang, director of
adult services for the Department of Public Health's Community
Mental Health Services, said she is confident that the city will
approve additional funds to continue the program.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
