r f BC-PROVIDIAN--ACCORD-SFC     05-10 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROVIDIAN--ACCORD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROVIDIAN CHIEF HINTS TALKS ARE PROGRESSING 
 &HT;     BY SAM ZUCKERMAN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Credit card giant Providian Financial is making progress in its
talks with law enforcement agencies to settle consumer fraud
charges against it, the company's top executive hinted Wednesday.
<P>
   Settlement talks aren't stalemated, even though there has been
no agreement in the seven months since negotiations between
Providian and the San Francisco district attorney's office were
first reported, Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Shailesh Mehta
suggested during an interview after the company's annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes time, but that doesn't mean it's not progressing,''
Mehta said about the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney's office disclosed a year ago that it was
investigating Providian for charging late fees when customers
actually paid bills on time, selling consumers products they hadn't
requested and other alleged abuses. The company says only that it
accidentally levied improper late fees, which it later refunded.
</P>
<P>
   Providian's chief didn't comment on the substance of the talks
or a timetable for reaching an agreement. But his remark went
further than previous statements from the San Francisco company, in
which it said only that it was cooperating with law enforcement
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been very guarded,'' said Banc of America Securities
analyst Caren Mayer. ``All they have said is that they continue to
have discussions and still hope for a settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   A representative of the district attorney's office declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a mistake to read too much into Mehta's optimistic
spin, said an attorney who has taken part in similar negotiations.
The attorney, who asked not to be identified, cautioned that
successful settlements depend heavily on last-minute give and take,
and that major issues between Providian and investigators
presumably still have not been resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Settlement talks between the district attorney and Providian
began last fall, the company later confirmed. Then, early this
year, the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency, a federal bank
regulatory agency that had opened a separate investigation of the
company, joined the discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations made little progress until the two agencies
presented the findings of their investigations to the company
several months ago, people familiar with the matter said. In
addition, the need to reach an agreement among three parties is
probably delaying a settlement, legal experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Any agreement would likely include tens of millions of dollars
in fines and repayments to victimized customers, plus Providian's
commitment to halt improper practices, the experts said.
</P>
<P>
   The company has already rewritten marketing materials and
changed other business practices, steps it claims have resolved
outstanding legal issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took criticism very seriously,'' Mehta said. ``I can assure
you we're very high integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Mehta said he hadn't been aware of improper late fees because
the company had adopted a liberal fee-waiver policy that hid the
problem. ``I should have (noticed) the late-fee problem a lot
sooner,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
