<HEADER>
A1655 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MEDIA--BYTES-SFCHRON &LR;      05-10 1713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA--BYTES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY FINDS SHIFT IN EXAMINER EDITORIALS AFTER LUNCH WITH MAYOR 
 &HT;     BY DAN FOST
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;         c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
A new analysis of San Francisco Examiner editorials has found a
``subtle but troubling shift'' in the paper's treatment of Willie
Brown after the mayor's now infamous lunch with Examiner Publisher
Tim White.
<P>
   The Examiner had been caustic in its portrayal of Brown before
the August 30 lunch but was more cautious and even supportive
afterward, according to the findings of John McManus, project
director of Grade the News, which objectively examines the Bay
Area's major news outlets.
</P>
<P>
   McManus dissected the Examiner's op-ed columns and editorial
cartoons published two months before and after August 30. He posted
his findings Wednesday on his Web site ( &LR; www.gradethenews.org &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   August 30 was the date _ according to White's testimony in an
antitrust lawsuit last week _ that White told Brown the Ex would
support the mayor on the editorial page if the mayor would support
the Hearst Corp.'s acquisition of The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   White later said he made no such promise, and Examiner
Editorial-Page Editor James Finefrock offered a spirited defense on
Sunday, writing that even if White had promised Brown kid-glove
treatment, he never could have delivered.
</P>
<P>
   But because the Examiner _ which had been among Brown's toughest
critics _ endorsed Da Mayor in his re-election bid, people wondered
if White's ``horse trade'' had been consummated.
</P>
<P>
   Now we know: After their lunch engagement, the Ex seemed to pull
its punches in its treatment of Brown.
</P>
<P>
   We know this because McManus, a former reporter and journalism
professor who launched Grade the News earlier this year,
scrutinized the Examiner's op-ed pages during the period in
question with a list of objective criteria. (Presumably, Hearst is
doing the same thing as part of its ballyhooed investigation into
White's ``horse trading,'' but those results may not be made public
for months.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Examiner does show a more positive tone toward Willie
Brown after August 30 than before, but it doesn't give him a free
ride,'' McManus said.
</P>
<P>
   Before that date, the Examiner ran two editorials favorable to
Brown, four editorials that were unfavorable, three negative op-ed
columns and no positive editorial cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   After August 30, the Examiner ran six editorials favorable to
Brown, four negative editorials, no negative op-ed columns, one
positive editorial cartoon and two negative editorial cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before August 30, they think Willie Brown is an arrogant SOB _
they're very negative,'' McManus said. ``After that, the coverage
becomes much more balanced.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ex's Finefrock took issue with McManus' findings. ``Some of
these things, especially the numerical analysis, are awfully thin
reads to base judgments on. This guy is seeing shadows,'' Finefrock
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I obviously don't agree with his analysis. It's not true. ...
I endorsed Brown because he was the best guy in the race.''
</P>
<P>
   McManus launched Grade the News earlier this year as a special
project of San Jose public television station KTEH. It is funded by
the Wallace Alexander Gerbode Foundation in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   It's an unusual attempt to apply the rubric of consumer affairs
reporting to local news. ``The biggest crisis in journalism is
happening at the local level, not nationally,'' McManus said.
Nationally, people can choose quality sources like the New York
Times, National Public Radio and the ``NewsHour With Jim Lehrer,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Locally, people are dependent on the daily newspaper and the
local television station,'' he said. ``The competition is a lot
thinner, and often the journalism is manipulative and not helpful
to people.''
</P>
<P>
   He is evaluating stories that appear in The Chronicle, San Jose
Mercury News and Contra Costa Times, and that run on channels 2, 4,
5 and 7. He measures each report based on criteria such as
newsworthiness, fairness, the quality and quantity of sources,
whether the news outlet is covering local government, whether it's
digging up ``enterprise'' stories and whether its news is locally
relevant.
</P>
<P>
   His Web site, for instance, slams most media outlets, including
The Chronicle, for too much coverage of the opening of Pac Bell
Park. It's fine with McManus if the story appears in the sports
section and occasionally on the front page, but he nailed The
Chronicle for putting it out front 14 times in 18 days, often
eating up half of this valuable real estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports isn't really news at all,'' McManus writes on his site.
``It's entertainment. If it attracts people who otherwise wouldn't
pay attention to the newspaper or newscast, I'm for it. But when it
takes over the front page of a newspaper, it's a distraction,
displacing what's important. It's pandering.''
</P>
<P>
   McManus, a former reporter for the Virginian-Pilot newspaper in
Norfolk, Va., is the author of ``Market-Driven Journalism: Let the
Citizen Beware?'' He is a particularly harsh critic of local
television news and its emphasis on crime and disasters. ``You'd be
surprised how many people watch local TV news and feel informed,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   McManus has set a ``grand goal'' for Grade the News: that people
will benefit from the comparisons between various media outlets.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes to ``induce at least a portion of the audience to forgo
schlock for serious journalism,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A MAGAZINE NO MORE: Salon.com has no one else to blame but
itself. It wants to be known as so much more than an online
magazine, yet it was the company's original Web address at, ahem,
 &LR; www.salonmagazine.com  &LR; that leaves the taint of pulp and ink on
its reputation.
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting to watch, however, as Salon continues to take
steps toward the multimedia reputation it so craves. This week was
the latest move, a $5 million move into MP3s.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry: Salon isn't likely to offend Metallica with this
one. Instead, it bought MP3Lit.com, a Web site that offers ``spoken
word and audio literature recordings'' in the MP3 format.
</P>
<P>
   The site features snippets of books-on-tape recordings,
downloadable in the MP3 format now popular with rap stars and
garage bands.
</P>
<P>
   It's part of Salon CEO Michael O'Donnell's agenda to branch out
into other media. ``This year, we make that final push from a
Webzine to a media company,'' he said, noting a variety of
initiatives: Salon is developing a television show for the Bravo
cable channel, it's working on an Internet radio channel and it's
publishing books based on content that's appeared on the  &LR; its Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Salon is looking to license more of its content to
others, both in print and online. For instance, Kimberly-Clark
Corp. _ the maker of Huggies diapers _ is licensing content from
Salon's ``Mothers Who Think'' section to put on its own new Web
site at  &LR; www.parentstages.com &LR; . &LR;   &LR; ``Syndication could be half of
our revenue,'' O'Donnell said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell watches the rise in online advertising with enthusiasm
and believes that Salon could reach profitability in 18 months.
Media firms need time to build their audience, he says. Once that
happens, though, ``it's a cash cow.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, O'Donnell's greatest challenge is to keep
staffers and shareholders calm as the stock flounders in the low
single-digits. It closed yesterday at $3.13, down 13 cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to keep blunt objects out of reach, and I tell the staff
it's a marathon, not a sprint,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   TALK TALK TALK: I spoke to Salon chief O'Donnell at a swanky
party his company was co-hosting with Talk Media, showing off the
Miramax movie ``Takedown,'' about hacker Kevin Mitnick. Talk tabbed
Salon as a local sponsor, so that it would invite the right crowd,
and suitable tech stars like Marc Andreessen and Kim Polese were
indeed in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Salon and Talk made for an interesting pair: Both are companies
somewhat on the ropes, Salon with its depressed stock price and
Talk with a revolving door of editors. But both also manage to
captivate other media outlets with provocative stories and
charismatic leaders, including Salon Editor David Talbot and Talk
chief Tina Brown.
</P>
<P>
   The two met for the first time in New York last month and
schmoozed again at the Delancey Street party in San Francisco.
Might there be some sort of teamwork coming up? ``We have been
talking about the various ways Salon and Talk might be able to
continue a national conversation,'' Talbot told the assembled
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   (O'Donnell later added: ``Maybe we can help them out with their
Web plans, and they can help us get into print.'')
</P>
<P>
   But, perhaps alluding to Sean Elder's thoroughly reported Salon
piece ripping Brown's latest hire, Vicky Ward, Brown said, ``I hope
all this collaboration with Salon doesn't mean I won't be trashed
in Salon.''
</P>
<P>
   Give the queen of buzz credit: She understands the rule that no
publicity is bad.
</P>
<P>
   MAKING A FORTUNE? Just wondering how it is that Fortune could
run such a sunny cover story on Cisco Systems at the same time that
Barron's found clouds gathering over the networking colossus.
</P>
<P>
   Barron's painted Cisco's acquisition strategy as a house of
cards and mocked Cisco's logo with the question: ``Does Anybody
Want to Buy a Bridge?'' But Fortune's cover asked a different sort
of question: ``Is John Chambers the Best CEO on Earth?''
</P>
<P>
   A clue appears in the third graf of the Fortune story, in which
reporter Andy Serwer discloses ``my few hundred shares'' of Cisco
stock. (Two hundred shares would be worth more than $12,000, for
some perspective.)
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Serwer's well-written piece examines many of the
risks threatening Cisco, and a section on risk factors closes with
a discussion of the company's ``arrogance and hubris.'' ``When
questioned about earnings for an upcoming quarter, one Cisco
employee said to me, `Don't you know, at Cisco we never miss our
numbers?' Well, I've got news for you, bub! Someday you will!''
</P>
<P>
   But given the recent spotlight Fortune placed on weak ethics in
the dot-com world, one has to wonder: Shouldn't the magazine have
avoided the appearance of a conflict by assigning a reporter who
doesn't own stock in the company?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
