A1658 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-SUMMERS--ECONOMY-SFCH     05-10 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMERS--ECONOMY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO KEEP THE ECONOMY BOOMING 
 &HT;     BY CAROLYN SAID
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maintaining and expanding the current economic boom is the
biggest challenge facing the government, Treasury Secretary
Lawrence Summers said Wednesday in a luncheon address to financial
analysts and technology executives.
</P>
<P>
   And even though the current prosperity stems from a
fundamentally different ``new economy'' centered on information,
not physical goods, sustaining it will require drawing on
old-fashioned virtues, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the next five years crucial, Summers outlined five
``economic imperatives'' during a speech at the Chase H&AMP;Q
Technology Conference, and later expanded on them at a private
meeting with journalists and The Chronicle's editorial board:
</P>
<P>
   Pay off the national debt. The enormously effective performance
of the economy presents the government with a golden opportunity to
reduce publicly held debt, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can do something historic for the future by paying off the
debt before the baby boom generation retires,'' he said, adding
that the government is on track to eliminate it by early in the
next decade. ``We're paying it off faster than we built it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Invest in education. ``The most important investments in an
information age are surely investments in the human brain,''
Summers said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite pronouncements such as ``kids need classrooms, not
closets,'' and ``we need to make teaching a valued and honored
profession and to attract and reward teachers,'' Summers did not
outline any specific plans for increased education funding,
although he said any increased federal funding for education should
be accompanied by increased accountability.
</P>
<P>
   Expand market size. The government should craft policies, such
as deregulation and international trade expansion, to grow larger
markets, allowing businesses to achieve economies of scale and
generating ``cascading benefits,'' Summers said.
</P>
<P>
   That's why his top priority is convincing Congress to grant
China permanent normal trading status. He planned to take a red-eye
flight back to Washington last night to testify on the matter
before the House Banking Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only vote with a chance of being in the history books
20 years from now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He dismissed concerns that the move could reduce U.S. power to
curb human-rights abuses, saying the current policy doesn't have
such an effect. This isn't an issue of ``whether the Chinese
deserve a merit badge,'' it's about what will benefit the U.S.
economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if it loses the Congressional vote, China will join the
World Trade Organization, allowing Europe and Japan to benefit from
increased trade with the world's most populous nation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Increase spending on basic science. Innovations built on
progress in basic science ``from group theory to quantum theory''
has driven the economy forward, Summers said. President Clinton's
budget for 2001 calls for the largest-ever public investments in
basic science, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The contributions of the capital markets to funding research and
development are also very important. ``We're the only country in
the world where you can raise your first $100 million before you
buy your first suit, if your idea is good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Bridge the digital divide. The strong economy in which instead
of people looking for jobs, jobs are looking for people, is
benefiting those who might otherwise be trapped on the sidelines,
he said. Just as access to electricity and running water for all
was paramount decades ago, the challenge now is to ensure access to
telecommunications, information technology and basic financial
services.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
