<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1659 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-DRUNK-LAWSUITS-KAN &LR;      05-10 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUNK-LAWSUITS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT ALLOWS SUITS AGAINST ESTABLISHMENTS THAT SERVE DRUNKEN
DRIVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAMBE and ERIC PALMER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Missouri Supreme Court has ruled that
bars and restaurants can be sued for serving too much alcohol to
patrons who injure and kill in drunken-driving accidents.
</P>
<P>
   The 4-3 ruling radically reshapes how Missouri treats
drunken-driving victims and liquor establishments. The decision
reverses a 1985 state law intended to stop such lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Only nine states and Washington, D.C., fare worse than Missouri
in percentages of traffic deaths that are alcohol-related. And
Kansas City leads Missouri in alcohol-related accidents and repeat
drunken drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to the ruling was split.
</P>
<P>
   Mothers Against Drunk Driving predicted it would save lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's for everybody's safety,'' said Lela McDuffy, president of
the Heartland chapter of MADD.
</P>
<P>
   Bar and restaurant owners said the ruling would result in
needless lawsuits and add to the cost of doing business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I think is that my liability insurance, which
is already high, is going to go up,'' said Bill Nigro, a partner in
the Beaumont Club and owner of Torre's Pizzeria.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's court ruling eliminates a requirement that forbade
victims from suing unless an owner or employee had been convicted
of a misdemeanor for serving an obviously intoxicated person.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors never filed such charges; so civil lawsuits for
injuries or wrongful death could not be filed.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ruled that section of the law created
``arbitrary and unreasonable barriers'' to the courts and
improperly gave prosecutors power over civil lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   With the decision, Maria Kilmer of O'Fallon can proceed with a
wrongful death case against a St. Charles pizza restaurant that
served beer to a drunken driver. Her husband, Tom, was on his way
home from work when he was killed in February 1998. The driver was
convicted of involuntary manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, James G. Krispin, Kilmer's attorney, praised the
court's ruling as a tool against establishments that serve ``drink
by drink, watching them load up.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell Watters, attorney for the restaurant, said he would ask
the Supreme Court to rehear the case. He noted that the split
decision overturned a unanimous 1988 Missouri Supreme Court
decision that had upheld the same law.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling makes Missouri the most liberal state in the United
States for such litigation, Watters said. He noted that many states
do not allow such lawsuits and some limit damages, but Missouri
does not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wide open,'' he said. ``Be ready to be sued.''
</P>
<P>
   Laws governing lawsuits against bars and restaurants vary from
state to state. Kansas has no such law, the Kansas Legislative
Research Department said Wednesday. In the past, measures have been
introduced in the Legislature but never passed.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri's sudden shift drew strong reactions.
</P>
<P>
   McDuffy said education was the best weapon against drunken
driving, and lawsuits would encourage more establishments to train
servers and promote designated driver programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money is not going to bring back the people we love,'' McDuffy
said. ``But the bars and restaurants need to take some
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   John Pelzer, executive vice president of the Missouri Restaurant
Association, called the decision ``poor public policy'' and said
the association was researching ``appropriate actions and
remedies.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City club and restaurant owners said they watch for those
who have had too much to drink, but that can be hard when the only
thing they hear from a customer is, ``Bud Light.''
</P>
<P>
   Nigro said most clubs work at being responsible, training staffs
to watch for those who have had too much to drink, but they don't
individually serve every drinker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we get 1,200 people in the Beaumont. You may get a
big group and one person will say, `Give me five Buds and three
shots' and take it back to the table. That can happen all night
long,'' Nigro said. ``We have cut people off when we think they
have had too much. But if you don't interact, there can be times
where people will get intoxicated and leave the club and leave us
open for litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Nigro added that some patrons bar hop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our typical customer has been to one or two, and we may be the
last place they left,'' he said. ``If they create a problem, it
will be that place someone will go after.''
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like a rough ruling for club owners, said Calvin
Shelby, co-owner of Epicurean II at 8625 Troost Ave.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can only go by what you see, and some people can be
legally drunk and we can't tell,'' Shelby said.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone can sue, Shelby said, ``and one lawsuit can put you out
of business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 2329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
