<DOCNO> NYT20000510.0400 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1662 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-GIULIANI-NYT &LR;      05-10 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: GIULIANI'S TURBULENT TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, May 11:
</P>
<P>
   New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani began the day Wednesday
with a sensible attempt to clarify his personal and political
future by saying that he and his wife, Donna Hanover, would
separate. But his situation moved into a more strained and more
public phase when Hanover responded with a statement saying that
her efforts to share her husband's public life and save the
marriage had been undermined by his turning to other relationships.
</P>
<P>
   In personal terms, it was a day of high emotion and personal
anguish for Giuliani. In political terms, it was certainly the most
complicated and perhaps the most critical moment of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani spoke with commendable candor about his sadness over
the state of his marriage, his determination ``to deal with it
honestly and directly'' and his priorities in meeting an
astonishing confluence of problems. In recent days he has received
news that he has prostrate cancer, publicly acknowledged a close
relationship with a single woman, confirmed long-rumored marital
troubles and seen the future of his Senate candidacy thrown into
uncertainty by his medical situation. Determining his political
course is a ``second, maybe third, maybe fourth'' priority, he
said. Indeed, the public will fully understand that choosing a
treatment for his illness comes ahead of all other concerns.
</P>
<P>
   But other issues will continue to press in upon the mayor. Even
before Wednesday's events, in what was widely read as a signal from
the state Republican hierarchy, the majority leader of the state
Senate, Joseph Bruno, called on Giuliani to bring order to his
domestic situation. The subtext of the statement was that GOP
leaders are worried that publicity about Giuliani's personal life
could cripple or even end his candidacy and allow Hillary Rodham
Clinton to win the Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani himself acknowledged that some people will be ``very
angry, very upset'' with him, adding a new element of uncertainty
to an already turbulent campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Hanover's statement had a subtext too, with its hints of a
bitter divorce and custody battle and potentially embarrassing
revelations. Her reference to Giuliani's ``relationship with one
staff member'' seemed a threat against the mayor's insistence that
he has maintained a wall between his personal and public lives.
</P>
<P>
   Even in a state that allows its politicians plenty of room, this
combination of medical, personal and political difficulty is
formidable. Giuliani has prided himself on being a mold-breaking
politician with an extraordinary capacity for work. But there is a
limit to the amount of political baggage that any candidate can
overcome.
</P>
<P>
   Common sense dictates that Bruno's advice about the campaign is
apt. Giuliani must move as quickly as his health allows to restore
a sense of order to his personal life and to inform voters about
his political future.
</P>
<P>
   His appeal for some confidential space in which to work out his
medical and marital decisions is reasonable. But with the
statements from Giuliani and his wife Wednesday, the issues
surrounding him have become part of the civic discourse. As the
manager of a complicated city and a declared aspirant for national
leadership, Giuliani has an obligation to bring clarity and
stability to a disorderly situation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-00 2338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
