<SLUG> BC-ALTAVISTA--LAYOFFS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALTAVISTA ANNOUNCES LAYOFFS 
 &HT;     BY VERNE KOPYTOFF
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
AltaVista, the Palo Alto Web portal, Wednesday became one of the
latest Internet companies to announce layoffs in an effort to
reduce costs.
<P>
   The company said it is laying off about 40 workers, including
ones in Palo Alto, Southern California and Massachusetts. The cuts
will affect a wide range of departments, including marketing, sales
and news, but not any of the executive staff, according to the
company.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement comes nearly a month after the company
postponed its initial public offering because of the slumping stock
market. Yesterday, the company said the initial public offering is
still on hold pending an improved climate on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``AltaVista is in serious trouble,'' said Rob Enderle, a
technology analyst with Giga Information Group. ``Because of the
delay in the IPO, they're not getting the money they expected and
have to reduce costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Enderle said the layoffs will worry potential investors and
could ``make the company's stock damaged goods.'' He added that
AltaVista may have trouble keeping the employees who remain because
of their fear of being laid off.
</P>
<P>
   David Emanuel, an AltaVista spokesman, said the layoffs are
intended to ``streamline operations'' as part of a goal to make the
company profitable by the end of the year. He added that the
layoffs were also a consequence of the industry's and investors'
new emphasis on cutting costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still very well funded,'' Emanuel said. ``We still have
very ambitious plans.''
</P>
<P>
   During the past year and a half, AltaVista has grown
significantly from its roots as a simple search engine through
several big acquisitions. The company, which trails far behind
competitors like Yahoo and Lycos in traffic, spent hundreds of
millions of dollars buying financial Web site Raging Bull and
Shopping.com, an online retailer.
</P>
<P>
   AltaVista's staff expanded accordingly, from 55 in January 1999
to more than 800. Yesterday's layoffs represent a workforce
reduction of about 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Several other large Internet companies have laid off workers
since the beginning of the year. Among them are e-retailers
Amazon.com, Beyond.com and Healthshop.com.
</P>
<P>
   AltaVista, owned by the venture capital firm CMGI, laid off an
additional 60 workers between August and March from its
Shopping.com division. But Emanuel said that had more to do with a
change in that division's focus from being an online retailer to a
search engine for shopping on other Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
