<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1665 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SC-FLAG-1STLD-WRITETH     05-10 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-FLAG-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 COLUMBIA, S.C.: a compromise. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``This plan received support across party and racial lines,''
said Hodges, clearly relieved that the support for the plan in the
House did not come entirely from white lawmakers. ``I believe South
Carolinians will join together and embrace this compromise as an
honorable way to resolve this debate once and for all.'' He said he
could not control what the NAACP does, but effusively praised the
three black legislators who supported the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Six of seven black senators had originally supported the bill,
and one of their leaders, Sen. Darrell Jackson, predicted their
votes would not change once the differences with the House bill
were worked out.
</P>
<P>
   But Todd Rutherford, a black House member who opposed the bill,
predicted another debate over the new flag in next year's
legislative session, vowing to propose legislation himself to move
the flagpole away from the entrance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a historic occasion, no doubt about that,'' Rutherford
said, after the vote. ``I'm just sorry that something this
momentous has to occur without African-Americans being in the
compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill failed to get much black support precisely because it
was designed to win the votes of white Republicans who had
previously refused to even consider a vote on moving the flag. On
Tuesday, Republicans angered black legislators by voting to make
the flag even more prominent, raising it to 30 feet high, from the
20 feet in the Senate bill, and illuminating it at night. Those
changes made it into the final House bill Wednesday night, along
with a provision mandating stiff penalties for anyone who
vandalizes the flag or the monument. (Wednesday morning, officials
had to remove some spray-painted graffiti from the monument.)
</P>
<P>
   The bill also removes the Confederate flags from the House and
Senate chambers, where they have flown next to the United States
and South Carolina flags for decades.
</P>
<P>
   The 63-56 vote came after nearly 10 hours of debate Wednesday
that starkly revealed the deep mistrust and animosity between the
races in the House. Black leaders had hoped to support a plan that
would move the flag from the Confederate memorial, but would also
erect flagpoles bearing military banners to honor soldiers who fell
in four 20th-century wars. Republican leaders would only accept the
plan if it included flying the flag from the dome on Confederate
Memorial Day every year, which by coincidence was Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But hardliners on each side found those aspects unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``To fly that flag for a day, even for an hour, even for a
minute, is unacceptable to us,'' said Rep. Joseph H. Neal, a black
Democrat from Chester, who would have supported the plan if not for
the one-day-a-year provision. ``It is not a sovereign flag, and it
is an insult to people of color.''
</P>
<P>
   White Republicans who want to keep the flag on the dome picked
apart the plan from the other end of the spectrum, criticizing it
for not honoring soldiers in the Revolutionary War, or for being
vague on which flags symbolize certain wars. The Republican
Majority Leader, Rick Quinn, who supported the proposal, said its
chances were hurt when black members compared the Confederate flag
to a swastika, and when a local activist burned the flag in front
of the Capitol shortly after noon.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle over the flag, which has overshadowed almost every
other policy issue in South Carolina for more than a year, became
so intense because it perfectly embodied the much larger political
gulf between the races in the state, which has persisted since
Reconstruction. Blacks have long felt that they were barely
tolerated as political equals, and saw every reference to
``Southern heritage'' as scarcely hidden nostalgia for the days of
white supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   White legislators, on the other hand, believed the flag was a
legitimate expression of honor for ancestors who had died fighting
for the South, and resented being lumped in with the racists and
Klansmen who had expropriated the flag for their own purposes. Many
made it clear they had also chafed over the years at the
encroachment of affirmative action and other social policies sought
by black residents, and considered the flag a last remnant of a
vanishing nobility.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the final hours, the arguments of the House leadership
to move the flag were based on how it was affecting the state's
image and business climate, rather than the moral or historical
problems engendered by the flag's presence atop the seat of state
government. One member complained to the House that South Carolina
had become the butt of jokes on the late-night talk shows, and
Wilkins asked his colleagues to imagine what would happen to the
state if the flag flew for another year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This issue is hurting our state,'' he said, explaining why he
had changed his position from solidly supporting the flag on the
dome. ``If you reach down deep inside, you'll have to admit that.
And this is the last opportunity we'll get to do something. You may
not get exactly what you want, but it will be in the best interests
of our state.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
