u a BC-NY-GIULIANI-TEXT-NYT &LR;      05-10 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-TEXT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(WITH NY-GIULIANI) 
EXCERPTS FROM GIULIANI'S PRESS CONFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Following are excerpts from Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's
news conference in Bryant Park on Wednesday, in which he discussed
his marriage to Donna Hanover and his relationship with Judith
Nathan, whom he has called a ``very good friend.'' The remarks were
recorded by The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   The Mayor's Comments
</P>
<P>
   This is very, very painful. For quite some time it's probably
been apparent that Donna and I lead, in many ways, independent and
separate lives. It's been a very painful road and I'm hopeful that
we'll be able to formalize that in a, in an agreement that protects
our children, gives them all the security and all the protection
they deserve, and protects Donna.
</P>
<P>
   And that's something we have to work out and we have to strive
toward and _ you know, I'm a public person, I'm elected to public
office. I do my job, I think, honestly and effectively and as well
as I can. And I, you know, I realize that my private life is open
to everyone. I just watch what's going on and I just wish that
you'd maybe respect it a little bit more.
</P>
<P>
   But in any event, you know, we'll do the best that we can to
make the decisions that we have to make that are, that are
consistent with our own lives and our children. But I don't think
I'm saying anything that you haven't, that you haven't all written,
that over the course of some period of time in many ways we've
grown to live independent and separate lives, and we should
probably strive toward formalizing that.
</P>
<P>
   Questions and Answers
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is that a legal separation, Mr. Mayor?
</P>
<P>
   GIULIANI. I _ I would _ I really don't want to go into, any more
than I want to go into the great details of, you know, what one
doctor said to me or what another doctor said to me, I don't want
to get into that. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Q. Would she move out of Gracie Mansion?
</P>
<P>
   A. Nobody, nobody, nobody is, nobody is moving anywhere.
Everybody is secure and safe. What I said is that we should try to
work out a separation agreement. That's different. . . . What I
said is what I said, a separation agreement; it's not a divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Mr. Mayor, are you at all motivated by the . . .
</P>
<P>
   A. And I should say _ no. I'm motivated by all of the tremendous
invasion of privacy that's taken place in everyone's life, my
family's, Judith Nathan's family's. This is something, this is
something that has developed over some period of time and it's
something between Donna and me, not anyone else, and really not
even the whole world, just between Donna and me.
</P>
<P>
   Q. . . . concerned about a backlash?
</P>
<P>
   A. No, you know, I don't really care about politics right now. I
don't. I'm thinking about my family, the people that I love and
what's, what can be done that's honest and truthful and that
protects them the best.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not thinking about politics. I'm not; politics comes at
least second, maybe third, maybe fourth, somewhere else. It'll all
work itself out some way, politically. I'm hoping that if I, maybe
if I say something, I mean, some of the things that the news
organizations are doing, horrendous. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are you still running for the Senate?
</P>
<P>
   A. It has nothing to do with the Senate. It has something to do
with the fact that there's a tremendous amount of intense scrutiny,
and I felt I had to say at least something that explains it.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Has the media caused damage to . . .
</P>
<P>
   A. Of course this is damaging and painful and very, very
difficult for everyone. . . . But you have to deal with it honestly
and directly. You can't, you can't pretend or hide.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Has the media caused the damage?
</P>
<P>
   A. No. The media makes the damage much worse; it didn't cause
the damage. I take responsibility for everything that I've done.
And you have every right to ask me, and then I have a right to
answer or not answer. And that's the way I think we can have a
respectful relationship with each other.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is the . . . is that affecting your . . . Senate race?
</P>
<P>
   A. I haven't thought about it yet in that context. Maybe I will.
I've been thinking about it more in the health context. Judith
Nathan is a very, very fine person. She's been a very good friend
to me before I had to deal with the decisions that I have to make
about my illness and what to do about it, and I rely on her and she
helps me a great deal. And I'm going to need her more now than
maybe I did before. These are decisions I have to make, you know,
at a very difficult time, so __
</P>
<P>
   Q. She has been more supportive of you than Ms. Hanover? . . .
</P>
<P>
   A. I, my, Donna Hanover is a wonderful woman. And she's a
wonderful mother. She's someone that I respect tremendously. The
fact that we've grown independent, we've grown more separate over
the years; who knows why those things happen? But she is a very,
very fine, wonderful person, and she's a, extraordinary mother and
I have tremendous respect for her.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is your emotional . . . right now?
</P>
<P>
   A. My emotional state is, I'm very sad. And I feel terrible. . .
.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Does your wife agree with you?
</P>
<P>
   A. My wife speaks for herself, as you know. She made a statement
the other day and she'll, she has her right to whatever she wants
to say, and Donna, Donna is an independent person and I respect her
for that. And there are obviously going to be things that we
disagree about, but __
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is there any chance that you might resign from office?
</P>
<P>
   A. No, there's no chance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
