<HEADLINE>
WOMAN, 24, SHOT TO DEATH NEAR HER HOME IN QUEENS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Fla.)   By WILLIAM K. RASHBAUM  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 24-year-old Japanese woman who worked as a music
promoter was fatally shot early Wednesday morning as she walked
home on a quiet Queens street, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Ryoko Chosa, who was from Nagano, Japan, was found
about 3:15 a.m. on the sidewalk outside 87-59 52nd Ave. in
Elmhurst, about a block from her home, police said. Chosa was found
after several neighbors were awakened by gunshots and called the
police.
</P>
<P>
   The young woman, who had majored in Spanish and Latin American
affairs and, according to one of her professors, had hoped to work
as a translator at the United Nations, had been shot in the face,
the neck and the stomach, police said. She was taken to Elmhurst
General Hospital, where she died about 5 a.m., the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Chosa's killer left behind her watch and her large black purse
containing her wallet, and police detectives said they were unsure
of the motive for the killing. ``We're seeking to determine if
robbery was the motive or if the young woman was killed by someone
known to her,'' said Richard Brown, the Queens district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives from the 110th Precinct and the Queens Homicide
Squad, who are investigating the killing, spoke with the woman's
family in Japan, who said they did not know whether Chosa had been
seeing anyone, a police official said.
</P>
<P>
   The murder shattered the calm of the middle-class neighborhood
of three-story brick row houses and single-family homes, where many
Asian families live. Jee Choe, 20, said that he and his girlfriend
moved to the neighborhood because they thought it was safe, but
that now they were not so sure. ``It worries me now, especially for
my girlfriend, that something like this could happen around here,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chosa had worked since December for YWA Music in Soho, where her
responsibilities included helping to promote Japanese bands in
Latin America and in the United States, the authorities said. Calls
to the office were not returned Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   She graduated in April 1999 from Flagler College, a small
liberal arts school in St. Augustine, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   An energetic and dedicated student with a ready smile, she
impressed her teachers and classmates because she had to study
twice as hard as some of her peers to master English so that she
could then master Spanish, said a spokeswoman for the school,
Laurin Bosse.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dawn Wiles, the head of the college's Spanish language/Latin
American studies department, said in a statement issued by Bosse,
``I think that anybody who knew her admired her so much because she
undertook such a difficult program of studies.''
</P>
<P>
   Chosa had spent the evening before she was killed at the
Limelight, a nightclub in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   She lived in a room on the second floor of a small house around
the corner from where she was killed, police said. The house was
divided into five rooms that shared a kitchen and a bathroom, and
most of the residents were Japanese, the authorities said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
