<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-REFORMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTORNEYS GENERAL IN 18 STATES SEEK CHANGES IN BOXING 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A group of attorneys general from 18 states called Wednesday for
wide reforms of boxing, including independent polls to rank
fighters and limits on a single judge's power to skew a fight's
result.
</P>
<P>
   The officials, including those from big-fight states like
Nevada, New Jersey and New York, issued their 60-page report after
more than a year of interviews with people in boxing. The attorneys
general pledged to push athletic commissions in their states to
adopt the measures.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Eliot L. Spitzer of New York, the chairman of
the committee, said the next step would be to persuade broadcasters
and pay-per-view companies to honor an independent writers' poll
rather than relying on rankings by the three main sanctioning
bodies, which have been shown to be arbitrary at best and corrupt
in many cases.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said if broadcasters ignored the sanctioning
organizations, it would break an ``unholy alliance'' between
ratings officials and promoters, who he said manipulate rankings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we will have stripped the sanctioning bodies of their
power,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The report also called for new rules to protect the health of
boxers, including guidelines for weight loss and a rule requiring
the final weigh-in to be the day of the fight rather than the day
before.
</P>
<P>
   The career of the welterweight Joey Gamache was ended at New
York's Madison Square Garden recently after Arturo Gatti, who
gained 19 pounds between the weigh-in and the fight, knocked him
out and caused brain damage.
</P>
<P>
   The task force also recommended standardized testing for judges,
referees and ring physicians, and standardized contracts between
boxers and managers that would disclose all financial arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   The attorneys general urged the adoption of a consensus scoring
system. Under such a system, if three judges cannot agree on a
round then the aberrant score is thrown out. Such a system would
have given Lennox Lewis the victory in the widely criticized
championship fight last year that ended in a draw between him and
Evander Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   While the recommendations, if put into effect in all 18 states,
could be a giant step toward cleaning up boxing, Spitzer said
national legislation was still needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fights can always migrate to states with less restrictive
laws,'' he said.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
