<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1684 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-GIULIANI-WOMEN-NYT     05-10 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-WOMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DONNA HANOVER AND JUDITH NATHAN: WOMEN AT THE CENTER OF GIULIANI'S
LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Donna Hanover &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It was a made-for-TV romance at the beginning. After a friend of
Rudolph Giuliani, then an associate attorney general in Washington,
suggested he call Donna Hanover, then a news anchorwoman, he had
his secretary make the call to arrange a meeting _ actually, a
television interview on a drug crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks later, at Walt Disney World, Giuliani proposed. They
married in April 1984.
</P>
<P>
   In the intervening years, Hanover has played a number of roles,
from an evangelist in ``The People vs. Larry Flynt'' to the dutiful
political spouse.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, she has increasingly shied away from
playing the role of the New York City's first lady, making a name
for herself with myriad jobs in television and in the movies.
</P>
<P>
   It was in recent weeks, however, that her role as the mayor's
wife again thrust her into the political spotlight. Her decision to
appear in ``The Vagina Monologues'' provoked controversy in light
of Giuliani's U.S. Senate run, and she later canceled her role in
the play after the mayor learned he had cancer.
</P>
<P>
   In the earlier years of her marriage to Giuliani, Hanover, a
graduate of Stanford University and the Columbia School of
Journalism, regularly accompanied her husband on his professional
duties, even visiting New Haven, Conn., as he prosecuted the
corruption trial of Stanley M. Friedman, the Bronx Democratic
leader.
</P>
<P>
   While campaigning for Giuliani's unsuccessful 1989 bid for the
mayor's office, Hanover, who was born in California, starred in a
campaign commercial, featuring scenes of him playing with their two
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first met Rudy, he seemed strong and at the same time
gentle'' she said in the advertisement. ``And I liked that. I
thought, this is the kind of man I want to be the father to my
children.''
</P>
<P>
   She worked at WPIX-TV from 1983 to 1990, and later as a
correspondent on WNYW-TV's ``Good Day New York,'' the morning news
program on Channel 5, and as co-host of ``In Food Today,'' a show
on the national cable Television Food Network. In dramatic roles,
she has appeared on the ABC series ``The Practice,'' as well as on
``Law and Order,'' ``Family Law'' and ``Ally McBeal,'' and was
praised for her performance as Ruth Carter Stapleton in ``The
People vs. Larry Flynt.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanover has played a television anchorwoman in at least seven
feature films, including ``Ransom'' with Mel Gibson. She has also
conducted celebrity interviews for Good Housekeeping magazine, and
has worked with the directors Sidney Lumet and Ron Howard.
</P>
<P>
   She has also branched out into teaching, as an associate faculty
member at Utica College and an adjunct professor in the journalism
department of New York University.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, she has increasingly distanced herself from the
role of political spouse, and was far less visible on the campaign
trail during Giuliani's second successful run for mayor in 1997.
Around that time, she also bristled when called ``Mrs. Giuliani.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout her various careers, Hanover appears to have taken
the advice that she offers on the Internet home page of the Food
Network: ``Work hard at several projects. That way, no matter what
is going wrong, something will be going right.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Judith Nathan &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Judith Nathan, the woman whom Mayor Rudolph Giuliani calls a
``very good friend,'' is an executive at a drug company who lives
on the Upper East Side with her 15-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani and Nathan have both declined to say how they met or
explain the nature of their relationship, asking reporters to
respect their privacy. But they have increasingly been seen
together at events attended by the mayor, such as parades, as well
as at private meals at restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor first responded to questions about their relationship
last Wednesday, the day that The New York Post published photos of
them together leaving a restaurant on the Upper East Side.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan, who is licensed as a nurse in New York state and whose
maiden name is Stish, was married for several years to Bruce Nathan
before the two had a contested divorce. The divorce included a
dispute over the custody of their daughter, who attends a private
school on the Upper East Side, people who know Nathan said.
</P>
<P>
   After Giuliani announced Wednesday that he was separating from
his wife, Nathan could not be reached for comment. But outside of
her apartment building in recent days, she has generally limited
her remarks to asking people to respect her privacy and to saying
that she was concerned about the health of the mayor, who has been
diagnosed with prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference Wednesday, Giuliani called Nathan ``a
very, very fine person'' and said that because of his illness,
``I'm going to need her more now than maybe I did before.''
</P>
<P>
   A former boyfriend of Nathan's, Manos Zacharioudakis, said he
had a long relationship with her until they ``ran out of steam''
last year. Zacharioudakis, a psychologist who said he works for the
city's hospitals agency, praised Nathan, saying that she was a
wonderful mother. ``If there is going to be a next Mrs. Giuliani,
she is going to make a perfect wife,'' Zacharioudakis said. ``She
is an extraordinary individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Nathan did not respond to two messages left for him at his home
on Wednesday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
