<HEADER>
A1686 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-HEAT-NYT &LR;      05-10 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HEAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAT'S MOURNING PROMISES TO BE MR. INSIDE IN GAME 3
</HEADLINE>
  By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COCONUT GROVE, Fla. _ Pat Riley and Tim Hardaway suggested to
Alonzo Mourning that he shot too many long-range jumpers in Miami's
82-76 loss to the New York Knicks in Game 2. Then his former
college coach, John Thompson, made it unanimous.
</P>
<P>
   Mourning had 17 points, but one of his worst shooting
performances of the season, missing 13 of 18 field goals and 6 of
13 free throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big John said, `One thing I've always told you is the game is
played from the inside out, and you settled for the outside
yesterday,''' a chagrined Mourning said Wednesday after the Heat's
practice at LaSalle High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said: `Just think about every opportunity that you had
yesterday to take the ball to the hole. Just think about all the
good things to happen out of it. You score or you're fouled or
somebody tips it. Or you kick it to an open player.' I know I
didn't really exploit that side of my game.''
</P>
<P>
   Mourning promised that he would assert his 6-foot-10-inch,
261-pound body closer to the basket on Friday in Game 3 at Madison
Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's got me into the position I am today,'' he said, ``is
taking the ball to the hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Mourning missed 10 straight shots from 9 minutes 59 seconds of
the second quarter until 1:26 of the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept thinking the next shot that I took was going to fall,''
he said. ``Then the next one I take is going to fall. Then the next
one _ instead of thinking, why don't I make the extra pass and get
the defense moving and get a deeper spot on the weak side or get
somebody wide open, based on patience and execution of the
offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Mourning, who had 17 points overall, misfired on eight shots
from beyond 13 feet and was 0 of 7 in the third quarter as the
Knicks built a nine-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm a better player than I showed yesterday _ by far,''
he said. ``It's a shame to say it took a game like this to make me
realize what I need to do, because I knew it already.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley said: ``We've got to find a better way to get him the ball
deeper. We know it. They know it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks sometimes have put Larry Johnson on Mourning, even
though Mourning is almost 6 inches taller. The Heat center knows he
can almost shoot at will over Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when it's not smart, I have to go to the next option,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mourning came into the game aware that any time he took a
15-foot or longer jump shot, he needed to make a high percentage of
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times I get caught up in the game so much that I
settle for what the defense is giving me, instead of putting more
pressure on the defense,'' he said. ``But like I said, It won't
happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Making the game a complete bust for him offensively were the six
missed free throws. He missed the first two, late in the first
quarter, then botched three of his next four. Overall, the Heat
missed 14 free throws, a transgression that looked pivotal in
Riley's day-after assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of felt like I started it,'' Mourning said of the
team's free-throw debacle. ``They caught the disease from me.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mourning didn't sound too worried that the disease will
carry-over to the next game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I was actually clanking them and they were
hitting the backboard and bouncing off to the side,'' he said.
``They were going in that rim, and coming back out. So it's just a
matter of mechanics. It's locking my elbow, following through,
getting up my toes, getting it over the rim _ things like that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
